HOW EIGHT WORDS CHANGED OHIO STATE
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fivemonths ago, before Ohio State plopped on the
college basketball couch and Jim O'Brien was named Big Ten Coach of
the Year for engineering the greatest turnaround in conference
history, a fellow named Scoonie uttered eight words that shocked
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make the NCAA Tournament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His coach cringed, reporters cackled, and the campus wondered if
someone had forgotten to dot his ``i.'' Ohio State in the NCAA
Tournament? In 1999? The Buckeyes hadn't had a winning season in
five years, much less participated in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Ohio thought I was crazy,'' junior guard James
``Scoonie'' Penn said.
</P>
<P>
   But Scoonie was money, and here they are _ facing No.1 seed
Auburn tonight in the South Regional Sweet 16 in Knoxville, Tenn.,
one year after they won eight games and endured a 17-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   From 1-15 to 12-4 _ the greatest turnaround in Big Ten
Conference history. All because of eight words that rocked a
program from its slumbering past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought Scoonie was far-fetched at the beginning,'' Ohio
State junior forward George Reese said. ``But we needed our point
guard to be a leader and give us some confidence. We started to
believe, then we started winning.''
</P>
<P>
   It figures it took two transfers to do it, two people with no
connections to Ohio State's troubled past: O'Brien, who joined the
Buckeyes after a tumultuous tenure at Boston College; and Penn, the
former Eagles star who followed O'Brien, sat out last season and
recently was named Big Ten Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Add Michael Redd, a smooth forward who last year became the
first freshman to lead the Big Ten in scoring, 6-foot-11 center Ken
Johnson, who has given the Buckeyes a presence in the pivot, a slew
of local kids eager to rebuild the state's once-proud program _ and
it's little wonder Ohio State (25-8) stood with Auburn and
Wisconsin as the regular season's biggest surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes entered the top-25 poll Jan. 11 for the first time
in six years, eventually finished second in the Big Ten to Michigan
State and earned a No.4 seed. Last week, in their first NCAA
Tournament appearance since 1992, they dispatched Murray State and
Detroit to advance to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, after the Buckeyes lost the Midwest regional finals to
Michigan's Fab Five, star forward Jimmy Jackson bolted for the NBA.
The Buckeyes slowly disintegrated under coach Randy Ayres, who won
15, 13, 6, 10 and 10 games over the next five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Boston College, O'Brien directed the Eagles to
three tournament appearances in 11 years, including a fabulous run
in 1994 when they slayed No. 1 seed North Carolina. He had finally
established Boston College as New England's team in 1996 when the
admissions department tightened its grip and rejected the
applications of two top Boston recruits, Elton Tyler and Jonathan
DePina. (Both were eligible under NCAA rules.)
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien won the Big East title in 1997, but with local high
school coaches and players rebelling, he fled to Columbus. Penn
followed a few months later, and together they hunkered down for a
season beyond imagination.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Brien on a preseason golf trip in Scotland, three players
were arrested within 72 hours. Another was lost for the season to a
back injury. A widower who spent two months living in a hotel,
O'Brien then dismissed three players and had just seven on
scholarship when the 1997-98 season began. The Buckeyes lost their
first 14 conference games and spent each day waiting for the season
to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach keeps reminding us of where we've come from,'' reserve
Shamar Herron said. ``He wants us to stay hungry, and it isn't
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The climb from there to here began last summer, when O'Brien
reloaded with five recruits. He welcomed Penn, the floor leader OSU
lacked, and he settled a lawsuit with Boston College in which he
claimed mismanagement in rejecting the recruits. His life was
starting to coalesce when Penn popped off in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to tone it down a little, but he kept talking
about the NCAAs all year long,'' O'Brien said. ``All we tried to do
was win the next game, then re-evaluated our goals as we went
along. I thought Scoonie was stretching it a little. I was looking
for a middle ground. This program had had five consecutive losing
seasons. You can't go from that to the NCAA Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
