<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE RALLY ENOUGH (AGAIN)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ The Pepperdine baseball team is getting ahead
these days by falling behind. What else could explain the best
start in school history?
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the sixth-ranked Waves trailed early against UCLA,
rallied for a comfortable lead and then held on to beat the Bruins
7-6 in a nonconference game at Eddy D. Field Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (21-2) has won 11 of 12 and notched its 12th
come-from-behind victory of the season. Freshman outfielder Woody
Cliffords, whose clutch hitting helped El Camino Real High win the
past two L.A. City Section championships, hit a leadoff home run,
his second of the season, in the bottom of the seventh to break a
6-6 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Cliffords also had an RBI single in the third and lifted his
average to .392.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a slider,'' Cliffords said of his homer, which
came off left-handed reliever Bobby Roe. ``I'm a smarter hitter
now. In high school, I wouldn't swing at breaking balls early in
the count. I'm learning that sometimes I'm only going to get one
good pitch to hit in each at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliffords is also playing left field for the first time in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cliffords) is doing a great job,'' Waves coach Frank Sanchez
said. ``A big reason we are where we are is because of Woody.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine began the season unranked. Now, only one Division I
team in the nation _ 17-1 North Carolina - has fewer losses than
the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to win, regardless of the first couple of innings,''
Pepperdine senior third baseman G.J. Raymundo said. ``We just find
a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggling Bruins (15-17) took a 2-0 lead in the third off
Pepperdine starter Steve Schenewerk. The Waves responded with four
runs in the bottom of the inning off UCLA right-hander Jon Brandt,
the Bruins' winningest pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Raymundo hit a two-run homer, his team-leading eighth, to
highlight the rally.
</P>
<P>
   After Pepperdine took a 6-2 lead, UCLA scored twice in the sixth
and twice in the seventh to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine junior right-hander Jay Gehrke pitched a shaky ninth
but ended up striking out the side to pick up his 11th save, tying
a school record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
