<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN MILITARY POLICE ARREST ARMY DISSIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A fugitive dissident army officer who has publicly
accused the armed forces of justice abuses was arrested on
Wednesday by military police, the Defense Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Hildegardo Bacilio Gomez, a 43-year-old army surgeon,
was detained in the main square of his hometown, the city of
Pachuca in central Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with sedition, insubordination and defaming the
armed forces, which are among the most serious crimes under the
military code. He had been in hiding since December.
</P>
<P>
   Bacilio led about 50 soldiers in a march down Mexico City's
central boulevard last Dec. 18 to protest what they called unfair
and heavy-handed treatment by the justice system of Mexico's highly
secretive armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first open challenge by a dissident movement to
military leaders since the turbulent decades at the beginning of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   The colonel, with 23 years of service in the army, claimed that
he had been hounded by military justice because of a 1996 incident
in which he left his post at an army hospital to give emergency
medical care to a civilian in a private clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The government has reacted sharply to the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Five other officers who attempted to deliver a letter of protest
to President Ernesto Zedillo's offices on Jan. 5 were also arrested
and charged with sedition. In a speech on annual Army Day in
February, Zedillo called the dissident soldiers ``buffoons.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he has been on the run, Bacilio has continued to give
press interviews and send broadsides by fax to news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we asking for from the military courts,'' he said in
an interview published this week in a Mexican political magazine,
``is just that they be honest and fair. We don't seek to abolish
the military system, we just want to modernize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Military leaders have noted that Bacilio is facing a series of
earlier charges for desertion and insubordination and have called
his public dissent a gross violation of military discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other soldiers in the movement have also run afoul
of military justice.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed that army commanders charged them with military
infractions out of personal vengeance or arbitrary use of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
