<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NUKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY ANNOUNCES STEPS TO TIGHTEN SECURITY AT NUCLEAR
LABS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to recast 3rd and 4th grafs)  (sw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department has begun an internal
investigation into accusations that its chief of intelligence was
improperly barred from briefing Congress last year about
allegations that China stole data from a nuclear weapons
laboratory, Secretary Bill Richardson announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The department's inspector general, Greg Friedman, will review
whether Elizabeth Moler, who was acting energy secretary at the
time, prevented Notra Trulock, then the intelligence chief, from
giving information about possible Chinese espionage to the House
Select Committee on Intelligence in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation announced on Wednesday comes about 10 days
after an article in The New York Times led to broad criticism of
how the administration handled evidence that China had stolen
nuclear secrets from Los Alamos National Laboratory, in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   According to the article, Trulock contended that Ms. Moler had
prevented him from briefing the House panel because the information
could have been used to criticize President Clinton's policy on
China.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moler has said she does not recall the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also announced six other steps intended to improve
security at nuclear weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony on Wednesday to the Senate Select Committee on
Intelligence, he said his department would ask for $8 million more
in next year's counterintelligence budget for a new computer
security program for systems at the labs, which are owned by the
Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   The department also plans to invest in systems to analyze
sensitive e-mail leaving the labs and other Energy Department
facilities, and will impose stricter controls on laboratory
documents that contain data on weapons design.
</P>
<P>
   With the new request for funds for electronic security, the
department is seeking to increase its counterintelligence budget
for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1, to $39.2 million, more than
double last year's spending.
</P>
<P>
   In response to widespread criticism of the failure of the labs
to conduct background checks on thousands of visitors from
so-called sensitive countries like China, Russia and Iran, John
Deutch, the former director of central intelligence, is to review
the security of the visitors' programs.
</P>
<P>
   His review will be in addition to the broader assessment of the
case being conducted by the CIA and an outside panel led by David
Jeremiah, a retired admiral.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the department will report annually to Congress
on its foreign visitors and its counterintelligence efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The department's office of counterintelligence also plans an
extensive review of old investigative files in order to identify
cases that should be examined further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
