<HEADLINE>
ST. PAT'S PARADE ENTERTAINS KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE LAMOY and LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ St. Patty himself wouldn't have prayed for a
nicer day for Wednesday's 26th Annual St. Patrick's Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   It came outfitted with a warming sun, a blue dome of Midwestern
sky, a light breeze and, organizers estimated, more than 200,000
attendees who jammed Grand Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   People showed up early. By 10:30 a.m., more than an hour before
the parade began, crowds jostled for curbside positions.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrators dressed in goofy hats and T-shirts with silly
slogans and sported shamrocks pasted and painted on cheeks, arms
and heads. By the time the parade began, the crowds were 14 deep on
sidewalks, spilling onto the street, from Pershing Road to Sixth
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The street was alive with noise: bullhorns and sirens, children
shouting, helicopter blades whipping the sky, police motorcycles
rumbling by. It was classic parade ambience _ and it delivered a
giant street party.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting to begin, Sgt. Robert Espino from the New Orleans Marine
Corps Band hoisted his 45-pound gold sousaphone off his shoulders.
His white gloves flashed in the sunlight as he straightened his
white sash over his black uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, this does get heavy,'' he said. ``But I'm used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A block away, Kathie Richard prepared to herd nine sheep down
the parade route. She worried about the herd dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be crazy to be here,'' she said, watching a group of
children pet her sheep. ``If the dogs flank too wide and get under
the wheel of a car...'' Her voice trailed off as she shuddered. She
soon dropped out of the parade when a dog was nearly hit by a truck
hauling a man in a rat suit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 11:40 a.m., a boom sounded, and a kelly green billow
of smoke poured onto Grand. A lone bagpiper, Jodie Watson, began to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the corner of Grand and Pershing, Pat Hughes,
wearing a ballcap that said ``The Boss'' on it, pointed his
bullhorn at the waiting Marine band.
</P>
<P>
   ``United States Marines,'' he barked, sweeping one hand in front
of him, ``the streets of Kansas City are yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Drums rolled, and the band began the opening bars to a Sousa
march. The parade awoke, lurching forward like a giant centipede
with nearly 200 entries. The displays ranged from those as simple
as pickup trucks with green fringe, to one with a three-story
helium-filled fox balloon, to one celebrating Irish police officers
that featured a circling airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the massive crowd and the chaotic atmosphere, there
were no catastrophes. Police reported that eight persons were
arrested for fighting. And there was one injury involving a
9-year-old girl who bruised her left knee when she ran into a
motorcycle driven by a police officer, said Kansas City Police Maj.
Joseph McHale. The girl fell but didn't require medical treatment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the floats, bands, dancing groups and funky cars tooled by,
mothers fed babies, boyfriends kissed girlfriends, and drinking
buddies shouted and whooped.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing up the end of the parade was Ken Henderson and a
menagerie of five snakes, a Great Dane//Labrador dog named Lady,
and Rosco, a red rooster.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson walked behind a beat-up old station wagon with an
albino Burmese python, Buttercup, draped over his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to drive the snakes out of Ireland,'' he shouted
to the dwindling crowd, apparently in reference to the legend of
St. Patrick driving snakes from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered, screamed and clapped at everything that moved
down the parade route, whether it was the Marching Cobras drill
team or truckloads of Irish American families or even parade
volunteers in golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   Around 2:30 p.m. the first parade was over and another began.
More than a dozen mechanized street sweepers from American Sweeping
Inc. worked their way north on Grand, clearing the discarded and
blowing cans, bottles, bags and miles of silly string, sucking up
debris in figure eights, avoiding one another with the grace of
dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, you couldn't even tell a party had happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
