<HEADLINE>
POSTURING FOR AN NFL PARTNERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With six months to put together a single Los
Angeles football franchise bid, rival camps made tentative
overtures Wednesday about opening what promise to be difficult
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the New Coliseum Partners and Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas voiced confidence their proposal to remodel the
Coliseum would be successful and urged competitor Michael Ovitz,
the entertainment agent, to join them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Magic Johnson, who is part of the Ovitz team's
plan to build a stadium and mall in Carson, said he believed the
two groups should join forces as soon as possible _ even before an
NFL site selection committee comes out within the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have unity and soon,'' Johnson said. ``I think in
the next week or so we can have some talks. Everyone brings
something to the table, If we join forces, we are stronger than if
we are apart.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, NFL owners agreed to award a franchise but set tough
conditions for a unified proposal, finalized financial support and
broad public and business support under a six-month timetable or
the franchise would be awarded to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The decision pressured both bidders in Los Angeles to begin
talks but Ovitz aide Peter Levin said no timetable has been set.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, we are thrilled for Los Angeles,'' Levin
said. ``We achieved this part of the goal collectively. We are
taking our lead from league officials and look forward to discuss
the procedures for the next step as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson reminded officials that Ovitz and Ridley-Thomas had
worked together early on in trying to see professional football
back in the city, but broke ranks when Ovitz became convinced the
league would not place a third professional football team in the
Coliseum after the experiences of the Rams and the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would take that much to get us working
together again,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Eli Broad and Ed Roski of the New
Coliseum partners said they would do whatever it takes to see
football returned _ including a surrender of its exclusive
negotiating rights for the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to say that we want it at the Coliseum and if
they have another group, we're not going to stand in the way,''
Broad said in a telephone interview from New York City. ``If
someone wants to pay more and is local, we won't stand in the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   As for joining forces with Ovitz and food magnate Ron Burkle,
Broad described himself as a friend of both men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see them part of this,'' Broad said. ``I have
said that all along.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step, he added, is for the Coliseum to be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once that happens, I am convinced the ownership group will
expand to show the NFL there is the support for a football team
here,'' Broad said.
</P>
<P>
   John Semcken, who represents Roski, said he didn't anticipate a
problem over the exclusivity agreement that the Coliseum gave
Roski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal is to have a strong local ownership group that's
concerned about Los Angeles,'' Semcken said. ``We've been burned
before and we want to make sure the new owners _ whether it's us or
someone else _ (are) committed to the city and what's best for our
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Semcken said Roski and Broad were prepared to make sure the NFL
doesn't feel it is being forced to select them as the new owners of
an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is solely the NFL's decision to decide who its partners are
going to be as a new owner,'' Semcken said.
</P>
<P>
   David Carter, a principal with the Sports Business Group that
works on professional sports, said he sees it as important for the
two sides to resolve any differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL doesn't want to get involved in local politics, but
any local bickering would be of concern to the owners,'' Carter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ridley-Thomas said he was convinced professional football would
return to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began this two years ago and no one said we stood a
chance,'' he said. ``Now, we've come full circle and the Coliseum
is now the logical choice. The Coliseum is Los Angeles. It is an
institution with significant sports history.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
