<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S GOMEZ UNLIKELY TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The topic hasn't been mentioned much because she's
just a junior athletically. But Erica Gomez might not be long for
the UCLA women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, the Bruins' point guard, is considering this season to be
her last.
</P>
<P>
   First, she is a senior academically and will graduate in June.
Second, she misses her New Jersey home.
</P>
<P>
   Third, she doesn't expect the WNBA to come calling because she
didn't have the breakout season she wanted. She averaged 7.4 points
and seven assists per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a role player,'' she said, ``and I don't
imagine people saying, `Oh, she could do so much for a WNBA team.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she recognizes the NCAA Tournament, in which the Bruins
play Colorado State in a Sweet 16 matchup Saturday at the Sports
Arena, is a place where stock can rise in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   After the season ends, she will meet and discuss her future with
coach Kathy Olivier. Gomez said Olivier, who was unavailable for
comment, knows of the situation and has been grooming Crescenta
Valley High graduate Michelle Greco to take over and recruiting a
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I graduate in June either way,'' Gomez said. ``They know my
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Only organized games, please: Maylana Martin leads the Bruins
with an 18.6-point and a 9.3-rebound average, but she's no gym rat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play, but I don't like pickup games,'' she said.
``All the other girls will go to the Wooden Center, but I won't.''
</P>
<P>
   The origins of her disdain are twofold. As an eighth-grader, she
played in a park and blocked a guy's shot.
</P>
<P>
   The next time down the court, she went up for the shot and he
tackled her.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as a post player, Martin's game relies on her receiving
passes from teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to do that in a pickup game?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   All alone: The players realize they're the only Pacific-10 team
_ men or women _ to remain alive in the NCAAs (The Cal and Oregon
men are still in the NIT).
</P>
<P>
   Yet what they hear around campus isn't praise for the
accomplishment. Rather, it's surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear, `Wow! Can you believe it? The women's team is the
only one left,' '' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Post player Carly Funicello can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me, `In three years, you'll be better
than the men,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance woes: The Bruins thought winning would fill Pauley
Pavilion. Instead, less than 3,000 turned out for each of the two
games there. ESPN showed the near-empty arena several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we have to do,'' Martin said. ``We're
winning, but that's not the answer. Maybe we have to start dunking
or shave our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that the two games started at 9 p.m. and UCLA
markets itself to children.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA tickets available: As of Wednesday evening, 4,300 tickets
had been sold for this weekend's NCAA West Regional finals at the
Sports Arena. Lower-level tickets can be purchased for Saturday's
and Monday's games for $30, which covers both sessions. Upper-level
seats are $25. Youth tickets for children ages 12-and-under are
$12. For information, call (213) 740-GOSC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
