<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA'S  CINDERELLA ERA OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - College basketball shimmers on the surface. But like
the rest of the student-athlete mirage, it's best to avoid the
crawl space and closets.
</P>
<P>
   It works on the floor, not under the microscope. Not with forged
homework and coaches who view ethics as a pack of chewing gum, and
the guy who blows the biggest bubble wins. Not with point-shaving
scandals, on-line gambling, Proposition 16.
</P>
<P>
   Yet amid the weeds, a flower has sprouted. And it's no mistake,
no great upset that a few unexpected outfits have arrived at
America West Arena. They are simply the petals of parity popping up
in the strangest places.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State. Miami of Ohio. Florida of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa. Oklahoma. And the quirkiest of all, Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Florida Coach Billy Donovan warned. ``Gonzaga will be a
top 20 team next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA would like to take credit for this, and in some ways,
it can. The proliferation of conference tournaments probably helped
toughen up Iowa, Ohio State, Purdue and Michigan State. And the
lack of one is probably why the Pac-10 plummeted like a paper
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   A reduction in scholarships from 15 to 13 has helped spread the
wealth and is the only reason that Gonzaga's Matt Santangelo is
here and Stanford is out of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they reduced scholarships, big schools couldn't take
everybody,'' Gonzaga Coach Dan Monson said. ``If there were still
15 scholarships, Matt would be at Stanford today. It was between
him and Arthur Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   But a part of it is dumb luck. And for all the hand-wringing
about underclassmen who bolt for the NBA, the steppingstone
mentality pervasive in college basketball might have its benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The great players go to the signa ture schools. They leave
before unpacking their hot plates. After a while, the dynasties are
ruptured, if not disbanded. And while it happens, the continuity in
lesser programs narrows the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Dean Smith would've hung around if Kobe Bryant wanted a
diploma. Michigan would've made the tournament with a senior named
Kevin Garnett. Kansas would look a lot different with the presence
of Paul Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the dominant college players staying in school
a very long time,'' said Donovan, a former Princeton star, part of
an era when Cinderella lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, the guys that were hardship would only leave after
their junior year. I remember Pearl Washington leaving Syracuse
after his junior year, and that was about it. Now, you have guys
going directly from high school to the pros, and the ones who don't
stay one year, maybe two.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is any lack of suspense surrounding the tournament, any
reason why the television ratings are down, it's because of an
impending coronation. But Duke is largely an anomaly, a superstar
blip, the kind of team that's almost impossible to build these
days. The other 63 you can put in a hopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard someone say we were the team that rolled through the
Big East Tournament,'' Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun said. ``He
must've missed that Thursday when we beat Seton Hall 57-56.''
</P>
<P>
   And who'd have thought that, in order to reach the Elite Eight,
Florida would have to beat Pennsylvania, Weber State and Gonzaga?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's parity all the way through college
basketball,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in terms of glamour appeal, we could've done better.
We could've landed Stanford and North Carolina and called it a home
run. But that's not reality any longer.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, the combined seeding of the four teams totals 22. In
the East, it's 29. In the Midwest, it's 27.
</P>
<P>
   So pick a team. Cheer for Iowa and Dr. Tom Davis before the exit
door hits him in the backside. He is worth cheering for, a lame
duck coach getting pushed out of a job at age 60, involved in a
messy spat with his own administration. On Tuesday, they finally
got around to sending Davis and his kids a note of congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Or be a Gon-Zagnut, a team that comes closest to the glass
slipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you have to give us a label because you've never
heard about us before,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for Cinderella.
</P>
<P>
   She's gone. Entered the draft a few years ago. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
