<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-ELLIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALE ELLIS GIVING SONICS, AND YOUNGER DEFENDERS, ALL THEY WANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dale Ellis' career-high in scoring is 53 points. The
most field goals he ever made in 48 minutes is 20, and nine is his
single-game high for 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the Sonics' veteran swingman recently demand the game
ball for connecting on the only shot he took during a win at
Chicago?
</P>
<P>
   ``I took one shot and was happy,'' Ellis said. ``They tried to
take (the ball) away from me, but I brought it back to Seattle. I
had one shot and made it. I was happy we won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning is all that matters to Ellis these days.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about the torrid streak he's sewed together from 3-point
land, and Ellis is unimpressed. He's hit 23 of his last 39 treys
(59 percent), yet Ellis says, ``I'm not shooting the way I want to
shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about cracking the starting lineup at small forward, and
Ellis is indifferent. He often jokes about his distaste for
starting because there aren't as many shots playing with Vin Baker
and Gary Payton, whereas he can be the first or second option off
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a young player anymore,'' he said. ``I don't care if I
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings you to Ellis' age. He is 38 years old and shooting
so well that every night he dares a youngster to match his
productivity. Sonics coach Paul Westphal doesn't know if he will
ever repress Ellis' role.
</P>
<P>
   For as much that has been made about Vin Baker's resurrection,
the Sonics feel lucky to have the oldest starter in the league. Ask
Ellis about that, and he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to re-do my contract,'' the 15-year veteran joked.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Ellis has been money well spent by the Sonics this
season, especially since he's been thrust into a starting role
because of Billy Owens' knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis will likely start even when Owens gets healthy. As for
there not being enough shots for him with the starters, that's
bogus, says Westphal, who is amazed by Ellis' productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always want to look for him. I hate to see him open and not
get the ball,'' Westphal said. ``He's proven that he delivers. So
if you have a shooter with his abilities, you want to set picks for
him and you want to put in him position where his man has to help,
where he'll get shots. We want to play to everybody's strength, and
his strength is certainly evident.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games he's started, Ellis has averaged nearly 16
points, shooting 52 percent from the floor and making 6 of 10
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 games, which included three starts, Ellis has
made 46 of 92 shots (50 percent) overall and 26 of 46 3-pointers
(56 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in with the attitude that I'd play any role I was asked
to play,'' Ellis said. ``I'm not a young player who's looking to
get minutes and points to prove himself. My concern is winning
basketball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the fact that his family is rooted here, Ellis still
sees Seattle as the place to win a title. His best chance was
during his first year with the 1986-87 Sonics, who lost to the L.A.
Lakers in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ellis' deft shooting is almost as much of a fixture
here as the Space Needle. From 1986-91, he played his best
basketball in a Sonics uniform when he averaged 24.6 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   He was a big part of the team's 61-win season a year ago. And
before Ellis signed a three-year contract this past offseason, he
had several suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Portland pursued the sharp shooter hard. And when the Sonics
played the Lakers at KeyArena last month, Del Harris, who then
coached the Lakers, told Ellis how interested they were this
pastoff season but couldn't work out the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to finish here,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis credits Westphal's offensive philosophy for invigorating
him this season. Under Westphal, everyone on the floor has the
green light to shoot if open. Westphal's concern is playing Ellis
too many minutes.
</P>
<P>
   No worry, Ellis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still at the point where I actually feel like if I'm
contributing during the course of a game, I can run all day and not
get tired,'' he said. ``I get tired when I run up and down the
court, and I feel like I'm just out there. I felt like that a lot
last year. But it's a lot easier to knock down shots knowing you're
going to get X amount of shots and knowing you're going to get
plays run for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun, and I'm enjoying winning.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Owens scrimmaged with the team Wednesday for the first
time in four days, but his status is day-to-day and he remains
doubtful for Friday's game at Golden State because of a sore left
knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
