<HEADER>
A4836 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-PLAYERS-AZR &LR;      03-18 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-PLAYERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WEST MIGHT BE WON: KEEP EYE ON THESE PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As much as the team concept is paramount in college
basketball, we can't help but keep our eyes fixed on that special
player, the one or two (or in Duke's case, seven or eight) who
stand out, either through sheer talent, sheer will or a combination
of both. Individuals, in other words, who make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gonzaga has 10 players and all of them play. The
you-can-call-them-the-Zags-but-don't-call-them-Cinderella Bulldogs
might be as balanced as anyone in the Sweet 16. Four of their
players made All-West Coast Conference. But they have come this far
largely on the strength of their guards, Matt Santangelo and
Quentin Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, which plays Gonzaga tonight in the first game at
America West Arena, is sort of the same. Ten players average at
least 10 minutes a game. Five score in double figures. The Gators
are known for talented freshmen like Mike Miller and Teddy Dupay.
But for inspiration and leadership, they look toward senior guard
Eddie Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration and leadership? Iowa is loaded with seniors, and one
of them, forward Jess Settles, is in graduate school and his sixth
season of eligibility after battling back from injuries. Another
senior, guard Kent McCausland, is a deadly three-point shooter who
helped bring the Hawkeyes back last week against Arkansas. But for
youthful spark and flash, the Hawkeyes have sophomore point guard
Dean Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's opponent in the second game, Connecticut, is the most
talented team in the field. Who stands out? Let's see. Forward
Richard Hamilton is a first-team All-American. Point guard Khalid
El-Amin runs the show with flair. Forward Kevin Freeman is as solid
as Camelback Mountain. Center Jake Voskuhl provides the inside
presence and guard Ricky Moore is a nasty defender. The bench is
pretty good, too.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, a 6-foot-1 junior, leads Gonzaga in assists and is
No. 2 in scoring. But he had to withstand a difficult switch from
the point to off-guard because Hall turned out to be so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I understood that role and I accepted it, that's when I
started to have more success as a player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is a 5-8 senior, a Bahamas native who somehow found his way
first to North Idaho College and then to Yakima Valley College in
Washington state before ending up in Spokane, Wash. He started just
one game last year. But he improved so much, learning to harness
his quickness, he forced his way into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken Quentin almost a year and a half to get comfortable
to where we don't have a point guard and we don't have an
off-guard,'' Gonzaga Coach Dan Monson said. ``We have two good
guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon averages 6.8 points a game, but forget that. Look
instead at his team-high 132 assists and his 50 steals that put him
atop the school career chart. Then look past those numbers at
what's inside.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-11 senior, Shannon is blind in his right eye. He was hit
with a rock while in the seventh grade, and his vision slowly
deteriorated. In October, he was fitted with a prosthesis. Last
week, he earned a national award for courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``His accomplishments,'' Florida Coach Billy Donovan said, ``are
completely unheard of.''
</P>
<P>
   One who did hear about Shannon when he was a star at Cardinal
Newman High School in West Palm Beach, Fla., was Arizona Coach Lute
Olson, who offered Shannon a scholarship. Shannon accepted. Then he
made one last visit, to Florida. And then he changed his mind. So
Olson offered the scholarship intended for Shannon to a Seattle kid
named Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything worked out,'' Shannon said. ``Those guys (Arizona)
were very successful. We struggled a couple of years, but we're at
the point now where anything can happen, and we're playing good
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   McCausland, the gunner, and Settles, the foot soldier, are
wrapping up their Iowa careers along with deposed Coach Tom Davis.
Whoever replaces Davis will inherit an emerging star, Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Denver, Oliver raised himself from the near-dead,
overcoming the flu to rack up 15 points and six assists in 19
minutes as the Hawkeyes beat Alabama-Birmingham in the first round.
Healthier two days later, he had 17 points, four assists and just
two turnovers in a helter-skelter game as Iowa beat Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver also put his signature on the game with a 360-degree
spin, behind-the-back, half-court pass to Settles that resulted in
a big basket down the stretch. It was a dead-solid play of the
week, replayed countless times. But Oliver, a 5-11 sophomore,
watched it only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that impressed,'' he said, laughing. ``It didn't seem
like anything no one else could do. It was just a
spur-of-the-moment move.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn is the team of the moment. Everyone knows about Hamilton,
the slashing scorer, and El-Amin, the animated, flashy floor
leader. Freeman is someone you should know about, too. Points?
Rebounds? Defense?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the team needs on that given day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A junior, Freeman is a healthy 6-7, 235-pounds. But he sometimes
labored in his teammates' shadows. Not in the Big East Tournament,
though, when he was named Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most underrated players in the country,''
Hamilton said. ``Without him, we wouldn't have won as many games as
we won. He does a lot of things.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
