<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-SHORT-TIMERS     03-18 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-SHORT-TIMERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY DEPAR TURES TO NBA TAKE BIG TOLL ON CONTENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't have to be Duke and the Little 63.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA tournament could have had several title contenders _
Wally's World is a nice little story, but champions? Come on. _ had
underclassmen not dashed for the big cash.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit 1: North Carolina. The Tar Heels likely would have been
as feared as the Blue Devils had Antawn Jamison and Vince Carter
not turned pro early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Duke would have beaten North Carolina by 20 on
North Carolina's floor,'' said Suns Senior Executive Vice President
Cotton Fitzsimmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this: Duke wouldn't have beaten (North Carolina) three
times,'' Arizona State Coach Rob Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels, knocked out of the West Regional by Weber State
in a first-round upset, aren't the only team damaged by
underclassmen turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit 2: Kansas. The Jayhawks were ousted in the second round.
They seemingly would still be playing if they still had forward
Paul Pierce, who could wind up as the NBA Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit 3: Arizona. If Mike Bibby stays past his sophomore year,
the chances of the Wildcats being stunned by Oklahoma in the first
round grow much more remote.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for an explanation of why the tournament has followed
such a wacky course so far this year? You may have hit upon
something here.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the upsets going on this season, you can trace some
of them to the early departures of college players to the NBA,'' UA
Coach Lute Olson said. ``There has been a lot of change in the
rosters of some of the traditional powers, and it has made for a
tournament that is more unpredictable than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Unpredictable isn't the word.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight of the top 16 seeds remain in the NCAA tournament,
the fewest since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Three No. 10 seeds still are alive, including Gonzaga, which
plays Florida in a West Region semifinal round game tonight at
America West Arena. The other No. 10 seeds still playing are Purdue
and Miami (Ohio), led by Wally ``World'' Szczerbiak, who scored 67
points in his first two NCAA Tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think reality has quite set in that we're still one of
16 schools playing while North Carolina, Utah, Stanford and UCLA
are home,'' Gonzaga guard Ryan Floyd said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami, Southwest Missouri State _ we're all in this together.
We're clearly for each other. We're the underdogs. Everyone pulls
for the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   The underdogs aren't all young pups.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga starts two seniors and two juniors. Miami of Ohio starts
three seniors and two juniors. Southwest Missouri State doesn't
have a sophomore or a freshman in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, meanwhile, replaced Jamison and Carter in its
lineup with freshmen Kris Lang and Jeff Capel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be a veteran team if those guys still were here,'' Tar
Heels Coach Bill Guthridge said. ``Without them, we're awfully
young. I think our freshman have done great, but they're
freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Evans said top-ranked Duke has dominated college
basketball this year because the Blue Devils have been able to
``keep their kids longer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have experience, that's what is going to win,''
Evans said. ``When we went to Mississippi, we said we were going to
recruit kids who were not high-profile kids but would keep them
four years. We started three freshmen and two sophomores at
Mississippi. Three of those freshman now are seniors. They won
because they started 100 games. There's nothing they came up
against they hadn't seen.
</P>
<P>
   ```When you're talking about a guy going through a conference
situation three or four years, he knows how to play like a coach.
Football has proven that. They try to redshirt all freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Coach Billy Donovan, who plays Gonzaga tonight, can
relate. He was an assistant at Kentucky when Coach Rick Pitino
signed one of the nation's top recruiting classes there in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our class of Tony Delk, Roderick Rhodes, Walter McCarty was
(rated) top five in the country,'' Donovan said. ``Then, Rick
Pitino says to me, `This class is better than Michigan's Fab 5.' I
said, `What? There's no Juwon Howard or Chris Webber in this
class.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You're right. These kids have to stick together.
They'll be there four years.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right. Four years later, we won a national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of Gonzaga's players were blue-chip recruits. But they've
meshed as they've stayed together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not spoiled,'' Evans said. ``They work hard. They
surpass the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northern Arizona (a 20-win team for the second consecutive
year) was an example of this. It was an experienced basketball
team, not tremendously talented. They have guys who can shoot the
basketball, guys who can defend. They can't do it all, but they can
do enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, who was coaching Kansas State when the Suns hired
him the first time in 1970, said he wouldn't enjoy coaching at a
big-time college program today.
</P>
<P>
   ``You recruit a kid now and hope he stays two years,''
Fitzsimmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mighty Blue Devils could be affected by the early
exits.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that sophomore center Elton Brand will
turn pro after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senior draft in the NBA has been depleted,'' Fitzsimmons
said. ``So if the senior draft has been depleted, the college game
has to be hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
