r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-GONZAGA-AZR &LR;      03-18 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-GONZAGA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA SEEKS A LITTLE RESPECT  
 ZAGS HAVE ODD NAME, GOOD GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In this under-appreciated, over-achieving world of
little guys, where respect is gained with proper enunciations and
knowing your geography, Florida, meet Gonzaga, your West Regional
semifinal opponent tonight.
</P>
<P>
   No, not ``ahg'' but ``aga,'' as in Zag.
</P>
<P>
   As Coach Dan Monson left the podium at America West Arena during
Wednesday's news conference, he again reminded everybody how to
pronounce Gonzaga, which he also did a lot in Seattle in the first
two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse Florida Coach Billy Donovan if his Long Island accent
gets in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from New York, and I still pronounce Florida with an `er'
at the end,'' said Donovan, in his third year as the school's
coach. ``Maybe it's motivation for them, but we've got respect for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the way you say their name has any bearing on
the respect level.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, the Gators (22-8) know all about 10th-seed Gonzaga _
that it's from Spokane, Wash., that it's the smallest school left
in the NCAA Tournament, that it has never gotten this far, that it
has won 27 games, that it has made 38 of 72 three-pointers in its
past three games, that it knocked off No. 2 seed Stanford to get
here, that much of the nation is behind it.
</P>
<P>
   They've gone over film. They see a smart, good-shooting team
that shows heart on the boards and feeds off the crowd's emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we've got a great challenge, going against a very
good basketball team,'' Donovan said. ``We need to focus on trying
to win than, `Wow, why aren't people talking more about us?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Attention comes with advancement, and Florida (22-8), the sixth
seed, which has advanced to the Sweet 16 for the third time in its
history, can't complain about how the tournament has unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, led by a talented trio of freshmen, have yet to face
a team with a higher seed. They avoided North Carolina in the
second round, thanks to Weber State and Harold Arceneaux. Now, they
get another lower-seeded team in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, you can take seedings and throw them out the
window,'' Donovan said. ``All I think seedings are for is who wears
the light and who wears the dark uniforms.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be needed to tell these teams apart. Both average
about 80 points a game. Both teams are 10 deep. Both feed off the
three-point arc. Both love to get up and down the court.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags have made 274 threes, behind Richie Frahm (87 threes),
Matt Santangelo (62) and Quentin Hall (52).
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, led by forward Mike Miller and guard Teddy Dupay,
have averaged 12.5 threes in their last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have incredible similarities,'' Monson said. ``Both are
superior shooting teams with tremendous skill players. Both can
step out four guys that can shoot quality threes. We are two of the
more skilled teams as far as being offensively skilled at all five
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   With 6-foot-7, 260-pound freshman Udonis Haslem giving the
Gators an inside presence, and senior guard Eddie Shannon, the
school's career steals leader, Florida will try to use its depth
and athleticism to wear down the Bulldogs with a relentless press
for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that our depth of playing 10 guys every game will help
us,'' Monson said. ``It's certainly a concern to me, because, in
our league, we've been this invincible team that can't be pressed
with two point guards (Hall and Santangelo) on the floor at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been challenged with full-court pressure much this
year at all. Whether we're good at it or not, we haven't had a lot
of repetitions at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga's a team that feels there should be no ``Cinderella''
tag to its journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like you don't believe and you're kind of lucky to
be here, that it's kind of magical that it's happening,'' Monson
said. ``Our kids don't believe that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
