<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJERUS HAS STANDARDS TEST WITH A TWIST FOR ALL RECRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Squatting in the middle of a semi-circle of reporters,
Rick Majerus was dispensing, Buddha-like, his wisdom on college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the NCAA basketball tournament last week in New
Orleans' Superdome, the Utah coach was holding forth on the
consequences of the end of Proposition 16, the college-sports rule
that precludes freshmen from competing if their SAT or ACT scores
are below minimums.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial rule was struck down last week in Philadelphia
by a federal judge who said that it had ``unjustified disparate
impact'' on African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have long contended that use of standardized tests as
primary filters for athletic participation were racially biased
because the athletes often came from impoverished schools that left
them ill-prepared to handle national tests.
</P>
<P>
   Majerus was citing the example of Andre Miller, his All-America
guard who had to sit out his first year because of a low SAT score,
which prevented some schools from even recruiting him. But since
Utah's rules allow acceptance of a non-qualifier, Miller blossomed
as a student and player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre Miller is a good guy, a good C student who will lead a
happy life and impact those around him,'' said Majerus, taking the
standard poignant coaching theme of hailing kids who are saved by
sports after surmounting what is popularly viewed as NCAA-imposed
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   Majerus advocated that each school set standards according to
its own ``academic mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that there are a number of schools
whose ``academic mission'' is to get Billy Packer to talk about
them on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   With vague or absent academic minimums _ which is exactly the
case at the moment, pending appeals of the court ruling _ there is
little stopping unscrupulous programs from getting the gnarliest,
thuggiest guys fresh from prison to fetch rebounds and 14th seeds.
</P>
<P>
   If these ``student athletes'' wash out academically after the
tournament, what the heck _ they would have gone to the NBA anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Even the supposedly scrupulous programs, such as the University
of Minnesota, seem to have a hard time with the student part of the
``student athlete'' phrase, unless their mission is to have the
smartest academic support staff money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Majerus what, in the absence of the now-invalidated
standards, he proposed would keep schools from signing up
illiterates, reprobates and other dubious characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the newspapers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers?
</P>
<P>
   Us? Me?
</P>
<P>
   In charge of policing academic standards at Division I jock
factories?
</P>
<P>
   Gee, I can't wait for the chance to tell Bobby Knight that,
according to my standards, he needs to boot two juniors and a
sophomore from his Indiana team. And while I'm in the mood, maybe
I'll wear a meat hat into a tiger cage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the notion of being cop on the admissions beat is
intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``Young man, I'm spotting you the C and the A, and
I want you to give me the third letter that spells a furry
four-legged pet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, how 'bout X?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. Sorry. Here's your admission forms to Washington State.
If you'd given me a D, M, P, or T _ anything that made a real word
_ you coulda been a Husky.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   As fair and exacting a standard as that test is, it still
wouldn't be enough. Here are one newspaper's standards that require
the prospective recruit to demonstrate aptitude in multiple
disciplines that would project to successful completion of a
Division I college career:
</P>
<P>
   English: Complete every sentence with at least one of three
fundamental phrases: ``You know,'' ``Know what I'm sayin'?'' and
``It was God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   Health sciences: When the drug test comes back positive, develop
the psychomotor skills to self-induce a case of asthma and forge a
prescription to justify the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Civics: Identify all highway signage at least by color, if not
words.
</P>
<P>
   Geography: When identified as the father, the ability to quickly
produce phone numbers of a doctor and a lawyer in a distant town.
</P>
<P>
   Economics: When shaving points for the frat-boy bookie, master
the distinctions between the fundamental doctrines that govern the
capitalist model: Over-under or win-loss.
</P>
<P>
   Mathematics: Break down a 64-team bracket so that one of the
regions gets a Gonzaga (trick question _ it's an impossibility).
</P>
<P>
   Psychology: Understanding of the dysfunctional patterns implicit
in the coaching behavior signaled by the phrase: ``I have no
intention of leaving this fine institution for another job.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, the thoughtful Majerus, instead of lamenting a
potentially disastrous development for college basketball, has come
upon a grand solution: Calling upon the fourth estate to set fair,
practical, common-sense standards, developed at the local level
consistent to the institution's academic mission as well as the
student-athlete's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Hedges, the P-I is at your service.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
