r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-REDWINGS-     03-18 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-REDWINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES BEAT THE BUZZER  
 TKACHUK SCORES WINNER WITH :01 REMAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ They started their new goaltender. They skated a new
player they just signed earlier in the day as a free agent. And
they showcased entirely new lines from top to bottom because seven
regulars were out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Why, the Coyotes even were kind enough to wear their new green
uniforms Wednesday night against the Detroit Red Wings, which was
appropriate considering they were playing on St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Not another same old loss, if you can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The new-look Coyotes looked a lot like their early-season selves
during their fist-pumping, 4-3 victory over the two-time defending
Stanley Cup champions, a win punctuated by Keith Tkachuk's dramatic
game-winning goal with just one second left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   It took a lot of the sting away from the 7-2 disastrous loss
they suffered just two weeks ago against these same Red Wings, who
got star center Sergei Fedorov back from a five-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge, just a huge win for the club,'' said Tkachuk,
whose 29th goal was his seventh game-winner of the season, one shy
of his franchise record. ``It was a game where we had control, they
had control, and right before we scored, Mike (goalie Mikhail
Shtalenkov) made some big saves and we came down a catch a break
there and Jeremy makes an unbelievable pass to me.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly beating Shtalenkov in close, Detroit's Vyacheslav
Kozlov, who scored twice earlier, turned the puck over in the
waning seconds. Roenick scooped it up and started a rush with
Tkachuk streaking in on his left on goalie Norm Maracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about taking the shot myself,'' Roenick said, ``but
I had to push it wide and then I saw Keith battling to gain
position and as soon as his stick went on the ice, I zipped it over
and he made a great play by putting it in.''
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 19,983 _ the 100th consecutive
regular-season full house at Joe Louis Arena _ let out a deafening,
collective moan as Maracle tumbled and the puck hit the back of the
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``One second left? Man, that's like a last-second field goal in
the NFL or a last-second shot in the NBA,'' Coyotes forward Rick
Tocchet. ``Very rarely, though, do you see a guy score in the last
second in hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov, getting his first start and first action in goal
since being acquired earlier this month from the Edmonton Oilers,
stopped 28 shots for his first win in nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' he said. ``I wasn't playing for a while, I
was nervous before the game, and it just feels good to get the
first one in the first game. Especially in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (33-24-11), who acquired veteran NHL forward Brian
Noonan Wednesday morning, now head into St. Louis for a game
tonight against the Blues with some much-needed momentum. They are
2-0-1 in their past three games after losing 11 of their previous
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great play by Jeremy and if you give Tkachuk enough
opportunities, he's going to find the back of the net,'' Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said, noting Tkachuk put a game-high eight shots on
goal. ``But this was a team effort. . . . It's a win in dramatic
fashion, but the most important ingredient for me is how the
players hung in there for each other. They refused to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look promising early. During the first shift of the
game, Coyotes defenseman Teppo Numminen went down in a heap after
getting high sticked in the face. The inadvertent stick drew blood,
but no penalty from referee Dan Marouelli.
</P>
<P>
   Numminen returned and toughed it out, but the Coyotes, playing
Detroit for the last time in the regular season, were slumping
their shoulders soon afterward when Kozlov buried a tic-tac-toe
play set up by Doug Brown and Igor Larionov just 1:38 into the game
for a 1-0 Detroit lead. Shtalenkov never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes tied it when Mike Sullivan screened Maracle on a
Mike Stapleton slap-shot goal and then went up when Bob Corkum fed
Greg Adams for a picturesque deke move. The Red Wings countered,
however, with two goals of their own, a power play score by Niklas
Lidstrom and a four-on-four tally by Kozlov.
</P>
<P>
   After blowing a lengthy two-man advantage late in the second
period, Numminen bailed out the Coyotes with an early third-period
score. Then the Red Wings, playing without suspended forward Kirk
Maltby, had a goal disallowed when captain Steve Yzerman was caught
in the crease on a deflection by Brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
