<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-PING-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IFFY GREENS GIVE TOURNEY NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Competing earlier this week in a pre-tournament event
for the Standard Register PING, defending champion Liselotte
Neumann was attempting a bunker shot almost identical to one she
had a year earlier on the 18th hole in a playoff against Rosie
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have forgotten, the Swede looked like a goner
against Jones in the 1998 tournament but managed a spectacular
blast to within 3 inches of the cup to save par and prolong the
playoff, which Neumann won on the third extra hole.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, Neumann's sand shot went whizzing by the
cup. Naturally, the circumstances were much different, but Juli
Inkster had a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, this is not the same green that Lotta won the tournament
on last year,'' Inkster said.
</P>
<P>
   She's right. Not only is the 18th green at Moon Valley Country
Club brand, spanking new, so are two others _ the 14th and the
15th, a hole that has been scaled down from a par 4 to a par 3.
</P>
<P>
   Add the other 15 greens at ``the Moon'' into the equation, all
of which are suffering to some degree from poa annua, patchwork and
other problems, this could be a whole new tournament for the next
four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's more of a big hitter's course,'' said Neumann,
meaning this will not be a putting contest. ``You still have to
make the 3- and 4-footers, which is difficult when the greens
aren't great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from tee to green, the fairways are good. And the rough is
up, which will make hitting the fairways just that more
challenging. It should be a very interesting tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb, an Australian who has been tearing it up this
season with two victories behind an incredible 68.42 scoring
average, agrees that the spotty putting surfaces might put more of
a premium on that portion of the short game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get disheartened out here,'' Webb warned. ``If you
put a good stroke on it and it doesn't go in, that's golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb said accuracy, as well as power, will play a big part in
who wins the $127,500 first prize on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've mowed the greens (down), so you have to be a good
irons player,'' Webb said. ``And the rough is longer, so it's
important to be on the short grass (fairways).''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the greens at Moon Valley are much better than they
were a month ago. Still, there are some areas on the putting
surfaces that would be deemed as ``ground under repair'' if the
blight wasn't on the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are pretty bumpy, even the new ones,'' Webb said. ``But I
don't see the winning score being too much different than last year
(13 under). Someone is going to be able to putt on these greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. All of the 144 players who are entered here will
have to roll the ball on the same 18 greens. And with the way the
pros on the LPGA are lighting it up these days, how low can you go
will still be the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the stronger players will be at an advantage,'' said
Inkster, last week's winner in Tucson. ``I think you're going to
have to hit it really good and stay out of the bunkers because the
ball tends to plug, and that's an automatic bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably looking at the usual suspects. I can get it
going here, and Karrie and Kelly (Robbins) hit it real long, which
is what you need to play this course. Annika (Sorenstam) is always
up there, and Laura (Davies) always plays well here. But any player
who gets the right bounces has a good shot to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is an authority on Moon Valley, it's Davies, who had
her streak of four straight Standard Register PING titles snapped
last year, when she finished 6 shots back after blowing sky high in
the second round with a 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing better than my scores suggest, but putting remains
the problem,'' Davies said. ``I've made every cut this year _ lo
and behold, I even made the cut in Tucson last week. So I could win
on any given weekend, and this course gives me a better chance of
doing that than most because of its length (6,292 yards).''
</P>
<P>
   But win, lose or draw, the substandard greens will not be an
excuse for the big-hitting Brit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny,'' Davies said of the greens, which will
undergo a renovation once the tournament ends, a makeover that will
temporarily send the tournament to a yet-to-be-named course next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard all of these horror stories about them, and they're
really not all that bad. They're a little inconsistent because of
the mix of old and new. But if this was Europe, these would be
great greens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
