<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA'S MONSON HAS SEEN IT ALL AS COACH'S SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Forgive Dan Monson if he does not demonstrate the
requisite high level of ``gee whiz'' considering where he is right
now.
</P>
<P>
   You might think a second-year head coach who has brought his
talented and determined Gonzaga University team to the Sweet 16 of
the NCAA tournament might be gushing, floating, happy just to be
here in the West Region that appears set to send mighty UConn to
the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But the poise and the temperament of Gonzaga's coach have been
forged to withstand extreme elements. That's what happens when you
are the son of a coach, the way Dan Monson is.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially what happens when, after 34 years of coaching,
your dad gets fired, the way Don Monson did at the University of
Oregon in 1992, all but ending a coaching life that began in 1958
at Cheney High.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the elder Monson moved to Pasco High, then to
Michigan State as an assistant to Judd Heathcote, then to Idaho for
five years before, finally, in 1983, he landed in Eugene, where Don
Monson got his biggest break, heading up a Pac-10 program.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dream fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Then, nine years after, it was a dream busted.
</P>
<P>
   Don Monson's fracture with Oregon grew more ugly when he sued
the school for all income he would have earned through radio and
shoe endorsements as well as his salary.
</P>
<P>
   He initially won his case, and a jury awarded him nearly
$300,000. However, he lost the case on appeal and ``I was left with
the lawyer's bill,'' Monson recalled Wednesday, talking as he
waited for his son's team to finish practice at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, he finds it difficult talking about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no qualms about the firing. I did not have good years
my last few years. But what sticks in my craw was what happened
with my contract. I had two years left and I felt that should have
been honored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Former Oregon star) Terrell Brandon went to the pros after
his junior year, and during my last season I lost three starters to
stress fractures,'' Monson said, offering reasons why the Ducks
faltered his last season especially.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fallout and the legal struggle over the contract were
so painful, you can still see it on Don Monson's face to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand. Until you walk in that person's
moccasins, you don't know. My son knows that. The anguish and pain
you go through as a family, only those who have been through it
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The son, now 37, carries his father's lessons inside him like
blood.
</P>
<P>
   That might be why Dan Monson has so coolly handled everything
this NCAA tournament has thrown at him. First, there was all that
conjecture that Gonzaga's first-round win over Minnesota was aided
by the suspension of four Gopher players. Monson did not let any of
that throw him or his players out of whack. In fact, Monson came
back with a rock-solid game plan that knocked out second-seeded
Stanford last Saturday at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be my second year as a head coach, but this is about
my 25th year of knowing the ups and downs of the profession,'' Dan
Monson said Wednesday, on the eve of Gonzaga's tournament matchup
against Florida _ one that has the nation crying ``Cinderella'' at
Monson and Gonzaga despite convincing whipping of the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that, yeah, this is a great time, but I have been on
the other side, living through those, too, as the son of a coach,''
Monson said. ``So I think I am more cautious during these good
times. Likewise, I think I will be able to handle the down sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, who never made it to the NCAA tournament, Dan
Monson is here so quick he is careful to take pleasure in it. He
knows 20 years could go by without another taste like this. There
are no promises.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the father, years ago, tried to warn the son off
from this intense, unsettling, crazy profession of high risk and
reward. Don Monson told his son to find another way to make a
living. He applauded Dan's decision to declare his college major in
math.
</P>
<P>
   That was even well before 1992, when the worst thing that can
happen to a coach happened to Don Monson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. My father very seriously told me not to go into
coaching. He said it's not a good profession to raise a family. He
said financially it can be very difficult. He said you have too
many other avenues you can go down,'' Dan Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   By his sophomore year at the University of Idaho, however, Dan
Monson decided he wanted to be a coach anyway. He told his father.
He said his father hugged him, told him he was happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he just didn't want me to be a coach because his dad
did it,'' Dan Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, though, the father was nothing but helpful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, while still at Oregon, Don Monson wrote letters to a
few coaching friends around the country. It was Gene Bartow at the
University of Alabama-Birmingham who wrote back, offering Dan
Monson a graduate assistant job. So, in the summer of '86, the
father and son drove from Eugene to Alabama _ although not without
a little gambling junket along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped in Reno and Las Vegas,'' Don Monson said,
remembering the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but we looked at each other and said if we don't get out
of Nevada right now, we're never going to make it to Alabama. After
that, we had about 40 hours of good, quality time,'' Dan Monson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The quality time continues, especially after Dan Monson watched
in pain as his parents left Eugene and moved back to Eastern
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Monson, who served as assistant coach at Gonzaga for nine years
before taking over last season, likes having his parents living in
the same town. Dan lives on the north side of Spokane. His father
and mother live on the south side. Dan and Don hook up for golf and
meals and, yes, basketball talk.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the old coach can't quite resist the urge to break
out the old playbook every once in awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play Florida (a fullcourt-pressure team), and we have not
been pressed all tournament,'' Dan Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this week (when the 'Zags were back in Spokane) he stops by
the office the other day and says: `Now, I know you don't want to
see this ...' Then he draws up his favorite press breaker,'' the
younger Monson said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The young coach said the old coach's idea about how to attack
Florida's press is a good one. You bring the Gonzaga point guard to
mid-court and try to get the ball to him there, as opposed to
having the point guard bring the ball from deep in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we didn't put it in, but it's in the back of my mind,''
the son said. ``If we are getting hammered in the first half, it's
always good to have some other plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the son won't need the father's favorite press-breaker. He
has his own ideas about how to beat Florida, just as he had his own
ideas about what kind of profession he should take up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you what,'' Don Monson said. ``My son has made
many good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The old coach will be in the stands watching Thursday night. The
young coach will be on his own, but not without knowing how he got
to this place and not without knowing all the pain that comes with
a little glory.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
