<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-HORNETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS CAN'T RECOVER FROM POOR START  
 HOME DEBUT SWEET FOR 2 EX-LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ All Danny Ainge wanted for his 40th birthday
Wednesday was a St. Patrick's Day victory.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't seem like too much to ask of the Suns, especially
against a Charlotte Hornets club that had won only six games, drove
its coach to resignation, traded its star and had an All-Star out
for the season because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ainge got a gag gift.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns presented their coach with with a first-quarter flop
that led to a 119-111 Charlotte victory and popped Ainge's balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Former Lakers Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell, who were obtained
in a March 10 trade that sent Glen Rice to Los Angeles, had their
own celebration in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Making their home-court debut, Jones scored 29 points, getting
15 from 17 trips to the free-throw line and hounded Phoenix star
Jason Kidd defensively, while Campbell took down a career-high 19
rebounds to go with 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were as focused as I've seen them all year,'' said
Charlotte's interim head coach, Paul Silas, who was on Ainge's
staff during his first season as the Phoenix head coach. ``I didn't
know whether this team could come together as quickly as they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about the potential. We were effective
pushing the ball up the floor. When Elden rebounds the way he did,
it provides some easy baskets on the other end.''
</P>
<P>
   Too often in a disastrous first quarter for the Suns, Campbell
and the Hornets didn't even need to worry about a rebound. The Suns
turned over the ball five times in the first five minutes, leading
to 10 Charlotte points.
</P>
<P>
   The rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Suns find themselves in midseason crisis. They undid
most of what they accomplished in a victory at Milwaukee 24 hours
earlier. They're one game over .500 (12-11) with the 50-game
season's midpoint approaching and still have Atlanta and Houston
ahead Friday and Saturday on their four-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst we've played in a long time,'' Ainge said.
``You look at their 119 points and it's easy to say we played bad
defense, but our offense was just as bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a lot of pride in making the fewest turnovers in the
NBA, and just trying to feed the post we turned it over three or
four times at the start of the game. They got some easy baskets,
and that gave them confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as the Suns were in a spectacular first half in
Milwaukee on Tuesday night, they were spectacularly bad in the
first half Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Getting uncontested shots in the half-court and fast-break
opportunities from Phoenix turnovers, Charlotte ran to a 20-point
lead in the opening 10 minutes. Forward Bobby Phills hit three
three-point field goals and scored 13 of his 24 points in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns spent the rest of the game trying to dig out of that
mess. They got within five late in the third quarter, but former
Suns forward Chucky Brown hit a three-point shot at the
third-quarter buzzer, the Suns missed several layups at key moments
and the Hornets closed the deal down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to force things instead of being patient,'' Kidd
said. ``We wanted to exploit some mismatches and we got too
anxious. That led to fast breaks, which led to three-pointers,
which led to their big lead.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Hornets exploited the Suns' inside, just as Phoenix had
exploited a soft Milwaukee interior the night before. With Jones
leading the way, the Hornets attacked the basket and that led to 42
free throw attempts. The Hornets hit 83 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with a 44-29 whipping Charlotte gave the Suns on the
backboards, it meant another defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was an All-Star for the Lakers last season, said he
and Campbell are anxious to turn around the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying as hard as we can to get back to .500,'' he said.
``If we can get to .500, we have a shot (at the playoffs). That's a
playoff team we beat, and if we play defense the way we did against
them, we'll beat a lot of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell took exception to suggestions that he is unhappy about
the trade, and said he hopes to finish his career with the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play hard and show everyone that I'm happy to be
here,'' he said. ``It seems the perception was that I don't want to
be here. That's totally untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, it was the Suns who didn't want to be in
Charlotte. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
