<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4847 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MEETINGS-REPLAY-A     03-18 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETINGS-REPLAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTANT REPLAY WILL RETURN  
 NFL OWNERS VOTE 28-3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -Without a rash of bad calls last season, the NFL might
not have voted on Wednesday to reinstate instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood was that we had to do this thing now,'' said Seattle
Seahawks Coach Mike Holmgren, co-chairman of the league's
competition committee.
</P>
<P>
   The owners voted, 28-3, to use replay next season, bringing it
back for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Cardinals, Cincinnati Bengals and the New York Jets
opposed the measure, which creates a challenge system and reverses
calls only when the referee has ``indisputable visual evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was coach of the Green Bay Packers last season when a
botched call cost him a playoff game. San Francisco wide receiver
Jerry Rice lost a fumble but the play was whistled dead. On the
next play, the 49ers scored the game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But with the system the league adopted on Wednesday, the Rice
play would not have been reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The play is over once the whistle is blown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Replay can't fix that, never could,'' NFL spokesman Greg
Aiello said.
</P>
<P>
   Boundary and possession plays can be reviewed. Pass interference
wouldn't be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want the best team to win and rightfully so, even if
it goes against us,'' Buffalo Bills Coach Wade Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was the victim of two bad calls in the final minute of
a 25-21 loss to New England, including a 10-yard catch by the
Patriots' Shawn Jefferson in which TV replays showed he was out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were one of nine teams that voted against replay a
year ago. Seven of those clubs, including the Bills, changed their
vote this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were willing to take a shot for one year,'' said Tampa
Bay Coach Tony Dungy, whose team voted against replay a year ago.
``Now, we had teams that maybe were burned on a call and changed
their votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill remained a staunch opponent of
replay even though he knows fans support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think the game should be left on the field,'' Bidwill
said.
</P>
<P>
   The league adopted a replay plan that is a blend of two systems
used in the past.
</P>
<P>
   For 56 minutes of the game _ all but the last two minutes of
each half _ coaches will be able to challenge calls. Each team will
be allowed two challenges a game.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes of each half, an official in the press
box, a replay assistant who is a recently retired NFL or college
official, will control the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't to correct every wrong, just the big play, the
obvious play,'' said Tampa Bay General Manager Rich McKay,
co-chairman of the league's competition committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system adopted, the referee on the field will remain
in control at all times. He will view the replay and determine
whether the challenge should be upheld.
</P>
<P>
   If the challenge is not upheld, the team loses a timeout. If the
play is reversed, the team keeps the timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose the challenge, you should lose a timeout,'' said
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, who unlike his owner favors replay.
``If you challenge and don't win, you should be penalized.
Otherwise, (coaches) would be challenging all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Coach George Seifert said he will challenge only the
most ``glaring calls that anyone at home can see'' because of the
timeout risk.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a 90-second limit on challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes more than 90 seconds, the (challenge) probably
doesn't have the evidence it needs,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the technology that would be used hasn't been
determined. A handheld digit recorder is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches likely will make their challenges by pushing a beeper. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
