<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONCIERGE-PROFILE-NYT     03-18 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCIERGE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF SECRETS, SERVICE AND BOTH AT THE WALDORF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By becoming a murder victim last weekend, a guest at
the Waldorf-Astoria created the ultimate crisis for his hosts. And
if you think Chief Concierge Michael L. Romei is going to talk
about it, it has been a while since you stayed in a nice hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Romei, who wears the gold keys of the prestigious concierge
society, Les Clefs d'Or, on his custom-made suit, does not tell
tales (well, not too many tales) about the guests who spend $295
and up for a room at the Waldorf-Astoria. He is even a bit worried
about revealing which guest most impressed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophia Loren,'' Romei says. ``It was very busy and she just
walks in and there was dead silence. She just has such a tremendous
presence. I don't know. Should I mention her name?''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the awkward matter of the death of a Brazilian national
named Joao Saboia at the Waldorf. How does one keep the guests from
fear when the body of a man with his throat cut is found in his
room and the prime suspect is nowhere to be found and the police
are traipsing around the premises?
</P>
<P>
   ``We really handle it the same as any other crisis or problem
that would occur in a public building,'' says Romei (pronounced
Ro-MAY). ``We continue to smile and behave as if there wasn't
anything going on. Because one of the things I do believe creates
worry or pandemonium is when the people working are visibly
stressed. I've been in all kind of crisis in the hotel business. ''
</P>
<P>
   Example, please.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a major crisis which closed the city in the winter at
'95. I have these regular guests from Mexico City and they have
their own plane. They called me from the plane and said they had no
place to land, so I'm on the phone with all these control towers,
trying to find them an airport. Philly, no; Atlantic City, no. I
finally got clearance in Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   Aren't pilots supposed to know how to do that for themselves?
</P>
<P>
   The closest to a complaint that will ever escape the
clean-shaven mug of Romei: ``People call me for everything. Not
everybody thinks of calling themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   From time to time as you lurch through life, you will spot a
perfectly-composed person who has never had cat hair on his suit
and never will. Nine times out of 10, this person will be a
concierge.
</P>
<P>
   Romei, though only 40, supervises the 12 concierges at the
Waldorf. His domain is not the main hotel, where the homicide
occurred (Room 2716; the suspect, who had been traveling with the
deceased, is believed to have returned to Brazil, his native
country), but the Waldorf Towers, which has its own entrance and
small lobby, and which is where the president stays when he's in
town. Rates at the Towers make rooms at the main hotel look like a
bargain. A one-bedroom starts at $675; the presidential suite is
$7,500.
</P>
<P>
   What is one to make of a job where Bruce Springsteen strolls by
and a guest literally throws her dry-cleaning at you and a Secret
Sercice guy yells, ``Hey, Michael, anything for the ambassador this
morning?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never give that mail directly,'' Romei whispers. ``It
has to go through the metal detectors in Security. I don't know if
I'm allowed to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Romei seems to consider his work a calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, this is Michael the concierge,'' he sings, no
matter how frantically the phones are ringing. ``How can I be of
service?''
</P>
<P>
   And, of his closetlike cubicle in the Tower's lobby, crammed
with magazines and phone books and a seating chart of the city's
theaters:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it is, my empire. This is where I part the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   His style is not aloof. Think Eagle Scout who could get you a
table at Le Cirque and also be able to provide the name of a
plastic surgeon or to speak French to the dog or give you the best
route to Bali. A Scout who can knot an Hermes tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a doctor as far back as I can remember,'' says
Romei, who was raised in New Haven, Conn., the son of a highway
engineer. ``I really enjoyed taking care of people. Which is
similar to what I do. Caretaking. I really believe there is no way
you could stand here all day and do what I do if you didn't do it
from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the sciences and the math, which he found ``kind of
dull,'' that got in the way of Romei's medical plans. Instead, he
studied international politics at Manhattanville College and New
York University, with thoughts of travel and a diplomatic career.
He wound up working for an oil company. Ten years ago, he moved
into hotel work. He knew at once he should be a concierge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy taking a bad situation and turning it around by
making a person feel special or comforted,'' says Romei, who lives
on Sutton Place. ``If I know they like hot chocolate or a special
newspaper I have it sent to their room. If they call me lost from
the street, I send a car. We have our own car service, our own
chauffeur, at the Waldorf Towers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other requests made to Romei include providing a Saudi prince
with fresh dates (the fruit) out of season and obtaining wholesale
bakery equipment for a guest who wanted to open a cafe in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted special racks and special curtain rods for the cafe
and all the equipment shipped to Ethiopia,'' Romei says.
</P>
<P>
   Did she tip?
</P>
<P>
   Only the slightest hint of a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, she didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
