<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOBBY AYALA SHINES IN WIN FOR MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Bobby Ayala threw a 1-2-3 ninth inning to close
out the Mariners' 7-2 win over the Oakland Athletics on Wednesday.
So what else is new?
</P>
<P>
   Ayala is getting used to pitching effectively this spring. In
six innings over five games, he has a 1.50 earned-run average. He
has eight strikeouts and one walk. And he's basically a smiling
machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really feeling strong,'' he said. ``I'm having a great
spring so far, and I'm happy about it. Things couldn't be going any
better than they are right now. I feel great about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, 1-10 last year with a 7.29 ERA, still could be traded,
and he said he'll be happy wherever he is. But if this Ayala is the
one the Mariners bring north, they just might want to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitching with a lot of confidence right now,'' said
pitching coach Stan Williams. ``He had stretches like this last
year where he knocked your eyes out. ... He's got a split-finger
that's almost unhittable, his change-up's as good as anyone's on
the ballclub, we have him at 94 (mph) on the gun down here and he's
got a good slider to boot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said it usually takes him a month into the season to throw
94 mph, which could explain why he struggles in April (career ERA:
5.66). But this winter, he threw more than ever in an effort to
start the year right, and he's seeing the results already.
</P>
<P>
   He's also trying to work more change-ups into his repertoire.
Ayala threw the pitch twice Wednesday, once inducing a ground out,
and said it's an ideal pitch for getting ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala rarely used the change-up last year, but he's trying to
bring it back so it can help his split-finger. The splitter comes
in at 87-88 mph, four to five mph faster than the change-up, but
has a much harder break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling comfortable throwing it a lot more now,'' Ayala
said. ``Maybe it'll knock hitters off-balance a little bit. It's
going to confuse them seeing something (breaking) soft off-speed
and then something (breaking) hard off-speed.''
</P>
<P>
   LEITER'S SIDE: In the Mariners' other game Wednesday, a 3-2 win
over the A's in Phoenix, Russ Davis homered twice and Jamie Moyer,
Mark Leiter and Jose Paniagua all pitched effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has worked 10 innings this spring, allowing three earned
runs. A reliever with the Phillies last year, he is being
considered for a starting job in Seattle but could work from the
bullpen. Leiter said he enjoys the set-up relief role, but his
preference is to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this offense, being a starter would be a lot of fun,
because they're going to score runs,'' said Leiter, who turns 36
next month. ``If you condition yourself and keep your stamina
going, then you can pitch 200-plus innings and you're going to get
a lot of decisions. I can't see how you wouldn't want to be in this
rotation. I mean, you would think you'd have a chance to win 15
games.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Right-hander Freddy Garcia continues to
impress. He pitched three scoreless innings in Peoria, striking out
four and allowing one hit. The Mariners would prefer more seasoning
for the 22-year-old Garcia, who had never pitched above Class A
before '98, but he could change their minds with more performances
like Wednesday's. ... Ken Griffey Jr. had a homer and five runs
batted in at Peoria. ... Non-roster outfielder Earl Johnson, who
manager Lou Piniella said is the quickest player in camp, hit an
inside-the-park home run in the Phoenix game. ... The latest
Mariner to be sidelined with a sore neck is Edgar Martinez, who sat
out Wednesday's split-squad action. ... Two things have impressed
Piniella most this spring: His pitchers have 40 more strikeouts
than walks, and his fielders have made only nine errors in 14
games. In fact, the Mariners were the last major league team to
allow an unearned run this spring, doing so for the first time on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
