<SLUG> BC-CAR-AMA-DUCATI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCATI POWER PAYS AT PIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - What is it about Phoenix International Raceway that
bonds Doug Polen, Troy Corser, Mat Mladin and Anthony Gobert?
</P>
<P>
   Ducati.
</P>
<P>
   In four previous AMA Cruise America Arizona Superbike Challenges
at PIR, Ducati has been the two-wheeled monster to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gobert, who made his superbike debut last year at PIR, had
no trouble reaching victory lane. He won by a lengthy 8{ seconds,
smacking defending champion Mladin, who was runner-up on a Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (Suzuki) feel we can stop the (Ducati) streak this year,
but the Ducati is a good bike for this layout,'' said Mladin, who
won two years ago on a Ducati. ``That 1000cc motor puts a lot of
power down to the ground and that's what you need at Phoenix
because the track is very tight and twisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can make that kind of power and acceleration off the
corners, that can make all the difference (at PIR).''
</P>
<P>
   Although not viewed as one of the circuit's more technically
innovative racetracks, PIR's 11-turn, 1.51-mile road course, which
encompasses much of the 1-mile oval, still can cause headaches and
sleepless nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say Ducati doesn't make as much power as some of the
other bikes, but the power it does make is very usable at lower
RPMs,'' said three-time superbike champion Doug Chandler, who will
tackle PIR on a Kawasaki. ``It has a lot of torque, which allows it
to get off the tighter corners better.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the usage of PIR's oval, there are enough infield
turns to apparently benefit the Ducati contingent.
</P>
<P>
   But Vance &AMP; Hines Ducati Team Manager Jim Leonard believes
Ducati's advantage may be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the rest of the field step it up last year,'' Leonard
said. ``I don't think by any means we have a huge advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, however, does admit the Ducati machine seems best
suited for PIR-type courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracks that have real slower corners, like that bus stop (Turn
9, the final corner leading onto PIR's dogleg along the
back-straightaway) tend to favor the Ducati because it tends to
drive off those corners very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rider on a Ducati has always got the power when he needs it.
Whenever he moves the throttle, he doesn't have to wait on it like
a lot of riders on Japanese bikes.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be good for Ducati's top riders, which includes
defending series champion Ben Bostrom, who finished fourth two
weeks ago in the season-opening Daytona 200 at Daytona
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But what does it mean for non-Ducati riders such as Daytona 200
champion Miguel Duhamel, who won on a Honda?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? All Duhamel knows is he has other worries.
</P>
<P>
   Although he won at Daytona, Duhamel said PIR's layout presents
larger problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytona is a long course and you have time to set up for the
corners,'' Duhamel said. ``Phoenix is left-right, left-right,
boom-boom-boom. I can't use my left leg that much and that's not
good at a place like Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting to come out of there with flying colors. If
I crack the top five, I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Duhamel, however, wouldn't be surprised to see Harley-Davidson
riders Scott Russell and Pascal Picotte do well.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harley-Davidson has yet to reach the winner's circle
since returning to the circuit five years ago, Duhamel believes the
motorcycle has similar traits as the Ducati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pascal and I get along well and he tells me the bike is
good,'' Duhamel said.
</P>
<P>
   Picotte crashed at Daytona, however, and finished far back.
</P>
<P>
   Russell didn't even make the show. He suffered two facial
fractures in an off-track incident at a Daytona Beach nightclub and
was forced to scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Russell underwent surgery last Thursday and a Harley-Davidson
team spokesperson said the rider will be at PIR. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
