<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' QUARTERBACK SEARCH TURNS TO JETS' FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ The Seahawks' search for a veteran quarterback
has led them to former New York Jets starter Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
   There have been talks between the clubs about the possibility of
a trade for Foley, 28, who has one year remaining on his contract
but is expendable because of the re-emergence of Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Foley would give the Seahawks the young veteran quarterback new
coach and general manager Mike Holmgren wants to backup and perhaps
challenge Jon Kitna for the starting job. The Jets would receive a
middle-round draft choice that could increase in value depending on
how much Foley plays.
</P>
<P>
   Each team, however, is exploring other options.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bears also are interested in Foley, although he
favors being traded to the Seahawks. The Seahawks consider Foley
just the latest alternative in their quarterback quest and also
would be interested in Jeff Blake if the Cincinnati Bengals decide
to release him or make him available in a trade. The Seahawks
already have courted but lost Doug Pederson (signed with
Philadelphia), Gus Frerotte (signed with Detroit), Stoney Case
(signed with Indianapolis) and Jim Harbaugh (traded to San Diego
this week).
</P>
<P>
   Two things are certain: Holmgren is determined to acquire a
young veteran, preferably before the start of the Seahawks'
four-day quarterback camp March 29; and Jets coach Bill Parcells is
even more determined to unload Foley before the team's offseason
conditioning program begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   Foley is scheduled to start receiving a $400,000 workout bonus,
at $10,000 per workout, next Wednesday. Plus, he will count more
than $2 million against the salary cap this year in base salary and
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, a seventh-round draft choice in 1994, was effective in
brief stints as the starter in 1996 and 1997. He opened 1998 as the
starter, but quickly played his way into Parcells' doghouse. First,
Foley hid an injury from Parcells in the second half of a Week 2
loss to the Baltimore Ravens. Then, Foley played poorly in a Week 5
loss to St. Louis, prompting Parcells' decision to go with
Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde led the Jets to 10 wins in their final 11
regular-season games and into the AFC championship game. He was
rewarded last month with a three-year, $19.5 million contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Foley completed 58 of 108 passes for 749 yards with four
touchdowns and six interceptions before being replaced. He has
never thrown more than 110 passes in a season.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: James Logan has agreed to a two-year, $1.2 million
contract and should re-sign with the Seahawks in the next day or
two. Logan missed the final 12 games in 1998 after breaking his
leg. But he is an outstanding special-teams player and burgeoning
linebacker who had drawn interest from the Philadelphia Eagles.
Logan will be the third unrestricted free agent to re-sign with the
Seahawks, joining TE Christian Fauria and K Todd Peterson. ... The
Seahawks also have added QB Mike McCoy, a former practice-squad
player for the Green Bay Packers who will provide an extra arm for
the upcoming quarterback camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
