<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HORNETS-KJ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KJ HAS HORNETS BUZZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ If former Suns star Kevin Johnson wants a job,
Charlotte Hornets Coach Paul Silas says he's got one for him.
</P>
<P>
   Silas, who is serving as interim coach here, said Wednesday
before the Hornets and Suns met at Charlotte Coliseum that he plans
to call KJ as early as today and attempt to persuade the veteran
point guard to sign with Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob (Bass, Hornets executive vice president, basketball
operations) called him already,'' Silas said. ``I'm going to call
him and see if he wants to do anything this year.''
</P>
<P>
   KJ could not be reached for comment, nor could his
representative, Kevin Hiestand, but Hiestand has let clubs know
that KJ wants to play an integral role, play for a championship
contender and have the ball in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Told indications are that KJ is likely to seek a two-year
commitment, Silas said, `I don't get involved in that stuff. I'd
just like to see what his interest level is. Then I'd go to Bob and
see what happens. We need a point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets currently have David Wesley and Eldridge Recasner at
the position, and they added Corey Beck to a 10-day contract
Wednesday. KJ would be the starter.
</P>
<P>
   But would the Hornets be a contender? They came into Wednesday
night's game with a 6-14 record, but with the additions of guard
Eddie Jones and center Elden Campbell, along with forward Derrick
Coleman, the Hornets could put a pretty solid starting five on the
floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
