<HEADLINE>
11-YEAR VETERAN FORWARD SIGNED AS FREE AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Coyotes picked up another player before next
week's trading deadline, but they didn't have to trade anything to
get him.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing  &UR; Brian Noonan, an 11-year NHL veteran who has played
all of this season with the minor league Indianapolis Ice, was
acquired Wednesday as a free agent. The 33-year-old Noonan, who
played on the New York Rangers' Stanley Cup championship team in
1994 and spent last season with Vancouver, joined the Coyotes in
time for their 4-3 victory Wednesday over the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The deal fell together fairly quickly, Noonan said. He got a
call Tuesday night from his agent, Boston-based  &UR; Bob Murray, who
also represents Coyotes captain  &UR; Keith Tkachuk, and in the morning,
he found himself skating at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was going to happen,'' said Noonan, who had
19 goals and 44 assists for Indianapolis this season. ``I was
having fun playing hockey down there, but I was still hoping to get
back. This is a good opportunity. I wasn't hearing much, but things
happen in a hurry. Last night I got a call, they said they had some
injuries here and needed some players, and here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Noonan, the 10th overall pick in the 1983 draft by Chicago, was
always one of former NHL Coach  &UR; Mike Keenan's favorite players. He
played for Keenan in Chicago, New York, St. Louis and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first couple years with him, it was tough. He's pretty
demanding, and sometimes you don't know what his reasons for doing
things was, but as I got older and the more time I spent with him,
I enjoyed it,'' said Noonan, who had 19 shifts in his Phoenix
debut. ``I was fortunate that he took me to a lot of places he
went. I learned a lot from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit forward  &UR; Joey Kocur was a teammate of Noonan's in New
York and said he will help the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bit like a  &UR; Ray Sheppard, he's got real good hands
around the net,'' Kocur said. ``He's shifty with a long reach, not
overly fast, but great with the puck _ a smart, reliable forward
who can play in any situation at any time.'' &QL; 
Roenick rumors &QL; 
Every year at about this time, it seems like  &UR; Jeremy Roenick's name
surfaces regarding trade rumors. ``Like clockwork,'' he likes to
say.
</P>
<P>
   The latest one making the rounds courtesy of ESPN's  &UR; Al Morganti
has the Coyotes trading Roenick, possibly after this season, to
pare the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't believe it,'' said Roenick, who has two more years left
on a contract that pays him an average of $4 million per season.
``I'm not going anywhere.'' &QL; 
The mighty Quint &QL; 
Defenseman  &UR; Deron Quint played a game-high and career-high 28
minutes, 22 seconds, and was credited with blocking a total of
seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dead right now,'' Quint sighed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
