<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BEARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL NINO GIVES, LA NINA TAKES  
 BEAR CUBS FACE DEATH IN DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1996, the second-largest wildfire in Arizona
history destroyed 60 square miles of vegetation near Four Peaks in
Tonto National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The Lone Wildfire didn't destroy everything. It missed six
square miles in various green islands, which saved a number of
animals by offering protection and food.
</P>
<P>
   But soon after the fire, ``We found out we didn't have any black
bears,'' said Stan Cunningham, a research biologist for the Arizona
Game and Fish Department. ``Even bears in the green islands were
gone. What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Because of their mobility as compared with smaller mammals,
bears and foxes escaped the fire for the most part. They just left.
But bears are creatures of habit and soon returned, even if just to
pass through.
</P>
<P>
   After three years, it became evident that the bears were coming
back in great numbers. A normal bear count would be about 1.3 per
square mile. The count in the burned area is 7.3 bears per square
mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the highest concentration in the U.S., except for
Alaska when they're eating salmon,'' said Cunningham. ``There are
10 to 12 per square mile there. Where there's food available,
you'll find bears.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, after two consecutive wet years, La Nina has
created the driest year on record. Wildlife once again faces severe
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was developing a research project on coyotes and
bobcats in the Four Peaks area when the fire struck.
</P>
<P>
   The agency responded by changing courses to see the fire's
effect on predators. It received funds from one federal and one
state source, and Cunningham started the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small mammals,'' Cunningham said, ``were hurt by the fire, but
they already were in bad shape because of drought.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears barely suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their great mobility and adaptabily, bears and gray
foxes fared well and returned to the burned out area. Bobcats
didn't. They will eat only meat, and there wasn't much of that
around. Bears and foxes have a wider range of possible food,
including vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the food shortage, males will come after cubs to eat
them,`` Cunningham said. ``Females may come after each other.
Finally we'll see a reduction of adult populations.''
</P>
<P>
   Few cubs survive the early months, and with food decreasing,
it'll be worse this year. Most will be eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Trapping is banned on public land in this state except for
research reasons. Cunningham prefers to use cable leg snares to
catch and study the animals. The only bear hurt was a trapped one
killed by another bear.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Cunningham and his assistant, Raul Vega, led
reporters to a den in the burned area. The female had been equipped
with a radio collar so she could be traced.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham and Vega used radio telemetry equipment to find her
den under a boulder field. Now the tough part began.
</P>
<P>
   Most people believe that hibernating bears sleep all winter. In
fact, they don't. They'll get up and move around.
</P>
<P>
   When Cunningham crawled to mouth of the den, the female was
sitting and looking at him while her two cubs suckled. Although he
has been victim of a mock attack, he's never been injured.
</P>
<P>
   Vega loaded a large syringe with a combination of a muscle
relaxer and a tranquilizer, and Cunningham attached the syringe to
the tip of a metal rod.
</P>
<P>
   Then he crawled into the den and jabbed the mother with the
syringe.
</P>
<P>
   In time she was down, and Cunningham brought out the two cubs _
a male and female, each weighing nearly four pounds. They were born
in late January. Cunningham examined and weighed the cubs and
pronounced them healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The cubs were hilarious. When Cunningham would peer into the
den, the cubs would chatter like crazy. When outside and being held
by humans, they'd start crying.
</P>
<P>
   Vega soon reported that the mother was becoming more alert. The
cubs quickly were returned to the den.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad to think that neither cub probably will survive the
summer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
