<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP DRIVERS HAVE SOLID REASONS TO RUN BGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Mike Skinner's victory in Saturday's NASCAR Busch Grand
National Series race has been reinstated, get ready for an official
crisis ``du jour''.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's off-again, on-again victory in the Yellow Freight 300
at Atlanta Motor Speedway means that NASCAR Winston Cup regulars
have won three of the first four BGN races of 1999. Recall that
Skinner's first career BGN victory was deleted by NASCAR officials
following a post-race inspection, which uncovered a non-approved
cylinder head.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner was dropped to the 43rd and last position. But
team-owner David Ridling filed an appeal, and the National Stock
Car Racing Commission modified the penalty against crew chief C.R.
Miller yesterday. The commission upheld the monetary portion of the
penalty but awarded Skinner the victory and first-place points.
</P>
<P>
   Good for Skinner, the Winston Cup points-leader who never turned
a nut or bolt on the Busch engine in question.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the intrusion of Cup drivers into the BGN series
already had become a hot media topic. It has been based upon the
inference that Winston Cup regulars are boldly stealing headlines,
purse money and valuable championship points from their aspiring
Busch brethren.
</P>
<P>
   The debate easily could re-ignite when the tour visits Texas
Motor Speedway for the Coca-Cola 300 on March 27. Approximately 22
Cup regulars are expected to make qualifying attempts for the Busch
race in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there are more Cup drivers ``dropping down'' into
Busch races in 1999 is a noteworthy trend, albeit one faced
regularly since the series' inception in 1982. A variety of
factors, however, apparently are accelerating the process.
</P>
<P>
   Start with money. As part of a four-year extension with title
sponsor Anheuser-Busch, the points fund for top drivers at season's
end has increased to $1.5 million, more than doubling the $650,000
total from 1998. Point-fund awards are paid to the top-20 finishers
in the final BGN standings, although not one Cup regular was in the
final 1998 top-20.
</P>
<P>
   So, what are other reasons for a Cup driver to run Busch?
</P>
<P>
   Some are using the series to test their prowess as team owners
and their marketability. Their name recognition in Winston Cup
surely has allowed drivers like Dale Jarrett, Jimmy Spencer,
Michael Waltrip and Terry Labonte to field BGN teams and attract
the sponsorship to keep them up and running.
</P>
<P>
   From a purely selfish standpoint, running a Busch race at TMS,
for instance, makes sense. The track has been reconfigured and
repaved since last year's Busch and Cup events.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Busch cars are lighter and less powerful than their
Cup counterparts, an extra 200 laps around TMS in a Busch car on
Saturday should help an astute Cup driver learn something he can
tell his crew chief about chassis setups, how the track changes
during a race and if two grooves might be developing for the
Primestar 500 the next afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And if a Cup driver happens to win the Busch race in Fort Worth,
so what?
</P>
<P>
   As long as his cylinder heads are NASCAR-approved, it will be a
trend. Not a crisis, for sure.
SPOTLIGHT ON: KENNY BERNSTEIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Bernstein has flown down quarter-mile drag strips and
flown off the deck of an aircraft carrier over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Louie the Lizard climbed aboard, Bernstein fashioned
a sponsorship relationship with Budweiser that has endured as the
second-longest in professional motorsports. Only NASCAR's Richard
Petty and STP have a longer track record than Bernstein as Bud
King. That pairing, however, nearly did not come together for the
1980 National Hot Rod Association season.
</P>
<P>
   The management at Anheuser-Busch was wavering when Bernstein
asked for, and received, permission for one final five-minute
presentation at the brewery headquarters in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I planned on taking the truck and trailer and race car to St.
Louis and putting it on display, even though we didn't know what
that really meant back then,'' said Bernstein, who was campaigning
a Plymouth Arrow Funny Car. ``I felt I had nothing to lose. I
wanted them to see the size of the 18-wheel tractor trailer, the
beauty of the race car, and where their signage could go.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein's meeting was scheduled for Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the brewery at 6 a.m., and set up in front of the
office building,'' Bernstein said. ``We set up in a dirt parking
lot. But everyone had to park there and walk past the display to
get to the office. At 8 o'clock, they started coming to work, and
it created quite a stir.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein scooted up to the fourth floor and returned with Bud's
marketing boys in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent an hour showing them everything,'' Bernstein said.
``At that point, the whole thought process changed. We were able to
secure the program, and to this day I believe that's what saved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein forever stamped himself as the ``King of Speed'' when
he became the first driver to break the 300 mph barrier at 301.70
mph on March 20, 1992, at Gainesville (Fla.) Raceway. The series
returns there this weekend for the Mac Tools Gatornationals, with
Bernstein's places in racing and marketing history secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was truly the first breakthrough of that caliber, Bud
joining the drag racing side of things,'' Bernstein said. ``I like
to think that opened a lot of doors and helped the whole sport.''
QUICK HITS
GORDON LOVES NY
</P>
<P>
   Three-time and reigning NASCAR Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon
says he is excited about the prospect of a NASCAR-style
superspeedway planned for the metropolitan New York City area.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate magnate Donald Trump and NASCAR president Bill
France Jr., in his role as chairman of the board of International
Speedway Corp., announced last week they have begun looking for a
site for a 75,000-seat superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the political part. The current schedule contains 34
race dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest question is who's going to lose a date?'' said
Gordon, driver of the No. 24 DuPont Chevrolet fielded by Hendrick
Motorsports. ``I do not want to see another race added. It's not so
much for me. It's more for the team. These guys are running with
their tongues hanging out right now. They can't afford to run
another race. I think it's ridiculous to say, `Oh, we'll just add
another race, no problem. You just add some more personnel.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anybody to lose a date, but I think that's the
only way we should be going to another venue. And we should be
going to New York, for sure.'' ANDRETTI FIRED UP
</P>
<P>
   Michael Andretti will attempt to become the first CART driver to
win three consecutive season-openers Sunday, with the running of
the Marlboro Grand Prix of Miami at Homestead, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti's Swift/Ford will be shod with Firestone tires for the
first time since Newman/Haas Racing ended its association with
Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   Only Michael's father, Mario Andretti (1984-85 and 1987-88),
Fort Worth's Johnny Rutherford (1980-81) and Rick Mears (1989-90)
have won back-to-back Championship Auto Racing Teams season
openers. `DRIVE' WITH THE DRIVERS
</P>
<P>
   Primestar 500 race-week activities are scheduled to kick off
with the ``Star-Telegram'' Speedway Children Charities Golf
Tournament on Wednesday at Tour 18. The course is 15 minutes from
Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch with Jeff Burton, winner of the first Cup race at TMS,
will open the day, followed by a shotgun start at 1 p.m. NASCAR
Winston Cup and Busch Grand National Series drivers scheduled to
tee off include native Texan Bobby Hillin, Randy LaJoie, Todd
Bodine, Adam Petty, Blaise Alexander, Boris Said and Tim Fedewa.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of four can enter for $1,000, and individuals may play for
$200 each. For information, contact Alicia Jenkins at (817)
215-8564. LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Mike he's the only person in the world who could be
sitting in the first row of church and still get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Larry McReynolds, to Mike Skinner before NASCAR reinstated his
Busch Grand National victory. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
