<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CAPITALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOBBLED STARS FALL TO CAPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There were no four-leaf clovers to be found for the
Stars last night, so maybe it was appropriate that they lost their
13th game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was also appropriate that they lost for the first time
in overtime this season and for only the second time in the past
two seasons. Maybe it was appropriate that all-time Stars franchise
goal-scoring leader Brian Bellows (342 goals with the Minnesota
North Stars) was the guy who flicked home the winner in OT _ with a
broken stick, at that _ and propelled the struggling Washington
Capitals to a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, it was just time for the Stars to lose. Missing three of
their top five scorers and six regulars overall, the Stars were a
mishmash of depth players, a couple who were called up from the
minors the night before. The only thing was, they were playing a
Capitals team that also was thin on depth, missing nine players to
injuries, including leading scorer Peter Bondra (hand),
third-leading scorer Joe Juneau (concussion) and top defensemen
Mark Tinordi (ankle), Sergei Gonchar (ankle) and Calle Johansson
(knee).
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some players out, they had some players out, it's the
guys you replace them with,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We
had some poor players today. Some of our forwards weren't very
good, not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars fell to 42-13-12 and have suffered eight of their
losses to teams with records below .500. The Capitals move to
28-34-6, good for 62 points. They still are eight points behind the
Boston Bruins for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a desperate team, and we didn't match their
energy,'' said winger Mike Keane, one of the Stars players who had
a solid night. ``The injuries are no excuses. We just have to play
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was a mucker's paradise, as many of the players were
seeing rare NHL ice. Stars defenseman Brad Lukowich was playing his
first NHL game of the season and the fifth of his career. He had an
assist, the second of his career, and played 18 minutes. Winger
Blake Sloan continued to provide energy in his fourth NHL game.
Center Kelly Fairchild played in his 24th NHL game, but his first
since 1997. He had more than 12 minutes of ice time.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Wright, on the other hand, was given less than two minutes
of ice time and continued to struggle in his bid to impress Stars
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars were trying to fill their holes with rookies,
the Capitals answered with veteran role players. And while the
Stars showed strong energy, especially in the second period when
they took a 1-0 lead on a fluky goal by Tony Hrkac, they were
outhustled and outmuscled in the third period. Andre Nikolishin,
who went 21-5 in the faceoff circle with Stars expert drawmen Joe
Nieuwendyk and Guy Carbonneau out of the lineup, won three
consecutive faceoffs in the offensive zone and finally cashed in on
the third.
</P>
<P>
   The last win helped set up a Nikolishin slap shot from the right
circle that found its way through a maze of bodies and past Stars
goalie Ed Belfour to tie the game, 1-1, with 12:08 remaining in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Washington then won it in overtime, when Adam Oates carried the
puck behind the Stars' net and tried a wraparound shot. The puck
squirted under Belfour and onto the stick of Bellows, who was
standing just to the left of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Just 35 seconds into the Stars' third consecutive overtime game,
they were finally worn down. On a three-game Eastern road swing,
the Stars allowed just five goals and still went 0-1-2.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe they need to get back home and get injured leaders like
Nieuwendyk, Carbonneau, Brett Hull, Darryl Sydor and Richard
Matvichuk into the lineup for tomorrow's home game with the Eastern
Conference-leading Ottawa Senators if they're hoping for a change
of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I'm looking at it,'' said Nieuwendyk, who
missed the game with a sore back. ``This is a good time to come
back.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
