<SLUG> BC-BKC-OREGON-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TAKE NY TRIP FROM FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The season hadn't been finished for more
than an hour when TCU coach Billy Tubbs was asked what his thoughts
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It ended in the same annoying and frustrating fashion that
defined it, a 77-68 loss to Oregon last night in the third round of
the National Invitation Tournament at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum in a
game the Horned Frogs could have won.
</P>
<P>
   It ended despite the best efforts of Horned Frogs preseason
All-American Lee Nailon.
</P>
<P>
   He almost single-handedly sent TCU (21-11) to New York, scoring
a game-high 27 points. He instead sent himself to an NBA draft camp
in two weeks, with his attention likely to remain on that pursuit.
He became the first player in TCU history to have consecutive
700-point seasons, finishing with 1,503 in his two seasons at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   His second season ended because of sloppy play (17 turnovers)
and sporadic shooting (38 percent shooting), and allowed Oregon to
walk away with a victory and the subsequent trip to the NIT
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just came out tonight in the second half and kind of let up
like we thought they were going to give us the game,'' Nailon said.
``Before we knew it, they were knocking down shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was the Frogs' to win, the victory was in their hands.
They just couldn't make a shot.
</P>
<P>
   They scored a season-low 28 points in the second half. They shot
a season-low 31 percent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed a lot of easy shots in the second half,'' Tubbs
said. ``It's hard to look good when your shots aren't going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs downplayed the fatigue factor in the Frogs' shooting
struggles, but the Ducks (19-11) engaged them in a game of keepaway
all evening. They played keepaway along the perimeter, forcing the
Frogs to frantically give chase. The Frogs, utilizing a six-man
rotation and a matchup zone, eventually wore down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting tired a little bit,'' Horned Frogs guard Prince
Fowler said. ``I just kept trying the best I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The too-tired Frogs were unable to nail their shots on one end
while the Ducks finally started hitting theirs on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon shot a luke warm 40 percent for the game, but were
6-of-12 on 3-pointers in the second half after hitting 3-of-13 in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our outside shooting was the difference,'' Ducks
coach Ernie Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   TCU had a 63-61 lead with 5:22 remaining. Oregon proceeded to
get a 3-pointer from A.D. Smith 14 seconds later. He led Oregon
with 18 points. Back-to-back 3-pointers from Darius Wright followed
with 3:37 and 3:02 remaining for a 70-63 Ducks' lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs never recovered _ unable to answer at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   TCU (21-11) already had spotted Oregon plenty of four-point
leads in the second half and already had spent a great deal of time
and energy scratching their way back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our depth has been there all year for us down the stretch and
particularly in the postseason when guys are tired,'' Kent said.
``Playing in the Pac-10 was a struggle, it's a grueling marathon.
What saved us tonight was our depth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what saved the Ducks was the Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the Oregon game ended a lot like the second
half of the season, frustratingly close and yet annoyingly not
close enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to wait by the phone. I'm sure there is another
tournament out there,'' Tubbs said. ``I'll wait by the phone until
one o'clock. If nothing comes up, then the season is over.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
