<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-STOTTLEMYRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA'S 2 BOWS IRK STOTTLEMYRE  
 CEREMONY UPSETS D-BACKS PITCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, ARIZ. - Wednesday was St. Patrick's Day, but Diamondbacks
right-hander Todd Stottlemyre certainly wasn't about to say ``Top
o' the afternoon to ya, laddie,'' to Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   He had a few other words in mind for the 1998 National League
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre's cabbage was steamed after Sosa hit two home runs
off him in front of a sellout crowd of 12,658 at HoHoKam Park. The
Diamondbacks won in 10 innings, 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the home runs that angered Stottlemyre, but what Sosa
did afterward.
</P>
<P>
   When Sosa joined a group of major-league all-stars for a tour of
Japan after the season, he started a habit of bowing to the fans
after hitting a home run. He decided to carry that over to this
season, to show the fans his appreciation for their support during
his home run chase with the St. Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting a two-run shot to right field off Stottlemyre in
the first inning, Sosa bowed to the fans about halfway between the
plate and the Cubs' dugout. It was the sixth spring homer for Sosa,
who hit 66 last season.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and nobody on in the third, Sosa hit one deep to
left center on a 3-2 pitch for his seventh spring shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respect for Sammy and what he's done as a player. He's
a great hitter and has busted his (expletive) to get where he is.
But I've busted my (expletive) to get where I am, too,''
Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did caught me off-guard. That has no (expletive) place
in this game. I don't bow after I strike somebody out or get
somebody out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like an (expletive) bullfighter out there. I
guarantee you that Mickey Mantle never (expletive) bowed and he hit
damn near 600 of them. I guarantee you Joe DiMaggio never bowed.
Lou Gehrig. Roberto Clemente. Jackie Robinson. The guys who paved
the way for us, the reason why we have it so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the bows, Sosa said, ``I don't see why anybody would
take it personal. I'm just showing respect for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that Stottlemyre thought it showed lack of respect for
him, the smile left Sosa's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said he is not one to hold a grudge, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never make excuses,'' he said. ``I gave him some pitches
he could handle. I wanted to get even by striking Sammy out the
second time, and on the 2-2 pitch (a slider), every ounce of
competitive juice wanted that call.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stottlemyre didn't get the strike call from umpire Greg
Bonin. He jawed at Bonin, and Manager Buck Showalter came out to
deflect return fire from the umpire, adding a few words himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who was removed from the game by Showalter after
issuing a two-out walk in the third, was ejected by Bonin in the
top of the fourth. Sitting in the dugout, Stottlemyre questioned a
couple of pitch calls to Arizona leadoff man Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the pitch and thought he got the hitter out,''
Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's take on the situation: ``My pitcher needed to get
some work done and I was trying to keep him from being run. The
bows? The fans seem to like it, but `Stott' didn't.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
