<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLYBALL FOLDS SHOW BEFORE HITTING BROADWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ New York would have been a grand stage for
Billyball, but TCU won't be doing Broadway this year. The closest
the Frogs will get to the big city is if they tune in to ``Saturday
Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Needing one more rousing Billyball performance in front of the
home crowd to earn a round-trip ticket to the National Invitation
Tournament semifinals at Madison Square Garden, Team Schizophrenia
submitted another edition of Sybilball instead.
</P>
<P>
   One thing about those Frogs, you never know who's going to show
up.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon _ quicker, faster, and in the end, better _ ended the
Frogs' season with a 77-68 victory in front of 6,036 at
Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to wait by the phone,'' coach Billy Tubbs quipped
in his best Jack Nicholson style after the Frogs' season took its
final breath. ``I'm sure there's another tournament out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that Billy. He would have been a riot on the Great White
Way.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' strange season ended with an overflow of would-haves
and could-haves.
</P>
<P>
   What would have happened if the Frogs had come out last night
with the same intensity, the same passion that marked Monday
night's heart-pounding, ear-throbbing victory against Nebraska?
</P>
<P>
   That electricity, some of it supplied by a raucous sellout
crowd, was missing last night.
</P>
<P>
   So were most of the Frogs' shots. They shot only 38 percent for
the game and scored a season-low 28 points on 11-of-36 (.306)
shooting in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we had the lead at halftime,'' Tubbs said, ``I
didn't feel all that good about the way we were playing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was going to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   By the final 10 minutes of the game, it appeared that Tubbs'
six-man rotation was running out gas. Players' shots were finding
more iron than net. Defensively, the Frogs were having a hard time
keeping up with the Ducks' mercurial guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think fatigue was as much a factor as some things we
did offensively,'' Tubbs said. ``Most of the shots we missed, we
had no one in position to rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the balanced scoring that marked the victory against
Nebraska when all five starters were in double-figures. Instead,
the Frogs had Lee Nailon and his 27 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Good, but not nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Frog in double figures was Vladimir Jaksic, who
managed to make 4 of 8 3-pointers for 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Marquise Gainous, who was so vibrantly alive and energized
against the Cornhuskers, made only 3 of 10 and finished with 9
points. His misses turned him into a lifeless post, lingering
beyond the top of the key. Ryan Carroll was 3-of-12, Prince Fowler
3-of-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We jacked some shots pretty quick,'' Tubbs said, ``and didn't
have enough patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Read that quote again carefully. Did you ever think you'd hear
Billy Tubbs complain about his team shooting too fast and not being
more patient?
</P>
<P>
   But then, this wasn't your normal Billy Tubbs team, as we
discovered in the season's final 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unusual season,'' Tubbs said. ``We had a lot of
opportunities we didn't capitalize on. We may have played above our
capabilities at times.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be as close as you'll ever get Tubbs to admit that
the team we saw in the second half was probably more the real Frogs
than the one that zipped off to a 13-2 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the guys who are coming back can be hungrier than we
were going into this season,'' Tubbs said. ``It wasn't that we
lacked heart. The guys had heart. My wife has a lot of heart, too,
but she can't go out there and force turnovers when we need them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs knew this season _ and any hopes of playing their way
to the Garden _ was gone when the Ducks got back-breaking
3-pointers from A.D. Smith, Darious Wright and Terik Brown down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait till 1 o'clock,'' Tubbs said, ``and if
nobody calls, then this season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   He sounded almost relieved. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7972
\Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
