<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS WAIVE BENITEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. - The Diamondbacks cleared room on their 40-man
roster for the arrival of Korean right-hander  &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim by
asking for waivers on outfielder  &UR; Yamil Benitez for the purpose of
giving him his unconditional release.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Benitez was selected from Kansas City in the
expansion draft and hit .199 with nine home runs and 30 RBIs in 91
games. This spring, he was 3 for 15 with no homers and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 14 against San Francisco, Benitez became the first
player to hit a ball that came in contact with a girder supporting
the retractable roof of Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks added several outfielders to their roster over
the winter, and Benitez became a victim of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy thing to do,'' General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola
Jr. said. ``We wanted to do this in a way that was as fair as
possible to Yamil, to give him time to attempt to hook on with
another team rather than waiting until the end of the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kim, he is to report sometime next week. Club officials
will watch him throw a few times before deciding where to assign
him. &QL; 
Not ready for Teddy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks were considering signing 40-year-old
left-hander  &UR; Teddy
 &UR; Higuera to a minor league contract, but after watching him pitch
Saturday in Tucson and again at Mesa's HoHoKam Park on Wednesday,
the chances of completing a deal are highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Higuera, who resides in the Valley, was 94-64 with a 3.61 ERA
for the Milwaukee Brewers from 1985 to '94 and more recently
pitched in his native Mexico, where he caught the eye of  &UR; Derek
Bryant, a manager in the Diamondbacks' minor league system.
Higuera's agent arranged for the tryout with Diamondbacks Assistant
General Manager  &UR; Sandy Johnson and  &UR; Junior Noboa, the club's Latin
American scouting director. &QL; 
Williams heating up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman  &UR; Matt Williams continued to gain momentum with the
bat after a slow start, driving in three runs with a two-run double
and a solo home run, his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he even broke his bat on the home run,'' Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter said. &QL; 
What a relief &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre was roughed up by the
Chicago Cubs'
 &UR; Sammy Sosa on Wednesday, Arizona's next four pitchers pitched
admirably.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Vladimir Nunez gave up a pair of runs on two hits
in two innings, but also struck out two batters. One was Sosa in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez dropped down for a sidearm release on a couple of pitches
to Sosa and got him looking on a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an impressive sequence of pitches,'' pitching coach
 &UR; Mark
 &UR; Connor said. ``I like what I'm seeing from him right now. He can't
get careless, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Dan Carlson pitched two scoreless innings and
struck out two to get credit for the victory, and right-hander
 &UR; Aaron Small set the side down in order in the 10th to chalk up the
save. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
