<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY TAKEN TO TASK IN SUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A federal judge has given class-action status to a
lawsuit accusing The Walt Disney Co. of illegally charging for
health benefits for 4,000 retirees and longtime employees.
</P>
<P>
   The certification, issued Tuesday by U.S. District Court Judge
Terry Hatter Jr. in Los Angeles, represents a potentially
embarrassing legal battle over the treatment of employees who
helped make Disney a global entertainment giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney's got some dirty hands on this,'' said Robert Carbines,
one of the seven plaintiffs and a 32-year maintenance worker at
Disneyland who retired in 1991 at the age of 62. ``I feel strongly
that we're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute revolves around two moves by Disney to change its
longtime policy that 20-year employees receive free medical
coverage once they turned 62. In 1994, Disney boosted the age of
eligibility for free coverage to 65; in 1995, it began charging
premiums unless the retiree joined a health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has contended its contracts allowed it to impose charges
when the costs of coverage increased. But Carbines said Disney's
pledge of free coverage was explicit for any employee meeting three
conditions _ 20 years service, 30,000 hours of work and at least 62
years old. A Disney representative repeated that pledge in 1990 at
a meeting for employees considering retirement, Carbines asserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until 1994, all the paperwork and promises said we would
get benefits at no cost,'' Carbines said. ``It was all in black and
white with no fine print. When I got the letter in 1995 that they
had the right to make changes, it was like being hit by a
locomotive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbines, who lives in Fullerton in nearby Orange County, said
he pays a quarterly premium of $255 for HMO coverage for himself
and his wife, who is receiving chemotherapy treatments. ``The
result is that even with Medicare, you end up paying a tremendous
amount of money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatter previously certified the suit, which seeks to restore the
benefits to the affected employees, as a class action, but
attorneys subsequently announced in November 1997 that they had
reached an agreement in principle calling for Disney to reduce
premium costs. However, that deal subsequently collapsed amid
accusations that Disney planned to make changes not agreed to in
the settlement, such as doubling yearly out-of-pocket costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they reneged, we had no choice but to continue to press
forward on behalf of the thousands of Disney workers covered by the
lawsuit,'' said plaintiffs' co-counsel William Payne in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Disney issued a statement Wednesday: ``We are disappointed that
the previous settlement has been dissolved but will go forward with
defense of our position.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had no further comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 0128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
