<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-WOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY WAITING TO HAPPEN  
 WOOD BELIEVES ME CHANICS AT FAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. - It was stored in Kerry Wood's memory bank, next to
the Rookie of the Year season and the 20-strikeout performance
against Houston: The crack heard 'round the world.
</P>
<P>
   When Wood was 12, he saw footage of San Francisco pitcher Dave
Dravecky breaking his left arm against Montreal in 1989. The
injury, which the Expos' Hubie Brooks said sounded like a
firecracker, caused Dravecky to fall to the ground in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the first time I saw that video,'' Wood said Wednesday,
``I knew that any given day, it could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It did. Although the injury is different _ Wood, 21, suffered a
full ligament tear in his right elbow _ it is devastating. Surgery
and rehabilitation will keep the Chicago Cubs pitcher out of
baseball for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm to a point where I've realized I have no other choice,''
he said at HoHoKam Park after flying in from Chicago on Tuesday
night. ``I'm just going to get it done as soon as possible. I've
known guys who have had the surgery and come back to the level they
were, and some that were even throwing harder and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is seeking a second opinion, he is expected to
undergo surgery within two weeks. Commonly known as Tommy John
surgery, a tendon from Wood's left wrist will be used to replace a
ligament in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, who missed all of September with what was termed sprained
ligaments, threw 26 pitches on Saturday against Anaheim in his
first spring appearance. It is believed he suffered the injury
while throwing his first warm-up pitch before the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Some have criticized the Cubs for bringing Wood back last
postseason and risking injury, but the pitcher was quick to defend
his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not fair to say, to blame a team or an individual,'' he
said. ``To me, I've seen tape of my mechanics last year, and my
mechanics weren't as good as can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood suggested his mechanics _ throwing across his body _ put
extreme stress on his elbow and could have contributed to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs Manager Jim Riggleman acknowledged that Wood's injury ``was
inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had his ups and downs and I was holding my breath a
bit,'' Riggleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he has a sense of what's in store for him in the
coming year because he watched what Cubs pitcher Jeremi Gonzalez
had to endure last season.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's season ended abruptly in July after 20 starts because
of a severe elbow injury that required surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you're going to have good days and bad days, maybe even
bad weeks,'' he said. ``I know he struggled at times because he
didn't feel like part of the team. It would be tough for me to come
to the park and not feel like part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the first chance Wood had to see his teammates. If
first baseman Mark Grace's attitude is any indication, the pitcher
won't be made to feel like an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a great blow to us,'' Grace said. ``But the
thing we've got to do is make sure this kid feels like he's part of
the team. Even though he's going to be feeling bad and have a good
case of the blues, we've got to make sure he knows he's still a
part of this team and that we're behind him 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss could be devastating to the Cubs, who have watched Wood
become one of baseball's top attractions. He recently was awarded a
$690,000 salary, a record for a player with less than one year in
the major leagues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
