r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-MILLER-AZR &LR;      03-18 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER MEETING WITH PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Cardinals free-agent linebacker Jamir Miller arrived
in Boston on Wednesday night and is scheduled to meet with the New
England Patriots today, the Patriots confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a 1994 first-round draft pick of the Cardinals, has
played his entire career with the club. He was their leading
tackler last season despite playing the final 13 games and the
playoffs with a dislocated wrist. He was considered by many to be
the most valuable player on the defense in the absence of injured
tackle Eric Swann.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who escaped having the franchise tag placed on him _ the
Cardinals instead placed it on wide receiver Rob Moore _ previously
interviewed with the Chicago Bears as he attempts to determine his
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to look at people who might be a good fit,'' said
Bobby Grier, Patriots vice president of personnel. ``We think he's
a good player. He made over 100 tackles last year and he's been a
good pass rusher. When they got (Andre) Wadsworth and (Simeon) Rice
they took on the nickel and dime rushing roles and Jamir's role was
diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have Chris Slade at strong side outside linebacker
but would be willing to move him to the opposite side if Miller
were to sign. Slade signed a new long-term contract last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have said they want Miller back. They have a
two-year offer on the table worth about $3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said Wednesday that the club
continues to negotiate with Miller and his agent, Steve Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as long as you're doing that you've got a chance to get
something done,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, Cardinals vice president for player personnel,
acknowledged that Miller (6-foot-5, 266 pounds) is a big, strong
run stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we're weak,'' Ferguson said. ``We've said all
along that Jamir is a key player for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has said that he wants to return to the Cardinals but he
wants to make certain that the team he signs with will use him
significantly as a pass-rusher. He considers that one of his skills
that has not been best used.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported initially that Miller was looking to become the
highest-paid in the league at his position, but Baker said what
Miller wants is the opportunity to establish himself as a pass
rusher, which in turn would escalate his value.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is one of four key unrestricted free agents the Cardinals
hoped to sign back. They also want to re-sign Moore, although
negotiations have slowed and are expected to remain slow now until
the summer. They successfully re-signed safety Kwamie Lassiter, the
NFC interceptions leader last season. They lost seven-time Pro Bowl
left tackle Lomas Brown to the expansion Cleveland Browns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
