<HEADLINE>
SAINTS WANT WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - New Orleans Saints Coach  &UR; Mike Ditka would do almost
anything to get a chance to draft Heisman Trophy winner  &UR; Ricky
Williams, the Texas running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would trade our whole (1999) draft,'' Ditka said Wednesday
at the NFL meetings at the Arizona Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he also would include picks from future drafts, Ditka
said, ``Sure, why not? That's me. I just think he's that good. He's
 &UR; Earl Campbell with speed.''
</P>
<P>
   To get Williams, the Saints likely would have to go as high as
the second pick overall, owned by Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Ditka's statement, Eagles Coach  &UR; Andy Reid said he
would have to consider that.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he was exiting the NFC coaches' breakfast, Reid tapped
Ditka on the shoulder and said, smiling, ``We'll make that trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints offered the Cardinals their entire draft last year to
move up to the No. 2 spot overall. But the Cardinals turned down
the trade and instead made a deal with San Diego, acquiring two
first-round picks, a No. 2 and two players.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans would have two problems making a deal to move up for
Williams. The Saints don't have a second-round pick, forfeiting it
to St. Louis in a trade for wide receiver  &UR; Eddie Kennison.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Saints' first-round pick of No. 12 overall is
probably further than the Eagles would want to drop. &QL; 
No kickoff change
</P>
<P>
   The owners didn't vote on placing the ball on the 25-yard line
instead of the 20 following touchbacks.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to vote on it in May, but  &UR; Rich McKay, Tampa
Bay general manager who is co-chairman of the league's competition
committee, said there was ``sentiment not to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're tinkering with (changing) the yardage, people get
nervous,'' said Green Bay Coach  &UR; Mike Holmgren, the other
competition committee co-chairman. &QL; 
Logical explanation
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bills owner  &UR; Ralph Wilson, one of two dissenting votes
to giving Los Angeles an expansion franchise with conditions, said
he remains a supporter of the city's bid to become the league's
32nd team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think we should pit one city against another,''
said Wilson, referring to Los Angeles being given until Sept. 15 to
meet the NFL's hurdles or else the franchise goes to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The only other owner to vote against Los Angeles was  &UR; Al Davis,
who maintains he owns the rights to the city despite moving the
team to Oakland in 1995. &QL; 
Being flexible
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Cardinals lost starting left offensive tackle
 &UR; Lomas Brown to Cleveland in free agency, Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin won't
guarantee that the team will use one of its two first-round picks
on an offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is that there's a giant void at left tackle . .
. woe the Cardinals,'' Tobin said. ``Don't buy into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're going to address the offensive line in the draft.
But to say that's the No. 1 spot . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said the Cardinals will miss Brown, but he is confident
Brown can be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lomas Brown was productive for many, many years,'' Tobin said.
``I hated to lose him. But at some point, we were going to lose him
because of his age (35). It's just that the timetable got moved up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of time to address the left tackle position. We
have
 &UR; Anthony Clement, Matt Joyce. We could trade, get somebody in free
agency who becomes available after June 1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
