<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS CLOSER TO REELING IN ISMAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolina Panthers free-agent receiver Raghib Ismail wants to be
a Cowboy, a source told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his agent Jack Mula and the Cowboys are working to get it
done, with an agreement possibly coming as soon as Thursday. Mula
confirmed that a decision could come Thursday and denied that
Ismail has ruled out returning to Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's between Dallas and Carolina,'' Mula said. ``Each side has
given me their final proposals. It's just a matter of us picking
one. \RIsmail\S is supposed to let me know \RThursday\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The source said Mula has not been in contact with the Panthers
since last Friday, while talks with the Cowboys have intensified,
with both sides trading several contract proposals Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mula has said before that Ismail is looking for a contract
similar to the five-year, $16.5 million deal signed by 49ers
receiver J.J. Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   The source said the Cowboys have tweaked their offer by
increasing the signing bonus to $5 million from $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The added bonus, in addition to the fact that Ismail relishes
the opportunity to play with quarterback Troy Aikman and cornerback
Deion Sanders, helped the Cowboys gain Ismail's interest over
Carolina, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys land Ismail, he would be their biggest free-agent
acquisition since they signed Sanders in 1995. The contract would
be the most lucrative deal they've ever given to a player other
than Sanders who didn't start his career with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The inability to make plays down the field last season had the
Cowboys going into the off-season with the primary focus of
acquiring a quality speed receiver to play opposite Michael Irvin.
Ismail, a former Notre Dame star, became the main target after a
breakout 1998 season with Panthers that included career-best
numbers of 69 receptions for 1,024 yards and eight touchdowns. His
previous season-best was 36 catches in 1997 with the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   A six-year veteran in the NFL, Ismail began his professional
career in the Canadian Football League in 1991, playing two seasons
with Toronto before joining the Raiders in 1993. He has played with
the Panthers the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail could be the first step in what could turn out as the
biggest free-agent haul in team history. Once the situation is
resolved, the Cowboys might turn their attention toward acquiring
former Pro Bowl center Mark Stepnoski and linebacker Quentin
Coryatt.  &LR; tagtop:Clarence E. Hill, Jr. (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:cehill &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
