<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SWEET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN DUKE'S DOMINANCE CAN'T SOUR YOU ON THESE STORY LINES
</HEADLINE>
 16-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, it looks as if Duke is treating this NCAA Tournament the
way Jeff Gordon treats a NASCAR race, albeit in a decal-free
manner. But that doesn't mean we should fast-forward to March 29
and give Duke the title in a walk-over.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of stories unfolding in the 1999 version of
March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Kentucky coach Tubby Smith is in the Sweet 16 for
fifth time in six years. But did you know Smith has done so with
three schools _ Tulsa in 1994 and 1995, Georgia in 1996 and
Kentucky this year and last.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, one of the record five double-digit seeds to reach the
second week, barely made the tournament as an at-large team. The
Boilermakers lost five of their last six games before winning their
first two tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his reaction would have been if someone had told him
he would be at the East Regional this week in East Rutherford,
N.J., Purdue forward Brian Cardinal had a simple answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have asked where my seat was going to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of the middle week of the tournament, here are 16 Sweet
16 story lines to follow and ponder: 1. RARE SIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Florida senior guard Eddie Shannon is the winner of the United
States Basketball Writers Association's most courageous player
award. Shannon lost his vision in his right eye. He was hit in the
eye by a rock in the seventh grade. Vision in that eye
deteriorated. Finally, last fall, he had the damaged parts removed
and he was fitted with a prosthetic eye. 2. INSPIRING HERITAGE
</P>
<P>
   Auburn guard Doc Robinson is the nephew and grandson of key
organizers and participants in civil rights marches near Selma,
Ala., in 1965 that helped lead to voting rights legislation for
minorities. 3. HE IS THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   No longer a secret weapon, the world now knows the World. Wally
``World'' Szczerbiak (pronounced: Zir-bee-ak) has led Miami of Ohio
to two victories. The versatile 6-foot-8 forward has scored 53.6
percent of his team's points (67 of 125). 4. REALLY BIG TEN
</P>
<P>
   For much of the season, the Big Ten Conference was ranked as the
nation's top league. Many basketball observers were cynical,
though, because the Big Ten had flamed out in recent NCAAs. But no
conference has more teams (four) still playing than the Big Ten. 5.
REALLY SMALL PAC-10
</P>
<P>
   Coaches in the Pacific-10 Conference clamored that their league
deserved five bids because of recent NCAA performances. Each of the
last two NCAAs, the Pac-10 had four teams reach the Sweet 16. This
year, all four Pac-10 teams are gone. 6. KID COACHES
</P>
<P>
   They led teams to the 1987 Final Four. Now, they're trying to
get back as coaches. Billy Donovan, 33, is in his third season at
Florida; Steve Alford, 34, is in his fourth season at Southwest
Missouri State. 7. MENTORING PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   When Alford's Southwest Missouri State team faces top-seeded
Duke on Friday in the East Regional semifinals, it will be a
meeting of coaches from the Bob Knight Coaching Tree. Alford played
for Knight at Indiana; Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski played for Knight
at Army and was an assistant at Indiana. 8. GRIZZLED VETERANS
</P>
<P>
   While there are young whippersnappers like Alford and Donovan in
the Sweet 16, five veteran coaches are still hoping for their first
Final Four trip _ Iowa's Tom Davis (27 seasons), Connecticut's Jim
Calhoun (26), Temple's John Chaney (26), Maryland's Gary Williams
(20), and Purdue's Gene Keady (20). 9. YOUTH WILL BE SERVED
</P>
<P>
   Just one-third of the projected Sweet 16 starting lineups are
seniors. Players leaving early for the NBA have made college
basketball an underclassmen sport. 10. NEW FACES
</P>
<P>
   Six of the Sweet 16 teams have never reached the Final Four.
Other than Duke and Kentucky, only two have won championships
(Michigan State in 1979 and Ohio State in 1960). Outside of Duke
and Kentucky, the only other Sweet 16 team to reach the Final Four
this decade is Florida (1994). 11. OLD GUARD
</P>
<P>
   East Region top seed Duke and Midwest third seed Kentucky are
old hands at this NCAA Tournament stuff. They've combined for nine
championships, 24 Final Fours and 147 NCAA victories. Each has two
titles in the 1990s. Just one Final Four (1995) this decade has
been without either Duke or Kentucky. 12. REALLY OLD GUARD
</P>
<P>
   In NCAA terms, Kentucky's Wayne Turner is nearing membership in
AARP. He has played in a record 149 regular-season games and in 19
NCAA Tournament games. He's trying to become the fourth player to
participate in four Final Fours. 13. MAN WHO CAME TO RETIREMENT
</P>
<P>
   Tom Davis won't go gently into exile. Iowa's players are
delaying Davis' departure. The Hawkeyes are in the Sweet 16 for the
first time since 1988. Davis retired (or was asked to leave by
athletic director Bob Bowlsby) before the season. And wouldn't you
like to be reading Bowlsby's mail? 14. TRANSFER OF POWER
</P>
<P>
   If the seeds hold in the South, No. 1 Auburn will face No. 2
Maryland in the regional final. Each team features one of the
nation's top junior-college transfers: Chris Porter of Auburn and
Steve Francis of Maryland. 15. IN FAVOR OF UPSETS
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and Duke are the only teams to be ranked No. 1 this
season in The Associated Press poll. Each is top-seeded in a region
(Connecticut in the West, Duke in the East) that was ravaged by
upsets the first weekend. The second, third and fourth seeds in
both regions are out. 16. HUSH, SWEET CHARLOTTE
</P>
<P>
   In its past five games in Charlotte Coliseum (three in the
Atlantic Coast Conference tournament, two in the NCAA Tournament),
Duke won by an average of 31 points while shooting 53 percent from
the field and 46 percent from 3-point range. Good news for Blue
Devils' opponents _ no more Duke games in Charlotte. Bad news for
East Regional opponents _ Duke is 8-0 in regional games in East
Rutherford, N.J., the site for the semifinal and final. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
