<SLUG> BC-NEWHALL-LAND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWHALL LAND GETS EARFUL FROM INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. _ Show us the money.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message from some Newhall Land and Farming Company
shareholders to Thomas Lee, chief executive officer and chairman of
the company's board, at Wednesday's annual unit-holder meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The company's share price _ well under analysts' estimates of
its value _ took center stage at the meeting despite the company's
record $304 million in revenues and $1.89 net earnings per unit in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders asked Lee about the company's attempts to promote
the firm to Wall Street and whether efforts were being made to
boost share prices.
</P>
<P>
   Lee acknowledged those concerns early, describing at the
beginning of his presentation how most real estate stocks have
suffered in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our unit price has been very disappointing, and I know that
has been frustrating for all of us,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he fielded questions, Lee said the company is worth a
lot more than the company's own appraised value of about $30 a
unit. Referring to past estimates of the company that fell between
$25 and $50 a unit, Lee said the company ``clearly is in the upper
end of that range.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land units closed up 12.5 cents Wednesday at $23.375 on
17,900 shares traded.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to boost its current unit value by expanding
income-producing properties, selling residential units and
developing the company's upscale Bridgeport development.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the company will also try to obtain most of the
remaining entitlements for its Valencia housing projects this year.
</P>
<P>
   With its new and continuing operations, Lee said, ``1999 could
well be another record year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   John Yaldezian, a financial adviser for Prudential Securities,
said many investors are frustrated with the company's unit price.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting tired of seeing everything else they can put
their money into go up while Newhall Land sits at $23 to $24 a
share,'' he said. ``There's a lot of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   But businessman Lou Amen, one of the company's larger
shareholders, said he was not concerned with the low unit price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see $35 a share right now,'' he said. ``I want
to buy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
