<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC SHARES POUNDED AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Things have gone from bad to worse this year for
telecommunications equipment maker Tekelec.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the firm based in Calabasas northwest of Los Angeles
fell 26 percent Wednesday, the first trading day after the company
announced it would miss analysts' first quarter earnings estimates.
On trading of 9.5 million shares, or roughly six times the 30-day
average trading volume for Tekelec, the stock dropped $2.8125 to
close at $7.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The drop corresponded to downgrades of Tekelec shares by
SoundView Technology Group, Volpe, Brown Whelan &AMP; Co. and BT Alex
Brown Inc., where analysts rated Tekelec shares a ``buy,'' ``hold''
and ``buy'' respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement released after the close of trading
Tuesday, Tekelec said lower-than-expected sales for both switching
and diagnostic products would push first-quarter earnings per share
below analysts' expectations and below earnings of a year ago.
Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had expected the company to
earn 11 cents per share for the quarter that ended March 31,
compared to 10 cents one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec makes switching equipment used to transfer large
quantities of data across computer and telecommunications networks,
and the company also produces diagnostic tools used to optimize
network performance.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec President and Chief Executive Michael Margolis said some
customers delayed major equipment purchases until after
industrywide year 2000 problems are sorted out, and sales will
likely remain weak until at least the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe that our industry positioning and
longer-term outlook remains strong,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec, which employs about 450 people, has seen its shares
hammered over the last year on a string of disappointing news.
Since reaching a 52-week high of more than $25 in May, the stock
has lost more than two-thirds of its value.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, investors sent it down nearly a quarter after
Tekelec missed fourth-quarter earnings estimates by more than
15percent, prompting analyst Tim Savageaux of Volpe Brown Whelan
officially to declare the company ``in the Wall Street doghouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
