<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHROW-HEARING-LADN     03-18 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHROW-HEARING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER'S KILLER GETS SECOND CHANCE TO LIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sixteen years after LAPD Officer Paul Verna died
on the side of a road from six gunshot wounds, the convicted killer
strolled into court with a smile and another chance to beat the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   For Bryce Verna, the 25-year-old son of the slain Los Angeles
police Medal of Valor winner, the court appearance by killer
Kenneth Earl Gay on Wednesday was almost too painful to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these years, I thought the guy who killed my father was
going to die. I expected it,'' Bryce Verna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, I think this is ridiculous. He's trying to
weasel his way out of paying for what he did, and it's a pitiful
last-ditch effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a very good person. I loved him, and so did a
lot of other people. I hope this guy gets the death sentence again.
He deserves to die.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a judge ruled in December that Gay has one last chance
to save his own life because his attorney failed to represent him
adequately during the original sentencing hearing in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in San Fernando Superior Court, 41-year-old Gay
said he plans to mount his own defense in a new penalty phase
trial, despite admonishments from the judge not to expect special
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The mere presence of the lanky murderer noticeably disturbed
Paul Verna's widow, Sandra Jackson, as she sat in the front row.
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, the hearing vividly brings back her painful loss
and reopens a case that seemingly won't die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be sitting in the courtroom through every day of
this hearing,'' she said, holding back tears. The sentencing
hearing is scheduled to begin April 5 and is expected to last seven
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another torturous step in Jackson and her family's
effort to bring Gay to justice. Jackson persevered through the
first trial and sentencing, and then she rallied enough public
support and outrage in 1994 to convince the Writers Workshop not to
peddle a script that Gay wrote on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1994 interview with Daily News columnist Dennis
McCarthy, Jackson described Gay as a ``cruel and vicious person''
who has manipulated things to his own advantage for his entire
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess total outrage is the best way you could put my
feelings,'' Jackson said. ``The taxpayers have housed and fed him
on Death Row waiting for his execution, and what's he been doing?
Polishing his writing skills at the public's expense. There is
something totally wrong and sick about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor who sent Gay to Death Row on Sept. 20, 1985, was
flummoxed by the prospect that Gay might escape a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gay has a history of bad behavior on Death Row. He's been
on Death Row for a long, long time. That's where he belongs,'' said
Los Angeles County Deputy District Attorney Jeffrey C. Jonas.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he was murdered, Los Angeles police Officer Paul
Verna was 35, a motorcycle officer, an LAPD Medal of Valor winner
and the father of two boys. Verna made what appeared to be a
routine traffic stop June 2, 1983, of a car driven by Raynard Paul
Cummings, with 27-year-old Gay sitting in the passenger seat.
</P>
<P>
   The car had been stolen, and Cummings took out a gun and fired a
shot at Verna. Cummings then handed the gun to Gay, who got out of
the car, walked up to the fallen officer and fired five shots into
his body.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Verna left behind 4-year-old son Ryan,
9-year-old son Bryce and his wife Sandra. The family moved to
Oregon shortly after the murder, and Sandra recently returned to
Los Angeles and remarried. But the memories of her late husband
will never leave her.
</P>
<P>
   The case lingers, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-page letter to the Daily News in 1994, Gay vowed to
``stir the pot until the truth simmers to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately in our system of justice, guilt is assumed,'' he
wrote. ``It takes cash money to prove your innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, the state's highest court granted Gay a new
sentencing hearing, finding that his attorney, Daye Shin, lied and
mishandled Gay's defense during the original penalty phase of the
trial. Shin since has been disbarred for his action in an unrelated
case.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, not happy with his new court-appointed public
defender, Gay dismissed attorney Kenneth Lezin during the hearing
and opted to represent himself in his final attempt to convince a
jury that he deserves a life sentence without parole rather than
the lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not relieving Mr. Lezin for his need for more time to
prepare for a case. I have other important differences with Mr.
Lezin, tactical trial differences,'' Gay said. ``I'm aggressively
pursuing my right to a speedy trial,'' Gay told Judge Ronald S.
Coen.
</P>
<P>
   Coen warned Gay that ``self-representation is always unwise,''
and he told the convict to expect no special indulgence by the
court or additional library privileges at San Quentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you know me, but we've never met,'' Coen said,
stressing to the defendant that he's been involved in 18 death
penalty cases as a judge and attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was charged myself with spitting on the sidewalk,'' Coen
added, ``I would hire myself an attorney.'' He then granted Gay's
request.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Jackson's new husband, Norm Jackson, an LAPD detective,
called Gay's decision to represent himself ``idiotic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question,'' Norm Jackson said, ``Gay deserves to
die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
