<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-CLIPPERS-     03-18 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-CLIPPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS NO SWEAT FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul Pierce grew up in Los Angeles, participated in
local Police Athletic Leagues, played pickup games at Rogers Park,
and, yes, even paid attention to the second-class Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I thought they were going to be the team of
the '90s,'' the Celtics rookie said of Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's opponent.
``They had Ron Harper, Mark Jackson, Danny Manning . . . they had a
nice squad.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus on the past is not coincidental, because the current
Clippers are a mess. And that was fine with the Celtics, who
thought they were a mess until they stepped on the court and saw
the very sad team from LA. By the time the Celtics finished an easy
night, their five-game losing streak was gone, and they were on a
plane headed for Milwaukee, laughing about a 118-84 win at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   You probably shouldn't be wondering about this, but just in case
you are let's get it out of the way: The game was never close.
Never. The Clippers led, 14-10, in the first quarter, which led
Rick Pitino to call a timeout. But it wasn't a true lead, because
very few people among the 18,263 on hand would tell you that they
thought the Celtics were in danger. Pitino said before the game
that the Clippers were a dangerous opponent. Maybe he meant they
are a danger to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the night, Clippers coach Chris Ford was saying
the Celtics intimidated his players. And the Celtics were saying
what they wanted to say all along: We couldn't lose to these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a team we knew we could go out and beat,'' Ron Mercer
said. ``We were getting everybody back in the groove. Guys were
coming off the bench and scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason no Celtic was forced to play 30 minutes. The
first Clipper shot of the night? Airball. They finished the game
shooting 36 percent from the field, while the Celtics made 57
percent of their shots. It was a 5-point game after the first
quarter, but by halftime it was 54-39 and the only question was,
how high?
</P>
<P>
   As Mercer said, heroes were everywhere on the parquet and bench.
Kenny Anderson led all scorers with 21 points. He missed only two
of his 12 attempts and even snagged five rebounds. ``If you look at
my career, I've always been a rebounder,'' Anderson said, sounding
like a 6-foot-1-inch Wilt Chamberlain. But, then, that's what the
Clippers do. They boost your esteem as well as your win total. They
have played 22 games this season and lost 21 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a team we should beat,'' Anderson said. ``You look at
the percentages and we have to beat a team like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was disgusted with his team after the game, saying, ``I
just wish they'd come out and play with passion.'' Pierce could
tell Ford stories about several Clippers coaches wishing the same
thing before they were inevitably fired. The Celtics outrebounded
the Clippers, 56-37. They had passion. One of the passionate ones
was Vitaly Potapenko, the newly acquired 6-10 center. He had 14
points and 11 rebounds. He excited the crowd in the second quarter
when he ripped a rebound away from Lorenzen Wright, forcing a jump
ball. Wright wound up on the seat of his pants after Potapenko's
pursuit. The fans loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys told me there were great fans here, and I felt it
tonight,'' Potapenko said.
</P>
<P>
   He and everyone else. The more the Clippers put up their
airballs (at least four) and flubbed their layups, the more energy
the Celtics seemed to gain. They led, 82-66, after three quarters.
By that time, Tony Battie was working on a nice field-goal streak.
He made all four of his attempts against the Pacers Sunday. He made
his first six Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. He missed his next attempt, but
this is the kind of night it was: He grabbed the rebound and made
the putback. He finished with 14 points and 9 rebounds in 20 active
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a scorer in college, but I don't have to do that here
with the three guys we have here,'' he said, referring to Antoine
Walker, Mercer, and Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he was happy with the bench, happy with Anderson,
happy with the effort, happy with the 29 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this for the team,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Minor had 13 points and five assists. Dana Barros had five
rebounds and six assists. The only complaint was from a merciless
crowd, which wanted the Celtics to shoot at the end for a nice
``120'' instead of ``118.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen. But the point was clear. The Clippers are
bad. Pierce was asked what people in LA said about them in his
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I can't tell you,'' he said. ``I don't
want anyone to get mad at me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
