<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-LEAFS-BOS &LR;      03-18 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-LEAFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS RUFFLE LEAFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ With a month to go, and no assurance that they'll be
north of the NHL's no-fly zone come playoff time, the Bruins made
their first visit to the Air Canada Centre Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and
left with their confidence flying high.
</P>
<P>
   Sparked by Jason Allison's tiebreaking goal with 6:31 to go in
the third period, the Bruins knocked off the Maple Leafs, 4-1, and
dug an inch deeper into the eighth _ and final _ playoff spot in
the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big, big win for us,'' said Bruins wing Rob DiMaio, who
rocketed in a rare power-play goal for a 1-0 lead with 6:27 to go
in the middle period. ``It's definitely a confidence booster
because our schedule right to the end now is very demanding. It's
nice to beat a team like this.''
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the Maple Laffs any longer. They've got one of the
game's premier centers in Mats Sundin. In the offseason, they made
arguably the best free agent signing in the game's history when
they brought in Curtis Joseph to protect their net. They're not
among the elite challengers for the Cup, but they came in
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night ranked fourth overall in the Eastern Conference
with 84 points.
</P>
<P>
   A tie against the Leafs would be a point well taken.
</P>
<P>
   Two points taken, especially in their building, could provide
the Bruins with an emotional charge over the final four weeks of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big win, but that's all it is until the next one,''
said captain Ray Bourque, who has been at this chasing-a-berth
business for two decades. ``We got two good points, especially on
the road, so we'll put our two points up there and wait till the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio's goal looked as if it might stand up for the two points.
A key to the club's top checking line, he came over the boards with
linemates Tim Taylor and P.J. Axelsson with only a few seconds
remaining on a man-advantage. Led slightly by a Grant Ledyard feed,
he moved to the outside of the right circle and unloaded a slapper
that beat CuJo to the near side, right post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw them out there because I didn't like what I'd seen
from our skilled guys,'' said coach Pat Burns, his club rebounding
well from an emotionless loss in Buffalo Saturday night. ``I put
them out, and they got the goal, and maybe those other guys got the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   The real spark for Boston didn't show, however, until the Leafs
tied it with 12:06 to go in the third, ending Byron Dafoe's bid for
a career-high eighth shutout. Parked in the middle, tough guy Tie
Domi gloved a Bryan Berard shot and shoveled the puck to the right
of the slot, where Igor Korolev banged it in for the 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was Tie, and nothing against him, but when he gloved
it I was sure he'd shoot it,'' said Dafoe, whose record improved to
24-22-8. ``I thought for sure he'd spin around and shoot. But he
psyched me out, and he psyched my D-men (Dave Ellett and Ledyard),
and pushed it to the side. I don't even know who scored it.''
</P>
<P>
   But 5:35 later, sent away with a pretty Sergei Samsonov feed off
the left-wing board, a breaking Allison motored in from center ice
and beat CuJo with a doorstep wrister to the top right corner. The
finish took touch, but the key was the relay, Samsonov feathering
his backhander to center ice, just slightly behind Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Khristich banged in an insurance goal on the power play
with 4:49 to go. Anson Carter potted an empty-netter for the 4-1
final.
</P>
<P>
   The only blemish on the Bruins' night was a bungled Landon
Wilson penalty shot with 7:41 gone in the second. Hauled down
rodeo-style by Alexander Karpotsev, Wilson was immediately awarded
the free attempt from center ice by referee Steve Walkom. A former
Leafs first-round pick, Wilson took off from the red line, swooped
in, and lifted a wrister from the slot that sailed over the
crossbar and hit nothing but glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was back there saying, `Hey, leave him alone,' '' said
Burns, trying to keep Wilson's teammates from offering advice on
how to shoot. `` `C'mon,' I said, `Just shut up and let him go.' I
didn't want him to listen to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't excactly the shot heard 'round the world. When the
night was over, two points put away, it instead was a shot easily
forgotten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
