<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASADENA OFFICIALS DENY RAIDERS REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Officials denied a report Wednesday that indicated
the City Council sent out feelers to Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis
about his plan to return the team to the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners meeting in Phoenix this week agreed to award Los
Angeles an expansion franchise in September if a suitable stadium
can be found and financing made available.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has long claimed that he owns the exclusive rights to the
area and that he plans to return some day, unless the league pays
him compensation for taking over the territory. Additionally, Davis
said he is not currently in negotiations with anyone in Los Angeles
about a return by the team.
</P>
<P>
   But when the unpredictable Raiders owner was asked if the
Pasadena City Council had contacted the Raiders, the Associated
Press reported his reply as, ``Oh, you heard about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena Mayor Chris Holden, whose father, Los Angeles City
Councilman Nate Holden, is an ally of Davis', said the city has no
current interest in wooing the Raiders to Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what (Davis is) talking about,'' Holden said.
``I've never talked to him about this issue, and there's nothing
that the City Council has been entertaining in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders officials were unavailable for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Paul Little affirmed that the city has not
undertaken negotiations with the Raiders _ or any other NFL entity
for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has been in contact with Mr. Davis I would actually
hope that the City of Pasadena would support the L.A. Coliseum
effort to bring an expansion team to Los Angeles,'' Little said.
``That seems to be in our best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Little said he is about to propose a resolution backing the plan
currently favored by the NFL for bringing an expansion franchise to
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl through its management, the Rose Bowl Operating
Company, has been a player in any deal to bring the NFL to Los
Angeles. It is likely the stadium would be a temporary home for a
team, while a permanent stadium is constructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said that the Rose Bowl would be an appropriate
venue for a transition facility,'' Holden said.
</P>
<P>
   Porfirio Frausto, a political appointee to the RBOC, who sits on
the football committee said it would be foolish to enter into any
agreement with Davis or the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be slicing our own throat to even entertain that,'' he
said. I'd be (upset) if something's going on behind our backs. But
... I just don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Jacobs said Davis was likely attempting to manipulate the
NFL with his comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just stoking the fire,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
