<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS' TAILSPIN NEVER ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Celtics were back home Wednesday night. They were
coming off an 0-5 road trip, one which had Rick Pitino noting they
were a much better team at the end of the trip than at the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, the Celtics were a much better team Wednesday
night than the one they played. Only a few, very lucky Eastern
Conference teams _ Boston, New York, and Toronto _ have the
privilege of hosting the Clippers this season. It's as close to an
automatic W as there is.
</P>
<P>
   It was a year to the day _ March 17, 1998 _ that the Clippers
last won a game on the road. That was in Golden State. There were
eight more road losses at the end of last season and 11 more this
season. The 118-84 drubbing at the hands of the Celtics dropped
them to a Washington Generals-ish 1-21. If they lose their next
three, they will be on a two-win pace for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once noted that the definition of modern art was that
you put the picture over a hole in the wall _ and then take it down
because you decided you liked the hole better. That's the sad,
almost inevitable fate of the Clippers. People come and go and
cover the hole, but in the end, the hole still looks a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   They were beyond horrible Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. They didn't defend,
they didn't rebound, they didn't shoot, but, worst of all in coach
Chris Ford's mind, they just didn't care. After 22 games, Ford said
he had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when coaches have to sugarcoat things,'' he
said, ``but there are times when you also have to tell it like it
is. Now is that time. I find it difficult to sugarcoat things. You
have to play with a passion. You owe it to the fans, to everyone
else, to play this game with a passion. You can go out there and
get clocked, but dammit, at least go out there and play your heart
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino had called the Clippers ``a dangerous opponent'' and they
are in this sense: Playing them now is as close to a no-win
situation as you're going to get in a league that counts wins and
losses. You lose to the Clippers, you end up leading the late
edition of ``SportsCenter.'' You beat them, you might not even
warrant a video highlight, although it does count the same in the
standings as a win over a real team.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino noted the Clippers go ``10 deep,'' although three of
those 10 are lads by the names of Charles Smith, Tyrone Nesby, and
Darrick Martin, all of whom started the season and probably belong
in the CBA. But even the supposedly gifted Clipper players _ and
they have a few _ Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night looked like the last place they
wanted to be was on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want professionalism from your team. They're putting on an
NBA uniform,'' Ford said. ``It's supposed to be the elite league in
the world. You'd think they'd have some passion to play the game.
You can forget money and all that. Go out and accept the challenge
and do what it takes to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might be undermanned or undersized, but nothing should
stop the passion. I don't care what the score is, or who the
opponent is, or where the game is being played. Respect the game
enough that you'll go out there and play with a passion. That's all
I want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were outscored in all four quarters, including a
humiliating 36-18 in the fourth. They allowed Greg Minor to merit
postgame consideration from the media. Prior to the game, veteran
Sherman Douglas sounded disgusted as he talked about the attitude
he sees.
</P>
<P>
   Someone made the mistake of asking Douglas if the Clippers' new
arena, scheduled to open next season, would be a plus. Douglas
looked mystified.
</P>
<P>
   ``A building doesn't score points,'' he said. ``You need
players. And direction. You need a game plan from the front office
all the way down. When you've been here a long time, you accept
losing. That's one of the biggest bridges we have to cross. You
can't accept losing.''
</P>
<P>
   We got our first look at center Michael Olowokandi. He's making
progress, but he's a project. There aren't many No. 1 picks who
know more about cricket and rugby than basketball, but the Candy
Man does. He's big, mobile, and supposedly a quick study, but Ford
wants him to take the ball into the middle and the first three
times the rook got the ball low, he went baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to play the way the coach wants us to
play,'' Olowokandi said. He hesitated, adding, ``although we make a
lot of mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, of course, knew exactly what the situation was, but it
does beat unemployment _ barely. Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, he looked like
that Buckingham Palace guard in the television commercial who
stands stoically on the sidewalk waiting for his uniform to come
back from the cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   A comedian once noted that he didn't like taking exotic or
dangerous vacations because ``my idea of a vacation is not to have
to worry about dying.'' That's how Ford must feel. If he keeps his
sanity, and what's left of his hair, then this will have deemed to
have been a successful season. No one waits till next year. They
try to survive this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
