<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESILIENCY MARKS TUGNUTT'S CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Guy Hebert jokes that Ron Tugnutt probably still has
that ``big goofy grin and looks like ``he's going to do your taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But on a serious note, Hebert says the bookish-looking Tugnutt,
who has a league-leading 1.67 goals against average, deserves a lot
of credit for turning his career around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot about him, said Hebert of his former teammate.
``To go down (to the minors for the entire 1995-96 season) and make
it back ... he's a pretty resilent guy. It's a great story.
</P>
<P>
   Tugnutt, who played 28 games for the Ducks in '93-94, good
naturedly said he looked Anaheim's first team picture and ``I think
he (Hebert) has lost some hair.
</P>
<P>
   When it was Tugnutt's turn to get serious the Ottawa goalie said
his year in the American Hockey League ``makes times like this so
much better.
</P>
<P>
   Tugnutt also said he would have retired before the '96-97 season
if he hadn't caught on with a NHL team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was good enough to play, he said. ``I was lucky that
(then Ottawa GM) Pierre Gauthier felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting out: Fredrik Olausson was scheduled to sit out
Wednesday's game due to various aches and pains, including a pulled
side muscle. But the Anaheim defenseman was forced to play when
Jason Marshall became ill before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Returns: After a nine-game stint with Cincinnati of the AHL,
Johan Davidsson returned to the Ducks' lineup, playing with Jim
McKenzie and Antti Aalto.
</P>
<P>
   Davidsson, who had one goal and seven points with Cincinnati,
had three goals and seven points in 51 games with the Ducks before
being sent down on Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Anaheim announced that single-game tickets for the
Stanley Cup playoffs will go on sale at 9 a.m. Saturday, March 27
at the Pond box office and TicketMaster outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert to start: Hebert, who was given both Sunday and Monday
off to recharge his batteries is expected to start tonight's game
against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie has played in 58 of Anaheim's first 68 games.
With 14 games remaining he could set a career-high in games. Hebert
played in 67 in the '96-97 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
