<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY IS FIGURING OUT WHAT NFL WANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Los Angeles has been given a six-month window of
opportunity by the magnanimous National Football League to produce
a worthy expansion package.
</P>
<P>
   To this, the groups representing Carson and the New Coliseum
humbly say thank you. Now all they need is to be told exactly what
the league wants.
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps the strangest component to the game the NFL
played this week here with L.A. With sweeping gestures and voices
dropped an octave for effect, owners expressed several concerns
about the two L.A. groups, from the financing of the stadium to the
suggested brand of toilet paper in the luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   But when pressed for specifics, exactly what they do or do not
like and what specifically needs to be done, many owners admitted
they haven't a clue. They haven't even seen copies of the
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know,'' said Buffalo owner Ralph C. Wilson, one of
two dissenters in the vote Tuesday giving L.A. a six-month leash.
``We didn't really get a recommendation from the (expansion)
committee. That's why we gave them six months. They'll find out if
L.A. is viable or not and come up with a recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners who are on the expansion committee may know,'' said
one team executive on background. ``But they really haven't told
us. That's one reason we had so much trouble this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The league hasn't said much to those intimately involved with
the Carson and Coliseum proposals, either. The league has yet to
tell either group what needs to be solved in the proposal, how much
it wants in a franchise fee, and how large the public investment
must be.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the full ownership heard either group was at a
special meeting in October. ``And I can't imagine a lot of owners
remember what they heard back then,'' said the team exec. The
expansion committee heard brief, 30-minute updates from the two
groups in January.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion committee is scheduled to come to L.A. in early
April to meet with both ownership groups and visit the sites. The
committee's mandate is to select one site by mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   You would think -- and hope -- that L.A.'s NFL future wouldn't
come down to one road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Sweeney, the Carson city councilman who has been on the
front lines of the bid, welcomes the league to study ever nuance of
the bid and tell the city exactly what it needs to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want feedback,'' said Sweeney. ``We want the chance to show
the league what we've covered to date, the chance to answer any of
their concerns. If something is important, tell us. We're ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner came out here and said he was satisfied with
the environmental report on the site, said we were further along in
the process. But I kept reading and hearing owners this week say
they had environmental concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Michael Ovitz, the chairman of Artists
Management Group who is speaheading the Carson project, said Ovitz
has no sense of what the league may want or need. But he added that
Ovitz is also not particular concerned about it, either, because
his proposal is viable and he's willing to do whatever the league
asks.
</P>
<P>
   The New Coliseum group has had a similar reaction to hints that
the league wants a broader base of owners involved if it is to
return to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   When the expansion committee questioned Ed Roski's debt load in
January, the Kings owner responded by adding billionaire Eli Broad
to the team and making him the principal owner, the man responsible
for the 30 percent investment in the team.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said Wednesday that if the league wants broader
participation, he's willing to listen. ``We already have a good
cross section of business people, but if the league suggests
someone else, we're open to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Published reports have said the league would like Roski to take
a less prominent role, but Roski said he's never been told that by
anyone in the NFL. Sources close to Roski said the group will be
adding a new equity partner to the team before the NFL visit. A
source also said that while Fox and Dodgers owner Rupert Murdoch
has a stake in the Staples Center, the Lakers and Kings, plus the
Sunday NFC TV rights, he has no plans to get involved in the L.A.
NFL debate.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the league will apparently cram all of
its due diligence and arm-twisting into the next six weeks. The
expansion committee is co-chaired by Carolina owner Jerry
Richardson and New England owner Bob Kraft, and it has been given
the power to shape the L.A. proposal the way it wants.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be as easy as asking the two parties to join forces.
Roski and Broad, actively committed to the redevelopment of
downtown L.A., are committed to the New Coliseum
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz was once approached by Roski to join the Coliseum group
and only has a memorandum of understanding in Carson. But he says
he and partner Ron Burkle are committed to Carson.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum has also received an endorsement from Disney's
Michael Eisner, too, who hired Ovitz away from the agency he
created and then fired him a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I hate this leverage game we're playing,'' said
Wilson, the Bills owner. He's not alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 0210EST &QL; 
