<SLUG> BC-RAC-VALENZUELA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY VALENZUELA ORDERED TO APPEAR FOR ARRAIGNMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL MONTE, Calif. _ Ex-jockey Pat Valenzuela was ordered
Wednesday to appear for arraignment in Superior Court on suspicion
he robbed a cabbie of $150 at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Valenzuela, 36, faces one count of robbery with the
special allegation that he used a gun to commit the crime. If
convicted, he faces a maximum of 16 years in prison, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arraignment is set for March 31 at 8:30 a.m. He has pleaded
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, of El Monte, was once one of world's best jockeys.
In 1989, he rode Sunday Silence to victories in the Kentucky Derby
and Preakness. He also rode winners at the Santa Anita Handicap and
the Santa Anita Derby on two occasions each.
</P>
<P>
   But, a string of drug-related problems, misdemeanor criminal
charges and brushes with the boards of stewards at various tracks
caused him to lose his rider's license. He was suspended from
racing in October 1997 and has not raced since.
</P>
<P>
   A motion by Valenzuela's attorney to dismiss the robbery case
for lack of concrete evidence linking the jockey to the robbery was
denied. Another motion to release the ex-jockey on his own
recognizance was also denied.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rio Hondo Municipal Court Judge Francis A. Gately
ordered Valenzuela's bail reduced from $70,000 to $40,000.
Valenzuela's sister said a bond freeing the jockey from custody
would be posted by this morning.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Jose Valdez, a driver for the Green Valley Cab
Company, testified through an interpreter that around 11 p.m. on
Feb. 24, he was dispatched to a home in the 2700 block of Gladys
Avenue in Rosemead.
</P>
<P>
   His fare, a clean-shaven man about 5-foot-6 or 5-foot-7,
weighing 140 to 150 pounds clad in a dark jacket and wearing a
baseball cap, was waiting outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got in the taxi and asked me if I was really busy that
night,'' Valdez recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, who wears a mustache and goatee, is 5-4 and weighs
125 pounds. The suspect, whose face Valdez did not see clearly,
asked to go to El Monte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was maneuvering (the cab) to back away and go to El Monte
and at the same moment he took out a gun and put it to my
stomach,'' Valdez said. ``My reaction was that if I struggled he
would probably unload it on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The robber took $150 in ones, fives, tens and twenties; then
fled into the night, Valdez testified.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than 24 hours later, Valdez said he was dispatched
to Spike's Bar on Garvey Avenue in Rosemead. At the bar, a man who
intended to take a cab home, declined Valdez's services.
</P>
<P>
   As the cabbie prepared to leave the dimly lit bar, he was
approached by a second man who asked for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez testified that because of the tone of the man's voice, he
believed he was speaking to the same person who had robbed him.
</P>
<P>
   At that point in the testimony, prosecutor Katie Albrecht asked
Valenzuela to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-jockey, handcuffed to a chair, and clad in a white dress
shirt, wool pants and oxford shoes recited twice: ``Take me to El
Monte.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdez then said Valenzuela's voice wasn't the same voice he
heard during the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 11 of Valenzuela's friends and family members
attended the hearing. His sister, Christine Wing, said the
prosecution case was ``unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat didn't do this she said. ``There's a lot of evidence to
show that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
