<HEADLINE>
SENATORS RALLY TO TIE KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Ottawa Senators had every reason to throw
in the towel. They were down by two goals and playing in
California, where they had won only twice in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   But these aren't the Ottawa Senators of old. Instead of folding,
they rallied to tie the Anaheim Mighty Ducks 2-2 Wednesday night at
the Pond before 16,026.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a great team, they've got speed from the first line
through the fourth line,'' Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said. ``They
might be the best team we've played all year other than Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The team that Mighty Ducks general manager Pierre Gauthier
helped mold, probably deserved even better. The Senators (38-20-9)
likely would have added another point to their Eastern
Conference-leading total of 85 had not a goal by flashy rookie
Marian Hossa been waved off in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 2-0 in the second period, the Senators
dominated the majority of the game. They outshot the Ducks 43-21
and on the rare occasion that Anaheim generated a scoring chance,
goalie Damian Rhodes was there to rescue them.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes' biggest save came with just over two minutes to play in
regulation when Tomas Sandstrom stripped John Gruden of the puck
and put a perfect backhand centering pass on the stick of Marty
McInnis, who was alone in front of the net. Somehow, Rhodes got his
left pad over to the post and stopped the Anaheim winger's
game-winning bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McInnis) made a great move and the goalie made a great
save,'' said Hartsburg, who knew full well that his team would have
its hands full after Ottawa was shut out by the Kings on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they had lost two in a row and that they haven't lost
three in a row all season,'' said Hartsburg of the Senators, who
are only 2-12-2 in games played in California.
</P>
<P>
   The tie was a mixed blessing for the Ducks, who fell six points
behind fourth-place Phoenix and lead sixth-place St. Louis by only
three points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't complain, but we can't be satisfied,'' said Teemu
Selanne, whose best scoring chance of the night was a shot that hit
the post in the second period with the Ducks up 2-1 at the time.
``It's not our best game, but one point this time of year is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning seven consecutive games, the Ducks are 0-2-2 in
their past four and have squandered a three-goal lead and a
two-goal advantage in the two ties. But Selanne says Anaheim must
look ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in good position, we want fourth, we can't look back,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' biggest break came midway through the first period
when Hossa appeared to have tied the game 1-1 just 70 seconds after
Pascal Trepanier had scored Anaheim's first goal in over seven
periods of play.
</P>
<P>
   Hossa beat Guy Hebert easily from close range, but the video
goal judge ruled that Magnus Arvedson's skate was in the crease,
even though he appeared to be trapped in by Fredrik Olausson and
Paul Kariya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
