<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPORTS-CALIFORNIA-SF     03-18 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPORTS-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SLUMPING ASIAN TRADE TAKES SPARKLE OFF CALIFORNIA'S ECONOMY  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A dark sign has appeared in the midst of
California's continuing economic boom. Foreign trade, which helped
bring the state out of recession several years ago, is shrinking,
with no turnaround in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis sweeping California's major trading partners
in East Asia has caused the state's exports to drop, costing
thousands of high-tech manufacturing jobs in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Governor Gray Davis and other elected Democrats in
Sacramento say, is to look south to Mexico and to the rest of Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Trade with Mexico and its neighbors has grown rapidly in recent
years, and California policymakers are planning an ambitious series
of initiatives to improve relations with Latin America and boost
trade.
</P>
<P>
   However, experts warn that although the new Latin gambit holds
promise, the difference between hype and reality will be hard to
sort out.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, they say, aside from reaching out across the
southern border, Sacramento has no clear strategy to help
California navigate the fast-changing global economy.
</P>
<P>
   The new initiatives include:
</P>
<P>
   -- WOOING MEXICO. When Davis and top lawmakers traveled to
Mexico last month on a high-profile trade mission, they said the
diplomacy would bring lucrative new business for California.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mexico imported $13.3 billion from California, rising
from No. 3 among the state's export destinations to No. 2,
outpacing Canada. In the second half of the year, Mexico even
bested No. 1 Japan, which is trapped in a lengthy recession, and
Mexico is expected to keep the top spot in 1999 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures may be misleading. Much of the increase in
exports is in components sent to Mexico's maquiladoras, or border
assembly plants, where they are put together and sent back to
California. As a result, official data show an increase in trade,
yet critics say the only net effect is to transfer factory jobs
from California to low-wage Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of Mexico's potential, Davis brought home from last
month's trip a deal with Telmex, the Mexican telecommunications
giant, to move its U.S. headquarters from Houston to San Diego _ a
total of 600 new jobs for California, Telmex officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After the hype faded, however, company officials admitted that
the move will create only 20 jobs in California in the near future
and that the deal was under way before Davis took office.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Flores, Davis' top aide for Mexican affairs, says that
although results won't be immediate, ``we're establishing a good
relationship, and out of that will come good business and good
policy on lots of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo is scheduled to make a
three-day visit to California in May, a sign that Mexico expects
the new relationship to produce concrete results.
</P>
<P>
   -- MAQUILADORAS. Davis and top lawmakers are planning to forge
close ties with Mexico's maquiladoras, hoping to create ``synergy''
between Southern California's white-collar industries and the
blue-collar brawn of Tijuana. The state Trade and Commerce Agency,
which is in charge of trade promotion, and influential lawmakers
such as state Senator Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, say
maquiladoras represent a lucrative source of contracts for
California firms.
</P>
<P>
   A provision in the North American Free Trade Agreement obliges
maquiladoras to cut their imports of components from Asia after
Jan. 1, 2001. Baja California's maquiladoras import $4 billion
annually from Asia, and Sacramento officials hope California
manufacturers will substitute much of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   However, some experts say that Asian corporations are now busy
building their own component factories in Mexico, leaving
California with little likely benefit from the 2001 change. In
addition, California's labor unions, which gave Davis crucial
support in his election campaign, complain about job losses to
Mexico and note that the Mexican government has a widely criticized
record of repressing independent unionizing in the maquiladoras.
</P>
<P>
   -- SOUTH AMERICA. Since the state opened its first foreign trade
office in Tokyo in 1987, the legislature has eagerly expanded the
number of offices _ which serve as the state's own embassies _ to
nine, and this year's budget includes money for four new offices,
including one in Brazil. Polanco, who calls South America
``California's biggest untapped market,'' is sponsoring legislation
to open an office in Argentina, too.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil and Argentina are indeed huge markets, part of Mercosur,
the region's prosperous trade bloc. Although they now rank only
16th and 25th among California's export markets, they have been
rising rapidly in importance, with big appetites for California
electronics, and electrical and transportation equipment.
</P>
<P>
   However, the timing of California's South American offensive
couldn't be worse: Brazil recently plunged into economic crisis,
pulling Argentina into recession.
</P>
<P>
   With or without the new Latin America focus, support among state
policymakers for foreign trade is strong and bipartisan because of
its undeniable economic logic. California is a giant on the
international economic stage, with exports exceeding those of all
but six nations. In the Bay Area, more than 1 in 4 jobs are
directly or indirectly linked to foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, California's foreign exports fell to $104.9
billion, a decrease of 4.2 percent from 1997. It was the first
decrease since state export records began in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco customs district, which includes the entire
Bay Area, the drop was worse: 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The trade slump has caused a wave of layoffs in Silicon Valley
and elsewhere. Last year, the number of manufacturing jobs in the
Bay Area decreased by 1.8 percent, a drop of 9,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The state government's economic policy now appears to be in a
period of drift, floating between the free-market philosophy of the
Wilson years and a Democratic strategy that is still undefined.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators, apparently waiting for leadership from Davis,
have refrained from reintroducing an ambitious series of bills that
were blocked by Wilson last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were influenced by the California Economic Strategy
Panel, an advisory group of business executives, labor leaders and
state officials that has advocated the creation of regional
alliances of business, academia and government.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis administration, in turn, appears in part to be waiting
for the panel, which is scheduled to release a series of policy
recommendations in April.
</P>
<P>
   The panel report is expected to recommend the creation of two
``clusters,'' or regional industrial alliances: around the
University of California's planned campus at Merced, which would
become the center of food-industry research and development; and in
Southern California's aerospace industry, which would be revamped
to focus on satellite communications.
</P>
<P>
   Both industries have huge potential for increasing exports,
especially to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say they hope the panel's backing for alliances
between the public and private sectors will prompt a policy
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the state's foreign trade programs have been cobbled
together over the years without a coherent organizational strategy
and without much regard for the kind of services the private sector
would really like to see the state provide,'' said Jock O'Connell,
a trade consultant and economic policy analyst based in Davis,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state might be best advised to torch the whole edifice so
we can start over from scratch with a true private-public
partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Another recommendation of the panel is expected to be an attempt
to address the state's increasing income gap, under which all but
the top 20 percent of state wage earners have lost ground in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lon Hatamiya, secretary of the Trade and Commerce Agency, says
he wants to spread business opportunity more evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to ensure more access by small and minority and rural
businesses, so that our programs don't just benefit large urban
business,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
