<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: How will Y2K B4U?
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, March 21, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ At first, I thought Y2K was a chemical element that I
never learned about in school _ like I thought AuH20 was a chemical
element until I found out it was just a simile, part of Barry
Goldwater's 1964 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The more I hear about Y2K, the worse it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you hoarding cash for Y2K?'' someone asked me the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have to pay for it?'' I asked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously,'' she answered, ``you're going to need hard cash
when that calendar turns. The banks are going to have to shut down,
you won't be able to use your credit card, you're going to need
cash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And how much do you figure I'll need?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``About $10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   How long is this thing going to last?
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, who usually takes a vacation trip in January of
each year, canceled plans for January 2000; won't fly in a plane
until someone else successfully makes it.
</P>
<P>
   My, oh, my, what is going to happen to all those Jan. 1 football
bowl games, and the later Super Bowl? We are talking serious stuff
here.
</P>
<P>
   I am finding Web sites dedicated to selling survival supplies to
make it through Y2K. As I read down the list of offerings, there
was a familiar ring to it: generators, water containers, radios,
flashlights, medical supplies, cooking supplies...
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I buy those every year!
</P>
<P>
   Down here in the Hurricane Belt, this form of preparation is a
routine occurrence. Every June 1, with the official start of
hurricane season, I go to the stores and stock up on just about all
of the above-named items, plus batteries, Milk Duds, canned goods,
potato chips, bottled water, pretzels, propane...
</P>
<P>
   (Northerners who come to Florida often complain that we lack the
four seasons here, but we do have them: Rainy season, stone crab
season, tourist season and hurricane season; that's four.)
</P>
<P>
   People throughout the U.S., plagued by annual floods,
earthquakes, blizzards and tornadoes as well as hurricanes, are
amiss if they do not keep a hoard of emergency supplies.
</P>
<P>
   (Among the items offeredby one Web site as emergency supplies
were seeds. Question: What good will seeds be in Montana or Ohio in
January 2000?)
</P>
<P>
   So I'm not going out shopping for Y2K. If whatever is supposed
to go down on Jan. 1 does go down, I've got my leftover supplies
from the 1999 hurricane season that ends Dec. 1 _ that is, provided
we don't get nailed with a dead-on hurricane as we did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, living as a homeless animal for three weeks after
Hurricane Andrew, I've become somewhat of a survivalist. That got
me to thinking about the $10,000 cash hoard I was advised to keep.
</P>
<P>
   After Andrew, when there was no electricity, no water, no stores
open, no gas stations operating, I recall telling a friend that if
I had a million dollars in my pocket those first days after Andrew,
they would be useless.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing available to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere I turn, there is concern about Y2K and the allegedly
imminent meltdown of the world's computers, upon which we have
become so dependent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean,'' I asked one of the ultra-concerned, ``that when
Y2K wipes out all its tapes, or whatever, that when I go to the
grocery store, the clerk will have to write down the prices on the
side of a paper bag with a big, fat pencil and add them up for me
like they did years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably so,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No scanners, no automated cash registers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How soon can we get to December 31?''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
