<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The pious for president
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had thought we'd be electing a president of the United States
next year, not the pastor of the United States, but much of the
Republican field seems to be running for a real pulpit, not just
the bully one.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is a longtime but low-key churchgoer, and George
W. Bush, like Augustine of Hippo, got religion after he had pretty
much played out an unsustainably raucous youth and just in time to
run for the Texas governorship _ George W., that is, not Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   But look beyond those front-runners and their ordinary pieties
and you find a scramble of pseudo-seminarians trying out for
theocrat. (On the Democratic side all you find after Al Gore is
retired Sen. Bill Bradley, which is like finding Gore all over
again.)
</P>
<P>
   Here's Pat Buchanan with another campaign strongly inflected
with pre-Vatican II Catholicism. Perennial Alan Keyes is pure
preacher. Gazillionaire Steve Forbes wowed the pat-answer crowd
four years ago with his flat tax proposal but flopped fatally with
the religious right. He soon after saw the light on the road to
Washington and now answers to, if not God, at least Pat Robertson,
more anti-abortion than thou and yearning to fund religious schools
with some of that flat tax money.
</P>
<P>
   New to this contest in political homiletics is Gary Bauer, who
is running to save the Republican Party's soul and everyone else's
while he's at it. Bauer, a onetime Reagan political operative, is
on leave from his Family Research Council. His council stand-in
recently blasted Rep. Thomas Davis III, R-Va., for meeting with gay
Republican constituents.
</P>
<P>
   There are two factors inciting all this morality mongering.
Neither has much to do with morality.
</P>
<P>
   With Bill Clinton notoriously a cad at the very least, it was
inevitable Republicans would put themselves forward as
anti-Clintons, with moral indignation a short cut. That gives them
a quick leg up against Gore, who at best can position himself as
merely un-Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And fully 25 percent of the GOP primary electorate is
self-described as conservative Christian. Any planet that big
exerts a lot of gravity. Bush is struggling to find a way to
satisfy the anti-abortion GOP right without being dragged into
all-out abortion opposition. But how? California Republicans,
putting down a mild stir by moderates, recently elected a state
party chairman who holds that ``killing babies is the issue of the
century.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the religious-right candidates has a serious shot at the
nomination, but with so many whooping it up for that ol' time
religion, they serve their goal just by keeping the likes of Bush
and Dole from lapsing fully into moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Americans expect political leaders to be steadied by a spiritual
infrastructure. We are not a value-free people, but neither do we
go to the polls as sinners looking for salvation. Their party's
demanding religious right continues making it difficult for
Republican moderates to campaign as the pragmatists most voters
want rather than as surrogate preachers most voters don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
