r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV21-C     03-18 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE PAYROLL TAX SCAM
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) business for release Sunday,
March 21.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Are taxes too high? Depends on what kind of taxes
you've got in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Take payroll taxes. They are supposed to fund Social Security,
Medicare, unemployment compensation and the like. Politicians are
fussing over how to raise these levies to ``save'' Social Security
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   But by any rational measure, payroll taxes should be cut. Since
many folks don't view these ``deductions'' as ``taxes,''
politicians get a free ride as they get ready to raise them once
again.
</P>
<P>
   Now take income taxes. They are supposed to fund everything
else, including defense. Politicians are fussing whether to grant
voters an across-the-board cut, as most Republicans want, or
targeted cuts, as the White House would prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Income taxes are based on the idea that the more you have, the
more you should pay. That's why they should be raised. The new
influx should then be used to slash payroll taxes, which are paid
equally by all workers earning up to $72,600, when the 7.65 percent
Social Security tax disappears.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's no chance that such a shift in the balance
of payments into the federal till will occur any time soon. But
that truth is driven by politics, not by economics.
</P>
<P>
   If politicians were up front about the fact that income taxes
(which are progressive in nature) and payroll taxes (which are
inherently regressive) both go into the same common pot to pay for
the same things, then perhaps we might make some progress to
redress the lousy deal now facing most struggling wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
   Out of each tax dollar collected from individuals this year, a
full 35 cents will come from payroll taxes. Even more telling: Most
Americans now pay more in payroll taxes than they do in federal
income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of even a relatively well-off middle-class family
that stands to earn $85,000 in 1999. That family will pay an
effective tax rate of 16.3 percent. Not bad, you might say, until
you note that two of every five dollars will go to meet their
payroll obligations.
</P>
<P>
   In inflation-adjusted income, 20 years ago their payroll tax
bite would have been half of what it is today, while their overall
tax bite would be about the same: 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin D. Roosevelt, the father of Social Security, was the
first, but not the last, president to con us about the real nature
of the program. In his 1958 biography, ``The Coming of the New
Deal,'' Arthur Schlesinger quotes FDR as saying: ``I guess you're
right about the economics. But those taxes were never a problem of
economics. They are politics all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, President Lyndon Johnson's Social Security Advisory
Council conveniently found that ``people view receipt of assistance
(i.e. welfare) as meaning a loss of self-support. In contrast, they
view social insurance as an extension of self-support.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Bill Clinton's economic gurus argue that labor market
distortions are being minimized because workers tend to view
payroll taxes as deferred compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Those guys should be arguing over how rich people can help meet
the coming Social Security and Medicare crunches, rather than
trying to do the job by trimming services or lifting payroll taxes
anew.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
