 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2528 - March 18, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2528 -- March 18, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. RESISTANT STRAINS MAKING TB CONTROL DIFFICULT A short
treatment for tuberculosis that has been adopted by the World
Health Organization may not be enough to control the disease in
populations where antibiotic-resistant organisms are common. By
Michael McCarthy. From The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words. 2. WHY
WE SHOULD NOT WRITE OFF RUSSIA Anatol Lieven, an editor at the
International Institute for Strategic Studies in London, writes
that the West's goal in dealing with Russia is now to keep it from
becoming a rogue state. New York Times Op-Ed. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
ANTI-MISSILE PLAN RISKS RUSSIAN LOOSE NUKES Reports from Moscow say
there's a new chance for Russian approval of the long-blocked START
II treaty to reduce Russian and American missile arsenals. It is a
good sign at a time when Moscow-Washington relations are not very
good. The treaty urgently needs to be put into effect because the
deteriorated Russian economy is seriously losing the capacity to
safeguard nuclear weapons. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
WHAT'S DOING IN GENEVA As Easter approaches, it's the time of year
that Geneva shakes off its winter doldrums, stops being a way
station for skiers and comes into its own as a lovely flower-filled
city on western Europe's largest lake. By Elizabeth Olson. From The
New York Times. 1,500 words + photos + map. 5. FROM THE NEW YORK
TIMES BOOK REVIEW :
</P>
