<P>
   A. HIGH-TECH UNDERWATER TOOLS YIELD CLUES TO DISASTERS AT SEA
Since the sinking in 1980 of the bulk carrier ``Derbyshire,'' a
star of the British merchant fleet, the sea has claimed 180 ships
of similar design and 1,465 lives. The vessels go at a rate of
nearly one a month, often mysteriously, like a fleet of Titanics
quietly disappearing from view. Advanced technology is now allowing
investigators to peer deep into the sea's icy darkness,
illuminating much that was once lost or hidden. By William J.
Broad. 2,300 words + graphic. B. CHEMISTS CREATE FOAM TO FIGHT
NERVE GASES By combining ingredients of hair-conditioning creams
and toothpaste, a new foam could neutralize many of the chemical
poisons and disease-causing microbes that might be spread by
terrorists in confined spaces. By Malcolm W. Browne. 580 words.
