<BODY>
 WHEN GOOD MOMS GET MAD 
 By Ann E. LaForge 
 c.1999 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of my worst moments as a mother. I had just gotten
back from a harrowing trip to the food store and was staggering
into the house with groceries in one arm and a screaming
18-month-old in the other. For the millionth time that morning, my
5-year-old was demanding to know when I'd help him build his Lego
fort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play after I make lunch,'' I said sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you promised you'd do it when we got home,'' Gus whined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will, but later,'' I replied as I wrestled Teddy into his
highchair. ``Can't you see I'm busy?'' I hissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always busy,'' he spat back. ``And you're a big, fat
liar, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a what?'' I yelled. Normally, I can ignore that kind of
remark. But on that day, I snapped. All the frustration I'd been
holding in burst forth as fury at Gus's disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   I grabbed him, hustled him into his bedroom and held the door
shut so I wouldn't do what I really felt like doing, which was to
slap him. My heart was racing, my hands were shaking, and all I
could think was: Why did I ever have kids?
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, after everyone had eaten lunch and calmed down, I
looked at my two beautiful children and wondered how I could ever
have been so angry when I loved them so much. I felt guilty and
ashamed_and I was certain that I was the worst mother in the world.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, I'm simply normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers are as capable as anyone of feeling anger, aggression
or ambivalence, and they often feel it toward their own children or
project it onto them,'' reports Meg Eastman, the author of ``Taming
the Dragon in Your Child: Solutions for Breaking the Cycle of
Family Anger'' (Wiley, $5.99).
</P>
<P>
   But even if it is normal, maternal anger can be hard to handle.
``Many women don't feel comfortable with anger to begin with,''
says Dr. Deena Harris, assistant clinical professor of psychiatry
at Columbia University in New York City. ``So when they feel it
toward their own child_the person they most expect to love and
protect_it seems frightening and unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, maternal anger is often denied and rarely
discussed. ``But ignoring anger doesn't make it go away,'' says
June Price Tangney, professor of psychology at George Mason
University in Fairfax, Va. ``It only sends it underground for a
while. Eventually, it resurfaces in less direct and often more
destructive behaviors like shaming, blaming and making hostile
remarks, for instance, or nagging and creating power struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   If we turn anger inward, it can lead to guilt, anxiety, and
depression. In extreme cases, it can lead to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far better to acknowledge maternal anger and face it
head-on,'' says Tangney. ``The feeling itself is inevitable,'' she
adds. ``It's what you do with it that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What Makes Mom See Red &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Understanding why you get angry is an important step in coping
with this disturbing emotion. Every mother has her own hot buttons,
of course. But there are certain aspects of motherhood that can
ignite fury across the board.
</P>
<P>
   One is the sheer strain of caring for children. ``No matter how
much a woman loves her child,'' says Harris, ``she's bound to
resent always having to be there to meet his or her needs''_to
nurse a baby around the clock, for instance, or comfort a colicky
infant; to change wet sheets at 2 a.m. or spend every Saturday
morning on a soccer field instead of sleeping in.
</P>
<P>
   We also have moments when we wish our kids were different:
smarter or braver, quieter or more aggressive, outgoing instead of
shy, more (or less) like us.
</P>
<P>
   These, too, can fuel the maternal fires. Harris observes,
``There's a lot of identification and expectation involved in the
parent-child relationship. You give more to a child, so you expect
more back. That leaves a lot of room for disappointment and anger_
like when your child throws a tantrum in the supermarket or is rude
to his grandmother, or when he's afraid to go near the water (and
swimming is your favorite sport).
</P>
<P>
   The impulse to lash out at a child_either physically or
verbally_is hard to resist when all I you can see is red. And,
based on the statistics for child abuse and neglect (some 3 million
cases were reported in 1997), many parents do not resist the
impulse. They use excessive force to discipline or use their kids
as punching bags to relieve their own stress and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   One day, I found myself thinking that if I gave him a good
spanking he'd probably shut up. I was so shocked and horrified by
this thought that I immediately went to hug him instead.
</P>
<P>
   Many women are so appalled or frightened by their anger that
they immediately repress it, says Harris. But rage always finds a
way to surface. For instance, you may end up exploding over a minor
mishap (such as spilled juice) when you're really angry about a
bigger issue (the fact that your child ruined a family outing by
whining all day). Or you may begin to act in a controlling manner
(insisting your child wear only the clothes that you choose).
</P>
<P>
   There are variations, but the result is the same: ``It eats away
at a child's self-esteem,'' says Tangney. ``When your anger comes
out in hostile remarks or aggressive actions, your child can sense
that something's up. But she may jump to the wrong conclusions:
that there's something wrong with her, or you don't love her, or
she's a bad person.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cool-Down Strategies &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to deal with maternal anger. Here are some proven
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Acknowledge your anger. When ambivalence or anger clouds your
motherly devotion, try to accept it for what it is_a normal
feeling. Remind yourself that even good mothers get mad, and try to
pinpoint the true source of your negative feelings. Is your child
really out of line, or is there a bigger issue involved?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you understand how your anger relates to your child, it
becomes far more manageable,'' says Harris. Rather than blindly
lashing out, you can focus on finding solutions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find support. ``The best relief for maternal anger is talking
with other others who feel the way you do,'' says Dr. Harris. Do
whatever you can to avoid feeling isolated: Organize playdates,
join a support group through your church or YMCA, start a mothers'
group. If you can't find another mother to commiserate with, find a
relative, friend, or counselor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't set impossible standards for yourself. Forget about
being the perfect mother. Instead, be the best parent you can be.
If that means not putting out a huge spread for Thanksgiving like
your mother did, or letting your cleaning standards slip, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't slow down for yourself, do it for your
children,'' Tangney advises. After all, you're their main role
model of what a mother should be.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ann E. LaForge is a Child contributing editor and author of
the forthcoming book ``What Really Happens in School.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
