<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRQUE-LIFEBEAT-ART-N     03-18 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRQUE-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CIRQUE SETTLES DOWN
</HEADLINE>
  Includes three color photos: a horizontal night exterior of the new
theater, and horizontal and vertical interior shots of acrobats in
costumes against a black background. The photos, in JPEG format,
are available via e-mail in minutes by calling Joe Applegate at
212-499-3342 or graphics assistant William Gonzalez at 499-3355. 
 By BILL DEAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One by one, seven performers grasp a trapeze bar and swing down
over a stage that is so high-tech its trampolines are hidden under
a remote-controlled, sliding floor.
</P>
<P>
   The pale-pink outfits the artists wear during this training
exercise only hint at the color, dash and artistry of the show at
the Cirque du Soleil's new theater at Downtown Disney's West Side
in Orlando, Fla. The spectacular building, which opened in
December, is Cirque du Soleil's only permanent, free-standing
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the structure as just a theater is a little like
calling a $400,000 Ferrari just a car.
</P>
<P>
   With an exterior built to emulate a circus big top, and an oval
stage with wraparound seating so close performers could leap into a
front-row lap, the new building feels like a prototype of
Broadway's future.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Cirque du Soleil is no ordinary circus. The production
blends acrobatic and aerial performers with colorful lighting,
striking costumes and original music ranging from rock'n'roll to
opera. No animals. No sawdust. What emerges from the circus
makeover has many of the elements of theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skeleton of what we have is acrobatic,'' says Gilles
Ste-Croix, Cirque du Soleil's director of creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the presentation and design, including the choreography,
the music, the costume and the proper setting for each piece, uses
a much more theatrical approach to create dramatization.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the proper lighting and proper approach, you really can
touch people.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Ste-Croix was part of a French Canadian group of street
performers that delighted crowds with juggling, fire eating and
walking on stilts (Ste-Croix's specialty).
</P>
<P>
   From their beginnings in Baie-Saint-Paul, Quebec, they formed a
traveling entertainers festival which debuted in 1984 as Cirque du
Soleil, French for ``Circus of the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Like traditional circuses, Cirque du Soleil originally roamed
with its own big-top _ which added another element to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we were street players, we were acrobatic and not
using any animals in what we did,'' Ste-Croix says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And moving into a big top... we basically brought this to a
level of theatrical experience. Suddenly, because of the tent, we
could do black (dark lighting ambience), we could do light, and we
could do dramatic music.''
</P>
<P>
   Another pivotal step came in 1993, when Cirque du Soleil began
performing in theaters including a custom-designed one for a
continuing show in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a challenge, because we had been working in a
big top ever since 1984 and suddenly we were going into a
theater,'' Ste-Croix says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we tried to project what we had in the big top, with the
public around a central stage, adding the backing and all the
elements of a theatrical building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibilities of lights, trap doors, rising floors and
other elements bring a greater experience, because under a big top
you cannot have all these,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, it brought even further, the theatrical experience we're
trying to create.''
</P>
<P>
   At its new home in Orlando, Cirque du Soleil follows the same
approach seen in touring productions in Europe, Asia and North
America, and in the continuing performances in Las Vegas _ but with
all new acts.
</P>
<P>
   And like each of its preceding productions, Cirque du Soleil's
newest show has its own name, ``La Nouba,'' which means ``to party,
to live it up,'' in French.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute show features more than 60 performers, including
the seven trapeze artists from Russia, and other performers from
Europe, China, Canada, the United States and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Training and rehearsals use up to five languages through
interpreters _ French, English, Chinese, Russian and Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bilodeau, a French Canadian who has performed for Cirque
du Soleil since 1990, teams up with his twin brother Stacy for a
performance on what is called the ``German wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfitted in a body suit like a Navy SEAL who ran away and
joined the circus, the 22-year-old Bilodeau will fit himself into a
6 1/2-foot-diameter steel wheel to gyrate and roll around the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Nouba,'' like other Cirque shows, is very loosely scripted,
meaning performers are free _ if not encouraged _ to ``experiment''
with their act and discover what works best with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, we were working on the wheel and there is a lot of
fire,'' Bilodeau says. ``And the stage is moving, so you can go on
stage and basically do whatever you want. And the director will say
'OK, I like it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So the show changes every day.''
</P>
<P>
   For Igor Arefiev, a Russian high-wire walker who has worked with
both the Moscow Circus and the Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey
Circus, performing with Cirque du Soleil offers a literal breath of
fresh air to a seasoned performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other circuses were traditional ones, and they bring in
mostly kids, with elephants and clowns,'' says Arefiev, 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's all I saw for four years: couples and four or five
kids with them. But here, it's more modern and for grown-ups. And
the show itself is more elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I performed before, it was just me, my partner and the
audience. But here, there are (other performers) above me, below me
and all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you have to communicate with them, and not just
concentrate on crossing the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT BOX:
</P>
<P>
   Cirque du Soleil's ``La Nouba.''
</P>
<P>
   Where: Downtown Disney's West Side (next to House of Blues).
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $56.50 adults, $45.20 ages 3-9.
</P>
<P>
   More information: (407) 939-7600.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bill Dean writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.) &LR;
</P>
