   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-MAIN17-C     03-18 2380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-MAIN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern folk artist Lonnie Holley at a crossroads
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARPERSVILLE, Ala. _ A dozen vehicles squat in the yard, but
none of them work. There are bedpans and televisions, and piles of
plywood and stands of Styrofoam, and nylon mesh flapping in the
breeze and cats brushing between the rusty legs of discarded lawn
chairs. If you didn't know this was a folk art environment, you'd
swear it was a trailer park after a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never take anything to the junkyard,'' Lonnie Holley says,
gesturing at the clutter that threatens to engulf him.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important figures in Southern folk art, Holley
started his career 20 years ago by carving the soft sandstone that
steel mills use as molds. Since then, he's led so many workshops at
schools and churches that children around Birmingham know him as
the Sandman.
</P>
<P>
   He wonders what the children would think now.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rainy Tuesday afternoon in December. Holley heard a
commotion downstairs. He hurried down the steps. Voices were
shouting. ``Get down!'' It was the police. ``Get down now!'' They
ordered him to the floor, face down on the living room carpet, and
clamped handcuffs around his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this some kind of a joke?'' Holley asked.
</P>
<P>
   It was no joke. He was under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Holley has known a world of trouble in his 49 years. He
has been beaten, shot, jailed. He has been abandoned, cheated,
stolen from. He has watched as his home of 18 years _ along with
much of the art and debris he carefully placed around it _ was
bulldozed into a trench to make way for an airport expansion. But
nothing in a life of Job-like tribulations has prepared him for the
misfortunes of the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Holley is credited with creating some of the most sophisticated,
conceptual work in Southern folk art. Museums and galleries from
New York to Japan have displayed his paintings, sandstone carvings
and assemblages. His vision burned brightly during the 1996
Olympics, when a re-creation of his art-bedazzled yard formed the
focal point of ``Souls Grown Deep,'' a major folk art exhibition in
Atlanta. Newsweek magazine judged it the best part of the Olympic
Arts Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Given the praise and publicity, this should be the best of times
for Holley. Instead, he finds himself spending more time talking to
lawyers and judges than making art.
</P>
<P>
   First he was uprooted from his Birmingham home in a tortuous
condemnation proceeding that dragged on for five years. Then, after
he moved to the small town of Harpersville, 25 miles away, his new
neighbors feuded with his family, one of them going so far as to
assault him, police say. Finally, on Dec. 8, he and his three sons
_ Ezekial, Kubra and A.J. _ were arrested in connection with a
burglary and arson at a golf course behind their house.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Holley is broke.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Holley first heard he was going to have to move in 1992.
Birmingham International Airport wanted to extend a runway, and the
project would require buying and demolishing hundreds of homes in
the predominantly black, low-income neighborhood of Airport Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The airport authority offered Holley $14,000 for his acre of
land. But his acre was nothing like the others. While his house was
crude, his yard contained thousands of pieces of art that seemed to
be as rooted in the soil as the trees.
</P>
<P>
   But one by one, the surrounding homes vanished as his neighbors
accepted resettlement checks. And the bulldozers crept closer.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was one house _ Holley's. The artist was trapped.
He knew he would have to leave, but he couldn't afford to buy
another home until the airport offered him more money. In 1995,
Joseph Strickland, a Birmingham probate attorney, volunteered to
represent him. He enlisted a litigator friend of his, Frank
Galloway, and they negotiated for two years. In October 1997, with
a trial date looming, the authority finally agreed to pay Holley
$165,700 _ more than two-thirds of it for the estimated cost of
relocating his environment to a new home in Harpersville.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers thought he had no chance of getting a mortgage loan,
with his erratic earnings, so he paid $91,500 cash.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Holley's new neighbors did not want him there.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Jews, the woman who had lived in the house for years, lost
the property in 1996 and was still enraged. One night shortly after
Holley moved in, he says, she burst into the house and his bedroom
demanding that he vacate the premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know who you are!'' he yelled.
</P>
<P>
   His new home was a fragile egg in a nest of resentment. The
woman's family lived near Holley's new house, and none of the kin
was pleased to see trucks dumping piles of rubbish and peculiar art
on what had been their relative's neatly mowed lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The bad feelings boiled over in a dispute over a small building
just within Holley's property. The Garretts use it as a sort of
juke joint. Holley's oldest son, 18-year-old Ezekial, wanted to set
up a silk-screen T-shirt shop in the building, but the Garretts
refused to surrender it.
</P>
<P>
   One day last summer, Ezekial got into a fistfight with Maurice
Garrett, the 28-year-old nephew of the woman who used to own their
house.
</P>
<P>
   The feud quickly turned violent. Someone opened fire with a
rifle. Ezekial ran into his house, and he and his brothers starting
firing back with a rifle, a shotgun and a pistol.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only Maurice Garrett was charged in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ____
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, in the midst of such troubles, Holley managed to make
enough paintings and sculptures for a show of his work last fall.
The pieces, priced from $170 to $5,000, sold reasonably well and
provided virtually his only income for 1998. The remaining works
are still on display at the Monty Stabler Galleries, a posh salon
in the upscale Birmingham suburb of Homewood.
</P>
<P>
   As she flips through the paintings _ all of them on paper _
Stabler wishes she had more on canvas, but knows why she doesn't.
``Lonnie works on what he can afford,'' she says. ``He can't afford
canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   The perpetually struggling artist is a figure as old as clay.
Perhaps nowhere in the art world is the stereotype more fitting
than in the realm of folk art.
</P>
<P>
   As folk art has grown more popular during the 1980s and '90s, a
few artists have fared well _ Georgia's Howard Finster and
Alabama's Thornton Dial, for example. But most remained poor or
close to it.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Holley's patronage has come from one man, Atlanta
collector Bill Arnett, a bespectacled 59-year-old whose combative
personality and zealous pursuit of folk art have made him one of
the most controversial names in the field. Arnett first beheld
Holley's environment in 1986 and was so moved that he agreed to
advance the artist a regular income in exchange for the right of
first refusal on his symbolic assemblages.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Holley's money problems go deep. Some galleries
have found the logistics of dealing with him too taxing. Others
have found Holley's art difficult to sell.
</P>
<P>
   There's one other reason for Holley's money woes. Almost
everyone who knows him believes he can be too generous for his own
good.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Holley has asked acquaintances in the art world if
they would assist him in managing his affairs. This winter, as
Holley's life scraped bottom, the lawyers who represented him in
his airport battle found a new recruit.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lasseter, an owlish Birmingham furniture maker who has
known Holley for a few years, read about his arrest in the December
golf course burglary and drove to Harpersville to see whether the
family had enough food. He ended up delivering considerably more
than dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonnie is one of the most decent people I've ever met,''
Lasseter says. ``I'm doing everything I can to ease his mind and
let him get back to his art. People have taken advantage of him.
I'm just trying to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   ____
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Dec. 8, the superintendent at the Meadows, the
golf course in Holley's neighborhood, arrived for work before dawn
to find the clubhouse burned down. Police followed muddy golf cart
tracks as they led back to Holley's property and, ultimately, to
his three teen-age sons.
</P>
<P>
   And then the tracks turned on Holley himself.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged with receiving stolen property: golf shirts,
liquor, walkie-talkies and other items deputies found inside his
house. His oldest son is accused of stealing the goods the night
before, with help from his two younger brothers, and then burning
down the clubhouse in a clumsy attempt to conceal the burglary.
Holley says he was asleep when it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cruelest aspect of Holley's current predicament is
the knowledge that his children got him into it.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking posed a problem after Holley and his estranged wife,
Carolyn, broke up, but instead of continuing the pattern, Holley
sobered up, he says. He took his children to the Holiness church.
He insisted they attend school. He taught them how to draw and
sculpt, and carried them to art fairs so they could sell their work
and buy shoes and clothes with the money. Angela, the firstborn,
kept records of her father's artwork. Ezekial, the oldest son,
liked to paint. Kubra (pronounced coo-BAR) took to carving, while
little brother Arthur James gravitated toward music. Carlonie, the
kid sister, won a blue ribbon at school for a painting that she
said was about ``women who forget to take care of their children.''
They were handsome youngsters, growing tall and lean like their
daddy, and people were impressed with their polite manners and
creative potential.
</P>
<P>
   But on Dec. 8, a juvenile judge warned Holley that if he wanted
to keep his children, their truancy had to stop.
</P>
<P>
   If Holley does not seem furious with his children, perhaps it is
because he understands their frustrations. ``I got angry with Zeke
when he stole the car. I got angry with Angela when she got
pregnant at 16 and dropped out of school. But I'm not in that angry
mood now,'' he says. ``My children have been through so much. I
think what happened in December, they were getting back at the
community. It was like they were saying, `Daddy, we need to get out
of here.' They were running away from the hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Elbert Buckelew, the Meadows majority owner, estimates the
clubhouse damage at more than $100,000. ``We were robbed _ I don't
have a problem with that,'' he says. ``But, dammit, why'd they have
to burn it down? I don't care if he's a damn Picasso, he's got to
be responsible for his kids.''
</P>
<P>
   To recover his losses, Buckelew is considering suing Holley
under an Alabama law that holds parents accountable for the actions
of their children. ``I find it hard to fathom that he didn't know
something about what his sons were doing,'' he says. ``We need to
see if he was involved in any way. Because if he was, he needs to
lose all that.''
</P>
<P>
   He means Holley's property, the only home he's got, the only
thing of tangible value that he has to show for 20 years of making
art and raising a family against the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all I've been through, I don't need to be losing this,''
Holley says. ``If I lose this ...''
</P>
<P>
   He draws a deep breath and falls silent. He cannot bear to
finish the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ____
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Holley has conducted hundreds of workshops over the
years. On the last Thursday in February, he conducted one that must
have been his most heartfelt. It was for teen-agers at the Shelby
County Regional Juvenile Detention Facility in Columbiana. One of
them, locked up since December, was his son Kubra.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children are artists,'' he says, ``not criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   As winter warms to spring, this cold passage in Holley's life is
beginning to show the first signs of thaw. The dispute with his
neighbors seems to be diminishing; they finally agreed to pay him
rent for the building they have been using as a juke joint. And the
golf course may not sue after all, because prosecutors hope to make
any plea bargains contingent on some restitution. The payments
would be hard to make, but at least Holley could keep his home.
</P>
<P>
   Life is returning to normal for three of his children. Carlonie,
the 12-year-old, is attending her sixth-grade classes more
faithfully. Angela, 20, plans to work on her high school
equivalency degree as she raises her infant son and 3-year-old
daughter at her father's house. A.J., the youngest son, was
released from the transitional juvenile home where he spent most of
the winter. The high-spirited 13-year-old was sentenced to
probation and community service, and has resumed the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the oldest sons, Ezekial and Kubra, who have always
assumed that they would become artists like their father.
</P>
<P>
   Ezekial is the quiet one. At 18, he seems to carry a chip on his
shoulder from all the troubles he has seen befall his family. ``I
still want to follow in my father's footsteps,'' he said,
mentioning his interest in drawing and silk-screen printing, ``but
I've just had some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubra is the outgoing one. The juvenile authorities were so
taken with Kubra that they nominated him for the Alabama School of
Fine Arts, a magnet program in Birmingham for gifted children from
throughout the state. When he was accepted, he asked his teacher if
she could help him with a subject he needed to know more about. Not
art. Math.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the creative flame has continued to burn within
Holley. The uprooting, the shooting, the arrests _ like the clutter
in his yard, the pieces of his life are so many materials for art.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Holley finally got his hands on some spare cash
and asked a friend to drive him to the nearest Wal-Mart. He bought
$50 worth of generic house paint and set up the cans on a table in
his living room, across from the framed picture of him and Hillary
Clinton at the White House, during the exhibition that featured a
piece of his sculpture. In the same room, 10 weeks before, police
had handcuffed him and taken him to the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in months, Holley dipped a brush into a
can and began to paint.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
