r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN19-COX     03-18 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas rookie judge courts political future
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It didn't take Ernest Garcia long to learn that
even rookie judges sometimes get treated like rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed by Gov. George W. Bush to fill the Travis County
judicial vacancy left by Joe Hart, Garcia was participating in a
game of musical courtrooms almost as soon as he put his hand down
from taking the oath. District Judge Suzanne Covington moved into
Hart's old courtroom _ with its prime location on the third floor
of the courthouse _ and Garcia wound up with a decent enough
courtroom, but a tiny office.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter the size of his office, Garcia shrugged while
recounting the opening episode of his judgeship. It doesn't matter,
he explained, because he'll be spending most of his time in the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   And when he's not in the courtroom, he'll be working on
retaining the judgeship. While Republicans are gaining ground in
Travis County, Democrats are hanging tough at the courthouse.
Republicans mounted several spirited and well-financed challenges
to county Democrats and picked up only one county commissioner
seat. That was Precinct 3 (South and Southwest Travis County), won
by Todd Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   Will Wilson was the only other Republican who has held a
district judgeship in Travis County in recent history. Appointed by
Gov. Bill Clements in 1989, Wilson lost a hard-fought general
election campaign to John Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional courthouse wisdom is that a similar fate awaits
Garcia. But if you ask him, he'll tell you that he's going to work
hard to hang on to the job.
</P>
<P>
   The son of working-class parents from Corpus Christi, Garcia is
a former federal prosecutor who got his law degree from the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He had not been very visible in local politics before the
governor tapped him to succeed the highly respected Hart. While
some may consider the political inexperience a drawback, it could
also be a blessing. He hasn't made that many enemies and he's
obviously made one friend who counts _ the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Visit with Garcia, though, and you're in the company of a fellow
who is obviously intelligent, and one who is working hard to
develop a political persona. It's not easy, he admits. What he will
find toughest, he said, is raising money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger and they passed out a box of candy bars to
sell at school, I couldn't stomach the thought of going door to
door and asking strangers for money. So, my grandmother would buy
the box and I would eat most of it,'' he related, then joked,
``that's why I have the physique I do today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly not a professional politician and I'll never be
comfortable raising money, but I'm going to have to do it,'' Garcia
said.
</P>
<P>
   Is that a good way to pick a judge?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied. ``Unfortunately, judges have to run in a
partisan election. It is my opinion that a judge's role is to
interpret the law that is there. Whatever philosophy I may have
shouldn't have a role.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as judges are elected, however, campaigning and raising
money will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The apathy that greets judicial races is widely known, but
proposals to change the system never suffer from a lack of critics.
</P>
<P>
   And Garcia's view is most realistic: ``I'm certainly not in a
position to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   What he can do, he said, is preside over a courtroom where
people are treated fairly and where the law the Legislature enacted
is applied.
</P>
<P>
   How the judge fares politically between now and the time he
faces the voters remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia, no relation to the judge, is the editorial page
editor of the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
