<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5089 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN19-COX     03-18 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If governor leaves town (or job), who takes over in his absence?
 &HT;    Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Did you know that Rick Perry, the Republican
lieutenant governor and presiding officer of the Texas Senate, is
also governor?
</P>
<P>
   Not always, to be sure. But under the Texas Constitution, when
Gov. George W. Bush is out of the state, Perry is acting governor,
while continuing in his role as lieutenant governor. With Bush
running for president, that could happen a lot.
</P>
<P>
   What if Bush is elected president in 2000? At least some who
read the Texas Constitution say it leaves the possibility that
Perry could continue in that dual status of lieutenant governor and
acting governor.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Tom Ramsay (D-Mount Vernon) is concerned enough about
that possibility that he wants to clarify it. The Northeast Texas
representative has filed a proposed constitutional amendment that
was heard in the House State Affairs Committee on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay said Texas has never known that a governor was likely to
leave office early while officials still had time to deal with
questions about succession and duties. ``We thought it would be a
good idea to make it clear,'' Ramsay said.
</P>
<P>
   The last gubernatorial vacancy was in 1949, when then-Gov.
Beauford Jester died. The lieutenant governor, Allan Shivers,
vacated that office by taking the oath as governor.
</P>
<P>
   But it is possible, some constitutional observers say, that
Perry could continue as the Senate's presiding officer and still be
acting governor if he simply avoided being sworn in as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay's proposal, House Joint Resolution 44, flatly states that
if the governor leaves office, the lieutenant governor becomes
governor.
</P>
<P>
   His proposed amendment also would make an important change in
the line of succession into the lieutenant governorship. Currently,
senators would select a colleague who would become lieutenant
governor while continuing to serve as a senator.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay thinks, and others agree, that whichever senator is
selected ought to be lieutenant governor and only that.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1984, if the lieutenant governor's office became vacant,
the president pro tempore of the Senate would become acting
lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate developed a habit of passing around the president
pro tem job to the most senior senator who hadn't yet held it, so
the senator could hold a ``governor for a day'' celebration at the
Capitol for supporters and others. The governor and lieutenant
governor would dutifully leave the state, or say they were leaving,
so the president pro tem could be acting governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, some of the more conservative senators began
to worry that someone _ especially a more liberal senator _ might
be president pro tem when both the governor and lieutenant governor
vacated office, through death or other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1983, then-Sen. Grant Jones, a conservative Democrat from
Abilene, got the Legislature to approve a constitutional amendment,
which Texas voters endorsed in 1984. It said if the lieutenant
governor's job becomes vacant, senators would come into session and
choose an acting lieutenant governor. It calls for senators to
select someone from among themselves ``to perform the duties of the
Lieutenant Governor in addition to his duties as Senator until the
next general election.'' So the Ramsay proposal says that when the
senator becomes lieutenant governor, his or her senate seat becomes
vacant and will be filled by special election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not political,'' Ramsay said. ``It's not partisan. I've
talked to both Republicans and Democrats in the House, and they
don't have any problems with it. There's widespread support in the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay said that the proposed rewrite of the Texas Constitution,
offered by Sen. Bill Ratliff (R-Mount Pleasant) and Rep. Rob Junell
(D-San Angelo), calls for the same clear succession arrangement,
although in slightly different words.
</P>
<P>
   But at Monday's committee hearing, several questions were
raised:
</P>
<P>
   _ Are the state's best interests served by having the senator
who acts as lieutenant governor quit the Senate seat?
</P>
<P>
   _ Should the new lieutenant governor/senator serve the remainder
of the governor's term, or just until the next election?
</P>
<P>
   _ If Bush is elected president, could an early resignation as
governor mean Perry's successor as lieutenant governor would be
chosen by the current Senate (which has 16 Republicans and 15
Democrats), but preside over the 2001 Senate (which could have a
Democratic majority)?
</P>
<P>
   How those questions are resolved may determine whether the
proposal gets the two-thirds vote necessary in the House and Senate
to be put before voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
