<HEADER>
A5090 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX     03-18 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teachers' battle scars worse when brass won't back them up
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Everybody knows, said everybody, that schools are
awash in violence.
</P>
<P>
   So when Horace Mann Insurance Corp. made news last year with
``assault recovery'' insurance for school personnel, everyone could
see policies selling like curly fries.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone except teachers.
</P>
<P>
   As of year's end, though available in 45 states, only about 300
policies had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Several theories: First, teachers can't afford it, even with
modest premiums of $4 a month. Second, falsely or not, some believe
themselves sufficiently insured against injury on the job through
workers compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Third, it's safe to say that most teachers don't look at their
students as the greatest threat to them.
</P>
<P>
   They think of students' parents, with attorneys at their elbows,
as that threat, and spineless administrators as No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers have a cop's mentality. They expect to step into fights
and expose themselves to cuts and scrapes. They expect to have
problem children explode in their faces. They expect the drill of
hauling a chronic brawler down the hall while the child bites at
your wrists.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't expect is to have the little brawler-mauler back
in class before the next potty break.
</P>
<P>
   They don't expect school districts to make mince meat of their
own zero-tolerance discipline policies because Johnny, into double
digits with his demerits (three is the expressed limit in Waco
schools), is judged a ``special needs'' child, meaning that
``zero'' computes as ``infinite,'' tolerance-wise.
</P>
<P>
   This was some of the frustration that bubbled forth in Austin
when teachers rallied on behalf of a bill called the Classroom
Discipline Act.
</P>
<P>
   The act, carried in the Senate by Houston Democrat John Whitmire
and in the House by Rep. Rick Noriega (D-Houston), would give force
of law to discipline techniques once considered sacrosanct.
</P>
<P>
   Protected under this act: teachers' authority to ``verbally
discipline'' a student; to physically isolate a student in the
classroom; to withhold classroom privileges; and to use ``a
physically harmless prop in disciplining a student.'' Yes, like a
dunce cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean to say,'' everyone will say, ``teachers can't do that
now?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes they can, by and large. But they know that school districts
quake at the sight of parents bearing lawyers, and that sometimes
principals will succumb to a lobbying Ma and Pa insisting that
their Precious was unfairly singled out, humiliated and
life-scarred by a stern teacher.
</P>
<P>
   One can see problems with legislation of this sort. If a teacher
goes off the deep end with an abusive, window-shattering rant, is
it protected as ``verbal discipline''? Is an ankle chained to a
tetherball poll the use of ``harmless prop''? What about when a
teacher truly and cruelly singles a kid out?
</P>
<P>
   But one can see more benefits than problems were the state to
provide backup for teachers on discipline matters when
administrators won't.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Texas Association of School Boards and
Texas Association of School Administrators oppose this.
</P>
<P>
   School districts ``already have the authority to do all of this
right now,'' said the administrators group. Yes, they do. But ask
teachers and find they too often feel that their hands, raw from
being gnawed, can be tied in trying to control things.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation runs counter to the ``local control'' mantra
lawmakers spout but rarely honor (see Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills). Whitmire says local control is fine, but his bill is the
backup teachers need. ``The bottom line is they're (administrators)
afraid of parents. They're afraid of lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator sounds like a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
