<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Veteran widow's' advice indispensable for women
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two decades after the death of her husband, Philomene
Gates, an 80-year-old New York lawyer, considers herself ``a
veteran widow,'' but she's quick to admit she still hasn't gotten
over the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get over your husband's death,'' she says. ``You get
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was March 1979 when her husband of 38 years, Sam, died of a
ruptured aneurysm, and Gates was struck with one undeniable
consequence: For the first time in her life, she lived alone. The
minutiae of daily life _ paying bills, finding health insurance,
handling home repairs _ seemed overwhelming. Soon, though, the
practical instincts of an urbane attorney kicked in, and Gates
started coping with everyday life, jotting down notes along the
way. The result was a self-help book called ``Suddenly Alone: A
Woman's Guide to Widowhood.'' Now, the book has been expanded to
include divorce, and the tireless Gates _ ``You rest, you rust'' _
is on a quick book tour. Shortly after flying into Atlanta from
Miami, she took a few minutes to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What prompted you to write this book?
</P>
<P>
   A: After Sam's death, my three wonderful daughters kept saying,
``Mother, you're doing so well.'' I certainly didn't feel like I
was doing well _ I was trembling inside so badly I was afraid of
falling down ... but I kept up the appearance of doing well. One
daughter suggested that I start keeping notes of all the problems I
encountered as they arose, so I could tell other women in the same
situation what to expect. ... It's a very practical book.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best piece of advice women can take from your
book?
</P>
<P>
   A: Be sure you know who's in control of your life, meaning your
money. Really, women need to read this kind of book before anything
happens to their husband, whether it's death or divorce. Ask
questions: What do we own? What do we owe? If you walk out of here
and a truck hits you, what am I supposed to do? What do you want to
happen to the children?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Don't women tend to do that more today than they did 20 years
ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: Younger women tend to do that more, but, you know, people
really don't like to talk about these things. And a lot of men feel
threatened if their wives start asking these kinds of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What surprised you most about living alone?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was suddenly not being invited to parties that I know I
would have been invited to if Sam were alive. ... An extra woman is
a problem. I think that's less so for younger couples. I don't
think my daughters are so hooked on the ``balanced'' table at
dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are some real pluses to living alone: You don't
have to ask anybody's permission to do anything, you get the icebox
all to yourself, and you have time to do the things that really put
a charge in your life _ reading, joining a book club, gardening.
... Anything that will give you more confidence is to the good.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your book, one of your rules is, ``Don't whine.'' Why is
that so important?
</P>
<P>
   A: You have to want to be happy. If you run into somebody who
asks how you're doing and you say, ``Oh, I'm so unhappy,'' the next
time they see you in the supermarket they're going to run the other
way.
</P>
<P>
   You have to discover what makes you happy and do that. It's also
really important to do volunteer work. I never would have survived
Sam's death if I hadn't volunteered. The friends I made through
volunteering got me through. If I had had to depend on my working
friends for my social life, I'd still be sitting in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
