<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Jew Store' honest account of small-town South
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The title of her book, ``The Jew Store,'' may be
off-putting to some, but Stella Suberman has never worried about
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tell the truth like it is, and that's what everybody
used to call these stores in small towns in the South,'' says
Suberman, 77. ``They were places where farmhands, sharecroppers and
factory workers could buy inexpensive clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jew Store'' (Algonquin Books, $19.95) is Suberman's richly
detailed memoir about growing up in the only Jewish family in a
small Tennessee town she calls Concordia (she changed the names of
the people and the town to protect privacy). It was here that
Suberman's Russian immigrant father, Aaron Bronson, opened
Bronson's Low-Priced Store in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Jews came South, they loved it,'' says Suberman, who
lives in Boca Raton, Fla., and writes book reviews for The Miami
Herald. ``Many of them had come from very tiny villages in the old
country, and the South in many ways was more like home'' than the
North was.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there was no prejudice in 1920s Tennessee. The
Ku Klux Klan would open their meetings by vowing to protect ``the
good white citizens'' of the town from Roman Catholics, Jews and
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Suberman says, laughing, ``then they would do
their shopping at Father's store.''
</P>
<P>
   Suberman's father became a hero in 1929 when the stock market
crashed and the shoe factory in town was about to shut down because
it could not pay a $45,000 loan. In a dramatic recounting of a
meeting between the factory owner and the townspeople, Suberman
describes how her father leaped onto the stage and offered to
donate $5,000. Then he began calling people by name and challenging
them to give money, too. As a result of his efforts, the factory _
and the town _ were saved.
</P>
<P>
   Although the family moved to New York in 1933 and then to
Florida, Suberman says they always regarded Concordia as home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to visit after I wrote the book,'' she says.
``Very little has changed. Our house is still there, but the large
meadow I used to play in across the street is a lot smaller than I
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Literary awards: Congressman John Lewis' civil rights memoir,
``Walking With the Wind,'' former President Jimmy Carter's essays
on ``The Virtues of Aging'' and Phyllis Alesia Perry's novel
``Stigmata'' were among the top winners at the recent Georgia
Author of the Year competition in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said the award couldn't have come at a better time. ``I've
been working on my next novel, `Second Sunday,' and I was feeling a
lot of pressure _ both internal and external. This helped my
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Second Sunday'' is a prequel to ``Stigmata,'' which dealt with
Lizzie, a young black girl who has strange dreams about slavery
after inheriting her grandmother's quilt. Sent to mental
institutions by her parents, Lizzie begins a 20-year journey to
learn about the past that haunts her.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners include Frank Manley for ``The Cockfighter''
(fiction), Barbara Ras for ``Bite Every Sorrow'' (poetry), Muriel
Phillips Joslyn for ``A Meteor Shining Brightly'' (biography),
Lewis Larson for ``The Georgia and South Carolina Expeditions of
Clarence Bloomfield Moore'' (historical), Linton Wright McKnight
for ``Birthflowers of the Landscape'' (nature), Clara Bell Hooks
Eschmann for ``Remember When: Family, Friends, Recipes''
(cookbook), Lynn Cullen for ``The Mightiest Heart'' (children's
picture book), Stan Applegate for ``The Devil's Highway'' (middle
reader division), Brad Strickland for ``The Spectre From the
Magician's Museum'' (young adult) and Sandra Markle for ``Outside
and Inside Alligators'' (children's nonfiction).
</P>
<P>
   _ Footnotes: Has the market for ``A Man in Full'' finally been
saturated? Tom Wolfe's hefty saga about race and real estate
dealings in Atlanta slips out of the Top 10 to No. 14 on this
Sunday's New York Times Best Seller List. ... Speaking of Wolfe,
three of the author's books made New York University's list of the
100 greatest works of 20th-century journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
