A5094 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHONGQ&AMP;A19-COX     03-18 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHONGQ&AMP;A19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Annabel Chong: A woman on a mission
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bundled in a long red coat, her black hair
lashing in the wind, Grace Quek lights a cigarette and talks about
what it's like to have sex with 251 anonymous men over 10 hours.
Just another day in the life of a porn superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Quek, known better by her nom de coitus, Annabel Chong, is the
star of ``Sex: The Annabel Chong Story,'' Gough Lewis' revealing
but ultimately pathetic chronicle of the issues that surrounded
Chong's record-setting feat of fornication. The documentary caused
a media stir at this year's Sundance Film Festival, and shows today
at the South by Southwest Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Quek earned a graduate degree in gender studies from
the University of Southern California, and her Olympian
sex-tathalon stemmed partly from her quest for gender empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   Quek is 26. She is poised and polite and seems either mildly shy
or vaguely chastened. She wears the patina of someone who is old
beyond her years.
</P>
<P>
   Quek sat on a documentary panel at SXSW on Saturday. I spoke
with her afterward on a chilly, wind-pummeled balcony at the Austin
Convention Center. She tried to smoke in the gales, while I tried
to keep my notes from blowing to El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did you have sex with 251 men?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mostly out of curiosity about myself and what I could enjoy
sexually, how far could I go and still find it fun.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The film ascribes the stunt to your contempt for female
repression and disempowerment. That sounds a little pat.
</P>
<P>
   A: I did it out of a complexity of reasons. A lot of it is
personal and some of it's out of curiosity. I didn't go into it
with this violent political vendetta. I wanted to find out for
myself several things: Is it fun? Is it true the women in porn are
these complete hopeless bimbos who are being exploited? The kind of
picture people paint of the porn industry is such a cartoon, and I
thought, ``It cannot be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were your conclusions?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a grain of truth in a lot of the criticism of the
industry, such as the fact that some girls aren't terribly bright,
sort of clueless, and they get themselves exploited. But I
discovered it's a business just like any business, and it's the
business of making movies, just that the subject matter is sex.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the film you say you wouldn't regret it if you got AIDS
from the event.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's like a one-of-a-kind experience that's so unique that
it's worth it. I always believe in being responsible for what you
do sexually. So for me to do something like that and not accept the
responsibility over my own body would be stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you going to keep your clothes on while in Austin?
</P>
<P>
   A: In this weather? Hell-o?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
