   OSCAR TRENDS -- Story will detail what might happen Oscar night
that would be a first. For instance, Tom Hanks might become the
only actor to ever win three best actor trophies. Judi Dench might
win an Oscar for one of the shortest performances ever. (Staff,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR NOMINEES RECOGNIZED -- A list of Oscar nominees who have
already won accolades from various guilds and critics groups.
</P>
<P>
   PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN -- A 2 column graphic ``Countdown to
`Star Wars''' outlining the number of days remaining until ``The
Phantom Menace'' opens.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS -- ``One True Thing,'' ``The Waterboy,''
``Bulworth,'' ``Living Out Loud.'' (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) With 2 column color studio photograph from
the film ``One True Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS - Beth Orton's ``Central Reservation'' Elton John,
others, ``Aida'' soundtrack, George Strait's ``Always Never the
Same,'' Joe Henry's ``Fuse.'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-PREDICT _ Eleanor Ringel and Steve Murray predict the
winners in Sunday's Acadeny Awards ceremony in all the major
categories (picture, actor, actress, director, supporting actor,
supporting actress, screenplay, adapted screenplay, costume,
foreign film) indicating not only who will win but who they
personally think was best. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
with COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-TV _ A rundown on all Oscar-related programming for
Sunday, including pre-shows, the Oscar show and any plans for
Monday on ``Entertainment Tonight'' etc. Would also try to include
a seating chart illustration showing which stars will be seated
where. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-BALLOT _ Our annual ballot, including all the nominations.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-FIRSTS _ Short story at bottom of ballot page detailing
what might happen Oscar night that would be a first. For instance,
Tom Hanks might become the only actor to ever win three best actor
trophies. Judi Dench might win an Oscar for one of the shortest
performances ever (only winner Beatrice Straight (''Network'') had
shorter screen time). (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-PREVIEW _ For Sunday's Oscars, ABC has literally grabbed
the spotlight. For the first time, the traditional star walk-up
covered by a myriad of electronic press from gushy ``Entertainment
Tonight'' to E!'s Melissa Rivers will be pushed aside for ABC's own
exclusive 30-minute pre-Oscar celeb show hosted by Geena Davis.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-TVLIST _ Bulleted rundown of what's on Sunday for the
Oscars. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-DOCUMENTARIANS _ Interview with Oscar-winning
documentarians Freida Mock and Terry Sanders, whose film about
American P.O.W.s ``Return With Honor,'' screens tonight. (BEACH,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-FORCES _ Review of ``Forces of Nature,'' a Ben Affleck
and Sandra Bullock date movie. Grade: B. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-RAVENOUS _ Review of ``Ravenous,'' a Guy Pearce non-date
movie (sort of a Donner party in the woods). Grade: C+. (StMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-RDP _ Roundup of reviews of ``True Crime'' (Clint
Eastwood) Grade: D; ``The King and I'' (animated redo) Grade C-;
``Children of Heaven'' (Oscar nom from Iran) Grade B; plus
mini-review of ``The Last Days.'' It opened Wednesday. Grade A-.
(Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOLL-LASTDAYS _ Director James Moll spent two years shooting the
powerful ``The Last Days,'' the first film to emerge from Steven
Spielberg's Shoah Foundation and an Oscar nominee for this month's
Academy Awards. The film opens Wednesday in Atlanta. Moll talks not
only about selecting five Holocaust survivors to talk for the
camera, but the huge emotional wallops in their tales in witnessing
the unimaginable. For instance, survivor Irene Zisblatt recalls
seeing a row of soldiers grabbing Jewish children and slamming them
brain-first against the sides of a truck. ``That's when I stopped
talking to God,'' she says quietly. (St.Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CHONG-Q&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A carefully written and sensitively
handled q&AMP;a with porn star Annabel Chong. ``Sex: The Annabel Chong
Story'' was one of the most talked about films at Sundance this
year, and it will be at SXSW, too. ``Sex'' screens tonight.
(Garcia, Austin Amnerican-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-NATURE _ Review of ``Forces of Nature.'' A man runs into
an eccentric woman as he travels cross-country to make it on time
to his wedding in Savannah. With Sandra Bullock, Ben Affleck.
(Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-WRAP _ Column wrapping up SXSW Film Festival, which ends
Saturday. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. The
layout is now available in the LIFESTYLE folder on the COX server.
WAN category: TRAVEL.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET_TRAVEL 0319: I have cruised on a lot of ships. I've taken
enormous mega-ships and small vessels. I've taken legendary, and
expensive, ships and those less storied, and less expensive. I
don't mention this to impress you, but to tell you firsthand that
there are huge differences between cruise lines and ships. Your
choice will determine whether you have a wonderful or disappointing
cruise vacation. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NYC TOUR GUIDES _ The only thing spinning faster than the
machines turning out New York guidebooks is the city itself.
Publishers cannot possibly keep up with the construction crews and
busy chefs, but they sure try. But here's a word of advice: When
shopping for a guide, do not be persuaded by the 1999 on the cover,
or copyright date. Most guides are researched more than a year in
advance. (Wade, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS _ The next Olympic Summer Games, to be held in
Sydney, are a little less than 18 months away, but it's not too
early to order hotel accommodations and tickets. (Staff, N.Y. Times
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DELIS _ NEW YORK _ On the first day of a Big Apple
vacation with her engineer husband, Jennifer Miller of Athens went
to the famed Carnegie Deli for her first real taste of ``deli.''
The pepperiness of pastrami, the lusciouness of lox, the garlicky
tang of pickles so steeped in brine that they're almost white:
these are treats that clog the heart with cholesterol and joy.
``There's enough meat in those sandwiches for five normal ones _
they make your eyes pop out,'' enthused the schoolteacher. ``To the
folks back home I would say: anything that you thought was a deli
before you came here _ isn't!'' Indeed, New York is not only the
capital of deli _ it is deli, in ways that are mysterious and
profound. A tour of five great ones: Katz's, 2nd Avenue, Barney
Greengrass, Carnegie, Stage. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS .
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MARCH 21.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DELITOUR _ NEW YORK _ A nosher's tour of Katz's, 2nd
Avenue, Barney Greengrass, Carnegie, Stage. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MARCH 21.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DELIMENU _ NEW YORK _ A sidebar on the deli menus
(particularly the tradition of naming sandwiches for the famous).
(Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MARCH 21.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-SUMMER FASHIONS/SPECIAL REPORT
</P>
<P>
   TRENDS _ Utility chic is the latest buzzword in fashion circles.
Utility chic looks are comfortable, versatile and oh, so practical
and have emerged as the strongest trend for spring/summer 99. Think
pants and jackets with zippers, drawstring pants, Velcro and hoods.
There's a move on to de-emphasize oranmentation and go with simpler
fashions for the latest transitory lifestyles. It's a case where
less is certainly more. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EVENINGWEAR _ The dressing-down themes continues in looks for
parties and After-5 affairs. Call it the ''glamour of comfort,''
which means sportswear separates in cottons and cashmere worn with
over long skirts in taffeta or jersey fabrics. Also think two piece
outfits instead of a single long gown. (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WOMENSWEAR _ Color is king,when it comes to wearswear. Look for
anything in pink, organge, red, blue and yellows. The more
colorful, the better. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SWIMWEAR _ The one-piece suit rules in the swimwear world.
Striking one-piece suits with flowers, athletic stripes and logos.
(Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MENSWEAR _ Style conscious men will want to lighten up in terms
of color, fabric and attitude. The warm weather season calls for
shades of light blue, gray and cream in tropical wools, linens,
seersuckers and even cotton. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFS _ Assorted shorts on must-have items for him/her. For
her: Capri pants, the low-heel slide, white sundresses, shifts. For
him: The utility show, any suit light in color and sturdy
briefcases. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGSTYLES-KIDS _ In a spinoff on the adult Fashion Atlanta,
``Fashion for a small Atlanta'' will focus on popular fashions for
the younger set for spring and summer. Categories include It's a
Girl Thing, Boys to Men, Sunday Best and Summer Fun. (AHill,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. The
layout is now available in the ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS folder on the COX
server. WAN category: BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET _ BOOKS 0319: ``All Too Human,'' the awkward title of the
new memoir by President Clinton's former adviser, George
Stephanopoulos, seems meant as a commentary on the author's
famously flawed former boss and on the author himself. The book
depicts Clinton as a man of contradictions, a politician whose very
``shamelessness is a key to his political success.'' (Kakutani,
N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW _ It should come as no surprise that the third volume of
Henry Kissinger's ambitious, all-embracing memoir of public
service, ``Years of Renewal,'' turns out to be a distinguished and
important work. (Bernstein, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW _ It is difficult not to pity the characters in Lois-Ann
Yamanaka's novel ``Heads by Harry.'' At first glance they all
appear to be such losers. Watching these lives, and the lives of
all the characters, existing on the edge of despair and hopefulness
is what gives ``Heads by Harry'' its appeal. (Reed, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE ON BOOKS _ Mary Pipher, best-selling author of ``Reviving
Ophelia'' and ``The Shelter of Each Other,'' is 50, a number
suggestive of halfway, a midpoint. It suggests that the long
backstretch is behind us and the homestretch around the next turn.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ On Mary Pipher's ``Another Country: The
Emotional Terrain of Our Elders.'' (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WIDOWHOOD _ When Philomene Gates' husband of 38 years died
suddenly in March 1979, the 60-year-old New York attorney lost
``the comfort of being half a couple in a couples society.'' In
1990, she wrote a book called ``Suddenly Alone: A Woman's Guide to
Widowhood,'' sharing some of her hard-learned ways of surviving and
thriving as a single. Now the book has been expanded and updated,
with new chapters on divorce and loneliness, and the tireless Gates
_ now 80 _ is in Atlanta to sign books and spread her message. A
Q&AMP;A. (Weaver, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-20. WITH PHOTO.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WECHLSER _ Interview with Suruba Georgette Ibumando
Wechlser, who grew up in Central Africa, enduring dictatorships,
war, refugee camps, the AIDS epidemic and other horrors. Now
Wechsler, who converted to Judaism and moved to Atlanta, has a book
out, ``By the Grace of God'' (New Horizon). (Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Some people are put off by the title of Stella
Suberman's book, ``The Jew Store,'' but the Tennessee writer says
that's what folks in the South really called the stores. Suberman's
book captures the mood of an era when almost every small Southern
town had a dry-goods store that was run by Jewish families. Even
Rich's started out small that way. Other notes: Georgia Writers of
the Year named and eight writers, including Don DeLillo and Cynthia
Ozick nominated for the $150,000 Dublin Literary Award _ the
world's richest literary prize. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 6 p.m. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HUGHES _ The late British poet laureate Ted Hughes, whose
last book of poems ``Birthday Letters'' just won the Whitbread
Prize, is reclaiming his own place in English letters. For years
his work was subsumed by public fascination with his personal life,
particularly his life with Sylvia Plath, who killed herself in
1963, shortly after the two were separated. New material just
acquired by Emory University in the Ted Hughes archive, including
hundreds of personal letters, shows how intimately intertwined the
two poets were, professionally and emotionally, but is also
changing the way Hughes is perceived by critics. (Emerson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Book commentary from The Palm Beach Post.
MOVED.
</P>
