<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, March 19,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-CLUBS _ AUSTIN _ SXSW brings to showcase clubs 2 to 3 times
their usual monthly income, a huge difference considering the thin
operating margin of most local clubs. If only the clubs could pack
people in and sell as many drinks year round.... SXSW this year
should find big crowds at Liberty Lunch, likely the last time in
its present location, and the Electric Lounge, which is just trying
to keep its doors open through the festival after being hit with
rent increases. Austin Blues is an example of a new club trying to
get established during the festival. (McLeese, Austin
American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFETIME-NEXT _ ``What next?'' is a question with much resonance
now at Lifetime, the 15-year-old cable network that ventured into
uncharted territory this season by creating three original series.
But are there enough viewers? That's the question facing Lifetime
now as it decides whether or not to bring each of the series back
for a second season. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   THEMOB-TV _ Everything we know about the mob we learned in a
movie theater. From ``Little Caesar'' (1930) to ``The Godfather''
(1972) to ``GoodFellas'' (1990), movies taught us how to do the
mob: to wisecrack ``you dirty rat'' and ``sleeps with the fishes''
and ``what, the way I speak, it amuses you?'' Mob movies showed us
how to pay tribute, erase somebody execution style (one bullet,
behind the ear), die at a table over a plate of linguini in a white
clam sauce, just like a real made guy. Movies owned the Mafia _
even if the Mafia was rumored to own a little piece of the movies.
Until now. With the mid-season debut of HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' TV
has killed off the mob movie and made it its own. (Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEWS _ Two reviews - One of AMC's special on the Hollywood
black list and another on ``Earthly Posessions,'' an HBO movie
starring Susan Sarandon. Both air over the weekend. (Kloer/Jubera,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MACKENZIE-PROFILE _ Profile of Norman Mackenzie, Robert Shaw's
longtime assistant as director of the ASO Chorus, who will conduct
the concert of Haydn's ``The Seasons'' that Shaw was to have led
March 25-27. With a sidebar on Haydn because Michael O'Neal Singers
are doing his other oratorio, ``The Creation,'' the very same
weekend. (Green, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 21
</P>
