<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JENNA-ELFMAN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNA ELFMAN: HOLLYWOOD'S NEWEST SHOOTING STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, contact New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides of Jenna Elfman and Matthew McConaughey in a scene
from ``EDtv,'' and of Elfman in a scene from ``Dharma and Gregg.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    One minute she was the dizzy, Lucille Ball-like half of a new
comedy series ``Dharma and Gregg,'' the next she was Hollywood's
most wanted leading lady. The original, one and only Jenna Elfman
has been zooming up the Hollywood success ladder like greased
lightning.
 &HT;    Internationally, she's best known as the effervescent Dharma
Finkelstein, the San Francisco yoga instructor and dog trainer who
was raised by Bohemian parents and is now the wife of stuffy,
Harvard-educated lawyer Gregg Montgomery_played by Thomas Gibson.
 &HT;    Gibson is himself a hot property having secured a starring role
opposite Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman in ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' to be
released in July. But it's the 27-year-old Elfman who has everyone
talking_including Elfman herself. Just try and stop her!
 &HT;    ``I'm Dharma,'' she says, ``It's no big act. Dharma is an alive,
passionate girl. We're so similar. In real life it's definitely me.
I'm zany and my husband says I'm loveable as well.''
 &HT;    She's right. Sometimes it's hard to see where Dharma leaves off
and Elfman picks up. Tall (5-10) and skinny, she is lunching on a
huge sound stage at 20th Century Fox studios, where the show is
shot, and hurls words at you at express-train speed barely pausing
to take a breath.
 &HT;    On the the success of her comedy series, she said: ``It's got a
lot to do with the writing and a lot to do with the actors not
playing 'comedy.' You can't deliberately try to be funny_people
will squirm and be embarassed for you if you do.''
 &HT;    On the movie front she appeared last year opposite Richard
Dreyfuss and Lily Tomlin in the farce, ``Krippendorf's Tribe,''
which flopped. But that didn't dampen her career hopes.
 &HT;    In the weeks to come she'll show up in Ron Howard's ``EDtv,''
playing a character who's the opposite of Dharma. She's the shy,
insecure girlfriend of Matthew McConaughey who suddenly becomes
famous.
 &HT;    ``It's about a video store clerk (McConaughey) whose life is
televised live 24 hours a day. Only unlike 'The Truman Show' he
knows it's on TV and enjoys it. Then the whole country falls in
love with him. It's about what celebrity does to someone's life and
what it really means.''
 &HT;    In ``Town and Country'' (to be released later this year), Jenna
joins the legions of screen beauties who've played Warren Beatty's
girlfriends. ``When people ask me what it's about I tell
them...'It's Warren's life story,''' she laughs. ``In the film he
goes through a midlife crisis and cheats with a bunch of
women_including me.''
 &HT;    Before the hippie Dharma came along, Jenna, the youngest of
three children, grew up in the middleclass Los Angeles suburb of
Northridge with her parents_father Richard worked for an aircraft
company, mother Sue was a housewife. She wanted to be a ballet
dancer but ankle injuries destroyed that dream. She admits she
drifted through her earlier career_smoking pot and paying the rent
by working on TV commercials.
 &HT;    Growing up, she says, she was not the ebullient, confident
personality she has become. Studying under renowned acting teacher
Milton Katselas helped boost her confidence. And Hollywood sat up
and took notice three years ago when she won rave reviews for her
scene-stealing performance in ``Townies''_a series that was quickly
cancelled. After that she appeared regularly in guest roles in
``Roseanne,'' ``Murder One'' and ``NYPD Blue.''
 &HT;    Like John Travolta, Kirstie Alley and Tom Cruise, Jenna is a
follower of Scientology which she, like Travolta, says helped her
in her personal life and career.
 &HT;    She met her husband of four years, actor Bodhi Elfman, the
29-year-old nephew of Batman film composer Danny Elfman, when they
were auditioning for a TV commercial. Now the couple live in a
remodelled '50s-style house in the Hollywood Hills. It was Bohdi
who introduced her to Scientology.
 &HT;    Between rehearsals for a stage play in Hollywood she spends a
lot of her spare time these days visiting local animal shelters.
``I'm into rescuing and adopting animals,'' she says. ``I raise
money for the shelters because tens of millions of dogs are killed
every year. My latest find was a 6-month-old half-Lab, half-chow
who was going to be killed the next day.''
 &HT;    Spending time with her animals keeps her feet on the ground when
the acclaim and fame get overwhelming. ``It's been tough dealing
with the insanity of success and I haven't had a chance to even
take a deep breath and say, 'Wow.' I try to do it every day but so
much is happening so fast that I have to readjust every few days. I
stop and say, 'Alright...I've got it_OK.' I just have to stay in
present time.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
