u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MARILYN-MANSON-     03-18 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MARILYN-MANSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCK ROCKER MARILYN MANSON COURTS CONTROVERSY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marilyn Manson has been described as sick, sacrilegious and a
serious threat to the moral fiber of America's children. His
concerts have been picketed by parents' groups and religious
organizations. Students have been sent home from school for wearing
his souvenir T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   According to Manson, all the hub-bub means he's doing what rock
stars are supposed to do: encouraging kids to think for themselves
while driving their parents crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``By changing the way they look, or playing a Marilyn Manson CD,
or wearing a Marilyn Manson T-shirt, they know that it infuriates
their parents, just the way their parents knew the Beatles
infuriated their parents, and Elvis Presley before them,'' Manson
said by phone from his home in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll should be dangerous. What I do, I try to make
provocative and challenging. Salvador Dali said that confusion is
the greatest form of communication, and I think that's absolutely
true. If it makes people think, then you're doing your job.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Manson and opening act Monster Magnet are set to
invade Compaq Center in Houston, even though Manson is recovering
from a sprained ankle suffered in a recent performance in Los
Angeles. He canceled shows in San Diego and Las Vegas this week,
but the Houston date is still on.
</P>
<P>
   Hole, which had been co-headlining the ``Rock Is Dead'' tour
with Manson, dropped off the bill following the Los Angeles
concert. While Hole's Courtney Love cited ``production issues'' as
her reason for quitting, the two stars had been taunting and
tossing barbs at each other from the stage since the tour began.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The interview with Manson was before Hole's departure. At the
time, he called the tour ``a perfect pairing ... that keeps the
excitement of rock 'n' roll alive.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said he'd had doubts about Love's commitment to
touring and her ability to control herself. On Monday, he told MTV
that Love's leaving was not a personal thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at times it looked like it could have been, and our
quarreling back and forth probably added to it all. The bottom line
was, it's not an easy slot going on before us. I think they were
unhappy with the way the crowds responded to them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to reconcile Manson's uninhibited and at times
grotesque stage performances with his articulate demeanor in
interviews. His replies were never less than thoughtful, if
somewhat disingenuous at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't comprehend extremes the way I do,'' Manson said.
``I don't see anything unnatural about me having different levels
to my personality, different parts of me that come out at different
times. Some people see that as having multiple personality
disorder. I see it as being a creative, imaginative person.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson's latest album, ``Mechanical Animals,'' represents a
significant musical and lyrical evolution from his previous work.
While his earlier albums consisted of industrial-strength noise,
this time Manson offers some strong songs to back up his shock-rock
persona.
</P>
<P>
   In its swaggering sound and sly sense of humor, as well as its
ambiguous sexual imagery, ``Mechanical Animals'' recalls the
glam-rock golden age of '70s David Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the few people that stood out to me as a kid.
Bowie combined the excitement of a book or a movie and put that
into rock 'n' roll,'' said Manson, 29, who grew up as Brian Warner
in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a whole world that he created, along with people
like KISS, and Prince and Madonna and Boy George. That's how I
expected all rock 'n' roll to be. From the beginning, I've always
considered my image and my songs to be just as important to my
whole aesthetic.``
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that Manson chose his stage name from two
American icons, Marilyn Monroe and Charles Manson _ one female, one
male; one viewed as a tragic victim, the other the psychotic
personification of evil in contemporary society.
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of Bowie's Ziggy Stardust, Manson assumes the
role of an androgynous character, Coma White, on ``Mechanical
Animals.'' But he says the album reveals more of the erstwhile
Brian Warner than his last album, ``Antichrist Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On `Antichrist Superstar,' I was trying to bring about my own
apocalypse. Out of dissatisfaction with the world, I was trying to
destroy it or destroy myself. So I just put myself through as much
as I could, hoping to either become something stronger or be done
with it all. And I think that I became something stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I realized was that it was a matter of having all the
emotions that I'd shut off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Manson is disavowing his earlier work or conceding
anything to those who object to his perceived influence on young
fans. When Manson performed at Houston's Aerial Theater in
November, concerned individuals, including city Councilman Rob
Todd, implored the city to ban the show.
</P>
<P>
   Citing First Amendment rights, Mayor Lee Brown upheld the
group's right to perform. The show went on, although Manson angrily
stomped off early after fans threw beer at the sound-mixing
console, causing technical difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no organized protest to this concert, but Todd
has not changed his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central issue is that publicly funded venues should
restrict their acts to those that are within community standards,''
he said. ``The fact that Courtney Love considered this act to be
beneath her standards shows you that it is not within Houston's
community standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps with an eye toward stirring up more controversy, Manson
compares himself to Christ and claims to know more about
Christianity than most Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus was really the first celebrity, if you think about it.
He symbolized so much suffering and so much sexuality. That became
an important part of the rock-star icon. So if people are going to
be mad at me, they have to be mad at themselves, because it's their
religion that I was inspired by, more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone who's mad at Marilyn Manson is mad at him for
religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Marks, former executive editor of Spin magazine, filed a
$24 million lawsuit against Manson last month. The lawsuit alleges
that Manson's bodyguards slammed Marks against a wall at a November
concert while Manson threatened to kill him because the star was
angry that Spin decided not to feature him on the cover of its
January issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole incident with Spin is someone's idea of
getting publicity,'' Manson said. ``Just because I had a simple
argument with someone doesn't mean that I did the things that he
said. I completely deny all of his allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ironic that he got fired from Spin. I think that
shows that he doesn't really have the backing of his magazine on
his side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Spin spokesman Jason Roth confirmed that Marks has been fired,
but said his departure had nothing to do with the lawsuit. He said
the magazine still supports Marks' claims against Manson.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding Manson came home to one Houston-area
family in a tragic way. In December, 12-year-old Beau Beasley of
Katy, Texas, shot himself to death, leaving behind a note quoting
Manson's ``Get Your Gunn.'' The lyrics include ``I throw a little
fit/I slit my little wrist/The most that I can learn/Is in the
records that you burn/Get your gunn, get your gunn, get your gunn
...''
</P>
<P>
   Manson _ who said he's discussed having children with his
fiancee, actress Rose McGowan _ was unaware of Beasley's suicide.
He said he sympathizes with the pain the boy's parents feel, but he
declines to assume responsibility for the impact his music may have
on listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put the blame on anything you want,'' he said. ``I'm
the easiest person to point the finger at, because it's
traditional, and I assume the role of the villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson hopes his music encourages kids to strive to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think I'm the only one who cares or believes in
the fans, the kids. What I'm telling them the most is that no
matter how much everyone doubts you or how much you think you don't
belong, it doesn't matter. The world is what you create in your own
head. Why let other people tell you how it should be?''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Beasley, Beau's father, said Manson underestimates
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the rock scene better than he might imagine. I
played in bands from 1967 to 1974 and enjoyed some success. Outrage
has always been a part of rock 'n' roll, but it has never been a
substitute for excellence. So far, he has excelled only at
controversy and deadly influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley is not planning legal action at this time, but he warns
that Manson would do well to consider his legacy and his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support freedom of speech, but there are limits, and Manson
has gone beyond them intentionally for fame and profit. I suspect
he will disappear on the scrap heap of rock once his shock value
fades. Maybe then he'd like to see my son's suicide note and
reconsider his part. Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
