<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOORMAN-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR BOORMAN TAKES `REVENGE' ON MASTER THIEF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The General,'' the latest outstanding film from John Boorman,
is much different from what we've seen before from the British
director.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman has twice been Oscar-nominated as best director, for
``Deliverance'' and ``Hope and Glory,'' both best-picture nominees.
</P>
<P>
   His personal approach and distinctly sensual visual styling have
enhanced such films as ``Point Blank,'' ``Excalibur,'' ``The
Emerald Forest'' and ``Beyond Rangoon.'' Even his failures
(``Exorcist II'') have had visually interesting elements and
personal touches.
</P>
<P>
   But Boorman does not think the almost documentary approach and
stark black-and-white photography of ``The General'' should
surprise those who really know him and his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to match the visual style to the subject and
particularly to the character,'' Boorman said, calling recently
from London.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's a way of expressing character, which is one reason
why I wanted to do it in black- and-white. I feel that color always
romanticizes, particularly poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not want to romanticize ``The General,'' the story of
real-life Irish criminal mastermind Martin Cahill. Cahill was a
burglar, but not a common one. He led his own extensive gang, which
robbed homes but also pulled off large capers, including the
largest jewel heist in Irish history. Cahill was murdered _
apparently by the Irish Republican Army, which he had crossed _ in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars Irish actor Brendan Gleeson as Cahill and
co-stars Jon Voight, a Boorman pal since ``Deliverance,'' as one of
the policeman trying to capture the crook.
</P>
<P>
   Movies about criminals often make their subjects into heroes.
Cahill, portrayed with stark, mug-shot clarity in ``The General,''
is no hero. He committed many dastardly deeds.
</P>
<P>
   But if not romanticism, a rather reluctant admiration for Cahill
does come through clearly. Boorman, who was once a victim of the
Dublin gangster, freely admits it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In common with a lot of people in Ireland, (I have) a grudging
admiration for the man because of his wit and humor and sheer
cheek,'' Boorman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of took on the world. Toward the end, when things were
falling apart around him and he was still determined to oppose the
police and all the other forces around him, you can't help but
somehow admire that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his twisted way, Cahill, whose title of General matched his
ability to pull off a virtual war against society, was amazing. He
openly thumbed his nose at the police, who knew of his crimes but
not how to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman, who has lived in Dublin almost 30 years, first became
aware of Cahill years ago when his house was burgled.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, (Cahill) was just a burglar, working on his
own,'' Boorman said. ``But he was pulling off extraordinary
burglaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the stolen items was a gold record Boorman had for the
music in ``Deliverance.''
</P>
<P>
   The record was never recovered, and no one was convicted of the
theft, but police assured Boorman that Cahill did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they couldn't get any evidence against him,''
Boorman said. ``That was the first time I heard his name. When he
started to do these bigger robberies, I remembered the name and
followed his career with great interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie has a scene in which Cahill, having come home from his
rounds, pulls out the gold record and is disgusted but amused to
find that it is made of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagined how he might have reacted when he found that it
wasn't actually made of gold,'' Boorman said. ``He thought it was
made of solid gold or he wouldn't have taken the trouble to steal
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The items he took from my house, (were) some Georgian silver
and one or two other things that were very valuable, and left
everything else. He didn't make any kind of mess; he got in very
cleverly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was very annoyed at the time. It was very
upsetting that he could get in that easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Boorman chuckles: ``But I got my revenge, if you like.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
