EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, March 18, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SISTERS-CATHOLICS (San Francisco) _ The Sisters of Perpetual
Indulgence, celebrating 20 years of campy outrage, street theater,
poor taste and good works, has drawn fire from the San Francisco
Catholic Archdiocese for planning its anniversary party on Easter
Sunday and closing down a city street to hold it. By LARRY D.
HATFIELD and RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS-LOGGING (Headwaters Forest Reserve, Calif.) _ After
standing in a redwood grove here in the new government-owned,
7,500-acre Headwaters reserve, Gov. Gray Davis travels to Eureka to
drop off a $12 million check from the state to compensate the
Humboldt County government for lost jobs because of a reduction in
logging operations. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LAWSUIT (San Antonio) _ A Hill County, Texas, man is suing
the California maker of his derringer because the .22-caliber
pistol put a bullet in his backside when it fell from the
wheelchair he was using at a Kerrville, Texas, hospital. By MARO
ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINE (Albany, N.Y.) _ To date, only 1,500 people have
signed up in the United States to test a new AIDS vaccine called
AIDSVax, less than the 5,000 the vaccine's manufacturer hopes to
enroll by this summer. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-VACCINE (San Antonio) _ A defiant Fort Sam Houston
soldier who is refusing an anthrax vaccination has been reduced in
rank and given extra duty mopping floors and cleaning toilets. Next
week he faces a court-martial. He is one of a about 100 Americans
in uniform, 10 of them in the Army, who have refused to take the
vaccine. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-SENTENCING (San Antonio) _ A lanky 19-year-old has become
the first person sentenced locally under a federal law banning guns
from schools, even as the judge questioned why Congress created the
statute. The last time federal authorities here prosecuted a
pistol-packing student, the U.S. Supreme Court tossed out the 1992
conviction along with the law itself. Since Congress resurrected it
in 1996, the law has had limited use and a mixed reception. By MARO
ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   UNWANTED-BEAVERS (Boerne, Texas) _ Four beavers exiled from
California are being freed at an undisclosed location in Texas.
``These guys just need somewhere that is compatible in the wild and
welcoming,'' said Lynn Cuny of Wildlife Rescue and Rehabilitation.
Trouble is, Texas already has enough of the critters and they are
the target of an aggressive state eradication program. By ZEKE
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS (Albany, N.Y.) _ On Oscar night, expect lots of jokes
about war movies and period movies and Shakespeare in tights, or
whatever it's called. Expect strange clothing and stranger hairdos.
Expect pomp. But don't expect too much from the awards themselves.
The Oscars never make much sense, so here I go with predictions. By
AMY BIANCOLI. (For release Sunday, March 21.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BOORMAN-PROFILE (Undated) _ ``The General,'' the latest
outstanding film from John Boorman, is much different from what
we've seen before from the British director. But Boorman does not
think the almost documentary approach and stark black-and-white
photography of ``The General'' should surprise those who really
know him and his work. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MARILYN-MANSON (Undated) _ Marilyn Manson has been
described as sick, sacrilegious and a serious threat to the moral
fiber of America's children. His concerts have been picketed by
parents' groups and religious organizations. According to Manson,
all the hub-bub means he's doing what rock stars are supposed to
do: encouraging kids to think for themselves while driving their
parents crazy. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-ART (Seattle) _ Among contemporary art collectors,
Virginia and Bagley Wright have achieved an enviable reputation for
intelligence, community responsibility and good taste. The current
exhibition celebrating them and the collection they have assembled
over a 45-year period (at the Seattle Art Museum through May 9)
demonstrates that the praise they and their collection receive is
well-merited. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-BREAK (South Padre Island, Texas) _ Thousands of thirsty,
sun-loving collegians have invaded South Padre Island, but some
merchants worry it is a dying ritual. The market has been weakened
by a strong dollar that is sending students to Cancun and Jamaica
and by the whimsy of MTV, which has decided to promote Spring Break
aboard cruise ships. Some merchants would like to see island
leaders market the resort as a year-round destination. By JAMES
PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERLINK (Austin, Texas) _ Concentrate, and a cursor on a
computer screen drifts toward a file you want to open. Clench your
jaw, and a program starts up. Focus hard enough, and the screen
comes alive in an electronic light-show-concerto controlled by your
thoughts. It sounds like science fiction, but Cyberlink, as it's
called, is here, and it was wowing crowds at a technology festival
here. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-BOWL (Phoenix) _ San Francisco lost a Super Bowl because
the National Football League ran out of patience with the 49ers'
footdragging over a new stadium. But the city won a multi-million
dollar IOU because the NFL has high hopes that the new people in
charge of the club will be able to get the playing facility built.
By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The headline on the press
release looks like a joke: ``Wealthy Taxpayers say, `No Thanks!'''
to GOP Tax Giveaways.'' Could this be real? A national consortium
of 400 fat cats, calling themselves ``Responsible Wealth,'' who
publicly condemn the benefits of several proposed tax break bills
that would benefit them most? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
