<HEADER>
A5148 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COYOTES-AZR &LR;      03-18 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP BIDS FOR PHOENIX COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - An ownership group headed by entertainment mogul and
Phoenix Suns partner Barry Kemp has an offer on the table to
purchase the Phoenix Coyotes from owner Richard Burke for an
estimated $80 million to $100 million and keep the team in Phoenix,
``The Arizona Republic'' has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Burke accepts the offer depends on a number of factors,
including the outcome of a May 18 vote in Scottsdale, Ariz.,
related to a new arena and whether he is willing to continue to
sustain large losses as the single owner of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Burke has been looking for a partner in the franchise but has
denied that he is interested in selling the team outright. Reached
late Wednesday, he said he isn't selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is no,'' Burke said. ``It was a verbal proposal and
I've turned that offer down. It's gone no further than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the timing of the leak about a sale could be meant
to subvert a positive vote on the Los Arcos Mall project with the
new arena, Burke said, ``I'm not one who attributes motives, but
the first this came up is when the Los Arcos project was announced.
The second time around it the was the (Scottsdale) City Council
vote. And the third time was the legislative vote (on stadium
districts).
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Arcos will happen and we're going to stick it through,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three out-of-town sources associated with both the National
Basketball Association and National Hockey League told ``The
Republic'' the sale will be done by June if voters side against the
formation of a stadium district in Scottsdale. If they say yes,
Scottsdale voters will go to the polls this fall on whether the
developers can keep about $200 million in state-generated sales
taxes from the new sports complex.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, when reached at his office in Southern California,
confirmed his group's interest in the Coyotes. But he indicated
that a sale is not set in stone and termed the time frame
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am heading a group, mostly comprised of people from the
entertainment world, that has expressed interest in purchasing the
Coyotes, if for some reason the new arena in Scottsdale does not go
forward,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, 49, is a former executive director of the Phoenix Chamber
of Commerce. He now owns a television and movie production
corporation called Bungalow 78 Productions, which has produced
long-running television hits such as ``Taxi,'' ``Coach'' and
``Newhart,'' as well as feature-length movies such as ``Romy and
Michelle's High School ``Reunion'' and ``Patch Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp owns 6 percent of the Suns and is involved both in limited
and general partnership groups with the team. He also owns the Long
Beach Ice Dogs of the International Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty it's still premature and there really hasn't
been any indication that Richard is that interested and he has made
it very clear that his first priority is Scottsdale. If the arena
doesn't go in Scottsdale, and he was going to sell the franchise
and move it, we would like the option to buy the team and keep it
in Phoenix. But, again, it's contingent on something not happening
in Scottsdale.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the reported purchase price, Kemp said, ``In fairness,
that's more or less what the range of offers is for the bulk of NHL
teams _ other than the New York Rangers, of course _ so it's in the
range.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke and his then-partner, Steven Gluckstern, purchased the
then-Winnipeg Jets for $68 million in October 1995. The team
changed names and began play in Phoenix at the start of the 1996-97
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest would be to keep the team at America West,'' Kemp
said. ``I have a strong feeling about Phoenix as a sports center. I
also have a strong feeling that as a result of what Jerry Colangelo
has done there, and as a small-percentage owner of the Suns who has
admired the way he has operated those franchises, it's where we
want to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think America West is one of the premier sports venues in
the country and one that other venues still compare themselves to.
The people like going there _ I know I like going there _ and you
can't discount something like that. Between it and Bank One
Ballpark, it's the center of Phoenix sports and the Coyotes have
certainly become part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp said no other minority owners of the Suns are included in
his group.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, 55, repeatedly has denied he has interest in selling the
Coyotes outright. But he has never denied an interest in finding
new partners, and last month told a Valley radio audience that he
had an offer to buy the team but wasn't interested.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kemp said that his group has no interest in becoming a
minority owner in the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally not interested in joining a new arena in
Scottsdale _ nothing against Scottsdale, because I love it there,''
he said. ``But Phoenix already has something that works in
Phoenix.`'
</P>
<P>
   That has been the center of debate between Burke, America West
officials and officials of Phoenix government, which recently
unveiled plans to reconfigure America West Arena to make it more
hockey friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Phoenix announced a plan to give the arena a $12
million upgrade that would leave the facility with about 17,500
seats with clear views for hockey and arena football. Count the
2,500 or so ``obstructed-view''seats that would remain after the
renovation, and the arena capacity would top 20,000. The arena
currently has 16,210 seats for hockey _ less than 12,000 of which
are unobstructed _ and 19,023 for basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, founder and former chairman and chief executive officer
of United HealthCare Corp., partnered with Gluckstern until
Gluckstern divested his interest in the Coyotes to head an
ownership group that purchased the NHL New York Islanders before
the 1997-98 season, leaving Burke the financial burden alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are estimated to lose $4 million to $6 million this
season. Burke said this year that he was expecting total financial
losses of at least $50 million by the time the NHL team's lease
expires at America West Arena in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have pointed to the losses that are created by 4,200
sight-obstructed seats at America West, and a lease agreement that
restricts revenue streams from luxury suites, signage and various
other forms of corporate partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Kemp, because of his partnership with Colangelo,
believes he can work out a friendlier lease agreement with Arena
Management, a subsidiary of the Suns. Along with the reconfigured
seating, a new lease agreement could make team ownership more cost
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I can do that,'' Kemp said about the lease.
``We would assume the same lease that Richard has. Whether it can
be improved, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked for his thoughts about the proposed sale, Colangelo
refused comment, only saying it is a situation involving Burke and
Kemp and that he is not involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
