u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-18 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AUCTIONS, IT'S `BIDDER'S BEWARE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: eBay is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I spend so much time on computers because most of my favorite TV
shows have been cancelled. Lovejoy, for instance--a charming
British series about a corrupt but kind-hearted antiques dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC cancelled Lovejoy just as the Internet was catching on.
Too bad. With Internet fraud complaints up 600 percent last year,
according to the National Consumers League, the Web could have
provided fodder for a dozen episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Cindy Allen. She's a biochemist turned
antiques expert, furnishing her home in North Andover, Mass. with
classic lighting fixtures purchased on-line. That's how she met
Zeev Shenkman , vice-chairman of USA Bancshares Inc., which runs a
bank in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and Shenkman share a love of fine glassware, a fondness
for Internet shopping and an unhappy relationship with Bette in
Oregon. Bette asked me to use her on-line name, but you can get her
real name in about 30 seconds. She's a former car dealer who now
tends her ailing husband at home. Bette fattens the household bank
account by purchasing garage-sale bric-a-brac and reselling it on
eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you know eBay, an on-line auction site that's become
one of the 'Net's most impressive success stories. eBay is open to
anybody with something to sell. Just register as an eBay member and
you can sell practically anything -- except guns and vital organs
-- to the highest bidder. eBay merely gets a listing fee and a cut
of the final sale price. But since eBay moves 700,000 items a day,
it's one of the few Internet businesses that actually makes money.
</P>
<P>
   eBay has always made me nervous. Partly it's because I like
eating. The eBay auctions compete against newspaper classified ads,
which generate about a third of the Globe's revenues and pay a
goodly part of my salary.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the nagging doubt that comes from doing costly
trades with people you've never clapped eyes on. What if you ship
the product and never get a check? Or what if the seller skips town
with your money, or sells you junk that doesn't live up to
expectations? eBay will provide the seller's real name and phone
number -- that's how I found Bette. But what if the merchant still
refuses to make good?
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the complaint that Allen and Shenkman have levied
against Bette. Allen paid $2,055 for a lamp; Shenkman $1,571 for a
vase. Each says the merchandise wasn't what they had in mind, and
asked for refunds. No way, Bette said.
</P>
<P>
   Now everybody's furious. Allen has complained to the Oregon
Department of Justice, with Shenkman's avid support. ``For the
wrong people,'' fumes Allen, ``the Internet is a license to
steal.'' Bette replies that Allen is trying to defraud her of her
rightful fee by stirring up other customers and the cops. ``I am
sure that I am going to be arrested and taken away to court,''
Bette gripes.
</P>
<P>
   So do Allen and Shenkman have a legitimate gripe? It's not
entirely clear. Indeed, their complaints may stem from a series of
misunderstandings. So a better question is how Internet shoppers
can avoid such unpleasantness.
</P>
<P>
   eBay can't afford to become known as Ground Zero for suckers, so
the company practically begs users to shop smart. ``Use your own
common sense,'' urges company spokesman Kevin Pursglove. For
instance, eBay posts customer feedback so you can see if a seller
or buyer has earned a bad reputation. Never do business without
checking the feedback messages. They'll include the person's e-mail
address.
</P>
<P>
   Look for sellers who actually pay for their Internet accounts.
If a seller uses a free Web-based e-mail service like Hotmail, he
may disappear once the check clears.
</P>
<P>
   eBay offers some transaction insurance for purchases below $200.
Above that, the company urges buyers and sellers to use escrow
services, fledgling companies that exist to provide security to
buyers and sellers alike. Ads on the eBay site tout San Mateo-based
I-Escrow Inc. For 5 percent of the purchase price, I-Escrow will
hold a buyer's money, releasing it to the seller after the goods
are delivered and the buyer is satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   But so far only a fraction of Internet trades are escrowed,
making sites like eBay a happy hunting ground for ripoff artists.
Poor Lovejoy. He got out of the business too soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
