<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORMER-SLAVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPED SLAVE'S STORY STUNS TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the audience: The students of Dover-Sherborn Regional High
School, some of the richest, most privileged public school students
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   On the podium: Moctar Teyeb, 39, runaway slave.
</P>
<P>
   The young people gaped at glimpses of a world they never
imagined could still exist. The visitor broke down and sobbed when
he was made an honorary Dover-Sherborn scholar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black families are ripped apart when masters give their
relatives slaves as gifts,'' Teyeb told an audience as utterly free
as any on earth. ``In your history classes, you have learned how
this was done to black slave families in America, but to me, it is
not history. It is happening today in my country, to my people, to
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Teyeb, a native of the West African nation of Mauritania, has
been likened to Frederick Douglass, who escaped slavery in the
South to become a leading abolitionist.
</P>
<P>
   Teyeb escaped Mauritania when he was 19 and his master moved
from a remote rural area to the capital. Passing through a
then-nascent network of slavery opponents, he found his way to
schools and colleges in Morocco and Libya. He moved to New York 3
1/2 years ago, and may soon move to Boston to work more closely
with Charles Jacobs, president of the American Anti-Slavery Group
in Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Teyeb and Jacobs stunned students with the revelation that
slavery still exists in the world, in varying forms, and then
challenged them to join a new world-wide abolitionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   While human bondage has receded to historical memory in much of
the world, the anti-slavery group estimates there are about a
million carpet-making slaves, mostly children, in the subcontinent,
hundreds of thousands of sex slaves in southeast Asia, and a
million blacks serving Arabs in North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Though a US-based movement against these practices has existed
since the early 1990s, interest has soared with the national
publicity given the issue last year when a Denver fifth grade class
raised $22,000 to buy freedom for slaves in the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs currently is embroiled in controversy with the United
Nations Children's Fund, which opposes buying freedom for slaves on
grounds that it constitutes participation in the slavery system and
spurs demand for more slaves to be captured.
</P>
<P>
   Teyeb thanked the Dover-Sherborn students for their concern, but
then challenged them to consider ``why have my people been
abandoned? There are so many international organizations and
government agencies. They fight famine, natural disasters, child
abuse, domestic violence, political detentions and more. Why have
all these organizations been silent'' on slavery?
</P>
<P>
   He told the students that, now that they were aware of the
reality of slavery, they had to grapple with what it means to be so
free as they are when so many people know no freedom at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today my family, my people, and I are all still waiting for
the right to become human beings,'' he said. ``And we are looking
to you. . .to use your education and freedom to help set us free.''
</P>
<P>
   For the students, their encounter with Teyeb was a most unusual
``seminar day,'' which the high school sets aside more or less
annually for discussion of regions and issues remote from the daily
life of the school. Students selected the topics and arranged for
the speakers themselves. A talk on child slavery in the Indian
subcontinent and a workshop on how wealth and privilege affect
community development also were on Wednesday's program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to have them understand issues of diversity and
intolerance both here and globally,'' said Donna Nuzzo-Mueller, the
principal. ``It is especially important for students who have such
a wonderful education and who will be successful to know what it is
that the world really needs.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, most of the teens said they were
chastened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know there was still slavery around. It's unheard
of,'' said Jonathan Boyd, 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew about child labor, but this, . . .'' added Corey
Johnson, 17. ``I didn't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
