<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TENURE-EXPERIMENT-BOS     03-18 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENURE-EXPERIMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARKANSAS COLLEGE'S OPTIONS INSPIRE TENURE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONWAY, Ark. _ Winfred Thompson wants to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But caveat emptor, his critics say; what he is selling could
destroy the soul of the modern American university.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is this: every new hire at The University of Central
Arkansas, where Thompson is president, can get tenure or a
tenure-track position, or a 50 percent salary premium and a
three-year rolling contract. Those on contract can be fired, but
they still get two years' notice _ far more, Thompson notes, than
anyone in corporate America would ever receive.
</P>
<P>
   To Thompson, it's a matter of choice and of increasing
professors' productivity at a time when universities are under
suspicion of not paying enough attention to teaching and tuitions
that continue to increase faster than inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But to tenure's defenders, the deal threatens to make
prostitutes out of professors. Tenure guarantees freedom, they say,
and freedom is not something to be surrendered to the highest
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the debate indicates the ground shifting under the
concept of tenure, codified 84 years ago to guarantee stability and
free expression in academia. While few institutions are getting rid
of it altogether, critics and advocates alike say tenure is being
eroded in many smaller moves.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's initiative, approved by the public university's
trustees last week, is the most dramatic of these moves. The
question it will answer, tenure watchers say, is this: Is tenure an
inalienable principle, or does that principle have a price?
</P>
<P>
   ``This shifts the debate from tenure as a cherished principle to
a negotiable condition,'' said Richard Chait, a professor who is
studying the case as part of a national project on tenure for the
Graduate School of Education at Harvard. ``It's no longer an issue
of whether to sell one's services; it's how much will it cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenures defenders and critics alike say that the more professors
operate without tenure, the harder it becomes for those who have it
to defend it as an inalienable right.
</P>
<P>
   To those who dislike putting tenure up for sale, ``it's a
question of whether people are being paid to have their viewpoints
muzzled,'' Chait said. ``On the other hand, choice and voluntarism
are hard to counter. In an academy where academic freedom is the
watchword, one has to ask does academic freedom extend to the
freedom to determine the best lawful circumstances under which one
wishes to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of tenure have always defended it on two points. One,
it ensures that professors can discuss controversial subjects
without fear of losing their jobs. Two, lifetime tenure, with
removal only for significant cause, was an incentive to enter a
relatively low-paying profession.
</P>
<P>
   But with downsizing and efficiency the new bywords outside the
academy, lifetime job security has come to seem more unrealistic
even within it. Just north of this college town, for instance, two
plant closings led to more than 1,000 job cuts in January. If
companies can do it, tenure critics say, why not universities, when
students begin to demand, say, fewer courses in literature and more
in computer science?
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change in tenure is the sheer decline in the
percentage of professors who have it, the lowest percentage since
the American Association of University Professors formulated the
first widely used policy on it in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   According to the association, the percentage of faculty with
tenure dropped to 30 in 1995 from 36 in 1975, and the percentage of
faculty on tenure track dropped to 12 from 20 in that same time.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities began replacing those faculty with
part-time and nontenure-track faculty; the percentage of faculty in
positions that were not tenure track increased to 16 from 13
between 1975 and 1995, and the percentage of faculty who work part
time increased to 41 from 31.
</P>
<P>
   But even within the ranks who have tenure, there are more
strictures. More and more schools began requiring professors to
undergo post-tenure review; a representative study done by the the
American Association for Higher Education in 1996 found that 29
percent of schools have post-tenure review, and legislatures in
Wisconsin and California now require it. The University of Nebraska
has used tenure buy-outs to thin its numbers of tenured professors.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson announced his initiative in a speech welcoming the
faculty back on campus in August.
</P>
<P>
   While most professors start at $35,000 a year _ a competitive
salary for universities of this size _ those on the three-year
rolling contracts would start at $50,000-$55,000, and would
continue to receive a salary that was 40-50 percent higher than
tenured positions as they stayed in their jobs. The contract would
be renewed every year for an additional three years if performance
remained satisfactory, meaning anyone who was fired would get two
years' notice. And contracts would include a provision guaranteeing
academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The state legislature approved funding for 30 of the new
positions for this year; the university will decide later whether
to offer now-tenured or tenure-track professors the chance to
switch to a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of tenure is fine,'' Thompson said in an interview
in his office on this tidy, new campus. ``After a certain period of
time, people should only be removed for cause. But the longer I
have served, the more concerned I have become that we tolerate
behavior and performance that is detrimental to students and to the
institution, and we're not doing anything about it because the
procedural requirements of the tenure system have made it so
cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only for the most egregious personal behavior that we
ever dismiss someone. It usually has nothing to do with the ability
to teach, and it results in the almost certainty of a lawsuit. The
expense is so great, the experience is just not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The boyish-looking former congressional aide has become known as
a change agent in his 11 years as president, setting up an honors
college and suing the state board of higher education for the right
to award doctorates in physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes, however, have included the removal of only one
tenured professor. The American Association of University
Professors is still investigating the case, so Thompson won't speak
about it, but articles written about it suggest that the professor
was fired only after he began spitting at administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators here say they don't envision firing many people
on the new contracts. The benefit to the university, they say, is
that it can cut positions in the event of a budget crisis. More
immediately, the threat of termination puts a fire under the
faculty on contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does provide some incentive for faculty to continue to
contribute to the institution,'' said Provost John Mosbo. ``There
certainly is a public perception that once faculty are tenured,
professors go into semiretirement. These may be isolated cases, but
these situations are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Of two people hired since the policy was discussed, Mosbo said,
neither was interested in the premium. One, he said, thought tenure
offered prestige, the other said tenure was simply ``the way it
works'' at a university.
</P>
<P>
   But Mosbo himself, a former chemistry professor, said it would
have appealed to him when he arrived 25 years ago. Like many, he
had heavy bills for his education, and faith that his work was
good.
</P>
<P>
   But professors on campus worry that the system will cause too
much disruption, with the potential for professors coming and
going. Those who take the deal might be less committed to the
institution. And whatever stress the six-year bid for tenure might
inflict, it also ensures that the university hires those who meet
the highest academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tenure is a very symbolic thing,'' said Linda Shalick, a
professor of occupational therapy. ``It's symbolic of job security,
and it represents a commitment, from the university to the
professor, and the professor to the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while there is some concern here, there is even louder
consternation outside Arkansas about the initiative for fear of any
contagious effect. The dismay among tenure advocates is the
creeping corporate model in a place long protected from the
concerns of profit-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we say the corporate model reigns supreme, even in
education, you've blunted the critical function the university
performs, which is to criticize established thought,'' said Matthew
Finkin, a professor of law at the University of Illinois and author
of ``The Case for Tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   Academic freedom, Finkin and others worry, cannot be guaranteed
with a contract; administrators can make up reasons for dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   To the American Association of University Professors, the small
but steady assaults on tenure attack the very essence of the
university.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
