<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO NEW ACURAS WORTH THE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos (2) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A is for Acura.
</P>
<P>
   B is for bargain.
</P>
<P>
   C is for car, but you wouldn't expect A and B to add up to an
Acura.
</P>
<P>
   But one Acura fits this formula.
</P>
<P>
   After having the privilege of spending two weeks with a pair of
Acuras, first a sporty/luxury 1999 3.2 TL, then the 3.5 RL luxury
sedan, I proclaim the 3.2 TL a bargain. Even though it carries a
price tag of $28,405 (including destination charge), it compares
favorably with cars selling for up to $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Acura calls it a ``performance luxury sedan,'' a bit grander
than my description of it as a highly desirable four-door sports
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   This was one car I really would have liked to hold onto when the
time came to turn it back.
</P>
<P>
   But, before giving it up, I spun by an Acura dealer just to
confirm that the price, as they say, was right.
</P>
<P>
   It was _ and all but one of the TLs on this lot had ``sold''
stickers on them, proving that buyers were seeing the same thing I
was: lots of car for the money.
</P>
<P>
   From the responsive 3.2-liter, 24-valve, VTEC V6 coupled with a
four-speed automatic with a Sequential SportShift (you can use it
strictly as an automatic or swing the selector lever to another
gate and use itas a semimanual) to the 16-inchtires, it was a
pleasure to drivethis car.
</P>
<P>
   This all-new for '99 TL is the descendant of the Vigor and the
previous TL in the Acura line. Andit's the best of the bunch.
Morepower, better rear-seat legroom,a quieter riding experience
andlower price make this more car for less money.
</P>
<P>
   The only available option _ the Acura Navigation System ($2,000)
_ was a hoot. Three programmed trips brought us:
</P>
<P>
   1. Directly to a restaurant at Marina Bay in Quincy, Mass. Not a
big deal, but this was our first venture off Quincy Shore Drive and
the voice of our ``navigator'' brought us directly to the door we
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   2. To Portsmouth, N.H., without missing a turn. On the return
trip, the ``voice'' demanded a left turn as we (er, I) blithely
drove by the on-ramp to Interstate 95, earning a carful of cheerful
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   3. Delivered us to the wrong end of Hanover Avenue, a tiny,
one-way alleyway off Hanover Street in Boston's North End.
</P>
<P>
   Add in the other amenities _ power everything, heated leather
seats, single-CD player/Bose five-speaker sound system, electric
moonroof _ and you've got quite a package.
</P>
<P>
   The responsive ride was appropriate for the car, the legroom was
fine in back, and all in our party of criics-for-a-day fell in
love with the car . . . right back to its silver-tipped dual
exhaust extensions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
RL as in really luxurious
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A is for act _ because the TL should have been a tough act for
the 3.5 RL to follow.
</P>
<P>
   B, however, is for a bonafide, as in bonafide luxury sedan,
which the RL is.
</P>
<P>
   C is for cost. This is a $41,900 MSRP (plus $455 destination
charge) luxury sedan, redesigned for 1999, that doesn't have to
apologize for anything, including its price tag.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.5-liter V6 is neatly matched to the four-speed
transmission for performance. The ride was able to smooth over
Greater Boston's potholes without depriving the driver of a good
feel of the road.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned exterior caused one neighbor plus good friend
Matt at Irving's gas station to comment that they first thought
this was a Mercedes. That may not be what the folks at Honda/Acura
want to hear, but it's hardly a putdown, either, for the flagship
of this line.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping from the Acura back into our Camry _ not a shabby
performer in its own right _ was a further revelation that the
Acura people have moved ahead and gotten it right. ``It,'' in this
case, being the whole package.
</P>
<P>
   The RL was a rich Navy blue with a parchment leather interior.
It had the requisite heated leather seats, moonroof, adjustable
seats with memory that adjusted the whole car _ seats, wheel,
mirrors. The trunk-mounted CD changer coordinated well with both
the radio controls and steering wheel volume and track adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Both Acuras had an emergency brake pedal instead of a handle. To
release the TL's brake you just hit the pedal a second time. The RL
had a release lever low on the left side of the dash. Reaching for
it blindly, I managed to also hit the hood release, resulting in an
embarrassing pull-to-the-side-of-the-Expressway later to relatch
the hood.
</P>
<P>
   You could spend a half-dozen paragraphs listing the standard
equipment. Suffice it to say, everything you need _ and a lot you
probably don't _ is there. As with the TL, the only option is the
$2000 Acura Navigation System.
</P>
<P>
   With both cars, Acura is building a modern day Model T because
everything coming down the line is the same . . . except for the
color. It has to have a positive influence on quality control;
indeed, we found nothing out of sorts on either vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   A Significant-Other comment from Mrs. G was simply that either
of these Acuras could park in her driveway anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Notable from the owner's manual: 20 pages dealing with proper
installation and restraints for children. It's recommended reading
for both parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Safety, with ``smart'' airbags, is a major feature of the RL
with two notable features. The system senses the size and position
of front seat pas-sengers and adjusts the deploy-ment speed to the
severity of thecrash.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the seven-sensors supposedly would recognize when a
child was in the front seat (a no-no in itself) and (worse) napping
against the door. In that case the side airbag would not deploy.
</P>
<P>
   Crashing, fortunately, is not encouraged on our test drives.
</P>
<P>
   Or yours.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the first ABC of driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
