<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS FALLS IF SNOW DOESN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much is written each year about the business of skiing. New
Englanders effect the same faintly paternalistic pride about the
ski industry they do about other colorful home-grown products:
codfish cakes, baked beans, cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   As to the latter, since my home lies on the edge of ``cranberry
country'' _ one of the state's largest agricultural products _ I
was somewhat discouraged one year to learn that Wisconsin's bog
country had outproduced Massachussetts for the first time in
history. The margin was not much, but there it was: one more thing
my home state was not first in any longer, not to mention the
diminution of ``King Cranberry'' here in my old Swamp Yankee home.
Over the years we'd lost clams, oysters, flounder, horse chestnuts,
and the shoe industry; here was one more sign of retreat for
southeastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to report that our cranberry crop has been topping
Wisconsin's for the last couple of years, but we're not over that
private little worry we harbor every fall.
</P>
<P>
   No, I have absolutely no association with cranberry growing,
except for the aesthetic, and so it doesn't really matter a whit
which region produces more berries. It all goes in the same sauce
and it's all put there by the same company, as far as I can see.
</P>
<P>
   Mix a bit of vodka with cranberry juice and it's called a Cape
Codder; how tragic to start having to call that wonderful cocktail
a Madison or maybe a Lake Woebegoner!
</P>
<P>
   Still, on one of those blue-gold October days when the water
harvest is going on, bogs brimming with that crimson tide of fruit
being trucked for market, it gives one a little glow of pride to
drive a visitor down Federal Furnace Highway to see one of the last
remaining agricultural spectacles in our state.
</P>
<P>
   People root for the home product, and I think New Englanders
feel that way about their skiing. Like cranberries, it is colorful,
haplessly tied to vagaries of climate, making it a lot like
agriculture. The crop, of course, is snow.
</P>
<P>
   When the bottom lines are crunched, this year will be a bit like
that year the Massachusetts cranberry harvest fell to Wisconsin's.
Except that, comparitively speaking, the Rocky Mountain ski areas
have not had much to crow about, either.
</P>
<P>
   After Christmas, the news of layoffs in the big resorts _ up to
15 percent of the work force _ appeared from nearly everywhere
except the Northwest, British Columbia, and Alberta, where the big
snow fell all season.
</P>
<P>
   And in New England, it won't be pretty. The snow that finally
started to fall from a heretofore constipated winter will not be
enough to make up for a very lackluster season.
</P>
<P>
   American Skiing Company, the Les Otten enterprise that looked so
dazzling as it came together _ nine resorts in New England and the
West, growing out of Maine's once-modest Sunday River _ is now
struggling to get over this hump. Two weeks ago, American Skiing
announced a net loss of $10.8 million on revenue of $109.5 million,
a worse loss than previously predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's any secret that Otten has been playing a
breathlessly high-risk, fast-growth game with tens of millions of
dollars being pumped into what Otten still believes can be the
largest winter recreation empire in North America.
</P>
<P>
   And, more than skiing and snowboarding is involved. As boomers
age, their legs weakening at the time their 401k's brim with cash,
the vision is to market high-end real estate in areas that offer so
many recreational and cultural activities that the business won't
be so dependent on weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long term,'' Otten told a New York Times financial reporter
last week, ``I don't think this is going to have a detrimental
effect to the company. In the short term, it (weather-related
financial setback) is something that we understand and expect will
happen from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   To speculate the economics past Otten's comment is far beyond
the depth of this English major. It does seem he has bet on a few
speculative notions, one of them being that if a winter resort is
attractive and active enough it can compete with the wildly growing
warm-weather cruise and golf industries. Another is that real
estate profits can outweigh short-term lift ticket revenue losses.
</P>
<P>
   Intrawest (Stratton) and Booth Creek (Cranmore, Loon, Waterville
Valley) are on variations of the same mission, but for the last 15
years in snow country the needle has been stuck at around 50
million US skier visits per year.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of told-you-so's in the wake of American
Skiing's bad news, mainly from those peculiarly crabbed souls who
would always rather see a wild swinger strike out than hit a home
run. But Otten is no newcomer to the ski business, and he's
obviously not surprised by a bad winter.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen next in the world of high-stakes skibiz is
anybody's guess. But with the last few years of huge improvements
in snow production, grooming, fast and comfortable lifts, a
guarantee of decent skiing with just a minimal cooperation from the
weather, there is no question that the big winners have been skiers
and snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for the latter in the last 10 years _ in the
development of terrain parks, halfpipes, on-slope board shops _ has
been nothing short of an amazing arms race.
</P>
<P>
   For all this, the sport owes the Ottens and Gillets _
entrepreneurs whose hearts and lives surely are as invested in
skiing as their money _ the same thanks it gives the Seiberts and
Schneiders, who got the snowball rolling a couple of generations
ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
