<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROWTH SPURT SAVED HUSKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Their NCAA tournament ride was very much in
jeopardy of ending before a stunned, disbelieving sellout crowd of
more than 10,000 that had come to Gampel Pavilion last Sunday night
to watch No. 1 seed UConn, making its 11th consecutive tournament
appearance, dispatch No. 8 seed Xavier, a new kid on the tournament
block.
</P>
<P>
   But with 2:40 remaining in the game, it was Xavier that held a
6-point lead over a young Huskies team that had no trouble
defeating 16th seed St. Francis in Friday's first round, but was
having lots of trouble finding a way to rattle the Musketeers and
feisty point guard Nikki Kremer.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn knows the way to San Jose,'' was one of the signs that
the Gampel faithful held up earlier in the evening, a reference to
the site of the women's Final Four. But as time wound down, it
seemed doubtful that the Huskies would even be packing their bags
for Cincinnati (Xavier's home city) for this weekend's Mideast
Regional semifinals and final.
</P>
<P>
   But UConn, with two freshmen, two sophomores, and one junior
(Shea Ralph) in its starting lineup and only one senior, Amy Duran,
receiving significant minutes, grew up in a hurry _ and just in the
nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 84-78, the Huskies scored the last 8 points of the game,
with freshman forward Tamika Williams converting a pair of foul
shots with 7.1 seconds on the board to overcome a Xavier team that
did all the right things for most of the game and just about all
the wrong things in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't ready for spring break yet,'' said Ralph, ``but with
it being March Madness and all, you know it's one and done. I think
it was important that we won this game. It seems like that when
we've been in these situations before, we've kind of crumpled, with
everyone kind of looking at each other. We didn't do that this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   If UConn's low point was a first-half steal by Kremer from Big
East Player of the Year Svetlana Abrosimova that Kremer converted
into a 3-point bomb and 10-point lead, then its high point of the
game _ and season _ was its stirring comeback that set up
Saturday's game in Cincinnati against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's grit, combined with two crucial Xavier turnovers and a
pair of missed free throws by Kremer with the score knotted at 84,
made the difference, but it's doubtful that Huskies coach Geno
Auriemma diagrammed the crucial winning sequence on his play-board.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kremer misses (she had been 8 for 8 at the foul line),
UConn called time. Shea took the first shot, a leaner into the lane
that wasn't close. Duran kept the ball alive with another fling
from under the backboard. The rebound came to Williams, who was
fouled as she shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to stay settled,'' said Williams, who carried the
Huskies down the stretch. Eleven of her team-high 19 points came in
the second half, including 8 in the final 7:02 and 4 in the last
two minutes. ``I just wanted to take my time, go through the
routine, bounce the ball, spin it, follow through, and put it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The first one was a perfect swish, the second a rim rattler to
make it 86-84, and Williams, who was also immense on the boards
with a game-high nine rebounds, had done something she had never
experienced in a game at any level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never made two free throws to win a game at the end like
this,'' she said. ``Maybe a last-second shot to win a game, but
never free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a Dayton, Ohio, native who knew a few players on the
Xavier team that was playing just its third NCAA Tournament game
ever, said the thought of returning to her home state never crossed
her mind when she stepped to the free throw line. ``I wasn't
thinking about anything but winning the game at the end,'' she
said, ``but now that we won, I think we have a lot to prove in
Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   But Big East champ UConn (28-4), which graduated stars Nykesha
Sales (an All-American) and Rita Williams from last year's 34-3
Elite Eight team, already has proven it can overcome adversity.
</P>
<P>
   It trailed Xavier by 10 twice in the second half. Its go-to
players, Abrosimova and Ralph, were a combined 12 for 28 from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   But freshman center Asjha Jones, like Williams, had a monster
second half, scoring all of her 12 points and hauling down five of
her six rebounds after the break. It all served to wear down Xavier
and the gallant, but tiring Kremer, who played the entire 40
minutes, but ran out of gas at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that it had to be your night,'' said UConn associate
head coach Chris Dailey, ``when an 80 percent free throw shooter
(Kremer) misses and a 60 percent free throw shooter (Williams)
makes them.''
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma paid tribute to both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we both couldn't go. It's a shame they can't go,
too,'' he said. ``That's a great team we played, but our defense
came up big at the end and we made a couple of big shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game for us was like going up a hill and not gaining.
Every time we made a mistake, they took advantage and they never
gave us a chance to go on a run. I was really proud of how we
battled at the end. Sometimes you just have to hang around and see
how it comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, it all came out just fine for the Huskies, who at
least know the way to Cincinnati.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1317EST &QL; 
