<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-18 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW BIG BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Citibank Chief Executive Officer John Reed had a
vision. He saw a day when Citibank would take a fee on virtually
every imaginable commercial transaction, while at the same time
offering virtually every imaginable financial service, and taking a
fee on that as well.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Citibank, the technology needed to realize
Reed's vision was not then operational.
</P>
<P>
   It is now. And it will only get better, smarter, and more
powerful. High technology is transforming financial services before
our eyes. By the time the transformation is complete, which should
be no longer than two decades, it is likely that the United States
will have six or eight financial supermarkets, once called banks,
that will dominate the global financial system.
</P>
<P>
   That's what all these deals are about. The merger of Citibank
and Traveler's into Citigroup is about building the foundation for
a financial supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of Wells Fargo-Norwest is about building the
foundation for a financial supermarket. The much-whispered
combination of Chase Manhattan and a major brokerage firm is about
building the foundation for a financial supermarket. Technology
requires these combinations and is consolidating the financial
services industry with breath-taking speed.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, not so long ago, when the banking business was
about relationships. Press coverage of Fleet Bank's acquisition of
BankBoston was heavy on the ``relationship'' angle. There were long
takeouts on the relationship between Fleet Bank CEO Terry Murray
and BankBoston CEO Chad Gifford. There were stories about how the
top managers of the two banks would ``get along'' with one another.
These stories were no doubt true, but they are beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that what will separate winners from losers in the
brave new world of banking and financial services is technology.
Fleet Bank Chief Executive Officer Terry Murray didn't acquire
Shawmut Bank and BankBoston because he wanted to have a
relationship with anyone. He bought them both because Fleet needed
Shawmut's and BankBoston's financial resources to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet needs those resources because the technology it needs to
remain competitive is really expensive _ hundreds of millions of
dollars expensive _ and some of it won't work well at first. But if
Fleet doesn't have the means to purchase this new technology and
use it, then it will fall behind some other bank that does. And in
very short order Fleet will watch its best customers migrate to
that bigger, technologically superior bank.
</P>
<P>
   Take an every day example, the cellular phone. Use it now and
you can make a phone call. Use it with wireless modems, Jini
technology, and voice recognition software, and suddenly you have a
secure super-computer, capable of conducting thousands of financial
transactions in less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   These technologies will be widely available by the end of the
year 2003 (Jini software is already available, as are wireless
modems). High-end financial services customers will own them. As a
result, they will have access to their money and financial markets
at any time, in any place, regardless of whether they are climbing
the Himalayas or driving to work on the expressway. The bank that
does not have the technology to communicate with these customers
will lose them. The bank that does will keep them.
</P>
<P>
   Technology makes possible banking without boundaries. John
Reed's new vision is that Citigroup will someday have one billion
customers all around the globe. It will make money on customer fees
(like ATM charges, credit cards, checking services, mortgages,
personal loans, brokerage services, insurance, and the like). It
will make money on a host of financial services that it provides to
corporations and nation-states. Most important, it will make money
on its databases.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, aided by high technology, will have real-time
information on the purchasing patterns of hundreds or millions of
customers _ sorted, mixed, and matched so that anyone who ever
bought a box of golf balls or Microsoft software (and everything in
between) can be, as they say, ``captured'' at the touch of a few
keystrokes. How much do you suppose Titleist or Bill Gates would
pay for that information? The short answer is a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Banks like Fleet Financial and Chase Manhattan will either have
the technology to compete in this environment or they won't. In
order to acquire and continually upgrade these technologies, they
must have vast financial resources. Which is why mergers and
acquisitions in financial services will continue apace.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Bank's acquisition of BankBoston marks the end of the
nation's oldest independent bank. But it is just the beginning of
what will be a massive consolidation of the financial services
industry. Terry Murray has always understood the basic truth of his
business. It is this: Get big, get wired, or get bought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
