<SLUG> BC-TELCOM-DEALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG FIRMS LOOK TO STARTUPS IN SCRAMBLE TO CATCH TECH WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Redstone Communications, founded just 18 months ago, has yet to
ship a single product. But it has ideas and a new Internet switch,
which is what German telecommunications giant Siemens AG is after.
Siemens is expected to announce plans to buy Redstone for a
half-billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone, of Westford, is the third telecommunications start-up
in Massachusetts Siemens has purchased this month. Siemens launched
its $1 billion spending spree in an attempt to enter the market for
data networking. And Siemens is not alone. Since the beginning of
the year, three other start-ups have announced deals collectively
valued at nearly $700 million in cash and stock while a fourth,
Kenan Systems Inc., of Cambridge, Mass., received a surprising
$1.45 billion in stock from Lucent Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecommunications is the most exciting industry on earth,''
said James Dolce Jr., the 36-year-old cofounder and chief executive
of Redstone, who declined to discuss the financial terms of the
deal. ``With the Internet changing our life, the changes in
telecommunications are tantamount to the next Industrial Revolution
_ and we are just scratching the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   For companies like Redstone, where more than a dozen employees
will reportedly become instant millionaires, the latest gold rush
is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity. The five founders of the firm
will divide up more than $140 million, according to sources close
to the deal. The venture capitalists who saw promise in the
technology will also profit handsomely _ Waltham-based Battery
Ventures, which invested $4 million in second-round financing six
months ago, will reap $30 million when the deal closes in the next
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For Dolce, the Siemens deal is his third in a decade. He sold a
small data communications company in Providence in 1989 before
moving to the Boston area and cofounding Arris Networks Inc. He and
his partners sold that company after six months to Cascade
Communications Corp. for $175 million, just before Cascade was
acquired by Ascend Communications Inc. (Ascend, in turn, was
purchased by Lucent for $19.6 billion in stock in January).
</P>
<P>
   Companies are scrambling to acquire switching products using the
latest technology to meet the mushrooming demand for data
networking created by the popularity of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   These high-speed devices, which often sell for a fraction of the
current voice-only switches, are sold to major local and
long-distance telephone carriers around the world, and scores of
smaller independent phone companies and Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   These firms then sell services to business and residential
customers who often are clamoring for easier, cheaper, and faster
access to ever-higher volumes of Internet voice, data, and video
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now a lot of the big companies are simply scared if they
don't buy some of these start-ups,'' said Dave Rickey, president of
San Diego-based Applied Micro Circuits Corp., which is spending
$120 million in stock to acquire Cimaron Communications Corp. of
Andover, a 14-month-old supplier of telecommunications chips used
in fiber-optic networks.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the Cimaron deal, two Bay State venture capital
companies, Matrix Partners and Greylock Management, will split
about $63 million in Applied Micro stock, after investing just
$4.25 million in Cimaron in January 1998, according to Ram
Sudireddy, president and cofounder of Cimaron.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it was simply time to market _ an opportunity to be
part of a bigger company where we could go after larger markets
together,'' Sudireddy said. Sudireddy said his company expects to
have $3 million in revenue this year, escalating to $15 million in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And while other domestic companies pan Boston's northwest
suburbs seeking golden start-up nuggets, European
telecommunications companies have also staked big claims in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens, by far the most aggressive, has formed Unisphere
Solutions Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary based in Burlington,
Mass. focused on data-networking and Internet communications. At
Unisphere's core are a trio of Massachusetts companies, led by
Redstone along with Argon Networks Inc. of Littleton and Castle
Networks Inc. of Westford _ two companies that Siemens acquired
earlier this month for $550 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the buyers like Siemens realize that unless they do
something innovative and relatively quickly, they will be left out
of the telecommunications market that will be worth many billions
of dolars worldwide,'' Dolce said.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens, headquarted in Munich, along with Paris-based Alcatel
S.A. and Ericcson AB of Sweden are turning to US telecommunications
start-up companies in Greater Boston and Silicon Valley to expand
into new markets that combine voice and data to serve the exploding
Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   Ericcson, in anticipation of making some data networking
start-up acquisitions, has also established a US headquarters in
Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   All three European companies are following a path blazed nearly
five years ago by such leading North American companies as Lucent,
Cisco Systems Inc., Northern Telecom Inc., and 3Com Corp. These
firms all decided it was ultimately less expensive and faster to
acquire promising technologies instead of developing new products
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   And while some critics claim the European giants are starting
their buying sprees rather late, they have a major advantage over
their US counterparts in foreign markets. Siemens/Unisphere, with a
worldwide sales force of 26,000 people in 141 countries, can sell
easily recoup its hefty investment in Redstone's technology if it
has made the right bet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
