<HEADLINE>
WALSH IS BACK WHERE HE BELONGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ He came to his first National Football League meeting
20 years ago, a virtual unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for the next decade, Bill Walsh dominated the NFL,
bringing the San Francisco 49ers to new heights and establishing
the franchise was one of the best in the history of the game. He
won three Super Bowls as a coach, and the team he left behind won
two more.
</P>
<P>
   Then Walsh wandered for a decade. Several years on NBC
television as an analyst. A few more as head coach at Stanford. And
the last few writing books and working as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But now he has come full cycle. He is back to recreate what he
started in San Francisco. He is the 49ers general manager again,
nearing age 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so good to see him back,'' said Mike Holmgren, a
disciple of Walsh, who went on to win a Super Bowl in Green Bay and
is the new Seattle Seahawks coach. ``I was sitting up the front of
the room the other day in a competition committee meeting and
looked out into this sea of faces, and there he was. Bill Walsh. It
stunned me for a second, and then it made me feel good. He needs
this. This challenge. If he has the energy to do it, then it will
be good for him and San Francisco. It's a lot tougher now to get it
done than it was when he came in before.''
</P>
<P>
   This notion was seconded by Minnesota Vikings coach Dennis
Green, who like Holmgren, got his NFL start under Walsh with those
wonderful 49ers teams of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Bill,'' Green said. ``It's going to be fun to
see what he does this time. It's a new world now with the salary
cap, free agency, and all of the other stuff. It will be a tough
challenge for him, but he's always been a guy that found a way to
get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   George Seifert, who followed Walsh as coach of the 49ers, won
two Super Bowls himself, and is now the head coach in Carolina,
also is pleased for his old boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs something like this,'' said Seifert. ``This will be
good for him and San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh returned to these meetings, and all of the memories of the
past, with a heavy heart. His wife, Geri, suffered a serious stroke
about a month ago and just recently came home from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up early and get into work,'' said Walsh, trying to get
his groove back. ``Then I go home early to be with her. It is such
a difficult thing she is going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, already in the Hall of Fame, finds himself in the midst
of a bizarre situation.
</P>
<P>
   The man who hired him, Eddie DeBartolo, has been pushed into
exile by his family and the league. Team president Carmen Policy
and general manager Dwight Clark have packed up and left for
Cleveland and the expansion Browns. Former player personnel
director Vince Cerrato has been let go.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has returned to a ghost ship and a foundering franchise
that appears to be on the way down after an unparalleled run of
success over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we had to try to do is stabilize some
things,'' said Walsh. ``We had to let a bunch of veteran plays go
because of salary cap problems. I tried to make deals for those
guys so we can get some draft choices and start to rebuild this
thing all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a lot of help on defense. The offense has to carry us
next season if we are going to be any good. We still have the
people on offense that can do it. Defensively, we have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh says Jerry Rice, the greatest receiver of all time, will
be rested and kept out of practices. Ditto for aging pass rusher
Charles Haley, who returned for two playoff games last year. ``We
won't wear out Rice and Haley during the week,'' Walsh said. ``If
they are rested, they can still give us a lot on Sunday. And, we
will not rush Bryant Young back. That was a devastating knee injury
he suffered. There is no reason to bring him back too soon. We will
make sure we are overly cautious with him. He has been one of the
best defensive linemen in the league and that is the area where we
need the most help right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has no coaching ambitions. He sees himself as a source of
support to Steve Mariucci, who has had an impressive start in his
first two years with the Niners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be around practices, in camp and during the season,''
said Walsh, ``but I'll be around the edges. I won't be with the
coaches. If I see something I will speak up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I came back. I feel I can help this team get back
to the top. It is going to take some doing, but it can be done. I
enjoy being back. When I left, I left too soon. I didn't see it
then, but I know it now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
