<SLUG> BC-TALIBAN-PROTEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD TAKING UP THE CAUSE OF AFGHAN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The weather has not been cooperating with Mavis
Leno's cause.
</P>
<P>
   First a snowstorm kept her from testifying before a
congressional subcommittee in Washington. Then a rainstorm made her
late to a related appointment in her hometown of Los Angeles. But
no force of nature has been able to stop her from working the
phones and her circle of celebrity friends.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the Feminist Majority Foundation's campaign to give
women in war-torn Afghanistan the right to work, the right to
attend school, and literally the right to walk outside without fear
of stoning, Leno is asking Hollywood to focus on a real-life drama
with no pat ending. For months now, she has been talking up anyone
who is anyone about human rights abuses under the Taliban regime,
hoping that attention here will bring relief there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told every celebrity I've talked to that their wattage is
going to add that much more light to the issue, that much more
pressure . . .,'' Leno said. ``I want us to say to the world:
They're going to have to find someone else to pick on.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno, relatively new to political activism, conceded that many
Hollywood types had not heard of the Taliban before she called. Now
she's got A-list involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The movement to restore human rights to women in Afghanistan has
swept Hollywood, not quite replacing a free Tibet or AIDS research,
but becoming the cause of the moment among the celebrity crowd.
Leno and her husband, ``Tonight Show'' host Jay Leno, have used
their names, their connections, and $100,000 of their own money to
make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   The confirmed guest list for a dinner buffet she is co-hosting
for the Feminist Majority Foundation on March 29 runs from singer
Paula Abdul to actress Renee Zellweger, with dozens more such as
Melanie Griffith, Wynona Judd, and Heather Locklear in between. The
entertainment will include celebrity readings of letters from
Afghan women, thanking Hollywood women for their involvement. In
turn, Leno called the actresses' need to assist Afghan women
``primal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them have expressed a deep level of commitment; others
were already involved in our organization,'' said Leno, a writer
who grew up in California and joined the Feminist Majority board
just months after the Islamist movement seized the Afghan capital
of Kabul in the fall of 1996. ``But who can predict what people
will do? If you had told me I would be deeply involved in foreign
affairs issues in the Mideast 10 years ago, I'd have laughed. But
when you hear the specifics of the cases, you don't have an
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno understands that Hollywood alone can bring only so much
heat to the issue. She needs more widespread support to keep the
Clinton administration from recognizing the Taliban as a legitimate
government. So she recently outlined the situation in a letter to
Dear Abby. The response from readers was so great that it jammed
the lines at the telemarketing firm the Feminist Majority had
hired.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of ``take action'' kits have been mailed, with half of
the requested $2 donation going to help Afghan women in refugee
camps and half going toward the campaign to raise awareness of
their plight. For the money, contributors receive names of US and
UN officials to contact and a swatch of mesh, the small opening
through which Afghan women, forced to wear head-to-toe garments
called burqas outdoors, must see and breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here in the entertainment capital of the world, for
heaven's sake, and we decided to mobilize the most famous women in
the world to speak out against gender apartheid in Afghanistan,''
said Kathy Spillar, national coordinator of the Feminist Majority
in Los Angeles. ``We're coming together to say you can't treat
women like this anywhere in the world and get away with it. . . .
We're drawing the line in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports coming out of Afghanistan and the refugee camps in
bordering Pakistan depict a female population imprisoned in its own
homes. Women can no longer go outside unless accompanied by a male
relative. Others have allegedly been raped by Taliban soldiers, or
forced into a sort of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Once university professors and government employees, women were
ousted overnight from the workplace. Girls were sent home from
school, and their education was outlawed. Women were ordered to
give up their medical practices at the same time women were
forbidden from being examined by male doctors. The result,
advocates say, is that 70 percent of Afghanistan's population _ a
high percentage due to the tens of thousands of men killed during
the civil war _ is without health care, opportunity, or even food
in households headed by war widows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of women who are starving to death,'' said
Zieba Shorish-Shamley, who has visited the refugee camps as
president of the Washington-based Women's Alliance for Peace and
Human Rights in Afghanistan. ``Some are committing suicide,
drinking caustic soda, a household substance, that takes them three
days to die. Others jump out of buildings to escape seeing their
own children dying of starvation in front of their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wiping out a 5,000-year-old culture,'' she added.
``What the Taliban is doing is they are making genocide in many
forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Shorish-Shamley said she is grateful for Leno's help, for
Hollywood's help, for anyone's help in restoring women's rights in
Afghanistan. With more than 130 women's and human rights groups now
involved worldwide _ and a US secretary of state and first lady who
have condemned the violations against women in Afghanistan _
Shorish-Shamley described herself as skeptically hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening to women in Afghanistan is despicable,''
said Alyse Nelson, a spokeswoman for the President's Interagency
Council on Women. ``It's not just rhetoric. We're following up with
programs and policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno and other activists take some of the credit for the
attention being paid in State Department cubicles and corporate
boardrooms. Petitions have been sent to Washington. Demonstrations
have been held coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   When Southern California-based Unocal Corp. was leading a
consortium that planned an $8 billion energy pipeline that would
traverse Afghanistan, Leno spoke against it at the annual
stockholders meeting. The company, also under pressure from low
world oil prices and concern about the Taliban's sheltering of
terror suspect Osama bin Laden, withdrew from the pipeline in
December.
</P>
<P>
   This week, under a deal brokered by the United Nations, warring
factions in Afghanistan agreed to the creation of a coalition
government that would include all of the political forces. Previous
agreements have fallen apart. Shorish-Shamley said she is also
concerned that women will be kept from any peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country can't get back on its feet with these women living
inside their houses,'' said Leno. ``They will have to soften their
stance or the country won't survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is plain,'' she added. ``I don't care if the
Taliban stays in power, or if some faction I haven't heard of comes
into power. All I want is for the human rights of these women to be
restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Leno excused herself. She had more calls to make, more
politicians to lobby, more celebrities to contact for support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
