<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEP STUDY URGES SLUMBER-ONE PRIORITY  
 HEART DISEASE ALERT SOUNDS FOR MINORITIES  
 SEX AFTER MENOPAUSE? WHY NOT, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Sleep study urges slumber-one priority
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bedroom should be just for sleep and sex.
</P>
<P>
   That's the advice researchers offer in a study on how older
Americans can overcome insomnia. The report found that behavioral
therapy works slightly better and more enduringly than sleeping
pills, and combining the two is even better, at least for the short
term.
</P>
<P>
   So, say the authors, instead of just popping a pill, go to bed
only when you're sleepy. Don't watch TV or read in your bed or
bedroom. What's more, check your worries at the door. Head to
another part of the house when you can't fall asleep, or fall back
asleep, within 15 minutes. And get up at the same time every
morning, regardless of how much sleep you got the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers came up with that advice after running tests on
50 men and 28 women, all of whom were 55 or older and had
experienced insomnia for six months or longer. All had suffered
from their inability to sleep, finding that they were overtired,
could not function well, or saw their mood sour.
</P>
<P>
   Subjects were then divided into four groups getting eight weeks
of behavioral therapy, treatment with the sleeping pill temazepam,
combined behavioral and drug therapy, or a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Results were best among those who got the combined treatment,
nearly 64 percent of whom saw a reduction in time spent trying to
fall asleep. The reduction was 55 percent in the behavior-alone
group, nearly 47 percent among those getting the sleeping pill, and
17 percent among those who received an empty pill. Over a two-year
follow-up, however, the benefits of drug treatment declined
substantially.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in the current Journal of the American Medical
Association, was closely followed partly because insomnia is so
widespread among seniors, affecting up to one in four. But its
results apply to people of various ages. It also offers what is
believed to be the best comparison of different treatments, and it
shows how effective it can be to change simple behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Heart disease alert sounds for minorities
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Changing behavior also is critical to prevent heart disease, and
a a study suggests those changes should come earlier than we
thought, particularly for many minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The report, in JAMA, compared cardiovascular risk factors among
more than 7,000 blacks, Mexican-Americans, and whites age 6 to 24.
It found that blacks and Mexican-Americans were at substantially
greater risk than whites, apparently because they were poorer and
less likely to engage in behaviors known to reduce the risk of
heart disease, such as eating healthily and exercising.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggests that ``heart disease prevention really needs
to begin at very young ages, as early as kindergarten,'' says
Marilyn A. Winkleby, the lead author and a senior researcher at the
Stanford Center for Research in Disease Prevention in California.
</P>
<P>
   While many in minority communities know a lot about their
increased risk of breast cancer and AIDS, Winkleby says, they
generally are not as aware of a greater risk of heart disease,
which is the leading cause of death in America. Genetics may play a
small role in raising the risk of blacks and Mexican-Americans, she
adds, ``but the bulk of it is lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sex after menopause? Why not, study says
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's widely believed in America that menopause spells the
beginning of the end for women when it comes to sex.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey debunks that myth. A majority of women age 50 to
65 say their sexual desire is as robust as before menopause, and
some say it's more so. The reasons, the women told pollsters, range
from fewer child-rearing responsibilities to no worries about
getting pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first study that really asked women their views
about menopause and sex,'' says Dr. Donnica L. Moore, a
gynecologist in New Jersey who chairs an educational campaign that
commissioned the survey. The poll, which involved 1,001 menopausal
women, was paid for by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, which makes the
nation's most popular hormone-replacement therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want women to look forward to menopause,'' Moore adds.
``It's the beginning of the last third of their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
