<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOBSON PUTS HEAT ON REYNOLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Jon Jacobson, a big Boston money manager who normally avoids
the spotlight, is going public to turn up the heat on managers of
Reynolds Metals Co. and to boost their slumping stock.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson's $1.8 billion hedge fund, Highfields Capital
Management, disclosed its 5.5 percent interest in the maker of
Reynolds Wrap Wednesday and detailed a behind-the-scenes dispute
now sure to spill into the company's annual meeting May 20.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson was the star stock picker who produced huge returns at
Harvard Management Corp., investor of Harvard University's $13
billion endowment, before leaving to start Highfields Capital last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Reynolds Metals stock is by far the most controversial
investment Highfields has made to date. In a regulatory filing, the
firm said Reynolds managers weren't ``fully committed'' to
maximizing the value of the company and should retain investment
bankers to look into their options, including a sale or a spin-off
of some units.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds executives were not immediately available to comment
Wednesday and Highfields officials declined to comment. Reynolds
stock rose 8 percent after the news, gaining 3 1/2 to 47.
</P>
<P>
   Highfields has become one of the largest investors in Reynolds.
Wellington Management Co. of Boston was the largest shareholder
with a 10 percent interest in the company, as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Highfields, the second-largest Boston hedge fund behind Jeff
Vinik's Vinik Asset Management, has tended to invest in large
stocks tangled in special situtations. Telecom Italia, the phone
company that whetted the merger interest of Olivetti, was by far
the firm's largest holding at the end of 1998, accounting for 17.7
percent of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Philips Electronics, which made a bid for VLSI Technology, and
Mobil Corp., which agreed to sell itself to Exxon, were other big
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson has always had a taste for concentrated investments,
which magnifies the success and failure of a stockpicker's
selections. That helped explain his annualized returns of 42.7
percent over his last three years at Harvard Management, which gave
Highfields $500 million to run.
</P>
<P>
   Highfields representatives first spoke with Reynolds managers on
Feb. 16 to discuss the company's performance and strategic options,
according to the documents filed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated the same day, they asked Reynolds to include a
shareholder proposal in proxy material for the company's annual
meeting. The proposal would request that the company hire bankers,
explore alternatives, and form a committee of outside directors to
manage the process.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, based in Richmond, rejected the request for a written
proxy proposal but said Highfields officials could make their case
in person at the annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, Reynolds directors amended the terms of its
antitakeover shareholders rights plan. The company said the changes
adjusted the plan to conform with court decisions and current
practices in similar plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rights under the plan become exercisable if any shareholder buys
or makes a tender offer for 15 percent of all Reynolds shares.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds is a well-known aluminum producer but also operates a
packaging business responsible for its well-known household foils
and other products.
</P>
<P>
   As a stock, Reynolds has been a mediocre performer. The shares
are down 40 percent from a high reached in May 1997 and trade for
less than their value of a decade ago. Part of the problem: A huge
glut of aluminum has depressed the commodity's value.
</P>
<P>
   In its regulatory filing, Highfields said Reynolds stock traded
at roughly half the value the company's two leading business units
would command if they were split up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The status quo has not and is unlikely to unlock this value,''
Highfields said in its papers. Reynolds told the SEC that such
estimates were ``potentially misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds had hired Merrill Lynch to conduct a ``portfolio
review'' of its businesses in 1996. Directors acted on Merrill's
proposal and later divested its North American can business and
other ``noncore'' operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiring the board to repeat the process with the assistance
of other or additional investment bankers would be a waste of
corporate assets,'' Reynolds said in its regulatory filing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
