<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SUNSCREEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREADING `SUNSCREEN' ON THE AIRWAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL BEGGY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most songs tell a story; this one is a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)'' is an unlikely tune to
be scorching up the charts, because it isn't really a song. It's a
spoken litany of advice over part of a movie soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Once you hear it, it sticks with you: the booming voice of
Australian actor Lee Perry giving the mock graduation address that
starts, ``Ladies and gentlemen of the class of 1999, wear
sunscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the common-sense speech _ often requested on radio
stations as the Sunscreen Song _ unfolds over the song
``Everybody's Free (To Feel Good)'' by Quindon Tarver from the
soundtrack of Australian director Baz Luhrmann's 1996 film
``William Shakespeare's Romeo &AMP; Juliet.'' It is filled with such
nuggets as: ``Stretch.'' ``Do one thing everyday that scares you.''
``Floss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's Free'' evolved from a graduation-time column by
Mary Schmich in the Chicago Tribune in 1997 that turned into an
Internet hoax involving Kurt Vonnegut and MIT before Luhrmann
decided the column and the story behind it would make a great
addition to a music compilation he was producing.
</P>
<P>
   From print to cyberspace to the airwaves to print again _ a
'90s-style media mash was brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea _ who could? _ when I wrote it that any of this
would take place,'' said Schmich from Chicago, where she's written
a thrice-weekly column since 1992. ``I wanted to write a graduation
speech and I said, `Not that anybody asked me.' '' But you can bet
come this commencement season, Schmich will be part of a lot of
graduations.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of Boston's largest stations play the song as part of
their regular rotation, so if you haven't heard it on the radio,
chances are you will soon. Local sales of Luhrmann's CD ``Something
for Everybody'' have increased tenfold in the last week, said
DeeDee Kearney, the regional representative for Capitol Records,
which has a sweet marketing dilemma on its hands. In every city and
station where it has been tested, the song has caught on, and the
record company can't get it to stores fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston area was one of the first to give the song airtime,
but it really took hold earlier this year in the Portland and
Seattle radio markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really on all formats, which is what makes it so
unusual,'' said Kearney. The only station that hasn't tried it yet
is WKLB, which has a country music format. ``I wouldn't be
surprised, if they tested it, that it didn't `pop' there as well,''
Kearney said.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful trends in music are usually driven by one
market segment, but ``Everybody's Free'' is a success across ages
and formats, said Robyn Ryland of Capitol's New York office. ``We
haven't had anything that compares to this in memory.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that the song's message is positive, if
simple. ``So many things are negative in music. Kids are requesting
it and parents think it's OK,'' said ``Kid'' David Corey, music
director for Kiss-108 in Boston. ``Parents are requesting it too.''
</P>
<P>
   For Schmich, who also writes the Brenda Starr comic strip, it
has been a somewhat anonymous brush with fame. Shortly after her
column appeared it was spread on the Internet as a graduation
address by Kurt Vonnegut to the MIT graduating class. Of course it
wasn't written by the novelist, nor was he the commencement
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The story was so convincing, even Vonnegut's wife, photographer
Jill Krementz, fell for it and forwarded it to his children as his
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 or so cities where the song is playing on the
airwaves, Chicago isn't one of them. But Schmich is starting to get
some recognition, has received about $100 in royalties, and has
spent several days ``on the wrong side of interviews'' with
reporters from around the country. To top it off, Schmich, who
confesses a secret passion for song-writing, could find herself
being nominated next year for a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh wow, hadn't thought of that,'' said Schmich. So what's the
columnist-songwriter's next project? ``Writing tomorrow's column.''
Simple and straightforward. Right where this all started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
