<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5214 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARPS-COLUMN-LADN &LR;      03-18 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING THE OSCAR ENTRIES FOR BEST DRAMATIC SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who will win the Oscar for original dramatic score
on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   We asked the husband-and-wife film composing team of Starr
Parodi and Jeff Eden Fair to handicap the nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite is clearly John Williams for his emotional ``Saving
Private Ryan'' score.
</P>
<P>
   ``His score will win,'' Parodi declared. ``It's brilliant and
moving. We tend to go for really emotional film music. But even
while Williams is the favorite, it's also the most amazing score.
His music reflected the maturity and bravery you see in the film.
In most action movies, directors generally like the music to
reflect the action. But in `Private Ryan,' the soundtrack was
silent during many of the action sequences, which made the music
more powerful when it did come in.''
</P>
<P>
   The versatile Parodi and Fair's first full-length score was for
Rysher Films' 1998 ``The 18th Angel,'' which starred Stanley Tucci
and Maximillian Schell, and in which the Los Angeles composers
worked with a 90-piece orchestra and boys choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scores this year really aren't on a level playing field in
terms of budget,'' Fair said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Williams' ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the Academy Award
nominees for dramatic score are David Hirschfelder for
``Elizabeth,'' Nicola Piovani for ``Life Is Beautiful,'' Randy
Newman for ``Pleasantville'' and Hans Zimmer for ``The Thin Red
Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Parodi pointed out that ``Pleasantville'' was more song-driven
than score-driven, and the subsequent soundtrack album consisted of
pop songs as well as Newman's orchestral score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The score didn't play as big a role in the film as it did in
`Private Ryan,''' she said. ``Newman is amazing, and his score is
beautiful. And even when we saw the movie, we didn't realize how
great the score was until we got the CD afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Parodi also liked Piovani's atmospheric ``Life Is Beautiful''
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very traditional Italian score with the exception of
the main title,'' she offered. ``It truly reflected the period.
There was a lot of emotion there.''
</P>
<P>
   Parodi and Fair _ who've scored such high-profile trailers as
``Deep Impact,'' ``Braveheart,'' ``Leaving Las Vegas'' and
``GoldenEye'' _ recently finished an indie titled ``Screenland
Drive,'' a dark comedy by first-time feature director Thomas
Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening back to a good score really allows you to relive the
move,'' Fair said. ``It brings back a lot of scenes that may mean
something to you. It should amount to more than just a passive
listening experience.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
