<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-VALENTIN-B     03-18 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VALENTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN: FAMILY MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Sometimes it's pretty hard to relate to
today's major league baseball players, what with their pampered
lifestyle and multimillion-dollar contracts. But every once in a
while, a dose of sobering reality strikes a player and we all are
reminded that ballplayers suffer sometimes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox third baseman John Valentin has gone through such a
situation this spring. Valentin had to make a quick reaction to a
family crisis over the weekend, and it may have helped save a niece
who on Monday had an operation for a brain tumor in a New York
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Valentin, 9, is doing just fine at Beth Israel North
Hospital in New York. So is her father, Arnold, of nearby Hazlett,
N.J. John Valentin is his younger brother and lives only a few
miles away in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Valentin is not a man without means. He is an
investigator for the prosecutor's office in Essex County, N.J. But
he needed some support once doctors discovered a recurring headache
that had bothered his oldest daughter was caused by a tumor in the
fourth brain chamber. On Monday, doctors removed a golf ball-sized
tumor. With some luck, says Valentin, she will recover fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed to be there and show my family some support,''
said the Red Sox third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   This is far from Valentin's first encounter with a cancer
patient. He's a regular visitor to the Dana Farber Cancer Institute
in Boston. His mere presence is said to brighten the spirits of
many of the children there.
</P>
<P>
   But it never hit as close to home as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really incredible,'' said Valentin. ``In Boston, I see
these children every day at the park or in the hospitals. You feel
for the families and you try to do as much as you can. You never
realize it can happen to your family, and it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family came together and we talked about a lot of things _
how you've got to be prepared for it, hope that everything will be
all right, put your trust with the doctors and let them do what
they do best, and just pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin had been following his niece's progress by telephone
until last Friday, when the team announced he was leaving camp
indefinitely for personal reasons. In a training camp starved for
news, this stirred suspicion of a possible trade. But it was
confirmed he was in New Jersey on a family matter a couple of days
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked for permission to go home,''said manager Jimy
Williams. ``It was a family situation and he thought he could help
out. I told him to go ahead and not to worry about things here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he arrived in New Jersey, Valentin said, he found he could
be helpful in a lot of ways. His family was shaken and needed some
comfort. He was there, and for them that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all the children I dealt with in Boston,'' said
Valentin, ``I kind of took it better than most of my family. It was
actually kind of good that I had that kind of experience behind me.
I could relieve some of the pain from my family. It was good that I
was there to talk with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they tell us that that everything is going to be OK and
that cancer is curable, then that's what you have to hold on to.
The important thing is that we were all there and were supporting
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin returned to camp Wednesday and held an impromptu press
conference, where he said he has a better understanding of life
because of this experience. Like his brother, he has two children,
Justin John, 4, and Kendall Marie, 2. What happened to Alexandra
could happen to his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball means nothing,'' said Valentin. ``A situation like
this puts things in perspective. I'm thankful in a way for having
the experience of dealing with so many families. It's given me
information about the whole situation and about the kids who get
this disease. I'm thankful for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this type of situation, you only think that the worst is
going to happen. You need to be there. We're fortunate it turned
out the way it did. We knew we had to think positive. I tell all
the families that I touch that I'm not just there trying to put a
smile on their face. I sort of hold their hands, lift up their
glass, and remind them that it is still half full.''
</P>
</TEXT>
