<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECAST OF 70 PUTS HEAT ON MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Life changes when you hit 70 home runs in a
single season. When you are Everybody's Man of the Year and some
goof pays $3 million for one of your $10 home run balls, you can't
expect to walk around anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire had fun in the offseason of his life. He did
Letterman, Rosie, and the ESPYs. He got in bed with Helen Hunt in
``Mad About You.'' He was a guest star _ or at least his voice was
_ on ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back playing baseball (already with five spring
training homers), preparing for an encore season and answering an
endless succession of barking dogs who ask, ``Can you hit 70
again?''
</P>
<P>
   He's not complaining. McGwire knows that school teachers and
plumbers don't want to hear about the woes of fame and fortune. He
knows he is truly blessed. But who wants to be a prisoner of fame?
How would any of us like it if we couldn't go to the local 7-11 for
a Slurpee without everybody knowing?
</P>
<P>
   There are no trips to 7-11 for McGwire. No stops at the ATM
machine. No movies. It's just not worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' he said Wednesday after going 1 for 3 (a hard
single) against the Kansas City Royals at Roger Dean Stadium.
``I've been out a few times at night down here and people come up
to me and go, `Oh, I think it's so great that you're out hanging
out with us.' It's nothing new to me but when I go out, I have to
be mentally prepared to go out because people want to talk and they
want to shake your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird went to matinees at Chestnut Hill _ under a baseball
cap. McGwire won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about going to the movies is, you walk in and the
people who work there tell everybody that works there, and they get
on the phone and call their friends and their friends start coming
over and the next thing you know you leave the movies and there's
people waiting for you outside.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he hasn't read most of the stuff that was written about
himself and Sammy Sosa after last season. Like most ballplayers, he
thumbs through the USA Today that the hotel slips under the door
for free.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs when reminded of Senator Ted Kennedy's famous
double-gaffe at a presidential fund-raiser last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean Mike McGwire?,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. And Sammy Soo-ser.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have latched onto the Summer of '98 and McGwire has
become his generation's Neil Armstrong. It seems that every person
he meets in the street just has to shake his hand and tell him
where they were and what they were doing when Big Mac cranked No.
62 and No. 70.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Matthew, the chunky batboy from '98, is playing ball,
doing what comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my son was going to be a switch hitter,'' said
McGwire. ``But I never say anything to him about baseball. I just
let him go. Have fun. Enjoy it. See the ball and take a swing at
it. He's starting to really sprout now. He's starting to get out of
his chubby stage. It'd be great if he became a pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   If you bought any signed McGwire stuff in a baseball card store
recently, get your money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every autograph in a memorabilia store out there is a forgery
because I don't do them,'' he said. ``The only way you can get an
autograph from me is if you see me in public or at a ballpark. I
sign 95 percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   If you followed McGwire down the stretch, it was difficult to
get past the notion that he was trying to hit home runs on that
final weekend against the Expos. Sosa pulled ahead of McGwire,
66-65, Friday night, but Big Mac finished with a flurry, cranking
five homers in is final 11 at-bats, including two Saturday and two
more Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never tried to hit a home run,'' he insisted. ``I'm so
mentally prepared every at-bat, if you're going to throw anything
over the white part of the plate and if my swing is on, I have a
chance. I got some balls to hit the last weekend of the season. We
were playing Montreal. They had young studs who threw hard and went
right at me. But what youngster wouldn't do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's the unrealistic thing of, `Can you do 70 again?'
What happened last year might never happen again. And if it
doesn't, does it mean there was anything wrong with it?''
</P>
<P>
   No. Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
