<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-PIPHER-BOS &LR;      03-18 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-PIPHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGING THE AGE DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer and psychologist Mary Pipher recalls the story of a
client who took her mother to a therapist. After the appointment,
the mother reported that she'd passed her mental health checkup and
didn't need to go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you tell him about the bankruptcy? Did you tell him about
your panic attacks?'' the daughter asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' her mother replied sharply. ``It was none of his
business.''
</P>
<P>
   To Pipher, the story is a perfect example of the exasperating
but common sorts of ``cultural collisions'' that take place between
older people and their children, two generations shaped by vastly
different cultures. In this case the clash was between an older
person raised to believe in the value of keeping one's feelings to
oneself, and her baby boomer daughter, whose peer group's credo is
``emote and be authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   There are countless examples of such collisions, Pipher writes
in her new book, ``Another Country: Navigating the Emotional
Terrain of our Elders'' (Riverhead). A father who gets upset
because his daughter wants to bring up the past, while he prefers
to ``let sleeping dogs lie.'' The son who wanted to know his
mother's medical condition, while she ``doesn't want him to
worry.''
</P>
<P>
   This vast psychological ``terra incognita'' that separates the
generations is probably wider now than it's ever been, Pipher
maintains, with families scattered across the country and little
exposure to one another's universes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``aging in America is harder than it needs to be,''
writes Pipher, 51, in her book, a kind of field guide to old age,
combining personal stories with social theory.
</P>
<P>
   Today's elderly and their families are dealing with the
vexations of old age _ physical decline, affordable housing, and
high health-care costs, she says, but the two generations ``don't
even know how to talk about our problems. We have no language for
nurturing interdependency.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Americans don't have the traditions and wisdom to
make the final years of life manageable. ``The last years of a
relationship are important ones,'' she says. ``We need to reconnect
the age groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipher previously tackled life's difficult passages in the
best-selling ``Reviving Ophelia'' (Ballantine), her empathetic 1994
book about how our culture affects the mental health of adolescent
girls.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Another Country,'' Pipher decided to focus on a
subsection of the population she says writers usually overlook. She
was not interested in the elders she calls the ``young-old'' _
healthy, ``you-are-only-as-young-as-you-feel'' seniors enjoying
their golden years _ but rather the ``old-old,'' whose lives are
characterized by ill health and loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``What tends to be written about less are the really difficult
last years, when health is failing, people are losing
relationships, and may be losing homes and bank accounts. As a
student of human behavior, I was interested in how people coped
with enormous amounts of loss,'' she said in a telephone interview
from her home in Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Pipher interviewed her clients, friends, and neighbors _ older
Midwesterners who had experienced the rigors of farm life, poverty,
and war _ as well as the children who were struggling to care for
them. She did hear happy stories of resilience and humor _ such as
the man, married 50 years, who shared the secret of a successful
marriage: He looked in the mirror every morning and said, ``You're
no prize, either.'' There were stories of parents and children
doing well together, such as the daughter who takes her mother to
Hawaii every February and drives 50 miles each Sunday to spend the
day with her.
</P>
<P>
   But more often she heard sorrowful tales _ from both generations
_ of conflict, frustration, guilt, and anger. ``While the old often
feel abandoned and misunderstood, their younger relatives often
feel unappreciated, stressed, and guilty,'' writes Pipher. ``Hurt
feelings often come from taking personally problems that are
cultural or developmental.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipher says she was motivated to write the book because, as she
herself aged, she was curious about how older people cope with
difficulties. She was struck by two significant differences between
old people and baby boomers. The elderly, who came of age before
the popularity of Freudian psychology, are less analytical than
their self-reflective children. And elders define themselves in
relation to their community, while boomers are more
individualistic.
</P>
<P>
   Older people grew up at a time when ``people had certain
communal responsibilities and reputations,'' Pipher says. ``In the
small town I grew up in, people had a role to play. That kind of
world has been replaced by one in which we are seen more as
consumers. People in the 1990s are thought about as demographic
groups and shopping niches.''
</P>
<P>
   These outlooks cause all sorts of trickle-down effects, which
make for no end of frustration and miscommunication, she says: Old
people show love by being useful, while their children touch, or
say ``I love you''; old people _ raised to put their trust in
authority _ are afraid to confront their doctors, unlike their more
cynical baby boomer children.
</P>
<P>
   Pipher notes being surprised at how resilient and adaptable
older people showed themselves to be. ``One thing that generation
knows how to do is put on their dancing shoes and go out on a
Saturday night. This is not something our generation knows how to
do. They know how to process pain but not how to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds: ``I would certainly not have seen the older generation
as having a lot to teach our generation about mental health. I
would show up at their homes, and despite the fact that I was young
and healthy and had a nice life, they would be more cheerful than
me. I thought: They know some stuff!''
</P>
<P>
   As she gets older, Pipher finds herself more apt to appreciate
the coping strategies developed by older people. Putting on a happy
face is not necessarily all that bad, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense you can see it as setting themselves up to being
hypocritical or in denial. Or you can see it as setting themselves
up to put on a happy face. And sometimes you feel better that way
than if you are trained to be in touch with your feelings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
