<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WOMEN TRUST THEIR BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; was passionate about natural childbirth and breast feeding
when I was having babies in the '60s. At the time, we rebellious
young mothers were fighting assembly-line methods of delivery,
uptight hospitals, and take-charge doctors. Natural childbirth is
far less popular these days, perhaps because we've all grown used
to being managed by managed care.
</P>
<P>
   When I received this letter from Sandra Steingraber, honoring
the birth of her daughter, Faith, I wanted to share parts of it
with you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first trimester was a return to childhood. I went to bed
at 9. I took naps. I threw up. I looked on all food with deep
suspicion. I even bought a baby toothbrush because my big grown-up
one somehow gagged me. During the fourth month, April, I began to
swell. By May, I was dreamy with estrogen and flush with blood.
(Pregnancy increases blood volume by a third.) By June, I was a
walking aquarium tank. Inside me, Sea World, water ballet, hourly
shows. Leaps of Faith.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Lightening' is an old midwifery term for the descent of the
fetus into the pelvis a few weeks before birth. The further the
baby drops down into its bony cage, the lighter the mother feels.
This happened for me just as August turned into September. Then one
day, amniotic fluid gushed down my legs and ran across the
floorboards; a half-hour later I felt as though I were having
intense menstrual cramps. On the scale of physical torment, the
pain of labor is not the strongest pain I've ever endured. Back
spasms are worse. So is orthodontics. But the pain of childbirth is
the most exhausting pain I have ever experienced. It is truly labor
_ this passing of one life through the body of another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain came in from the sides, like my pelvis was caught in
an ever-tightening vise. The labor of labor was the fact that I was
both the squeezed and the squeezer. Being squeezed was bearable _
as long as I kept breathing and listening to my husband's voice. It
was the completely involuntary work of doing all the squeezing that
was so overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was good at letting pain pass through me like wind through a
tunnel, but during delivery I was asked to push into the pain
instead of casting my consciousness away from it. I balked. I
wanted to go home. At some point, as the baby's head appeared, the
tissues around the mouth of the vagina become numb, like a foot
that has gone to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is useful. I pushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I ignored all the advice I got about having a
`flexible birth plan' and remaining `open to' narcotics, epidurals,
and other pain-numbing drugs. There is nothing heroic, childbirth
educators are fond of saying, about experiencing pain; there is
nothing to prove through suffering, they emphasize, when so many
alternatives exist. Frankly, hospital-based childbirth classes are
more about making women familiar with (and therefore compliant
consumers of) medical interventions than they are about helping
women trust their own bodies. Thus, drugs hang in the birthing room
like the apple in Eden. I am glad I closed my mind against them.
Hell yes, drug-free childbirth is heroic. What does it prove? That
desire is greater than fear, that women are brave and
self-sufficient, that consciousness is better than numbness, that
out of pain comes joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra is also choosing to breast-feed her daughter. She
recalls:
</P>
<P>
   ``My milk did not come in until Day 5. When it did, I was taking
a nap and had the vague sensation that my chest was fizzing, as
though my breasts were two Coke bottles that someone had shaken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning to breast-feed is like learning the tango. You wonder
how we managed to overpopulate the earth. First, the baby screams
and there is no milk. Then there is milk but the baby sleeps five
hours and the breasts harden painfully. Finally, the baby and the
breasts fill and empty in synchrony. It took weeks. For Faith,
mastery of the breast has brought a kind of complete bliss I've
never seen before; eating, intimacy, and play all in the same
gesture. No one has ever enjoyed my body more. When she is finished
eating, she pops her mouth off, heaves a sigh, and then throws her
head down on my chest, arms spread, with a nipple in her ear _ as
if listening for the milky tide to rush back in.''
</P>
<P>
   My own daughter Laura has just turned 35, and I still remember
my ecstatic return from the delivery room, and saying to my
husband, who had been banned from my side during the birth, ``I
could go back up there and do it again.'' I still treasure the
memory of that daring adventure and the bliss of those mutual
moments of satiation, one of us full of milk, and the other filled
to the brim by the rapture of loving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
