<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOSTON ACCENTS HITS THE SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ What is this, the NCAA South Regional, or
some sort of coaching Beanpot?
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four coaches with teams in this most competitive of
all regionals have Boston backgrounds. We've got St. John's coach
Mike Jarvis, a Cambridge native whose resume includes playing at
Northeastern and coaching at Cambridge Rindge &AMP; Latin, Harvard, and
Boston University; Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien, Boston College
'71, who coached 11 years at his alma mater; and Maryland coach
Gary Williams, who spent one year as assistant and four years as
head coach at BC.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth coach is Auburn's Cliff Ellis, who says he has heard
of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The entanglement is even more pronounced when you consider that
O'Brien now has the job Williams had from 1986 through 1989. ``I
know Jim O'Brien well,'' Williams says. ``He followed me at BC, and
he got to Ohio State eventually. I hope he's not coming to Maryland
to take my job.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien plans on staying in Columbus for a while. He is still
acclimating himself to life in the Big Ten. He would have been
ecstatic had someone told him his team would finish in the upper
half of the league this season. When you're 1-15 in league
competition, you don't have grandiose notions, even if you are
getting a transfer guard you know intimately. In the normal course
of hoop events, the simple addition of one 5-foot-9-inch guard
doesn't have an enormous effect on a team. But, then, there aren't
many Scoonie Penns floating around.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Scoonie told everyone in the fall that Ohio State
would be in the NCAA Tournament this season. ``I don't know how the
other kids responded,'' O'Brien says, ``but I thought he was off
the wall. The only goal I had for us this year was to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   His fourth-seeded squad improved enough to face top-seeded
Auburn in the second game of the South Regional doubleheader. The
truth of the matter is that the Ohio State season has already been
made just by getting into the tournament. Making it to the Sweet 16
is a bonus. Getting to the Final Four might turn out to be the
Third Miracle of Fatima.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien won't, or can't, admit this, but he has less at stake
here than the other three coaches. His team is seeded fourth among
this group for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the most internal pressure is Williams, who has
never taken a team to the Elite Eight and who has an athletic squad
led by a sensational guard sure to be a high lottery pick, and
probably sooner, rather than later. This may or not be the best
shot of his career at a Final Four, but it is a very good one and
he needs to get there sometime. Since he is unlikely to be coaching
Steve Francis next year, this might be a good time to get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland (28-5) will be meeting St. John's (27-8) in the opener.
If you like mid-size teams loaded with athleticism and exceptional
basketball versatility, this game is for you. With Maryland having
lost 6-10 center Obina Ekezie to a torn Achilles' tendon a while
back, the Terps are strictly a greyhound, finesse team now. St.
John's doesn't employ anyone taller than 6-7 in any meaningful
capacity. This doesn't mean there won't be ferocious rebound
battles. It just means that this will be a pure basketball game and
not, as Johnny Most would say, a ``muscle tussle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have similar players,'' Williams maintains. ``It's a great
matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis has done a sensational job with a St. John's team
bequeathed to him by Frantic Fran Fraschilla. Whereas the
diminutive Frashcilla was about a 12 on the Uptight-O-Meter, Jarvis
has brought a more relaxed form of quiet intensity to the team.
``One thing I have been preaching to this team all year,'' he says,
``is that no matter how much you want to win a particular game, and
how focused you are on the task, don't forget to have fun. All too
often you can get caught up in the destination, rather than the
journey. The journey, for us, has been a hell of a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis and Williams have a long history. ``I used to bring my
Rindge &AMP; Latin teams to BC to see Gary's teams practice,'' Jarvis
recalls. ``I have always admired the great intensity level of his
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a lot of direct contact on the floor in Boston,
where the Jarvis tenure at BU and the Williams tenure at BC
overlapped for just one year, and where BC just wasn't going to
play BU, period. But Jarvis was able to claim a Maryland scalp for
his Terriers in a 1990 game at the Olde Gahden (65-61). Maryland
wasn't in the habit of playing George Washington when Jarvis
arrived at the Foggy Bottom campus, either, but again Jarvis
finally got a measure of satisfaction with a 70-66 December
tournament win in the MCI Center last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say about playing Gary's teams is that you'd better
be ready to `bring' it, because they are going to `bring' it,''
Jarvis says.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's wasn't supposed to be anywhere near this good,
either, but because the Red Storm play in New York, and because the
newspaper climate there has a tendency to exaggerate many a
situation, they are playing under a lot of pressure. If it's too
much, Jarvis isn't saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the only team left in the tournament who has given Duke
a game,'' he points out, alluding to a 92-88 OT loss Jan. 24 in
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave Auburn's Ellis, the only one of these
four coaches who has never been stuck in traffic on the Southeast
Expressway or eaten a Hoodsie? That leaves him with the No. 1 seed.
And while Auburn may be a football school, folks down there might
not take too kindly to a No. 1 seed in possession of what many
coaches feel is the best collection of athletes in America that
does not do what a No. 1 seed should do.
</P>
<P>
   But why should we care about Cliff Ellis? The guy has never even
owned a snow shovel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
