u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-GONZAGA-BOS &LR;      03-18 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-GONZAGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL GONCAGA ANYTHING BUT AN UNDERDOG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ First of all it's pronounced Gone-zag-uh, not
Gone-zaw-guh. Not that anyone at the 4,800-student Jesuit school in
Spokane, Wash., really minds a mispronunciation these days.
</P>
<P>
   You can call them anything you want, as long as you mention that
they are one of 16 teams still alive in the NCAA Tournament. As
long as you point out that no Gonzaga team has won more than the 27
games that coach Dan Monson's Zags have won this season, including
two last weekend in Seattle, which is why they faced Florida in the
first game of the NCAA West Regional at the America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't want you to call call Gonzaga (27-6) anymore is
Cinderella or any of those other terms that are pinned on teams who
are not supposed to be playing past the Ides of March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to accept any term that people give us,'' Monson
said Wednesday as his 10th-seeded team went through its final
preparations for No. 6 seed Florida. ``But I think at this point,
the players take a little exception to the Cinderella label because
it has a connotation that we're lucky to be here and our players
don't feel that way because they believe they can play with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubts about the team coming out of the
low-key West Coast Conference, they should have been answered with
Gonzaga's solid 82-74 win over No. 2 seed Stanford last Saturday in
a West Regional second-round game.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags have one ingredient that is a necessity for success in
tournament play _ confident, veteran guards. With senior Quentin
Hall and junior Matt Santangelo, Monson knows his team will not
panic in times of stress.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen in the West Coast Conference tournament when a
loss could very well have ended the season. It didn't happen last
weekend in wins over Minnesota and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it happens against the pressure defense of a young, but
talented and deep Florida team remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga has enjoyed the ride into the national spotlight. ``It's
great to be seen,'' said Monson. ``It's been an overwhelming week
for myself and our kids, one that we'll cherish forever. It's one
that we're trying to enjoy, but at the same time stay focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is easier said than done. Gonzaga is not the center of any
college basketball universe. The school named after St. Aloysius
Gonzaga, a 16th-century Jesuit priest, was founded in 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Other than being the alma mater of John Stockton, the athletic
notoriety of the school is limited. It's only NCAA profile was
sharing the 1950 boxing championship with Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   From the common mispronunciation of the school's name to its
location in Eastern Washington, far from media centers, Gonzaga has
accepted it's out of the limelight status.
</P>
<P>
   After spending nine seasons as an assistant, Monson has been
head coach two seasons and has two NCAA berths and now a Sweet 16
berth on his coaching resume. A Spokane native, Monson appreciates
how far Gonzaga has come more than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost equal to what Washington State did a couple of
years ago,'' said Monson, referring to the school's first Rose Bowl
appearance since 1931. ``We had almost a sense of state pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson, like his players, has tried to maintain a sense of
composure, despite celebrations back home and expectations that
have thus far not proven to be unreasonable. ``It's like you're in
the middle of a hurricane and everything is swirling around you and
you're just watching it,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the whirlwind has been the play of guards Hall (5-8) and
Santangelo (6-1), who have provided stability all season.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who arrived at Gonzaga via the Bahamas, thinks his team
has gotten beyond the underdog stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're a Cinderella team,'' he said. ``And we're
not cocky about saying that, just confident. We think that we can
come in here . . . and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they can. If they do, they will undoubtedly have to
carry Cinderella's shoes for a couple of more days, especially if
No. 1 UConn is waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that for Cinderella it always gets to be midnight,''
said Monson. ``We're not looking for midnight. We're looking to
stay dancing all night long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
