<HEADLINE>
DAVIS GOING OUT IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Somehow it is fitting that what could be the last game
of Tom Davis's coaching career comes against a New England team.
</P>
<P>
   It was in New England, at Boston College (from 1977-82), where
Davis established himself as a major Division 1 college coach.
</P>
<P>
   So if this is it for Davis, who was told earlier this season
that the University of Iowa would not renew his contract, having it
end against old Big East rival UConn somehow would seem right.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there are any guarantees that it will end for Davis and
the Hawkeyes, who are riding an emotional last hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   After all, few people expected the fifth-seeded Hawkeyes (20-9)
to get past fourth seed Arkansas last week in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But they are here, playing in the NCAA West Regional semifinal
against No. 1 seeded UConn as an underdog and a sentimental one at
that.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes have been in that role since Iowa athletic director
Bob Bowsby decided that the 60-year-old Davis, after 13 seasons at
Iowa, no longer fit in the school's long-range basketball plans.
</P>
<P>
   During the up-and-down regular season, as Iowa absorbed injuries
and losses, it did not seem a big deal. Everyone understood Davis
was a lame duck and whether or not you agreed with the decision, it
was a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   It still is, to the point where Southwest Missouri coach (and
former Indiana player) Steve Alford has all but been anointed the
next Iowa coach.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's success over the weekend in the NCAA Tournament has
caused a mixture of emotions in Iowa City, primarily happiness for
Davis, but also uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   What if Iowa keeps winning, and makes it to the Final Four?
</P>
<P>
   Would the school offer a contract extension with the possibility
that Davis would say no, which would only increase the
embarrassment? Or would it fire a coach who has taken the school to
its first Final Four in 29 years?
</P>
<P>
   Davis says he's not worried about it. Not yet at least. ``I have
no plans other than to reflect,'' he said Wednesday. ``When the
season is over, most of us are wiped out. You're exhausted mentally
and physically. At the end, I will try to reflect and recover and
then see what I want to do and where I want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis says he is enjoying this run as much as he has enjoyed
anything he has done in coaching. ``I tend to live life for the
moment,'' he said. ``I appreciate the experience, but I don't know
if I've approached this season any different than any other time in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa players say they have done their best to separate
Davis's situation from the day-to-day business of the season. It
has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not been really spoken about by the players or coaches,''
said Kent McCausland, Iowa's senior guard. ``It's just been a
subconscious reason to get ready to practice, to get ready to
fight, to play hard, and to leave everything on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after the public practices, UConn coach Jim Calhoun
was in a room talking to members of the CBS staff while Davis
waited outside. When Calhoun came out, Davis said kiddingly, ``You
kept me waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, who has admired the high road Davis has taken publicly
and has called him a role model for all coaches, kidded right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting a lot of years to have you wait,'' Calhoun
said with laugh that turned into a hug.
</P>
</TEXT>
