u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-ROSEMARY-BOS &LR;      03-18 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-ROSEMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING A $320-A-POUND PINCH OF ROSEMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing works as well as freshly picked herbs to gussy up a
modest meal. They grow well in pots and for the most part can be
grown indoors or out. They even stand some neglect.
</P>
<P>
   When space on the windowsill or countertop becomes too crowded,
the leaves can be easily dried in the refrigerator, if one is
patient. I always grow some herbs and am just finishing last fall's
parsley harvest.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of my previous herb growing prepared me for the
$320-a-pound rosemary. It all began in early winter when my local
florist had the most beautiful rosemary topiary just dripping with
irresistible blue flowers.
</P>
<P>
   It was perfect for the winter blahs and would be a wonderfully
fresh adornment on hot lamb dishes. But that cheerful scenario
didn't quite work out.
</P>
<P>
   First the flower buds stopped opening. Not enough light, I
thought, so two fluorescent lights were installed and the pot hung
to receive the maximum exposure. Neither change helped.
</P>
<P>
   Next the leaves began to dry up and fall off, as had the buds,
so I tried the latest soil-care amendments. It got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, at a professional show, The Herb Lady appeared, selling
beautiful rosemary grown in her greenhouse. They need full sun, a
light, sandy soil and alkaline, and they shouldn't be too wet. I
was overwatering, said she, and should let the soil dry out between
waterings. So, I tried that, but it didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the commercial potting mix of acid peat and wood
chips? I repotted it in lovingly prepared perfect loam and waited
for new shoots. But it was deader than a doornail.
</P>
<P>
   Being a stingy Yankee, I carefully harvested all the dried up
leaves which just filled a one-ounce spice bottle. The plant cost
$20, so a quick calculation revealed that my dried rosemary cost
$320 a pound, not counting the lights.
</P>
<P>
   An ounce of supermarket rosemary in an identical bottle sells
for about $4 (or $64 a pound), which explains why the ship captains
of yore went to the Spice Islands to make their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   What's my $320 lesson? It is: Coddled plants, forced with
fertilizer and bright lights in a commercial greenhouse, suffer
serious shock when moved into a cool, dim house. Used to
scientific, perfect care, a little over or underwatering or other
minor abuse can be fatal. This is more true in potting mix than in
forgiving garden soil.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually many such plants adapt to their new environment and
sprout new leaves, but flowering is harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   If a plant looks spectacularly better than anything you've ever
been able to grow, it probably won't last. Just think of it as a
temporary visitor, and when it peters out, harvest whatever is
edible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Forcing branches
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make spring come earlier to your house, bring in some
branches for forcing into flower and leaf. Cut long branches with
fat buds. (The flower buds are bigger than the leaf buds.)
</P>
<P>
   Plunge them immediately into a pail or vase of very deep warm
water. After a few days arrange them, cutting the stems under
water. Then wait until they think it's spring and their time to
open. Warmth hastens their perception, sun makes them fade faster.
</P>
<P>
   The classic harbinger of spring is pussy willow, a small tree
that grows in any wet area. The arcane relationships among living
things are fascinating. When a freshly cut willow branch is put in
water, it usually roots, and what's more, if other plants are put
in with it, they, too, often produce roots. Willow produces a
rooting hormone in its sap in springtime and is also a source of
the active ingredient in aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   The plants that burst into flower fastest indoors are those with
the shortest time until their regular outdoor blooming date. For
March cutting, that means those that flower in April. Forsythia and
pussy willow should pop in about two weeks indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Cherries, quince, and peach will take a little longer. Forced
dogwood and crab apples may take a month. Because crabs leaf out
before flowering, they are not as effective as dogwood or cherry,
which flower on bare branches. Late blooming kousa dogwood and
lilacs don't force well.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I cut branches just for their small new leaves. Red
maple is very effective with its tiny red flowers followed by
red-bronze leaves, while the golden branches of weeping willow put
out little chartreuse ones. Branches with baby leaves are great for
flower arrangements, especially with tulips, and best of all, they
can be gathered free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
