<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-18 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOUR BABY WANTS TO BABY-SIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the typical 10- to 14-year-old who feels like both his world
and his body are chaotic and out of control, baby-sitting may be
the magic elixir.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a powerful self-esteem builder,'' says educational
psychologist Mary Ann Rafoth of Indiana University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   After a successful baby-sitting experience, a preteen can feel
better about herself than she did before she walked in the door; a
3-year-old who is thrilled to see her can counteract days, maybe
weeks, of peers who are friends today, enemies tomorrow. Indeed,
sometimes the good feelings can be so powerful that they spill over
into other areas of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen kids who were underperforming academically not be so
down on themselves and perform better,'' says Rafoth.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you know if your middle-school-age child is ready to
baby-sit? How do you maximize potential benefits and minimize
possible dangers? Unfortunately, the most typical yardstick _ a
child's relationship with siblings _ can be misleading, and a
reliable predictor of success _ the match between a child and the
family she is sitting for _ is often ignored.
</P>
<P>
   It took two years of coaxing as well as a certificate from a Red
Cross course before Marina Varshavsky of Lexington, Mass. finally
spoke the words her 13-year-old daughter, Julie Minevich, was dying
to hear: ``OK, I think you're ready to baby-sit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to death about it,'' says Varshavsky. ``It was a
letting go. She's still my baby, and my baby wants to take care of
someone else's children? What if a child fell and was hurt? What
about Julie's safety? You hear stories, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Varshavsky's fears were soothed by the course Julie took, as
well as by her loving care for her sister, Lana, almost 3.
</P>
<P>
   That there is a developmental need to nurture is partly what
draws a preteen to baby-sitting. But parents in the United States
underrate the importance of providing nurturing opportunities,
whether with siblings, pets, or neighbors, says pediatrician Barry
Zuckerman, chair of pediatrics at Boston University School of
Medicine. ``Parents don't want to burden a child or take time away
from an activity. For a boy, they don't even think of it,'' he
says, even though there is no gender difference on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, if a 12-year-old has a stormy relationship with a
sibling, parents assume that doesn't bode well for sitting. A
rancorous sibling relationship, however, is not the best guide to
whether a preteen will make a good baby-sitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Middle school is a time when sibling rivalry heightens because
the 10- to 14-year-old is very touchy about possessions and
privacy,'' says Margaret Sagarese, coauthor of ``The Roller Coaster
Years: Raising Your Children Through the Maddening Yet Magical
Middle School Years'' (Broadway).
</P>
<P>
   This touchiness doesn't extend to children outside the family,
however. ``A 13-year-old might go ballistic if a sibling empties
out her wallet,'' she says, ``but she'll think it's cute if a child
in her care does the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another developmental change that can affect readiness
to baby-sit. Sometime between 10 and 12, a new level of cognition
enables a child to see the world differently, as more
adventure-filled but also more dangerous. This can prompt a new set
of worries, particularly around safety and strangers.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a problem for most children, but, Sagarese says,
``You know it's no longer in the normal range if you go to the mall
and he tells you, `Don't park there, it's too dark,' or if he goes
around pulling down all the shades in the house at dark.'' The
child in this overly fearful range probably will not be comfortable
baby-sitting in a strange house, she says.
</P>
<P>
   A general lack of maturity, of course, is another sign a child
is not ready. Parents, however, may not be the best judge of this.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Rapoza, a registered nurse, has been teaching Basic
Baby-sitting at Deaconess-Nashoba Community Hospital in Ayer for 15
years. Every once in a while, she'll spot a child who isn't ready,
usually because he is uncomfortable learning diaper changing or
CPR. When she tells parents, they will often have had a sense he
wasn't ready but were reluctant to act on it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it important for parents to tell a child to wait
when that's appropriate _ a good experience can boost self-esteem,
but a bad one can deflate it _ it's also critical for a child to
know how to judge if a family is a good match for her and to be
able to negotiate parameters: what she's capable of doing, how much
she's paid, how many and what ages of children she can care for.
</P>
<P>
   This is an important focus of Rapoza's class. ``They need to
feel empowered to say they can't come back if parents expect too
much or if a child is too hard to handle,'' she says. A baby-sitter
may love the idea of an infant, for instance, but be unnerved at
how much he cries.
</P>
<P>
   She poses all sorts of ``what-would-you-do-if?'' scenarios: What
if a child doesn't want to do what you want him to do? (Find a way
to compromise.) What if neighborhood kids come over to play, too?
(Send them home nicely; otherwise, they're your responsibility.)
What if a parent has been drinking and you're not comfortable
having her drive you home? (Stand your ground and call your parent,
even if they get angry.)
</P>
<P>
   While parents might think such scenarios would worry or frighten
a child, Sagarese says the opposite is true: hashing out problem
situations in class enhances their real-life decision-making
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful muscle for them to have to flex, to have to
decide if they can read another book to a 4-year-old or insist it's
time to turn out the light. Talking about it in advance helps them
to trust their own judgment,'' she says. As for the worst-case
scenarios, ``It's not as if they don't think these thoughts
themselves,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as much as Rapoza throws out tricky what-if's, children
throw tougher ones at her. A recent one that stunned her came from
a 13-year-old boy. ``What if a child confides he is being abused by
a parent?'' he asked, and then acknowledged that a boy in his care
had told him just that. He told the class that he told his mom, and
she helped the child and his mother get help.
</P>
<P>
   Asking your parents for advice is almost always the right thing
to do, Rapoza tells children. She tells parents that the commitment
we must make to our child who baby-sits is no small thing. ``You
need to be reachable whenever your child sits,'' she says. ``Even
if nothing goes wrong, knowing he can call you is a security
blanket.'' If he calls, give advice over the phone but don't rush
over to rescue him unless it's an emergency. ``That undermines the
independence and competency he is trying to gain,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Since she's been sitting, Julie sees a difference in her
self-confidence. ``I was always shy talking to grown-ups,'' she
says. ``When I'm doing a job, I feel respected. I can talk to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of her success, Julie mentions the $500 she's earned
in nine months. She's saved most of it, but she can spend some as
she wishes, on nail polish or gifts for friends. This financial
independence is another benefit of baby-sitting. ``Having
experience making decisions about money adds to a preteen's
decision-making capability,'' says Sagarese.
</P>
<P>
   Julie's mother notices other pluses, too, particularly an
increased sense of responsibility. Not only does Julie keep a card
file with each family's vital information, but she also is managing
her time well. ``One of the conditions for baby-sitting was that
homework didn't get neglected,'' says Varshavsky.
</P>
<P>
   That an 11- to 14-year-old takes the responsibility of
baby-sitting so seriously is a hallmark of the age. ``There's a lot
of identity formation and skill mastery going on,'' says Rafoth.
She thinks preteens make excellent sitters. So does Rapoza, who
says, ``It's not just a job to a child this age; there's nothing
ho-hum about it for them. Plus, they want to engage the children.
That's part of the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing this for the money,'' says Julie Minevich. ``I
do it because I really love it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --If you can't meet the parents your child is going to baby-sit
for, at least introduce yourself over the phone to find out what
their expectations are. Then you can help your child determine if
this is a good match.
</P>
<P>
   --Baby-sitting is as important for boys as it is for girls.
</P>
<P>
   --A child who wants to sit but isn't ready can phase into it by:
working as a mother's helper; assisting an older friend while she
sits; sitting first during the day only.
</P>
<P>
   --If you are hiring a preteen, consider a baby-sitting course a
prerequisite. Before you leave him with your children, have him
watch them while you're home, especially if you have a baby.
</P>
<P>
   --Many communities offer baby-sitting courses sponsored by the
American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   --The closer your children are in age, the less likely you can
leave one to baby-sit the other. If they are both willing, leave
each in charge of himself, with specific, age-appropriate
responsibilities spelled out beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended reading: ``Great Books for
African-American Children'' by Pamela Toussaint (Plume Books).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
