<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINT THINNER CLEANS WOOD, AND METAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have an old wood chair in which you can see the grain of
the wood, but it is dirty and tired-looking. How can I clean it?
Also, I have a metal bar stool that is tired-looking, too. How can
I clean that one? It is not rusting.
</P>
<P>
   CAROL DRISCOLL, Randolph, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Paint thinner to the rescue, for both the chair and the
stool. Apply liberally with a cloth, let it sit for a minute or
two, but don't let it evaporate. Then scrub with the same cloth and
rub dry with a new cloth. This will clean the wood but dull the
finish; you can bring back some of the shine by buffing with a dry
cloth. If the finish is still dull, you can sand it lightly and
apply one or two coats of an oil-based, semigloss polyurethane
varnish.
</P>
<P>
   For stubborn dirt on the stool, dip fine steel wool in the paint
thinner and rub lightly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having a new roof put on my house. I also have to have
the chimney repointed. What should be done first?
</P>
<P>
   BERNIE KEENAN, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the repointing should be done first; that way, any
damage to the shingles by the masons repointing the chimney will be
covered by the new roof.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having four dormers on my two-family house covered with
vinyl. Will the workmen wreck the roof when they are working up
there?
</P>
<P>
   HUMPHREY GRADY, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. They won't wreck the roof if they do it right, and the right
way is to put up scaffolding so they can stand on that instead of
the roof. If they have to stand on the roof, then they should put
down a big piece of plywood or other protective cover to stand on.
Twisting and turning shoes can really do a job on asphalt shingles,
so the right way _ scaffolding or plywood sheets _ is important.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My hardwood floor was installed in November 1997 and treated
with water-based polyurethane varnish. Now the boards are opening
up, enough to be unsightly, and the varnish is cracking in the
gaps. Did I do something wrong? Can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL SOULE, Newburyport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You did nothing wrong, neither did the installers, and the
boards were installed at the right time of year: November, when
they were at their driest and smallest. All wood floors should be
installed this way. Then when they gain moisture and expand, they
will be even tighter; and when they dry out and contract, they
won't contract so much as to open up. Thousands of floors have been
installed this way without problems.
</P>
<P>
   All I can think of is that your hardwood had excessive moisture
when it was installed (20 percent water content is considered
ideal), so that when they dried out, they contracted more than
normal, creating the gaps. Treating with water-based varnish has
nothing to do with it, although I feel oil-based varnish is better
to use on floors.
</P>
<P>
   The cure? You can't fill the gaps with any hardening material
because it will break up with future expansion and contraction.
Filling the gaps with wood is not practical because the gaps are
very shallow, and the results would be unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Stop me if you've heard this one, but the only real, permanent
cure is to take up the boards now and relay them tight. It can be
done, but it is a lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   When you revarnish, use water-based again, because oil-based is
incompatible with the water-based varnish on the wood now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My concrete foundation has a crack from one of the windows
down to the footing. I've had three offers to fix it; one man said
he would enlarge the crack and inject epoxy, but he could do it
``tomorrow.'' Another would inject a hydrophobic material; the
third would inject a hydrophilic material. What is the best?
</P>
<P>
   JACKIE COONS, North Hampton, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. I can't say what is best, but all three suggest injecting a
material, which is good, if they work, because they do not require
digging down on the outside and patching the crack. All three
techniques should also enlarge the crack, because it is difficult
to inject anything into a hairline or very small crack. Hydrophobic
means incapable of uniting with or absorbing water; it will reject
water. Hydrophilic means capable of uniting with or absorbing
water; it will stop the leak by accommodating the water.
</P>
<P>
   So, take your chances with any of the three, although I would be
leery of anyone who says he can do it ``tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The grout between the new ceramic tiles on my kitchen floor
is bleeding onto the tiles. The tile people suggested removing it
with SOS pads and a toothbrush. Will that work?
</P>
<P>
   KATHY MAHONEY, Roslindale, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I doubt it. If the grout bleed is a haze, then rubbing it
with a dry cloth will take it off. So will SOS pads. But if there
are bits of grout on the tile that are not coming off, then here's
the ony cure: Buy muriatic acid in a hardware store, mix it half
and half with water, and apply to the grout. The acid will attack
the lime in the grout (you will see the grout fizz up like an
Alka-Seltzer pill in water), and you can rub the rest off. A
warning about muriatic acid, or any acid, for that matter: Use
extreme caution, and wear skin and eye protection. When mixing acid
with water, always pour the acid into the water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
