<SLUG> BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ISLE MERCHANTS BLAME COSTS, COMPETITION FOR STUDENT DECLINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: S.C.) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas _ The sun-bronzed hordes of college
students thronging to this narrow island couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   Spring break, South Padre-style, is a nonstop beach party fueled
by mass quantities of cold beer and icy margaritas _ a bacchanalian
romp from bikini pageants, wet T-shirt contests and topless
bungi-cord jumping to jet ski and parasail rides, concerts and
tug-of-war competitions. And collegians not old enough to drink
legally in Texas can party 25 minutes away in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The island's Visitor and Convention Bureau expects at least
125,000 students to dump an estimated $68.8 million into local cash
registers this spring break season.
</P>
<P>
   So why are so many island merchants glum?
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, up to this point, spring break has been dying,''
laments Mike Lemmons, manager of Amberjacks Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons, a South Padre resident since 1976, blames the decline
on the island's relatively high cost for hotels and condos, along
with increasing competition from other resorts for the millions of
dollars that college kids spread around. And MTV is not featuring
South Padre as it did during last year's spring break programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rates are really high, and plus there's Cancun (Mexico),
there's Panama City (Fla.),'' Lemmons said. ``There's a lot more
places to go now than what there was say 10 years ago when it was
basically us, Daytona Beach and Fort Lauderdale.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the visitors bureau say they expect the same
number of students as in 1998. To lure them, the bureau spent
$150,000 to insert color brochures in newspapers in a dozen large
Midwestern universities, and radio station promotions offered
all-expenses-paid trips for two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're hot this year, because of word of mouth,'' said
Cindy Dubois, the bureau spokeswoman. ``Panama Beach is probably
going to be real big this year, and so is Cancun. And MTV was in
Jamaica last year, and it might be hot this year.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV producers originally said they would return to South Padre
this year after island officials agreed to pony up $85,000 to cover
production costs, Dubois explained. But the producers changed their
minds, opting instead to cover spring break from cruise ships
calling on Cancun and Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Dubois conceded that the December 1994 peso devaluation, and
resulting bargain prices at Mexican coastal resorts, knocked the
island's spring break crowd down to what is considered a historic
low of 110,000 visitors in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has sort of been crawling back ever since,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials in Florida's top resort said foreign
competition has caused them not to expect the 500,000 or 600,000
students who visited last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring break is a fickle market. It tends to move around,''
said Dan Stark, president of the Panama City Convention and
Visitors Bureau. ``We're probably down 15 or 20 percent, and some
of that has to do with MTV not coming here ... and not being quite
as affordable as Cancun or Jamaica.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the official attendance figures touted in Texas,
which tourism officials say are calculated from city hotel tax
receipts, several Padre Island merchants agreed with Lemmons that
the much-ballyhooed financial spring break bonanza falls short of
its billing.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I've seen less and less numbers (of students) since 1991, and
that is counter to some of the claims I've heard, but the sales
don't warrant those claims,'' said Verne Lewis, a former Houstonian
who owns a clothing and jewelry store called Isla.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis visited Panama City last January to satisfy his curiosity
about the resort South Padre considers its major U.S. rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw was a budget-oriented spring break destination, and
that's what the kids want,'' said Lewis, adding hotel prices on
South Padre during the peak week can reach $250 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see the quality I thought Florida would offer, in
terms of environment and amenities. I saw a lot of mom-and-pop
motels that kids could rent for $60 a night,'' Lewis said. ``I
guess prices are the main reason kids have stopped coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, most South Padre Island hotels and condos were
booked. But those who were able to secure lodging did so at a
fairly competitive price. At the Radisson Hotel on the beach, for
example, four students could book a room for $170 a night total.
Condos operated by the same hotel ran about $360 a night for six
people.
</P>
<P>
   But students who went to Florida last year agreed it was less
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we stayed for five days in Panama Beach and it was
cheaper,'' said Amy Suppinger, a 22-year-old senior at Clemson
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy. We stayed in a place that was full of kids and
it was nonstop party,'' she recalled. ``And there were a lot more
spring break deals. You could get wrist bands where you'd get a
free drink or get in without paying the cover.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, Suppinger and 10 other classmates drove 22
hours from South Carolina to South Padre, wanting a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida _ been there, done that,'' said Peter Olson Jr., 23,
as he added to the waist-high stack of empty beer cans along the
kitchen wall of a beach condo he's sharing with five other
students. ``It's something with a different twist,'' he said of
South Padre. ``Many more new bars and hot women!''
</P>
<P>
   Olson and the other Clemson students gave South Padre high marks
for the diversity of events _ both during the day on the beach and
at night in the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ayer, a 22-year-old senior, said he went to Key West,
Fla., last spring break and ``the only thing you could do was jump
from bar to bar and drink alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many more activities here, like the bungi jumping
and the games on the beach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while spring break overall might not bring the windfall
merchants would like, this week things are definitely hopping on
the island.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``Texas Week,'' when most major universities in the state
take their midterm break. And this year Texas Week coincides with
recess at other large universities in Michigan, Kansas and Iowa.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; By mid-week, merchants were busy and guardedly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us, as the years have gone by, spring break becomes less
and less important,'' said Susan Bagley, who owns On The Beach surf
shop and the upscale Calypso gift shop with husband, Gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, this year spring break seems better than last year
and I don't know why that is. They (students) seem to have a little
bit more money, they're staying on the island more, and there's
more of them.''  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
