<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMY AWARDS: GUESSING THE INEVITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do not take this article seriously. And while you're at it,
don't take the Oscars seriously, either.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopi Goldberg is hosting this year's event; expect lots of
jokes about war movies and period movies and Shakespeare in tights.
Expect strange clothing and stranger hairdos. Expect pomp.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect too much from the awards themselves. The Oscars
never make much sense, particularly to folks who try to predict
them. Which, of course, we're about to do: Predict the Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast which films and filmmakers will walk away with the big
gold dude. Prognosticate. Foretell. Prophesy. Guess.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, with a perfunctory rub of the crystal ball, we here
present a list of Wild Guesses for six major Academy Award
categories: best picture, actress, supporting actress, actor,
supporting actor and director. Each Wild Guess is followed by a
Lovable Underdog, which is then followed by an official Pithy
Commentary replete with obtuse journalistic thinking.
</P>
<P>
   So read on. Have fun. And lighten up, all right? It's only the
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   The Nominees: ``Elizabeth,'' ``Life is Beautiful,'' ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``The Thin Red Line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Guess:``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lovable Underdog: ``Life is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pithy Commentary: In the race between ``Saving Private
Ryan'' and ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``Ryan'' will probably win by a
nose despite the fact that ``Shakespeare'' earned more nominations
overall (13, compared with ``Ryan's'' 11). One reason: ``Ryan'' had
bigger box office ($208 million, compared with ``Shakespeare's''
$66 million).
</P>
<P>
   Another: ``Shakespeare in Love,'' for all its hyper-literate
chest-heaving, is a comedy. And Oscar snubs comedies.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   The Nominees: Cate Blanchett, ``Elizabeth''; Fernanda
Montenegro, ``Central Station''; Gwyneth Paltrow, ``Shakespeare in
Love''; Meryl Streep, ``One True Thing''; Emily Watson, ``Hilary
and Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Guess: Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   The Lovable Underdog: Fernanda Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The Pithy Commentary: How many Oscars has Meryl Streep already
won? Two. How many will she have after Sunday? Three. Why? Because
she gets cancer and dies in ``One True Thing'' (and Oscar loves
illness). Because this is her 11th nomination. Because she last won
in 1982, seven nominations ago. And because she deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Academy may decide that Paltrow's star turn in
``Shakespeare'' is just too yummy to ignore (and Oscar loves
yummy).
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   The Nominees: Kathy Bates, ``Primary Colors''; Brenda Blethyn,
``Little Voice''; Judi Dench, ``Shakespeare in Love''; Rachel
Griffiths, ``Hilary and Jackie''; Lynn Redgrave, ``Gods and
Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Guess: Rachel Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   The Lovable Underdog: Lynn Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   The Pithy Commentary: Do you remember The Rule in this category?
No? Well, we'll repeat it for you: For best supporting actress, the
Academy generally chooses whichever nominee its male constituents
would most like to sleep with. Exceptions tend to be comic foils or
esteemed character actors (Linda Hunt, Dianne Wiest) which,
considering the esteemed character work of Bates, Blethyn, Dench
and Redgrave, would seem to blow the category wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Dench was nominated and lost in '98 (Blethyn in '97), so who
knows?
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   The Nominees: Roberto Benigni, ``Life is Beautiful''; Tom Hanks,
``Saving Private Ryan''; Ian McKellen, ``Gods and Monsters''; Nick
Nolte, ``Affliction''; Edward Norton, ``American History X.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Guess: Nick Nolte.
</P>
<P>
   The Lovable Underdog: Roberto Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   The Pithy Commentary: Benigni's a comedian (plus he's Italian),
Norton's performance was seen by only 12 or 13 people, and Hanks'
mantelpiece is already crowded with Oscars imagine the headache if
he had to make room for a third. McKellen has a chance (he is a
Sir, after all), but Nolte has the edge: He yells louder. And he
pulls out his tooth with a wrench in ``Affliction.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   The Nominees: James Coburn, ``Affliction''; Robert Duvall, ``A
Civil Action''; Ed Harris, ``The Truman Show''; Geoffrey Rush,
``Shakespeare in Love''; Billy Bob Thornton, ``A Simple Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Guess: James Coburn.
</P>
<P>
   The Adorable Underdog: Geoffrey Rush.
</P>
<P>
   The Pithy Commentary: Ed Harris' role is too small. Robert
Duvall already owns an Oscar; so does Geoffrey Rush. Billy Bob
Thornton rubs people the wrong way (besides, he won a screenplay
Oscar for ``Sling Blade''). That leaves James Coburn, who's never
been nominated (much less won) and is now riding a cool Hollywood
comeback. If, on the other hand, Academy members are still feeling
guilty about Duvall's best-actor loss last year, he may find
himself clutching Oscar No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   BEST DIRECTOR
</P>
<P>
   The Nominees: Roberto Benigni, ``Life is Beautiful''; Steven
Spielberg, ``Saving Private Ryan''; John Madden, ``Shakespeare in
Love''; Terrence Malick, ``The Thin Red Line''; Peter Weir, ``The
Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Guess: Terrence Malick.
</P>
<P>
   The Lovable Underdog:
</P>
<P>
   Peter Weir.
</P>
<P>
   The Pithy Commentary: Most of time, who wins the directing Oscar
depends on what wins the best picture Oscar which means either
Spielberg or Madden will walk away with the statue. But every now
and then, the Academy will veer wildly from the norm, instead
honoring some well-admired auteur whose film has zilch chance of
winning best picture. Ergo Malick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
