<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-TRUCK-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        OFFICE OF MOTOR CARRIERS NEEDS BETTER DATA, FASTER ACTION,
DOT INSPECTOR GENERAL SAYS   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 18 -- As the number of deaths from large truck
crashes is growing, the agency that regulates trucking safety
continues to be weighed down by data problems and slow action,
national transportation safety officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Transportation Inspector General Kenneth Mead told
a congressional panel Wednesday that the Office of Motor Carriers
collects insufficient data on crashes. Also, he said the OMC moves
too slowly in implementing safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``OMC still cannot target all carriers with the worst safety
records because its database is incomplete and inaccurate and data
entry is not timely,'' Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   Those were just a few of the findings national transportation
regulators highlighted at a hearing that examined the OMC's role in
truck safety. The federal government oversees more than 490,000
trucking businesses and 6 million drivers. OMC collects crash data
and citations to identify problem carriers with the worst records
and study the causes of crashes.
</P>
<P>
   While the rate of fatalities per 100 miles traveled by large
trucks has stayed steady in the last few years, the number of
actual deaths has increased. Deaths have jumped 20 percent from
4,462 in 1992 to 5,355 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   OMC is unlikely to meet its goal for 1999 of reducing the number
of fatalities to fewer than 5,126. That was the number of deaths
three years ago, said Phyllis Scheinberg, associate director of
Transportation Issues for the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, if current trends continue, Scheinberg predicts there
will be about 5,800 deaths related to large truck accidents in
1999. The federal government defines a large truck as having at
least 6 wheels and weighing more than 10,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   OMC also fell short in its data collection from the states. For
example, the agency did not receive data from states on 38 percent
of truck and bus crashes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some states did not record the information properly or in
a usable format, Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said in his review of OMC, he found the same problem areas
that have challenged transportation safety officials for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Yogi Berra said, it's 'deja vu all over again','' Mead
said. ``Thirty years ago, there were too few trucks being inspected
and too many trucks were found unsafe for operations. These are the
same concerns we have today.''
</P>
<P>
   More inspectors are needed at the U.S.-Mexico border, just one
area that needs more attention, Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   About 44 percent of trucks entering the U.S. from Mexico do not
meet American safety standards, Mead said. He pointed to El Paso,
Texas, where there is only one inspector at a point where 1,300
trucks enter the country daily. An inspector can conduct about 10
or 14 inspections a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``OMC and the border states disagree over who has responsibility
for these inspections,'' Mead said. ``Therefore there has been
little improvement. It is time to resolve this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   To bring down the number of deaths, Mead suggested: improving
driver accountability, requiring more vehicle inspections, and
setting a 60 mile maximum speed limit for trucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
