<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-18 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISDOM FROM THE RICH: NO TAX BREAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The headline on the press release looks like a
joke: ``Wealthy Taxpayers say, `No Thanks!' to GOP Tax Giveaways.''
</P>
<P>
   Could this be real? A national consortium of 400 fat cats,
calling themselves ``Responsible Wealth,'' who publicly condemn the
benefits of several proposed tax break bills that would benefit
them most?
</P>
<P>
   Such protest is expected from low-income, high-outrage
anti-capitalists, but not from women and men who sit very
comfortably in the country's top 5 percent income bracket.
</P>
<P>
   But Responsible Wealth is real. Based in Boston and part of an
advocacy group called United for a Fair Economy, the members of
Responsible Wealth say they are committed to turning back the tide
of greed that Congress has helped to flood the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 135 of them put their money where their condemnation
is and gave away $1.2 million worth of 1997 tax breaks they'd
received. Most of the donated money, they say, went to social
justice organizations and other nonprofit groups dedicated to a
fairer economy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 135 is Michele McGeoy, who made a bundle in 1993 when
she sold her software company in Berkeley, Calif., Tailored
Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Now the director of a nonprofit organization called ASAP, which
donates technology and training to public high school students and
welfare-to-work women, McGeoy said she couldn't stomach the idea of
receiving special tax privileges just because she's already rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be ashamed to pay less taxes on my stock sales than a
nursing home aide or child care worker pays on what she earns for
caring for people all day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other members of Responsible Wealth, giving back some
of her good fortune is not enough for McGeoy; she wants to tackle
some of what she terms ``the root causes'' of our decidedly skewed
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the philanthropy in the world just perpetuates the cycle
until we look at the rules that are set up to favor people with
wealth,'' McGeoy said. ``Now that I'm in this position (wealthy), I
see these rules that are allegedly in our favor but that I don't
think are actually healthy for our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of those rules _ proposed tax-break bills that would make
the McGeoys among us even fatter cats _ are especially offensive to
the group. They know that, despite talk of ``surpluses,'' a tax cut
for the haves almost always results in an economic penalty for the
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   The nastiest proposals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Repeal of the capital gains tax on individuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Repeal of the estate or inheritance tax.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 10 percent tax cut for all taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 percent tax cut proposal is the inspiration of House
Budget Committee Chairman John R. Kasich, R-Ohio. It looks
non-discriminatory and fair, but, as the Responsible Wealth folks
point out, nearly two-thirds of the ``giveback'' would go to the
wealthiest 10 percent of U.S. households who'd average about
$20,700 per break.
</P>
<P>
   For taxpayers who make less than $38,000 per year _ 60 percent
of individual income taxpayers _ the average break would be a
measly $99.
</P>
<P>
   The two pending tax repeals are the creation of Rep. Joe
Knollenberg, R-Mich. Responsible Wealth says both proposals should
be identified for what they are: more privilege for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 percent of U.S. households possess substantial enough
estates even to owe taxes, so Knollenberg's proposal to do away
with estate taxes affects only a rarefied, monied group.
</P>
<P>
   How substantial? Thanks to the big heart of Congress, currently
no estate smaller than $1 million can be taxed. If Congress passes
the repeal, the planet Pluto will be the limit; a person can
inherit billions and pay nary a penny for the windfall.
</P>
<P>
   As for Knollenberg's other proposed tax repeal, capital gains
tax cuts already have made for fatter fat cats. If the tax is
completely wiped out, even more of the nation's tax burden will be
switched from wealthy shoulders _ the richest 10 percent of
Americans possess 87 percent of all individually owned stocks _ to
the bent backs of the workaday wage earner.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the wealthiest 1 percent of households averaged a
$7,680 capital gains tax cut and grabbed two-thirds of all benefits
from the reductions. Meanwhile, the lower 80 percent of U.S.
households realized an average capital gains tax cut of $6.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if most of the people she knows in her income bracket
think she's nuts for her allegiance to Responsible Wealth, Michele
McGeoy laughed and said, ``Yeah, pretty much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not the popular stance to take. It's not what
people want to hear,'' she said. ``But until people like me do
something about it, things are never going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's no joke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
