<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SISTERS-CATHOLICS-HNS     03-18 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTERS-CATHOLICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET THEATER GROUP DRAWS FIRE FROM CATHOLIC ARCHDIOCESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD and RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, celebrating
20 years of campy outrage, street theater, poor taste and good
works, has drawn fire from the San Francisco Catholic Archdiocese
for planning its anniversary party on Easter Sunday and closing
down a city street to hold it.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese wants the city's Board of Supervisors to
reconsider its blessing of the April 4 event, but two key
supervisors have said there's no chance of that.
</P>
<P>
   Archdiocese spokesman Maurice Healy said the closing of a public
street on Easter, Christiandom's holiest day, for a group that
``mocks the Catholic church'' is tantamount to allowing a group of
neo-Nazis to close a street on Passover.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the supervisors to rescind their 8-0 vote on March 1 to
permit the Sisters' street fair, saying it showed ``extraordinary
insensitivity to people of all faiths.''
</P>
<P>
   Healy also said Catholics for Truth and Justice, a grass-roots
organization that ``traditionally has taken a role when the church
has been defamed or attacked,'' may take action as well.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over their 20th birthday celebration came as a
surprise to the Sisters, even though they are no strangers to
protests. The street theater group consists of some 30 gay,
lesbian, transgender and straight members who dress in nuns' habits
and take to the streets for the shock, outrage and amusement of
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really know that the archdiocese had feelings about
this,'' Sister Ann R. Key said. ``I think they're taking it too
seriously. We take our work seriously but we don't take ourselves
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Ann said her group planned no form of protest,
demonstration or condemnation of the Catholic Church during the
event but were focusing instead on a long-standing goal of
providing aid to the poor, homeless, young, and gay and lesbian
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically a bunch of do-gooders,'' she said. ``Speaking
out of hate would not get us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The offices of board President Tom Ammiano and Supervisor Mark
Leno, who sponsored the resolution to close a block of Castro
Street here, have received an avalanche of calls protesting the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners attending Mass on Sunday were given copies of a
commentary by Wade Hughan, vice chairman of Catholics for Truth and
Justice, which said ``only the Catholic Church could be the target
of such officially sanctioned ridicule, deliberately scheduled so
as to add insult to injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughan added, ``Members of the board (of supervisors) would be
falling over each other to be the first to condemn a march by the
Ku Klux Klan on Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday, or a rally by
the American Nazi Party on Yom Kippur. We would not be hearing any
bold defenses of free speech at those hearings. Somehow we are
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Its bid for a permit to close Castro Street was denied last
month by the Department of Parking and Traffic, which raised
traffic and parking concerns, as well as worries of merchants about
business disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   But on March 1, the supervisors voted 8-0 on a resolution by
Ammiano and Leno to permit the closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I completely understand and respect that all people may not
warm up to the Sisters,'' Leno said, adding he did not expect the
board to reconsider. ``But I think part of the uproar is lack of
familiarity with who they are and what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're an all-volunteer organization that raises money and
does good deeds for smaller non-profit organizations. They work on
behalf of improving the health of our community. They do it with
humor and they touch on a very delicate subject (religion). And
that's where some feathers are ruffled. But they mean no disrespect
and they certainly do good work.''
</P>
<P>
   Healy said the Sisters do mean disrespect to the church, noting
they practice something called the ``condom savior mass,'' which
denigrates the sacred Mass. He also said the Sisters mocked the
pope with a theatrical exorcism in Union Square during his 1997
visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano also said the supervisors would not reconsider their
vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
