<HEADLINE>
AUBURN'S BASKETBALL SUCCESS HELPS SALVE FOOTBALL MISFORTUNES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Who would have believed that a basketball
team could mend hearts broken by the passionate fans who still
speak the names Pat Sullivan and Bo Jackson in reverent terms?
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has meant a lot to a lot of people,'' said forward
Bryant Smith of the Auburn Tigers, the NCAA Tournament South
Region's top-seeded team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our season came at a perfect time. It was a down time for our
university and for our fans. Football didn't do well, and Auburn is
looked at as a football school. Now, people are noticing Auburn
once again, for different reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn fans again have reason to cheer after being stunned by
the midseason resignation of football coach Terry Bowden, a 3-8
season and the embarrassing buyout of its scheduled 1999
season-opening football game with Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our season has picked up the spirit all around campus,''
agreed Scott Pohlman, hero of last week's 81-74 victory against
Oklahoma State that thrust the Tigers into the Sweet 16 for the
first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put a value on what this team has done for Auburn
University,'' coach Cliff Ellis said. ``People are proud of this
team, and that helps Auburn in more ways than just selling out
(Beard-Eaves) coliseum and making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allowed the Auburn family to heal. Our season has been good
for Auburn football, good for the chemistry department. Good for
Terry Bowden and good for (new football coach) Tommy Tuberville
because this team has been the center of national attention. It's
pushed all the controversy to page three or four. And it has been a
season of history as far as our program is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (29-3) set a school record for victories, won the
Southeastern Conference championship for the first time in 39
seasons and set home attendance records. Its No. 2 national ranking
(Feb. 22) after starting the season 19-0 was the highest an Auburn
team had been ranked in 40 years. Auburn became only the ninth team
in NCAA Tournament history to be awarded a No. 1 seed after a
season when it was not in the 64-team field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten the attention of all America,'' Ellis said.
``We've been the Cinderella story from Day One. Our media has
crowned this the best (basketball) team in the history of Alabama.
What we've accomplished goes a long way toward establishing our
basketball program.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who already has been selected national coach of the year
by one publication, first burst on the tournament scene with his
South Alabama teams in 1979-80. He then breathed life into the
Clemson program, where his sixth team won the first-ever ACC
championship in 1990 and reached the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis had taken three of his four previous Auburn teams to the
postseason National Invitation Tournament. This is a team of stars
that plays together. Forward Chris Porter and point guard Doc
Robinson made the all-SEC first team. Bryant, the only senior, made
the second team and 7-foot center Mamadou N'diaye the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers have one more plateau to reach. Auburn's most
successful tournament team was led to the 1986 Elite Eight by Chuck
Person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get into that,'' Ellis said. ``We've faced questions
like that all year. This team has defied all odds. It's won a
Southeastern Conference championship, finished fourth in the
country, it's in the Sweet 16 after not being ranked (in
preseason). It's a great basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what will happen against Ohio State. But I
think it will be a beautiful game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's already been a beautiful season. Even at Auburn. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
