<SLUG> BC-UNWANTED-BEAVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA BEAVERS FIND REFUGE, FOR NOW, IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOERNE, Texas _ Four beavers exiled from California are being
freed at an undisclosed location in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys just need somewhere that is compatible in the wild
and welcoming,'' said Lynn Cuny of Wildlife Rescue and
Rehabilitation near Boerne, where the refugees played in an
enclosure earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some landowners here have agreed to take the beavers, joining
hundreds of thousands of their wood-chewing, creek-damming Texas
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, those cousins are the target of an aggressive state
eradication program.
</P>
<P>
   The critters were among 16 beavers trapped at a reserve in
Riverside County, Calif., where their appetite for native trees put
them on the least-wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   The beavers were evicted this week from the 13,000-acre reserve
to protect the habitat of an endangered bird, the Bell's vireo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the beaver, which are not a species of
concern, were impacting the habitat of species that we do have some
concern for,'' said Mike McBride of the California Fish and Game
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Picketers protested last month after officials said the beavers
would be killed if new homes couldn't be found.
</P>
<P>
   Cuny, who has a permit to import mammals and release them on
private land in Texas, stepped in to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled. These are wild beavers, and they have the
chance to be wild again,'' said Jane Garrison of the Los Angeles
chapter of People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, which paid
$1,000 to fly the beavers to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the welcoming committee didn't include animal control
specialists and those all too familiar with the pesky critters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beavers cause millions of dollars of damage each year,
predominantly in East Texas,'' said Gary Nunley, director of the
Texas Wildlife Damage Management Service. ``They burrow into banks,
weakening dams and highway foundations and dikes and even railroad
track beds. Their dams flood county roads, plug culverts, and a lot
of timber dies in standing water.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, state legislators approved hiring five ``beaver
specialists'' to corral the flat-tailed troublemakers, and 4,118
beavers were killed last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest number we've had in a long time,'' Nunley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Word that West Coast beavers were coming to Texas didn't sit
well with Houston County agricultural extension agent Ed King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say they need to keep their beavers,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the landowners who now welcome the beavers
``will soon love to hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuny, president of the National Association of Sanctuaries,
takes a dim view of government efforts to ``manage'' wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are the problem, not the beavers,'' she said. ``God
forbid that wild animals be where they were naturally intended to
be. What could be worse?''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the California beavers died during trapping, seven went
to zoos, and the remaining three will live out the Hollywood dream
as Worldwide Movie Animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We named them Harry, Muffy and Fuzzy,'' said David McMillan,
founder of the company that provides filmmakers with animal
``actors.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan has resisted pleas from PETA officials to let those
beavers also go to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's funny? In their minds it's a better thing for
them to go out in the wild and get killed by ranchers or coyotes
than to have a good long life working for a motion picture
company,'' he said. ``That's the picture I get of the PETA
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Parks and Wildlife officials _ who granted
Cuny her importation permit _ are caught in the middle of the
battle over beavers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the population wants to save everything, and the other
half wants to kill everything, so what are you going to do?'' said
Rosie Roegner, a permit coordinator for the agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
