A5255 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TRUECRIME-TEX     03-18 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRUECRIME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A `CRIME,' ALL RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new Clint Eastwood thriller ``True Crime'' sizes the
audience up like a pickpocket. Simultaneously crass and slickly
assembled, it may also be the crummiest-looking major film in some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood plays Steve Everett, a talented and self-destructive,
womanizing reporter who has fallen so precipitously that he's
clinging to a job at the Oakland (Calif.) Tribune with what's left
of his fingernails. (If you know the racial makeup of Oakland,
you'll realize that there are probably more white people in this
movie than there are in the entire city.)
</P>
<P>
   After a prime story falls into his lap _ a human-interest piece
on Death Row inmate Frank Beachum (Isaiah Washington), who
maintains that he is innocent and refuses to apologize _ Everett is
spurred into action. He opens his eyes, and reporter's nose, long
enough to realize that Beachum has to be telling the truth, and
sets about trying to prove it in the remaining hours before the
execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' has its strong points. Now that Eastwood's voice
is shot, he has learned how to use tricky line readings that he
never could've as a younger man. (All those years of devoting
himself to jazz have helped _ he's become the Red Rodney of
actors.)
</P>
<P>
   The cast, apparently left to its own devices, includes: a
bizarrely under-directed Denis Leary, who looks to be begging for
help; James Woods, who plays the grim comedy in all of his scenes;
and an extraordinarily modulated piece of acting from Diane Venora
as Everett's ex-wife, who bleeds anger and betrayal at the hands of
a man she still wants to love.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who has shown growth as an actor in his past few
roles, is used as a hood ornament for quiet dignity here. Lisa Gay
Hamilton (who does fine, sensible work every week on ``The
Practice'') brings much honor to a part that essentially asks her
to weep at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   And opportunistic is what ``True Crime'' is, mostly. There's
some smart writing that employs cold-hearted humor and attention to
detail of the kind that ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' used when
it was at its best a few years ago. The prison staff preparing for
the execution is an all-business scene and has a grim pride. But
there are moments _ shamelessly wringing tears out of Beachum's
young daughter _ that are cringe-inducing.
</P>
<P>
   The climax, when Everett is trying to drive to an appointment
that could save Beachum's life _ on a road called Dead Man's Curve,
where this broken-down drunk reporter suddenly has the motoring
skills of an Indy driver _ is a serious version of the fake climax
of Robert Altman's ``The Player,'' when Bruce Willis storms the
death chamber to save Julia Roberts. (Each cut to the execution is
ominous, while the chase is played for laughs. The script keeps a
manipulative eye trained on you at all times.)
</P>
<P>
   There probably isn't another movie star as shrewd as Clint
Eastwood in terms of using his image. Sure, he pulls embarrassing
gambits like almost-nude scenes of himself, and this movie is
directed like he had to rush to get it to Fotomat before it closed.
But he plays on our perception of him as the iconic hero, making
himself a beaten-down object of sympathy. Of course, at the end, as
in ``Unforgiven,'' he pulls it together in a way that's totally
uncharacteristic and makes no dramatic sense.
</P>
<P>
   It's also weird to see a man with no interest in listening to
another human being play a reporter, someone who has to get
information out of people. But he basically plays him like a
hard-nosed cop, anyway. He's smart _ ``True Crime'' gets the job
done on its own flat-footed terms; it's the ``Driving Miss Daisy''
of crime stories.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``True Crime''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Clint Eastwood
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Clint Eastwood, Isaiah Washington
</P>
<P>
   Length: 127 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, a scene of a Death Row execution, adult
language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
