<HEADER>
A5257 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TANGO-TEX     03-18 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TANGO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCES WITH POINTLESSNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oscar-nominated Argentine film ``Tango'' might seem too
elegant to evoke a Sex Pistols song, but it does nevertheless:
``Pretty Vacant.'' The film is pretty _ indeed, stunning _ to look
at, but it doesn't have much to say. And it doesn't have much to
say because it tries to say too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tango'' aspires to be an epic, and as with all epics, it has a
simple story at its center: Filmmaker Mario Suarez (Miguel Angel
Sola) is attempting to make the ultimate movie about tango,
although it would appear that he's trying to encapsulate the entire
history of Argentina. Mario meets with a backer who has mob
connections. The backer asks Mario to find a role for his much
younger mistress. She turns out to be talented, and Mario
predictably falls for her, endangering himself and her.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Carlos Saura might be trying to start a new
sub-genre here: dance noir. But he pays little attention to the
love triangle. ``Tango's'' pattern goes something like this: People
talk in tones that you might use to tell someone that their mother
had suddenly died of a heart attack. Dance number. People talk some
more, in dialogue that might sound better to native
Spanish-speakers but looks like a bad soap-opera script in English
subtitles. Another dance number. People talk some more, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The dance numbers get increasingly interesting and elaborate,
albeit pretentious _ one number about Argentine repression looks
like one of the demented high-school plays from ``Rushmore.'' The
talk gets increasingly sleep-inducing, the kind of portent-loaded
conversation that makes many mistrust foreign films in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, however, isn't about words _ it's so much not about
words that you wonder why Saura bothered with them. Saura is a
fascinatingly visual director, and his opening shot is a grabber: a
nearly 360-degree pan of Buenos Aires during a winter sunrise, in
which the camera moves like a warm lover's caress (you regret the
decision to superimpose opening credits over this shot). The next
scene, equally intriguing, shows Mario in a moody apartment going
over his tango film's screenplay, which turns out to include the
real movie's two opening scenes. So ``Tango'' is also about
filmmaking, right down to its terrific slow-crane closing shot.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about filmmaking, in a way: Not only is the
cinematography beautiful, with languid camera movements that
slither through the movie like a curious snake, but the movie has
been meticulously lighted, costumed and art-directed within an inch
of its life. Saura and his crew favor striking, solid colors _ one
male-to-male pas de deux is filmed in color, but everything in the
scene is in black and white _ and even his most pretentious shots
(superimpositions upon superimpositions upon silhouettes) are
hypnotic.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also about dance, and Argentina, and illicit love, and
ultimately about so much that you wonder what the heck it's really
about. Because ``Tango's'' screenplay is its weakest link while the
rest of the film looks extraordinary, it's tempting to call it the
``Titanic'' of dance films. But it's more like ``The Thin Red
Line'' of dance films _ a movie that's beautiful to look at while
it's absolutely unengaging emotionally. If you love dance, or you
just like to look at pretty pictures, you might want to raise the
star rating here by at least a half-notch. Most of us, however,
need more _ and a story would have been a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Tango''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Carlos Saura
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Miguel Angel Sola, Mia Maestro
</P>
<P>
   Length: 114 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ adult themes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5259 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RAVENOUS-TEX     03-18 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RAVENOUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNIQUELY CONSUMING HORROR STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the ads that make ``Ravenous'' look like a
``Hot Shots/Naked Gun''-style comedy about cannibalism. It's not.
This is a new-style horror movie that wears its themes of terror
and redemption on its sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd that director Antonia Bird, who replaced another
director several weeks into shooting, wasn't the original choice,
because her films _ ``Priest'' and the little-seen ``Safe'' (not to
be confused with the Todd Haynes film of the same name) _ are
fixated on similar themes. (Though Bird is said to have seen the
script a few years ago, before it went into production, and was
impressed with it.)
</P>
<P>
   I hate to say this kind of thing, especially since it's only
March, but ``Ravenous'' is the most distinctive picture of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   As befits the movie's uniqueness, it's received a lot of bad
buzz, which may be because people aren't sure what to make of it.
The movie is genuinely disturbing, and its to-the-bone creepiness
isn't the cheap, easy-to-shake-off shocks of the recent spate of
slasher films. As Bird subtly shifts the tone of the picture from
dreamy delirium to panicked narrative to confrontation, you'll find
that ``Ravenous'' is a movie you'll feel days later; it sticks with
you.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Pearce is a cavalry officer who, after a moment of cowardice
in a battle, is sent to a remote, half-forgotten outpost in the
Sierra Nevada. Haunted and ashamed _ he hid from an attack under a
pile of bodies during the Mexican-American war _ Pearce straggles
into a fort peopled with oddballs and freaks. Jeffrey Jones is the
pallid, kindly commander _ he's as pale as cotton candy _ who
attempts to keep some dignity in this purgatory of an outpost.
</P>
<P>
   One more eccentric is added when a fearful, and feral-looking,
survivor (Robert Carlyle) of a westward wagon train scurries into
the outpost. According to him, when the wagoneers were trapped in
the frozen wild, they were forced to turn to cannibalism. And he
escaped, so that he could bring help to any survivors. But it turns
out that Carlyle wasn't the victim of a cannibal threat; he's the
cunning, murderous instigator who trolls for human meat. And Pearce
becomes not only his prey, but a potential acolyte _ Carlyle wants
to make Pearce a part of his tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravenous'' makes underhanded fun of the American westward
expansion, and the soul-destroying compulsion of the mania for
superficial health at the expense of an inner life. (Carlyle is
explained as a Weendigo, a Native American figure of legend who
consumes human flesh and can be stopped only by sacrifice. Which
means that the coward, Pearce, is the only man who can possibly end
the threat.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie toys with themes of addiction and disease, but it is,
in the end, a love story with dollops of bleak humor. It's also a
showcase for the immensely talented, fearless Carlyle, who's shown
more range than any actor working today. From the rude-boy thug in
``Trainspotting'' and the conflicted protagonist of ``Priest'' to
his small-time charming schemer in ``The Full Monty,'' Carlyle has
a presence and a protean quality that you may not have seen in a
British actor since Daniel Day-Lewis (though he lacks standard
matinee-idol looks).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravenous'' is potent, full of ideas and wildly divergent
acting styles. It may not be your type of movie, but it's safe to
say that there's nothing else out there like it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Ravenous''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Antonia Bird
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Guy Pearce, Robert Carlyle
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ gore, violence, a frank depiction of cannibalism, and
adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
