<HEADER>
A5260 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CHILDRENOFHEAVEN     03-18 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHILDRENOFHEAVEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF LOST SHOES LACED WITH SUBTLETY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've heard that a journey of a thousand miles begins with a
single step. ``Children of Heaven's'' journey begins with a pair of
lost pink shoes. They belong to Zahra, a poor Iranian first-grader
whose older brother, Ali, loses the shoes while running an errand.
</P>
<P>
   Third-grader Ali (Mir Farrokh Hashemian), the film's
protagonist, and sister Zahra (Bahare Seddiqi) are good kids,
always helpful and seldom disobedient to their struggling father
and injured mother. The lost shoes create a crisis for the
siblings, because they believe they'll be punished for the loss,
especially with their family's dire financial standing. So Ali and
Zahra concoct a cover-up: She'll borrow his sneakers (which are of
course two sizes too big for her) while she attends school in the
morning, then run, run, run through Tehran's streets and alleys to
share them with Ali, who runs, runs, runs back to school to attend
in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   This is a simple tale, and these are indeed children of heaven:
Ali and Zahra are two of the most self-sacrificial people you'll
ever run across. ``Children of Heaven,'' a Best Foreign Film
nominee, sometimes feels like an Iranian ``Afterschool Special,''
the type of movie parents might show to unruly children to
demonstrate how ``polite'' kids behave. But it frequently avoids
falling into those kinds of didactic traps, because nobody here
acts quite like you expect them to. The movie lays it on a little
thick when the pink shoes show up on another little girl's feet,
and her family turns out to be even worse off than Ali and Zahra's.
It overcomes these missteps, though, with a considerable amount of
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Majid Majidi, a veteran of the Iranian kid-movie
scene, sought out amateurs for his cast and made quite a discovery
in Hashemian, who hardly needs to have acting talent because he's
blessed with the largest, saddest eyes this side of a velvet
painting. His face adds to Ali's against-the-world pluck _ the only
bad people in the film are adult authority figures, and even
they're comparatively benevolent _ and almost fear-based
resourcefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Majidi varies his uses of Tehran locations, from poor to
affluent neighborhoods, and he and set designer Ashghar Nezhad
Imani give the interiors a colorful, rumpled-and-crowded look that
comes from the sort of art direction that doesn't look like art
direction. Iranian films celebrate the color that so many American
films take for granted, and Majidi saturates the movie with
everything in the spectrum. His shots of the various styles of
children's shoes here, indicative of the importance of the kids'
individuality, are especially entrancing.
</P>
<P>
   The movie climaxes with Ali in a lengthy footrace, with the kind
of goal you likely wouldn't see in an American film _ and with the
kind of wordless visuals, heightened sound and exquisite
slow-motion we've rarely seen since 1979's ``The Black Stallion.''
The movie's poetic closing shot is the kind of ending that most
filmmakers would want to make more explicit, and Majidi's subtle
touch is what elevates the movie above the sort of sentimental,
heavy-handed morality tale that it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Children of Heaven'' (in Farsi with English subtitles)
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Majid Majidi
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Mir Farrokh Hashemian, Bahare Seddiqi
</P>
<P>
   Length: 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ a couple of swear words
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
