<HEADER>
A5261 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FORCESOFNATURE-T     03-18 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FORCESOFNATURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIRKY `FORCES' LACKS STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' may be the most insistently quirky romantic
comedy to come along in some time. Sarah (Sandra Bullock) is the
force of nature who overwhelms Ben (played by, uh, Ben Affleck), a
staid groom-to-be on his way to his wedding.
</P>
<P>
   The real force of nature operating in this movie is fear. At his
bachelor party, Ben is suddenly struck by a feeling that he hasn't
done much with his life. It's a feeling instigated by a grandfather
who talks about not having been with enough women, and a feeling
encouraged by his pleasure-seeking-missile of a best friend (Steve
Zahn) _ a conceit more than a role, but a standard in these kinds
of stories.
</P>
<P>
   The plane Ben boards for his wedding to Bridget (Maura Tierney),
the bride-to-be who seems as conflicted as he is, has a mishap
during takeoff. Before he knows it, he's on the road with an
irrepressible free spirit (Bullock) _ the kind who in real life
would be irritating, but she wins him over because ... well, she's
the star of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   As they careen from misadventure to misadventure, pelted by
almost every kind of precipitation that Mother Nature has to offer,
Ben is more and more convinced that Bridget isn't the one for him _
and that, maybe, his new travel mate is. Flashing as many teeth as
a great white whale, Bullock is constantly sizing Affleck up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tierney is plagued by her twittery Southern-belle
mother (Blythe Danner) and a moony ex-boyfriend who croons
``Against All Odds'' to her. It's rare that a movie huffs and puffs
as hard to create memorable sequences as does ``Forces.'' It's as
if someone decided to take a bunch of high points that would make a
great trailer and cram them into one picture. A bizarre combination
of antic and melancholy, this picture's begging to be considered a
classic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``Forces'' being a road comedy, it's more like one of
those the-road-as-test comedies about spiritual crisis that include
``National Lampoon's Vacation'' and, more specifically, ``Trains,
Planes &AMP; Automobiles.'' ``Forces'' plays like a party remix with
hefty samples of ``Planes, Trains'' and ``The Philadelphia Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, with his broad-beamed, placid good looks, Affleck
behaves as if it would take a force of nature to rouse him from his
cooled-out state. Emotionally, he's more of an immovable object.
He's incapable of appearing as troubled as this role calls for.
</P>
<P>
   A chic soundtrack keeps things chugging, featuring a remix of
U2's ``Everlasting Love'' cover and a way-too-festive remix of
Pigeonhed's ``Battle Royal.'' (It's a sad state of affairs when a
soundtrack to a movie as middle-of-the-road as this one is hipper
than the playlist of almost any radio station in the United
States.)
</P>
<P>
   After directing ``Ever After,'' Bronwen Hughes seems eager to
create a new kind of mythology, using a busy yet dreamy directing
style. Spirals of rain pelt the stars from overhead angles as they
run to keep ahead of the emotional cloudburst dogging them.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie doesn't make much sense, emotionally. It borders
on the cruel for Affleck to consider having an affair, since
Tierney's such a sweetie. And Bullock's restless, bulldozing style
is someone's idea of a '90s screwball comedy heroine, I guess,
especially after she turns out to be as flawed as anyone else in
the picture _ more so, even. If only someone had tried to shoehorn
some emotional logic into the film along with the big comedy
moments.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Forces of Nature''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bronwen Hughes
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Sandra Bullock, Ben Affleck
</P>
<P>
   Length: 102 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
