<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAUTICALNEWENGLAND-TE     03-18 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAUTICALNEWENGLAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEE-WORTHY NEW ENGLAND: SCENERY, HISTORY SET THE COURSE FOR SAILING
SOJOURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN BAUMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an adventure I had longed for, a solo trip to explore a
part of the country I had never seen. I chose New England for
several reasons: to do research for a book on sailors, to sail as
much as possible, and to see whether New England was as scenic and
charming as I had always imagined it to be. I was not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   I traveled up the New England coast, surrounding myself with
picturesque seascapes, landscapes and sailing sights.
</P>
<P>
   Though New Englanders have a reputation for stoicism, I found
them to be friendly and generous, which made traveling alone a
pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, I asked the dock master at the Newport Yacht Club
when the club held its races; then I made a habit of showing up
about an hour early to see if anyone needed a crew member. Many
captains will take you along, whether they need more hands or not.
I crewed on a boat called Air Force during the National Offshore
One Design, a three-day series of races.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Joan, a spunky 64-year-old I met at the Star
Lunch diner where I ate breakfast several times and who generously
put me up at her home in Newport for six weeks while I interviewed
sailors and crewed on racing boats.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have a set itinerary for my trip but rather played it
by ear, traveling the coast, photographing endless harbors and
nestled coves, stopping whenever I was enchanted by the sights.
</P>
<P>
   The first place I dropped anchor was Mystic, Conn., where I
headed straight for Mystic Seaport, The Museum of America and the
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Mystic Seaport is like stepping back in time. You
stroll through a 19th-century village of working seafarers' shops,
where a ship's smith forges nails, hoops and harpoons; a cooper
works at barrel making; and carpenters craft a small boat. You can
walk the wooden deck of a whaling ship, the Charles W. Morgan, and
see the crews' quarters, the blubber room and the galley. Built in
1841, the Morgan is the last surviving wooden vessel from America's
19th-century whaling fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Mystic, you can watch shipbuilders construct a replica
of the freedom schooner Amistad, which is expected to be completed
in 2000. The revolt of slaves aboard the Amistad and their
subsequent trial was the subject of a 1997 Steven Spielberg drama.
</P>
<P>
   I spent the most time in Newport, R.I., ``The Yachting Capital
of the World.'' Besides crewing on racing sloops, I visited Fort
Adams, one of the largest seacoast fortifications; took the ferry
to Block Island; toured Hammersmith Farm, the childhood summer home
of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis; and strolled The Cliff Walk, a 3
1/2-mile path with mansions on one side and a cliff falling to the
Atlantic Ocean on the other, described by some as the best walk in
America. Some of the mansions along the Cliff Walk are open for
touring, including The Breakers, built for Cornelius Vanderbilt in
1895, and Astors' Beechwood Mansion, the home of John Jacob Astor
IV.
</P>
<P>
   As you wander up the coast of Maine, the sandy shoreline turns
rocky. (I checked out former President Bush's home in
Kennebunkport.) When you get near Camden on Highway 1 in Maine,
every other car seems to have a kayak or canoe on the roof. Camden
Hills State Park has a variety of trails for hikers, each with a
rewarding view at the end. An evening stroll around the docks at
Camden Harbor, and the quaint surrounding shops, is a great way to
enjoy the cool summer night before heading back to the campground.
</P>
<P>
   From Camden, I drove to Bar Harbor on Mount Desert Island, where
I pitched my tent at the Blackwoods Campgrounds in Acadia National
Park and joined up with some friends, Bettina and Frank from
Germany (we had met in Camden and agreed to share a campsite in
Blackwoods for three days). The three of us signed up for a
four-hour kayak tour around the Porcupine Islands. We also drove to
the summit of Cadillac Mountain, elevation 1,530 feet, for a
spectacular view of the Atlantic Ocean and the surrounding islands.
At the Island Chowder House, in Bar Harbor, I finally had a bowl of
creamy New England clam chowder. Delicious! (No, I never had
lobster; I was on a tight budget.)
</P>
<P>
   For me, the magic of New England will always be the lure of the
seacoast and the maritime activities. Add in the picturesque towns,
the colonial history and the many friends I made, and the draw to
return is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI
</P>
<P>
   Mystic Chamber of Commerce, Mystic, Conn.: www.visitmystic.com
</P>
<P>
   Mystic Seaport, The Museum of America and the Sea, Mystic,
Conn.: Open daily except Christmas, admission $16 for adults, $8
for ages 6-12; children 5 and under free: (888) 9SEAPORT ( (888)
973-2767); www.mysticseaport.org
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island Vacation Kit: (888) U-UNWIND ( (888) 886-9463)
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Office of Travel &AMP; Tourism: (800) 227-MASS; (
(800) 227-6277) www.massvacation.com
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod Chamber of Commerce: (888) 33-CAPECOD ( (888)
332-2732); www.capecod.com/maine
</P>
<P>
   Camden Hills State Park, Camden, Maine, opens for camping May
15; $16 per night without a reservation, $18 with a reservation;
(207) 287-3824 for reservations
</P>
<P>
   Newport County Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau: (800) 976-5122
</P>
<P>
   Hammersmith Farm: (401) 846-7346
</P>
