   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The trade deficit in goods and
services set a record in January as imports surged and exports
declined for the fourth consecutive month. While the economic
troubles of other countries ate into orders to American factories,
American consumers continued to buy goods at an active rate, and
much of that demand was met with imports. The trade deficit grew to
$16.99 billion in January from $14.06 billion in December. The
deficit with Japan narrowed, the shortfall with China widened and
the deficit with Canada, the largest trading partner, was the
largest since November 1986. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   SONY-PLAYSTATION-II (San Jose, Calif.) _ The state of the art in
consumer electronics is shifting from CompUSA to Toys ``R'' Us.
Sony's new Playstation II is sending shockwaves through Silicon
Valley. The fruit of a joint development project between Sony and
Toshiba, the new machine marks the creation of a mass-producible,
supercomputer-class processor _ for a toy _ and trumpets the dawn
of the post-PC era. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   DUAL-PURPOSE-DRUGS (Undated) _ While drug companies have long
found second and third uses for existing drugs, never have they
worked as actively as they are now to expand their brands.
Virtually every major pharmaceutical company is rushing to
reintroduce an existing compound as a treatment for another
disease. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-IMPORTS (Undated) _ A folo on the House vote to limit
steel imports and its import for U.S. and world trade. By Leslie
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAWEST-LABOR (Undated) _ America West Airlines is facing a
possible strike by its flight attendants. The cooling-off period
expires at the end of Friday. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BROWSER (Redmond, Wash.) _ Microsoft introduces the
newest version of its Internet Explorer browser. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-LVMH (Rome) _ Gucci's earnings rose 11 percent in the
latest year, more than expected, sending its shares up as much as 9
percent in Amsterdam. Meanwhile, LVMH, which has a disputed stake
in Gucci, had an indicated profit decline of 48 percent in the
second half, but its shares gain 6 percent in Paris because the
company says an improvement in Asia should boost operating profit
by at least 15 percent this year. Not surprisingly, Gucci says that
a comparison of the two sets of results shows that Gucci does not
need LVMH. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-AWARDS (New York) _ Magazine Award nominations are
announced. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 13
points, at 9,892. The Nasdaq index was up 6 points, or 0.2 percent.
Elsewhere, prices fell 3.4 percent in Tokyo and 2.6 percent in Hong
Kong. They decreased 0.7 percent in Frankfurt, 0.8 percent in
London and 0.3 percent in Mexico. They were flat in Brazil. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 9/32 point, with the
yield at 5.48 percent.
</P>
