<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED19-COX     03-18 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW PROGRAM TO HELP FIRMS FIND DISABLED COLLEGE GRADUATES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New help for private employers in recruiting
college-educated applicants with disabilities was announced
Thursday by the President's Committee on Employment of the
Handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program helps us get on with the business of making a
living and serving others by so doing,'' said Ellen Rogers, one of
the 299 persons who received paid internships or jobs last year
under a similar program for federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of three said her poor vision led to being turned
down for 12 different jobs in schools in and around Tampa, Fla.,
despite her master's degree in English. But the Workforce
Recruitment Program helped her get a summer internship in a Public
Health Service office in Rockville, Md., where she then was hired
for a permanent job.
</P>
<P>
   To expand the program to private jobs, the committee's
recruiters interviewed 1,200 seniors and recent graduates on 148
college and university campuses during this school year. Then they
prepared a CD-ROM that contains a brief resume and the
interviewer's evaluation of the credentials, abilities and
attitudes of each of the 1,026 job-seekers from 143 campuses in 34
states who were judged qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Most are seeking jobs or internships in administration,
engineering, computer work or science. But the CD-ROM, which can
searched by state or job category, includes applicants for just
about every kind of white-collar job.
</P>
<P>
   Employers can obtain the free CD-ROM by faxing a request on
company letterhead to the attention of ``WRP Manager'' at (202)
376-6878. Or they can call toll-free at 800-526-7234 to have a
specialist use the CD-ROM to prepare them a list of job-seekers who
appear to meet specific job qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters from big companies said the new program will be
useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this tight job market, we're trying in every way, shape or
form to locate qualified people,'' said Joel Kahn, an engineer at
Procter &AMP; Gamble headquarters in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a business basis, as well as a moral one,'' said
Phyllis Jackson of Bank of America. ``Our customer base, our
associate population (employees) and the labor force include people
with disabilities. If we're going to be an effective employer and
competitor, we have to tap into that market.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1442EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
