 ART ADV.: Photos with AUTO-REVIEW are being transmitted to NYT
Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TALIBAN-PROTEST (Los Angeles) _ Joining the Hollywood pantheon
of such social causes as freedom for Tibet, AIDS, and breast-cancer
research is a protest against the Taliban and its treatment of
women. By Lynda Gorov. 1200 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   TENURE-EXPERIMENT (Conway, Ark.) _ The University of Central
Arkansas' new plan for tenure is being both hailed and decried by
professors. Schools are watching to see how this experiment works.
By Kate Zernike. 1550 words.
</P>
<P>
   FORMER-SLAVE (Undated) _ Moctar Teyeb, born into slavery in
Mauritania until he escaped, tells students about life in bondage,
and about how Westerners have little comprehension that slavery
endures. By Charles Radin. 800 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELLIS-COLUMN (Undated) -- Technology will rule the brave new
world of banking. By John Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Jacoby-Column by Jeff Jacoby will be unavailable until
March 25.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-ROSEMARY (Undated) -- Raising a $32-a-pound pinch of
rosemary. By Ruth Foster.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-COLUMN (Undated) _ After a successful baby-sitting
experience, a preteen can feel better about herself than she did
before she walked in the door. By Barbara Meltz. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-COLUMN (Undated) _ When women trust their bodies. By
Linda Weltner.
</P>
<P>
   HANDYMAN-HOTTON (Undated) _ Paint thinner cleans wood, and
metal. By Peter Hotton.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Diane White's column is unavailable today.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-PIPHER (Undated) _ Writer and psychologist Mary Pipher
has dedicated herself to unraveling the exasperating but common
