<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERLINK-HNS &LR;      03-18 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERLINK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVICE PROVIDES COMPUTER SKILLS AT THE BLINK OF AN EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Finally, it's mind over computer.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrate, and a cursor on a computer screen drifts toward a
file you want to open. Clench your jaw, and a program starts up.
</P>
<P>
   Focus hard enough, and the screen comes alive in an electronic
light show concerto, the various notes and corresponding colors
controlled by your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like science fiction, but Cyberlink, as it's called,
is here, and it was wowing crowds at the South By Southwest
Interactive Conference, part of a technology, music and film
festival in Austin that closes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost scary, watching the computer do things you're
thinking about,'' said David Martin, an electronic musician from
New York who stepped away from the demo booth, sweating. ``Very
science fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyberlink was pioneered by Andrew Junker, a researcher at the
Wright Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio. Junker was part
of a program to create links between a pilot and the instruments of
an aircraft, the better to deal with information overload while
hunting down enemy jets and dodging surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cyberlink, hands-free computer control involved
coordinating a command to an eye, head or facial movement.
</P>
<P>
   Junker, while retired and living in the Caribbean, said he
invented a way of harnessing a range of brain waves, muscle
contractions and eye movements. These impulses are captured by
three silver chloride-coated plastic tablets held to the head with
a Velcro strap.
</P>
<P>
   The strap is connected to a small box of electronics _ including
a microprocessor and amplifiers _ that boost and filter brain
waves, muscle and eye impulses into a recognizable signal fed into
a Windows-based computer through its serial port.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle was over how to convert all this information into
something usable,'' said Chris Tate, 37, a biomedical engineer and
director of research at Brain Actuated Technologies Inc., the
Yellow Springs, Ohio-based company Junker formed to find practical
uses for his invention.
</P>
<P>
   The device doesn't actually read thoughts. It associates certain
facial muscle movements and/or brain waves with a certain computer
function. Users can repeat the function by repeating the movement
or brain wave.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when a user thinks, ``move cursor up,'' he
generates a unique combination of eye, muscle and brain waves for
that thought. The software is trained to move the cursor up when
the signal for that combination of reflexes is sent to the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell you what I do to make the computer do certain
things,'' Tate said. ``If you consciously try to make it happen,
you exaggerate and throw everything off. You just have to accept
that you do generate this signal and tell the computer to take a
certain action based on the signal. It's very, very Zen.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tate, the software can be trained to perform any
number of tasks, depending on a user's ability to generate a
specific signal for that task. He added that an interface to type
is being developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyberlink technology also drives Brain Actuated
Technologies' new Brain-Actuated Music software, which translates
the headband signal into musical notes. Again, certain brain waves
and corresponding muscle and eye movements trigger a synthesized
chorus of high notes or deep bass. Tate already is compiling a
catalog of original works, starting with the ``Cortex Concerto.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate said the company is searching for investors, but it has yet
to find what he called the right deal.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 Cyberlinks are being field-tested as a computing
aid for disabled people who cannot use their hands to manipulate a
mouse and keyboard, Tate said.
</P>
<P>
   The device costs $1,900.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
