r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-VACCINE-HNS &LR;      03-18 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS TEST LACKS VOLUNTEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Only 1,500 people have signed up to test an AIDS
vaccine that is close to receiving federal approval, far fewer than
the 5,000 the manufacturer hopes to enroll by summer.
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVax, manufactured by VaxGen Inc. of South San Francisco,
Calif., is one of about 40 vaccines being studied worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge has been getting people to understand
we're not injecting them with the AIDS virus,'' said Nicole Lynch,
a spokeswoman for VaxGen.
</P>
<P>
   To combat that fear, some of the 53 testing sites in the country
have been taking unusual steps to boost enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, one outreach worker dressed in drag before
hitting the town with information about the new drug. Las Vegas
recruiters passed out flyers and condoms at a gay rodeo. In Kansas
City, Mo., an outreach worker is a regular visitor to a gay men's
chat room to find enrollees on line.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only the testing center in Denver has succeeded in
meeting its participation quota with 190 enrollees, 40 more than
its goal. ``I think people have to start getting more creative,''
Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other vaccinations, AIDSVax does not contain live
virus. Rather, it's made from genetically-engineered proteins that
make up the outer shell of human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV. In
theory, the body will think the proteins are the virus, prompting
the production of antibodies that would prevent future infection.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last three years. Two-thirds of the
participants will receive the vaccine, while one-third will receive
a placebo, a neutral substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Meier, clinical director at the Kansas City AIDS research
Consortium, said one challenge is keeping people in the study once
they enroll. Since November, Kansas City has recruited 70 of the
150 people they hope to enroll. Outreach workers visit local gay
bars nightly, handing out condoms and answering questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management of the information that's out in the public is
the number one thing you've got to worry about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
