<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO LOSES 2003 SUPER BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The National Football League dropped San Francisco as
the site of the 2003 Super Bowl because of delays over a new
stadium for the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   League owners took the action Wednesday, the final day of the
NFL's annual gathering. But they reaffirmed their commitment to
play a Super Bowl in San Francisco when it has a suitable stadium.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue declined to commit himself on
the earliest possible date the game would be played in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He said the league would work with Denise DeBartolo York and her
husband, John York, who control of the 49ers, to establish ``an
aggressive timetable'' for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the entire organization, beginning with Denise York
herself as the new chairman of the board of the 49ers, is committed
to that project,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   The league's decision to yank San Francisco's invitation, which
dated from 1994, was long expected. It arose from uncertainty over
club plans to build a new $525 million stadium and commercial
center, which was approved by city voters in 1997 but has been
stalled by management problems and cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   In all probability the decision also was influenced by the NFL's
problems with Edward DeBartolo Jr., the embattled co-owner of the
San Francisco team.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo was suspended for the 1999-2000 season and fined $1
million Tuesday for conduct deemed detrimental to the NFL. The
move, also long anticipated, came in the wake of DeBartolo's guilty
plea to a federal felony in October in connection with a Louisiana
gambling-and-bribery case.
</P>
<P>
   When DeBartolo's role in the federal investigation was made
public in December 1997, he relinquished all management posts in
the club and the family corporation that owns it, the Edward J.
DeBartolo Corp. of Youngstown, Ohio. Denise York, DeBartolo's
sister and partner in the corporation, assumed complete control,
and recently delegated operating authority over the club to her
husband, John.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium is to be partly financed through a $100 million city
bond issue approved two years ago. But a design plan for the new
park doesn't exist. The Yorks say it is their intention to build a
new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's decision permits San Francisco to withdraw from a
commitment it couldn't keep, but spares the city any embarrassment
or financial harm because it virtually guarantees a game in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Cities covet the Super Bowls because the games generate as much
as $300 million in business for hotels, restaurants and merchants,
plus priceless exposure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
