</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH FAKES THAT ATTRACRT CONNOISSEURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is more valuable in the long run, style or
authenticity? That question is increasingly redefining the rules of
connoisseurship, especially in an era when a small folding table
worth around $100 can bring more than $12,000 simply because
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis owned it.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more 20th-century tastemakers die and their goods
and chattel come on the auction block, it has become apparent that
reproductions are valuable because faking it _ commissioning and
living with reproductions _ can be a crucial part of a celebrity's
personal style.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings and most forms of art are exempt from this theory; to
art collectors of every stripe, a copy is a forgery, with little
redeeming value, whatever its provenance, materials or accuracy.
But in the furniture world, it seems anything goes if the quality
is high, the object useful and the owner lived with enviable flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not one of those decorators who insist on originals,''
wrote the late, great Elsie de Wolfe (1865-1950), whose career is
being celebrated in a monthlong exhibition at the Municipal Art
Society, in Manhattan. ``I believe good reproductions are more
valuable than feeble originals, unless you are buying your
furniture on speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Curated by Jane Stubbs, the show features dozens of
black-and-white photographs of, and evocative vignette
installations recalling, the designer's epoch-making interiors,
ranging from the Manhattan penthouse of the publishing magnate
Conde Nast to the Villa Trianon, de Wolfe's home near Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few of the images include the designer's favorite
item to reproduce: a graceful Louis XV sofa that she first spotted
in the Petit Trianon in France and that, she admitted in ``The
House in Good Taste'' (1913), ``I have copied many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Stylish fakes of a slightly later era and a more prosaic quality
are included in Thursday's sale of the estate of Maureen,
Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava, at Christie's in London. A famous
1930s beauty, and once the mother-in-law of the painter Lucien
Freud and the poet Robert Lowell, Lady Dufferin, who died last year
at 91, lived in stage-set splendor in London, Kent and Sardinia, in
houses masterminded by the now obscure English decorator Felix
Harbord (1906-81).
</P>
<P>
   His pasteboard drama appealed to the generation whose exploits
dominated society columns between the wars. An enemy of genteel
English decoration, Harbord called for decors of ``a certain gaiety
which will be more welcome'' than ``the drabness in which many are
forced to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the designer invented deliriously pastel interiors for
Lady Dufferin's elder sister, Aileen Plunket, perhaps the most
famous of his installations was the multicolumned drawing room at
Reddish House, which was completed in the 1950s for the
photographer Cecil Beaton. Its burgundy-velvet walls and
gilt-trimmed white furniture were a luxurious high-camp evocation
of Second Empire chic.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Dufferin, as theatrical as Beaton but less demanding when
it came to creating stylish surroundings, apparently was content to
use the popular Harbord as a source for good-looking but largely
pedestrian ready-mades.
</P>
<P>
   A few examples stand out, like Lot 351, a white Regency-style
card table highlighted in a frosty shade of pale lingerie blue,
with four matching chairs; formerly in Lady Dufferin's cottage in
Kent, it is estimated to sell for $1,200 to $1,600. But only three
of the chairs date from the early 1800s; to complete the set, the
fourth was made in 1957, as was the table, and, the catalog says,
Harbord apparently made more copies of the chairs for a South
American client.
</P>
<P>
   Better copies of grander historical mien will come onto the
market when the contents of Chateau de Groussay, an early
19th-century country house in the Paris suburb of
Montfort-L'Amaury, go on sale from June 2 through June 6.
</P>
<P>
   The French division of Sotheby's was originally scheduled to
sell the items at its premises opposite the Elysee Palace, but the
domestic monopoly on auctioneering forced the company, an American
firm, to hold the auction at the chateau.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The sale, of more than 2,000 objects, will be conducted by the
auctioneers Poulain Le Fur, with Sotheby's assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Extensively remodeled and decorated by its owner, Charles de
Beistegui _ a Spanish-born, English-bred silver-mining heir whose
lavish entertainments enlivened international society in the 1930s
and 1940s _ Groussay's glamorous, neo-historical interiors have
been considered a high water mark of 20th-century high style. And
this is fully in spite of its trickery, what one British journalist
called ``high-class Walt Disneyfication.''
</P>
<P>
   A fantasy par excellence, Groussay is ultimately about the
triumph of inspired artifice, a temple of confection. The house,
circa 1815, is chockablock with real treasures _ including an
outstanding collection of Old Master drawings assembled by
Beistegui's nephew Juan, who inherited the 120-acre estate, its
garden follies and furnishings after his uncle's death in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the contents, from its celebrated so-called Goya
tapestries to numerous pieces of furniture, are exquisitely
rendered imitations. Still, the sale is expected to bring more than
$32 million, not including the house, which was built for the
Duchess de Charost and is priced at $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Laure de Beauvau Craon, Sotheby's president in France,
says one of the sale's star fakes is a large ormolu-encrusted
mahogany bureau set with Wedgwood medallions.
</P>
<P>
   Obsessed with symmetrical furniture arrangements, Beistegui
commissioned it in 1940 to match exactly a Louis XVI original that
he had bought for Groussay's two-story library (whose majestic
corkscrew staircases inspired the set of Henry Higgins' library in
the movie ``My Fair Lady''). Sold together as Lot 328, the bureaus
are expected to bring between $33,520 and $50,280.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beistegui was an esthete, and like any esthete he wanted to
create an atmosphere of beauty without following a set of rules,''
said the princess, who added that the imitation bureau was made by
Lucien Toulouse, a cabinetmaker known for superb bronze work. ``The
bureau is a creation of the 20th century,'' she said, ``but in the
spirit of an earlier time for a house that has become a landmark of
neoclassical decoration.''
</P>
<P>
   So are numerous other Beisteguian baubles, like a towering
painted plaster blackamoor, circa 1925, that imitates an
18th-century Baroque original and a dining table centerpiece, circa
1930, made in the style of 18th-century Nymphenburg porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   The blackamoor is expected to sell for $840 to $1,340, and the
centerpiece for $6,700 to $10,055. Incongruously, both were among
the furnishings of Beistegui's youthful apartment, a hard-edged
modernist penthouse in Paris designed for him by Le Corbusier.
</P>
<P>
   The look of the centerpiece, like the Eisenhower-era table and
chairs in Lady Dufferin's sale, perfectly represents the period it
presumes. And that presumption, de Wolfe wrote, is the whole point
of great decoration: ``The effect is the thing you are after, isn't
it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
