<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S COMING OF AGE RUINS PARENTS' OMNISCIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Puberty is an odd word, isn't it? I mean, it looks funny and it
sounds funny. It doesn't even rhyme with anything. Like, ``I
started puberty at the Statue of Luberty?'' Nope, doesn't work.
It's a strange word for a strange time of life.
</P>
<P>
   Hormones raging, hairs sprouting everywhere, voice changing, and
the B.O.! Whoa, mama! I recently made the mistake of sniffing the
underarm area of my son's basketball jersey because I wasn't sure
whether it was clean. The next thing I remember was waking up on
the floor with little tweeting birds circling my head singing
``Rainy Night In Georgia.'' It took three days to pry my upper lip
away from my nose.
</P>
<P>
   But that's OK. I expected these things. I remember these sights
and sounds from my own travels along Growing Up Boulevard. What's
driving me crazy is all of the questions. Before puberty came, I
was Mom the Magnificent. Now I'm the hypocritical idiot who can't
remember anything. Oh, he doesn't use those words, of course, but
that's what he's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell from his tone of voice and his facial expression when
he says, ``Mom, why do grown-ups tell us not to do things and then
they do them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what, son?'' I respond, assuming he's talking about that
pop can I forgot to recycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you tell us not to drink and then you had a glass of
champagne at that wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, I never told you not to drink. That was your father. I
told you not to hit yourself in the head with a sledge hammer. You
have never seen me do that, now have you?''
</P>
<P>
   Geez, Louise. These kids see everything. I'm trying to set a
good example for them. I've given up almost everything but
chocolate and coffee. I've got to have something to look forward
to, don't I?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, occasionally I do forget where I left my keys or my purse.
Sure, I forgot how to get to the soccer field one morning. All
right, I also forgot how to get home one day, but I was really,
really tired. Does that truly warrant the comment, ``Mom, what will
you do when I'm gone? You'll never find your car again.''
</P>
<P>
   To which I reply, ``I'll do all of my shopping at small
convenience stores. We won't need as much food then anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles smugly and hums to himself in response. He's thinking,
``She's loony. I'll be running this place in a few years. I'll just
keep her around until she can't help me with my homework anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but I know something he doesn't know. Fortunately, I've
already been where he's going. As I went from being a pubescent to
a teen-ager to a young adult, I got smarter and smarter.
Eventually, I got so smart that I realized how very much I didn't
know _ like, if you are not sure about the cleanliness of a
pubescent boy's T-shirt, don't sniff it; just go ahead and wash it.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
