<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-18 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE KING AND I': IF RODGERS AND HAMMERSTEIN HAD WRITTEN FOR LOONEY
TUNES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the middle of a storm at sea, Anna, her son and several
sailors sing and march around to ``I Whistle a Happy Tune.'' This
completely freaks out the fire-breathing sea monster who was
attacking them, and it goes away.
</P>
<P>
   This, the first musical number in the new animated version of
``The King and I,'' gives an idea of the kinds of departures the
film takes from its original source _ a 1943 novel, ``Anna and the
King of Siam,'' based on the real Anna Leonowens' 19th-century
memoirs _ not to mention its stage and film predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most startling additions, the King of Siam takes a
hot-air balloon ride to search for his runaway son and ends up
dangling from the balloon by a rope like a muscle-proud action
hero.
</P>
<P>
   The animation is done in rich, jewel-like colors, but it seems
strangely flat. The overall film does, too, although the glorious
Rodgers and Hammerstein music makes up for a lot. This should help
make the film enjoyable for adults, but I've never heard a small
child hum ``Hello, Young Lovers'' or ``Shall We Dance?''
</P>
<P>
   The actors who do the characters' voices, including Miranda
Richardson as Anna and Martin Vidnovic as the king, do fine jobs,
but the cartoon characters' faces and body language aren't doing
much of an acting job for them. Films like this illustrate just how
much really goes into brilliant animation.
</P>
<P>
   Every possible opportunity has been taken to add cute animals
and slapstick-comic humans, on the theory that children are always
suckers for that sort of thing. Anna's son, Louis, has a pet monkey
that is always jumping onto the heads of stuffy adults. Tuptim the
slave girl makes friends with a baby elephant that she names
Tusker.
</P>
<P>
   The Kralahome has been turned into an evil wizard (``Let's show
them something truly barbaric'') with a magic screen that lets him
spy on everyone. He also has a short, fat assistant, Master Little,
who is constantly finding himself trapped in a tree or pinned to a
wall or in some other kind of slapstick peril. The film's lifeless
running gag is that Little's teeth fall out, one by one.
</P>
<P>
   The overall story is familiar, of course. In the mid-19th
century Anna, a British widow, travels with her son to Siam to take
a job as tutor to the king's children.
</P>
<P>
   She finds the king stubborn and immorally authoritative but
charming. She clashes with him on matters of tradition and what we
would now call human rights issues, but she also helps him prove to
the English that he is no barbarian. The two eventually bond in a
serious way, as the king's innate wisdom wins out over his ego and
the old ways.
</P>
<P>
   There is one more variation on the plot that parents may want to
know about: In this version the king does not die.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE KING AND I'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Rich; written by Peter Bakalian, Jacqueline
Feather and David Seidler, adapted from the musical by Richard
Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein II, conceived and adapted for
animation by Arthur Rankin; edited by James D. Koford; music by
Rodgers, with lyrics by Hammerstein, arranged, orchestrated and
conducted by William Kidd; produced by James G. Robinson, Rankin
and Bakalian; released by Warner Brothers Family Entertainment and
Morgan Creek International. Running time: 100 minutes. This film is
rated G.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Miranda Richardson and Christiane Noll
(speaking and singing voices of Anna Leonowens), Martin Vidnovic
(the King of Siam), Ian Richardson (the Kralahome), Darrell Hammond
(Master Little), Allen D. Hong and David Burnham (speaking and
singing voices of Prince Chululongkorn), Armi Arabe and Tracy
Venner Warren (speaking and singing voice of Tuptim), Adam Wylie
(Louis Leonowens), Sean Smith (Sir Edward Ramsay), and J.A. Fujii
(First Wife).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
