<SLUG> BC-NATURE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORCES OF NATURE': A FILM WITH LITTLE FORCE OR DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does Sandra Bullock's loopy girl-next-door charm really make
audiences want to follow her anywhere? If so, they'd better be
prepared for the amusement-park ride with senior citizens, the
gay-bar strip scene and the antic, hourslong romp through a K-mart
that ``Forces of Nature'' so desperately offers.
</P>
<P>
   This would-be screwball comedy pairs Ms. Bullock's zany drifter
with a nervous groom-to-be (Ben Affleck) who is en route to his
wedding. It's so anxious to bolster this frail comic setup that it
makes every possible detour along the way.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, bohemian Sarah (Ms. Bullock with flowing hair
and heavy eye makeup) shakes the resolve of Ben ( Affleck) to marry
Bridget (Maura Tierney), who fumes her own way through a funnier
part of the movie while stranded in Savannah. Sarah bewitches
straight-arrow Ben in ways that reveal the film's eagerness to turn
itself into ``Something Wild.''
</P>
<P>
   So Sarah and Ben move along from cute hostility (``I don't know
you that well, but I think something may be wrong with you'') to
the inevitable budding romance. But there are complications.
Bridget is appealing, even when being driven crazy by her
quarrelsome parents (Blythe Danner and Ronny Cox) or going to
pieces when a hurricane threatens to wreck the wedding day.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah proves less carefree than she first appeared and has some
unfinished business in Savannah with her young son. Ben quakes to
the film's frequent warnings that marriage is a nightmare, but what
will he do? The film has no good answer. There can't be a focus
group under the sun that would have advocated the ending ``Forces
of Nature'' finally chooses.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Bronwen Hughes (``Harriet the Spy'') and written
by Marc Lawrence, the film shows off Ms. Bullock to amusing if
overly frenetic advantage. It also leaves Affleck without enough of
a Cary Grant aura to play his wimpier character with style. (He's
far more clever in ``Shakespeare in Love.'')
</P>
<P>
   Not even Steve Zahn, who steals the forthcoming ``Happy, Texas''
so hilariously, has enough comic opportunities in the small,
sketchy role of Ben's best man. Some of the gaps are filled in by
special-effects hail and wind storms, which are as close as the
title comes to making any sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes mild profanity and a few suggestive
moments.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `FORCES OF NATURE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bronwen Hughes; written by Marc Lawrence; director
of photography, Elliot Davis; edited by Craig Wood; music by John
Powell; production designer, Lester Cohen; produced by Susan
Arnold, Donna Arkoff Roth and Ian Bryce; released by Dreamworks
Pictures. Running time: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Sandra Bullock (Sarah), Ben Affleck (Ben), Maura Tierney
(Bridget), Steve Zahn (Alan), Blythe Danner (Virginia), Ronny Cox
(Hadley) and Michael Fairman (Richard).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
