<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-LOGGING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIF. GOVERNOR GIVES $12 MILLION CHECK FOR LOST JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEADWATERS FOREST RESERVE, Humboldt County, Calif.) _ Standing
on the slope of a fir and redwood grove the new, government-owned
7,500-acre Headwaters reserve, Gov. Gray Davis reflected on the
long battle to buy it and impose tough environmental standards on
about 200,000 acres that the landowner, Pacific Lumber Co., plans
to log nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you come here yourself, and this is my first time, you
cannot understand how awe-inspiring this is,'' Davis said. ``If you
stand up here, you'll understand what this battle was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he had traveled to Eureka, Calif., to drop off a $12
million check from the state to compensate the Humboldt County
government for lost jobs because of a reduction in logging
operations.
</P>
<P>
   There are no strings attached to the money, which means the
county can use it to, say, put in new sidewalks, start a
job-training program or sweeten the pot for a new Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber President John Campbell, who was in the Board of
Supervisors' chamber during the check ceremony, estimated that
about 250 workers would have to be laid off, although he said a new
cycle of harvesting in the county could mean some would be rehired.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $10 million for local assistance is coming from
the U.S. Department of Interior, which makes a visit by a prominent
federal official likely. Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., a major negotiator in the deal for the
government to buy the land, have yet to visit the new park.
</P>
<P>
   After handing over an enormous mock check, Davis drove to the
reserve, which is about 20 minutes to the south.
</P>
<P>
   As he was speaking to reporters under the trees Wednesday, Davis
noted that one tree probably was 1,000 years old. Another bore blue
markings, signaling it had been destined to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you're fighting for the redwoods, you're doing
the right thing, but you don't have an emotional investment in the
transaction until you come here to see what you are a small part of
saving,'' Davis said. ``This is just spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of curious hikers already have entered the Headwaters
Forest Reserve since the land was transferred from Pacific Lumber
to the government March 1. Hikers can enter the area through a
narrow, 5-mile trail to the north of the park _ the spout of a
public forest area that resembles a teapot on a map.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal environmental officials fear that visitors to
the new Headwaters park will trample important forest cover. The
area is home to the endangered marbled murrelet, a seabird, and the
point of buying the forest was to help save endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   There likely will be no campgrounds or visitor center or tramway
or revolving restaurant on a hill. Just a simple sign, a marked
trail or two, and a gravel parking lot at the entrance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
