<HEADLINE>
DELL SHARES ACCOUNT OF HOW INDUSTRY POWERHOUSE WAS BUILT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people think of Michael Dell as a wunderkind of the
personal computer business.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp., launched from a dorm room at the University
of Texas in 1983, has grown into a powerhouse that generates $18
billion in annual revenues by selling built-to-order PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Dell stock has risen faster than that of any
other publicly traded company during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   What most people are just beginning to realize, though, is that
Michael Dell may well have been the Internet's first entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   By selling PCs to people calling in on the telephone, Dell spent
more than a decade building the quick-response infrastructure
needed to succeed in the emerging world of online selling. Already,
the Dell Web site at www.dell.com generates $12 million in sales
every day. In time, the company expects the Web to account for more
than half of its overall sales.
</P>
<P>
   Such figures start to make perfect sense as you read ``Direct
from Dell'' (Harper Business, $26, 236 pages), a new book penned by
Dell and writer Catherine Fredman.
</P>
<P>
   Dell has crafted an American version of the just-in-time
inventory principles long popularized by Japanese manufacturers.
The secret to Dell's success is that it doesn't start building a
computer until a customer orders it. At the same time, the company
tries to minimize the inventory of parts on hand, maintaining a
rolling parts supply that leaves it holding computer building
blocks in inventory for days or, in some cases, just hours.
</P>
<P>
   That's a crucial advantage in the computer industry, where
technical advances can make old computers as hard to sell as wilted
lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Dell sells suppliers on just-in-time inventory by promising to
buy more products overall if suppliers will deliver daily or even
hourly.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Dell is emerging as the ultimate broker of
marketplace information, streamlining communications between
customers and suppliers. As the Internet emerges as a widely used
tool, that flow of information is almost sure to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using the Internet to maintain a continuous flow of matters
from our suppliers into our factories,'' Michael Dell writes, ``our
people spend less time (to) place orders or expediting parts and
more time adding value.''
</P>
<P>
   But his book is more than a missive on electronic commerce. It
is two very different books in one. The first half is a chatty,
informative, easy-to-read account of how Dell launched and manages
his company.
</P>
<P>
   Interwoven are anecdotal nuggets that provide useful lessons for
businesspeople in any field. Stories highlighting the need for
listening to customers, prioritizing goals, focusing on data and
recruiting employees make this a useful primer for individuals in
small and midsize businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Dell's approach to separating data from
emotion in making business decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come across data that are strikingly different from
what you previously thought, how long does it take for you to shift
your thinking? Do you deny the data and say, `Well, I don't believe
this,' '' Dell asks. ``The longer it takes to accept new data, the
more you're relying on your emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the book, though is more typical of tomes
written by high-profile corporate chief executives. In that
portion, Dell moves more into the mode of preaching on more
nebulous conepts such as ``Expand Your Range of Vision'' and ``Turn
Your Customers Into Teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   The book still weaves some of his personal experience into the
narrative and can be instructive; it's just not as relevant to most
day-to-day business operators as the advice in the first half of
the book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding and Keeping Great Employees''
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Harris and Joan Brannick
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Hiring and maintaining good employees is possibly the greatest
challenge of business managers. Yet most companies have roadblocks
in hiring and retention policies that keep many good people from
applying, or, if hired, from staying. Jim Harris and Joan Brannick,
Ph.D.s with a consulting business on human resources, discuss the
trends in this important area.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Global Jumpstart: The Complete Resource for Expanding Small
and Midsize Businesses''
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth Stanat and Chris West
</P>
<P>
   Perseus Books, $25
</P>
<P>
   The authors, both international market researchers, describe
their book as a primer for smaller firms to ``develop a global
mind-set.'' They also offer interesting case studies illustrating
how smaller companies are ``going global.'' Topics include global
research, selling, exporting and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Close the Deal: Smart Moves for Selling''
</P>
<P>
   By Sam Deep and Lyle Sussman
</P>
<P>
   Perseus Books, $13
</P>
<P>
   Written by a motivational speaker, trainer and consultant, Sam
Deep, and a professor of management at the University of
Louisville, Lyle Sussman, this book helps you devise a selling
``system,'' and then shows you how to stick with it, ultimately
controlling the sale. The book has little narrative, but rather
presents tips, ideas, suggestions and other nuggets of information.
The format is based on two successful previous ``Smart Move'' books
by the authors.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1609EST &QL; 
