<HEADLINE>
HISTORY SHOWS OSCAR IS A STATUETTE OF LIMITATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oscars are some big deal. In Hollywood, a festival
atmosphere spins around Oscar night, rather like Derby week in
Louisville or the Super Bowl wherever it's played.
</P>
<P>
   National interest in the Oscars, which unfold Sunday on ABC, has
been ever more frenzied since 1953, when the overdressed ceremony
became a network television event. But what does it all mean? Not
much.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, copping the coveted statuette may strengthen or revive a
career, but many of the major Academy Award conquests, perhaps
most, have been invalidated by the judgment of history.
</P>
<P>
   Consider cinematography, for example. Some years ago, the
cinematography award went to Robert Redford's fine ``A River Runs
Through It,'' which was fine for reasons other than cinematography.
It was poorly photographed. The key to good cinematography is
lighting, and all of the outdoor fly-fishing scenes were too dark.
The scenery was lovely, and that's what members voted on. Year
after year, they confuse cinematography with art direction.
</P>
<P>
   In the acting awards, prejudice and sentiment are traditional
voting tools. Chicanery and intimidation also are heard from. Let's
go all the way back to the second edition in 1929, when Mary
Pickford captured the award (not yet named Oscar) for her first
talking screen appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The academy then was a small and exclusive society, with
membership by invitation, and only board members voted for the
awards. Pickford's win was assured when she invited the whole board
to her Pickfair estate for high tea. Ruth Chatterton probably
should have won for ``Madame X,'' or perhaps the late Jeanne Eagels
for the first screen version of ``The Letter.'' Pickford certainly
shouldn't have won for her insecure performance in ``Coquette.''
The miniscandal had the effect of opening up the academy and giving
everyone the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1930s and '40s, the Oscars gained stature and
respect, despite occasional acts of robbery precipitated by studio
strong-arming. There were, of course, the deferred payoffs, this
actor or that actress winning an Oscar because he or she missed out
the year before, thus recycling injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying the worst of all Oscar calls may be almost as
difficult as trying to determine the worst movie ever made. But
there is wholesale agreement among film scholars that two
performance nods are forever tainted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Harold Russell, having lost both hands in World War II,
played a returning handless veteran in William Wyler's ``The Best
Years of Our Lives.'' He was voted best supporting actor, although
his was the only amateurish performance in a beautifully acted
film. It deprived the great Claude Rains (four times nominated, no
wins) of an Oscar for the keenest sympathetic-villain account of
all time in Alfred Hitchcock's ``Notorious.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for sentiment. How about prejudice?
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Grace Kelly was named Best Actress for a downright poor
performance in ``The Country Girl.'' But Grace Kelly was the new
girl in town, and here she was cast against type, deglamorized; and
Judy Garland was a shopworn commodity, whose virtuoso turn in ``A
Star Is Born'' is a wonder to behold _ a marvel of acting, even if
she hadn't sung a note.
</P>
<P>
   History affirms too many miscarriages of Academy Award justice
than may be recorded here, but let's have a go:
</P>
<P>
   1933: Katharine Hepburn was new and hot, so they gave her the
award for ``Morning Glory,'' her third picture, at the expense of
grand old May Robson, whose glorious Apple Annie in ``Lady for a
Day'' launched director Frank Capra on his string of box-office
smashes. Ironically, Hepburn would lose favor and be denied two or
three Oscars she should have won, long before the academy made
amends by giving her four Best Actress plums.
</P>
<P>
   1935: ``Mutiny on the Bounty'' was a huge MGM moneymaker but not
near the artistic quality of John Ford's ``The Informer'' from RKO,
a studio that had little clout at Oscar time. The Selznick-Cukor
``David Copperfield'' also was (and is) far superior to ``Mutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   1936: MGM's ``The Great Ziegfeld'' is an absolute monstrosity;
there may have been 50 better movies that year. For starters,
consider ``Dodsworth,'' with the superb performance of Walter
Huston, who should have had the award won by Paul Muni for ``The
Story of Louis Pasteur.''
</P>
<P>
   1940: ``Rebecca'' was David Selznick's ``GWTW'' encore, and
Hitchcock's first American-made movie. It's still wonderful, but
Ford's ``The Grapes of Wrath'' was a level above, surely the finest
screen adaptation of a major American novel.
</P>
<P>
   1941: But if Ford was robbed twice previously, the Hearst press
helped make him Best Director and ``How Green Was My Valley'' Best
Picture. It's an honorable achievement, but Orson Welles' ``Citizen
Kane'' is the consensus choice as greatest film never to win the
top Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   1944: The moviegoing public made Leo McCarey's ``Going My Way''
popular, and its Best Picture win came as no surprise. But several
other films, not all of them nominated, were much better _ ``Meet
Me in St. Louis,'' ``Double Indemnity,'' ``Laura,'' perhaps even
``Wilson.'' Taking the Best Picture prize for ``Gentleman's
Agreement'' in 1947, producer Darryl Zanuck saw fit to rebuke the
academy for having passed over ``Wilson'' three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   1950: ``All About Eve'' triumphed. If the voting were held
today, Billy Wilder's ``Sunset Boulevard'' would win easily, and
its stars _ William Holden and Gloria Swanson _ would take the
acting honors that went to Jose Ferrer and Judy Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   1952: ``The Greatest Show on Earth'' as Best Picture? You've got
to be kidding. Finally, they just had to give Cecil B. DeMille an
Oscar. But what about ``The Quiet Man?''
</P>
<P>
   1956: Welcome back, Ingrid Bergman, all is forgiven. So they
gave her the Oscar for ``Anastasia.'' But check out Katharine
Hepburn's cunning in ``The Rainmaker,'' amazingly lifting Burt
Lancaster to her own level.
</P>
<P>
   1962: As a kind of valediction, Gregory Peck is anointed Best
Actor for ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' a role remarkably short in
footage. It pales beside Jack Lemmon's in ``Days of Wine and
Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   1968: Cliff Robertson supposedly ``bought'' the Oscar with an
expensive promotion campaign. His ``Charly'' actually is as worthy
as any of the nominated male performances. The best job _ Charlton
Heston's ``Will Penny'' _ didn't secure a nomination.
</P>
<P>
   1985 and 1991: After a stretch of almost two decades for which
most film and performance arguments are merely academic, the
academy shows its flagrant lack of integrity by giving supporting
performance Oscars to Don Ameche and Jack Palance for ordinary
work, because they endured and came back. Some say this may happen
again, if James Coburn wins for ``Affliction.'' But who's to say he
won't deserve it?
</P>
<P>
   1990: Kathy Bates' villain role in ``Misery'' is the obvious
stuff Oscars are made of. Joanne Woodward's beleaguered wife-mother
in ``Mr. and Mrs. Bridge'' is more demanding and more creative.
</P>
<P>
   Oscars of the '90s, though, are too close for historical
evaluations. There surely have been some wrong calls, and more will
come. Still, watch the telecast and enjoy it. Just understand, the
Oscars aren't really so meaningful in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
