<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLDIER WHO REFUSED ANTHRAX VACCINE AWAITS COURT-MARTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A defiant Fort Sam Houston soldier who is refusing
an anthrax vaccination has been demoted and faces a court-martial
for not following orders.
</P>
<P>
   Army Spc. Robert Garner Jr. is charged with refusing to follow
an order requiring that he take the first of six inoculations for
anthrax, a highly lethal biological agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that it is an immoral order,'' Garner said Wednesday.
``I don't think anyone should be able to tell me that I have to
take something like that into my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Garner, 23, is among nearly 100 Americans in uniform who have
refused to take the vaccine. He was told to take the shot because
he was scheduled to be transferred to South Korea, said Phil
Reidinger, a spokesman at Fort Sam Houston in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly can refuse to obey the order, but he will pay the
consequences,'' Reidinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Garner was demoted from sergeant for disobeying an order and
faces a court-martial on March 25.
</P>
<P>
   Garner and others contend that the vaccine poses threats to
their health, including the possibility it might trigger Gulf War
Syndrome. That mysterious ailment has struck thousands who helped
drive Saddam Hussein's troops from Kuwait in 1991. More than
150,000 American troops in that conflict received the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon says there is no link between the vaccine and the
syndrome, and insists there is nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 218,965 soldiers, airmen, sailors and Marines have
received the inoculations, with only one serious reaction requiring
hospitalization, Defense Department spokesman Jim Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine is not 100 percent effective. But the government
will spend $130 million over six years on the vaccine, rather than
risk exposing troops to invisible airborne anthrax spores that
can't be detected until victims develop pneumonia symptoms and face
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an incredibly successful program, and it's something
that we need to do to respond to a real threat,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and Army medical authorities point to the vaccine's
relatively mild side-effects, among them brief periods of soreness,
chills and fever, as proof of its safety.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen has taken the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   But Garner isn't convinced, and he isn't alone. Twenty-three
sailors aboard the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt recently
refused to take anthrax shots, and nine Connecticut Air National
Guard pilots quit rather than roll up their sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Garner said there was no scientific evidence the vaccine would
protect troops against airborne anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration, which has licensed the vaccine
since 1970, tests samples of all vaccine lots, as does the
manufacturer, BioPort Corp. of Lansing, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   A third, independent company performs additional tests to ensure
potency and safety, said Cynthia Vaughan, a spokeswoman with the
U.S. Army Medical Command headquartered at Fort Sam Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Educated consumers are important but this is not comparable to
counting calories,'' Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   Garner said he was ready to face trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me you've got to stand for what you believe in or you're
not much of a man,'' he said. ``And to me this is what it's all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
