<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ Peace talks on Kosovo concluded Thursday
night with representatives of the ethnic Albanian majority in the
province signing an agreement on autonomy that was worked out by
international mediators, but Serbian authorities still refusing to
accept it. That left France and Britain, who are leading the talks,
with little choice but to declare the negotiations over, since most
of the Albanians plan to leave Friday. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LOANS (Washington) _ Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin
told a congressional panel that he suspected that much of the $4.8
billion in loans sent to Russia last summer by the International
Monetary Fund ``may have been siphoned off improperly.'' Rubin's
comments marked the first public confirmation by the Clinton
administration that much of the bailout money the Treasury
organized last year simply helped wealthy Russian oligarchs move
billions of dollars to Switzerland and other safe havens. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
