<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAVENOUS-FILM-REVIEW-     03-18 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVENOUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RAVENOUS': HIS FAVORITE DESSERT? WHY IT'S LADY FINGERS! 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's anything worse than a cannibal movie, it's an
undead-cannibal movie with pretensions about Manifest Destiny in
the American West. And the problems with Antonia Bird's
``Ravenous'' don't end there.
</P>
<P>
   Buried beneath laughable fake facial hair and frequently awash
in gurgling blood, a potentially strong cast makes its way in
deadly earnest through material that's often better suited to a
Monty Python skit. The result is better appreciated as a 110-minute
diet aid than as a film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravenous'' begins as a Donner Pass tale of expedient human
recycling, but that's just the kid stuff. Things soon turn even
weirder at the remote outpost in the Sierra Nevada mountains, where
the story is set. (These scenic vistas look authentic despite the
fact that the film was shot in the Czech Republic, Slovakia and
Mexico.)
</P>
<P>
   In this rugged setting, Captain John Boyd (Guy Pearce of ``L.A.
Confidential'') finds himself marooned amid a pack of hirsute
oddballs. Oddest of all is wild-eyed, bushy-bearded Colqhoun
(Robert Carlyle of ``The Full Monty''), who escapes from the
snowbound wilderness looking not nearly as hungry as he should be.
</P>
<P>
   The film could have ended happily with the moment where Colqhoun
is asked just why starvation hasn't made him skinnier. He explains,
with a meaningful look, that the absence of food in the woods
doesn't necessarily mean he hasn't (italics)eaten.(end italics) The
details are left to the imagination for a while, but the culinary
fate of Colqhoun's traveling companions is eventually revealed in
all its oozing, dripping glory.
</P>
<P>
   So is the fact that Colqhoun actually advocates the health
benefits of a human diet. ``I ate five men in three months,'' he
acknowledges. ``Tuberculosis: vanished!''
</P>
<P>
   Having Colqhoun in residence at the military outpost soon
creates problems. For instance, there is a middle-of-the-night
licking incident that frightens another soldier (Jeremy Davies of
``Saving Private Ryan''), even though Colqhoun claims he was merely
having a bad dream.
</P>
<P>
   After this, it begins to be clear that Colqhoun is not the
innocent cannibal that he claimed to be. By the time the movie is
an hour old it features audible baying at the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The story's eat-or-be-eaten tension yields a lot more vicious
fighting than might be expected from a small cast, since cannibals
can dodge death like vampires and still come back for more. The
icing on the cake is the large bear trap featured in the climactic
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is also time for leaden sardonic touches, as
when Carlyle's character presides over a bubbling stew pot to the
tune of ``There's No Place Like Home.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, while chopping up the remains of somebody else in
the cast, Carlyle, an otherwise irresistible actor who has made
three other films with Ms. Bird, has the chance to explain what all
this has to do with the devouring of the frontier. With metaphors
like that, the film doesn't need enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravenous'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). Stomach-turning violence is on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `RAVENOUS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Antonia Bird; written by Ted Griffin; director of
photography, Anthony B. Richmond; edited by Neil Farrell; music by
Michael Nyman and Damon Albarn; production designer, Bryce Perrin;
produced by Adam Fields and David Heyman; released by Fox 2000
Pictures. Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Guy Pearce (Boyd), Robert Carlyle (Colqhoun/Ives), David
Arquette (Cleaves), Jeremy Davies (Toffler), Jeffrey Jones (Hart),
John Spencer (General Slauson), Stephen Spinella (Knox) and Neal
McDonough (Reich).
</P>
</TEXT>
