A5453 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      03-18 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SUES GUN MAKER CLAIMING WEAPON WAS FAULTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A Texas man is suing the California manufacturer
of his derringer because the .22-caliber pistol put a bullet in his
backside when it fell from the wheelchair he was using at a
veterans hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed Monday in San Antonio federal court, Robert
Curtis accuses Chino, Calif.-based Davis Industries of
manufacturing a faulty weapon that could discharge unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Davis General Manager Aaron Davis said the company's product is
safe when used properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half-cocked and the safety on, there's no way the gun's going
off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit states Curtis was in a wheelchair at the Veterans
Affairs Hospital in Kerrville when a pouch carrying the pistol
dropped from his waist onto the floor. The gun fired and the
bullet, the lawsuit says, hit him in the buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hall, a lawyer representing Curtis, said the bullet remains
lodged near his client's spine two years after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, Hall said, is a licensed peace officer who was at the
hospital for treatment related to an automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Veterans Affairs spokesman said Curtis was
off-duty and in the cafeteria when the gun, which was forbidden in
the facility, fired.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Nick Villanueva, said Curtis was treated and
released four days later.
</P>
<P>
   Metal fatigue was part of the pistol's problem, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety mechanism had fractured inside the gun,'' he said.
``When the gun hit the floor, it went off.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar complaint was made against the company in 1997 by a
San Antonio man who claimed he was shot in the leg when his
Davis-made .32-caliber derringer fell from his back pocket as he
removed a handkerchief, hit the floor and fired.
</P>
<P>
   That dispute ended in an undisclosed cash settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, which once advertised its products as ``affordable
personal protection,'' was one of nine gun makers cleared by a
federal jury in New York last month of negligently marketing guns
used in several shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen other companies were found negligent in the same case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
