<SLUG> BC-ROOK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ROOK': A MURDER INVESTIGATION IN A PAST FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first scene of ``The Rook,'' Martin Donovan, dressed like
a character from a Henry James novel (one of his best looks), rides
into town in a mule-driven carriage. Then he photographs a dead
body with what looks like a very modern mini-camera.
</P>
<P>
   The police chief he has come to see wears something resembling
20th-century Chinese fashion and a coat with a bulky fur collar. He
offers his guest ``Tea? Water? Lemon soda?'' Telephones ring like
old alarm clocks, and offices have electric desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rook,'' whose structure is a murder investigation, has an
intriguing look, a bit like that of the 1984 film version of
``1984.'' It is set in some misconceived future (like the 19th
century, the filmmakers suggest, as it might have been imagined by
someone living in the 16th), and seems to hint at a drastically
different society, one that could, like ``1984'' or ``A Handmaid's
Tale'' (the book, anyway), enlighten us about our own.
</P>
<P>
   But the film never comes through with the information _ any
information _ so the experience of this generally soporific
84-minute film is that of being teased and abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, John Abbott, the detective played by Donovan,
reflects on some group of people, possibly the revolutionists who
have just taken the town he lives in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you realize they've distanced themselves from the church?''
he says. ``They don't even believe in the tempting. The spiritual
reunion.'' This is the most detailed description we hear of the
dominant religion of this time and place.
</P>
<P>
   We also never know who the revolutionists are, what the
revolution is about or where (some imaginary country?) all this
takes place. (Greenwich, where Abbott lives, is apparently not far
from the town of Sutheridge, where the film takes place. And the
murder victim is from Carmel, but something tells me that's not in
northern California anymore.) OK, it's an allegory, but of what
idea(s)? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rook'' was directed by Eran Palatnik, who had previously
done commercials and industrial films. It was written by Richard
Lee Purvis, a first-time screenwriter, and reportedly filmed in 18
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rook'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It contains some strong language, partial
nudity and considerable violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTON NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE ROOK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Eran Palatnik; written by Richard Lee Purvis;
director of photography, Zack Winestine; music by Robert Een;
production designer, Sebastian Schroeder; produced by Palatnik and
Alan J. Abrams; released by Phaedra Cinema. Running time: 84
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Martin Donovan (John Abbott), John A. MacKay (Bob Brice),
Michael Finesilver (Donald Heller), Sean Clark (Fritz Fox),
Harrison Baker (David P. Dawson) and Diane Grotke (Dr. Abby
Trent). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
