<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSISI-EXHIBIT-ART-12     03-18 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSISI-EXHIBIT-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHES FOR A SAINT WHO SCORNED THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The curving road from the Umbrian plains up to the
Basilica of St. Francis in Assisi has been a pilgrim's path for 700
years. In spring, the air is pasture-sweet; in winter, the cold can
be stinging. Francis himself, native son and a man inclined to
joyousness, took pleasure in both seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The great basilica, set on its aqueductlike arches, was begun
soon after his death in 1226 and houses many beauties. The first
flower of a radical new Italian art is here in frescoes by Giotto
and Cimabue. The church treasury is a gold mine of medieval
metalwork and textiles.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder collective hearts skipped a beat when word came in
September 1997 that Assisi had been hit by an earthquake and the
basilica had been damaged, with portions of the painted ceiling of
the upper church reduced to rubble. Plans to finish restoration by
the year 2000 seem to be on track. (The church is scheduled to
reopen at Christmas.) But with much of central Italy still in
recovery from the disaster, government money for rebuilding is
spread thin.
</P>
<P>
   To draw attention to the the situation in Assisi as well as to
showcase a remarkable body of art that was temporarily out of
public view, the Metropolitan Museum collaborated with Italian
cultural agencies and the Vatican to organize ``The Treasury of St.
Francis of Assisi,'' an exhibition of some 70 objects from the
church's holdings, supplemented by 30 related works from other
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Like many ``treasures'' shows, this one is an extravagant
hodgepodge of splendors, embracing illuminated manuscripts produced
in royal scriptoria, exquisite 13th-century paintings and
reliquaries that suggest the fanciful, miniaturist intricacy of
doll houses.
</P>
<P>
   And they are all united by a paradox. They were gifts to the
basilica from the high and mighty of Europe to honor a man who
despised wealth and learning, who wanted to be buried in a pauper's
grave and who lived a life of unconditional, evangelical poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Francis was born at Assisi in 1181 or 1182 to a wealthy merchant
family. A spoiled child, he was a cutup with an eye for fashion and
a taste for pop music, which at the time meant the courtly songs,
idealistic and erotic, of the medieval French troubadours. He soon
dropped out of school, skipped church on Sunday and shrugged off
the prospect of entering the family business.
</P>
<P>
   But after a stint in the army and a long illness, he changed.
One day he stopped on the road and exchanged clothes with a beggar;
next he kissed a leper who was asking only for a handout. At first,
everyone assumed he was just going through a phase, then they
started to view him as a kook.
</P>
<P>
   Their suspicions were confirmed when, without asking permission,
he sold cloth from his father's warehouse to pay for the repair of
a decrepit church, pitching in on the fix-up work himself. He
explained that a voice coming from a crucifix had urged him to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Hauled before a bishop, Francis was ordered to restore what he'd
taken. Instead, he stripped off his clothes and handed them over,
the last remnants of an old life. Thereafter he wore a tunic of
rough brown cloth. He said he liked brown because it was the color
of earth, and some historians have seen his attire as a gesture of
solidarity with a humble peasantry. It was certainly a signal, one
made by the Buddha in India centuries earlier, that doing without
had been elevated to an existential option.
</P>
<P>
   From this point on, Francis' all-or-nothing passions only
intensified. For a while he was fixated on martyrdom and traveled
to Egypt to find it. But the Muslims he encountered knew a saint
when they saw one and received him with cordial respect.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy he founded a religious order but refused to be
consecrated as a priest. A figure of stature in church politics, he
was also a performance artist of enormous charm. (He gave his
itinerant monks a rock-group name, the Jesters of God.) He spurned
books but was an innovative poet: his ecstatic Canticle of the Sun,
inspired by the troubadour songs of his youth, is among the
earliest works in the Italian vernacular. And although he is often
thought of as being fey and not quite all there, he was an
insistent realist who operated on the interesting idea that
everyday life, seen with eyes unclouded by desire and the fears it
produces, is a visionary state. Like the Buddha, he experienced
nature as an extended family in which mutual support, loving
discipline and good manners were the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   What he could not do was care for himself, and heedlessness took
its toll. He died in his mid-40s, lying, as he wished, on the bare
ground. He asked to be buried in a cemetery set aside for criminals
but ended up in the basilica that bears his name. Conceived as a
kind of Franciscan theme park, it was intended to be the largest
Italian pilgrimage site outside of Rome and a magnet both for
ordinary folk and for the secular and ecclesiastical royalty of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Monarchical largesse is the central theme of ``The Treasury of
St. Francis of Assisi,'' organized by Laurence B. Kanter, curator
of the Robert Lehman Collection at the Met, and Pia Palladino, a
research associate. And it is instantly apparent in a monumental
Flemish tapestry hanging directly across from the entrance to the
Lehman wing.
</P>
<P>
   Donated to the basilica in the 15th century by Pope Sixtus IV,
its elaborate pattern takes the form of a family tree tracing a
direct blood line among the pope, St. Francis and the Virgin and
Child in heaven. And self-advertising continues on an embroidered
altar cloth installed in the Lehman wing's lower galleries.
Designed by the painter Antonio Pollaiuolo, it shows Sixtus and
Francis as equals. The saint stands and the pontiff kneels, but
they're almost exactly the same height.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular royal commissions are on display nearby. One of them
is the 13th-century gilded silver Reliquary of the Seamless Robe, a
tabernacle-style triptych with arches and spires and an exquisite
nativity scene rendered in low relief on its back.
</P>
<P>
   Another is a missal thought to have been donated by Louis IX of
France, who had been educated by Franciscan friars in Paris and who
was canonized as a saint in 1297. The book is open to a Crucifixion
painted in royal blue and gold, and its figures, with their thin
necks and large nodding heads, are as slender and elegant as
fiddlehead ferns.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a show-stopper, though, it's the chalice made around
1290 by the Sienese goldsmith Guccio di Mannaia for Pope Nicolas
IV. One of the finest surviving examples of Gothic metal casting,
its stem and base are covered with raised leaf and ribbon motifs
and studded with 80 enamel plaques depicting saints, angels,
biblical scenes and the inevitable papal portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Francis is included in this VIP gallery, but one gets a far more
vivid sense of his spirit in the paintings on view. He appears, for
example, dressed in his familiar brown tunic in an altarpiece
attributed to the so-called Master of St. Francis, the artist who
painted the earliest frescoes of the saint's life at Assisi.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those frescoes vanished long ago, and the altarpiece,
reassembled for the show from panels in various museum collections,
is fragmentary. But there is no question that its style _ a
softening of Byzantine formality with a fresh, funky naturalism,
evident in the saint's plump white hands and pensive face _ has a
distinctly personable, Franciscan feel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And Francis takes center stage in the renowned panel by the
artist known as the Master of the Treasury. Here he is typecast as
an unsmiling Byzantine saint, but he is framed by four lively
illustrations of miracles said to have occurred soon after his
death. In one scene, a possessed woman thrashes spasmodically as a
demon flies from her mouth; in another, a crippled man regains the
use of his legs after touching the saint's tomb.
</P>
<P>
   If this work was executed in the second third of the 13th
century, as the show's catalog proposes, one can assume it had a
sense of personal immediacy for its early viewers, some of whom had
probably known Francis. And because the painting's wood panel was
reputed to have been used in preparing the saint's body for burial,
the work itself qualifies as a relic, still radiant with his
energy.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be too far-fetched to view many of the objects from
the Assisi treasury as similarly, if less directly, animated by his
presence. The altar vessels and embroideries are emblematic of a
material magnificence that he rejected. But the impulse to give
tangible form to the ineffable that they represent, so vital to
popular religion, is something he understood well.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, at the outset of his own brilliant, earthshaking
career, he listened to an image that spoke to him and, at the risk
of name and fortune, set about repairing a ruined church. That
church, San Damiano, still stands near Assisi. And one likes to
think that Francis' handyman skills and restorative zeal are at
work today in the hilltop basilica that bears his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
