<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-18 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIALOGUE BETWEEN EAST AND WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Western rationalism versus Eastern mysticism is the theme of
``The Monk and the Philosopher,'' a dialogue between
representatives of each side of that great divide who happen to be
father and son. The father and the philosopher is Jean-Francois
Revel, a leading political commentator in France. His earlier
books, most notably ``The Totalitarian Temptation'' and ``How
Democracies Perish,'' were important documents of the Cold War,
stirring affirmations of liberal-democratic values when, in Revel's
view, they were being undermined by self-doubt, guilt and utopian
illusions in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Matthieu Ricard, born in 1946, is Revel's son. (Their surnames
are different because Revel is a pseudonym.) He has a doctorate in
molecular biology, but rejected a career in science (``an endless
dispersion into detail,'' he says, that is unable to ``solve the
fundamental questions of life'') to become a Buddhist monk. He
lives in Nepal, occasionally serves as a translator for the Dalai
Lama, whom he reveres, and translates Tibetan manuscripts into
French and English.
</P>
<P>
   Ricard, not surprisingly, is a fervent believer in what he
regards as the Buddhist ``science of the mind,'' the mastery of
``the absolute truth,'' which he sees as a more fundamental and
profound salvation for humankind than anything that Western
rationality can offer. But Ricard, with his deep knowledge of
science and European thought, can argue his points from within the
Western tradition, and that is what gives this conversation its
special promise.
</P>
<P>
   In places the promise is realized. One reads these often
difficult dialogues with an appreciation for the seriousness and
intellectual depth of both participants. Revel is a gently
skeptical prober of his son's beliefs, for example, pressing him to
defend and refine points he makes on reincarnation. Ricard has a
broad knowledge of his subject, which he explains in often
trenchant, metaphorical fashion. He says reincarnation is not
simply the phenomenon of being born over and over, as many assume
it to be, but has more to do with the transmission of a stream of
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Different readers will come to different conclusions after
finishing this book. I ended up agreeing with Revel, who concludes,
``I have become more and more appreciative of Buddhism as a system
of wisdom, and more and more skeptical about it as a system of
metaphysics.''
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, Revel is unable to accept, say, reincarnation
merely on Ricard's say-so, and Ricard's ultimate argument is that
if you haven't spent years in meditation, the only path to the
absolute truth, it will be impossible for you to understand the
world as he has come to know it.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from the question of agreement with either the
philosopher or the monk, too often both seem to talk past each
other, issuing careful, politely crafted statements of position
that are not responsive to what was said just before. Revel at
times seems unwilling to press the rationalist case, and he does
not ask what seem to be the obvious questions at critical points.
Ricard is rather repetitive in his arguments, returning again and
again to the same few points as if simple reiteration will make
matters clear.
</P>
<P>
   Most interesting would be a far greater sense of Ricard's
experience, a description of his trajectory from Western
rationality to Eastern wisdom. He does sketch in his experience
early on, but very briefly. He tends to explain Buddhism in
scholarly and abstract terms when one really wants to know what it
was like to meditate in a hut for years. What does enlightenment
feel like?
</P>
<P>
   ``For anyone who's attained the omniscience of Buddhahood,
there's no longer any discrepancy between the ultimate nature of
things and the way they appear,'' Ricard says. ``The perception of
apparent phenomena continues, but the perception's no longer
distorted by the ignorance of taking such phenomena as entities
that have some intrinsic existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Here Ricard is trying to explain the concept of ``emptiness''
and how it differs from nothingness, which in turn is related to
the Buddhist concept of the illusory nature of the apparent world.
</P>
<P>
   Revel accuses him of playing with words, and one tends to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an absolute point of view, the world doesn't have any
real or concrete existence,'' Ricard says a little later. ``So the
relative aspect is the phenomenal world and the absolute aspect is
emptiness.'' If you understand that statement, you probably don't
need to read this book.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that one fails to appreciate the courage and
power of Ricard's spiritual search. His main point has to do with
the belief in the self, in solid, individual identities as the
source of all ignorance and therefore all suffering. ``Buddhism
recommends a very detailed investigation of the notion of ego,''
Ricard says early on.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat later: ``What we want to abolish is the illusion, the
mistake that has no inherent existence in the first place.'' No
doubt that fundamental notion, the dissolution of selfishness and
the acquisition of a tranquil kindness, is what has given Buddhism
its growing appeal in the West. Ricard speaks of it eloquently.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, another element in this picture is strangely missing,
and that is the sense of a personal relationship between this
father and son. There is some cursory acknowledgment of their
relationship early on in ``The Monk and the Philosopher,'' but then
that theme is dropped in favor of an exchange that could have
occurred between two strangers at some ecumenical conference.
</P>
<P>
   After all, here we have a son who, in adopting Tibetan monks as
his teachers, rejected the very rational system that his father
famously embodies. The Oedipal theme practically screams out.
</P>
<P>
   That neither the monk nor the philosopher seems to hear it comes
across as a concealment carefully maintained in a conversation that
supposedly addresses the deeper meanings of things, or, as Ricard
puts it, the absolute truth.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE MONK AND THE PHILOSOPHER'
</P>
<P>
   A Father and Son Discuss the Meaning of Life
</P>
<P>
   By Jean-Francois Revel and Matthieu Ricard
</P>
<P>
   Translated by John Canti. 311 pages. Schocken Books. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
