<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Old Wabbit is Wehabilitated
</P>
<P>
   It still makes one of the better cartoon standoffs. The year is
1936 and in Tom Palmer's animated short Cupid is doing his best to
bury arrows into the obstinate W.C. Fields and an equally irascible
woman with whom, or so Cupid supposes, Fields might make a match.
</P>
<P>
   A tall assignment. Using trash-can lids as shields, the cartoon
Fields battles back with everything he can lay his hands on. In the
end its takes a firing squad of small Cupids dressed as Canadian
Mounties to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the suddenly smitten Fields and his now rapturous
``little chickadee'' will gambol in the restored ``Cupid Gets His
Man,'' one of 15 animated features on a video called ``Cartoon
Crazys Sci-Fi,'' to be released by Winstar.
</P>
<P>
   Together with two other animated collections, ``Cartoon Crazys
Kids All-Time Favorites'' and ``Superman: The Lost Episodes,'' the
video joins a large-scale cartoon reclamation project under way at
Audio Galaxy, a production company based in the Universal Studios
complex in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of cartoons from the 30s and 40s, many of them in
tatters, have been rescued from dusty places. Pieced back together
and sent to England for a special bath, they look clean and fresh
on tape and especially on digital video disk.
</P>
<P>
   One Audio Galaxy collection, ``Max Fleischer's Superman,'' drawn
from the original series that ended in 1942, has been a best seller
on tape and disk for several months. With the three titles to be
released on Tuesday, 14 hours of vintage cartoons are on tape.
</P>
<P>
   The DVDs, which usually are issued shortly after the cassettes,
include much extra material, from plot synopses to histories of the
films and recommended reading lists.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these cartoons were made by the studios to run in
theaters before feature films. ``Bugs Bunny and Elmer Fudd: The
Wabbit Who Came to Supper'' and ``Doggone Tired,'' both on
``Cartoon Crazys 2,'' are examples.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, a Fleischer cartoon cost $100,000 to produce, an
equivalent of several million dollars today. ``If they played
before an M-G-M film or other A-list feature, the studios wanted
them nice,'' said Tom Reich, director of the Cartoon Crazys series.
``They wanted a Popeye or a Disney, or they wanted adult-oriented
cartoons that were made in the 30s before censorship came in.''
</P>
<P>
   These would include the adventures of the sweetly sexy Betty
Boop. In ``House Cleaning Blues,'' another title in ``Cartoon
Crazys Sci-Fi,'' the miniskirted Betty laments having to clean up
after what must have been a very lively party. All the whisky
glasses and ashtrays bothered censors, as did Betty herself, who in
other films brought out the groper in some of her male
acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   In those times cartoons often were judged to be too violent,
though they were usually bucolic by present standards. An example
is ``To Spring,'' a fascinating contest between old man winter
howling from above and an underground army of elves all working
madly to pump spring colors and fragrance up through the soil.
</P>
<P>
   On the same tape, ``Cob Web Hotel'' features a spider that, as
spiders do, dismembers flies before dining. Critics dubbed it the
first snuff cartoon. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pleasantville
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the placid 50s scene he sees on reruns of his
favorite 50s show, a high school student named David (Tobey
Maguire, with Marley Shelton) and his unwilling, very 90s sister,
Jennifer (Reese Witherspoon), get sucked into that world through
their television set.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the tube, Dad (William H. Macy) yells the inevitable
``Honey, I'm home'' and Mom (Joan Allen) obligingly has those
artery clogging meals on the table at 6 sharp. Chafing at the
sterility, the liberated Jennifer shakes up the young set, and even
David sees the need to introduce change and passion.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasantvillers either go along or resist, but by then, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, an ingenious fantasy has
``seriously belabored its once-gentle metaphor and light comic
spirit.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $107.37. 123 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: March 23. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Joe Young
</P>
<P>
   After his mother is shot by hunters who want to pack him off to
a zoo, a baby gorilla called Joe escapes and grows tall in the
bush. That's 15 feet tall, a good height for theme park planners.
Cared for by a leggy blond naturalist named Jill (Charlize Theron),
Joe eventually gets flown to Los Angeles after a well-meaning
zoologist (Bill Paxton) convinces Jill that the gorilla would be
better off in a specially prepared natural habitat (or as natural
as it gets in Los Angeles).
</P>
<P>
   Joe, however, gets upset and goes on a mild rampage in a film
that ``is essentially `King Kong' for kids. Very young kids''
(Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. $24.99. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release date:
March 23. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Best Man
</P>
<P>
   To help her bourgeois father with his money problems, the
beautiful Francesca (Ines Sastre) agrees to marry a sleazy,
affluent older businessman (Dario Cantarelli) who can brighten the
financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   The year being 1899 and the place a small north Italian town,
the situation necessarily places restraints on the young woman, who
tries to leverage herself out of her intolerable predicament by
attaching herself to the best man (Diego Abatantuono).
</P>
<P>
   As it examines the bartering of ripe flesh for property, Pupi
Avati's film makes a ``fascinating, microscopically detailed
study'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $99.36. 101 minutes. Italian with English
subtitles. PG. Release date: March 23. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Living Out Loud
</P>
<P>
   Freshly divorced and desperately needing direction, Judith
(Holly Hunter) pours her heart out to everyone she meets. Soon she
is taken under the wing of a cabaret singer (Queen Latifah) who
helps change her life and a kindly doorman (Danny DeVito) who turns
out to be a kindred spirit. Richard LaGravenese's film gets too
ardently introspective at times, but Ms. Hunter imparts
``intelligence, thwarted passion and obvious depth of feeling''
(Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $105.77. 93 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER. The setting is 1990s St. Petersburg, but the feel is
30s gangster movie. Intent on getting his little piece of the pie,
a young hoodlum freshly discharged from the Russian Army joins his
brother, a contract killer, and plunges into intimidation and
murder in a city torn by gang warfare and rampant crime. In Aleksei
Balabanov's film, the mood is stark and the effect ``terrifically
stylish,'' Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times. 1997.
$79.95. 96 minutes. Russian with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   COMING HOME. In a miniseries drawn from a novel by the British
romance writer Rosamunde Pilcher, a young girl comes of age in
England before and after World War II. Emily Mortimer, Katie
Ryder-Richardson, Peter O'Toole and Joanna Lumley star. 1999. Four
cassettes. $59.95. 205 minutes. Information: (800) 999-0212.
</P>
<P>
   CARLA'S SONG. Ken Loach's film follows an unemployed Scottish
bus driver who gets a lesson in CIA-sponsored treachery and
atrocities when he accompanies his suicidal girlfriend to her
native Nicaragua during the time of the conflict between the
contras and the Sandinistas. 1998. Fox Lorber $89.95. 127 minutes.
No rating.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL MONETTE: THE BRINK OF SUMMER'S END. In Monte Bramer's
documentary, the gay activist and author of ``Borrowed Time: An
AIDS Memoir'' and ``Becoming a Man: Half a Life Story'' movingly
lives out his days (he died of AIDS four years ago). 1998. $39.95.
90 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
