<SLUG> BC-TRUE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE CRIME': EASTWOOD STARS IN A STORY OF SECOND CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``True Crime,'' Clint Eastwood makes his entrance perched on
a barstool, putting his codgerly moves on a 23-year-old blonde.
Flashing a silly grin, he looks worn and more than a little
ludicrous. That's the point, since Steve Everett, the veteran
newspaper reporter whom he plays, has a knack for the embarrassing
fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   His failures are both professional and personal. We next see him
courting both by sleeping with another blonde, the wife of his
editor, so flagrantly that the angry editor (Denis Leary) knows he
has to call his own house if he's looking to find Everett. This is
no way to land plum assignments, needless to say. Nor is it a way
for Everett to redeem all the past missteps that are indirectly
summoned by this film's title.
</P>
<P>
   In his most quietly poignant film since ``A Perfect World,''
Eastwood directs a death row thriller with redemption very much in
mind. It's about what happens when Steve's drinking companion is
killed in a car crash and he is hauled in to replace her on the
so-called human interest beat. She had been scheduled to talk to a
convicted murderer named Frank Beachum, played powerfully and
affectingly by Isaiah Washington, on the day of his scheduled
execution. Into the breach steps the jaded, sardonic Everett, who
isn't the type to play hero, but . . . well, you can take it from
here.
</P>
<P>
   In an involving thriller that takes on growing urgency as
Everett gets hooked by the Beachum case, Eastwood devotes as much
attention to rueful character study as he does to the crime story
at hand. The sources of Everett's cynicism are laid out carefully.
(``Great work, Steve,'' says James Woods as the top editor of the
Oakland newspaper for which Everett works, once Everett starts
suggesting Beachum may be innocent. ``Should we hold the front
page, or wait for two unnamed sources, or what?'')
</P>
<P>
   So is his way of exasperating anyone who deals with him. So is
the wreck he has made of his home life, with an apparently reckless
alcoholic past and a marriage (with Diane Venora as his wife) that
hangs together by a thread. ``If this were a bullet,'' she
eventually says, slamming down her wedding ring, ``you'd be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The one bright light in Everett's life is an adorable daughter
who brings out the best in him. (Though Eastwood is noticeably
older than the man he plays, there's no arguing with the
plausibility of his having such an enchanting young child. She is
his daughter, Francesca Fisher-Eastwood, which is perhaps why he
addresses her so fondly as ``Ya little goon.'') No less touching,
for either Everett or the audience, is the pretty little girl on
whom Beachum dotes with equal affection.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it begins to examine just why Beachum, who is black, has
been convicted for the killing of a pregnant white college student
at a convenience store, ``True Crime'' strikes a deeper note as it
watches Everett get in touch with his inner good guy. It watches
wrenchingly as Beachum and his wife (Lisa Gay Hamilton, so
impressive in ``Beloved'') prepare their final farewells, which are
among the film's most devastating moments. Then the clock-ticking
suspense rises to a breathless crescendo, one that gives some
unexpected new twists to death row suspense. The film's biggest
surprise comes in an especially effective final scene.
</P>
<P>
   As sharply written by Larry Gross, Paul Brickman and Stephen
Schiff from a mystery novel by Andrew Klavan, ``True Crime'' is
directed by Eastwood with righteous indignation and increasingly
strong momentum. As in ``A Perfect World,'' his direction is
galvanized by a sense of second chances and tragic
misunderstandings, and by contrasting a larger sense of justice
with the peculiar minutiae of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he goes a shade too far in the latter direction, though.
A-1 Steak Sauce and potato chips play much more significant roles
in the convenience store killing than anyone might expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes re-enactments of violence and an
implicit sexual situation.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRUE CRIME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Clint Eastwood; written by Larry Gross, Paul
Brickman and Stephen Schiff, based on the novel by Andrew Klavan;
director of photography, Jack N. Green; edited by Joel Cox; music
by Lennie Niehaus; production designer, Henry Bumstead; produced by
Eastwood, Richard D. Zanuck and Lili Fini Zanuck; released by
Warner Brothers. Running time: 127 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Clint Eastwood (Steve Everett), Isaiah Washington (Frank
Beachum), Denis Leary (Bob Findley), Lisa Gay Hamilton (Mrs.
Beachum), James Woods (Alan Mann), Diane Venora (Barbara) and
Francesca Fisher-Eastwood (Kate Everett).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
