<P>
   BELLSOUTH-PORTALS _ Bell South starts new portal called Atlanta
buzz. There are 62 new local portal sites from Bell South in the
nine state region. Atlanta's presence will be live Friday. Partners
include Thompson Financial networks, USA Today and Access Atlanta.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RAILWATCH _ A new nonprofit group, RailWatch, says it is
``composed of more than 300 public officials, dedicated to
educating the public about rail safety issues.'' At a Washington
news conference in February, the group issued a report titled ``Why
is there a train accident every 90 minutes?'' and demanded
congressional action. But some of the 300 public officials have
since said they had no idea they were enlisting as supporters when
they stopped by a RailWatch booth at a convention last year. And it
turns out the group has a quiet corporate backer: United Parcel
Service (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WEBMD _ ATLANTA _ WebMD has purchased 50,000 copies of Premiere
Technologies' hot messaging software that ties together all sorts
of communications. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ Stocks moved higherafter the government reported that
inflation remained stable last month. Labor Department reported
consumer prices rose just 0.1 percent last month, a signal that
inflation is under control. That news boosted prices in the bond
market, where the 30-year Treasury bond was up 9/32 point and its
yield, which moves opposite the price, was at 5.48 percent, down
from 5.5 percent late Wednesday. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-TECHNO _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Christy Jones, founder of
pcOrder.com, leads off the regional meeting of Women in Technology
International in Dallas. The theme of the conference is ``advancing
women in technology.'' Jones's company went public last year and
now has a market capitialization of $870 million. (Hawkins, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
