<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DELIMENU21-COX     03-18 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DELIMENU21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkey? Lox? Egg? A menu will tell what's in a name
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever wonder how celebrity sandwiches get named?
</P>
<P>
   Looking down the rotating list of 24 celeb-wiches at the Stage
Deli, one can't help pondering hidden significance in the
ingredients. Why is there tongue only on the Bill Cosby and Winona
Ryder? Why does the Julia Roberts alone feature hard-boiled egg?
There is no mystery in how the Dolly Parton (twin rolls of pastrami
and corned beef) was named, but doesn't a persona like Marv Albert
demand more complex ingredients than mere corned beef and Swiss
cheese?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's on that list has been here, and that's the
sandwich they ask for,'' says Gil Kashkin, manager of the
62-year-old noshery. ``We change the names regularly, but a few _
like Joe DiMaggio, Frank Sinatra, Barbra Streisand _ stay the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the street at the archrival Carnegie Deli, owner Sandy Levine
scoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbra Streisand will eat chopped liver when I grow hair on my
head! They'll put any fly-by-night on that list _ hot today, gone
tomorrow? Adam Sandler?! C'mon!''
</P>
<P>
   The 1-year-older Carnegie (founded 1936) prides itself on having
only two celeb sandwiches. The Woody Allen (``lotsa corned beef
plus lotsa pastrami,'' says the menu) was established after the
filmmaker shot scenes of ``Broadway Danny Rose'' in the deli.
Henny's (Youngman) Heaven (Nova lox and cream cheese on toasted
bagel) salutes the late comic, who used to stand up and try out new
material on his fellow diners.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you see we have a higher standard,'' says Levine, whose
cousin, Paul Zollinger, owns the Stage. ``If Hillary Clinton comes
in and asks for (her own sandwich) while she's running for senator,
they might do it down the street, but it ain't gonna happen here.
We have a higher god.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5498 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DELIS21-COX     03-18 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DELIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The deli planet: New York pate of mind deli-cious
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 30 years old, Jennifer Miller of Athens (GA.) had
her first matzo ball but swore it would not be her last.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of a Big Apple vacation with her engineer
husband, Steve, the Georgia schoolteacher went to the famed
Carnegie Deli for her first real taste of ``deli'' _ the taste, one
could argue, of a vanishing New York of yore. The pepperiness of
pastrami, the lusciousness of lox, the garlicky tang of pickles so
steeped in brine that they're almost white: these are treats that
clog the heart with cholesterol and joy. And real deli gets harder
to find every year. So here were the Millers again on Day 2,
waiting in the busy sidewalk line for the Carnegie Sunday brunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough meat in those sandwiches for five normal ones _
they make your eyes pop out,'' Jennifer enthused. ``To the folks
back home I would say: Anything that you thought was a deli before
you came here _ isn't!''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, New York is not only the capital of deli _ it is deli,
in ways that are mysterious and profound. Deli outside New York is,
somehow, a shadow of itself, for it was here in Gotham that so many
Jewish immigrants landed in the 19th and early 20th centuries,
carrying their written and unwritten recipes from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Their delicatessen was originally working-class provender, the
people's food. It served as the raw fuel of upward mobility. The
immigrants strove, raised families, noshed, debated politics and
culture and sports between bites, and noshed some more. They were
what they ate, and what they ate was pungent, salty, richly
flavorful. You can see their descendants on, say, ``Seinfeld.''
Sure, the show was set in a bland diner marked ``Restaurant,'' and
some of the wacky characters had Italian and Greek surnames, but it
was all a ploy to make the show more marketable to diverse
audiences. No, these are really deli people. They have deli
attitude and talk deli talk. Every time they bite into a grilled
cheese, think: It's really a Reuben, with sauerkraut and Thousand
Island dressing slithering out the sides.
</P>
<P>
   As a gentile living in the South, I always thought deli was
simply great eating. But as I've gotten older and returned
regularly to New York I've begun to appreciate that for Jews, deli
is so much more: a state of mind, a cultural touchstone, a glow of
fullness and well-being that radiates from the belly to the spirit.
Perhaps it's Jewish soul food?
</P>
<P>
   Even more than Southerners like to debate barbecue or Texans to
deconstruct chili, New Yorkers love to argue about deli. Witness
the recent Chopped Liver War. When Ron Rosenbaum wrote in the New
York Observer last summer that the chopped chicken liver at the
Barney Greengrass deli is ``the supreme achievement of
Jewish-American civilization,'' he was ridiculed in New York
magazine by Gael Greene. Her own chopped liver picks were topped by
the takeout counter at Zabar's. The journalistic salvos went back
and forth all autumn, with hotter-than-horseradish letters to the
editor on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   I tracked down Rosenbaum (who claims to have been vindicated in
The Jewish Daily Forward on the issue of Greengrass' chopped liver)
and invited him to serve as my guest deli critic.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DELITOUR21-COX     03-18 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DELITOUR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The deli planet: Samples of five only - in - New York Eateries
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ K A T Z' S
</P>
<P>
   Now the truth can be told. When the famous ``fake orgasm'' scene
in ``When Harry Met Sally'' was filmed in Katz's, Meg Ryan's verbal
expressions of rapture were not entirely forced. She'd just eaten
the pastrami.
</P>
<P>
   As for the hot dogs, ``They are indescribable _ maybe the best
ever,'' says New York Observer writer Ron Rosenbaum, serving as my
guest deli critic. When it comes to ambience, Katz's is the real
deal, the holy of holies among delis. Founded in 1898 in the heart
of the Jewish Lower East Side, it is marked by a 1950s sign of red
letters on white plastic squares that looks very much like the
Varsity's. And not unlike that North Avenue landmark, Katz's ``has
a kind of funky, populist splendor,'' in Rosenbaum's words, and a
legend based on the fattiest of delights.
</P>
<P>
   Katz's is cafeteria style, vast and noisy, more of a dining hall
than a restaurant. The decor, if you can call it that, froze around
World War II. There are neon signs for vanished beers (Rheingold,
Ballantine) that quenched many a thirst at Brooklyn Dodgers games.
``Send a salami to your boy in the Army!'' proclaims one wartime
sign, craftily converting Katz's mail-order business into an act of
patriotism. Among the satisfied customers pictured on the wall:
President Clinton, Jimmy and Rosalynn Carter and boxing promoter
Don King.
</P>
<P>
   My choice for funniest sign: ``Wine, red/white/rose: $3.05
glass.'' I saw no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Along one wall, half a block long, is the self-serve counter and
behind it a continuous cutting board where men in greasy aprons
spear great briskets and pastramis and fling them on the board with
a slippery thud, like fishermen landing their whoppers on a dock.
The deli men saw away at the meat to keep up with the frantic
demand. The air is filled with the tinny clatter of steam-table
lids, the barking of food orders. Customers crowd the counter (few
tables have wait service) to place their orders, ``feet dancing
with impatience,'' in the words of an amateur poet whose tribute to
Katz's is displayed in the front window.
</P>
<P>
   To make the wait more bearable, the carvers have the charming
custom of handing you the first slice of meat as a kind of
bare-handed hors d'oeuvre (napkins are available, too).
</P>
<P>
   When my exquisite corned beef on a kaiser roll was ready, the
man flung several pickle spears at the plate with the abrupt
insouciance so typical of Katz's. Luckily, two stuck.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heavenly lunch.
</P>
<P>
   205 E. Houston St. (at Ludlow Street), 212-254-2246.
</P>
<P>
   2 N D A V E N U E D E L I
</P>
<P>
   This establishment is to food what Katz's is to atmosphere:
tops. Rosenbaum says the crowded, aroma-filled restaurant is
``great for just about anything,'' but his particular favorites are
the matzo ball soup, noodle pudding and ``anything stuffed''
(cabbage, derma, breast of veal).
</P>
<P>
   ``And of course the pastrami's wonderful,'' Rosenbaum adds,
``but for God's sake don't order it lean or you defeat the whole
purpose of pastrami.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the main dining room has been remodeled with a pleasant,
nondescript decor, circa 1960s, the deli has stood on this corner
since the turn of the century and served as the gustatory
crossroads of one of New York's most colorful neighborhoods.
Actress Molly Picon held court here up through the 1960s, and one
of the smaller rooms has memorabilia of her and other Yiddish
theater stars. On the same block one can find Polish and Ukrainian
restaurants and an Irish pub. Across the street, in the park named
for deli founder Abe Lebenthol, stands St. Mark's in the Bowery
Church, a crucible of politics and culture in the '60s where Pete
Seeger sang, Allen Ginsberg read his poems and Sam Shepard mounted
his earliest plays.
</P>
<P>
   I got middling service during a hectic lunch hour, but this was
nothing new. Deli waitpersons tend to be grumpy even by Gotham
standards. Combination sandwiches and entrees tend to be in the
$10-$20 range.
</P>
<P>
   As in all the great delis, there are amusing photos of
celebrities. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is pictured wagging a salami
like a baseball bat. I stared at the Dustin Hoffman photo,
pondering the actor's cryptic message to the management: ``Your
heart is as big as your liver!''
</P>
<P>
   To Rosenbaum's favorites, I would add the divine apple strudel.
</P>
<P>
   156 Second Ave. (at 10th Street), 212-677-0606.
</P>
<P>
   B A R N E Y G R E E N G R A S S (T H E S T U R G E O N K I N G)
</P>
<P>
   It's not a physically impressive place _ in fact the dining
room, with its inexplicable, bogus-looking mural of old New
Orleans, is downright drab. But if you have a certain taste in deli
this upper West Side place looks like the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supreme for smoked fish,'' declares Rosenbaum. ``The Nova
lox is a beautiful experience. Don't just ask for lox or what
you'll get is too salty. And the sable is spectacular.'' Also on
the menu are platters of sturgeon, kippered salmon and whitefish.
They're all pricey ($16-$31.50) but can easily fill up two people
with their extras of two bagels or bialys, potato salad or cole
slaw and salad-type fixings.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the non-fish items are cheaper than at the
other big-name delis. There are triple-decker sandwiches under $10,
including one (for hard-core deli fans) with roast beef, turkey and
chicken fat. (I passed on that particular delicacy).
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum wasn't exaggerating about the chopped liver. Creamy
and velvety, with large chunks of crisp onion and egg white, the
heavenly stuff somehow holds a hint of sweetness below its smoky
savor. The $6.25 appetizer portion, almost meal-sized, is such a
deal, as they say.
</P>
<P>
   The charming takeout store, with its high ceiling and
checkerboard floor tile, looks much as it must have when it opened
in 1908.
</P>
<P>
   541 Amsterdam Ave. (at 86th Street), 212-724-4707.
</P>
<P>
   C A R N E G I E D E L I
</P>
<P>
   A veritable palisade of salamis hanging across the display
window hints at the scrumptious noshing to be found inside this
boisterous New York landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The decor is nothing special _ what passed for ``modern'' in the
1950s _ but the walls are packed with signed photos of legions of
celebs (Woody Allen, Barry Manilow, Rosie O'Donnell). The waiters
are brusque, and with good reason: There are almost always hungry
people jammed in the doorway ready to take your seat. Rosenbaum
says the place is becoming a tourist trap, but remember, he's a
purist.
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic at the prices of those ``Gargantuan Combo''
sandwiches ($11.45 for chicken salad and egg to $19.45 for Nova
salmon and sturgeon), for they contain two entrees' worth of food.
If you can eat more than half a G-combo at a sitting, you're a sumo
wrestler. For the rest of us, there's nothing like wrapping up half
a G-combo for a late-night snack in the hotel room (I recommend the
Brisketball: beef brisket, turkey, onion and fixings).
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times once rated Carnegie's blintzes tops in the
city, served in the ``Great White Way'' (with apple sauce and sour
cream).
</P>
<P>
   854 Seventh Ave. (at West 55th Street), 212-
</P>
<P>
   757-2245.
</P>
<P>
   S T A G E D E L I
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom about the Stage is that it's the
Carnegie wannabe, the slicked-up cousin to the more famous noshery
a block north. But I've always enjoyed the sandwiches here and
generally have some combination of pastrami, brisket, corned beef
and turkey (there's also tongue). Dr. Brown's sodas, for some
reason, are the official drink of delidom, and I always seem to
have a bottle of the Cel-Ray whenever I visit the Stage (yes, it
does taste like celery but it's also sweet and good).
</P>
<P>
   Once again, hard-sell Rosenbaum says the Stage is a borderline
tourist trap, and like the Carnegie does a booming business because
it's so convenient to the theater district. Still, I had a
delightful pastrami omelet ($11.95), crispy around the edges,
tender and moist in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Stage is set up for people-watching, with a beer-and-wine
bar in the center of the room, cheery checkerboard tile floor and
glassed-in greenhouse seating on the sidewalk. Broadway posters
include ``The Last Night of Ballyhoo'' (by Atlanta's own Alfred
Uhry) and ``Hello, Dolly!'' signed, with four giant ``X'' kisses,
by Carol Channing, probably one of the few people who can actually
wrap her mouth around the towering combo sandwiches
($13.95-$17.95).
</P>
<P>
   The dessert case is a house of decadence, stuffed with partially
ravaged pineapple, blueberry and cherry cheesecakes.
</P>
<P>
   834 Seventh Ave., 212-245-7850.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
