<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A SPACE AWAITS AN EMBASSY, BUT JERUSALEM IS STILL A
CONTROVERSIAL CAPITAL
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim at 675 words.
 &HT;    With information for locator map.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Someday, the U.S. embassy to Israel could be moved
from Tel Aviv to an awaiting vacant lot on a busy Jerusalem street.
But, before that happens, the diplomats will have to clear away a
lot more than the pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   Like so much other land here, the Israelis gained control of the
rocky slope after Arab states attacked them in 1948. But, a
Palestinian still holds the old deeds and his old dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that it might be forever lost to a U.S. embassy, he
leased it three years ago for just $1 to a famous tenant _ Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot keep it and protect like he can,'' said Ali Fitiani,
a wealthy Palestinian businessman. ``If the Americans build an
embassy there, they will be getting the land from the Israelis, but
(the Israelis) do not own it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitiani's deeds have little practical value, as the land is
firmly under Israeli control. But, they are a pointed reminder of
the underlying dispute over the 5,000-year-old city. The dispute
has made this the only place on earth where the United States,
along with most other countries, keeps its embassy outside the
declared capital of the host country.
</P>
<P>
   That policy is now coming under increased scrutiny and faces a
deadline soon. Back in 1995, a pro-Israel U.S. Congress passed the
``Jerusalem Embassy Act,'' which recognized Jerusalem as Israel's
capital and ordered that, by June 1999, the U.S. Embassy be moved
there from Tel Aviv, about 35 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton will likely fend off the mandate,
exercising a ``national security'' waiver that would delay the
embassy move but face congressional criticism.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials often meet Israeli leaders in Jerusalem,
treating it as a de facto capital, administration officials see an
embassy move as too inflammatory a gesture. Amid the troubled
Palestinian-Israeli Oslo peace process, such matters of real estate
quickly become battles over sacred homelands.
</P>
<P>
   Riots against Israeli troops erupted in the Palestinian West
Bank in 1997 when the U.S. Congress earmarked $100 million for an
embassy move. Faisal Husseini, Palestine Liberation Organization
leader for Jerusalem, said riots would break out again ``for sure''
if the embassy were moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in the United States' interests to take a step that
would have clear negative repercussions for the negotiations on
peace and security between the Israelis and Palestinians,'' said
U.S. Embassy Spokesman Larry Schwartz. As of last week,
administration officials said they had not decided whether to
exercise the waiver allowed in the embassy law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., sponsored the Jerusalem Embassy
Act and wants Clinton to make the move. He notes that the land is
in predominantly Jewish West Jerusalem -- albeit on the very edge
-- and not in the more controversial Arab areas captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels that this is land that no one can argue will fall
under Palestinian jurisdiction and the (peace) negotiations, to
that extent, are irrelevant,'' said Lieberman's press secretary Dan
Gerstein. He adds that threats of violence should not control U.S.
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   But, as administration officials point out, the Oslo accords
make no distinction between east and west. They just state that
Jerusalem is at issue and an embassy move would therefore
short-circuit the agreement, which was signed by Israel, the
Palestinians and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, U.S. policy toward Jerusalem is often
contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   One one hand, Congress recognized it as the capital.
Administration officials routinely meet Israeli leaders there.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, official policy leaves the city's status
pending.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the child of an American is born in Tel Aviv,
the baby's U.S. passport lists the birthplace as ``Tel Aviv,
Israel.'' But, an American baby born in Jerusalem will get a U.S.
passport that states just ``Jerusalem,'' followed by a blank space
-- as if the city belongs to no country at all.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Such ambivalence is nearly worldwide. To the consternation of
the Israelis, who base their government in Jerusalem, only Costa
Rica and El Salvador keep embassies here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this rather absurd situation in which all the
government activity is in Jerusalem but all the embassies are in
Tel Aviv,'' says David Bar-Illan, adviser to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu. ``This is discriminatory, and an absurd and
politically loaded snubbing of our capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel solidified it's hold on the western portion of the city
in the 1948 war. In 1967, it captured the rest of the city,
including the Arab areas and Muslim, Jewish and Christian holy
sites in the walled Old City.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli leaders -- especially at election time -- frequently
pledge to keep Jerusalem their ``eternal, undivided, capital.''
</P>
<P>
   After a row with European officials last week over the status of
the city -- the European Union considers Jerusalem an international
city -- Israeli officials angrily called for a world-wide public
relations campaign to explain why Jerusalem is their capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis with Europe made us realize that many things we
take for granted here are not taken for granted elsewhere,''
Bar-Illan said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
