<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GALLERY GETS SCULPTURES  
 ART FOR BEACON, N.Y.  
 PHOTOS IN BROOKLYN  
 A 20-CENTURY FAIR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly two years ago the National Gallery of Art in
Washington broke ground on a $12 million sculpture garden, on six
acres adjacent to its West Building on the Mall. At the time, there
were about 12 outdoor sculptures in the permanent collection, and
museum officials said that they were planning to double that
number.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Earl A. Powell III, director of the gallery, said it
had acquired 10 major sculptures in time for the garden's opening
on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptors represented include Louise Bourgeois, Mark di
Suvero, Roy Lichtenstein, Tony Smith, Claes Oldenburg and Coosje
van Bruggen, Ellsworth Kelly and Magdalena Abakanowicz. Seven of
the new acquisitions were donated by the Morris and Gwendolyn
Cafritz Foundation, which also underwrote the garden itself. The
other three works _ by Barry Flanagan, Sol LeWitt and Lucas Samaras
_ were given by individual donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the artists whose outdoor pieces we've acquired are
new to the National Gallery,'' Powell said, noting that until now
the Gallery has had no works by either Flanagan or Ms. Abakanowicz.
</P>
<P>
   The garden was designed by Laurie D. Olin, a Philadelphia-based
landscape architect, in collaboration with the National Gallery
staff. It includes a reflecting pool, with a fountain in its
center, that will be transformed into an ice-skating rink in
winter. There are also walks and seating areas, as well as a
renovated pavilion that will have a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1991 the National Park Service and the National
Gallery signed an agreement, which was approved by the National
Capital Planning Commission, transferring jurisdiction of the
sculpture garden site from the Park Service to the National
Gallery. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barely a week after the Dia Center for the Arts said it would
open a large branch in an abandoned factory in the Hudson River
town of Beacon, it has announced the acquisition of a seminal
series of 15 plywood floor pieces by Donald Judd, which it plans to
display in its new space.
</P>
<P>
   Dia, based in Chelsea, owned these floor pieces once before.
They were made in 1976 and exhibited the next year at the Heiner
Friedrich Gallery, which was then in SoHo. Friedrich bought them
and then donated them to Dia, which he had founded with his wife,
Phillipa de Menil, in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The floor pieces were among the extensive holdings of Judd's
work that in 1986 Dia gave to the Chinati Foundation, the museum in
Marfa, Texas, that Judd created for the permanent installation of
large-scale contemporary art. The artist died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A provision of the gift was that it could be sold to benefit the
foundation. Thirteen years later, that is exactly what has
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Chinati needed to raise money to establish an endowment fund,
and so Dia was able to buy back the floor pieces with a $1.9
million grant from the Houston-based Brown Foundation. Proceeds
will establish a fund for the operations of the Chinati Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The work is a series of 15 variations on a box, three feet tall
and five feet wide, made from five-eights-inch-thick sheets of
plywood. It became a prototype for Judd's 100-mill aluminum pieces,
commissioned by Dia as the focal point of Judd's permanent
installation in the converted Army camp in Marfa where the Chinati
Foundation is based. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gaping hole not to have an important work by Judd in
our collection,'' said Michael Govan, director of Dia, who was
quick to explain that the acquisition was not an attempt to ``just
fill the new museum with works.'' Rather, he said, it is a purchase
``very targeted to re-enforce Dia's strength _ artists who emerged
in the 1960s and 1970s.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to vary its exhibitions to attract different audiences,
the Brooklyn Museum of Art has scheduled a show of installations
and photographs by Mariko Mori, the Japanese photographer and
performance artist. ``Mariko Mori: Empty Dream'' will open on April
8 and run through Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The show will be an adaptation of several recent exhibitions.
Within the last year, large shows of Ms. Mori's work have been held
at the Serpentine Gallery in London, the Museum of Contemporary Art
in Chicago, the Andy Warhol Museum in Pittsburgh and the Los
Angeles County Museum of Art. Brooklyn's version is being organized
by Charlotta Kotik, its curator of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   The show will fill a gap in the museum's schedule. Originally
``From Hip to Hop: Black Fashion and a Culture of Influence'' was
to have opened on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been able to answer all the questions that were
raised once we started working on it,'' said Arnold Lehman,
director of the Brooklyn Museum, explaining the postponement. A new
date has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman decided to pursue the Mori exhibition after seeing her
work in Chicago. ``I think it will have an important effect on
collectors, artists and young people who have not had the
opportunity of seeing her work here,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dealers who specialize in 20th-century art and design may have a
new Manhattan venue. Anna and Brian Haughton, who first shook up
the art-fair circuit 10 years ago by organizing the International
Fine Art and Antique Dealers Show, are hoping to announce a new
fair.
</P>
<P>
   The London-based couple plan to introduce an International
20th-Century Art and Design Show over Thanksgiving weekend. It will
be at the Seventh Regiment Armory, joining the three fairs the
Haughtons already hold there: the International Fine Art and
Antique Dealer's Show every September, the six-year-old
International Fine Art Fair each May and the International Asian
Art Fair, which opens Thursday for its fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   The Thanksgiving date is no accident. It was planned to coincide
with the 20th-century decorative-art auctions that are generally
held at Sotheby's and Christie's around that time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Magda Grigorian, a spokeswoman for the Haughtons, confirmed that
such a show is under discussion but declined to comment further.
</P>
</TEXT>
