<HEADLINE>
A HOME FOR `BY JEEVES'; EMPTY SEATS FOR OFF-BROADWAY SHOWS;
FAREWELL TO ANOTHER THEATER; MOM AS ROLE MODEL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The closing of ``Band in Berlin'' at the Helen Hayes
this weekend has set off rampant speculation about the next tenant
at the theater, Broadway's smallest.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the talk centered on ``By Jeeves,'' the Andrew Lloyd
Webber/Alan Ayckbourn musical. Its producer, the Goodspeed Opera
House, made a frantic push this week to open by April 28, in time
for the deadline for Tony nominations. Michael Price, the executive
director of the Goodspeed, said the theater was committed, actors
had been put on call, the $1.2 million budget was ready and Lord
Lloyd Webber had signed off on the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, after a day of calls, Price said Ayckbourn's
schedule would not allow enough time to rehearse and open the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Alan, we just can't do it,'' he said. ``My adrenaline
has been going so high, but it's not going to happen. But it will
happen eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   With a small field of new musicals eligible for Tonys, the logic
was that ``By Jeeves'' might have done well, Price said. It was not
to be.
</P>
<P>
   After rumors arose about ``Wit,'' its producers released a
statement denying that there had been an offer from the theater's
owner, Martin Markinson, and saying that they were quite happy at
the Union Square Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway wags also had ``Night Must Fall,'' which closes at the
Lyceum on April 11, in the running. But Gary Springer, a spokesman
for the show, said that Matthew Broderick, the star, was committed
to a show at Hartford Stage in May.
</P>
<P>
   Too Many Good Shows?
</P>
<P>
   While most of the season's straight plays are doing nicely on
Broadway, several of the best reviewed off-Broadway entries have
been fighting for audiences.
</P>
<P>
   At the Century Center, for example, ``Snakebit,'' a light drama
about three friends and a secret affair, has recovered from some
abysmal preview weeks to gross $43,852 last week. Still, that is
only $4,000 above the break-even mark, said Roy Gabay, the show's
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking even is also the norm at the Douglas Fairbanks, where
Kenneth Lonergan's comedy ``This Is Our Youth'' is staged. Eric
Krebs, the theater's owner and the play's co-producer, said the
weekly gross had recently built to around $30,000, which is
slightly less than its weekly costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful Thing,'' a love story about two teen-age boys,
started out strong but has sagged in recent weeks. Gabay, the
show's producer, said that the gross two weeks ago, $22,000, was
his first weekly loss but that last week was better. The show's
running cost is about $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strongest entry is ``The Most Fabulous Story Ever
Told,'' which has been making a small if steady weekly profit at
the Minetta Lane Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been building,'' said Richard Frankel, a producer, of
the gross. He declined to give the exact amount, but one person who
had seen the figures estimated the average at $80,000, or some
$20,000 above operating costs. The recent addition of the actress
Lea DeLaria and the comic Julie Halston has also improved business,
Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   The producers say the surfeit of quality shows may be to blame.
``We're all going after the same audience,'' said Gabay. ``And
there's a lot of product out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lamb to Bow Out
</P>
<P>
   Times Square may soon be losing another theater. The Manhattan
Church of the Nazarene, which owns the Lambs Theater on West 44th
Street, is in negotiations with the Hampshire Hotels and Resorts
chain to turn its building into a hotel, church officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Calhoun, the church's pastor, said that the plans
called for a 108-room hotel and that the building's 349-seat
off-Broadway theater would be demolished, although the facade of
the building, a historic landmark designed by Stanford White, would
be preserved, as would a small church theater space. Calhoun said
the deal depended on approval by the city's Landmarks Commission
and that it was necessary to the church's fiscal well-being. Calls
to Hampshire Hotels were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   The 1904 building was long the home of the Lambs Club, a
theatrical social club whose members included Irving Berlin, Fred
Astaire and John Wayne. Legend has it that Alan Jay Lerner met
Frederick Loewe at the club, and that the duo composed their 1947
musical ``Brigadoon'' there. Carolyn Rossi Copeland, a producer
with a long history at the Lamb's Theater, said she and her
husband, the architect James Copeland, would try to save some of
the building's interior woodwork and marble fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   A Cue From Mom
</P>
<P>
   As Kristine Nielsen will tell you, being a cast member of
``Betty's Summer Vacation'' isn't always easy. Besides the general
strain of playing a broad comedy eight times a week, the play's
subject matter _ media, molestation and masculine mutilation _
hasn't sat well with some audience members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are nights where it is very quiet out there,'' said Ms.
Nielsen, in typically seriocomic style. Often, though, those
moments are broken by laughter and it is Ms. Nielsen the audience
has to thank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' by Christopher Durang, opened on
Sunday to good reviews, with many critics citing Ms. Nielsen's
portrayal of Mrs. Siezmagraff, the cheerfully unhinged hostess of a
cursed summer share, as one of the year's funniest.
</P>
<P>
   The show has since been extended by two weeks. Several producers
are considering reopening elsewhere, though the show may take a
hiatus after closing on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nielsen, a veteran of the regional theater circuit, met
Durang in 1989, during a production of ``Ubu'' at Lincoln Center
Theater. ``We were known backstage as the town gossips,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The two remained close, and last year, when Durang was finishing
``Summer Vacation,'' he began to write the role of Ms. Siezmagraff
specifically for Ms. Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   The actress, who grew up in Washington, said she modeled her
performance on another Nielsen. ``My mother would kill me, but I
think I used her as a starting point,'' she said. ``She has that
Southern charm and civility, and very positive energy.'' She added,
``I've just made it a little misguided.''
</P>
</TEXT>
