<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIENS AHEAD: NOT CUTE OR CUDDLY LIKE E.T. 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are so many things to learn about the coming alien
invasion. First, stay away from exclusive, secret downtown clubs in
New York: everybody there is a space alien inhabiting a genetic
duplicate of a human body. If you find yourself there anyway, do
not let anyone nuzzle your ear, especially someone who might be
hiding a worm in his or her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   This is how they infect you, downloading your DNA and your
memories to make a duplicate of you. The only known solution is to
drink blue agave tequila, which makes the worm leave your body.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not making this up. Writers for ``First Wave'' did.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Wave'' is one of two new hourlong series the Sci-Fi
Channel is introducing Friday night. One show wants to be the new
``X-Files''; the other, the new ``Star Trek.'' Both are a long way
from their goals but they have potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Wave'' was, in fact, created by a former ``X-Files''
writer, Chris Brancato. Its Fox Mulder equivalent is Cade Foster
(Sebastian Spence), a cocky young security-system salesman with a
beautiful wife, a nice house and a fabulous life.
</P>
<P>
   But in the premiere, he begins having strange hallucinations,
loses his job, suddenly has a zero balance at the ATM, finds his
house broken into with the number 19 painted in red on the walls,
meets a seemingly insane prisoner who commits suicide, digs up a
centuries-old book of Nostradamus' predictions, discovers an alien
invasion, is committed to a psychiatric hospital, is framed (by
aliens) for the murder of his wife and goes on the run, making him
a Dr. Richard Kimble equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Wave'' is a little earnest, but maybe a line like Cade's
``Someone's out to tear our lives apart'' isn't unreasonable under
the circumstances. Spence, who played the adult Kevin (the sexually
abused central character) in ``The Boys of St. Vincent,'' is
appealing, and it looks as if he'll be getting into interesting
situations: aliens go into group therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Aliens try to undermine the institution of family to destroy
society. Aliens distribute an elixir of youth. And, of course, the
tequila and worm episode.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can only hope that Cade's initial discovery of the
invasion doesn't represent the credibility level of the series as a
whole. Why would aliens line the walls of their headquarters with
black-and-white 8-by-10 photographs of their victims?
</P>
<P>
   ``First Wave'' has its ``X-Files'' connection and Francis Ford
Coppola as an executive producer. ``Farscape'' has the Jim Henson
Co. So when its hero, John Crichton (Ben Browder, who looks a
little like Paul LeMat in ``American Graffiti''), a
second-generation American astronaut, accidentally goes through a
worm hole during a shuttle mission and ends up in another galaxy
several of his new colleagues are Muppets.
</P>
<P>
   These, of course, are Henson's more intimidating, not so cuddly
Muppets. Rygel XVI, for instance, may be 26 inches tall and shaped
sort of like the Liberty Bell but as a former sovereign who has
been a prisoner for 250 years he's pretty grouchy and not likely to
burst into heartwarming song.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton's other new comrades on the biomechanoid spaceship Moya
include Aeryn Sun (Claudia Black), an imprisoned Peacekeeper who
looks human; General Ka D'Argo (Anthony Simcoe), Lexan warrior and
Chewbacca the Wookiee look-alike, and Zhaan (Virginia Hey), a
spiritual leader with blue skin.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since the ``Star Wars'' bar scene.
Television now seems crowded with so many alien species with
meaningful cultural characteristics that we hardly need any new
ones, but ``Farscape'' has its pluses.
</P>
<P>
   In the premiere, Crichton leaves behind the vast silence and
solitude of Earth space and emerges from the wormhole into a
section of outer space that looks like a ``Star Wars'' battle
scene.
</P>
<P>
   There is humor. (``Don't move! Or I'll fill you with _ little
bolts of golden light,'' says Crichton. And when Aeryn asks him
what she could possibly need him for, he waits until she walks away
and mutters: ``Talent. Personality. Stock tips.'') And there are
welcome original ``Star Trek''-style paradoxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Peacekeepers, for instance, are the particular brutal
soldiers. And in the show's third episode, the Moya crew learns a
valuable lesson when it makes the assumption that having giant
space cockroaches aboard is bad. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   FIRST WAVE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Subject 117 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sci-Fi Channel, Friday night at 10 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created and written by Chris Brancato; Brenton Spencer,
director. Produced by Larry Sugar Entertainment Ltd., a subsidiary
of Vidaton Entertainment Group and Pearson Television
International; Francis Ford Coppola, Chris Brancato and Larry
Sugar, executive producers; Randy Cheveldave, co-producer and line
producer; Colette Aubin, production manager; Henry Chan, director
of photography; Rob Paller, special effects coordinator. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Sabastian Spence (Cade Foster), Stacy Grant (Hannah) and
Emmett Mayhew (Myron Natwick.)
</P>
<P>
   FARSCAPE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Brian Henson, Kris Noble, Rockne S. O'Bannon and Robert Halmi,
Jr., executive producers; David Kemper, co-executive producer and
executive producer for episode No. 9; Matt Carroll, producer; David
Wilks, consulting producer for episode Nos. 2 though 6; Richard
Manning, Ro Hume, executive consultants; Sally Lapiduss, creative
consultant; Richard Clendinnen, line producer. Andrew Prowse, Brian
Henson, Pino Amenta, Rowan Woods, Tony Tilse, Brendan Maher, Ian
Watson and Peter Andrikidis, directors. Produced by the Jim Henson
Co. in association with Hallmark Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ben Browder (Cmdr. John Crichton), Claudia Black (Aeryn
Sun), Anthony Simcoe (Gen. Ka D'Argo), Virginia Hey (Pau Zotoh
Zhaan), John Eccleston (Rygel, XVI), Jonathan Hardy (Voice), Sean
Masterson (pilot), Lani John Tupu (Capt. Bialar Crais) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
