<SLUG> BC-SOC-YOUNG-PRO-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 DaMARCUS BEASLEY, 16, SIGNS PRO CONTRACT WITH MAJOR LEAGUE SOCCER  
(rk) 
 By BRIAN EVERS McGEE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ In the same week he was named the top
midfielder on the Parade Magazine All-American team, DaMarcus
Beasley became the youngest player ever to sign a Major League
Soccer contract.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley signed with U.S. Project-40, an MLS development program,
on Wednesday. Beasley, 16 years, 10 months of age, will train with
MLS clubs this summer to help prepare him for the professional
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley, a junior at Bradenton Academy, will not see action in
MLS matches this season. He will train and play games with U.S.
Pro-40 under coach Lothar Osiander when Under-17 national team
duties do not conflict with the Pro-40 team's A-League schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a dream of mine, to play a pro sport since I was
a child, Beasley said. ``And now, to be a pro, it's an exciting
time for me. My option was college but I spoke to my parents, I
talked to coaches, friends and everyone was 100 percent behind me
whatever I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said the contract includes $24,000, to be paid in $2,000
monthly installments, $2,500 from Nike and $1,500 in merchandise
from Nike plus bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Project-40 is a joint venture between MLS and U.S. Soccer aimed
at providing America's young talent a chance to compete with the
top countries in the 2000 Olympics and 2010 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley will be assigned to a MLS squad and will report
following his graduation from Bradenton Academy in the spring of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``DaMarcus Beasley is the youngest player to ever sign a MLS
contract,'' said Ivan Gazidis, MLS executive vice president of
player relations and operations. ``He can be thought of as a
prototype for the young American soccer player developing on our
soil. We are delighted that DeMarcus has chosen to progress his
talent in MLS.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the U-17 national team, Beasley scored 17 goals and
collected 16 assists during the last two years as the team prepared
to qualify for FIFA's World Youth Championships set for Nov. 10.
His nine goals in 1998 were tied for second on the club.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-7-inch, 126-pound Beasley scored three second-half
goals in the Florida High School fall state soccer championships to
lead the Blazers to the state title. Beasley is part of the U-17
national team residential program at the Bollettieri Sports Academy
in Bradenton.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Wayne, Ind., native is following in the footsteps of
his older brother, Jamar, who went from Project-40 to the New
England Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla. is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
