<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-VOYAGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTOIANNI'S LAST FILM A TRIP DOWN ROAD OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This prophetically sad film by 91-year-old director Manoel De
Oliveira was Marcello Mastroianni's 171st _ and final _ movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voyage to the Beginning of the World'' is a meditative,
reflective journey through the past.
</P>
<P>
   Like many films that are personal reflections and laments to
passing time, the infirmity of old age and the presence of ghostly
memories, it's truly only interesting for the people involved
despite its universality.
</P>
<P>
   In a van traveling through northern Portugal, four riders
discuss age, youth and the barriers that they present. Manoel
(Mastroianni) is a film director. His companions are Afonso (Jean
Yves Gautier), a French actor born in Portugal who is starring in
Manoel's latest venture; Judite (Leonor Silveira), a vibrant, young
actress, and Duarte (Diogo Doria), the driver who acts as tour
guide.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Manoel reminisces about his early life in Portugal.
He remembers many of the things he now misses _ especially the
women. Everyone has also agreed to help Afonso find his father's
village and what is left of a family he's never known. The meeting
will bring ultimate acceptance and a discovery that will help one
man's life begin as another's approaches twilight.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense of circular motion and completion to De
Oliveira's contemplative missive. Like the wonderful French film,
``A Sunday in the Country,'' the sense of family, love and creative
purpose is a redeeming factor.
</P>
<P>
   But De Oliveira's vision is more circumspect and may not
translate well for all viewers. It's slow going for a while and
there is a shadow cast over the first half _ mostly because
Mastroianni is so visibly frail. He died in 1996, a year before the
film's release. But the film picks up as it becomes a redemptive
story about belonging and creative pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Death and memory are two things nobody can avoid. And as the car
zooms away from the camera in scene after scene and the lines in
the road blur, we're left with a sense of our own fragility and
mortality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1729EST &QL; 
