<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     03-18 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO STARRING ROLE FOR AGENTS  
 JUST BEING NEIGHBORLY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Once a year on Oscar night, and only then, toute
Hollywood turns out to celebrate the industry's accomplishments, to
share a bit of movie glamour at an event in which everyone is
included. Well, almost everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The coveted Oscars are voted upon by the members of the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences. Though the group's roster is
secret, its executives admit to having about 5,500 members in 13
branches, including everyone from actors, directors, public
relations officials and studio executives to musicians, art
directors and agents.
</P>
<P>
   As George Orwell might have put it, all academy members are
equal, but some are more equal than others. And that is never felt
more keenly and bitterly than at Oscar season, when agents are
reminded that they are the only major branch of the academy that is
excluded from voting.
</P>
<P>
   This is because the academy is a relic from a bygone era in
which the big studios held sway over the industry. Agents were on
the fringes in the prewar days when the academy was organized, but
today they are among the most influential players in piecing
together film projects. Many studio executives and producers were
once agents.
</P>
<P>
   Their lack of voting rights is an anomaly that pleases no one.
The ostensible reason for their status is that agents are advocates
for their clients and would thus be biased voters. In addition,
they are said to be peripheral to filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   But the agents reply that nearly everyone in the academy is
motivated by some self-interest. Most notably, there is the public
relations branch, made up of people who promote, spin and
glamourize movies and stars but have no hand in film production.
</P>
<P>
   The 350 or so public relations officials in the academy vote, so
why not the 65 or so agents?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone you talk to says: `I can't believe you can't vote.
How can that happen?' '' said Martha Luttrell, an agent at
International Creative Management who heads the agents' branch of
the academy. ``We have been fighting for the vote for years now
with great frustration. We always talk to a board member who says
this year people will come to their senses. It never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy wrestles with this fact occasionally, but always
maintains the status quo and the old-fashioned rationale behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is agents make deals rather than movies,'' said
Bruce Davis, executive director of the academy. ``I know what
people say about the PR branch. There may be a logical
inconsistency there. But if an error was made in giving them a vote
in the past it's not going to be fixed by making an error in the
present.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the agents raise the issue frequently, Davis added, ``the
idea has not been embraced even mildly by the board.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has suggested taking the vote away from the publicists,
but members of the public relations branch chafe at the notion of
allowing agents to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of think of them as the management for individuals as
opposed to overseeing an entire film,'' said Cheryl Boone Isaacs,
the head of marketing at New Line Cinema and a former head of the
public relations branch of the academy.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Angelotti, who heads his own publicity agency and is on the
academy committee that admits new members to his branch, said:
``The historical perception is the agents are advocates and
therefore they would vote accordingly. I don't think the PR people
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Luttrell said that the idea that any branch would be more
fair than another was nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   The voting process is secretive and is also the subject of
debate. The academy's voting members can make nominations only in
the categories involving their own branches of expertise, except in
the best picture category, in which any voting member may make a
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The five top vote-getters become the overall nominees. Voting
members then choose the winners, who are to be announced at the
extravaganza here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have complained about the intensity and cost of the
lobbying by some of the studios. The battle between ``Shakespeare
in Love'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' this year, for example, has
been hugely expensive as well as a gimmick to attract attention to
the Academy Awards broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics also complain that the vote tallies are kept
secret. That way, it is never clear if a movie or a star won by 3
votes or 300, information that would be relevant in determining the
extent to which the academy membership reflects popular views.
</P>
<P>
   But change comes slowly at the academy, which has fended off
nearly all proposals for major shifts. The agents' complaints
usually draw little sympathy because they are famously well paid
and are seen as fee-hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lantz, a highly regarded agent who helped set up the
movie ``Amadeus,'' wrote to the academy a year and a half ago
complaining bitterly that agents were ``second-class citizens
within the academy.'' He described how he helped create
``Amadeus,'' then closed by saying, ``I urge you to end one of the
more absurd instances of discrimination in our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been all sorts of active campaigns on this,'' said
Sandy Bresler, an agent and chairman of the Association of Talent
Agents. ``But they have not met with the desired results, and I
don't know if they will.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just Being Neighborly
</P>
<P>
   So the neighbor says, ``Joe, c'mon, do this movie with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe says, ``I've kept a low profile all my life. I'm not going
to put my mug on a 40-foot screen.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor asks again and again for years. Pressed by the
neighbor's son, long-retired Joe finally says, ``Everyone at some
point in life wants to do this. OK''
</P>
<P>
   And so began Joe Viterelli's second career as an actor. The
neighbor was the television director Leo Penn, the father of Sean
Penn. The older Penn, who died in September, lived in Malibu, where
Viterelli had retired after a business career in New York that he
described vaguely as involving owning a few gin mills and a
trucking company and playing the stock market. His new career has
most recently brought him the role of Jelly in ``Analyze This,''
the year's first big hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' is a gangster film sendup in which the head of
a Mafia family, played by Robert De Niro, loses his nerve and
recruits a therapist, played by Billy Crystal, to bring back his
happy old murderous ferocity. But Jelly, the don's trusted
lieutenant, is an occasional scene stealer. He is a lovable killer
with a face like an oversized pork chop who frequently utters
malapropisms, like calling a bad headache a ``mindgraine.''
</P>
<P>
   Viterelli said the call that finally encouraged him to accept
the challenge of acting came not from his neighbor Leo, but from
Sean Penn. It was 1990, and the younger Penn was making the
gangster film ``State of Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean just told me: `I know you always said no to my dad, but I
thought I'd catch you on a whim. We're shooting this mob stuff on
Mott Street, and I know you know the area.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Viterelli grew up in Little Italy with plenty of real
gangsters. He said he always had an interest in the arts _ he plays
classical guitar, and his son, Joseph, is a well-regarded composer
of film scores _ but had to conceal that from his childhood friends
because of the tough environment. But the call from Sean Penn
brought him to New York, where he played a heavy in what became the
first of several dozen pictures; he has been in ``Bullets Over
Broadway,'' ``The Firm'' and ``Eraser.''
</P>
<P>
   Viterelli said he originally read the script for ``Analyze
This'' about three years ago and immediately fell in love with
Jelly, an old-line gangster who worries that, if his boss is seeing
a therapist, next he may turn gay. He said he was finally called to
audition in New York for two lesser roles, which was heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'd come and read with one condition,'' Viterelli
said. ``I've been carrying this guy Jelly around with me and I have
to get him out. If you'll indulge me, I'll read those other parts
if you can just let me do Jelly first.''
</P>
<P>
   They agreed, and Viterelli said that after doing a bit of Jelly,
he was told not to bother with the other roles. Two days later he
got the call saying he would be Jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Viterelli said that acting came naturally and that he felt no
fear in front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I don't know where I'm at,'' he said. ``I just do it.
It's all real for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The terror, he added, comes when he sees himself on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really frightening, but I'm not looking to do
Shakespeare or `Hamlet,' '' he said. ``I'm happy that people are
happy watching me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
