<HEADER>
A5559 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HARMONISTS-SPI &LR;      03-18 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HARMONISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFRESHING `HARMONISTS' NOT SAME OLD SONG AND DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were fortunate enough to catch the harrowing 1994 German
World War II drama, ``Stalingrad,'' you know that its director,
Joseph Vilsmaier, has as strong a feel for genre and character, and
as clear an eye for the epic, as any European filmmaker of this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Harmonists,'' he turns that eye toward a totally
different but no less structured movie genre: the musical
biography. The results are almost as impressive, and the film _
which is getting a big U.S. push from Miramax _ is likely to
finally establish him as one of Germany's top directors.
</P>
<P>
   His subject is the Comedian Harmonists, a six-man German a
cappella group that is far from a household word in this country,
but was a sensation in Germany and much of the rest of Europe in
the late 1920s and early '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Their story begins in 1927 when a 20-year-old drama student
named Harry Frommermann (Ulrich Noethen) decides to model a German
singing ensemble after the American group The Revellers, and places
an advertisement for open auditions in a Berlin newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   As the sextet comes together, it passes through the usual stages
we've come to expect from the musical biopic: endless rehearsals,
personnel squabbles, a disastrous audition in front of an important
agent (who rudely tells them they stink), and the gradual discovery
of their unique sound.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, they move on to fame and fortune; tour Europe and the
States; and develop a stronger and even more unique comedy element
to their act _ while offstage Frommermann and the group's other
leader, Robert Biberti (Ben Becker), contend for the favors of the
same girl (Meret Becker).
</P>
<P>
   What gives their story a particular bite is that three of the
members _ half the group _ are Jewish, so their rise against the
growth of Nazism in Germany of the early '30s puts them on a
collision course that the audience feels right from the opening
frames.
</P>
<P>
   The film debuted locally last weekend at the Jewish Film
Festival, but it's not really a Holocaust film and, like
``Stalingrad,'' its sensibility is much more sympathetic to the
German people than we're used to seeing in movies dealing with that
era.
</P>
<P>
   Vilsmaier's main point of view and most admirable character in
the film is the non-Jewish Biberti, who is more vocal in his hatred
of the Nazis than the Jewish characters, and stands as a
representative of the ``good'' Germans who claimed they didn't see
Hitler coming, but loathed him when he did.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your feelings about this slight twist, ``The
Harmonists'' is a big, broad, period musical that wonderfully
recreates the Berlin of the ``Cabaret'' era, gives us a series of
entertaining and splashy production numbers, and does what '90s
cinema so often fails to do: It tells us a story that we haven't
heard before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     03-18 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: be true.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film's simplicity is appealing, as is Gyllenhaal in the
central role of a boy in a West Virginia coal mining town who
becomes obsessed with rocketry. But the story, filled with
father-son conflict and down-in-the-ground versus up-in-the-sky
contrasts, often follows a familiar trajectory (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``PAYBACK,'' starring Mel Gibson and Gregg Henry. Directed by
Brian Helgeland (R, 110 minutes). In this inept, excessively
sadistic film-noir spoof adapted from the same Richard Stark novel
(``The Hunter'') that inspired the 1967 genre classic ``Point
Blank,'' Gibson is a thief named Porter who retaliates with a
vengeance after an attempt on his life.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to recover $70,000 that was stolen from him by a
double-crossing partner in crime, he works his way up the pecking
order of a crime syndicate, brutally dispatching all who stand in
his way. The hard-boiled dialogue is ludicrous, the storytelling
clunky, the acting fair to awful, the gore ankle deep. Credit the
star with being able to keep a straight face through this loathsome
mess (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SAVING PRIVATE RYAN,'' starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon,
Tom Sizemore, Jeremy Davies and Edward Burns. Directed by Steven
Spielberg (R, 168 minutes). Spielberg's soberly magnificent new
film is the finest war movie of our time. Turning back the clock to
restore passion and meaning to the genre, he works in a spirit of
urgent communication to look at war as if it has not been looked at
before.
</P>
<P>
   Tour-de-force battle scenes are frank without sensationalism,
and the same great storyteller who made you believe there was an
extraterrestrial hiding in the closet has made this an irresistibly
vibrant, gripping tale. Hanks continues to astonish with admirable
modesty, and the rest of the casting is comparably inspired. As he
did with ``Schindler's List,'' Spielberg has made a landmark film
of devastating power (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,'' starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth
Paltrow and Geoffrey Rush. Directed by John Madden (R, 113
minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily literate delight, with an
exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets better as the film
unfolds. The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm
and turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of
his ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile this tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today and has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo
and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a
fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first great, fully
realized starring performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``TANGO,'' starring Miguel Angel Sola. Written and
directed by Carlos Saura. Cinematography by Vittorio Storaro
(PG-13, 100 minutes). A thrilling display of tango heat and
virtuosity. And it's no slight to the actors who play lovers to say
that the dancing here is steamier than any kiss. In his most
electrifying dance film, Saura offers transfixingly beautiful
glimpses of the dance and the great range of emotions it can
conjure. Storaro's dazzlingly fluid cinematography captures all the
nuances this material demands. Everyone in the film is utterly
consumed by tango fever; audiences will be, too (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE THIN RED LINE,'' starring Jim Caviezel, Ben Chaplin, Nick
Nolte and Sean Penn. Directed by Terrence Malick (R, 166 minutes).
From the first frame of this huge, drifting war epic loosely
derived from James Jones' Guadalcanal novel, it's viscerally clear
that Malick is back. The exquisite, oddly detached visual style
that made ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven'' the most beautiful
films of the 1970s is instantly apparent here, even if the
narrative vagueness and brooding voice-overs are also familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The film sprawls, gets lost and occasionally delivers visual
poetry, the kind that could have been greatly helped by tighter
editing. Bottom line: No one who admired Malick's early work should
miss this. But those expecting anything simple will not find it
here (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``20 DATES,'' starring Myles Berkowitz. Directed by Berkowitz
(R, 88 minutes). The filmmaker's gimmick is to make a film about
dating. His goal: to go out with 20 different women, get them on
camera by any means necessary and promise to fall in love with one
before the experiment is over.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz, pesty and proud of it, has absorbed enough of Jerry
Seinfeld and Garry Shandling to create a diffident, nit-picking,
sitcom-ready persona. But whenever his film establishes a playful
mood, it's liable to do something to make you squirm. Crassness and
mock candor aren't all that funny (unless they're coming from
Albert Brooks, whose ``Real Life'' paved the way for this). And
discovering that cheese makes Berkowitz constipated or that one of
his dates disappoints him by not looking enough like Jessica Rabbit
is more than you need to know (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``200 CIGARETTES,'' starring Paul Rudd, Kate Hudson and Courtney
Love. Directed by Risa Bramon Garcia (R, 102 minutes). This
contrived but cheery party movie is the feature directing debut of
a well-known casting director. And in making her film, Ms. Garcia
does what she does best: cast. A group of bright young players is
brought together for a largely plotless New Year's Eve, rambling
around a colorfully evoked East Village, circa 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially just a set of interwoven skits, this comedy still
makes good use of the actors noted above, along with Casey Affleck
as a nice-guy punk, Dave Chappelle as a cabbie full of advice and
Martha Plimpton as a hopeless hostess. Ms. Hudson, who is Goldie
Hawn's daughter and has her mother's grin and giggle, makes an
adorable debut despite spending part of the movie with dog
excrement on her coat (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
