<SLUG> BC-FILM-RAVENOUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPHISTICATED TALE OF CANNIBALISM SETTLES FOR OVERCOOKED
CAMPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This darkly funny, subversively arch horror film is smarter than
most. At least for the first hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravenous'' fortunately shies away from the formulaic high
school or college campus-set teenage slice-and-dice that has
permeated the genre for the past decade. And its cast is above par
as well, featuring a smart blend of international talent, including
Australian Guy Pearce (``L.A. Confidential''), Briton Robert
Carlyle, who had his first big hit with ``The Full Monty,'' and
American Jeremy Davies (``Saving Private Ryan'').
</P>
<P>
   The movie has a rather sophisticated, psychological dimension
despite the grim theme and the trouble the production apparently
weathered. Initially the film was to have been directed by Milcho
Manchevski, but he was replaced by English director Antonia Bird
(``Priest'').
</P>
<P>
   Bird brings a suitably gray, rugged and gritty texture to
``Ravenous,'' which is set in 1847 just after the Mexican-American
War. Young Captain John Boyd (Pearce) has just been awarded a medal
for bravery but secretly knows he acted with cowardice, pretending
to be dead in order to avoid being killed in battle. His body is
pitched onto a pile of corpses and the bloody, blown bodies drip
onto him, scarring him forever to the horrors of the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's superior officer brusquely transfers him to a remote
outpost in the California Sierra Nevada as a kind of punishment.
Boyd's new regiment includes the drunken Knox (Stephen Spinella),
religious Toffler (Davies), war-monger Reich (Neal McDonough),
crazy Cleaves (David Arquette) and commanding officer Hart (Jeffrey
Jones).
</P>
<P>
   One day a stranger appears. Colqhoun (Carlyle) is half-starved
and freezing and as he thaws, he relays a horrible tale; he was
traveling with a group of settlers when the accompanying officer,
Colonel Ives, suggested a shortcut through rough terrain. The
settlers are waylaid by a snowstorm and are forced to take refuge
in a cave during the terrible winter, which has just begun. Slowly,
the food disappears. They eat the oxen, the horses and a dog. One
of the party dies and they eat him. Soon they begin to kill each
other to survive. Only Colqhoun has escaped. But there is still one
woman left in the cave with Ives, and he has developed a ravenous
taste for human flesh and blood. Hart decides he and his men will
make the three-day trek to save the woman's life. But Colqhoun
isn't being quite honest and soon the small band of soldiers find
they are up against an unmitigated terror with a huge appetite. And
they're the main course.
</P>
<P>
   Bird and screenwriter Ted Griffin combine the myth that one who
ingests the flesh of another will gain the victim's strength and
spirit with references to such historical horrors as the Donner
Party. The result is a grisly tale of cannibalism that is original
and initially suspenseful.
</P>
<P>
   After that, however, ``Ravenous'' stumbles. It doesn't know what
to do with itself or how to end its story, so it relies upon a
one-on-one duel between good and evil set against a bloodbath of
body parts that feels out of place with everything that has come
before.
</P>
<P>
   Had the script maintained the same deft rawness and energy of
its set-up, the film could have been a rare contender in the horror
genre, but it settles, unfortunately, for over-cooked campiness
instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
