r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TRUE-CRIME-SPI &LR;      03-18 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRUE-CRIME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MANY FLAWS MAKE A LIE OF `TRUE CRIMES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like his last few films, producer-director-star Clint Eastwood's
latest offering, ``True Crime,'' seems a return to the kind of
flimsy storytelling and sloppy filmmaking that characterized his
career in the '80s. More and more, his 1992 ``Unforgiven'' triumph
seems a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he plays one of the more preposterous journalists to ever
grace the screen, and an all-around lout _ irresponsible father,
philandering husband, self-pitying alcoholic _ who Eastwood the
director obviously believes is actually a pretty cool guy.
</P>
<P>
   The plot has this Oakland Tribune reporter and his ``famous nose
for a story'' racing the clock to prove that a man (Isaiah
Washington) on death row for murdering a young woman is actually
innocent. Yes, roughly the same plot as the 1948 Jimmy Stewart
classic, ``Call Northside 777.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Stewart took a few weeks to do the job, Eastwood has
12 hours and the handicap of having to take his daughter to the
zoo, write a human interest story on the execution and cover up his
extramarital affair with the wife of his editor (Dennis Leary).
It's a busy day.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood fans will find a few Dirty Harry-ish one-liners to
relish and a few entertaining (if highly improbable exchanges) with
the Trib's managing editor (James Woods). Also to its credit, the
film has an unusually good feel for Oakland (Eastwood's boyhood
home).
</P>
<P>
   But its story is so clumsy, predictable and dependent on
coincidence that it's never much fun as a mystery; and so absurd
and anachronistic as a newspaper drama (taking place in a macho
journalistic world that didn't even exist in the '30s, much less
the yuppified '90s) that it's just plain stupid.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't help the credibility of the movie that the
convict is so completely noble _ a born-again Christian, a devoted
husband and father, a combination of Sidney Poitier and Dr. Ralph
Bunch. The man's too obviously innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' is also not helped by the fact that Eastwood the
star looks like Methuselah having a bad day. You wish he'd, if not
have a face-lift, at least brush his hair. The scenes in which he's
striking nude poses in bed with his mistress or putting the make on
a 23-year-old co-worker are almost pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Other superstars of his generation _ Dustin Hoffman, Warren
Beatty, Jack Nicholson _ have found ways to successfully temper
their persona and grow old gracefully on the screen. But this part
almost seems to have been written for an actor in his 20s. Never in
his 40-year-career has Eastwood been so completely, tragically
miscast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
