<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will be much cooler Friday as brisk winds usher in
chilly air from Canada. A slow-moving storm over the St. Lawrence
Valley will circulate moisture into the higher terrain of New
England and this will produce snow showers. Air descending the east
slopes of the Appalachians will become noticeably drier leading to
frequent intervals of sunshine along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of cooler air will reach into the Southeast
ending the brief warm spell. Sunshine will dominate as temperatures
return to near seasonal levels. Florida will stay rather warm and
quite dry.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure crested near Lake Superior will dominate
conditions over the Middle West. Sunny skies and light winds will
accompany seasonable conditions in the western Lakes. A return flow
of milder air from the south will promote above normal readings in
the northwest Plains and northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   A large, but weakening disturbance over Texas will drift
eastward. Clouds will cover much of the southern Plains and western
lower Mississippi Valley. Chilly rain will dampen Oklahoma and
southern Kansas. A little wet snow will diminish over the
panhandles of Texas and Oklahoma. Cooler and drier weather will
spread into south Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mild air and a mixture of clouds and sun will cover most of the
Northwest. A disturbance entering California will bring a variety
of unsettled conditions. Rain will dampen much of the Central
Valley with snow in the Sierra. Showers will move into the southern
sections with thickening clouds in the deserts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Winds of March
</P>
<P>
   March is known for its wind. Large temperature contrasts, which
provide energy for storms with high winds, linger during the third
month. Though the Arctic's coldest assault has long passed,
burgeoning warmth from the tropics regenerates temperature
differences across the nation. While readings reached 70s in the
Ohio Valley on Thursday, there were periods of snow across the
northwestern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   On stormless days, the sun's energy stirs up the lower
atmosphere, blending winds near the ground with stronger winds from
above, thereby spawning the famous breezes of March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
