</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMA AND INTRIGUE: OSCARS PROMISE TO KEEP US ON EDGE OF OUR
SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, the armada of critics, pundits, Wall
Street analysts and Vegas odds-makers who handicap the Academy
Awards have been almost unanimously saying Sunday night's Oscar
Fest is the most wide open of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   As we enter Oscar weekend, that consensus is beginning to look
like an understatement: this 71st running of moviedom's biggest
event could be one of the more totally unpredictable of all time _
that rare Oscar-cast in which no outcome seems impossible, or
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   This strange haze in the collective crystal ball is, of course,
due mostly to the presence of two unusually strong contenders for
the lion's share of prizes _ each so strong, in fact, that they've
thrown the near-exact science of Oscar forecasting out of kilter.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be the year of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' in
the same way last year was the year of ``Titanic.'' When it was
released last July, Variety suggested the Academy might ``just
Fed-Ex the Oscars over to (Steven) Spielberg's house and save
everybody the trouble of voting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oscar voters have notoriously short memories, and the World
War II epic's overpowering lead for the best picture honors has
diminished during the past six months, and leveled to near 50-50
since the year-end release of that anachronistic charmer,
``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the front-runner? ``Ryan'' won most of the critics
accolades and still has the edge of being the weightier subject,
but ``Shakespeare'' received the most nominations (13 to ``Ryan's''
11). In 14 of the past 15 Oscar races, the top prize has gone to
the picture with the most nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare'' also won the best ensemble cast award _ the
equivalent of best picture _ at the recent Screen Actor's Guild
Awards (another accurate indicator of how the Oscars will go, since
most of the 5,000 Academy members are from the acting branch).
</P>
<P>
   And ``Shakespeare'' also has the Miramax publicity machine going
for it. This is not a small factor, since the Tiffany's of movie
distributors has re-written the book on Oscar campaigns in the
'90s, and spent more than $10 million to boost the chances of
``Shakespeare'' alone.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the situation is the fact the best picture field
contains two other films that have striking similarities to the
front-runners: ``The Thin Red Line,'' a second WWII combat film,
and ``Elizabeth,'' a second Elizabethan period piece (ironically
with two of the same stars as ``Shakespeare'').
</P>
<P>
   When similar films are nominated for the same award, they tend
to cancel each other out, or at least take away a significant
number of votes from each other. So the door could be open for the
long-shot best-picture victory of the fifth nominee, Roberto
Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, maybe it's not such a long-shot. The
Italian Holocaust comedy also has the Miramax publicity machine
behind it, it's received more nominations than any foreign-language
film in history, and it offers voters an opportunity to make
history with Oscar's first foreign-language best picture.
</P>
<P>
   Because the top spot is so wide open, this could also be one of
those rare years when the picture and director races split, which
has not happened since 1989. Torn between the two worthy films (as
in 1972, between ``The Godfather'' and ``Cabaret''), Oscar voters
have occasionally given one best picture, the other best director.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down the rest of the list, the only sure-thing seems to
be Gwyneth Paltrow of ``Shakespeare.'' Not only has she won the SAG
and Golden Globe actress awards for this slot, her
movie-star-radiant performance as the inspiration of literature's
greatest love story is the spirit _ the keynote _ of her movie.
</P>
<P>
   Her chances look ever better alongside her competition: Meryl
Streep in the underwhelming ``One True Thing;'' Australia's Cate
Blanchett in the highly overrated ``Elizabeth;'' and Brazil's
Fernanda Montenegro and England's Emily Watson in the little seen
``Central Station'' and ``Hilary and Jackie,'' respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Oscar slots are up for grabs _ especially best
actor. Ian McKellen of ``Gods and Monsters'' may still wear the
smile of a winner, but veteran Nick Nolte of ``Affliction'' is the
sentimental favorite, two-time winner Tom Hanks of ``Ryan'' is
America's most beloved star, and Hollywood has fallen in love with
goofy Roberto Benigni of ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even darkest of dark horses Edward Norton of ``American History
X'' would seem to have a shot. As the only one of the best actor
nominees to take the high road and not mount an Oscar campaign, he
could be the beneficiary of the growing resentment of the buying of
the Oscar. This stand-back approach has certainly worked for
Katharine Hepburn over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actor category is even more of a dogfight. Oscar
voters have lately made a habit of giving this prize to slumming
A-level stars (hence last year's Robin Williams) and to previous
best-actor winners (like 1992's Gene Hackman) so Robert Duvall of
``A Civil Action'' (who won the SAG award) and Geoffrey Rush of
``Shakespeare in Love'' both look strong here.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Harris, the godlike manipulator of ``The Truman Show,''
could be the beneficiary of his film's slight in not getting a
best-picture nomination; 40-year-veteran James Coburn of
``Affliction'' is more than worthy of a career-achievement award;
and Billy Bob Thornton of ``A Simple Plan'' took not one but two of
the year-end critics awards.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actress field is similarly tough. Kathy Bates of
``Primary Colors'' _ the only American in this field _ perfectly
embodies America's mixed feelings about the Clinton sex scandal.
And even though her performance in ``Shakespeare'' is tiny,
England's Judy Dench could take home a consolation prize for losing
out last year as a later Queen of England in ``Mrs. Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be counted out are Dench's fellow British
previous-nominees, Lynn Redgrave, the befuddled German housemaid of
``Gods and Monsters,'' and Brenda Blethyn, the shrewish mother of a
bizarre musical genius in ``Little Voice''; or even Australia's
Rachel Griffiths, the loyal sister of another musical genius in
``Hilary and Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, the lower-profile awards will balance the ticket of
the higher-profile awards. Thus, if ``Life Is Beautiful'' misses
best picture and best actor, it will surely take best foreign
language film. And ``Shakespeare'' and ``Ryan'' will, in some
arrangement, split the awards for screenplay, art direction,
cinematography, sound, score, editing and make-up.
</P>
<P>
   The good news about all this Oscar uncertainty is that it makes
for more interesting viewing on Oscar night. In contrast to last
year's dull tribute to James Cameron, this year's event should
offer surprises, upsets and genuine drama.
</P>
<P>
   With the move to Sunday night further shaking things up, and the
possibility of a boo-out for honorary winner Elia Kazan (still
loathed by much of Hollywood for naming names in the McCarthy era),
the 71st promises to be the most exciting Oscar show in years.
</P>
<P>
   Here, based on an unscientific mixture of the usual pre-Oscar
indicators, gut feelings, wild guesses and my own sense of who
deserves to win, are my personal picks:
</P>
<P>
   Best picture: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Madden
</P>
<P>
   Actor: Nick Nolte
</P>
<P>
   Actress: Gwyneth Paltrow
</P>
<P>
   Supporting actor: Ed Harris
</P>
<P>
   Supporting actress: Kathy Bates
</P>
<P>
   Foreign film: ``Life Is Beautiful''
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay (original): Marc Norman &AMP; Tom Stoppard, ``Shakespeare
in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay (adapted): Terrence Malick, ``The Thin Red Line''
</P>
<P>
   Art direction: ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Cinematography: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Sound: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Sound effects editing: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Musical or comedy score: ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic score: John Williams, ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``That'll Do,'' ``Babe: Pig in the City''
</P>
<P>
   Costume: ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Documentary feature: ``The Last Days''
</P>
<P>
   Makeup: ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Visual effects: ``What Dreams May Come''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
