A5570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACISM19-COX     03-18 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACISM19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE MEMBERS, CIVIL RIGHTS LEADERS CONDEMN 'RACIST' COUNCIL
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan group of House members, civil rights
leaders and conservative activists Thursday called on Congress to
adopt a resolution condemning the Council of Conservative Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The council ``attempts to mask its hateful ideology by posing as
a mainstream conservative think tank, but the racist agenda of this
group is undeniable,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., who
introduced the resolution and organized the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CCC has directed its hatred towards millions of Americans,
including African Americans, Hispanic Americans, Jewish Americans,
homosexuals, immigrants and virtually all minorities,'' Wexler
said.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which critics have dubbed the ``white-collar Ku Klux
Klan,'' became the center of political controversy recently after
it was reported that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
and Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., have spoken to the group. Lott and Barr
have disavowed the organization's views, but have declined to
condemn the group.
</P>
<P>
   The council issued a statement denying the allegations raised
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Council of Conservative Citizens categorically rejects
'white supremacy,' 'anti-Semitism,' 'neo-Nazi ideology' and the use
of violence, and we have always done so. These charges are lies,''
said Gordon L. Baum, the council's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Potok of the Southern Poverty Law Center said an
extensive study indicated ``there is a great deal of evidence that
this is a flat-out racist group.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension flared at the news conference when several people who
identified themselves as council members challenged Wexler to
denounce the militant Jewish Defense League. When Wexler declined
to comment, they yelled: ``Why the double standard?''
</P>
<P>
   The most devastating criticism of the group came from
conservative columnist and author Arianna Huffington, who called
for Gov. Kirk Fordice of Mississippi to denounce the group and for
former Vice President Dan Quayle to drop Fordice from Quayle's
presidential exploratory committee until he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to expressions of racism and bigotry, saying
that you disagree with them is not enough,'' Huffington said.
``There can be zero tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Huffington said the Republican Party's efforts to reach out to
blacks, Hispanics and other minorities were contradicted by the
failure of its leaders to condemn the council.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Andersen, president of the Douglass Policy Institute and a
vice chairman of the Republican National Committee's New Majority
Council, which is aimed at attracting blacks and other minorities
to the GOP, echoed Huffington's call for Quayle is disassociate
himself from Fordice.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Forbes, R-N.Y., said he was hopeful Wexler's
resolution would be allowed a vote by House leaders. An alternative
resolution condemning racism and anti-Semitism in general, but not
identifying any specific groups, has been offered by Rep. J.C.
Watts, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., chairman of the Congressional Black
Caucus, and Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., chairman of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus, said they were not trying to stifle
free speech but were taking a stand against the organization's
message.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
