</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-TIPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR NIGHT: TIPS FOR THE BEST VIEW AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Whoopi Goldberg opens the telecast of the 71st Academy
Awards ceremony Sunday, it will be like the season premiere of a
much-loved series, back by popular demand with a large cast of
familiar faces, and some new ones, too.
</P>
<P>
   After years of viewing the event, whether privately or at a
raucous Oscar Night bash, each of us knows pretty much what to
expect. But for anyone seeking a more fulfilling viewing
experience, we offer these guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   COMPLETE COVERAGE: Maybe it's the deluge of decolletage that
spills out at Oscar time like an avalanche of cantaloupes in the
produce aisle, but trust me on this: The sexiest fashions are the
ones that cover, not the ones that reveal.
</P>
<P>
   So don't spill merlot on the rug just to gaze upon the enhanced
flotation system of some fabric-challenged bimbette. The most vivid
Oscar-night image in my brain's photo gallery is of Nicole Kidman
two years ago in that spectacular high-necked chartreuse satin gown
by John Galliano. (As they say in all the fashion houses,
``Yowza!'') Right next to it is a shot of Jodie Foster from 1995 in
a higher-necked, jet-and-pearl beaded gown by Giorgio Armani.
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, friends, cleavage is just a town in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   PICKING OUT PATTERNS. When trying to handicap the Oscar race and
impress friends at the same time, it helps to be knowledgeable
about movie history.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you need to know Cecil B. DeMille's middle name
(Blount) or Lauren Bacall's real name (Betty Joan Perske). But it
might come in handy to know that, in four of the past five years,
the winner of the Oscar for best actor has had a one-syllable last
name (Hanks, Hanks, Cage and Rush).
</P>
<P>
   This year's only monosyllabic hopeful: the estimable Tom Hanks.
Similarly, in four of the past five years the woman voted best
actress has had a two-syllable first name (Holly, Susan, Frances
and Helen). This year's nominees so favored: Gwyneth Paltrow and
Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   BLADDER PATROL. For some time now, the Oscar telecast has been
gracious enough to provide at least five bathroom breaks. These
occur when each of the five nominees for Best Original Song is
performed by Celine Dion or a Disney character. Incidentally, if
``When You Believe'' from ``The Prince of Egypt'' wins the Oscar
this year, it will be the seventh time in the past 10 years that
the best song is from an animated film.
</P>
<P>
   BLATHER PATROL. Where's Camryn Mannheim when you need her?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the winners this year will issue more thank-yous in 30
seconds than they've sent in the past 10 years, but few will say
anything of substance. Aside from Hanks, who's good for a few
minutes of pithy discourse, and the British nominees, who usually
manage to seem erudite, Oscar winners tend to be a surprisingly
inarticulate bunch. You'd think creative people could come up with
more than ``you like me, you really like me!''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought: Starting next year, the Academy should require
the nominees to prepare a short essay on their feelings about
winning the Oscar. Then, as they're reciting their little essays on
stage, a crawl at the bottom of the TV screen could provide the
perfunctory information that no one wants to hear: ``The winner
would like to thank God/Allah/Disney, his/her family, the
producers, the director, the cast members, the key grip, the best
boy, the worst boy, his/her manager/agent/publicist, not to mention
his/her sixth-grade music/history/gym teacher, for this honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to pass along this idea to anyone you know at the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   POTTY ON, DUDE. To prevent a nationwide outbreak of nodding off
_ scientific term: acute zoning-out syndrome _ the Oscar telecast
has graciously shied away from the big production numbers in recent
years. Still, there's always a moment of tribute that allows for
taking an additional potty break, or putting out the recycling
bins, or separating the junk mail from the important stuff like
Pizza Hut coupons.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with two war films in the spotlight, viewers can
probably expect a ``Kudos to Khaki'' salute sometime during the
evening. These are good times to take a breather, unless you have a
burning need to see John Wayne die one more time in ``Sands of Iwo
Jima.''
</P>
<P>
   MAN FOR ALL SEASONS. John Madden is nominated as best director
for ``Shakespeare in Love.'' If he wins, don't expect him to thank
Pat Summerall and all the folks at Fox Sports. It's not that John
Madden.
</P>
<P>
   QUIET ON THE SET. People who eat in the living room during an
Oscar telecast are protected by the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Example: If someone is holding a bowl of Chee-tos and a person
sitting nearby makes a hostile grab for some, the Chee-tos party
can invoke the Fourth Amendment, which covers illegal search and
seizure. However, if the Cheetos party hasn't had the sense to take
the Cheetos out of the bag and is rustling so noisily that no one
can hear Whoopi Goldberg explain the balloting procedures, the
aggrieved party can cite the Eighth Amendment's protection against
cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, it is permissible to send the violator to
another room and force him to watch whatever is on CBS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
