<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL TRAGEDY BRINGS A `HA!' WHEN JULIA SWEENEY TALKS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talking head, one-person shows are, more often than not, tricky
balancing acts that turn into laborious, unsatisfying moviegoing
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Since cinema is such a visual medium, it's hard to keep interest
in a solo running dialogue filmed on a single set unless it's done
exceptionally well.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Julia Sweeney recounts her very personal
experiences dealing with parents, siblings, dreams and the deck of
cards we're dealt in life, as opposed to the hand we'd prefer to
have, with such great humor, wonder and wryness that the concept
works with grace and ease in ``God Said, `Ha!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her funny, intimate film, based on her stage show, was so
universal in appeal that it won the Golden Space Needle award for
best film at last year's Seattle International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for her work as a regular on ``Saturday Night Live''
and for the sexually ambiguous character Pat (whom she thankfully
avoids here), Sweeney recalls how she had just gone through a
friendly divorce, bought the bungalow of her dreams in Los Angeles
and was looking forward to spending some time alone reading,
cooking and hanging out with her cats.
</P>
<P>
   But fate intervened: Her brother Mike, who was diagnosed with
cancer, moved into her new pad. After Mike came her parents, who
made the long drive from Spokane, Wash., to be with their dying
son. The family cohabitated in Sweeney's little house for seven
months and, just when the cords were about to fray, Sweeney was
diagnosed with a rare form of cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney recounts how she immediately became a kid again under
her parents' surveillance and how hard it was to deal with dating
and sex beneath her folks' omnipresent eye.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a truckload of tragedy _ enough to make any sane person
crack under the stress and strain _ she touchingly proves with this
enjoyable visit, which was produced by her pal Quentin Tarantino,
that laughter is the best medicine for heartbreak and pain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
