<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER AIDS, ALONG COMES A NEW KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, March 25)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marshall Aronowitz needs $250,000 for a liver. He doesn't think
he's going to raise it, yet he has no choice but to try. He needs a
liver transplant and insurance won't cover it because he is HIV
positive and people infected with the AIDS virus don't usually
qualify for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall, who has lived for more than 15 years without
getting AIDS, thinks he's a good guinea pig. If a transplant works
for him, he says he'll be doing medical science a favor.
</P>
<P>
   The ironic part about Marshall's surviving AIDS is that two
years ago he found out he has hepatitis C. This is starting to be a
common double whammy for people who are dealing with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   For years he worried about getting something that had killed
most of his friends and would likely kill him. ``I don't know why I
survived,'' he says. ``All of my crowd are dead.'' He said one day
he started calling people he knew in different parts of the world
and it was the same with his friends in San Francisco. All gone.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall lived, only to be tapped on the shoulder by another
would-be killer.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can now do more for someone with AIDS than they can with
hepatitis C. About the only thing they can do to fight hepatitis C,
which attacks the liver, is a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   But people with compromised immune systems, like AIDS patients,
were long considered bad risks for organ transplants because after
the procedure patients have to be on immune suppressor drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors began to rethink that a couple of years ago when the
epidemic changed and people started to live with new treatment
therapies. Marshall has been free of any of the infections
associated with AIDS and shows virtually no evidence of the virus
in his body. In December he qualified for a transplant and went on
the national liver registry at UCSF-Stanford Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so few HIV patients with organ transplants that
it's too early to show a success rate. Many insurance companies,
like Marshall's, aren't yet convinced. Neither is MediCal.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the request for a quarter of a million dollars so he can
pay for it himself, if and when he moves to the top of the
transplant list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be living proof. My duty is to get this transplant
and stay very healthy and live very long so insurance companies
will no longer be able to say there's no proof it works. It's not
just for me. It's for anyone who follows me.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, after he tested HIV positive, he closed his
picture-framing and art restoration business in San Francisco, sold
his little Victorian and moved to rural Lake County where he
expected his condition to worsen and he'd die like his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid for two to three years to live,'' he says. All he hoped
for was not to die before his old Doberman. He made it through that
one's life and now has another Doberman.
</P>
<P>
   Things were starting to look up. He thought about working again.
Then two years ago he was diagnosed with hepatitis C, which he
figures he probably contracted about the same time he did the AIDS
virus. But this killer is even more insidious and took longer to
announce itself.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall speaks with great urgency and hauls out medical
records, transplant studies and medical journals from a bulging
briefcase to make his case. But he agrees he's asking for the moon
and that the world is full of needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me I haven't a chance in hell of raising
this enormous amount of money, but I have to show some
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   For a man who has lost just about everyone near and dear, he has
an amazing amount of hope and trust that things will go his way.
</P>
<P>
   His family, two sisters and an aunt, live in Florida where he
grew up. They can help out a little, but Marshall doesn't want to
lean on them.
</P>
<P>
   They actually thought he was dead until a few years ago.
``They'd been saying Kaddish (mourning prayer for the dead) for me
every year on my birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Rejoining the family circle, he says, ``has made life worth
living.''
</P>
<P>
   He's printed letters explaining his situation which he's sent to
friends and acquaintances and intends to distribute at an upcoming
AIDS conference in San Francisco. He's been trying to get to
Elizabeth Taylor and Sharon Stone, who both raise money for AIDS
research, and Naomi Judd, who does the same for hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can fund the first few transplants for people like me
and they're successful, then there won't be a reason for insurance
companies not to fund.''
</P>
<P>
   He's pretty indomitable even though he gets tired and has pain
from his fourth-stage cirrhosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me the other day they wished they had a new car
and I said, `Me, too, but I'll settle for a used liver.'''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
