<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-     03-18 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAND OF SUN AROUND A BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Once upon a time, when there were more orange
groves than golf courses in Florida, Tampa Bay was surrounded by a
series of distinct communities: industrial, ethnically mixed Tampa,
white-bread St. Petersburg and its retirees from the Midwest,
laid-back Bradenton and Clearwater and, down the coast a bit,
artsy, cosmopolitan Sarasota, where the circus spent the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never went to St. Petersburg,'' says my colleague David
Rosenbaum, who grew up in Tampa in the 1940s and '50s. ``We had the
port and the unions and Latins; they had the beaches and tourists
and shuffleboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in fact if not law, it's one big metropolitan area, laced
together with bridges and freeways. People watch the same
television stations and root for the same professional sports
teams. Many of them send their children to the booming, multicampus
University of South Florida. They shop at the same enormous malls,
like the the brand-new Citrus Park Town Center, until recently a
pasture, which drew upward of 100,000 cars on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   On the road maps, this entity of 2.5 million people doesn't
exist. Only the old place names are there. But everyone calls it
Tampa Bay, and it is a prototypical example of the Sun Belt's
explosive growth. Its subdivisions (mostly gated now) sprawl under
postcard-blue skies. Its service-based economy thrives, and
cultural and sporting diversions thrive with it.
</P>
<P>
   Even baseball spring training, a seasonal ritual hereabouts for
decades, is attracting new interest, thanks to last season's home
run derby and the sprucing up of some of the ball parks where the
big leaguers strut their stuff. No fewer than six teams train in
the area, including the New York Yankees, whose main owner, George
Steinbrenner, is a Tampa tycoon. They play their springtime games
at the immodestly named Legends Field at 1 Steinbrenner Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Summertime, and the living is easy, the Gershwins wrote; if they
had lived in Tampa Bay, they might have mentioned the other
seasons, too.
</P>
<P>
   The First Tourist
</P>
<P>
   Historians think Hernando de Soto was Tampa Bay's first tourist,
landing near modern Bradenton in 1539 and lingering only briefly
before heading west on a fruitless search for jewels and gold that
ended with his death on the banks of the Mississippi in 1542.
</P>
<P>
   Not much happened for the three centuries after that, until
Henry B. Plant built a railroad linking the bay to the rest of the
country in 1883. In 1891 he added the astonishing 500-room Tampa
Bay Hotel, built in an eccentric Moorish style, with keyhole-shaped
windows and 13 silvery minarets topped with golden crescents. It
had telephones in the rooms, electric lights, a private casino, two
ballrooms, a billiard room and a peacock park, almost making good
on Plant's pledge to ``turn this sandheap into the
Champs-Elysees.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa was the staging point for the U.S. forces dispatched to
Cuba in the Spanish-American War, and in the summer of 1898 the
Tampa Bay Hotel provided a broad veranda where Army and Navy
officers and assorted hangers-on could sit in rocking chairs,
sipping champagne and iced tea, waiting for orders.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Theodore Roosevelt was one of them, slipping away from
his Rough Riders camped on the flats east of town, according to
historian Edmund Morris, to spend three nights with his wife,
Edith, in one of the hotel's grander suites.
</P>
<P>
   One hot, sticky night, Roosevelt and his handpicked men rode
their horses into a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The expeditionary force sailed away in June, its commander
having received his orders to embark while coffee was being served
at the hotel one evening. The hotel never recaptured the glory of
the Gay Nineties, and it closed in 1930. But it still stands as a
monument to the man who built the Gulf Coast, used partly as a
municipal museum and partly by the University of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Waterfront Museums
</P>
<P>
   Once its railroad came, St. Petersburg flourished by luring
white-collar refugees from the cruel winters and high taxes in
Ohio, Michigan and Indiana. It is one of those cities, like Des
Moines, that were shaped by newspaper editors with a determination
to lead. They, too, came from the Midwest: W.L. Straub, who stopped
the industrialization of the waterfront, preserving it for tourism,
and his successor at The St. Petersburg Times, Nelson Poynter, who
campaigned hard for good government and civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Three art museums have opened along the waterfront in recent
years, lending a new dimension to the city and contributing to a
regional surge of cultural development. Oldest is the Museum of
Fine Arts, whose 20 galleries house a small but comprehensive
permanent collection. Its highlights, for me, include an
aggressively scarlet ``Poppy'' by Georgia O'Keeffe; a subtle Lely
portrait of Nell Gwyn, the actress mistress of Charles II; a
shimmering Monet from the Parliament series, ``Effect of Fog,'' and
a supremely 1920s portrait of Mr. and Mrs. Chester Dale,
benefactors of the National Gallery in Washington, by Guy Pene du
Bois.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, improbably sited next to a pleasure-boat
marina, is the world's largest collection of paintings and drawings
by the flamboyant Catalan Surrealist, Salvador Dali. There are
plenty of ``melting'' watches and a telephone shaped like a
lobster, the kinds of things that made Dali's fame, but the four
immense ``masterworks'' are the star attractions. The best of them,
``The Discovery of America by Christopher Columbus,'' pays homage
to the explorer, to Dali's idol, Velazquez, and to Dali's wife and
muse, Gala.
</P>
<P>
   The third of the trio, the Florida International Museum, housed
in a former Maas Brothers department store, is not so much a museum
as a 20,000-square-foot hall for hire. It has no collection of its
own, relying instead on a succession of special shows: Romanov
treasures, artifacts of the Incas and, soon, roomsful of personal
effects and other objects associated with John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
