 (Eds.: Newspapers that used the Boston Globe story ISRAEL-JERUSALEM
(i) by Charles M. Sennott, which moved this week, will wish to use
the following corrective.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Because of an editing error, a Boston Globe story about Ariel
Sharon gave the wrong site for the 1993 peace accord between
Israelis and Palestinians. The agreement was negotiated in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-     03-18 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TAMPA: F. Kennedy.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To get to the best museum in the region, perhaps the best in
Florida, you have to take a drive. Happily, you go by way of the
magnificent Sunshine Skyway Bridge across the mouth of Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1987, patterned after the Brotonne Bridge across the
Seine near Rouen, it is supported by a single, central set of
cables rather than cables on both sides of the roadway. Many
consider it the most impressive span built in this country since
the Golden Gate Bridge in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   It will take you, eventually, to Sarasota, and the John and
Mable Ringling Museum of Art, a spectacular Italianate bayfront
building with gleaming white rooftop statues. Inside the spectacle
continues; Ringling was a circus man, with little taste for
understatement. He sought to stun with art as he did under the Big
Top, so he bought pictures by Baroque masters like Rubens and
Pietro da Cortona at a time when their exuberance was out of
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Today they anchor a collection of rare originality that ranges
from Guercino to Titian to Piero di Cosimo's ``Building of a
Palace.'' The high point, perhaps, is the quartet of gigantic
tapestry cartoons by Rubens, bought in 1926 from the Duke of
Westminster and shown in a 40-foot-high gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Performance Time
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota is also a center for the performing arts. Every
February and March its opera company stages four productions, and
it does not confine itself to warhorses. This year's program
includes ``May Night,'' an early, little-known, folkloric piece by
Rimsky-Korsakov, based on a Gogol story.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly for a city of only 50,000 or so, Sarasota supports
a 40-year-old Equity company at the Asolo Theater, adjacent to the
Ringling museum. Its current eight-month season includes new plays
by Jane Martin and Richard Greenberg, as well as four one-act
comedies by Shaw and plays by Wilder, Sheridan, Odets, Sherwood,
Joan Littlewood, Alfred Uhry and Steve Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Each June, Sarasota stages a well-regarded chamber music
festival, and all year long the Van Wezel Performing Arts Hall,
painted a jarring shade of purple, presents an almost nightly
parade of visiting musicians. Recently the Boston Pops, the Berlin
Radio Symphony under Rafael Fruhbeck de Burgos and the Moscow
Philharmonic have paid calls, along with the Moiseyev Dance
Company, the Guarneri String Quartet and Bernadette Peters. (Next
month, it closes for several months of repairs.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact the whole area is on a performing arts roll, with Ruth
Eckerd Hall in Clearwater, the Mahaffey Theater in St. Petersburg
and the huge Tampa Bay Performing Arts Center in Tampa full to
overflowing with music and drama. On a single night not long ago
the local music fan could choose among Gordon Lightfoot, Tony
Bennett, the Rolling Stones and the Vienna Choir Boys.
</P>
<P>
   And that is not even reckoning with the Florida Orchestra, which
plays a seven-month season in several halls under the music
directorship of Jahja Ling, who is also Christoph von Dohnanyi's
No. 2 in Cleveland. The orchestra administers to the bay the
prescribed monthly doses of Mozart, Mahler and Beethoven, but this
year it has also programmed works by Hovhaness, Kodaly and William
Schuman.
</P>
<P>
   An Airport's Impact
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, bigger has proved to be better for Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the Tampa airport, which must be the best in the
country. Opened in 1972 and currently undergoing modernization, it
is more convenient in its state of upheaval than most airports at
their most settled. The main terminal is linked to four remote
buildings, housing the gates, by fast two-car automated trains that
run above ground, up in the sunshine, not buried in some dingy
tunnel. Bright, close in, with plenty of elevators and escalators
and lots of easily understood signs, TPA ought to be cloned
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the climate _ the sun is said to shine 361 days a
year _ the airport has helped to attract all kinds of businesses,
including the Home Shopping Network and back-office operations for
big financial institutions, as well as biotechnology and other
high-technology companies. (``High-tech in the mangroves,'' a local
booster calls them.)
</P>
<P>
   It has also brought tourists, who head west to 50 miles of
beaches along the Gulf of Mexico and east to Busch Gardens, the
wildly popular offshoot of the local Budweiser brewery.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Kingdoms
</P>
<P>
   You can take your wild animals in Tampa with or without roller
coasters. For the purist, there is the fine Lowry Park Zoo, where
you can see not only a Sumatran tiger but also a rare Florida
panther and a rarer Indian rhinoceros. It also specializes in the
rehabilitation of the manatee, an endangered species of huge,
cowlike marine creatures. Only 2,500 remain in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Busch Gardens is bigger and brassier. It has four roller
coasters, which flip and plunge and twist and climb until you think
you've left your insides in another time zone, and bumper cars
called Ubanga-Banga. (Geddit?) Its theme is Africa, more or less,
but no one is too rigorous about it; you will see koalas from
Australia and elephants from India and flamingos from Chile, too.
The ``Nairobi'' train station looks just like South Africa, not
Kenya, and the dolphin show inexplicably takes place in a mock-up
of landlocked Timbuktu.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
