<SLUG> BC-TV-EARTHLY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EARTHLY POSSESSIONS' REALLY STACKS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just to get noticed, familiar stories need special treatment. In
``Earthly Possessions,'' a pleasant HBO film based on the Anne
Tyler novel, it starts with the casting of Susan Sarandon in a rare
television role.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad beginning. But ``Earthly Possessions'' on Saturday has
a lot more going for it, including a sprightly script by Steven
Rogers (``Hope Floats'') and direction by James Lapine
(``Impromptu'') that makes an older woman/younger man romance
reasonably plausible.
</P>
<P>
   Though ages aren't specifically mentioned, it is safe to assume
that Sarandon's character, Charlotte Emory, is at least a
generation older than Stephen Dorff's unsophisticated bank robber,
Jake Simms, Jr. And yet a romantic connection between the two _ a
disillusioned homemaker taken hostage by a confused criminal _
makes sense in the chemistry Sarandon and Dorff manage to achieve.
Certainly it's more honest than the older man/younger woman
linkages so popular in current filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tyler's hostage-in-love story is so timeworn, the key to
its success is the eccentricity of the characters. While Lapine
spends little time on Tyler's goofy assortment of supporting
players, he does coax enough oddness out of Sarandon to make
``Earthly Possessions'' richer than it might have been without her.
</P>
<P>
   With a beguiling sparkle in her wide-set eyes, Sarandon
successfully negotiates the trip from sheltered wife planning to
leave her husband, to frightened victim unsure of her future, to
sympathetic companion winning her captor's trust, to complicitous
lover willing to risk her life for his.
</P>
<P>
   As the film starts, both are failures in their lives, or so they
think. At the end, after several days on the lam, their voyage of
self-discovery has changed them both. Yes, we've seen this
transformation before, but Sarandon and Dorff make it a trip worth
taking again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-     03-18 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TAMPA: landlocked Timbuktu.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But I doubt that there is anywhere else on this continent with
anything to rival the hundreds of antelopes and other animals that
roam more or less freely on Busch Gardens' simulation of the
Serengeti Plain. Many are rarities, seldom encountered in Africa:
greater kudus and blesboks, elands and addaxes, sable antelopes and
magnificent roan antelopes, bred at the park. Hokey the rides may
be, but the young staff members care a lot about the animals; one
of them, Erin Leach, spent 20 minutes establishing for me that a
spectacularly colored bird that neither of us recognized was a
saddle-billed stork.
</P>
<P>
   A good sequel to either Busch Gardens or the zoo is the new
Florida Aquarium in downtown Tampa, an $84 million, shell-shaped
extravaganza in green glass whose tanks contain exhibits of aquatic
life on Florida's coral reefs, in its oceanic depths and in its
streams and mangrove swamps _ everything from menacing sharks to
playful river otters to darting rainbow parrotfish.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of Identity
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is crazy about Tampa Bay's coming of age, and St.
Petersburg, in particular, worries about losing its identity.
Politicians there, and taxpayers, too, complain that visiting
out-of-towners too often assume they are in Tampa. They grumble
about politicians and reporters who came for the vice presidential
debate in 1996, and sportswriters who come to cover the new Tampa
Bay Devil Rays baseball team at the slope-domed Tropicana Field in
St. Petersburg, also the site of this year's college basketball
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa has lost something, too, in the regional amalgamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are turning Tampa into the customary nothing,''
complained mystery writer John D. MacDonald a quarter-century ago
in one of his Travis McGee novels, ``Bright Orange for the
Shroud.'' ``They've opened up the center of the city into a more
spacious characterlessness, and more and more they are converting
Ybor City into fake New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual the gloriously grumpy MacDonald overstated the case. If
the post-modern skyscrapers of downtown Tampa lack architectural
distinction, it is much less sterile than many late-blooming
cities, and the bankers, lawyers and deal makers have to work
somewhere, don't they? As for Ybor City, where Hispanic tobacco
workers and Italian immigrants once lived, it has indeed turned
into an ersatz French Quarter, loaded with wrought-iron balconies
and chockablock with bars; on Friday and Saturday nights, it
belongs to the young and the rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   Old-Time Flavor
</P>
<P>
   Only faint hints remain of the days, long before a new
generation of immigrants arrived from Castro's Cuba, when Ybor City
was the cigar capital of the world. Along Seventh Avenue, you can
still see the Columbia Restaurant, now frequented mainly by
tourists, and the neoclassical Italian Club.
</P>
<P>
   But Tampa has not lost all of its authentic Latin flavor. To
sample that, visit La Teresita at 3248 West Columbus Drive, a
landmark Cuban-American restaurant with green oilcloth on the
tables, nestled amid shabby stores selling guava turnovers and
Cuban sandwiches, not far from the airport. Go for Sunday lunch if
you can, eat the Capdevila family's wonderful black beans and
yellow rice, with vinegary roast pork on the side, and drink a cafe
con leche. (I did; it cost $8.81 with tax and tip.) And be sure to
look around. The clientele is young and old, rich and poor, Anglo
as well as Latino: rednecks mingling with blue rinses, young girls
in communion dresses with older ones wearing skimpy crop-tops.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has St. Petersburg (named by a pioneer developer for his
Russian hometown) lost all its old Midwestern blandness in the rush
to tomorrow. It remains a low-key place, represented by politicians
like Rep. C.W. Bill Young, the chairman of the powerful House
Appropriations Committee, a conservative, of course, but not the
kind who goes out of his way to punch you in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   If you linger a while in the vicinity of Fourth Avenue North and
Fifth Street, you will see institutions that cater to the city's
still sizable geriatric population: the St. Petersburg Chess Club,
the St. Petersburg Lawn Bowling Club, founded in 1926, and the
proudly self-proclaimed ``World's Largest Shuffleboard and
Duplicate Bridge Club,'' on the shore of Mirror Lake.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A VISIT TO THE TAMPA BAY AREA
</P>
<P>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting the Tampa Bay area of
Florida:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   DON CESAR BEACH RESORT, 3400 Gulf Boulevard, St. Pete Beach,
(727) 360-1881. Discerningly restored a few years ago, this
peachy-pink neo-Moorish palace, built in 1928, offers a fine beach,
a spa, tennis courts, two pools and 232 handsome rooms. If Scott
and Zelda stayed there, as everyone says, they knew the town as St.
Petersburg Beach; local lawmakers, no poets, later clipped off two
syllables in the interests of brevity. Double room rate: $289 to
$329 weekdays; $319 to $359 on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   HYATT REGENCY WESTSHORE, 6200 Courtney Campbell Causeway, Tampa,
(813) 874-1234. Facing tranquil Tampa Bay, surrounded by flora and
fountains, this crisply up-to-date, 14-story, 400-room hotel stands
a head or two taller than the average Hyatt. It has three top-notch
restaurants; Oystercatchers, named after a clever, bivalve-loving
local bird, serves the region's best seafood. Double room rate:
$225 weekdays; $149 on weekends through April, then $179.
</P>
<P>
   LONGBOAT KEY CLUB, 301 Gulf of Mexico Drive, Longboat Key, (941)
383-8821. A resort, not really a club, on the strip of land across
Sarasota Bay from Ringling-town, it emphasizes sports, with 45
championship golf holes and 38 tennis courts. The 213 trim rooms
have kitchens and washer-dryers. Double room rate: $220 to $335;
apartments from $270 to $735.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-     03-18 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-TAMPA-BAY-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TAMPA: to $735.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENAISSANCE VINOY RESORT, 501 Fifth Avenue NE, St. Petersburg,
(727) 894-1000. On the bayfront in downtown St. Petersburg, the
Vinoy is another reborn survivor from the 1920s. Pink as a flamingo
on the outside, ornate on the inside, with stenciled pecky cypress
beams in the lobby, it is listed on the National Register of
Historic Places. Its 360 luxurious rooms, plus pools, steam room,
tennis courts and croquet lawn, attract an affluent clientele.
Double room rate: $259; $139 starting in June.
</P>
<P>
   WYNDHAM HARBOUR ISLAND, 725 South Harbour Island Boulevard,
Tampa, (813) 229-5000. There's nothing too special about this
modern establishment except the location, but that's very special
indeed: on an artificial island, linked by bridge and monorail to
skyscraper-studded downtown Tampa. The rooms are amply sized, and
there's an on-site marina, if you're taking your sailboat. Double
room rate: $149; $99 in April.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   BEACH BISTRO, 6600 Gulf Drive, Anna Maria Island, west of
Bradenton, (941) 778-6444. Four good reasons to visit this
out-of-the-way spot: 1. remarkable smoked salmon, which the
Canadian proprietor imports weekly from J. Willy Krauch, an
artisanal smoker in Tangier, Nova Scotia; 2. moist, perfectly
cooked grouper, the local fish of choice; 3. a bountiful wine list,
which includes Australia's prized Grange and five vintages of
Chateau Pichon Longueville; 4. fabulous sunsets over the gulf. Only
one quibble: Here as elsewhere in the area there is a regrettable
tendency to litter plates with superfluous garnishes.
</P>
<P>
   BOCA, 1930 E. Seventh Ave., Ybor City section of Tampa, (813)
241-2622. Boca's Nueva Latina dishes include shrimp ajillo (with
garlic), exceptional flan and updated Cuban sandwiches (ham, roast
pork and Swiss cheese on light Cuban bread). The surprise is the
house salad, a tangy blend of field greens, manchego cheese,
tomatoes and onions, dressed with a guava- and chili-flavored
vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   MISE EN PLACE, 442 West Kennedy Boulevard, Tampa, (813)
254-5373. Marty Blitz pioneered modern American cooking in the
region, and his restaurant remains the local leader. A plate of
tasty house-made charcuterie epitomizes the ambition and technical
savvy of the kitchen. I was taken with a mustard-crusted rack of
lamb, served on a hillock of Cheddar grits and moistened with a
bourbon shallot demi-glace. The room is suave, the service less so.
</P>
<P>
   TED PETERS SMOKED FISH, 1350 Pasadena Avenue South, St.
Petersburg (727) 381-7931. This is the place, a local foodie told
me, that he'd take Calvin Trillin to if he ever came to St.
Petersburg. Since 1950, not long after the proprietor pulled into
town from Olean, N.Y., this roadside shack has dished up definitive
versions of local delicacies like smoked mackerel and gray mullet,
as well as a tangy fish spread that tastes best on saltines.
</P>
<P>
   REDWOOD, 247 Central Ave., St. Petersburg, (727) 896-5118.
Competent Pacific Rim cooking near the Atlantic rim, in a restored
downtown storefront. I wish the menu featured more fish from the
gulf and less marlin, albacore and yellowfin flown across the
continent, but that didn't keep me from enjoying a nicely presented
sashimi of rich ahi tuna coated with sesame seeds. The handsome
copper bar is stocked with premium cognacs and single-batch
bourbons.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBERN'S, 2208 West Morrison Ave., Tampa, (813) 258-2233. For
decades the only Tampa Bay restaurant with a national reputation
was Bern's, known for an awesome wine list, good steaks and not
much else. It carries on. But the sizzle has shifted to SideBern's,
down the street, where Jeannie Pierola, a gifted young chef of
eclectic bent, sets off fireworks nightly with westernized dim sum,
like duck buns with vinegar syrup and crab-lobster dumplings with
tamarind butter; Moroccan seared red snapper with harissa, and
(homage to the older generation) a dynamic duo of short ribs and
hanger steak. Selections from Bern's cellar insure that you won't
leave thirsty.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS, 255 Beach Drive, St. Petersburg, (727)
896-2667. Through May 31, ``Treasures of Chinese Glass Workshops:
Qing Dynasty Glass.'' Through June 13, ``In the American Spirit:
Realism and Impressionism.'' Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to
5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m. Admission: $6; $5 for the elderly; $2
for students; free on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR DALI MUSEUM, 1000 Third Street South, St. Petersburg,
(727) 823-3767. Mondays through Saturdays, 9:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.;
Sundays, noon to 5:30 p.m. Admission: $9; $7 for the elderly; $5
for students.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA INTERNATIONAL MUSEUM, 100 Second Street North, St.
Petersburg, (800) 777-9882. ``Empires of Mystery,'' objects from
the Incas and their predecessors; through May 16. Sundays through
Fridays, 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.; Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. Admission:
$13.95; $5.95 for students.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN AND MABLE RINGLING MUSEUM OF ART, 5401 Bay Shore Road,
Sarasota, (941) 359-5700. ``Blurring the Boundaries: Installation
Art 1969-1996,'' through May 2. ``Restoration and Rediscovery:
Craft and Materials in the Ca' d'Zan Restoration,'' through May
2000. Daily, 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Admission: $9; $8 for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   VAN WEZEL PERFORMING ARTS HALL, 777 North Tamiami Trail,
Sarasota, (941) 955-7676. March 19 at 8: Nikolais Dance,
modern-dance group; tickets, $24 to $28. March 20 at 8 p.m.:
Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden; tickets, $60 to
$75; $10 student rush tickets available day of concert. Sunday at 8
p.m.: Los Angeles Philharmonic; tickets, $65 to $70.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY PERFORMING ARTS CENTER, 1010 North W.C. MacInnes
Place, Tampa, (813) 222-1000. March 19 at 7:30, March 20 and 21 at
2 p.m. and 7:30 p.m.: ``Hollywood Nights,'' a cabaret performance
about film history; tickets, $15 to $36. March 20 at 8 p.m.:
``Bayou to Bourbon Street,'' Cajun, Creole-zydeco and New Orleans
jazz; tickets, $15.50 to $29.50.
</P>
<P>
   ASOLO THEATER, 5555 North Tamiami Trail, Sarasota, (941)
351-8000. March 19 at 8: ``Ladies of the Chamelions.'' March 20 at
8 p.m.: ``Abraham Lincoln in Illinois.'' Sunday at 8 p.m.: ``The
Rivals.'' Tickets, $12 to $38.
</P>
<P>
   SARASOTA OPERA COMPANY, 61 N. Pineapple Ave., Sarasota, (941)
366-8450. March 19 at 7:30, Bizet's ``Carmen.'' March 20 at 2 p.m.,
Puccini's ``Rondine''; at 8 p.m., Verdi's ``Luisa Miller.'' March
21 at 2 p.m., Rimsky-Korsakov's ``May Night''; at 8 p.m., Studio
Artists present ensembles and arias. Tickets: $15 to $380; Studio
Artists concert, $15 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH GARDENS, 3605 Bougainvillea Avenue, Tampa, (813) 987-5082.
Daily, 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission: $40.95; $34.95 for children
under 9.
</P>
<P>
   LOWRY PARK ZOO, North Boulevard at Sligh Avenue, Tampa, (813)
932-0245. Daily, 9:30 a.m to 5 p.m. Admission: $8.50; $7.50 for the
elderly; $4.95 for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA AQUARIUM, 701 Channelside Drive, Tampa, (813) 273-4000.
Daily, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $11.95; $10.95 for the
elderly; $6.95 for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There From New York
</P>
<P>
   From La Guardia Airport, American Airlines offers a nonstop
flight to Tampa-St. Petersburg, and Midway Airlines has a flight
with a stop in Raleigh, N.C.. Delta Airlines and Trans World
Airlines offer nonstop flights out of Kennedy Airport. For these
airlines, a 14-day advance fare with a Saturday night stay-over is
$190. A three-day advance fare is also $190, but travel is limited
to Saturday, Tuesday and Wednesday, depending on availability.
Information: American Airlines, (800) 433-7300 or www.aa.com;
Delta, (800) 221-1212 or www.delta-air.com; Midway, (800) 446-4392
or www.midwayair.com; Trans World Airlines, (800) 221-2000 or
www.twa.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
