<SLUG> BC-TV-FARSCAPE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALING `FARSCAPE' BLASTS OFF ON RATHER CHEEKY TRAJECTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anyone can't wait till ``Star Wars'' mania officially kicks
into warp drive in May, there's always ``Farscape'' on the Sci-Fi
Channel. Starring Ben Browder in the hunky-guy role and Australian
actress Claudia Black in the strong-woman role, ``Farscape'' isn't
groundbreaking science fiction, but it's made passable by the
special effects of the Jim Henson Company and Hallmark
Entertainment, both of which collaborated on such ambitious network
miniseries as ``Gulliver's Travels'' and ``The Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   Browder (``Party of Five'') plays John Crichton, an American
astronaut/scientist who gives new meaning to ``lost in space.'' In
Friday night's (March 19) premiere, a NASA experiment accidentally
sends him into a galaxy so far away that no one is ever bothered by
telemarketers selling AT&AMP;T long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   Small consolation. Crichton ends up in the middle of a galactic
war and ultimately aboard a living, breathing alien spaceship _
later in the season it will actually get pregnant _ with some
escaped prisoners and a stranded soldier named Aeryn Sun (Black).
</P>
<P>
   Although not a comedy, ``Farscape'' tries to pass along the
``Star Trek'' do-unto-others message with a lighter touch,
alternating between life-and-death moments and frothy quips from
Crichton. Example: While holding a couple of bad guys at bay with a
weapon completely unfamiliar to him, our hero says: ``Don't move or
I'll fill you full of little yellow bolts of light.''
</P>
<P>
   The tongue-in-cheekiness of ``Farscape'' is part of its appeal _
Crichton's name rhymes with that of the android Kryten from ``Red
Dwarf'' _ and sci-fi fans will no doubt find all sorts of homages
to other shows that have boldly gone before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
