<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO19-COX     03-18 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE REJECTS EFFORT TO CONTROL TOBACCO MONEY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate rejected an effort Thursday to force
states to spend at least half of their money from tobacco
settlements on health-related programs.
</P>
<P>
   The 71-29 vote came on an amendment by Rep. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., to the $1.9 billion supplemental appropriations bill now
being considered by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a right and obligation to say that some portion of
that money, that federal money, ought to go to health-related
obligations,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who led the effort
with Specter.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators argued that without their amendment, states
could use tobacco money for any purpose. They said at least half
should be specifically earmarked for health care and smoking
reduction programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Rep. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, attached an
amendment to the spending bill that would prevent the federal
government from claiming a share of state tobacco settlements. The
Clinton administration has taken the position that the federal
government is entitled to a portion of the money under the Medicaid
law.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of that position argued that the states fought and won
the legal battles and are entitled to spend the money as they
please.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to tell Texas how to spend its money, quit the
Senate, move to Texas ... and run for the state Legislature,'' said
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``The federal government needs to butt
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, the tobacco industry settled with the states,
agreeing to pay $40 billion over 25 years to settle four state
lawsuits, including Texas's, and an additional $206 billion in a
broader deal with the other 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced in January that he was instructing the Justice
Department to initiate a suit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
