<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5595 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTORS-TYPECASTING-TE     03-18 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-TYPECASTING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C'MON. MOVIEGOERS WON'T PAY TO SEE CLINT EASTWOOD MAKE LIKE THE
DALAI LAMA
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ACTORS-REINVENTED) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After ``Speed'' made Sandra Bullock America's mid-'90s
sweetheart, the actress spent three years playing variations on
that plucky-woman-against-the-world role. Then in 1997, Bullock
became bored and tried to stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bullock tried to play romantic and ``serious'' as a World
War I nurse who falls for a young Ernest Hemingway in the flop ``In
Love and War''; then she starred in ``Speed 2: Cruise Control,''
one of the worst blockbusters of the decade. Bullock became an
annoying party girl in that sequel; she was still fighting the
world, but by stamping her feet on it as hard as she could.
</P>
<P>
   After last year's popular but calculated ``Hope Floats'' and the
uneven but entertaining ``Practical Magic,'' Bullock is stamping
her feet again in ``Forces of Nature,'' a forced romantic comedy
that opens Friday. ``Forces'' is loud and abrasive, but it will
probably have a good opening weekend because it shows Bullock as we
want to see her: playing, essentially, Sandra Bullock, albeit an
irritating version.
</P>
<P>
   If her last three movies are any indication, Bullock has learned
a sad truth about movies: There are stars, and there are actors,
and only rarely do the two meet. There are people we go to see
perform, and there are people such as Bullock we go to see because
of their personalities or looks: their beaming or impish smiles,
their cocky or terse one-liners, their effortless charm, even their
machismo. But for some stars, it's not enough that they're paid
millions of dollars and have the adulation of millions; they want
to prove that they can ``act.'' They don't understand how they can
be loved without being respected.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, more often than not, these stretches fail. Clint
Eastwood, also in a movie opening Friday (''True Crime'') learned
the hard way: After more than a decade of playing laconic action
heroes in spaghetti westerns and ``Dirty Harry'' movies, Eastwood
spent much of the late '70s and all of the 1980s trying to prove
that he could be something more, alternating a series of
self-mocking roles with his more traditional tough-guy persona.
</P>
<P>
   Only the tough-guy movies worked, and even then sporadically,
but Eastwood wouldn't settle down till 1992's ``Unforgiven,'' an
Oscar-winning movie that revised his image without parodying it.
He's back to growling and squinting, even in tear-jerkers such as
``The Bridges of Madison County,'' and among the few things that
work in the ludicrous ``True Crime'' are the occasional moments
when he all but spits his lines at the camera.
</P>
<P>
   We all get bored with our jobs, but few of us have the kind of
followings that these stars have, and when they change on us and it
doesn't work, it's like an act of betrayal. Even when an actor
gives a good change-of-pace performance, he risks alienating fans;
Kevin Costner gives one of his best performances as a prison
escapee in the Eastwood-directed ``A Perfect World,'' but the movie
did only middling well at the box office. Somehow, winning an Oscar
for directing ``Dances With Wolves'' and receiving good reviews for
``World'' convinced Costner that he's not a limited actor, leading
to annoyingly surly and mannered performances in ``Waterworld'' and
``The Postman.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Costner would even want to be surly onscreen is a mystery;
we like him best when he's having fun, as with his mischievously
sexy performances in ``Bull Durham'' and ``Tin Cup.'' Even in the
recent ``Message in a Bottle,'' where he's shut off and moody, he
at least cracks a smile and a few jokes. ``Message,'' which was
well-timed as a Valentine's weekend ``date movie,'' became a hit,
but darned if Costner's brooding side doesn't screw up the romance.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the roll call of stars who have attempted and failed to
stretch are Julia Roberts, trying her hardest not to be just a
pretty woman in ``Mary Reilly'' and ``Michael Collins''; those were
such misguided performances that many reviewers overreacted
positively when Roberts decided to be charming again in the
radically uneven ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' She's in the company
of such performers as Dennis Quaid, who shut off his cockiness and
devilish grin to play it dour in ``Flesh and Bone'' (which worked
in spite of itself) and ``SwitchBack'' (which was beyond
redemption). One of the pleasures of last summer's innocuous remake
of ``The Parent Trap'' was seeing Quaid smile again, and although
he lapsed back into glumness in the recent ``Playing by Heart,'' at
least he had a brief good time as a guy who enjoys telling lies to
strangers in bars.
</P>
<P>
   Change of pace also hasn't been good to Bruce Willis, who has
sulked through a series of movies during the past couple of years;
he hasn't been enjoyable to watch since the over-the-top sci-fi
weirdness of spring 1997's ``The Fifth Element.'' Well, he hasn't
in the movies, anyway; he stormed onto TV's ``Ally McBeal'' early
this year in an unbilled cameo as a sarcastic therapist, almost
unrecognizable in bad comb-over, bow tie and mismatched clothes.
His looks might have been camouflaged, but his attitude wasn't: It
was the return of the smart-aleckiness that made him a star in TV's
``Moonlighting'' and the movies' ``Die Hard.'' It made you wonder
where he'd been.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those actors would hate to be put in the company of a
rapper-actor or an immature comedian, but they could learn from a
couple of people: Will Smith, whose effortless charm has led to a
series of hits, even though he repeatedly plays himself; and Adam
Sandler, who has spent his past half-dozen movies looking like what
he is _ a goofy frat-boy type indulging himself in silly skits.
Sandler knows he'll never win an Oscar, and he doesn't care; he's
making $20 million a picture, and he probably never dreamed that
he'd be this popular. If a doofus like Sandler is smart enough to
know that that's all you need, why can't the more ``intelligent''
stars understand that?
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
