<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-REINVENTED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING IT: ACTORS WHO HAVE REINVENTED THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies ACTORS-TYPECASTING) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many stars have failed to make a successful transition to
respected actor, but a few have succeeded in reinventing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   TOM HANKS: Here's a guy who started as a sitcom actor (''Bosom
Buddies''), and went on to a mixed-bag series of comedies
(''Splash'' being the best, ``Volunteers'' the worst) before
proving that he could act in ``Big.'' By 1993's ``Philadelphia,''
people were comparing him with James Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   SALLY FIELD: Another veteran of lightweight sitcoms (''Gidget,''
``The Flying Nun''), Field broke through in 1976 with a tour de
force performance as a woman with multiple personalities in TV's
``Sybil.'' Within 10 years, she would win two Best Actress Oscars,
for ``Norma Rae'' and ``Places in the Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   TOM CRUISE: Cruise separated himself from a series of
teen-oriented movies, teaming himself with more experienced stars
(Paul Newman, Dustin Hoffman) and visionary directors (Oliver
Stone, Brian De Palma, Stanley Kubrick and, soon, Steven
Spielberg). By the time ``Jerry Maguire'' rolled around, even
longtime detractor Pauline Kael started to say nice things about
him.
</P>
<P>
   JODIE FOSTER: Foster has done such a good job of restyling
herself as an intelligent, somewhat aloof actress that people
almost forget that she once starred in such innocuous family movies
as ``Napoleon and Samantha'' and ``Freaky Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL J. FOX: Fox, another sitcom-bred actor, took risks,
giving good performances as a yuppie drug addict in ``Bright
Lights, Big City'' and a moralistic Vietnam soldier in ``Casualties
of War.'' The movies were box-office disappointments, though, and
Fox went back to where he came from: a sitcom, ABC's ``Spin City.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
