<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-18 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL BUSH PULL OUT BIG GUNS FOR VOUCHERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The eyes of the nation are focused upon Texas because the former
republic's Legislature stands poised to create the largest school
voucher program attempted by any state so far.
</P>
<P>
   That focus is intensified by the fact that the Lone Star State's
governor is the not-yet-officially-announced front-runner for the
2000 Republican presidential nomination. And George W. Bush said in
his State of the State oration in January that ``the time has come
to try a pilot voucher program.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush can't provide enough push to get the voucher legislation
passed, some in his party may begin to wonder if he really has what
it takes to spearhead a national GOP triumph. The governor,
therefore, most go all out to show his bona fides in the voucher
donnybrook that is about to occur in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   And that means that those who see the proposed voucher program
for the cynical deception that it is need to understand that this
is the Alamo as far as public education goes in Texas. They must do
their utmost to buy enough time to show some significant
improvement in the performance of the state's public schools, or
there will be no San Jacinto for those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the so-called pilot program came within an eyelash of
being passed in the 1997 session. The House deadlocked 68-68. The
governor's need to stand tall on the voucher issue for the national
audience could provide just the edge to get the pilot program
through this session.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot program, indeed. Whether it's the version proposed by
state Rep. Kent Grusendorf, R-Arlington, or that from state Sen.
Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, something in the neighborhood of 150,000
students would be involved, and the state's largest school
districts _ including Dallas' and Fort Worth's _ would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   During a five-year trial period, the so-called pilot programs
could siphon between $2 billion and $3 billion from the public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' proposal would provide $4,000-per-year scholarships to
private schools only to poor children who failed the most recent
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test.
</P>
<P>
   Grusendorf's proposed legislation would allow up to 10 percent
of the students at low-performing campuses in the Houston, Dallas,
Fort Worth, Austin, El Paso, Northside (Bexar County) and San
Antonio school districts to receive scholarships equating to 80
percent of each district's per-pupil maintenance and operations
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The terms ``voucher'' and ``scholarship'' are used
interchangeably. And that is fitting because vouchers originally
were referred to as scholarships when Georgia enacted a law in the
'60s providing them for white children to attend private schools
instead of desegregated schools.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of the current voucher proposals, of course, would be
to exacerbate the resegregation of the public schools that has
occurred in Texas because of white flight to the suburbs and to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Grusendorf's voucher plan has no income limits. And it would
obviously open the door for more white students to leave schools
with large or predominantly minority student populations.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' plan appears more ``compassionate'' (in Bush's political
vernacular). But it is merely a way of getting the camel's nose
under the tent flap.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Texas' most savvy political prognosticators are now
saying that Bush's and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry's backing will assure
passage of voucher legislation despite strong opposition from
teacher organizations and others who might be loosely lumped under
the ``liberals'' umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   But those forecasters fail to take into account that this
radical idea, which amounts to taxpayer funding for a parallel
school system, is not embraced wholeheartedly by a considerable
number of conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable concern on the right about the state
giving money to private schools with the usual kind of strings
attached. In Bivins' bill, for example, the private schools that
take state vouchers will have to administer the TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   And private schools could find themselves burdened with the same
kinds of paperwork burdens, special programs and restrictions that
now distract public school teachers and administrators from their
primary mission.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's biggest challenge, therefore, may be to convince real
Texas conservatives that a voucher program can be fiscally
responsible without being excessively intrusive. And that might not
be easy.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5598 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-BOOKS-TEX     03-18 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING THE OSCARS BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that the book is better than the
movie. It's the same _ almost _ with books about the Oscars, which
tend to be better than the Academy Awards telecast (for one thing,
the books don't have those awful production numbers).
</P>
<P>
   One new book, one updated one and one standby are on the market
this year. Here's a quick evaluation of the three|
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE TRIVIA BUFF
</P>
<P>
   ``The Envelope, Please: The Ultimate Academy Awards Trivia
Book,'' by Arnold Wayne Jones (Avon, $5.99): To be more precise,
this quick-read paperback by Dallas-based Jones, who has
contributed to The Met and the Dallas Observer, is for the
trivia-obsessed. Jones dissects everything into tiny little pieces,
often starting off with fascinating tidbits only to end up sounding
like the guy you want to escape at a party.
</P>
<P>
   Examples: Jones includes a quiz in every chapter (the questions
would be a lot tougher if the answers didn't immediately follow
them). A question about homosexual characters in movies has an
answer that's two pages long.
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the trivia is fun to read, the best parts of
the books are the introductions to each chapter, which when taken
together form a capsule history of Hollywood. Points off, though,
for such easy-to-fix errors as listing the original Gloria's year
of release as 1988 _ the movie came out in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DISH
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside Oscar: The Unofficial History of the Academy Awards,''
by Mason Wiley and Damien Bona (Ballantine Books, $23): The only
thing wrong with this book is that it's in drastic need of an
update _ the last year covered is 1994. Wiley and Bona cover the
Oscars year by year, with each chapter following a strict but
entertaining structure: anticipation, nominations, the awards
ceremony, and its aftermath. There's also an extensive appendix of
nominees and winners, complete with a yearly ``Points of Interest''
guide to Oscars trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's unauthorized, the guide isn't reverential toward
the Oscars _ but it isn't disdainful, either. In an irony-free
deadpan style, it reports on some of the more Spinal Tap-moments _
such as John Wayne leading a sing-along of ``You Ought to Be in
Pictures'' at the 1972 ceremony (the large group on stage only knew
the first two lines of the song). Of the books covered here, this
is the most exhaustive _ and the one most worth reading cover to
cover, even at nearly 1,000 pages of pre-appendix text.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU JUST LIKE TO LOOK AT THE PICTURES
</P>
<P>
   ``70 Years of the Oscar: The Official History of the Academy
Awards,'' by Robert Osborne (Abbe Mille Press, $65): Yes, that's a
steep price, but then this oversize volume is really a coffee-table
book. Osborne, the erudite host from Turner Classic Movies and the
academy's official historian, is not as concise in print as he is
on the air. This updated volume takes the Oscars decade by decade
with almost biblical reverence (''1988-1997: The Academy's Seventh
Decade''), and year by year, somewhat less pompously.
</P>
<P>
   Like you're gonna read the text, anyway. The photos are amazing,
from a winsome Janet Gaynor with the first Best Actress Oscar (for
a trio of 1927 movies) to the spectacle of hundreds of people
fleeing the big boat in a still from Titanic. Each chapter features
poster art from Best Picture winners, stills from nominated movies,
photos from the ceremony and, often, pictures of the production
numbers. The book is beautiful _ it's like a dessert so
well-presented that you feel guilty about eating it _ but it isn't
very deep.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
