<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIEFS21-COX     03-18 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIEFS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Must haves for spring
 &HT;    She's gotta have it
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. sole searching
</P>
<P>
   Comfort is in, and so is the shoe that keeps you grounded. The
slide, with a lower heel or a thin wedge heel, leads the style
parade, followed by thongs, sandals and mules. Look for these shoes
in white, pastels, red or orange and all shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   2. whiten up
</P>
<P>
   ``White is an instant mood booster,'' says Jill Hinson, a
fashion director for Nordstrom. Look for sheaths, shifts, A-line
shapes, drop and empire waists. ``It can project an image that's at
once innocent and urbane.''
</P>
<P>
   3. pretty in pink
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular shades this season is pink; it's
lighthearted and conjures up visions of all things feminine. For
warm weather, slip into a pink twin set, a halter-neck dress or a
rosy pink lipstick. Blend pink with black, gray or deep blue for
more impact.
</P>
<P>
   4. cropped and chic
</P>
<P>
   Pants with slim and wide legs are inching upward and come in a
slew of shortened styles. They range from Capris, which stop two to
three inches above the ankles, to below-the-knee pedal pushers, to
midcalf-length clam diggers. Wear them with short-sleeve camp
shirts, twin sweater sets, a peasant blouse or a simple white
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   5. neck and neck
</P>
<P>
   The romantic look of an illusion necklace _ also called a
floater _ is making waves this season. The necklace is made from
super-thin wire adorned with pearls, diamonds and beads that look
like they are floating in air. The look is perfect with sundresses,
evening gowns or V-neck sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   He's gotta have it
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   1. sport-utility shoes
</P>
<P>
   They're not entirely sporty, and not quite dressy either. But
these are still the new do-everything shoes. They're trendy,
comfortable, versatile and masculine. Some shoes were made for
walking . . . these were meant for much more.
</P>
<P>
   2. `upscale casual' outfit
</P>
<P>
   Stylish men don't have to wear suits everywhere. But when the
occasion allows for dressing down, that shouldn't mean dumbing down
your look. Having one coordinated, comfortable and classy look to
don on casual occasions is the wisest of buys.
</P>
<P>
   3 . tone-on-tone suitings
</P>
<P>
   The season's sharpest-dressed men will be the ones wearing
lightweight suits in paler shades of gray, blue and brown, with
shirts and ties in similar shades. Start with the suit, then find a
shirt in a matching tone. Finish off the look with a tie that binds
the outfit together.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
