A5602 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINGSTYLES-KIDS21-C     03-18 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTYLES-KIDS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The latest looks for kids this spirng and summer
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Style isn't about age, it's about attitude.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to children, there's no kidding around. Trends
mean everything. Most know what's hot and what's not years before
they're old enough to drive.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, are parents down with it? The
crazy-carefree-cool looks this spring make it hard not to be.
</P>
<P>
   Grunge is washed out. Low-riding baggies have been slimmed down
and softly constructed. Tweety and his cartoon friends are
outnumbered by designer logos. And electrifying neon has fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   For girls, ``pastels are the only way to go. That's all we're
seeing,'' said Barbara Collins, personal shopping manager for
Macy's By Appointment at Lenox Square.
</P>
<P>
   Boys favor primary colors, and the all-American red, white and
blue rules.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the ground rules are defined, here's a look at what
some cool guys and girls will be sporting in Atlanta this season.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It's a girl thing: Capri or carpenter pants in denim, khaki or
plaid, with T-shirts and color-coordinated blouses. Cargo skirts
with drawstring waists are also the rage this spring, while
sundresses and shifts remain classic ``Hotlanta'' attire.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boys to men: Cargo pants in khaki, navy or olive. Drawstring
shorts with pockets. Plaid Bermuda shorts. Knit V-neck vest
sweaters with T-shirts underneath. Logo T-shirts under plaid,
button-down shirts, worn open, for added style and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layered look is very trendy, plus in Atlanta it's so
practical, because as the day gets hotter you can peel off the
layers,'' says Janet Myers, manager of Kids Wear Boys at Nordstrom
in Perimeter Mall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Special occasion: For her, dresses in any style paired with
straw hats, matching purses and white gloves (hey, it's a Southern
thing). For him, khaki pants, navy blue blazer and button-down
shirts in French blue, white or sky blue work anytime, anyplace.
For really special events, consider a tie and tailored suit like
Dad's. On hot days, a suit vest with a short- or long-sleeved shirt
and slacks will do.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Summer fun: The surfer look is in for boys, with trunks in
bold colors that stop just above the knee. Most guys wouldn't be
caught out of water these days in trunks that resemble underwear.
``Everyone still wants to be like Michael Jordan and wear long
shorts,'' says Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Tankinis are the thing for girls _ swimsuits consisting of tank
tops and bottoms that provide more coverage than the typical two
piece.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vanities: Both boys and girls are sporting the Gilligan hat,
also known as the bucket hat _ a bucket-shaped hat with soft brim
like the one Bob Denver wore in the 1960s TV show ``Gilligan's
Island.'' Baseball caps are always in style for both sexes. Clear
plastic tote bags and big floppy hats are must-haves for her. And
wrap sunglasses for boys and girls still have it made in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
