A5604 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVENINGWEAR21-COX     03-18 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVENINGWEAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soft and pretty rules the night
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes you simply have to dress down to dress up.
</P>
<P>
   And this spring, dressing for after-5 parties and galas takes on
a new look with something called evening sportswear. Think actress
Sharon Stone in the Gap turtleneck and full skirt she once wore to
the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Donna Karan refers to these clothes as ``the glamour of
comfort,'' meaning sportswear separates done in unexpected,
easy-to-wear fabric combinations. You could pair a twin set _
cotton cardigan plus camisole _ with a floaty tulle ankle-length
ballerina skirt. Or wear a simple cashmere tank with a body-hugging
crinkle silk skirt. The effect is pretty and romantic, especially
when the sweaters are in shades of pink, blue, yellow and lavender.
</P>
<P>
   Also a contender for top sweater honors is the shrug. This tiny
cropped cardigan, which stops right below the bustline, looks
newest in gray jersey fabric and paired with a strapless tube top.
Wear it with a taffeta skirt or narrow-cut silk Capri pants for a
decidedly '50s feel.
</P>
<P>
   Other luxe cardigans look as if they are knitted from cobwebs or
the finest of meshlike yarns. They can be worn over funky tanks
emblazoned with ethereal angels or simple camisoles. These sets are
the perfect toppers for evening trousers in black or white chiffon.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
