A5605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENSWEAR21-COX     03-18 0220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENSWEAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Light, bright are just right for spring
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring arrives, and one guy takes the same work-wear route he
followed all winter long: dark suit, white shirt, maybe a splash of
color in his necktie.
</P>
<P>
   Another guy heralds spring's arrival by blazing a stylish new
trail: pale suit, a comparably colored shirt and maybe a tie of the
same shade . . . or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Who looks smarter? The latter lad, of course. Style-conscious
men realize that lightening up _ in terms of color, fabric and
attitude _ is the wiser way to dress for work.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas navy, brown, black and charcoal are the correct colors
for cold-weather career wear, the warm-weather season calls for
suits shaded light blue, tan, light gray and cream. Tropical-weight
wools, linens, seersuckers and cottons are the best materials for
keeping cool. And a lighthearted approach to pairing suits, shirts
and (maybe) ties is the sharpest, surest response to rising
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Dark is dull. Light is bright. Pick pale apparel to avoid
arriving for work looking uptight.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5606 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIMWEAR21-COX     03-18 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMWEAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flattering styles perfectly suited for every body
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For most of us _ men and especially women _ finding
the right swimsuit is no day at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, designers have gotten more daring by
whittling one-piece suits into skintight little nothings. In doing
so, they've added more inner construction _ cleavage enhancers,
tummy control panels, bun lifters _ to make our abs, bottoms and
breasts look beach-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   And women are taking to these form-fitting one-piece suits like
ducks to water. The clean lines flatter most figures, and the suits
can be as revealing as bikinis, especially with high-cut legs, deep
V-necks and cutout backs and sides.
</P>
<P>
   Making Waves
</P>
<P>
   Before you hit the sand or surf, here's the skinny on the latest
trends:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The competitive edge: Look for tank suits with patches, racing
stripes, piping and color blocking. These are for serious swimmers
who like to combine fashion and function.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Flower power: Whether they're tropical hibiscus or smaller
daisy patterns, flowers are making a splash. Colors can be bold or
pastel pretty.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gray matters: Call it platinum or silver, this color is hot
for swimwear; it combines well with brights or pastels. Look for
shiny fabrics like satin or jersey.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Details, details: Look for strapless suits, sky prints with
clouds, embroidery touches, zippers and drawstring accents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Palette pleasers: In addition to gray, go for white, the other
hot neutral. For color, add any shade of pink, red or orange. The
whole blue family, from turquoise to deep ocean blue, is also
popular.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fast-moving fabrics: Quick-drying nylon/Lycra and comfy
cotton/Lycra blends give swimmers ease of movement.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
