<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Practical panache: `Utility chic' a look you can live with
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winter weather's behind us, so shrug off that
``performance fleece.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's spring, get ready to embrace the next phase in
fashion's evolution: ``utility chic.''
</P>
<P>
   The utility chic look is comfortable, versatile, modern and
practical. It's the next step in a progression that began with the
widespread popularity of sportswear made from performance fabrics
and continued with the worldwide embrace of cargo pants.
</P>
<P>
   Utility chic styles emerged as the strongest trend during the
spring/summer '99 runway fashion shows, for good reason:
Everywhere, at every price level, the clothes we favor are the ones
that prove most useful.
</P>
<P>
   See how ornamentation's been steadily de-emphasized in favor of
simplicity. Observe the way truly stylish people do more with less.
</P>
<P>
   Notice how silhouettes get more streamlined despite the fact
that Americans are getting stouter. The two concepts seem
diametrically opposed. But designers worldwide prove _ with what
they're offering this season _ that they're attuned to our needs,
they acknowledge our burdens, they feel our pain.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to innovative fabric treatments and the design
world's collective nod to transitory lifestyles, people can wear
cashmere or leathers or synthetics or linens year-round. Now, the
same clothes you wear from 9 to 5 look appropriate from 5 until.
And, as spring's trendiest styles prove, shades of white, black and
gray look equally edgy.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, the shoes that used to look comfortable look
sharp. And, until further notice, utility features such as zippers
and drawstrings, Velcro and hoods and bags big enough to hold your
essentials are the bare necessities of a stylish life.
</P>
<P>
   Does the utility chic trend reek of novelty? Yes. Dressing this
way will take some getting used to. But, unlike most trends that
rise only to fade, utility chic's got staying power.
</P>
<P>
   It's the most logical style for the millennial age. With so many
other uncertainties facing us, at least this early glimpse at how
we'll likely dress in the future makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton covers fashion in Atlanta as well as on the
runways of New York, Paris and Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
