</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENSWEAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Color is abloom everywhere
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gray skies are going to clear up. So put on a happy
face. And if that doesn't get you in a spring mood, stock up on
some of the ``Have a Nice Day''-colored clothes in stores this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas last spring was the season of pastel twin sets and
sensible gray skirts and pants, this spring heralds widespread
acceptance of suits, dresses and separates in bold and bright
shades.
</P>
<P>
   Women needn't worry if they're wearing the right colors, because
this spring there are no wrong colors. Designers weren't limited to
producing clothes in any particular shade of pink, orange, red,
blue or yellow because advances in dyeing processes enable them to
mimic any color found in nature and invent some that are not.
</P>
<P>
   Spring's outburst of rich colors is a key aspect of the overall
femininization of the season's styles. And color complements the
one neutral shade _ gray _ that shows no sign of losing its place
as a wardrobe staple.
</P>
<P>
   It's reasonable to suspect that designers are flooding the
marketplace with color to counteract the pessimism that rises each
time the approaching millennium _ and the anticipated accompanying
Y2K glitches _ comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget your troubles . . . c'mon, get happy,'' seems to be the
designers' sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies who hate taking neutral stances on style should take
advantage of this mood swing; it's only a matter of time before
fashion's infatuation with color fades.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
