<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-OSCARS-500&AMP;ADD-SFC     03-18 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OSCARS-500&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEENA ELBOWS JOAN OUT OF PRE-OSCAR SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joan Rivers had every reason to trash Geena Davis, who'll be
seizing Rivers' pre-Oscars territory Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivers wasn't flexing her famous talons. In a telephone
interview, she turned each invitation to nastiness into a ``Who
cares?''
</P>
<P>
   Will Geena Davis be hosting a new, academy-sanctioned pre-Oscar
show on ABC _ horning in on Rivers' annual E! Entertainment cable
show?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares?'' barked Rivers. ``It's just the Academy Awards.
This is not the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And isn't this the Geena Davis who's been something of a fashion
Chernobyl in previous years, a prime morsel for a Rivers rip job?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares?'' repeated Rivers. ``Good luck to Geena Davis.
She's a tall girl. Let her have her day.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Davis will have her 30 minutes at 5 p.m. Sunday,
launching ABC's ``Sunday at the Oscars'' spectacle. The awards
ceremony, hosted by Whoopi Goldberg, will begin at 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' half hour will feature live interviews with movie stars
as they arrive at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion, fashion coverage,
backstage glimpses and a ``road to the Oscars'' segment.
</P>
<P>
   The show is the property of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts
and Sciences. The academy apparently noted the success of other
pre-Oscars shows _ including the E! Entertainment program hosted by
Rivers and her daughter, Melissa _ and decided to grab the game
ball for itself.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, from 5 to 5:30 only the official pre-Oscars show
will have live camera access to the red carpet area to buttonhole
stars.
</P>
<P>
   So won't the academy be prohibiting those other shows from
capitalizing on Hollywood's big event?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's too bad,'' Robert Rehme, the academy's president,
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Joan and Melissa Rivers will still have their say Sunday on E!
Entertainment; their show will simply end 30 minutes earlier, at 5.
Their ``1999 Academy Award Pre-Show'' will be on from 3 to 5 p.m.,
as part of a daylong block of Oscars programming on E!
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Another annual pre-Oscars show also will have to douse the
lights at 5 p.m. Sunday in deference to the academy's new show on
ABC. That's ``An Evening at the Academy Awards,'' produced by the
ABC-owned KABC-TV in Los Angeles and syndicated to more than 50
cities in the United States and to Canada. It will air from 3:30
until 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Film critic Roger Ebert is back to host the show but with a new
partner. He'll be joined by Karen Duffy, a Revlon model and writer.
</P>
<P>
   That could be fun. This is the Ebert who, during the 1994
pre-Oscar show, stared down an arriving actress' plunging neckline
and blurted, ``I'm not a fashion expert, but I know what I like.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress whose, uh, instrument so appealed to Ebert that year
was none other than Geena Davis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Davis is an Oscar winner herself, as supporting actress for
1988's ``The Accidental Tourist.'' Eleven years later, her film
career seems to have withered; perhaps Sunday's exposure can give
her a jump start.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Davis on the shock of winning an Academy Award:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in such a parallel universe. I have no concept how long
I spoke or what I said. I remember it was Melanie Griffith and Don
Johnson presenting it, and I was talking to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They handed it to me and I was saying, `Oh, your dress is so
pretty,' and `Oh, it's so nice to meet you, da-da-da.' And they
were kind of going, `Uh huh. Go _ go there.' And I started talking
and wandered away. I don't know. It was a different dimension that
I entered.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Davis will be ensconced in a specially designed set
inside the Chandler Pavilion. Another contributor, CNN Los
Angeles-based news anchor Jim Moret, will be reporting from outside
the building.
</P>
<P>
   Moret, said ABC spokesman Dan Duran, is on loan from CNN and,
for the night at least, will be employed by the motion picture
academy.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises a question. How can Moret work for an organization
that he and his CNN colleagues cover as journalists? Isn't that a
classic conflict of interest?
</P>
<P>
   That might require a more satisfactory answer than ``Who
cares?''
</P>
<P>
   Moret said he is being paid ``a nominal fee'' to work on the
program. He said that his participation was cleared through Richard
Kaplan, president of CNN/U.S., and that the academy is placing no
restrictions on the questions he asks.
</P>
<P>
   If CNN wants him to, Moret said, ``I have no problem waiving the
fee, it's that small.''
</P>
<P>
   Moret said he wanted to appear on the pre-Oscars broadcast
because the Academy Awards are ``the biggest single entertainment
event in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a matter of appearances more than anything else. Moret
still appears to be making himself part of the industry he's
supposed to cover, and he's planning to accept payment for it from
the academy.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said that appearances didn't count in show business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
