<HEADER>
A5612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-PREDICT21-COX     03-18 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PREDICT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In close combat with `Shakespeare,' Spielberg's war epic pushes
to front line in depiction of America at its heroic best
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So what does the well-dressed and well-informed
Oscar-goer wear to tonight's Academy Awards? Combat boots or
Elizabethan ruffles?
</P>
<P>
   The gut says to go with the GI guys in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
Though the film's early shoo-in supremacy has been challenged by
the lovable, nomination-laden ``Shakespeare in Love'' (the leader
with 13 nods compared with ``Ryan's'' 11) and by Italy's
unpredictable dark horse ``Life Is Beautiful,'' Steven Spielberg's
World War II powerhouse remains the movie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It's a beautifully done film with a virtuoso sequence _ the
opening D-Day assault _ that's as memorable as anything we've seen
on screen since the invention of movies.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, ``Saving Private Ryan'' celebrates _ with
precious little sentimentality and a total absence of false
patriotism _ a time when being an American meant something heroic.
In a sense, Spielberg has given us a Joe DiMaggio of a movie, a
picture of our country and ourselves at our best. And as this
complex, identity-wrenched century draws to a close, Spielberg's
timing is eerily appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick for best picture: ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``Life Is Beautiful,''
``Elizabeth,'' ``The Thin Red Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other picks in major categories that might help
win your Oscar-party betting pool. Just don't bet the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   The usual prognosticator, the Screen Actors Guild Awards, went
with Roberto Benigni (``Life Is Beautiful''), while the critics
groups were all over the place. But maybe the Oscar voters will
realize that Benigni is just Robin Williams with an Italian accent.
And they gave Williams his award last year.
</P>
<P>
   My hopes are with Ian McKellen of ``Gods and Monsters,'' one of
the best actors of his generation. His portrayal of Hollywood
eccentric James Whale is both nuanced and courageous. Besides, he
was robbed more than a decade ago when the role of Salieri, which
he created onstage in ``Amadeus,'' went to F. Murray Abraham for
the film version. The Oscar back then went to Abraham, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: McKellen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: Benigni, Tom Hanks (``Saving Private Ryan''),
Nick Nolte (``Affliction''), Edward Norton (``American History
X'').
</P>
<P>
   ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   The Elizabethan blondes _ ``Shakespeare in Love's'' Gwyneth
Paltrow and ``Elizabeth's'' Cate Blanchett _ could cancel each
other out. And Brazilian actress Fernanda Montenegro (``Central
Station'') may benefit from actors' mentality that her win can't
threaten their careers (though you could probably say the same
these days about two-time winner Meryl Streep, nominated this year
for ``One True Thing'').
</P>
<P>
   But the momentum seems to be with Paltrow, and considering that
she actually played four different roles in one movie _ and played
them all beautifully _ that's fine by me. Even though I personally
preferred the dramatic complexity offered by Blanchett.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: Blanchett.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: Montenegro, Streep, Emily Watson (``Hilary and
Jackie'').
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORTING ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   A real toughie, as usual. I once thought James Coburn
(``Affliction'') was a sure thing. Longevity and all that. But
memories have gotten shorter in Hollywood. So have careers.
</P>
<P>
   I think the Academy might lean toward Ed Harris (``The Truman
Show''). It's a way to honor an actor with an honorable body of
work _ remember ``Apollo 13,'' ``Places in the Heart'' and ``The
Right Stuff''? _ and to throw a bone to ``Truman'' (the film and
Jim Carrey were shut out of nominations).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: Harris.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: Coburn, Robert Duvall (``A Civil Action''),
Geoffrey Rush (``Shakespeare in Love''), Billy Bob Thornton (``A
Simple Plan'').
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORTING ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   The SAG Award went to Kathy Bates (``Primary Colors''), which
was something of a surprise considering how her movie tanked in
theaters. Oscar might go for her, too.
</P>
<P>
   And while I like Judi Dench (``Shakespeare in Love'') and Lynn
Redgrave (``Gods and Monsters''), Bates' performance is what
supporting work is all about. She gave ``Primary Colors'' its
secondhand soul.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: Bates.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: Dench, Redgrave, Brenda Blethyn (``Little
Voice''), Rachel Griffiths (``Hilary and Jackie'').
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the easy pick of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Directors Guild of America said Spielberg was the best. So
did a bunch of critics groups, the Golden Globes and the other
usual suspects. Plus, he deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: Roberto Benigni (``Life Is Beautiful''), John
Madden (``Shakespeare in Love''), Terrence Malick (``The Thin Red
Line''), Peter Weir (``The Truman Show'').
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN FILM
</P>
<P>
   Here's where Italy's Benigni gets his statue and chance to be
adorably _ how-you-say-in-English? _ gushy and effusive and so
wonderfully Mediterranean. Brazil's ``Central Station'' is still
the better film.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: ``Central Station'' (or, even better, non-nominee
``The Celebration'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: ``Children of Heaven'' (Iran), ``The
Grandfather'' (Spain), ``Tango'' (Argentina).
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   The script was the worst thing about ``Saving Private Ryan.''
Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful'' could pull an upset, but my
instincts say ``Shakespeare in Love.'' It's got distributor Miramax
waging a formidable Oscar campaign and Broad-
</P>
<P>
   way's Tom Stoppard (who co-wrote the screenplay with Marc
Norman).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: ``Bulworth,'' ``Life Is Beautiful,'' ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   SCREENPLAY ADAPTATION
</P>
<P>
   The script was the worst thing about ``The Thin Red Line,''
while ``Gods and Monsters'' just doesn't have the clout. The
Writers Guild of America went with Scott Frank's terrific
adaptation of Elmore Leonard's ``Out of Sight.'' Oscar probably
will, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: ``Out of Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: ``Primary Colors,'' ``A Simple Plan,'' ``The
Thin Red Line.''
</P>
<P>
   COSTUME DESIGN
</P>
<P>
   Here's where ``Beloved'' makes its last-minute surge. Gotcha.
</P>
<P>
   The two Elizabethan films are a toss-up; both are gorgeous. I
prefer ``Elizabeth'' simply because it's the underdog. Academy
members will likely prefer ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's pick: ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My pick: ``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The also-rans: ``Beloved,'' ``Pleasantville,'' ``Velvet
Goldmine.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
