<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-RDP19-COX     03-18 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-RDP19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini movie round up
 &HT;    By Steve Murray, Bob Longino, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Jill
Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``True Crime''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clint Eastwood, Isaiah Washington and James Woods.
Directed by Eastwood. Rated R for language and violence. 2 hours, 7
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Trial by ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' really is one. Producer-director-star Clint
Eastwood's ham-fisted, beat-the-clock mystery is so full of cliches
and accidental humor that it verges on self-parody. He plays a
philandering, alcoholic-workaholic newspaper reporter (gee, there's
a new character) convinced that a convicted murder (Isaiah
Washington) is innocent. The problem is, the guy is due to be
executed at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   As Eastwood tracks down increasingly arbitrary clues, the movie
veers from laughable depictions of newsroom life to mawkish scenes
of Washington bidding his family goodbye (actually, he's very good,
and so is Lisa Gay Hamilton as his wife). The film also gets jolts
of energy from Denis Leary and James Woods, and a wasted Diane
Venora as Eastwood's weary wife.
</P>
<P>
   The movie exposes what better scripts have hidden: Eastwood is
equally stiff as a director and actor. His scenes meander and veer
wildly in tone, and his movies dawdle past the two-hour mark for no
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the issue of Eastwood, 68, wooing several women
young enough to be his granddaughters onscreen. The leering tone
outdoes Woody Allen, but at least Allen keeps his shirt on these
days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   ``The King and I''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Animated version of the 1956 Yul Brynner-Deborah Kerr musical
with songs from Rodgers and Hammerstein. Voiced by Miranda
Richardson and Martin Vidnovic. Directed by Richard Rich. Rated G.
1 hour, 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Kids will probably be charmed. For everybody else,
it's a puzzlement.
</P>
<P>
   They should have called it ``The King, His High-Five Slappin'
Panther and I.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Beauty and the Beast,'' Disney, never a slouch in the
'toon department, proved some time ago that animated musicals could
really be, well, something wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Now Richard Rich (``The Swan Princess'') has taken a brush and
made ``The King and I,'' the first animated feature based on a work
by Rodgers and Hammerstein. But does this second-rate animated King
of Siam really need to high-five the paw of his pet black leopard?
Is that the only way to lure the youngest of moviegoers into the
story of an English schoolteacher instructing a whip-smart Asian
ruler in the ways of mid-1800s worldly culture?
</P>
<P>
   Rich's heavy hand doesn't stop there. The king now has a hot-air
balloon to fly around in and to swoop into action when somebody's
about to drown. And Anna does warble ``I Whistle a Happy Tune,''
but it's to fend off a big, scary dragon.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Too much more.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, some folks learned nothing of Mister Rogers'
eloquent teachings: A happy tune by itself can calm and charm a
child.
</P>
<P>
   If children really need for ``The King and I's'' crown prince to
be a martial-arts expert in order to stay glued to the screen, we
might as well give up right now and declare Nintendo the winner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   ``Children of Heaven''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mohammad Amir Naji, Mir Farrokh Hashemian and Bahare
Seddiqi. Written and directed by Majid Majidi. Unrated. 1 hour, 27
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The shoe fits.
</P>
<P>
   You can go see ``Children of Heaven'' intent on divining all
sorts of hidden messages in its tale of abject poverty, scary
authority figures and other aspects of Iranian life.
</P>
<P>
   But then you'd miss seeing a simpler, much more delightful story
about two children and one pair of pink shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Ali (Mir Farrokh Hashemian) accidentally loses his little sister
Zahra's (Bahare Seddiqi) shoes. Because their family is poor, they
fear their father's (Mohammad Amir Naji, a.k.a. the scary authority
figure) punishment. So they scheme to share Ali's battered sneakers
until a better solution comes along.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually it does, in the form of a boys' footrace where
finishing third means winning snazzy new shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Will Ali place third or, worse, win?!
</P>
<P>
   The ending, much like the rest of this movie (an Oscar nominee
for foreign language film), is by turns touching, heartbreaking and
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   With its subtitles and mostly child's-eye viewpoint, ``Children
of Heaven'' sometimes feels about as workmanlike as Ali's father,
in the family's one-room home, breaking a block of sugar into cubes
as a favor for the local mosque. But then he refuses to add even
one precious cube to his own tea (``It's not ours,'' he tells Zahra
solemnly), and suddenly it's all about the kind of dignity that
mainstream Hollywood rarely captures.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad message to divine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   DOCUMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   A documenary about the Holocaust. Directed by James Moll. Rated
PG-13 for extreme adult themes, including genocide. At Lefont
Plaza. 1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An extraordinary, small-scale history lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Editor's note: A full version of this review appeared in
Wednesday's Living section.
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't beautiful in ``The Last Days,'' a searingly memorable
documentary about five survivors of Hitler's Holocaust in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Prouced by Steven Spielberg and an Oscar nominee for best
documentary, this small-scale history lesson gains its impact
through its narrow focus: 438,000 Jews sent to the camps in six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inevitably, some of ``Last Days''' stories and footage
are familiar. There are the obscene piles of corpses, the walking
near-dead whose skeletal bodies chilled the Allied liberators who
discovered them, the appalling horror tales of ovens and showers.
Yet the film manages a unique focus by confining itself to one
small country and to five people who made it out alive _ less, as
they all point out, because of any resilience or resourcefulness on
their part than because they were lucky. Very lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The movie says a kind of kaddish for the dead Jews of Hungary,
and it does so with respect, with honor and, oddly enough, with a
kind of undiminished hope.
</P>
<P>
   They should have called it ``The King, His High-Five Slappin'
Panther and I.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Beauty and the Beast,'' Disney, never a slouch in the
'toon department, proved some time ago that animated musicals could
really be, well, something wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Now Richard Rich (``The Swan Princess'') has taken a brush and
made ``The King and I,'' the first animated feature based on a work
by Rodgers and Hammerstein. But does this second-rate animated King
of Siam really need to high-five the paw of his pet black leopard?
Is that the only way to lure the youngest of moviegoers into the
story of an English schoolteacher instructing a whip-smart Asian
ruler in the ways of mid-1800s worldly culture?
</P>
<P>
   Rich's heavy hand doesn't stop there. This king's now got a hot
air balloon to fly around in and to swoop into action when
somebody's about to drown. And Anna does warble ``I Whistle a Happy
Tune,'' but it's to fend off a big, scary dragon.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Too much more.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, some folks learned nothing of Mister Rogers'
eloquent teachings: A happy tune by itself can calm and charm a
child.
</P>
<P>
   If kids really need ``The King and I's'' crown prince to be a
martial-arts expert in order to stay glued to the screen, we might
as well give up and declare Nintendo the winner right now.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray, Bob Longino, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Jill
Vejnoska write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
