<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-FIRSTS21-COX     03-18 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-FIRSTS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oscar records could be in the stars tonight
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' made Oscar history last year, tying ``Ben-Hur'' for
the most Oscars ever won _ 11.
</P>
<P>
   It's less likely history will again be rewritten tonight, but
there are plenty of possibilities among the nominations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bigger than ``Titanic''? _ Technically, both ``Saving Private
Ryan'' (with 11 nominations) and ``Shakespeare in Love'' (with 13
nods) could match ``Titanic's'' feat. ``Shakespeare'' could win
enough to become Oscar's winningest film of all time. Just don't
count on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The actor factor _ A Tom Hanks victory for ``Saving Private
Ryan'' would be the first time a male performer has won three
trophies in the top acting category. Hanks already has Oscars for
``Forrest Gump'' and ``Philadelphia.'' Jack Nicholson has three
Oscars _ for ``As Good as It Gets,'' ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest'' and ``Terms of Endearment, '' but the first two were for
lead actor and the last was a supporting trophy. In Oscar's early
years, Walter Brennan won three trophies, all in the supporting
category. Katharine Hepburn, of course, is the all-time acting
leader with four best actress Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It would be a wonderful ``Life'' _ ``Life Is Beautiful'' could
become the first foreign film ever to win best picture. Plus,
Roberto Benigni is up for three Oscars for best actor, director and
screenplay. No one has ever swept those categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The big sweep _ Speaking of foreign language films, four of
the top categories could go to non-English speaking movies if
``Life'' takes best picture, actor and director and ``Central
Station's'' Fernanda Montenegro wins the best actress category.
That would be a first.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  They're playing his song _ Lurking in the music categories are
three separate nominations for music by Randy Newman: best song
(``That'll Do'' from ``Babe: Pig in the City''), dramatic score
(``Pleasantville'') and musical or comedy score (``A Bug's Life'').
In 1973, Marvin Hamlisch scored an Oscar music hat trick, winning
the same three categories for his work on ``The Way We Were'' and
``The Sting.''
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT STUFFINGS
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few nominees who've already won accolades from
various guilds and critics groups:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nick Nolte _ New York Film Critics and National Society of
Film Critics, actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ian McKellen _ Los Angeles Film Critics, actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roberto Benigni _ Screen Actors Guild, actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cate Blanchett _ Golden Globe, dramatic actress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gwyneth Paltrow _ SAG, actress; Globe, comedy actress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fernanda Montenegro _ Los Angeles Film Critics, actress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ed Harris _ Globe, supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Robert Duvall _ SAG, supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Billy Bob Thornton _ Los Angeles Film Critics, supporting
actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Judi Dench _ National Society of Film Critics, supporting
actress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lynn Redgrave _ Globe, supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kathy Bates _ SAG, supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
