<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-CONGRESS-HNS     03-18 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE PASSENGER BILLS WOULD BOOST FARES, INDUSTRY ARGUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation that would impose consumer-oriented
rules on the nation's airlines drew fire Thursday from industry
officials, who said the new rules would boost airfares.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks several key lawmakers have introduced so-called
``passenger bill of rights'' legislation that would, among other
things, require airlines to give customers accurate information
about why flights are delayed.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal, by House Transportation Chairman Bud Shuster,
R-Pa., would require airlines to reimburse passengers if they are
kept waiting on the ground for more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. Warren, senior vice president for the Air Transport
Association of America, which represents large U.S. airlines, told
Shuster's Aviation Subcommittee that the industry is working to
voluntarily improve its customer service and does not need Congress
to impose new rules.
</P>
<P>
   He said the various measures would ``result in higher fares,
fewer seats available, fewer seats available at lower fares and
confusing requirements and additional pressures on our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hirst, a senior vice president for Northwest Airlines,
said in written testimony that the proposals would ``produce
unintended and highly undesirable consequences including raising
air fares.'' He also said he was concerned that safety might be
compromised if airline employees felt pressured to get planes in
the air to avoid monetary penalties for long delays.
</P>
<P>
   In the past Democratic lawmakers have offered bills aimed at
improving airline customer service, but now several Republicans
have jumped on the issue after hearing reports of airline
passengers being forced to sit on airport runways up to nine hours
during a January snowstorm in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster said Thursday he decided to introduce his bill when he
realized that long runway delays are not an isolated event. More
than 3,600 planes sat on the ground for more than two hours last
year, according to the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot go through a day where people aren't coming up and
telling my their horror stories,'' Shuster said. ``I hope the
airlines won't have their heads in the sand and can appreciate that
this is a really serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the House panel heard from passengers who were
involved in long delays in Detroit and other places. At Thursday's
hearing, airline industry officials gave their views.
</P>
<P>
   Hirst apologized for the Detroit incident and explained why the
airline was unable to get 30 planes to the airport's gates.
Instead, they were forced to sit on the runway for several hours
after landing.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem, he said, was that 68 empty airplanes were
snowed in at the gates and in airfield areas nearby and were thus
blocking the incoming planes. He said airline and airport workers
believed they would be able to move the snowed-in airplanes before
the incoming flights landed but were unable to do so because of the
fierce storm.
</P>
<P>
   Warren repeated industry suggestions that Congress focus on
improving the nation's air traffic control system rather than
imposing new regulations on airlines. He noted that most delays are
mandated by air traffic controllers. The government's General
Accounting Office has long advocated that the computers running the
air traffic control system be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. John E. Sweeney, R-N.Y., said, ``It strikes me that the
industry itself is in great depths of denial, that everything is
going well and it's somebody else's fault.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week the Clinton administration proposed legislation and in
addition issued Department of Transportation regulations that
include many of the provisions contained in House and Senate
airline bills.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional proposals would require airlines, upon
request, to disclose the number of seats on a flight that are
reserved for frequent flyer awards and it would allow passengers to
use any portion of a ticket without penalty. This would end airline
restrictions on passengers who find they can save money by buying
two inexpensive round-trip tickets and then using one segment of
each ticket for such a trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would require airlines to hold a reservation for
48 hours at the same price, giving people time to comparison-shop.
Passengers are often told they must book a flight immediately to
secure a particular price.
</P>
</TEXT>
