<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIGERS19-COX     03-18 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGERS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wild cat refuge considering haven in Atlanta
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Facing mounting legal problems with officials in Roane
County, Tenn., the operators of a big-cat sanctuary have won an
apparent reprieve from the prospect of trying to find a new home
for their 65 lions, tigers and other exotic felines.
</P>
<P>
   But the operators of Tiger Haven say they likely will move
anyway, possibly to metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent action in a two-year zoning fight over the
nationally known refuge for abused wild cats 40 miles west of
Knoxville, the Roane County Planning Commission voted narrowly 4-3
to rezone the 10-acre sanctuary site to permit the keeping of
dangerous animals.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, a county judge found that Tiger Haven violated
the county's zoning ordiance. The judge also upheld the county's
decision last year to deny Tiger Haven permission to rezone 30
adjacent acres for expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need more room to spread,'' says Joe Parker, who
along with his wife, Mary Lynn, founded Tiger Haven. ``We still
hope to move. This just give us time to make an intelligent decison
on where and when to move.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is far from settled, however, as the county commission
must approve the rezoning recommendation of the planning panel. It
was the county board that sued the Parkers for noncompliance with
the zoning ordinance last year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the zoning battle over Tiger Haven has bitterly split
the eastern Tennessee county between those who fear the cats as a
threat to their community and those who contend the felines are the
only ones threatened. ``I think the ideal place would be 50 miles
north of Atlanta,'' says Parker, a fomer bingo operator who once
used bingo proceeds to support Tiger Haven. ``We've already gotten
a lot of support from the Atlanta area.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven years, the Parkers have provided a home for
unwanted and abused exotic felines in a rural neighborhood near the
small town of Kingston. Most of the animals are discarded pets or
rescued animals from abusive road-side zoos.
</P>
<P>
   While the Parkers have won praise from Tennessee wildlife
authorities, the Roane County Humane Society and other animal
advocates, some of their neighbors contend they are a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents express fears that one of the cats might escape and
attack them or their children. They also say the compound, which is
visible from narrow Harvey Road, has depressed property values.
Other complaints center around concerns that fecal waste is
contaminating streams and ground water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't anti-animal,'' argues Juanita Raymer, who lives near
the sanctuary. ``We just don't think it's the right place for it.
There are 26 families on that little road. We just feel like Mr.
Parker should follow the rules just like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Haven began in 1991 as a home for one tiger and slowly
grew to more than 50 animals by 1997. The Parkers say they have
never had an escape.The tract is encircled with an 8-foot high
perimeter fence, while the pens are enclosed with a 16-foot high
chain link fence.
</P>
<P>
   And a number of neighbors support Tiger Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a wonderful place,'' says Alma Carter, a
next-door neighbor who volunteers at Tiger Haven. ``The county
should be proud of it. It's the best-maintained, cleanest animal
facility I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
