<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT     03-18 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAN MOSS: SWINGING SHADOWS AND DANCING GHOSTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ghosts from several worlds and times inhabit Dean
Moss' new ``Spooky Action at a Distance,'' performed on Wednesday
night at the Kitchen. Most immediate are the ghosts embodied by
Moss and his dancers, Kacie Chang and Marcelo Coutinho. Fred
Astaire is seen as clearly, on a television monitor, putting on
blackface for his ``shadow'' dance with Bill (Bojangles) Robinson
in ``Swing Time,'' an inspiration for the piece.
</P>
<P>
   The next layer of ghosts includes a large silver creature,
dressed in a stiff black net suit, that hangs over the shadowy
half-lives unfolding below. In the furthest reaches of this
universe are film images of dancers projected on the black back
wall, as insubstantial as wisps of smoke. Crowding in around them
are wisps of another sort: bits of 1930s-era popular music and
music by African composers, and excerpts from the writings of Noam
Chomsky, Richard Feynman and David Ruelle, some of them about
quantum physics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spooky Action at a Distance'' is probably not for those who
like dance with a strong center. Moss' images fly off like sparks
from a non-existent torch, creating a moment's glimpse of the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Moss also is not interested in delivering gut-wrenchingly plain
messages about society. Instead, the black dancer and choreographer
puts on the black suit and slips in and out of a solo that draws on
the kind of eccentric capering that came to represent slave dancing
and a generation of black performers in Hollywood film, including
stars like Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tale Telling Telling,'' a 1997 solo choreographed and
performed by Moss to music by Kevin Volans, is less subtle but just
as ghostly. Its central image, of a black man in a dark suit that
becomes dusty with white chalk powder, is powerful.
</P>
<P>
   David Fritz designed the lighting for the program. The stylishly
insubstantial costumes for ``Spooky Action at a Distance'' were by
Gia Grosso and Leah Chalfen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
