<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREWORKS-ARTISTS-600     03-18 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-ARTISTS-600&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREWORKS   ARTISTS GET TOGETHER TO DISCUSS THEIR CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Pa., Wash.)  (rk) 
 By KAREN VOYLES The Gainesville Sun.    
1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLIS, Fla. _ They rarely advertise, yet most are already
booked up past New Year's Day 2000. They freely share their trade
secrets, but only with people who figure out how to contact them.
Some of their favorite merchandise have names like Red Thousand
Coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of the pyrotechnic artist.
</P>
<P>
   The medium? Fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I got into this because I was always the little boy
who wanted to play with matches,'' said Fred Partin, a member of
the Florida Pyrotechnic Art Guild.
</P>
<P>
   Partin was among the 200 or so who gathered last weekend for the
guild's annual spring meeting, which was held at a campground near
Inglis. The experience of these guild members ranged from
first-year beginners to full-time professionals, but they share a
common desire for privacy. They don't announce the times and
locations of their meetings because they don't want to attract a
crowd as they learn and experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These get-togethers and our competitions in the fall are a
chance for us to help each other and learn from each other,'' said
Partin's wife, Lee Partin. Together the Partins operate
Dragonworks, a business based in Homosassa Springs, Fla., that
displays fireworks, including specialty items they design and
manufacture for use in competitions with other guild members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we got into 10 years ago and today I think
of it as a serious hobby,'' said Fred Partin.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Partin is considered a grand master in the guild and teaches
the course required to be certified in pyrotechnics. She also has
developed recipes for making striking displays.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Partin said her experience working with and teaching the
formulation of pottery glazes gave her a knowledge of chemistry
that she has used in pyrotechnics. Her biggest fireworks show last
year was a $70,000 extravaganza in Lancaster, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   While the Partins consider pyrotechnics a fascinating hobby,
Mark Ferguson says fireworks are the only way he ever wants to make
a living.
</P>
<P>
   He runs a business called Pyrobros in Crystal River, Fla., that
imports, exports, distributes and displays pyrotechnics. He can
readily explain the cryptic names given by Chinese manufacturers to
fireworks. For example, The Red Thousand Coconut: It's 12 inches
across, costs $60 and bursts into glorious color after 12 seconds
of upward thrust.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the year Ferguson and a staff of about a half dozen
employees can handle the details involved with shipping fireworks
to 48 states and six countries, plus putting on 100 or so shows.
But come July and December, his staff significantly increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the Fourth of July, we'll probably employ 80 people for
our various shows,'' Ferguson said. ``We could have at least that
many working for us New Year's Eve because we already have shows
booked for Seattle and Boston and Tampa and a city in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks haven't changed much in recent years, but the way they
are shot off has changed dramatically. Fuses used to be lighted by
hand but now electronic systems are used. Operators at large shows
use computer systems that choreograph displays.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said a pyrotechnician will know _ based on the fuse
length, size, type and manufacturer _ how many seconds each display
item will take to go off. To choreograph a show, fuses need to be
lighted from five to 15 seconds ahead of key parts of a piece of
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we enter into the computer all that information and the
computer can figure out when each item should be lit,'' Ferguson
said. Pyrobros now uses four computer systems, each worth at least
$10,000, to choreograph its shows.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Guild members do not need a computer to know they must have 70
feet of clearance from a crowd for every inch of shell. That means
a 3-inch shell must be fired at least 210 feet away from the
nearest spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Those standards are set by the National Fireworks Protection
Association. Additional standards are set by the U.S. Bureau of
Alcohol Tobacco and Firearms. The federal agencies track the
movement of all fireworks coming in, going out and moving around
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the part I least enjoy _ the paperwork and having to
account for every single shell,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting ready for a show can be tricky without a safe place to
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we have meets,'' Fred Partin said. ``They create an
environment for people to exchange information and a place to try
out new things that have made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really stress the importance of safety,'' said Lee Partin.
</P>
<P>
   Several guild members have had accidents that could have been
life-threatening. Ferguson and his brother were both blown off a
barge into the water when they were hand lighting a show several
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my mom probably worries a little bit because when I
first started doing this, she would ask me all the time, `Why don't
you get a real job?' '' Ferguson said. ``But now that my company is
doing 100 shows a year, she is starting to think this is pretty
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Karen Voyles is a reporter for The Gainesville Sun.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
