<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUGGENHEIM-PHOTOGRAPH     03-18 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUGGENHEIM-PHOTOGRAPHY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUGGENHEIM SOUNDS THE ALARM: IT AIN'T NECESSARILY SO 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The Giant,'' a black-and-white photo-collage that
Cindy Sherman made in 1976, is the unsung center of the Guggenheim
Museum's exhibition of its brand new photography collection.
</P>
<P>
   In the piece, a collage of sequential black-and-white
self-portraits, cut out and arranged in a long line, Ms. Sherman
appears as a lumberjack in a wool cap, flannel shirt, jeans, thick
socks and boots. If the collage is viewed like a slow-motion movie
or flip book, the young woodcutter in glasses slouches with hands
on hips, slowly straightens up, looks at the camera, snaps her
suspenders, looks down, puts her hands back on her hips, takes her
hat off, looks at the camera again, puts her cap on her head and
finally bows her head and ducks behind the next to last Cindy in
line.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways ``The Giant'' is an exception in the exhibition,
``Photography: An Expanded View.'' It is a collage; there are only
a few in the show. It is a proto-video; there is only one video. It
is a self-portrait; there are no others evident. But ``The Giant,''
made when Ms. Sherman was only 22, even younger than most of the
young photographers in this show, is its soul. It is central
because it inaugurates, quite innocently, a climate of visual
distrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giant'' foreshadows Ms. Sherman's Untitled Film Stills,
frames of movies that never were, starring Ms. Sherman as every
movie star who ever was. (In this exhibition there are two Film
Stills, one of a Gidget-like figure in the big city, the other of a
showgirl in heels sitting on a window ledge.)
</P>
<P>
   By creating seemingly factual documents of nonexistent fiction
and insuring that they were excruciatingly exact, Ms. Sherman made
everything unbelievable. She seemed to say: Don't ever believe your
eyes. Now her lesson has been thoroughly absorbed by younger
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the work of Reneke Dijkstra. In this show there are
three giant beach portraits taken against three different backdrops
of puke green or pale blue sky: one in Coney Island, one in Poland,
one in Odessa, Ukraine. Into each seascape, an awkward giant or two
has fallen. In Coney Island a girl in a black suit stands with one
hand clenched, one ankle braceleted. She looks cold, bare, small
and large against the sky and sea.
</P>
<P>
   In Poland two boys are in their underwear. One stands straight
with his hands held behind him. The other is contrapposto, with his
hands on his thighs, and he squints. In Odessa a skinny pale boy in
a red suit stands, hip jutting. The space between his arm and his
body looks vast. These photographs are so painfully real and large
and colorful that they look, well, impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for a pair of Roni Horn iris prints of an owl.
White and gripping a brown branch against a white background, the
owl looks alive and well, but the viewer knows better. The label
says ``Dead Owl.'' And of course the two prints are identical. Or
maybe not. One owl appears to be a little fatter. Maybe it was shot
from a slightly different angle. No, maybe not. Once again, the
message is: Don't believe your eyes. These owls must be different
because they are identical. They must be dead because they look
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Demand's photograph almost provides relief from the
pervasive disbelief, if only because it is obvious that he has
fabricated the scene. ``Archive,'' a C-print of a storage room, is,
on closer inspection, a fake that doesn't even try to conceal
itself. It is a giant photograph of a tiny model of a stockroom,
filled with identical boxes tucked in identical cubbyholes,
accessible by a toy steel ladder.
</P>
<P>
   If the storeroom is fictional, what about James Casebere's
``Asylum,'' a photograph of a concrete floor and a slab of
concrete, a bed, that floats above it? Is it a real asylum, a fake
prison, a monk's cell or none of the above? And what about the huge
C-print of the Japanese stock exchange by Andreas Gursky?
</P>
<P>
   Surely this vast sea of red, turquoise and yellow jackets
serving Money, the queen bee, cannot be real. Miles Coolidge's
C-print of a street corner with a flimsy police station, a
terrifying Kids ``R'' Us store and a pathetic McDonald's looks like
a plaything. So probably it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This show indicates that there is an unofficial law for the
eyes: Anything that looks real must be doubted, and anything that
declares its artifice _ by garish color, size, blurriness, fakiness
_ is automatically more trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Consider two blurry prints, acrylic lacquer on canvas, by Uta
Barth. They have absolutely nothing in focus. But one doesn't think
for a second that they represent something that never was. They are
clearly real street scenes because they are blurry. One strains to
see reality because the photographer has made it a challenge. Are
those the headlights of a car? And what's that white blur? A
street?
</P>
<P>
   The second Barth print, also blurry and dreamlike, with blotches
of blue, pink and yellow, appears to be an image of some
storefronts. There's no doubt here that nothing is fabricated. It's
just blurry.
</P>
<P>
   How different this climate of visual distrust is from the school
of reality represented by George Platt Lynes and Robert
Mapplethorpe. The only kind of fictional frisson one gets with
these is an occasional goof of attribution: ``I didn't know
Mapplethorpe did that! Oh, it's by George Platt Lynes. They are so
much alike! I didn't know Mapplethorpe got so much from Lynes. I
didn't know the Guggenheim had so many of both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   There are too many photographs by Mapplethorpe (22) and by Lynes
(24) in this exhibition, which was financed by the Robert
Mapplethorpe Foundation. But they do provide a nice foil for the
newer photographs. The Mapplethorpe and Lynes portraits don't doubt
their own reality or even raise a question about it.
</P>
<P>
   They present their figures as part of a super-real,
super-classical race. These are great bodies, great artists, great
celebrities, and like statues they are more real and cast bigger
shadows than you or I. They are utterly out of place in a gallery
of visual distrust.
</P>
<P>
   Josef Albers' photographs from 1929 and 1930 hang better with
the newer photographs. His crisp, clear picture of a clothesline
with the wind filling its dresses, shirts and undies and his
photo-collage of Mrs. Lewandowski in her beach wear both seem to
anticipate by 70 years the idea that the strangest things, the most
ad hoc, seem most reliable to the eye.
</P>
<P>
   An inadvertent gloss on the exhibition is added in ``Exile
Brands,'' a series of portraits of Havana cigars by Andrea Robbins
and Max Becher. Each photograph shows two cigars that go by the
same name. The only difference is that one of each pair is made in
Havana and the other is not.
</P>
<P>
   So which one is authentic? You immediately think it's the one
from Havana. But think again. As Ms. Robbins and Becher point out,
many Havana cigar makers left Havana and took their businesses and
names with them. So the exile brand is arguably more authentic.
</P>
<P>
   The wall text reads, ``Which version of a classic brand is more
`authentic' depends on whether one places more importance on
continuity of soil and location or on family and country
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar question can be asked of photographs: Which is more
authentic, the one that flaunts its unreality or the one that
pretends to be real? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Photography: An Expanded View, Recent Acquisitions,'' remains
at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, through May 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
