<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      03-18 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM POSES TECHNICAL CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the House on Thursday overwhelmingly approved
a futuristic system to guard against limited missile attack, such a
weapon is fraught with technical hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and lawmakers are planning a system
that relies on ground-based interceptors to shoot down incoming
enemy intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs) in the outer
reaches of the Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The program, known as National Missile Defense, is designed to
hit a few missiles sent aloft by Iraq, Iran, North Korea _
countries the United States brands as rogue nations _ or a single
ICBM accidentally launched by Russia or China.
</P>
<P>
   The effort has been in the research and development phase for
several years. The House voted 317-105 Thursday to deploy such a
system, while the Senate approved it 97-3 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While technically challenging, National Missile Defense is a
scaled-back version of what Ronald Reagan envisioned in 1983, with
lasers and rockets parked in space intercepting thousands of Soviet
nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan called the project the Strategic Defense Initiative, or
SDI, and critics _ mainly Democrats _ dubbed it ``Star Wars.'' SDI
never came to fruition in large part due to the technical setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   No final decision has been made on deploying National Missile
Defense. Instead, the Clinton administration has set June 2000 as
the deadline to make the call on whether to take the concept out of
the laboratory and build a functioning system. The goal would be to
have it in place by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The final cost could top $38.5 billion, according to
congressional estimates, and could climb much higher depending on
the number of interceptors and launch sites.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision to deploy would turn in part on whether the
Pentagon can achieve the technological breakthroughs required for
this complex system of advanced sensors, radars and missiles to
actually work.
</P>
<P>
   The major concern is that given current technology, it may
simply be too difficult to track and destroy an enemy missile
traveling several times the speed of sound and them to blow it up
by ramming it with another missile _ all in the span of several
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pentagon plans, the concept would employ four main
components, according to the Ballistic Missile Defense Office, the
Pentagon agency responsible for managing the effort:
</P>
<P>
   _ Space- and ground-based sensors to provide early warning of
attacking missiles;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ground-based radars to track the threatening warheads;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ground-based missile interceptors based in North Dakota and
possibly Alaska to collide with and destroy enemy warheads; and
</P>
<P>
   _ A battle management system that would link all the components
with military commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the Pentagon has not had much success with the
concept.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Gen. Larry Welch, in a report released by the
Pentagon last year, warned that the National Missile Defense
program was ``highly unlikely'' to succeed because it lacks
coherence and a realistic plan. The report accused Pentagon
managers of a ``rush to failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch's report found that of 17 tests conducted by the Pentagon
since 1982 of ``hit to kill'' interceptors, only four, or 23
percent, actually struck their targets. Welch found that of the 14
tests directed against high-altitude targets _ an ICBM is
considered such a target _ only two hit their targets for a 14
percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
   Since the report, the Pentagon conducted another test against a
high-altitude target. It also failed.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the congressional investigative
arm, last year said the administration's plan involved ``high
technical risk.'' For example, the GAO said the weapon that would
ram into an incoming missile, called the exoatmospheric kill
vehicle, is considered ``one of the most technically challenging
components of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cirincione, a senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace, an advocacy group in Washington, asserted
that the technical challenges are insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to design an effective ballistic missile
defense system,'' he said. ``What we are talking about is hitting a
bullet with a bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirincione added that an enemy intent on striking the United
States with missiles could overwhelm such a system with missile
decoys, the same strategy NATO planned to use against the Soviet
Union during the Cold War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
