<HEADER>
A5650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOMALIA-ART-NYT &LR;      03-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOMALIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID GROUPS TRY NEW APPROACHES FOR GETTING FOOD TO SOMALIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAYEGLU, Somalia _ It took three days _ and one gun battle _ for
the ratty caravan of trucks, piled with sacks of corn, to arrive
here from a port near Mogadishu. When there is little rain, food is
like money, and this caravan was guarded by no fewer than 132 young
toughs with machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who is looting,'' said convoy leader Daahir Abdulleh
Ali, 49, ``you kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least shoot at them. No one died in this particular
firefight, but three people, along with several cows, were hurt. In
Somalia, the cycle of food and fighting churns on, after three
years of drought, floods and failed crops, along with the hope
these days that normal rains will finally fall and make life
easier.
</P>
<P>
   But there are differences now from five years ago, when the
United Nations ended its famine relief mission here and the name
Somalia became a one-word explanation of why so many outsiders were
giving up hope on Africa. Certainly after 18 U.S. Rangers were
killed here in 1993, U.S. policy in Africa became largely one of
striving to avoid another disaster of human deprivation where it
might have to send troops.
</P>
<P>
   With most aid agencies gone, and clan warfare continuing in the
only nation in the world with no central government, Somalia has
been left largely on its own, for good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   A recent appeal to outside governments for half a million
dollars in seeds _ a child's allowance in the multibillion-dollar
aid industry _ has gone largely ignored. The World Food Program, a
U.N. agency that has been organizing food deliveries to parched
parts of the south, is warning that another failed harvest, through
lack of rain or seed, could bring on another severe famine, six
years after the one that killed some 300,000 people. Somalia's
population is roughly 10 million.
</P>
<P>
   But skepticism about investing in Somalia _ and skepticism in
general of aid agencies always warning of the next disaster _ runs
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has had a bad experience in Somalia,'' said a
European aid official in Kenya, who insisted on anonymity. ``If
there is already international donor fatigue for Africa, it is even
worse for Somalia.''
</P>
<P>
   And so aid agencies have been turning more to programs that
involve Somalis directly and are claiming some success. CARE
International, for example, has trained some 40 local groups, often
associated with the clans, to carry out relief projects, including
distributing food in small quantities that do not make such
tempting targets to militia groups.
</P>
<P>
   Abdi Yussef, chairman of Soma-Action, one of the most respected
Somali non-government organizations, acknowledged a criticism of
these local groups: that some had been created merely for profit
and are too close to the local powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jokingly, someone will tell you when he wants to start a
business, `I am bringing up an NGO,' '' he said. But in recent
years, he said, this has been less of a problem because so little
money now flows into Somalia. And looters, he said, have been less
likely to steal food from local groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a part and parcel of the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the World Food Program, saying it
learned from the mistakes of the early 1990s, has completely
reworked the way it delivers food. In November it began delivering
food to southern Somalia, mostly to the Bay and Bakool regions in
the south, where fighting and water shortages have uprooted some
34,000 people in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency does not deliver the food itself. Rather, it
contracts Somali businessmen, who rent trucks, hire gunmen and put
up a bond equal to the worth of the food.
</P>
<P>
   Ali, the convoy leader, said he and his partners had to provide
a $1.5 million deposit on the 370 metric tons of corn they
delivered from Mogadishu to here to Hoddur to the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the maize is stolen or we are attacked, I have to go out
and buy the same maize,'' Ali said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials say the program has worked well because
contractors are docked for whatever food they do not deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pay a premium for that,'' Steve Gluning, chief security
officer for the World Food Program in Somalia, said as aid workers
distributed food in the town of Bardera, on the Juba River in the
south. ``All the onus is put on the trader to get the food from
point A to point B, and he loses if he fails. Yes, he may have to
fight his way through. But it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much contention among aid workers about just how bad
the situation is in southern Somalia. The World Food Program has
not called it a famine but says the situation is one more failed
harvest away from disaster, and now is a critical time because it
is both when the rains come and the summer crop is planted.
</P>
<P>
   Both here and in Bardera, people said they had walked many miles
to find water and, in some cases, to escape fighting. They said
they were hungry, but no one seemed to be starving, in part because
aid is arriving.
</P>
<P>
   But the Somalis themselves are finding ways to cope beyond what
outsiders bring them.
</P>
<P>
   In Bardera, Habiibo Salaad, 40, stood under the broiling sun as
an aid worker scooped out 20 cupfuls of corn for her and her family
of 11 people. This should last two weeks. But she and her family
have been collecting firewood and fetching water to sell at the
market. It is just enough to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The rains are supposed to start there soon, and there has been
some rain already in southern Somalia. If enough rain falls, Mrs.
Salaad said, the family will walk back to their farm, nearly 20
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect Allah will give us rain,'' she said. ``Otherwise, we
will be in bad shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
