<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-PAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LAWMAKERS COME UP WITH PLAN TO RAISE SALARIES FOR TEACHERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Senate Republicans on Thursday said they've
devised a $2.5 billion plan to give most Texas public-school
teachers a $2,000 pay raise in 2000, increase their retirement
benefits and provide homeowners a small measure of property-tax
relief _ all without violating court orders governing
school-finance equity.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide voter approval of a constitutional amendment would be
required in November to implement the strategy, whose linchpin is a
proposed $1 billion state contribution to individual teachers'
retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   By reducing retirement-related deductions on teachers'
paychecks, their take-home pay will increase an average of $2,006 a
year, lawmakers said, adding that teachers with above-average
salaries would see a bigger increase and those with below-average
salaries would get smaller increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does get the money where Texans want it to go _ in the
pockets of school teachers,'' said Senate Education Committee
Chairman Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Months in the making, his measure, Senate Bill 4, was endorsed
by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry and Senate Finance Committee Chairman Bill
Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, while Senate and House Democrats reacted
cautiously to the multipronged proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps this is a beginning point,'' said Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos, D-Austin.
</P>
<P>
   A major concern is whether the plan will appease rank-and-file
teachers that have been pleading for a $6,000 annual pay boost.
Another lingering question is whether homeowners' tax relief will
be sufficient to allow Gov. George W. Bush to declare he
successfully delivered on one of his biggest 1998 re-election
campaign promises _ a $2 billion ad-valorem property-tax reduction
made possible by at least $2.5 billion in surplus income.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasn't the only political figure who advocated property-tax
cuts along with higher teacher pay, and Bivins said his plan gives
colleagues an opportunity to fulfill their 1998 campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally everybody that ran for statewide office and the
Legislature said that education was their No. 1 priority, and
filing SB 4 today, I plan to hold them to that promise,'' Bivins
said.
</P>
<P>
   He described the legislation as a ``work in progress'' that is
likely to undergo bipartisan-backed improvements as it makes its
way through the committee process in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Committee Chairman Rob Junell, D-San
Angelo, said Bivins' proposal ``is one of a number of good ideas''
that will be considered by the House. Even so, the House Public
Education Committee has not decided what approach it wants to take
to deliver promised teacher pay raises, and the House Ways and
Means Committee is mulling numerous property-tax relief measures _
all made possible by rosy surplus predictions for the fiscal year
ending Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   As filed, Bivins' plan provides $1 billion to replace teachers'
contributions to the Teacher Retirement System; increases the
crucial TRS ``multiplier'' from 2 to 2.1; and lowers
school-district property-tax rates by an average 10 cents
statewide, at a cost approaching $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The multiplier is part of a formula used to determine retired
teachers' standard monthly annuities. Currently, the annuity is 2
percent, times the average of the three highest annual salaries,
times years of credited services, divided by 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan is a triple play,'' said Perry, who presides over
the Senate, by ``increasing education funding, improving teacher
pay by 6 percent and cutting property taxes significantly all at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation demonstrates what Gov. Bush, Teel Bivins and
Rick Perry have been saying for a long time _ our No. 1 priority is
our children's education,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Bivins' package ``represents the largest single
increase in school funding in the history of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, who devised the strategy to circumvent an equity
squabble, said an across-the-board teacher pay raise would not have
been possible under ``Edgewood'' equalization rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would inevitably wind up sending money to wealthy school
districts. When we do that, we fly in the face of the Edgewood
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, even if more monies were factored into existing
school-funding formulas, poorer districts might not have the cash
to deliver the mandated across-the-board raises, Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   His plan entails removing a constitutional provision that
requires teachers to contribute no less than 6 percent of their
salaries to the retirement system. Currently, teachers contribute
6.4 percent, with the state adding 6 percent. The Constitution also
would have to be amended to remove a 10 percent cap on the state
contribution, Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state picks up the entire 6.4 percent that is now paid
by the teacher, it's a raise by virtue of the fact that the
teachers get to keep it in their pocket,'' Ratliff said. ``We're
able to get it to every teacher, all across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not as much as some people were promising during the
campaigns, but I'm sure that everybody understands that's not
possible,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
