<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, March 19. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ As U.S. exports continued to fall,
the U.S. trade deficit jumped to a new monthly record of $17
billion in January, fueled by a flood of imports from China that
could stir further protectionist sentiments in Congress. Among the
imports that surged into the United States from China was a huge
increase in steel, and the protectionist movement may gain momentum
now that China joins Japan, Brazil and Russia on the list of
nations pouring inexpensive steel into the U.S. market. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ With the Kosovo talks at a dead end
and Yugoslavia's Slobodan Milosevic more recalcitrant than ever,
the Clinton administration is faced with pushing forward on a
policy _ the NATO bombing of a sovereign country _ that its
officials have repeatedly said they really don't want to carry out.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LOANS (Washington) _ Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told
a congressional panel that he suspected that much of the $4.8
billion in loans sent to Russia last summer by the International
Monetary Fund ``may have been siphoned off improperly.'' Rubin's
comments marked the first public confirmation by the Clinton
administration that much of the bailout money the Treasury
organized last year simply helped wealthy Russian oligarchs move
billions of dollars to Switzerland. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS (New York) _ Protesters of the shooting here
by police of an unarmed West African immigrant have adopted an
event-a-day strategy. They have also put an emphasis on celebrity
rather than just numbers, as in the recent arrests and handcuffing
of Rep. Charles B. Rangel and former Mayor David Dinkins. By Dan
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MOOD (Washington) _ More and more, the president looks
and sounds like yesterday's man, spending large measures of his
precious final days in office revisiting the scenes of yesterday's
glories and trying to forget the pain of the humiliating
impeachment battle he survived. He is clinging to his last hours on
stage, as the spotlight shifts to the rising careers of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-SAFETY (Undated) _ When a semiautomatic's magazine is
removed, a round can remain in the chamber, ready to be fired, and
scores of people have died or been seriously hurt in recent years
as a result. Gun producers have long known of the danger, and some
responded by building into their guns an inexpensive mechanism
known as a magazine safety. But the fact that many gun makers have
chosen not to use simple devices like magazine safeties and gun
locks is now a focus of a growing wave of lawsuits in which cities
are accusing the firearms industry of making guns needlessly
dangerous. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIDEPRESSANTS (Undated) _ The new generation of antidepressant
drugs, of which Prozac was the first, is not any less _ or any more
_ efficacious in treating major depression as are older
antidepressants, a government report released Thursday concluded.
The report puts to rest lingering doubts about the relative
effectiveness of the new drugs, but it also notes that there is
insufficient research to conclude that the new drugs effectively
treat mild depression, a condition for which they are widely
prescribed. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-SENATE (New York) _ A month after announcing her
interest in a U.S. Senate seat from New York, Hillary Rodham
Clinton has discussed her potential candidacy with 60 influential
Democrats, including the major party chairmen from the suburban and
upstate counties crucial to winning a race. Many officials describe
their conversations with the first lady as lengthy and
extraordinarily detailed about local issues. By Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
</TEXT>
