<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-HOMES-0319-CO     03-18 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONDITIONS IN NURSING HOMES MAY BE WORSENING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A quarter of the nation's nursing homes have severe
health and safety infractions that often go unpunished, although
the conditions jeopardize residents, federal auditors said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Their study concluded that federally mandated surveys of the
nation's 17,000 nursing homes indicate conditions have not improved
_ and may have worsened _ since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating on problem nursing homes in four states, the
report found that fines were rarely collected and sanctions were
usually blocked by appeals that took years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is not doing enough,'' said Sen. Charles
Grassley (R-Iowa) chairman of the Senate Special Committee on
Aging, as he released the study, which was conducted by the General
Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients suffer and taxpayers are suckers,'' he said. He cited
one case in which a nursing home resident wandered off and was
found days later, stabbed to death. ``The nursing home had never
reported the person missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas had some of the worst cases in the study, which cited one
chain that had 72 civil fines imposed on it totalling more than
$4.1 million. Yet the chain, identified by state and federal
officials as Texas Health Enterprises, Inc., has paid only
$120,000, according to logs provided by the Texas Department of
Human Services. The rest of the penalties, involving at least 62
cases going back to 1995, have been appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The largest chain in the state, Texas Health Enterprises owned
about 11 percent of its nursing homes during the period of the
study, but accounted for more than 18 percent of enforcement
actions for health and safety infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, problems with the Texas-based chain extended to
Michigan, where six of its facilities were the targets of 27
separate enforcement actions.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Moors, a spokesman for Texas Health Enterprises, had no
immediate comment on the findings.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office survey, which also looked at
California and Pennsylvania, found enforcement of regulations to be
lax throughout. Nursing homes frequently corrected problems to
escape fines, only to be cited for the same violation later in what
the report called a ``yo-yo'' effect.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the study cited an unidentified Texas home that was
cut off from Medicare payments for six months after a string of
violations. Five months after payments resumed, state surveyors
found new problems, including bed sores and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of sanctions appeared to have little effect,'' said
the report, in part because of a backlog of some 700 cases in the
appeals process that must be completed before penalties are
collected.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the critical report, the Health Care Financing
Administration, which regulates nursing homes, announced earlier
this week that it would toughen penalties and direct states to
speed up investigations of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   California, Michigan and Pennsylvania have endorsed the GAO
findings and promised to cooperate. Texas has offered no formal
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on a system'' to improve nursing home care, said
Rosemary Patterson, spokeswoman for the Texas Department of Human
Services.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Wisdom, founder of Texas Advocates for Nursing Home
Reform, expressed doubt about a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad homes are paid the same as good ones,'' she said, adding
that operators have no incentive to offer top quality care. She
said that nursing home companies ``pocket profits and then put
money into political action committees and lobby the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate aging committee offered few
assurances that nursing homes would improve. ``I intend to do my
oversight responsibility to make sure the laws are enforced,''
Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he's encouraging the public to be careful
consumers by inspecting the records of nursing homes with state
agencies and by using a federal Internet web site
(www.medicare.gov) (cq) for comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   He urged ``visiting with residents and the family of residents''
before picking a nursing home, and then visiting loved ones
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that are visited have a higher quality of life,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
