<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5657 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-18 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOVERNMENT SHUT-DOWN REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You'd think the Republicans would have the grace to
be embarrassed about their pivotal role in twice shutting down the
federal government, creating the shocking political crisis that
helped reelect President Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of sensibly trying to forget it, the Republican
National Committee in its wisdom is sending out fund-raising
letters seeking to blame Clinton for that budget debacle. The RNC
denounces what it calls the ``Clinton-Gore shutdown strategy'' that
it predicts will lead to another government collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians frequently try to rewrite history to make themselves
look good, but this is silly. The public memory may be short, but
it's not totally blotto.
</P>
<P>
   The government was closed for six days in November 1995 and for
21 days beginning on Dec. 15 of that year. Because the conservative
House refused to compromise over conflicting policy goals, Congress
was unable to agree on how to keep paying the federal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Remember House Speaker Newt Gingrich conceding that he forced
the shutdown because he was piqued after the president didn't speak
to him during a diplomatic trip on Air Force One and forced him to
exit at the rear of the plane? He told reporters he was so miffed
``that is part of why you ended up with us sending down a tougher
interim spending bill'' that he knew the president could not
accept.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's outburst was featured in the national television
newscasts and produced a memorable New York Daily News headline,
``Crybaby,'' accompanied by a caricature of the speaker in diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans also rushed to take credit for the standoff,
cheering the fact that federal workers were unpaid and public
services disrupted, including the processing of passports and
Social Security papers. Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, then a GOP
presidential hopeful, chortled in an ABC interview: ``Have you
missed the government? Doesn't it strike you funny that 280,000
government employees are furloughed, large segments of the
government are shut down?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the GOP, it didn't strike voters as funny at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The White House pressed for a settlement and so did both Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole and Minority Leader Tom Daschle. ``I
believe the White House, and I certainly believe the Democratic
leader, would like to see this thing ended,'' Dole observed after a
two-week layoff, pointedly failing to mention his Republican House
colleagues. Daschle was more blunt: ``The House wants
confrontation, not solutions,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   The country got the message, and the Republicans got the blame.
When the polls showed the GOP suffering over the issue and in
danger of losing congressional control in 1996, Gingrich and his
dogmatic troops finally backed down.
</P>
<P>
   But RNC spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick now says disingenuously, ``Our
party certainly takes issue with the fact that the president seems
to be disavowing any responsibility ... when it was his veto power
that led to the government shutdown in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsk, tsk. That naughty Clinton actually had the gall to use the
constitutional tool the Founding Fathers gave the president to help
keep the three branches of government co-equal and the legislature
in check. Under Fitzpatrick's unique theory of governing, the
executive branch is apparently supposed to automatically capitulate
to a Congress that insists on having its own way regardless of
potentially draconian consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had warned in advance that he would veto an
appropriations bill that went too far in cutting domestic programs.
The House deliberately ignored that in passing Gingrich's
``tougher'' measure. It was a game of chicken, and the president
refused to sacrifice his own budget goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans underestimated Clinton, not for the first time.
They thought that the ``train wreck'' they eagerly engineered would
help their cause. Instead voters saw it as the same old partisan
gridlock they had hoped to end when they tossed out the
congressional Democratic majority and substituted GOP control in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   To remind voters of this sorry scenario would not seem to be in
the best interests of the Republican Party. Surely there are more
credible ways the RNC can pummel Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
