<HEADER>
A5659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR-NYT     03-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S POLITICAL INTRIGUE NOW HAS A SEX SCANDAL, COMPLETE WITH
VIDEOTAPE  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the focus of Russia's latest political scandal
shifted from corruption to sex, President Boris Yeltsin appointed a
special commission Thursday to investigate the making and
distribution of a videotape that showed Russia's top prosecutor in
bed naked with two young women.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who was discharged Thursday from a Moscow hospital
after a three-week stay, held an early morning meeting with Yuri I.
Skuratov, the embattled prosecutor who just Wednesday mounted a
political challenge to Yeltsin by refusing to keep a promise to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov, who had a lackluster record during his three and half
years as chief prosecutor, resigned on Feb. 1 for what he said were
health reasons. His resignation was promptly accepted by Yeltsin,
but on Wednesday it was defiantly rejected by the Federation
Council, or the upper house of parliament, which under the
constitution must give its consent.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not clear whether Yeltsin will again ask the
Federation Council to approve the resignation, or whether he is
hoping that Skuratov will offer to quit again on his own.
</P>
<P>
   After his morning meeting with Yeltsin, with Prime Minister
Yevgeni M. Primakov present, Skuratov kept a low profile through
the day, as his supporters picked their way through the thorny
moral and legal issues posed by the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The film clip, a few minutes of which were aired late at night
on the government television channel, is now at the center of a
debate over who has sunk lower in the Russian public's esteem _ the
government for using unauthenticated and vaguely pornographic
material as a political weapon, or its chief prosecutor for setting
a bad moral example.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Skvydkoy, head of the government radio and television
committee, justified the showing of the film on the ground that
Skuratov had violated the moral standards of his office, and opened
himself up to blackmail. He said the tape had come from an
anonymous source, and that after last night's showing, the Kremlin
had asked him not to show it again.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov has claimed that the film was part of a blackmail
attempt to stop him from investigating political corruption cases.
``This is the result of a thoroughly planned provocation carried
out in connection with a criminal case being investigated by me,''
said the prosecutor in a telephone interview with a Russian
television reporter, given as he drove to his 8 a.m. appointment
with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Although the existence of the tape was widely known, and copies
had been distributed to television stations and parliament, its
broadcast seems to have dampened the enthusiasm of some of
Yeltsin's political enemies to make Skuratov the hero of an
anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecutor is going to whores, and only whores,'' said
Aleksandr Lebed, the governor of Krasnoyarsk and former
presidential contender. ``Yesterday the wedge was driven between
the president and the prosecutor, the president and the Federation
Council. Now the prosecutor will have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov's most faithful supporters were the leaders of Russia's
Communist Party who doggedly defended Skuratov's right to a private
life. ``We have fallen so low,'' said Viktor Ilyukhin, a top
Communist party leader and parliamentary deputy. `'We compromise a
highly skilled lawyer by showing him in some bed, having found no
other argument for his dismissal.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor has already said that he will sue the Russian
state television channel for violating his rights to privacy, but
legal experts said Thursday that while Skuratov may have a case,
the law could cut both ways.
</P>
<P>
   If the women were prostitutes, he may have broken the law, some
noted. There is also the matter of the oath he took on taking
office, to be a ``paragon of moral purity.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues to be clarified by the special commission are
the origins of the videotape _ reported in one newspaper Thursday
to be 51 minutes long _ and who first brought it to Skuratov's
attention, and why. The commission, which includes members of the
Federation Council, will be headed by Yeltsin's chief of staff,
Nikolai Bordyuzha, and includes the interior minister and the head
of the Federal Security Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
