<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-JEEPS-ART-650&AMP;A     03-18 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-JEEPS-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING VINTAGE MILITARY VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PAUL DUCHENE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Collectors of vintage military vehicles can
drive around with all the bravado of Gen. George Patton, confident
that the objects of their affection were built to last. After all,
going to war is the ultimate in endurance testing.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that these vehicles are not full of creature
comforts. ``If you have a choice between the highway and
cross-country, go cross-country,'' goes a joke passed among Jeep
owners. ``It'll take the same length of time and the ride's
better.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can leave your vehicles out in any weather, and any time
you stop for gas or wait for a parade to start, you hear stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 8,500 members, our club's not all that big compared to
some,'' said Kay Willard-Hinga, manager of the Military Vehicle
Preservation Society, based in Independence, Mo. ``But the vehicles
do stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Greenberg's certainly do. The Portland tree surgeon has a
1944 DUKW amphibious truck that looms more than 8 feet above the
highway. At the top is a replica .50-caliber machine gun (which
cost $600, about one-tenth the price of the real thing). The DUKW,
or ``Duck,'' is 31 feet long and weighs 14,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It has pumps on board to raise tire pressures from 10 pounds for
driving on sand to 40 on the highway. (The intermediate 30-pound
setting was used for landing on coral reefs in the Pacific.) It
reaches 55 miles an hour on the road and 10 knots on water.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg has owned the Duck since 1991 and admits to splashing
into the Columbia River when he has an excuse, ``like with a troop
of Boy Scouts the other weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   As impractical as these half-century-old craft may seem, there
has been a resurgence of interest in them; entrepreneurs are using
survivors of the 22,000 war-era Ducks to ferry paying passengers
into lakes and rivers, headed for spots inaccessible by road. ``I
know there's one in Seattle, another in D.C., one in Branson, Mo.,
and one in Chicago,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Duck may seem an apt name for these amphibious vehicles, but
DUKW was actually their production code. D was for 1942, U for
amphibious, K for two driven rear axles and W for a driven front
axle.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for World War II armor are marching upward. Greenberg,
41, paid $7,500 for his Duck, ``and there was one sold in a
magazine for $35,000 recently.''
</P>
<P>
   His interest in military vehicles began in high school in the
'70s when he bought a Dodge Power Wagon pickup dating from World
War II. ``It had the wrong motor _ a big V8,'' he said. ``But I'd
go camping in it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he became a tree surgeon, he found a '44 Chevrolet 6-by-6 _
a six-wheeled truck with six-wheel drive _ worked fine.
</P>
<P>
   But most collectors get started with Jeeps. Battered '40s models
still show up in rural newspaper advertisements (``Good hunting
rig'') for less than $1,000, but Greenberg dived into Jeep history.
By 1991, when Jeep celebrated its 50th anniversary, he owned one of
each of three prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   American Bantam, Willys-Overland and Ford had all bid on the
original government contract for a light scouting vehicle. The name
``Jeep'' came from ``GP,'' for general-purpose vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The designs were similar, with four-cylinder flathead engines,
three-speed transmissions and open, four-seat bodies. Bantam was
the successful bidder, but was too small to deliver the quantity
the Army needed. So the best ideas were added to the Willys design;
Ford and Willys shared production.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 600,000 Jeeps were built in 1941-45. Willys made
368,000 and Ford the balance. Tiny Bantam built only 2,675 units,
which went to England on lend-lease.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg bought a Bantam Jeep in pieces in Boise, Idaho, and
found a Ford version on a side street here. He no longer has his
Willys prototype (one of six survivors out of 1,600 built) _ it
went to a friend in England who desperately wanted one.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Greenberg's other vehicles include a wheeled 1942 White M3A1
scout car (more often found as a half-track, with conventional
wheels in front and tank tracks at the rear), a 1942
Harley-Davidson military police tricycle, and an unusual 1940 Dodge
VC1 command car prototype with a ``toast rack body'' _ that is,
lacking doors. Of 2,155 command cars made, it is one of 15
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   He belongs to the Military Vehicle Collectors Club of Oregon.
Its 148 members own many Jeeps and Dodge trucks, 11 Ducks, four
scout cars, three half-tracks and two tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Does he ever think of buying a tank?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it costs $50,000 to $70,000 for a restored Sherman tank,''
Greenberg said. ``And then you have to buy a transporter. You can't
exactly drive it on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   His Duck, however, is not just street legal, with a license
plate and added-on turn signals; it is river legal. Greenberg
obtained an Oregon boat license for it.
</P>
<P>
   American collectors tend to want American vehicles. It's mostly
a matter of familiarity, not because collectors served in the
military. ``Not a lot of our members are veterans,'' Ms.
Willard-Hinga said. ``People get interested as a father-son thing.
And there are the stories. They participate in parades and the
vehicles always spark stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet collapse and new access to Eastern Europe haven't
changed the market much. ``Some groups collect foreign vehicles,''
Greenberg said, ``but it's hard to find parts for Russian tanks in
the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   A collector car has been defined as ``one you rode in the back
seat of between the age of 5 and 15'' _ which explains why
progressively newer cars are restored. Does a similar rule apply to
military vehicles? ``It does,'' Greenberg said. ``People are
collecting Korean War vehicles, Vietnam and even Desert Storm
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Most military vehicles in the hands of American collectors were
sold directly to the public and never left the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Antique vehicles still accompany veterans on sentimental
journeys overseas. ``A number of our guys went back to Normandy in
1994 for the D-Day anniversary,'' Ms. Willard-Hinga said. ``They
shipped their vehicles and left them over there with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Like fondly remembered comrades, the trusty machines never came
back.
</P>
</TEXT>
