<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-STATES-HNS &LR;      03-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-STATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OPPOSES PLAN FORCING STATES TO SPEND TOBACCO FUNDS ON HEALTH
PROGRAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting up a confrontation with the Clinton
administration, the Senate on Thursday rebuffed an effort to force
states to spend at least half of the money from tobacco settlements
on smoking and health programs.
</P>
<P>
   By a 71-29 vote, the Senate rejected the amendment, which two
lawmakers had sought to attach to a $1.9 billion emergency spending
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued the federal government should not be mandating
to states, which initiated the lawsuits against the tobacco
companies, how to spend billions of dollars in settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents responded that since the tobacco settlements involved
Medicaid, a federally funded program, Congress had a right to
dictate how some of the money should be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest skirmish over how to spend the tobacco funds may well
be academic in Texas, where a $17 billion settlement with the
tobacco companies already stipulates that most of the money be
spent on health and smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Texas' two Republican senators argued for the
principle of state's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to tell Texas how to spend its money, quit the
Senate, move to Texas ... and run for the state Legislature,'' said
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``The federal government needs to butt
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said ``this is state money,
it is not federal money.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of the amendment ensured that a provision crafted by
Hutchison that would bar the federal government from recouping any
of the tobacco settlement money will remain in the Senate's
emergency spending measure.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration officials have argued that the
federal government does have the right to some of the money or at
least to dictate how it is spent because the basis of the state
lawsuits was that tobacco-related illnesses had pushed up Medicaid
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government funds, on average, about 57 percent of
the costs of Medicaid, the health insurance program for the poor.
In Texas, the federal government pays for 62.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote was the latest battle in the ongoing struggle
over how the government should be compensated for treating those
who suffered from tobacco related illness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 tobacco companies, besieged by state lawsuits, offered
to pay out $368 billion to settle those suits. That triggered a
yearlong debate in Congress that culminated in Senate Republicans
killing an administration backed plan that would have extracted
$516 billion from tobacco companies in the form of higher cigarette
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Congressional failure to reach a national
settlement, a majority of states negotiated on their own with
tobacco companies. Forty-six states have agreed to accept $206
billion from tobacco companies over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But governors and federal officials have continued to tangle
over whether the federal government should have a share of the
settlement funds.
</P>
<P>
   The failed amendment offered by Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa, and
Tom Harken, D-Iowa, was intended as a compromise between the White
House and the governors.
</P>
<P>
   It would have allowed the states to keep the tobacco money but
would have mandated that half of it be spend on health-related
programs. Under the proposal, 20 percent of the tobacco funds would
have to be spent for smoker cessation programs and 30 percent for
public health.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said some states have been proposing to use the tobacco
money for such purposes as highways, mental health programs, debt
reduction and to increase teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Republican said that while he believed that
``the federal government should not micromanage the use of the
funds, I am not prepared to turn all of this money over to the
states carte blanche to use on matters unrelated to tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of the compromise is likely to set up a fight with
the White House. In a letter to Specter, Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala stated the administration's ``strong
opposition'' to the Hutchison provision prohibiting any federal
control over the tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   She said that under the Texas Republicans' plan, ``states would
not have to spend a single penny of tobacco settlement funds to
reduce youth smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala, however, said the White House would be willing to work
with Congress on an alternative approach that would ensure that
funds are used to reduce smoking and ``for other shared and
national priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   An HHS spokeswoman said that the president's advisers have
recommended that Clinton veto the emergency spending bill if it
contains the Hutchison provision barring any federal role in the
tobacco money. However, the spokeswoman said the administration was
willing to accept the compromise crafted by Specter and Harkin.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency spending bill would primarily fund a relief effort
for Central American victims of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
