<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-DAIMLER-CHRYSLER (Undated) _ Two years ago,
Mercedes-Benz wowed the world with its M-Class, an ``all activity
vehicle'' that set the standard for performance and versatility in
the sport utility market, yet was priced to compete with midsize
sport utilities derived from aging truck designs. So what could be
better than the 3.2-liter, 6-cylinder, 215-horsepower all-wheel
drive ML320? Well, DaimlerChrysler is back with the 4.3-liter,
8-cylinder, 268-horsepower ML430, a more muscular-looking variation
on the same bankable theme. By Peter Passell.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-G-WAGENS (Undated) _ Just over 20 years ago,
Steyr-Daimler-Puch, an Austrian contractor for Daimler-Benz,
developed a heavy, Jeep-like, four-wheel-drive military vehicle for
the Shah of Iran. After he was overthrown, Mercedes sold this
Gelaendewagen _ ``cross country vehicle'' in German _ to various
European armies and then to a few civilians. In 1983, David
Holland, the founder of Europa International, a dealer of vintage
Mercedes cars in Santa Fe, N.M., got the idea of importing G-Wagens
for their curiosity value. From 1995 to '98, Europa sold a few
dozen lushly-equipped three- and five-door versions (labeled the
G320 for their 3.2-liter six cylinder engines). Now Europa is
importing a yet-swankier version, a model that preserves the
G-Wagen's squarely retro look but uses a new Mercedes engine that
meets environmental requirements in all 50 states. By Peter
Passell.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
