A5669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-PORTALS-COX     03-18 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PORTALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: Today in lead means Friday, March 19.
 &HT;    BellSouth launches new portal
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _BellSouth.net is launching a new portal service today
called BellSouth Buzz to boost usage of its online yellow pages and
attract advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The sites, to be maintained by 40 BellSouth employees, will be
customized for each of the 62 markets served by BellSouth's
nine-state region.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta users can access Atlanta Buzz at http://www.
bellsouth.net. The site will have city-specific news, information,
entertainment, discussion groups and the opportunity for users to
build community areas similar to those on AccessAtlanta, one of the
top Web sites in the area.
</P>
<P>
   AccessAtlanta will contribute content to BellSouth's Buzz.
through a linking agreement. Buzz users who click on AccessAtlanta
content will, in turn, be referred back to the AccessAtlanta site.
AccessAtlanta is a unit of unit of Cox Interactive Media, part of
Cox Enterprises which owns The Atlanta Journal and Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's vice president of Advanced Data Systems Donna
LaChance, who heads up the Buzz project says, ``We want to provide
a compelling starting place for people who want to get the most out
of their time online. We are going to do this by focusing on their
local community, local commerce and advanced communications.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz sites will be built and maintained by BellSouth.net
content developers and managers who will build community, chat and
other areas for users.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth seems to have ripped a page from not just
AccessAtlanta, but also from Microsoft Sidewalk's local buying
guides.
</P>
<P>
   The company has more than 30 content providers contributing to
the site in addition to AccessAtlanta, including USA Today and
Thompson Financial Networks.
</P>
<P>
   LaChance says that part of BellSouth's strategy is to
incorporate local news content into its site wherever it comes
from. That's why she's turning to local sites like AccessAtlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yellow pages are integral to this local portal,'' says
LaChance. ``The whole purpose of the site is to help people live
their lives.'' She says BellSouth's yellow pages can't be found
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only (southeastern yellow pages) that will be
up-to-the-minute current,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   LaChance says she also hopes to sell display ads online which
will push local advertisers to the top of the listings heap.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester analyst Bill Bass says BellSouth's portal strategy is
a way to drive users to its online yellow pages. ``BellSouth is
going to have the best yellow pages directory in the southeast with
the most updates and the most phone numbers. They are sitting on a
tremendous asset, but the problem is, how do you get people to go
to that site, `` he says. ``The best way to do that is to build out
functionality.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why BellSouth is turning to other local media companies
like AccessAtlanta for local news and other content
</P>
<P>
   Users don't have to be subscribers to BellSouth.net, the
company's Internet service provider to access the service.
</P>
<P>
   Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
