<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dow misses a 10,000 close by a whisker
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thrill of victory eluded stock market investors
againThursday, although they avoided the agony of defeat when the
Dow Jones industrial average remained within three points of
10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark index of 30 blue chip stocks crossed 10,000
several times in the closing minutes, topping out at 10,001.51
before falling back. Even so, it closed up 1.2 percent at a new
high.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for a major stock index to hit a wall when
approaching a highly publicized benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, computerized sell programs get in the way; other
times the number starts to lose its magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, crossing a round number seems to be an
anti-climactic event,'' Merrill Lynch chief market strategist Dick
Mccabe said.
</P>
<P>
   The index first traded above 10,000 early Tuesday, reaching
10,001.78 before dropping back.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge Thursday were American Express, up $6.68 3/4
to $127.62 1/2; Philip Morris, $3.75 to $42; J.P. Morgan, $2.68 3/4
to $124.18 3/4; and Merck, $2 to $86.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts give the Dow good odds of closing over the top in
today's ``triple witching'' session, when stock options, index
options and index futures expire, adding to market turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 and the Nasdaq composite indexes both rose 1.4
percent, with the S&AMP;P 500 also closing at a new high.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury yields fell after a government report that February
consumer prices rose only 0.1 percent due to cheap imports. But
those imports also sent the U.S. trade deficit to a record $17
billion in January.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
