<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, March 19, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-KAZAN (Los Angeles) _ Sunday night's Oscar-cast is
shaping up to be the most controversial in years as opposition to
the special award to Elia Kazan heats up. Hollywood's most powerful
guilds representing directors, writers and actors held a press
conference outside the Academy's Wilshire Boulevard headquarters
Thursday to denounce the academy's decision to honor the
89-year-old director who named names in the 1950's McCarthy
hearings. By Michael Coit. (Will move in the ``e'' entertainment,
``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOY-DONOR (Los Angeles) _ Seven-year-old Amador Navarro meets
for the first time the donor who saved his life after a three year
battle with leukemia. The boy and his donor, Christina Ozaeta, a
mother of two from Las Cruces, New Mexico, have only corresponded
by mail and by phone since she donated bone marrow transplant more
than a year ago. By Yvette Cabrera. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ A small maker of computer power
converters said it had no explanation for recent speculation in its
stock that has pushed the price up from 2 cents per share to 18.75
cents at the close of trading Thursday. Golden Systems is about a
year behind schedule in its SEC filings after nearly going broke in
1995-96. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOUR-MEDIA-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ Shares of Four Media gain 14
percent after the fast-expanding postproduction specialist
announces better than expected earnings and issues a bullish
forecast. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
