<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBMD-COX     03-18 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD purchases health-care software
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD has agreed to buy 50,000 copies of souped-up
communications software for health-care professionals from Premiere
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the largest sale thus far of Premiere's flagship
product, the Orchestra software, acccording to company Senior Vice
President Randy Salisbury, senior vice president of Atlanta-based
Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   While the announcement is a boost to a pair of ambitious
companies, it is also a deal done between two that already are
closely related. The two companies share the same building and at
least one board member _ Billy Payne, former president of the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Premiere also owns about 10 percent of WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Via the Internet, WebMD offers a range of specialized medical
data to professionals, who pay for the service, as well as a
variety of free health information to consumers. The company is
planning to provide the Orchestra software to doctors, nurses and
other healthcare professionals who subscribe to the company's
$30-a-month service.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Premiere will let WebMD offer doctors signing up
for its Internet service a more effective way to receive and send
messages through a feature called ``virtual receptionist.''
</P>
<P>
   Premiere's Orchestrate software lets a user on a phone hear
voice mail, as well as fax and e-mail messages. The user can
respond with the push of a button, either being connected with the
caller or by having the system record a message and send it through
the Net as an audio file to the sender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just making it more convenient and simplifying
communications,'' Salisbury said. ``Now doctors can use different
devices to communicate with all the people who are trying to
communicate with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Orchestrate also lets the user tap into voice and e-mail
messages via computer. However, it would not be possible to respond
via the computer to any caller whose e-mail address is not
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's top officials were traveling and unavailable for
comment. But Salisbury said Premiere is confident that WebMD's
business will do so well that 50,000 copies of Orchestra will not
be enough, Salisbury said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will also not be the last large deal, although it comes
in marked contrast to previous sales to small and home offices,
Salisbury said. ``Those are mostly onesies and twosies. But we have
other partnerships pending. WebMD is the only the first of a number
of companies.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, which launched its service in the fall, has recently
announced plans for an initial public offering of stock sometime in
the next few months. The company had similar plans in August, then
pulled back from the brink when the market for IPOs went sour.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
