<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUACKERY-0319-COX     03-18 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKERY-0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'AMAZING RANDI' TAKES CAMPAIGN AGAINST QUACKERY TO CONGRESS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - James Randi, the former magician who has found a
second career in debunking what he calls ``pseudoscience,'' called
on Congress Thursday to protect a gullible public from a flood of
untested and unproven ``natural'' products.
</P>
<P>
   To dramatize what he called the ``quackery'' of homeopathy,
Randi gobbled down a box full of homeopathic pills that purport to
treat insomnia, even though the label said the ``maximum'' dose was
a pill every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words 'natural' and 'herbal' are seen and heard aplenty in
advertisements for quack products,'' Randi said in an appearance
sponsored by the House Science and Technology Committee. ``And
American citizens, some 70 million of them, are embracing untested
and unproven nostrums. We owe them better than to ignore their need
for information.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling homeopathy ``one example of the sort of nonsense we have
to deal with,'' Randi held up a box containing the ``homeopathic''
insomnia remedy, which he said he had purchased at a store operated
by a national drugstore chain.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum dose, according to the label on the box of
``Naturelife'' insomnia pills, was one pill every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 45 tablets (in the box),'' he said. ``I'll take the
whole works.''
</P>
<P>
   Munching away and sipping water, Randi explained that the pills
purport to contain coffee in a concentration of ``30x.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just how much coffee did I get when I ingested all 45 pills in
this package?'' he asked. ``Zero. Zilch. Nada. In fact, the
concentration of '30x,' the favored concentration in most
homeopathy, would mean that there is one part coffee in one
thousand, billion, billion, billion parts milk sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that number means that he would have to consume ``16
swimming pools filled to the brim with these pills'' in order to
get a single molecule of caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Morris, who said he was an education specialist for
Nature's Way of Provo, Utah, the apparent manufacturer of the pills
Randi took, said the pills don't have to actually contain caffeine
to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Morris insisted that homeopathy works, although he said no one
knows why. One theory is that substances that have come into
contact with active ingredients, such as caffeine, ``remember'' the
ingredients and convey their effect in some way, according to
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine, normally thought of as a substance that keeps people
awake, is taken as a homeopathic cure of insomnia under a theory
that it ``immunizes'' the user in some way.
</P>
<P>
   Randi, who won a MacArthur Foundation prize several years ago
for his work debunking ``paranormal'' science, faith healers and
medical quackery, spoke to about 50 people in the committee's
hearing room. All members of the committee were involves in House
floor debate, so none attended his presentation.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that he was not the first ``conjuror'' to appear at a
congressional event (cq). The famous magician Harry Houdini
testified before a packed house in 1926 to promote a bill against
fortune-telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houdini, as I, was dismayed at the public belief in
supernatural forces and pseudoscientific notions,'' Randi said.
``But perhaps his solution, legislation, was not the ideal one. I
favor education over legislation, so that citizens will avoid
surrendering to the charlatans due to better information and an
``understanding of how the real world works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all subject to bad judgment from time to time,'' he
added. ``But much of that weakness can be avoided by education, at
a very early age. We owe it to our kids to inform them and train
them how to think, not what to think.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
