<HEADER>
A5680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS &LR;      03-18 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS CONTINUE TO REJECT PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ In a symbolic act that held more promise of a
threatened airstrike than of making peace on the ground, ethnic
Albanians Thursday put their sole signatures on a peace plan for
the disputed province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, however, are continuing to refuse to sign the
Western-crafted document, heightening the possibility that a
long-threatened NATO assault on Serbia might be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, the ruling Serbian regime continued a massive
military buildup, fueling fears that they are gearing up for a
fight against the Kosovo Liberation Army, a pro-independence
militia that has been battling Serb forces for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian delegation ``signature shows their commitment to a
peace settlement and for a future of democratic self-government,''
US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said after the Paris
signing ceremony. ``Unfortunately, the Serb negotiations have gone
backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to remind Mr. (Yugoslav President Slobodan)
Milosevic that NATO stands ready to take whatever measures are
necessary,'' Albright said after briefing Senators in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There was some talk in Paris that the Serbs would be given a
grace period _ perhaps until Wednesday _ to sign. But White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart and Philip Reeker, spokesman for US peace
negotiator Chris Hill, said no deadline was set.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian delegation was given more than two weeks after the
talks ceased in Rambouillet, France last month to canvass their own
constituency and amass support for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   A second round of peace talks in Paris appeared ready to
dissolve Thursday, with the Albanians leaving town and the Serbs
showing no sign of wanting to negotiate further.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, designed by a Contact Group of six Western powers,
gives broad political autonomy to Kosovo, a southern province of
Serbia, which is itself a republic of Yugoslavia. The proposed deal
would give more authority to local ethnic Albanians, who make up an
estimated 90 percent of Kosovo's 2.2 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are refusing to even discuss one of the Contact
Group's critical demands _ that there be 28,000 NATO troops,
including 4,000 Americans, in Kosovo to keep the peace after an
agreement is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the Serbs also were trying to change elements of the
political agreement already agreed to in the first round of peace
talks last month in Rambouillet, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   In a year of attacks and retreats by both sides, an October
cease-fire agreement that has been honored by neither side, and two
sets of political negotiations that have been signed by only one
side, the outlook for Kosovo has never been so grim.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has continued in Kosovo, where more than 2,000 people
have been killed and well over a quarter of a million people have
been displaced.
</P>
<P>
   More Albanian villages were burned this week, forcing thousands
of refugees to flee. Aid organizations have reported an influx of
refugees into neighboring Macedonia, on Kosovo's southern border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has been threatening an air strike against Milosevic since
October. After the peace negotiations began last month, Albright
said NATO would strike only if the Albanians signed, but the Serbs
did not.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's solemn signing ceremony in Paris made the warning of
a NATO attack more acute.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the international mediators _ Hill and European
Union representative Wolfgang Petritsch _ signed the plan as
witnesses. The Russian mediator, Boris Maiorsky, did not add his
name to the document. Russia traditionally has had stronger ties
with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock also puts pressure on NATO, which has repeatedly
warned Milosevic it might strike, but has not followed through.
Advocates of an air assault insist force is the only language
Milosevic understands, noting that it was only after NATO air
strikes in Bosnia in 1995 that a peace agreement was forged.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting Serbia is trickier politically, since it would be an
assault on the national army of a sovereign nation involved in an
internal conflict. In Bosnia, there was the pretext of cross-border
aggression by the Serbs to justify an attack by international
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bombing Serbia could well produce American casualities, one of
the Pentagon's chief military commanders told Congress Thursday.
The prospect would make an air attack on Serbia more difficult to
sell to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Since Yugoslavia's air defenses are well-defended, ``there is a
distinct possibility we will lose aircraft in trying to penetrate
those defenses,'' Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff,
told the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
