<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARRAKHAN-ILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MUSLIM LEADER DENIES FARRAKHAN SERIOUSLY ILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The rumor mill has been working overtime lately within
the Nation of Islam. Reports have circulated that one of its
leaders, the fiery Louis Farrakhan, was gravely ill with an unknown
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Minister Don Muhammad, leader of the Nation of Islam
mosque in Boston, denied the reports, circulated by a top Nation of
Islam official that Farrakhan was battling a life-threatening
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an erroneous story going around,'' said Muhammad,
standing in his daughter's restaurant in the city's Grove Hall
section. ``He will be taking a much-needed rest.'' Farrakhan has a
home in Arizona, but officials have not disclosed where he is
resting.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Farrakhan himself helped inflame rumors when he
told followers in Chicago that he had been sick for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I am nearing 66 years of age, I have never been ill
like this in my life,'' Farrakhan said during a Nation of Islam
celebration that drew more than 20,000 people to a Chicago
convention hall. ``This illness took me down so fast that I lost
nearly 20 pounds in less than two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan's speech is included in the nation's official website.
In 1991 Farrakhan announced he had prostate cancer, for which he
has been receiving treatment on and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no appetite,'' he said in Chicago. ``And night sweats,
pain, bouts of insomnia. I was anemic, dehydraded. But I thank
Allah, the healer, for gradually returning my health and my
strength back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Several phone calls to the Nation of Islam headquarters in
Chicago Thursday were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   At Mosque Maryam, Farrakhan's home base on the city's South
Side, there was a steady flow of vehicles, but nothing to suggest
anything out of the ordinary. Mosque members refused to discuss
Farrakhan's health.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published earlier this week in the Final Call, the
Nation's official newspaper, and posted on the paper's website,
Jabril Muhammad, one of Farrakhan's closest advisers, said the
sharp-tongued Muslim leader was ``struggling to overcome the forces
of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Jabril Muhammad said Farrakhan was so sick it was uncertain
whether he would be able to appear during the February celebration.
But Farrakhan, Jabril Muhammad added, not only appeared, but spoke
for more than three hours.
</P>
<P>
   According to another person who saw the speech, Farrakhan was
thinner than usual, but looked vigorous. Although Farrakhan hinted
several times that this might be his last appearance at the
February event, he has made such suggestions in the past, often
with the implication that someone might try to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest issue of the Village Voice, Farrakhan reportedly
told his followers that he had been poisoned by the US government.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, rumors that Farrakhan was close to death reverberated
across Roxbury, where as a child growing up he was known as Louis
Eugene Walcott.
</P>
<P>
   Elma Lewis, a Boston cultural arts legend, said she received
calls Thursday morning inquiring about her friend's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was shook up, but I knew if that was true I would
have known,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, when Lewis was very sick, Farrakhan and
his sons visited her Roxbury home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is like a little brother to me. He was a beautiful,
beautiful little boy,'' said Lewis, 78. ``Now Malcom (Malcolm X)
was a bad boy turned good, but Farrakhan was always a good boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they don't subscribe to the same philosphy, Lewis said
they have remained close friends. Whenever Farrakahn visits Boston,
he calls or visits her. Sometimes he will call from Chicago, and
the two will talk about current events or their lives in Roxbury so
many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said she knew Farrakhan had been sick throughout January
or February, but was shocked and annoyed to hear rumors that his
health had taken a turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   She said black leaders Farrakhan, Malcolm X and Martin Luther
King Jr. expect to die by a gun, not by illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, if someone would have told me that he was assassinated,
then I would have believed it. But to be felled by a disease at
such a young age, when he lives such a clean life is shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Farrakhan eats only once a day, subscribes to a strict
diet, and regularly exercises.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Farrakhan and his boys visited her home, he handed
her a copy of a video that documents his life as a violinist.
Sitting in her study Thursday, Lewis proudly watched it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks so young,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent David Moberg contributed to this report from
Chicago.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
