<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0319-C     03-18 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PENTAGON OFFICIALS WARN OF 'LOSS OF LIFE' IN KOSOVO CAMPAIGN, AS
SERBS REJECT PEACE PLAN
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trims throughout.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Serbs rejected a U.S. peace plan for Kosovo on
Thursday and advanced preparations for an all-out ground war, as
the Pentagon warned of the perils and uncertainties of NATO air
strikes in the troubled Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Flying into the jaws of aggressive air defenses over craggy
terrain in foul weather and, at times, chasing hard to find mobile
targets, U.S. and other NATO pilots could run a substantial risk of
being shot down, cautioned Air Force chief of staff Gen. Michael
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a distinct possibility we will lose aircraft in
trying to penetrate those defenses,'' Ryan testified before the
Senate Armed Services Committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be under no illusions that this would be easy,''
echoed Adm. Jay Johnson, chief of operations for the Navy, which
would likely front pilots as part of a NATO air campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is high, in my view,'' said Johnson, ''And we must be
prepared to take losses if we engage that system.''
</P>
<P>
   With target lists complete for more than 350 NATO warplanes --
half of them American -- standing by to launch strikes against Serb
military and communications sites, the White House said the
long-looming military showdown with the Serbs was near.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached the final and decisive phase,'' President
Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, told reporters. ``The military
planning is complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart made the remarks shortly after ethnic Albanians from
Kosovo, a province in the Yugoslav state of Serbia, signed onto a
U.S.-brokered peace treaty in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic, however, remained
intransigent, refusing to sign the accord, which calls for sending
28,000 NATO peacekeepers into Kosovo, where more than a year of war
has left some 2,000 dead and more than 230,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has threatened air strikes against Serbs if they refuse to
sign the peace treaty, or if they continue a campaign of attacking
ethnic Albanians -- who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population
of 2.2 million -- and villages across the rural province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Such strikes likely would not begin before early next week,
officials said, to give time to evacuate more than 1,000
international monitors and humanitarian workers now on the ground
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is as clear as it could be,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright told reporters on Capitol Hill. ``The Albanians
have said yes to the accords and the Serbs are saying no.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, Belgrade's security forces are stepping up
their unjustified and aggressive actions in Kosovo, and if Belgrade
doesn't reverse course, the Serbs alone will be responsible for the
consequences,'' Albright added. ``NATO stands ready to take
whatever measures are necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins.)
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon estimates that more than 30,000 Serb troops --
backed by scores of tanks and other armored equipment -- have
massed in and around Kosovo, in apparent preparation for a major
ground assault.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the rebel group, the Kosovo Liberation Army, reported
seeing Serbs setting up mobile surface-to-air missiles in the
rugged mountains outside of the Kosovo capital of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The region is also bristling with Soviet-built surface-to-air
missile defenses, some shoulder-fired heat-seeking missiles and
more than 2,000 anti-aircraft guns, remnants of the Cold War days
when Yugoslavia was part of the Soviet defense structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a robust, highly integrated, well-equipped air defense
system, operated by well-trained people,'' Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth Bacon told reporters. ``They have been rehearsing and
training fairly aggressively in the last several weeks, and it is a
system to be taken very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Air strikes would likely begin with the firing of scores of
long-range cruise missiles, capable of flying hundreds of miles to
destroy their targets with no risk to the troops firing them. There
are six U.S. ships and submarines in the region capable of firing
such weapons, which can also be launched from aircraft flying at
high altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, cruise missile attacks would be followed up with
air strikes from warplanes protected by U.S. EA-6b jets -- packed
with sophisticated electronic jamming equipment to thwart radar --
from nearby Aviano Air Base in Italy, as well as F-16s armed with
radar-seeking missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a dozen radar-evading F-117 stealth bombers now
at Aviano, Gen. Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Even using the most sophisticated warplanes in the U.S. arsenal,
however, success in Kosovo is not assured.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be tremendously dangerous,'' warned Marine
Corps Commandant, Gen. Charles Krulak. ``The systems are, in many
instances, mobile. The terrain is very tough. And the weather
cannot be underestimated. That can be a show-stopper in many
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet to be worked out, Krulak said, are a host of strategic and
political questions unrelated to the logistics of military strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom-line question that needs to be resolved is 'Would
the strikes, and will the strikes, achieve an end? What is that
end,''' Krulak said.
</P>
<P>
   Krulak's concerns were echoed by Senate Republicans, some of
whom said the White House hasn't laid the political foundation for
the country to support high-risk air strikes in far-off Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is not comfortable with the situation as it now
stands,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
immediately following a closed-door briefing with Albright, Defense
Secretary William Cohen and other members of Clinton's national
security team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be briefed more, we need to be advised what the
risks are,'' Lott said, ``and the American people need to have a
better understanding of what the United States national security
interests are, if any.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lott stopped short of saying he would oppose strikes,
others did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am more convinced than ever that this is a mistake at this
time,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas. ``I am very firm
that I will oppose action in Kosovo until there is a clear peace
agreement and until we know what the mission is, we know what is
expected of our troops, how many it will take, what it will cost,
and what our timetable will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House maintains that it does not need congressional
approval for U.S. forces to participate in NATO air strikes against
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed an activation order formally authorizing U.S.
participation in such strikes last October. That move spurred
Milosevic to agree to a set of peace accords -- including
withdrawing military forces from Kosovo and ending aggression
against ethnic Albanians there -- that the Serbs have since
violated.
</P>
<P>
   While part of Serbia's territory, Kosovo has been a tinderbox
for years. Majority Albanians largely favor independence. Under the
U.S.-backed peace accord Kosovar Albanians signed Thursday, Kosovo
would be granted autonomy -- the same status it enjoyed until 1989
as part of the former Yugoslavia -- but not full independence.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles in Kosovo loosely mirror those in nearby Bosnia,
where NATO air strikes combined with U.S. diplomacy in the fall of
1995 to end three and a half years of ethnic fighting among Serbs
and non-Serbs. A U.S.-led NATO peacekeeping mission has been posted
in Bosnia for the past three years, policing the fragile peace
there.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
