<HEADLINE>
EMIL GUBA, 101; WAS SPECIALIST IN PLANT DISEASES, MUSHROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emil F. Guba, a professor of plant pathology and mycology who
helped develop a species of greenhouse tomato resistant to leaf
mold disease, died Tuesday in Bethesda at Evanswood Nursing
Facility in Kingston, Mass. He was 101.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Guba was a professor at the University of Massachusetts and
researcher at the Waltham Field Station for nearly 40 years. His
work led to the elimination or amelioration of many plant diseases,
including the propagation of varieties of carnations resistant to
several maladies, and the formulation of techniques that allow
fruit to avoid spoilage both in storage and in the field.
</P>
<P>
   He was the author or co-author of more than 100 agricultural
bulletins and scientific papers.
</P>
<P>
   A grant from the National Science Foundation allowed him to
preserve all the study materials and fungus specimens that he
accumulated in the research for his magnum opus, ``Monograph of
Monochaetia and Pestalotia,'' which was the result of 40 years of
work and was published by Harvard University Press. Those materials
now repose in the collection of the Smithsonian Institution in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the book ``Wild Mushrooms, Food and Poison,'' he
was a consultant to the Boston Poison Information Center at
Children's Hospital Medical Center and an enthusiastic participant
in mushroom tastings sponsored by the Boston Mycological Club, of
which he was a honorary member.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring in 1962, he cultivated an interest in history,
particularly that of Nantucket, where he had studied the vegetation
for several scientific papers. He was the author of the history
book ``Nantucket Odyssey'' and a biography of the woman who posed
as a man and fought in the American Revolution, titled ``Deborah
Samson, Alias Robert Shurtliff, Revolutionary War Soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Guba was born in New Bedford, Mass. He graduated from
Massachusetts Agricultural College and the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a son, Robert, of Acton, Mass.; a daughter, Anne, of
Kingston, Mass.; four grandchildren; and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
