<SLUG> BC-DRUNKEN-DRIVING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILLS TO LOWER ALCOHOL LIMIT, IMPOSE PENALTIES FOR
DRIVERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas senators, seeking to save lives and draw
$26 million in federal highway funds, passed bills Thursday to
lower the legal alcohol limit for drivers and hike penalties for
those refusing breathalyzer tests.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 114 by Sen. Mario Gallegos, D-Galena Park, would
lower the legal limit from .10 percent to .08 percent blood-alcohol
content.
</P>
<P>
   A separate measure, SB 388, would suspend drivers' licenses for
those refusing to take a breathalyzer or blood test for a year
rather than the current 90 days. The bill sponsored by Sen. Eddie
Lucio, D-Brownsville, also increases jail time for drunk-driving
offenders from at least three days to a minimum of five days.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who endorsed the legislation along with
Gov. George W. Bush and Mothers Against Drunk Driving, said it will
go a long way toward ``cracking down on the drunk-driving carnage''
on Texas highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bills also say we care about our friends, neighbors and
families,'' he added. ``Too many in our state have already suffered
the great loss associated with drunk driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Gallegos' bill, a 170-pound man would have to stop
drinking after four drinks in one hour on an empty stomach. A
120-pound woman would have to stop at three drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all heard the heart-breaking testimony from our
constituents,'' said Gallegos, whose bill drew parents and friends
of four high school girls killed by a drunken driver to hearings
before the Senate Criminal Justice Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he said, 1,700 Texans were lost to drunk-driving
accidents, he said, with another Texan killed every eight hours and
13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced an effective way to curb this kind of insanity
is through the enactment of Senate Bill 114,'' Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Berman, general counsel for the American Beverage
Institute, argues the lower alcohol limit targets responsible
social drinkers, and other critics say these are not the drivers
causing the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only effect of an .08 law is that many social drinkers
will be jailed, fined and suffer costs up to $15,000,'' he said,
``for behavior that is presently considered responsible in most
states and that is not part of the drunk-driving problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos faced a series of questions in the Senate from Lucio,
who sponsored the companion drunk-driving bill but also was
responsible for killing Gallegos' bill last session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every newspaper in this state reiterates that I was the one
that tagged your bill last session at the eleventh hour. That's
history,'' said Lucio who said he joins in expressing condolences
to families who've lost loved ones in drunk-driving accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio said he felt at the time that the legislation would
incriminate law-abiding citizens. He also said that the driver who
killed the four high school girls had a blood-alcohol levels of
.16, or twice the proposed new rate.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio, who supported the bill anyway, underwent scrutiny himself
on his companion bill regarding how much more it will cost counties
to keep drunk drivers in jail longer.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, and others questioned the high price
tag Lucio's bill carries, according to estimates in the fiscal note
to the bill. It shows that if two days are added to the minimum
jail time for those guilty of drunken driving, it would costs
counties $1.8 million more statewide.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the 33 percent of drivers refusing to take the test took
it and were found guilty, the costs would rise by another $2.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio said if the bill saves lives by keeping drunken drivers
off the street, the cost should not matter.
</P>
<P>
   A third bill seeks to stop courts from routinely letting teens
off easy for violating a zero-tolerance law on drinking any amount
of alcohol and driving. The bill, sponsored by West, clarifies that
even when teens agree to deferred adjudication to avoid a trial,
they must agree to perform community service in a addition to
paying a fine. Also, their drivers' licenses must be suspended for
a time beginning with the 11th day following a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
