<SLUG> BC-ENDLIFE-CARE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARE FOR THE DYING CAN BE IMPROVED, COALITION INSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Jack Kevorkian offers dying patients a false choice
between suicide and a painful, technology-filled death, a panel
representing more than 300 health, religious and consumer
organizations said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Good end-of-life care with compassionate treatment and effective
pain relief is possible for all patients if the public demands it,
the Last Acts coalition said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans should expect and be able to get end-of-life care
that respects their own wishes and needs,'' said Ira Byock, a
physician on the Last Acts panel. ``Dying is always hard, but it
need not be horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Byock spoke at a press teleconference in Detroit timed to
precede Kevorkian's first-degree murder trial in Michigan next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, a retired pathologist, claims to have been involved
in the assisted suicides of more than 130 people. He is charged
with murder for allegedly injecting a lethal dose of chemicals into
a man with Lou Gehrig's disease. A videotape of the incident was
aired on television's ``60 Minutes'' in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Acts coalition includes the American Medical
Association, the American Nurses Association, the American Cancer
Society and the Alzheimer's Association. Its honorary chairwoman is
former first lady Rosalynn Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition hopes to shift the public debate on end-of-life
treatment away from legalization of physician-assisted suicide,
such as Kevorkian practices. Instead, it wants greater public
involvement in initiatives to improve care for dying patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Kevorkian's provocative act raises important questions,''
said panel member Timothy Quill, a physician who supports
legalization of physician-assisted suicide. ``But his answers are
clearly in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian offers a ``very stark and false choice'' between
suicide and a lingering high-tech death, when there are actually
many options for relieving pain and suffering, Quill said.
</P>
<P>
   Much progress in end-of-life care is occurring at the local
level, said panel member Myra Christopher, president of the Midwest
Bioethics Center in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Among the successful programs, Christopher said, is one in
Birmingham, Ala., that provides inpatient hospice care to indigent
patients, and another program in Nevada to monitor patients closely
for pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many, many places there are exciting things being done to
make things different,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Acts panel released a national public-opinion survey
that found widespread dissatisfaction with the job the medical
community was doing providing end-of-life care.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the 1,000 people interviewed by telephone said
the health-care system was doing a poor or only fair job of helping
dying patients stay free of pain, helping them maintain their
dignity and involving patients and their families in care
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Byock said Last Acts hoped to ``dramatically raise public
expectations'' for end-of-life care. To that end, the panel offered
a five-part ``blueprint'' of adequate palliative care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palliative care means taking care of the whole patient, body,
mind...and soul,'' Byock said. ``As long as there is life, we can
treat people with medically excellent care, but also tender loving
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the blueprint:
</P>
<P>
   --Respect for the choices of the dying person. Doctors and
nurses should try to meet treatment preferences of the patient and
family. For example, some patients may prefer care at home.
</P>
<P>
   --Looking after the medical, emotional, social and spiritual
needs of the dying person. Palliative care should offer ways to
reduce pain, ensure that the patient is not alone and help the
patient make peace.
</P>
<P>
   --Support of family members. Family caregivers need time off for
rest, help coping with the costs of caregiving and help with
grieving.
</P>
<P>
   --Access to care providers and appropriate care settings. Good
palliative care assumes that clergy, social workers, and personal
caregivers are as important as doctors and nurses. Home, hospice
and hospital treatment are offered as options.
</P>
<P>
   --Better training of health professionals in end-of-life care
and more comprehensive insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have people say, `I want good end-of-life care. I
know what it is and I'm going to get it for me and my loved ones,'
'' Christopher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
