<HEADLINE>
A GLORIOUS SEASON OF NEW LIFE UNFOLDS ON A VISIT TO THE COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Yesterday was a day of several textures. And everywhere
were the signs of spring coming on with a rush.
</P>
<P>
   The morning was passed with friends on a river, the bluff
sliding by steep and forested, with pale green moss glistening on
the stones. By 9 o'clock, the sun was so warm no coat was needed
except where a bend of the current put the boat in deepest shade.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in afternoon, a couple of hours were spent with a farmer
and his wife, looking at new calves. One had come sometime the
night before. The other was even newer _ hours old only _ and still
had not yet quite found its balance. Of 60-some so far this spring,
the wife said, only two had needed help in getting born.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it's been a fine calving season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have those long, terrible cold spells,'' she said.
``And there weren't any that came when it was so awfully wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost while we watched, it seemed, the latest youngster was
gaining confidence and spunk. He even bucked and kicked a little,
to make clear to us or anyone else who might be watching that he
was a critter to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   Then he teetered away after his mother, looking apt at any
moment to subside in a tangle of knobby legs.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't help thinking what a grand day it was for making
one's start. The forecast told of a chance the bright sky might
give way to storms in a day or two. But for one still tasting the
world's novelties a breath at a time, tomorrow surely is
unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place rich with history, that farm _ three generations in
the same family. And rich with the many shapes that life can take _
the fine cattle herd; mares and their spindly legged foals; five
dogs; 13 cats keeping order in the 100-year-old barn. Also the wild
things, turkeys and deer, that shelter in the band of woods along
the creek at the bottom of the field.
</P>
<P>
   There were stops to make after that. One at a store in the town
close by. Another where a different friend was working in his barn
lot. I spied his truck from the road, and turned up the lane to
visit a bit.
</P>
<P>
   In such an easy, aimless fashion a country day can get away.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner than I'd have thought, the shadows were beginning to be
longer, the air cooler. I left the car at my cabin and walked down
the path to the pond.
</P>
<P>
   New pale-green candles showed at the tips of the pine branches.
The leaf buds of the maples were thumb-sized and bright scarlet.
Birds chittered in the thickets below the dam. I even thought I
heard the creaking of an optimistic _ perhaps fatally foolish _
tree frog.
</P>
<P>
   In only a moment then, late afternoon turned to evening, and I
hurried back up the path to start a stove fire to keep the chill
away. As I came into my clearing, I thought I saw a small movement
at the cabin's west side _ thought that, but wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, a fox has sometimes denned and brought off her
litter of kits in the crawl space beneath the cabin floor. It
pleased me to imagine she might be back.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the light was out and all was still, I heard a
scuttling from down there, followed after a bit by some whining,
yelping complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the noises seemed too robust to be made by foxes.
Coyote pups, possibly.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that something's made a home under my floor.
Tomorrow morning, when daylight comes, will be soon enough to
identify my lodger or lodgers. In any case, I don't mind sharing.
</P>
<P>
   It's the season of birthings and beginnings, and everything
alive needs some place to start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
