<HEADLINE>
A CHANGE OF TENOR FOR TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The workplace of the '90s is defined by downsizing,
loss of corporate job security and increased job-hopping.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, the median tenure of workers with their current
employer has been a fairly constant 3.4 to 3.8 years. The most
recent data available, for February 1998, put median tenure at 3.6
years. In other words: Same old same old.
</P>
<P>
   That longevity number, from the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
applies to all wage and salary workers over age 16. But there are
some deeper wrinkles in the blanket statement when tenure
statistics are analyzed by sex and age.
</P>
<P>
   For example, women traditionally have had shorter job tenures
than men. The gap is narrowing, though. In January 1987, men's
median time on the current job was 4 years and women's was 3 years.
Eleven years later, men's median tenure had slipped to 3.8 years
and women's had increased to 3.4 years.
</P>
<P>
   There's another interesting point in the job record of men age
45 and older. While women in that age category maintained or
increased their median tenure rate in the last 15 years,
45-and-older men have seen their tenure drop.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, men in that age group recorded a median tenure of 12.8
years. By 1998, their median had fallen to 9.4 years. Meanwhile,
women in that age group moved up, from medians of 6.3 years to 7.2
years.
</P>
<P>
   There was an even bigger employment tenure change for men ages
55 to 65. Their median tenure dropped from 15.3 years in 1983 to
11.2 years in 1998. Over the same period, tenure of women in that
age group stayed fairly constant: 9.8 years to 9.6 years.
</P>
<P>
   The employment stability record of the 55-and-over men
reinforced two trends that are definite hallmarks of the '90s:
</P>
<P>
   The downsizing ax _ wielded for cost-cutting reasons _ hit the
older male work force hard. Job fairs and outplacement offices are
full of 40- and 50-something men who were let go from their
well-paying corporate jobs.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many workers in that demographic category
have opted out of their previous employment by personal choice.
Many of them are financially comfortable because of profit-sharing
and other investments and are eager to explore self-employment
opportunities or enjoy early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   So the tenure median shows a big change, but it isn't easy to
say whether the change is mostly bad news or mostly good news for
those involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics didn't put a value judgment on
the change, but it did note that the shortened tenure defied
demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1983 to 1998 ... the share of men (in the work force)
ages 45 to 54 rose from 16 to 20 percent,'' the agency's report
said. ``All other things being equal, this age shift would have
been associated with an increase in median tenure. However, the
median tenure decline from 1983 to 1998 for men in every age group
offset the aging effect.''
</P>
<P>
   As tenure falls _ and experience and institutional memory go
with it _ one wonders about the consequences to organizations. Or
you could consider that it's nice to spread that expertise around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
