<HEADLINE>
IOC CHANGES WAY HOST CITIES ARE TO BE CHOSEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The Austrians had a TravelMate laptop at
their promotional booth in the lobby of the Palais de Beaulieu. If
an International Olympic Committee member wanted a look at
Klagenfurt this week, he could push a button and have a ``virtual
visit.'' But he can't go there _ at least not before the site for
the 2006 Winter Games is chosen in June.
</P>
<P>
   No more trips to bid cities, the IOC has ruled. No more loans,
no more scholarships, no more cosmetic surgery, no more drooling
bulldogs. No more of the cornucopia of improprieties that produced
the most unsavory chapter in modern Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake give-and-take has gone low-budget. ``We can give a
money clip _ with no money in it,'' said Dieter Kalt, general
manager for the Klagenfurt bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   While Kalt was handing out symbolically empty clips Thursday
morning (``Let me corrupt you,'' he joked), the IOC members were
upstairs putting a formal end to the bidding process that brought
them scandal and shame.
</P>
<P>
   Though the full body still will pick the 2006 host city at its
next meeting in Seoul, it will choose from only two finalists
picked 30 minutes earlier by a 16-member panel (only 11 of them IOC
members) assembled that morning.
</P>
<P>
   For information, they will rely solely on a detailed report from
the IOC's site evaluation committee and a one-hour presentation
from each city. No visits _ period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, really, that's enough,'' stated IOC president Juan
Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, insist most of the six European candidates for 2006, who
claim that the no-visit rule gives a huge advantage to Sion, the
Swiss town that was a runner-up to Salt Lake last time. Sion got to
entertain roughly 70 IOC members under the old cashmere-and-caviar
rules. Nobody can do anything close this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can send them a book, but it is not the same thing,'' says
Marco San Pietro, international relations director for the Turin
committee. ``They cannot taste our wine or our food.''
</P>
<P>
   Turin, which has never bid before, was counting on wooing the
Lords of the Rings in person and pointing out that Italy's auto
capital has mountains nearby. ``Turin is not well known,'' says San
Pietro. ``It is perceived as an industrial city, the home of
Fiat.''
</P>
<P>
   Finland, bidding with the Norwegians, wanted to show that
Lillehammer is a long walk from Helsinki but a short flight.
Klagenfurt, which is pushing an unprecedented three-country Games
involving Austria, Italy, and Slovenia, wanted to prove it could
handle the complex logistics of a `bid without borders'.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show them that you could have breakfast in
Klagenfurt, lunch in Tarvisio, and dinner in Kranjska Gora,'' says
international relations director Petra Oberrauner. ``Now, they
cannot see our hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   The H-word is taboo in the post-Salt Lake era and the 2006
cities grudgingly accept that. ``They all understand the crisis
we're in,'' says IOC vice president Richard Pound of Canada. ``They
understand that visits are now regarded as anathema by almost
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The visits led to the ski vacations, which led to the
scholarships, which led to the five-figure payoffs that has torn
the IOC apart and produced the most radical reforms in its 105
years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides expelling six members Wednesday beyond the four who had
already resigned, the IOC, as expected, Thursday unanimously pushed
through a series of changes that will open up what has always been
a private club to global scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the month, the IOC will name both an independent
ethics panel and a reform commission (half of its members
outsiders) that will recommend changes in everything from how the
IOC chooses its members to how it distributes its money. Thursday,
the IOC posted its interim financial audit on the Internet
(www.olympic.org) for the world to pore over. ``We promised to
clean our house and begin reforms,'' said Samaranch. ``I think we
kept our word.''
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown on bid cities, Samaranch said, was both necessary
and overdue. ``The system of visits was a very bad system,'' he
said. ``So we cancel the system.''
</P>
<P>
   A 16-member panel, picked the morning of the vote in Seoul in
June, will narrow the six bid cities (Sion; Turin; Helsinki;
Klagenfurt; Zakopane, Poland; Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia) to two
finalists. The entire 100-plus IOC membership will choose the
winner. The panel will include: Samaranch, IOC dean Joao Havelange,
eight other IOC members, the chairman of the IOC's site evaluation
commission, one representative from both the winter sports
federations and the national Olympic committees, and three
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the IOC chose a winter site, in Budapest four
years ago, the Salt Lake City bidders brought nearly $50,000 for
last-minute lobbying. This week, Turin was handing out red silk
ties (``only worth $30,'' San Pietro insisted) and pens. And
Klagenfurt offered ``virtually'' nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Oberrauner said Thursday, clicking on a laptop map.
``Here is a 360-degree view of our downhill site. Want me to zoom
in?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
