<SLUG> BC-BOSCI-TOBIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBIN NAMED PRESIDENT OF BOSTON SCIENTIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than three months after dismissing speculation that he
might be a candidate for chief operating officer at Boston
Scientific Corp., James R. Tobin Thursday was named the company's
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, former chief executive of Biogen, joins the Natick, Mass.
medical devices company immediately. His appointment helped push
Boston Scientific stock up 4 1/2 Thursday to close at 38.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific has had its difficulties, among them a product
recall, recent accounting problems in Japan, and a US Justice
Department investigation. The company manufactures minimally
invasive devices used in cardiology and gastrointerology surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's decision to join Boston Scientific follows his surprise
resignation from Biogen Inc. last Dec. 23. That news sent Biogen
shares down eight percent and put a spotlight on Tobin's business
relationship with James Vincent, Biogen's strong-willed chairman
who had rescued the company from near bankruptcy in 1985. Vincent
ran the company until Tobin, who joined Biogen in 1994, took over
as president in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although they publicly agreed on the strategy for running the
company, sources had said Tobin, 54, felt his decisions were being
second-guessed by Vincent. Differences in management styles and
decision-making finally led to a showdown: in the end, Biogen's
board of directors sided with Vincent, prompting Tobin to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in December, some Wall Street analysts suggested that I
ought to consider Boston Scientific, which was looking for a
president,'' said Tobin, ``but it was not until mid-January that I
got a call from a headhunter and another analyst who said I really
ought to look at them.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific's founders _ Peter Nicholas and John Abele _
have been running the company together since 1979. And while they
are the largest shareholders, they have created a company that last
year had revenues of $2.23 billion and currently employs about
11,000 people. Yesteday, Tobin said he could see the company's
revenue double, but he declined to say when that could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Nicholas, 62, said he had discussed with Tobin the
reasons for his departure from Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't second-guess my management,'' said Nicholas. ``I work
with people, and I think Jim Tobin's approach is the same as mine.
But this change should not be viewed as Pete Nicholas' swan song. I
will be involved in many different ways. I will continue to focus
on long-term issues and strategies and be a partner with Jim,
responsive to the different ways he chooses to rely on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Thursday's announcement, several Wall Street
firms raised their ratings on Boston Scientific to a ``buy'' from a
``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's appointment ``is exactly what they need,'' said Robert
Faulkner of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, who was among the Wall Street
analysts who changed their Boston Scientific rating. ``He has a
reputation for being honest, a straight shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin _ who prior to joining Biogen spent 21 years at
health-care company Baxter International and rose to its number two
spot as president _ acknowledged that his employment contract with
Boston Scientific is significantly different than his Biogen
contract.
</P>
<P>
   At Biogen, if Tobin was not named president by a certain date in
1997, Biogen was to pay him a considerable amount of money. Biogen
did fulfill its contract.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, there is no such stipulation with Boston
Scientific, said Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am dealing with very different people here,'' said Tobin,
declining to discuss his relationship with Vincent. ``This time, I
sort of looked Pete in the eye and asked whether we can trust each
other. The answer for me was yes. That is all it took.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Information from Bloomberg News was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
