<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-NATURE19-COX     03-18 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-NATURE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unnatural `Forces'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The title ``Forces of Nature'' refers to the
streak of natural phenomena that prevents Ben Affleck from reaching
his wedding and Sandra Bullock from reaching her young son across
country. An errant goose aborts their flight. There's a train
mishap. Rain. Fire. Hurricane. By mid-movie, you'll pray for a
tidal wave to swallow them up and flush them to the bottom of the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   But Mother Nature rarely is so kind. Instead, she inflicts one
more natural force on the hapless, dentally blessed couple _ that
kooky cyclone called love.
</P>
<P>
   Call FEMA: There's a federal disaster area in a theater near
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' is a screwball love story punched up with a
visual panache that's just plain screwy. Director Bronwen Hughes
(``Harriet the Spy'') appears to have rigged the camera to a bungee
cord and mistakes gratuitous oblique angles and close-ups for
clever use of cinematic grammar. It's more like cinematic pig
Latin. But, boy, she sure has fun with those blue lens filters!
</P>
<P>
   In ``Forces,'' as in screwball comedy, bickering opposites are
launched like pinballs on a journey of adorable misadventures. They
pull through tribulations as an unwitting team, and soon the
friction between them blunts their spiky differences.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next is obvious, and never more so than in this
movie. Just when they're tearing into each other and things are
getting lively, Affleck and Bullock melt into a gooey snooky
session, and heavy nostril-breathing ensues. Affleck's poor fiancee
(Maura Tierney) is shown moping at home getting drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Lawrence's anemic script owes plenty to those querulous
romantic larks of yore _ ``It Happened One Night'' and ``The Lady
Eve'' are classic blueprints. But that implies that the movie
sweeps us into its vortex of comic cutes, blowing us around in its
giddy thrall. Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   When Affleck's staid book-blurb writer and Bullock's zany
freespirit find themselves stranded at the airport after the goose
goof, their wild odyssey commences. The road movie template is
abused so they can find themselves in planes, trains and
automobiles, not to mention a kitschy carnival ride, a tour bus
filled with lusty geriatrics, the plastic wonderworld of Kmart, a
swimming pool (with their clothes on), and a gay bar, because we
all know how funny gay people are.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock _ playing perhaps the most unconvincing wacky girl ever
put to film, despite the wicked tattoo on her belly and the way she
sticks her tongue out all crazy _ is the unbound id to Affleck's
superego. His decorous veneer starts to crack when she cajoles him
to do Tarzan yells from the top of a train. Depending on your mood,
it's a fun little moment, or the end of courtship as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   A theory: Sandra Bullock and Ben Affleck are not actors. They
are mugs whose portrayals amount to smartly delivered lines,
strategic smirks, arch eye-play and fashionable haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   Little is going on here behind the porcelain masks; the whir of
thought, of actually etching and nailing a role, is supplanted by
the thud of tics being trotted out. They are thespian hydroplanes,
grazing emotional surfaces, and flashing those magnificent teeth
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing natural about it. It's just forced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Sandra Bullock, Ben Affleck
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bronwen Hughes
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter: Marc Lawrence
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: PG-13 for lanuage, sexuality
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
