<SLUG> BC-SXSW-WRAP19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everyone else at film fest is relaxed, but I'm exhausted
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ About two weeks ago, I kissed my life on the
cheek, said bon voyage and sent it on a jet plane that would circle
the balmy skies in a holding pattern until Saturday, the final day
of the South by Southwest Film Festival. It lands tomorrow. We will
party.
</P>
<P>
   If you swallowed that metaphor, you probably tasted self-pity
with a dash of whining. There are 164 films at the festival and
dozens of celebrities in attendance. So I have been very busy and I
am tired and I would like your sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, SXSW Film Festival executive producer Nancy Schafer
is smiling. There she is amid the logistic hubbub, laughing into
her walkie-talkie and saying hi to folks in a tone that bespeaks
serenity. All she's missing is a party hat. I hate her.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer's job is roughly 398 times harder than mine at this time
of year. So what gives? Were her brain cells frizzled from watching
hyped festival feature ``Desert Blue'' more than once? (Note to
Christina Ricci: You make a lot of indie films. Quality control,
Christina, quality control.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good,'' says Schafer. ``Things are pretty
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right on that count. A slow-motion calm permeates this
year's bash. Registrants don't look so lost and harried, and there
seems to be fewer of them eddying through the Austin Convention
Center. That's an illusion, since 400 more registrants are here
than last year, knocking the total to 2,200 _ 200 more than Schafer
forecasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so relaxed because they know the drill,'' she
explains. ``They're teaching new registrants, and that gives the
vibe of it being easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Panel attendance might be thinner, she says, because daily
screenings are siphoning off big crowds. This year boasts ``tons
more'' movie sellouts, including the 10 a.m. weekend shows, a
first. All shows at the Paramount Theatre are getting crowds of
1,000-plus. Even shorts programs are selling out. ``We've never had
that,'' says Schafer.
</P>
<P>
   And the capacity crowds are liking what they see. ``The buzz on
the films is amazing. I'm hearing across the board that the movies
are good,'' Schafer says.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzed-about features include ``Spent,'' ``Dill Scallion'' and
``Standing on Fishes.'' In documentaries, ``Wadd: The Life and
Times of John C. Holmes,'' ``Home Page'' and ``The Accident'' are
word-of-mouth hits.
</P>
<P>
   Just when I was planning to write how fall's Austin Film
Festival surpasses SXSW in glamour and celebrity voltage, along
comes the splashy ``EDtv'' premiere Wednesday at the Paramount.
Matthew McConaughey, Woody Harrelson, Ron Howard, Elizabeth Hurley
and others took the city by storm and reduced me to Liz Smith for a
day.
</P>
<P>
   (It was worth it. Hurley and I have big plans. She doesn't know
it yet, but she'll be delighted.)
</P>
<P>
   A bed-ridden Quentin Tarantino was a no-show to the groans of
little boys all over. He was supposed to introduce movies at the
Jack Hill retrospective, with Hill and actor Sid Haig, who starred
in such Hill exploitation flicks as ``The Big Doll House.'' Jack's
films might be over-the-Hill, considering the watery turnout for
Sunday's screening of ``The Big Doll House.'' Monday's outdoor Hill
screening at GSD&AMP;M, however, hauled 'em in.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer's already winding up for SXSW 2000, which she expects to
be bigger than ever. I'm winding down, waiting for a plane.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
