<SLUG> BC-NHAMP-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOME TAX PLAN STILL ALIVE IN N.H. SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMINEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N. H. _ No accord was reached Thursday as New
Hampshire's legislature continued to look for a way to avert an
impending school funding crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee Thursday rejected every option
bought before it save the one Gov. Jeanne Shaheen has threatened to
veto _ a plan that includes the state's first income tax.
</P>
<P>
   That controversial bill, which passed the more conservative
House by a narrow margin earlier this month, calls for a 4 percent
personal income tax combined with a $6 per $1,000 valuation
statewide property tax. The committee will take it up when it
reconvenes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member committee rejected two other plans: a call for
a 4 percent sales tax or a plan backed by Shaheen. Shaheen's
proposal includes a statewide property tax, an increase in the
state's Business Profits Tax by one point to 8 percent, an
estimated $200 million from opening the state up to video slot
machines at eight of the state's race tracks and grand hotels and
an increase in liquor and cigarette taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators found something to hate in Shaheen's grab bag of
taxes. ``Video slot machines have earned the reputation of being
the crack cocaine of gambling for good reason,'' said Sen. Clifton
Below, one of the sponsors of the income tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   The finance committee is expected to pass some form of an income
tax bill along to the full Senate for consideration on Tuesday. If
the Senate approves a bill different from the House's, which most
observers expect, it would then go to a House-Senate conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The full senate could also decide to test Shaheen's resolve by
passing the original income tax bill which would send it to her
desk. ``They think we will be in a crisis mode when the bill gets
to the governor and she won't veto it but she will,'' Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   All sides agree that only the delusional could hope for an
override of the popular governor's veto in the house. ``Not even if
the schools closed,'' said Republican Rep. Elizabeth Hager, a prime
sponsor of the income tax bill. ``I hope that something can be
worked out before it gets to that,'' Hager said.
</P>
</TEXT>
