<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE-BUYER SALE OF FLEET-BANKBOS BRANCHES OPPOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Eight Massachusetts congressmen said Thursday they
would ``oppose vigorously'' any deal in which bank branches sold
off as part of the Fleet-BankBoston merger go to one large buyer,
rather than to a variety of buyers that includes small and
community-oriented banks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, in a letter to federal banking regulators and to
Fleet and BankBoston, also urged that the merged bank show a
greater commitment to affordable housing and to local economic
development than they make today.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. earlier this
week announced a $16 billion merger, which will produce the
nation's eighth-largest bank and a regional powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two banks currently provide the bulk of competition
in many communities, they are expected to sell off about 270
branches across New England. Analysts say it could be one of the
largest bank divestitures in US history.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts lawmakers, in their letter to the banks and to
five regulatory agencies, asked for ``the strictest scrutiny'' of
the merger for its effects on competition.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said that the most robust competition to the
merged Fleet Boston Corp. would arise if a single, large bank
bought the branches sold by Fleet and BankBoston. But the
Massachusetts lawmakers specifically rejected that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, the Massachusetts Democrat who led
the letter-writing effort, said that big borrowers are already
well-served by large banks, but that many smaller borrowers want to
work with the small banks that might be hurt financially when
surrounded by ever-larger rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the local officials we deal with, and the smaller
business people, say they'd like some smaller banks to deal with,''
Frank said. ``The sense we have is that (the merger) will make it
harder for some of our smaller banks to stay alive. We're not in
the business of protecting smaller banks, but of protecting people
who feel comfortable borrowing from smaller banks.''
</P>
<P>
   The best outcome, he said, would be ``a mix of big and little
banks. And since we're now going to have one very big bank, we
don't want a second pretty big bank. What we want is a lot of
strong little banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said that while the lawmakers ``do not have a button we
can push'' to reverse regulatory decisions, they can influence the
outcome because they have a role in approving a range of requests
that the Justice Department, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
and other regulators make of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   James Mahoney, a Fleet spokesman, said that the banks' plan for
divesting branches must be approved by federal regulators.
``There's a big federal role,'' he said. But he would not discuss
which banks are potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've identified the scope of the divestiture, and with regard
to the actual sale, we would decline to comment pending further
discussions with regulators,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the lawmakers also said that companies often
talk up the ``synergy'' that a merger produces -- the notion that
two firms together form something greater than the sum of their
parts. They asked the banks to commit to producing the same synergy
in adhering to the Community Reinvestment Act, a federal law that
requires banks to make loans and provide other services to spur
local economic development.
</P>
<P>
   The merger should improve ``the banks' performance in assisting
with the vital issues of affordable housing and community economic
development,'' the lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   They also asked the banks to keep layoffs to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said that many of the 5,000 projected job cuts at Fleet
and BankBoston will be accomplished through attrition and by not
filling positions that are currently vacant. He said the banks
would continue community reinvestment at their current levels, even
though their combined market share will be smaller after selling
the 270 branches.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Frank, the the letter was signed by
Representatives William Delahunt, Jim McGovern, Martin Meehan,
Michael Capuano, John Olver, John Tierney, and Edward Markey. All
are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Capuano are members of the House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The letter went to Fleet chief executive Terrance Murray,
BankBoston chief executive Charles Gifford, and to the top
officials at the Justice Department, the Treasury Department, the
Federal Reserve, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and the
Comptroller of the Currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
