A5716 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIATION-SUIT-BOS &LR;      03-18 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIATION-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SEEKS SUIT IN '61 RADIATION TREATMENT DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- By all accounts, George Heinrich died a painful death.
Afflicted with a fast-growing brain tumor, Heinrich underwent an
experimental treatment at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
in 1961 that scorched healthy brain tissue even as it destroyed the
tumor, hastening his death rather than saving him.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight years later a federal judge heard Thursday why
Heinrich's family should be allowed to sue MIT, Massachusetts
General Hospital and others involved in Heinrich's treatment
despite the passage of so much time. The family charged that
Heinrich's doctors used him and up to 236 others as human guinea
pigs in dangerous experiments without telling them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were doing was research, not medicine,'' said
Anthony Roisman, who represents Heinrich's widow as well as the
families of three other patients who received the controversial
treatment, called boron neutron capture therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Massachusetts General Hospital and Dr. William
Sweet, the retired chief of neurosurgery who treated Heinrich,
called on US District Court Judge William G. Young to dismiss the
whole case, arguing that it was decades too late. They noted that
Massachusetts law in 1961 required malpractice claims to be filed
within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they defended the treatment of Heinrich and the others
as a good faith effort to save patients who had a disease that
probably would have killed them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that something is experimental or developmental
doesn't mean it's not treatment,'' explained Joseph Doherty, who
represented Sweet and Massachusetts General Hospital. ``Dr. Sweet
was one of the top neurosurgeons in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't satisfy family members who believe doctors they
trusted exposed their loved ones to painful treatments that had no
prospect of making them better. They said they didn't suspect
deception until a presidential commission questioned the ethics of
the research in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully Boston will see what has been hidden all these
years,'' said Walter Van Dyke, who was two when his father died in
1957 after receiving boron neutron capture therapy at Brookhaven
National Laboratory on Long Island, N.Y., where Sweet also
administered the tumor treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The complicated lawsuit, which also names Brookhaven and several
other parties, re-opens a sad chapter in the history of nuclear
medicine when Sweet and Brookhaven's Lee Edward Farr led a team
that tried, without success, to find a way to halt the spread of an
aggressive cancer called glioblastoma multiforme.
</P>
<P>
   From 1951 to 1961, the researchers injected desperately ill
patients with varying concentrations of boron, a chemical that
concentrates in brain tumors. Then, they exposed the chemicals to a
beam of neutrons from the nuclear reactor at MIT or Brookhaven,
causing a mini-nuclear reaction that they hoped would destroy the
tumors.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers could not confine the damage to the tumors,
resulting in extensive damage to healthy tissue and blood vessels
that may have killed at least 10 patients, including Heinrich,
according to the lawsuit. The protocol finally ended in 1961 after
one patient died of brain swelling two weeks after her treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Roisman said Sweet and his associates may have treated 66
patients with boron neutron capture therapy without informing them
that the procedure was highly experimental. In addition, he said
one memo shows the researchers had funding to inject 160 people
with boron, and records show they injected uranium into another 11
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet ``lied to us. He said he could save George's life if we
sent him to the reactor,'' said Evelynn Heinrich. Instead, George
Heinrich, a 35-year-old father of a young daughter, died a
lingering death four months later.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet, now in his late 80s, agreed in a 1995 interview that the
boron neutron capture therapy had failed, but he did not apologize
for his research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes some courage to embark on a highly experimental
procedure . . . instead of settling for a known unhappy outcome,''
Sweet said. He also noted that neurosurgeons have revived boron
neutron capture therapy in the last few years, building on the
results of his earlier work.
</P>
<P>
   And lawyers for all the defendants said it was too late to
second-guess the work of Sweet and Farr, who died last year. Based
on the published studies on boron neutron capture therapy and the
side effects patients suffered, they argued that the families
should have known enough to file a lawsuit at the time of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But Young said the issues were too complex and important to
dismiss from the bench. Instead, he dismissed only one minor claim
in the lawsuit, and gave lawyers 30 days to provide more
information about possible civil rights violations in the
treatments as well as the research at Brookhaven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
