<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANOTHER NFL SHAKEDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Please, call a doc, I'm bent over in a fetal
position, nearly unconscious from the uncontrollable seizures of
laughter I've been having from the hilarity emanating from the NFL
comedy show staged earlier this week in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   As you might have heard, the NFL, God bless its kindly souls,
finally decided to grant Los Angeles an expansion franchise, but
attached a few conditions to the offering that will be good for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the NFL was quite vague about the specificity of
these conditions, but you need not be an attorney for Bill Clinton,
or even a Paul Tagliabue, to figure out that L.A. is not so subtly
being shaken down for the kind of money _ $600 million in franchise
fees _ that recently was wrangled out of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the NFL is asking L.A. to do what it has a sacred
history of doing worst getting a bunch of disparate groups to pool
their financial resources and agree to work together for the common
good of the community.
</P>
<P>
   There's a better chance of Leno and Letterman one day co-hosting
a late-night television talk show, even a honest decision being
rendered in a Don King-promoted heavyweight title fight before that
would happen.
</P>
<P>
   There are even reports that L.A.'s beloved mayor, Richard
Riordan, is trying to get Michael Ovitz to defect from Carson and
join the Ed Roski-Eli Broad New Coliseum group.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, the chances of Michael Ovitz, whose ego extends even
beyond his massive bank account, agreeing to becoming a secondary
player in any L.A. pro football enterprise is roughly tantamount,
say, to his once agreeing to turn down the $100 million he received
from Disney after being fired by Michael Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz is not a guy with a history of sharing adulation with
other people _ ask Michael Eisner _ and you can be sure he will do
everything within his power to keep his Carson dream alive.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is coyly dangling the threat of Houston over L.A., which
has me shaking in my Guccis.
</P>
<P>
   It won't surprise me if the NFL reluctantly winds up awarding
that sterling Texas city with an expansion franchise if L.A. is
unable to meet its financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL knows that Houston is quite willing to fork over the
same inflated amount that Cleveland did, and that its owners again
would then be able to cut up around $20 million each among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   I just can't envision all the disparate parties in this area
suddenly forming a peaceful alliance, nor can I see the Coliseum,
with its sordid political history of losing the Rams, Raiders and
UCLA, suddenly becoming a bastion of tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   I just can't envision L.A. coming up with the public funding
that the NFL says will be needed for a new franchise, and I'm not
sure it should.
</P>
<P>
   I just can't envision my ceaseless laughter disappearing until
the NFL pulls back its veiled threats against L.A. and realizes we
here aren't like the desperate burghers of Cleveland. We'll take an
NFL team, fine, but none of the money for it will be subsidized by
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, we can survive nicely without professional football,
as we have for the past four years. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'd rather see the Raiders yes, the Raiders! return than an
expansion franchise. L.A. may have the most intolerant athletic
fans in America. How do you think they'll react to watching an
inferior brand of football for several years, an inevitability for
expansion franchises with the notable exception of Jacksonville.
...
</P>
<P>
   I get the distinct impression from reading Al Davis' quotes out
of Phoenix that he is maniacally desperate to get his Raiders out
of Oakland and return to L.A. What a shock!. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I don't think the new version of instant replay goes far enough.
I think all suspect calls should be scrutinized, even if there are
more than two before the two-minute warning of each half. And
allowing the referee on the field to determine the outcome of
suspect calls is like allowing a defense attorney to serve as a
jury foreman in a trial for one of his clients. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas sources tell me the casinos have cut off Dennis
Rodman's credit because his gambling markers now exceed seven
figures. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles sources tell me that Rodman's wagering excesses
don't cause him nearly as much private grief as does the stormy
relationship he has with his pint-sized wife, Carmen Electra. They
tell me he's hopelessly smitten by her. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Laker sources tell me that, despite Rodman's absence, his
teammates aren't too upset with him, and are willing to welcome him
back without rancor. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I've been asking Kevin Malone the moment he got rid of Charles
Johnson and brought in Todd Hundley who would be doing the catching
for the Dodgers this season. I still want to know. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I've been told by various people that the relationship Don King
has with Bob Lee, the IBF president who assigned the incompetent
Jean Williams to work the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight, is
far cozier than the one he long has had with the WBC president,
Jose Sulaiman. . . .
</P>
<P>
   People don't change. Believe me, they don't. Latest example:
Gary Sheffield. . . .
</P>
<P>
   This NCAA Tournament to me is a preordained skit in which we all
know that Duke will emerge victorious at the end. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I've come to the conclusion that New York has to be the most
shamelessly provincial city in America after three days of reading
insufferable drivel in the tabloids about how the Holyfield-Lewis
was being held at the boxing mecca, Madison Square Garden. Please,
the Garden hadn't had a truly major fight in 27 years, while Las
Vegas has had hundreds of them during that span. . . .
</P>
<P>
   A guy with intimate knowledge of the New York Mets told me that
it's all set up for the brilliant Seattle shortstop, Alex
Rodriguez, to join the Mets for the 2001 season. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's now apparent that the most tragic development of the season
for the Clippers came the moment the NBA lockout was resolved. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the Clippers ruined what could have been the most
inglorious season in the history of professional athletics last
week with their regrettable win against the Sacramento Kings. So
they got to do a cameo on the Leno Show the next evening? Big deal.
They would have established their own unique sporting legacy had
they only gone winless the entire season, a record Donald T. (As In
Terrific) Sterling's ghastly franchise richly deserves. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
