<SLUG> BC-NHAMP-SHAHEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICALLY IN A JAM, SHAHEEN STILL PLEASES VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ It seems like just about everyone is mad at
Jeanne Shaheen, the popular Democratic governor with the shy smile,
soft voice and granite gaze.
</P>
<P>
   As Shaheen and the state legislature struggle to find a new way
to pay for public schools that passes constitutional muster, her
leadership and her motives are being questioned by Democrats and
Republicans alike, including friends and financial supporters who
helped her win two statewide elections in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's certainly on the dunking stool these days,'' said
Representative Peter Burling, the House Minority Leader from
Cornish who supports a statewide income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen faces facing a court-imposed April 1 deadline to find an
equitable way to fund schools, which will mean an annual bill near
$1 billion, in a state notorious for its hatred of taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There is danger for Shaheen in every direction. When she offered
a plan last year, Republicans criticized her and the court shot it
down. When she hung back this year, Republicans and Democrats
condemned her lack of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, when she offered up a new plan, the plan was
quickly picked apart by critics of every political persuasion. She
suggested a new tax on businesses, and business doesn't like it.
She called for expanding video gambling, and good government types
are appalled. She proposed a statewide property tax, and proponents
of an income tax are upset.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more of her friends and supporters are becoming
disillusioned, complaining that Shaheen refuses to spend any
political capital to forge a solution, that she is only considering
her personal political possibilities _ a run for the US Senate,
perhaps, or even the vice presidency _ rather than what's best for
the children of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaheen, who remains wildly popular outside the state's
tight political circles, gives a tight smile and shrugs off the
criticism, resolute in the course she is charting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philosophically, I don't think an income tax would be good for
New Hampshire,'' Shaheen said Thursday during an interview in her
State House office. ``It's part of the state's identity that we
haven't had a sales or income tax and it's been good for the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   During each of her gubernatorial campaigns, Shaheen took the
famous New Hampshire pledge, promising voters she would not support
any broad-based taxes, including a statewide property tax, a sales
tax and an income tax. So far, though, she has jettisoned her
opposition to a property tax and said that she could support a
sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But the 52-year old former school teacher with a masters degree
in political science has adamantly refused to give in to members of
her own party who say that an income tax is the most equitable way
to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't like an income tax because they feel like, `This
is my money, I earned it and why is the government taking it from
me,' '' said Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   That explanation does nothing to appease Howard M. Moffett, a
Concord attorney, who has given Shaheen money and even co-sponsored
a fund-raiser for her last year. He was outraged after Shaheen said
she would support an amendment to the New Hampshire constitution
that would have effectively reversed the court order, and refused
to attend a fundraiser for her, even though Moffett's name was
printed on the invitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard for me to explain how deeply disappointed I
have been in what I believe is her lack of leadership on this
school funding issue,'' said Moffett. ``There are a lot of people
who feel the way I do,'' he said. ``If she tried to talk to all of
us she wouldn't get anything else done.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the criticism of Shaheen reflects today's cynicism
toward politicians and a belief that campaign promises are made to
be broken. Many Democrats and many Republicans thought Shaheen
intended to walk away from the pledge when she took it in 1996 and
even when she repeated it in 1998. Democrats who support the income
tax thought she secretly agreed with them.
</P>
<P>
   If the criticism hurts, Shaheen doesn't show it. She just smiles
and grimaces and rolls her eyes at some of the zingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were some people who thought when I took the
pledge I did it for political expedience, not because I felt that
way,'' she explained. ``Once I got a chance, boy, I was going to
pass that income tax, just let me get that chance. And they were
wrong, that hasn't been my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, she insisted, is her goal to find another job in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being governor of New Hampshire, I'm having a great
time,'' said Shaheen, the mother of three daughters who lives in
Madbury. ``I'm not interested in thinking about anything else right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The voters are happy having her where she is as well. A poll by
the Concord Monitor this week put her approval rating at 66
percent. But the deadline, and with it the promise of more chaos on
an issue that voters value highly, is quickly approaching. Already,
some teachers are beginning to receive pink lay-off slips for the
following school year because the funding has not been agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   In political circles, along with the strains of anger and
frustration toward the governor, there is also sympathy for the
woman who helped mastermind Jimmy Carter and Gary Hart's upset
victories in the state's presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would want to go through the process of having some of
your best friends yell at you?'' asked Burling, the House
Democratic Leader. ``It's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen's husband, William H. Shaheen, admits that the pressure
and the unkind letters and phone calls from friends does take a
toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, if her policy is right, then I think
those friends will come back,'' he said. ``At the end of the day,
if she's wrong, then they won't come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
