<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Testimony heard in defense of Texas law charging property owners
liability for crimes
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Her voice was restrained, but Barbara Ayres, who
lost two daughters in Austin's infamous yogurt shop murders in
1991, urged a Senate committee Thursday not to weaken Texas law
that she said helped assure safer work for kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wanted this to happen in this business,'' Ayres told
the subcommittee on technology and business growth. ``No one
does.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the yogurt shop where her daughters were killed,
with two other girls in a closing-time robbery, trained its
employees only in cleaning the equipment and not safety.
</P>
<P>
   The four teen-agers were shot in the head and burned when the
shop was set afire.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers testified against a tort-reform bill by state Sen. David
Sibley (R-Waco) that would allow juries to calculate in a civil
lawsuit against a business owner how much fault should be
attributed to a criminal. Such lawsuits allege that property owners
failed to protect employees or customers when a danger was
foreseeable.
</P>
<P>
   In the yogurt shop murders, the company that owned the I Can't
Believe It's Yogurt shop and the shopping center owner settled with
Ayres and families of the other girls for $12 million in 1994. The
families alleged lax security when crime had increased in the North
Austin neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the settlement proceeds established a foundation in the
girls' memory _ We Will Not Forget SAJE _ that helps educate
children about safety at work. SAJE refers the victims, Sarah
Harbison, 15; Amy Ayers, 13; Jennifer Harbison, 17; and Eliza
Thomas, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres is the mother of the Harbison girls.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's bill, backed by the Texas Association of Business &AMP;
Chambers of Commerce, also would allow juries to calculate the
amount of fault for workplace injuries attributed to an employer in
lawsuits brought against product manufacturers or contractors.
Under current law, the employer is immune from such suits because
workplace injuries are covered by the state's worker compensation
program.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Sibley's law told the committee that juries
currently do not figure in any fault that might be the employer's.
The third party then pays the total of the jury's award, even
though the employer might have been responsible too, testified
Austin lawyer Alan Waldrop, who is representing the chambers of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But Hartley Hampton, president of the Texas Trial Lawyers
Association, said the bill could reduce an award to an injured
worker who might not recover as much from workers compensation
insurance _ even if the employer were grossly negligent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a fair share system,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
