<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-TECHNO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not much networking at Women in Technology International
conference
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Women in Technology International regional
conference in Dallas is another reminder of just how different
high-tech Austin, with its free-wheeling start-ups, and high-tech
Dallas, home to large corporations, really are.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's regional meeting, held in Austin, drew a large
number of women who either entrepreneurs or working at start-up
companies. The hot topics were breaking out on your own and raising
venture capital. The talk in the hallways and over glasses of
Chardonnay at receptions was of stock options and job hopping.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, the scene at the Fairmont Hotel is dominated by
corporate workers wearing matching shirts with their companies'
logos. How to work your way up the management chain is the burning
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Networking _ an art form in Austin _ is in low gear. Considering
that most of the participants are from Texas Instruments Inc. or
Raytheon Systems Co., the opportunities for circulating resumes are
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Jones, a co-founder of Trilogy Software and founder of
pcOrder.com, showed her Austin roots in her breakfast keynote
address by encouraging women to run with their ideas and start
their own companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no better time to be an entrepreneur because the
Internet is providing huge opportunities to change how entire
industries work,'' said Jones, who last month led pcOrder through
its first sale of stock to the public that raised $46.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Jones inspired anyone to put in her two weeks notice
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia Boone, a TI product specialist who transferred from
Dallas to Austin two years ago, doubts it.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, Boone says, high-tech employees tend to focus on
moving up within large corporations, whereas in Austin ``everyone,
both the men and the women, want to be the next Michael Dell.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is common ground. The power of mentoring is a
conference theme that resonates in both cities because senior-level
women remain the exception at large corporations and small
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Shaunna Sowell, one of Texas Instruments' top ranking female
executives, told the audience that if a brutally honest mentor
hadn't set her straight more than a decade ago, she would never
have gotten to where she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started out by talking about how much potential I had, and
of course I was too naive to see where it was going,'' Sowell, vice
president and manager of TI's worldwide facilities, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he told me I expressed my opinion so often and so vocally
that the minute I opened my mouth people stopped listening.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a mortifying moment, but it caused her to change her
approach.
</P>
<P>
   She encouraged women to start formal mentoring programs at their
companies. Two years ago, TI began matching women and minorities
with mid-level managers, most of whom are white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides get a perspective they aren't usually exposed to,
and they talk about things they have never thought about,'' Sowell
said. This year's conference, which ends today, attracted 1,000
women, about the same number as last year's.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to rotate the Texas conference between Austin and
Dallas, said WITI's executive director Carolyn Leighton-Tal. But
whether the group will actually make it back to Central Texas is
still in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can find enough hotel space in Austin,'' she said, ``we
will be there absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Lori Hawkins at lhawkins(at)statesman.com or
445-3639.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
