<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech's engineering school rises in U.S. News estimation
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If only it were basketball. Georgia Tech made the
polls in a big way this week when U.S. News &AMP; World Report ranked
its engineering school third best in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   That is up from last year's fourth-place finish in the
magazine's annual rankings of graduate and professional schools.
The magazine, which hits the newsstands Monday, also ranked Tech's
computer science program 13th and its college of management 33rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased that the impressive work of our faculty is so
highly regarded at the national level,'' said Tech President Wayne
Clough. ``Graduate education is extremely important as we continue
the transition to a high-tech, information-based economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Tech, several other Georgia colleges made the list:
</P>
<P>
   _ Emory University's school of medicine moved from 21st to 19th
among research-oriented medical schools; the Goizueta Business
School's MBA program ranking remained unchanged at 21st; the School
of Law was ranked 28th this year, after being 25th last year, but
its trial advocacy program was ranked third.
</P>
<P>
   _ The University of Georgia's school of education ranked 18th,
with four of its programs ranking in the top 10, while its law
school ranked 36th, down from 34th. UGA's speech pathology program
ranked 41st.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia State University's part-time MBA program dropped from
fourth to sixth this year; its law school moved from the second
tier to the third tier. Mercer University's law school also dropped
from second tier to third tier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
