<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVORCE DIPLOMACY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: (AT) in the e-mail address in the last graf should be
replaced with the typographical symbol.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm getting a divorce. I hope it will be amicable, but you
never know. In any case, it will take a lot of time to arrange for
our children, establish separate households, confer with lawyers
and attend to all the details. What should I tell my bosses and
colleagues? And how, more generally, do I keep a personal disaster
from becoming a professional one as well? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: The consensus of several experts: Keep it to yourself, at
least initially.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, you want to avoid having your private life become
grist for the office gossip mill, said Virginia Byrd, a career
counselor based in the San Diego area. ``There's no need for you to
lay that all out and have people have opinions about it,'' Ms. Byrd
said. ``It just makes it more difficult for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Telling all runs another risk: Supervisors may assume that your
job performance is suffering. ``The boss then begins to watch you
with suspicion, and people sometimes read mistakes into things that
would not otherwise be viewed as mistakes,'' warned Martha A.
Fineman, a law professor at Columbia University who has been a
consultant in several high-profile divorce cases, including that of
Gary C. Wendt, the former chief executive of GE Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Women face this perception problem more often than men, Ms.
Fineman said, ``because women are always fighting against the more
generalized notion that they are more emotional or more crushed by
family concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your sex, there is sometimes no way to keep your
personal life separate from your work life. Many companies try to
maintain such walls, however, so as soon as the divorce starts
affecting your behavior, you need to tell the boss that something
is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case I was acting strange or was not in the office, I
wouldn't want the boss to assume that I was looking for another job
or just going crazy,'' said Leonard Florescue, a partner at Tenzer
Greenblatt, a law firm in Manhattan. The need for disclosure may
depend largely ``on how much you can compartmentalize your life, a
la President Clinton,'' Florescue said. If you're snapping at your
staff or otherwise acting strangely, he added, ``you probably owe
it to people to tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   But maintain discretion, even at this stage. ``Don't tell
everything,'' Ms. Byrd advised, ``but say that you're working
through a personal problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Find people outside the office to help you cope with the
inevitable distress. ``You are going to have to share your
emotional trauma with somebody,'' Ms. Fineman said. ``But talk
about it with friends and professional counselors, and really try
as much as possible to separate it from the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   As for telling your colleagues, Ms. Byrd said there was nothing
wrong with waiting until you've worked through some of the rough
spots. After all, you have enough to worry about without co-workers
whispering around the water cooler or asking, ``Are you sure you're
all right?'' 30 times a day. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by E-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
