<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-G-WAGEN-ART     03-18 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-G-WAGEN-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 STEALTH STATUS FOR THE FEW, THE PROUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
(af) 
 By PETER PASSELL  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do Arnold Schwarzenegger, Bill Cosby, Liam Neeson, Christie
Brinkley, Boris Becker and Tommy Hilfiger have in common?
Obviously, they all have incomes that make it unnecessary to do
much heavy lifting. But they also belong to an exclusive, well,
cult: the cult of the Gelaendewagen.
</P>
<P>
   Allow me to explain. Just over 20 years ago, Steyr-Daimler-Puch,
an Austrian contractor for Daimler-Benz, developed a heavy,
Jeep-like military vehicle for the shah of Iran. After he was
overthrown, Mercedes sold this Gelaendewagen _ ``cross country
vehicle'' in German _ to various European armies and then, spruced
up, to a few civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Because its military specifications made it so expensive,
Mercedes opted not to bring it to North America. But in 1983, David
Holland, the founder of Europa International, a dealer of vintage
Mercedes cars in Santa Fe, N.M., got the idea of importing G-Wagens
for their curiosity value.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to '98, Europa sold a few dozen lushly-equipped three-
and five-door versions (labeled the G320 for their 3.2-liter six
cylinder engines). Now Europa is importing a swankier version from
the Austrian factory, a model that preserves the G-Wagen's squarely
retro look but uses a new Mercedes engine that meets environmental
requirements in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   The price: $135,000 for the five-door wagon and convertible,
$5,000 less for the three-door model. Luxury taxes run another
$6,000.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you _ or, more to the point, what will a handful of
screen and boardroom stars _ get for the money? The G500 is a very
tall midsize sport utility with full-time four-wheel-drive and all
the luxury features you'd expect: stiff but comfortable heated
leather seats, walnut trim, five-speed electronic automatic
transmission, halogen headlamps, power sunroof, theft-protection
system.
</P>
<P>
   Plus a few you wouldn't: a gizmo that warns of obstacles when
you're backing up; a supercool lighted Mercedes logo inside the
front-door frame. Options include running boards, grille guard,
voice-activated phone and a powerful winch recessed in the bumper.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-liter, 300-horsepower aluminum V8 is a potent variation on
the engines that Mercedes stuffs into several E- and M-Class
models. The anti-skid vented disc brakes behind the 18-inch alloy
wheels stop the G-Wagen forcefully despite its 5,260-pound curb
weight.
</P>
<P>
   In ordinary driving, the G-Wagen is a mix of naughty and nice.
The view from captain's chairs high above the road couldn't be
better. And thanks to the monster V8, acceleration is literally a
kick. But the ride is not as comfortable as that of most high-end
sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The rigid rear axle makes the G-Wagen less than sure-footed on
choppy pavement, and the weight of all that military steel makes it
an unwilling partner on sharp turns.
</P>
<P>
   The soul of the G500 is more apparent in difficult off-roading,
where Pathfinders and Troopers fear to tread. Lockable center, rear
and front differentials allow the G-Wagen to gain traction through
any combination of wheels. The center of gravity is fairly low
despite the high clearance, giving the G-Wagen superior stability
on inclines as steep as 45 degrees. And even an amateur off-roader
like me felt safe and secure on a jaunt along a dry creek bed full
of boulders.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest selling point, though, is bound to be the G500's
exclusivity. Roughly 100 of the 2,000 or so made this year will end
up in the United States, making them much rarer than another
celebrity vehicle with a military pedigree: the far flashier
Hummer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Inconspicuous consumption for the rich and
famous. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
