<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-DAIMLER-CH     03-18 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-DAIMLER-CHRYSLER-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE M-CLASS ADDS V8 MUSCLE TO ITS MARVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
(af) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Mercedes-Benz wowed the world with its M-Class,
an ``all activity vehicle'' that set performance and versatility
standards in the sport utility market, yet was priced to compete
with models derived from aging truck designs.
</P>
<P>
   So what could be better than the 3.2-liter, 6-cylinder,
215-horsepower all-wheel drive ML320? Well, DaimlerChrysler is back
with the 4.3-liter, 8-cylinder, 268-horsepower ML430, a slightly
more muscular-looking variation on the same bankable theme.
</P>
<P>
   Improved on-road performance and tougher-guy styling comes at a
price, though: $43,750 to be specific, or about $5,000 more than a
comparably equipped ML320.
</P>
<P>
   Why is the ML430 so easy to like? Count the ways. Bold curves
and lots of glass make it better looking than boxy,
earlier-generation sport utilities (though nearly everyone says it
looks like a minivan from the rear). Integrated body-color trim and
17-inch wheels give it a more macho look than the ML320.
</P>
<P>
   Every version of the M-Class has a spacious _ airy, even _
interior, offering as much shoulder and leg room as a Mitsubishi
Montero in a package six inches shorter. The seats are what you'd
expect from Mercedes: firm, but comfy in an ergonomically correct
way. And while the ML430 looks tall, the step-in height is a modest
18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Early copies of the M-Class, built at a new Mercedes factory in
Alabama, generated complaints about fit and finish. But the car I
tested was rattle-free. The plastic trim meshed beautifully with
the standard leather seating; the cup holders opened as if their
surfaces were coated with Teflon.
</P>
<P>
   The ML430 maintains Mercedes' tradition of one-step-ahead
engineering. Unlike most sport utilities, the M-Class features an
independent rear suspension for superior ride and handling, as well
as a drivetrain that can deliver power to all four wheels, all of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-lock brakes are standard, and Mercedes complements the
brake sensors that detect wheel slippage with sensors that measure
lateral forces. When the computer's ``electronic stability
program'' determines that the tires are about to give way on the
front or rear _ in a condition of ``understeer'' or ``oversteer'' _
it applies the brakes to a single wheel to maintain control.
</P>
<P>
   All this worked perfectly fine in wet but temperate conditions
in Southern California, but the system is apparently not
infallible. A writer for USA Today reported that the computerized
sensors ran amok on icy roads in a Midwest blizzard, intermittently
applying the brakes and cutting the power just when it was needed
most.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes engineers have worked almost as hard to placate
environmentalists as it has to satisfy safety mavens. The new V8 in
the ML430 has dual sparkplugs that make for cleaner burning, along
with a three-valve-per-cylinder design that speeds the warming of
the catalytic converter. This combination sharply reduces emissions
in the critical minutes after the engine starts, qualifying the
ML430 as a low-emission vehicle nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Tree-huggers (including me) will also appreciate the fact that
the new V8 uses electronics to minimize the need for oil changes. A
sensor measures oil quality, warning drivers when the lubricant is
dirty, rather than simply reminding them to service the engine
after a fixed number of miles or revolutions. The result: a lower
volume of contaminants to threaten groundwater and fewer trips to
the dealer's service department.
</P>
<P>
   None of this technical razzle-dazzle is on display in ordinary
driving. What is apparent is that the ML430 is an exceptionally
potent people mover. The V8 pushes this 4,550-pound vehicle from 0
to 60 miles an hour in 8 seconds flat _ a full second faster than
the V6 in the ML320. And it feels even quicker, perhaps because
maximum torque is achieved at a relatively low engine speed of
3,000 revolutions per minute.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed electronically controlled transmission shifts
virtually seamlessly, and it automatically adjusts shift points to
each driver's habits. The very sophisticated suspension makes for
carlike stability on twisting roads.
</P>
<P>
   I never pushed the ML430 anywhere near its limits, but it should
be able to stay in the game with proven off-roaders. Low range
five-speed gearing, available at the push of a button, permits
steep ascents; clearances are adequate for moderately bad terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints? The stiff suspension generates a fatiguing,
un-car-like jiggle even on smooth pavement. One might be tempted to
chalk this up to the engineering compromises necessary to create a
vehicle that is as competent off the road as on it.
</P>
<P>
   But truth is, the ML430 is a less comfortable ride than the
Toyota Land Cruiser, which is also admired for its versatility.
</P>
<P>
   The more significant question is value. The ML430 combines car
and sport utility features in a well-engineered package. But so,
too, does the ML320, which offers comparable safety and comfort _
and most of the performance _ for a lot less money.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, other manufacturers are beginning to offer
very competitive products in the luxury end of the mid-size SUV
market. The Lexus RX300 won't get you very far on mud or sand, but
is quieter and more comfortable than the M-Class on the highway.
And the BMW X5, due later this year, is bound to be a formidable
rival for the loyalty of the big-bucks crowd.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Muscle, versatility _ and hefty monthly payments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
