<HEADLINE>
DEATHS FROM MAD COW DISEASE INCREASED LAST YEAR, BRITISH REPORT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of people who have died in Britain from a human form
of mad cow disease increased at an ``alarming rate'' at the end of
last year, according to a scientific report being published in
Saturday's issue of The Lancet, a British medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of 1996 through September 1998, the number of
deaths reported each quarter year stayed relatively constant, said
Dr. Simon Cousens, a scientist who is helping track the disease at
the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine. Usually no more
than four people died in any three month period, he said. But in
the last quarter of 1998, nine deaths were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Given the steady death rate in previous years, the probability
of observing nine deaths in three months is low, Cousens said. But
he said it was hard to gauge the public health significance of the
new statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths ``are bad news rather than good news but how bad news
they are is difficult to tell,'' he told the BBC in an interview
Thursday. ``We are going to have to wait another six or nine months
to see'' if the increase continues.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995 when the human form of mad cow disease was first
recognized in humans, 39 Britons have died from the disease. Three
cases were confirmed in 1995, 10 in both 1996 and 1997 and 15 in
1998. There has been one confirmed case this year. But Cousens
added that it is possible that doctors have simply gotten better at
diagnosing the disease which in humans is called new variant
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease or variant CJD. The increase could also
be a statistical fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, scientists from Britain's National CJD
Surveillance Unit projected as few as 75 and as many as 80,000
deaths from nvCJD, depending on the length of the incubation period
and how the infection is passed from animals to humans. Neither has
been determined.
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic began in 1986 when a bizarre brain disease called
spongiform encephalopathy began killing cattle in the U.K. Infected
animals developed spongy areas in their brains, suffered
personality changes and began staggering in circles _ hence the
term mad cow disease. By the beginning of this year, 173,718 cows
had been positively diagnosed with the disease while more than 4
million animals have been destroyed in an effort to stamp out the
infection. Cows appear to have gotten ill from eating the rendered
remains of infected animals.
</P>
<P>
   At first government officials assured the public that people
could not get the brain disease from eating infected cattle. But
when young people began to develop CJD _ a disease almost
exclusively found in people over age 50 _ scientists began to
worry. Two years ago researchers showed that the brains of infected
cows and the brains of young people dying from CJD have identical
characteristics. The human form of mad cow disease was then named
new variant CJD.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last year, Dr. John Collinge, a leading CJD expert at Imperial
College in London, discovered that the tonsils of variant CJD
victims carry an infectious particle, called a prion, that seems to
be responsible for the disease. The infectious prions are found
throughout nervous and lymphatic tissue, including tonsils, and may
incubate for many years before causing overt signs of disease. Thus
medical facilities throughout Britain are now testing tissue
samples saved from thousands of tonsilectomies that took place in
the last decade to see how many, if any, carry infectious prions.
It is another method to gauge the spread of mad cow disease in
humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
