<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-LIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER METEORITE MAY SHOW LIFE ON MARS, SCIENTISTS REPORT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England, Egypt)   By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same scientists who caused a sensation by claiming that a
meteorite from Mars appeared to contain fossil and chemical traces
of microbial life announced Thursday that they had found another
meteorite with similar intriguing characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to a conference at the Lunar and Planetary Institute
in Houston, a team of geochemists led by Dr. David S. McKay of the
Johnson Space Center said the recently analyzed meteorite
``contains variable concentrations of tiny round to ovoid objects
which can plausibly be interpreted as bacterial cells in various
states of mineralization.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire report was couched in similarly cautious language.
The researchers noted that the size, shape and distribution of tiny
minerals in the meteorite are ``reminiscent of dividing bacteria,''
and that the texture ``closely resembles some mineralized bacterial
cells grown in Columbia River basalt microcosms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not claiming we have found direct evidence of Martian
life in this meteorite,'' McKay said in a telephone interview. But
some of the minerals, he added, strongly suggest biological origins
and should be examined in even more detail by other scientific
teams with more powerful analytical technology.
</P>
<P>
   Other planetary geologists and specialists in meteorite studies,
many of whom remain unconvinced by similar findings by McKay's team
three years ago, said they were skeptical of the biological
interpretation being applied to the new research.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, McKay, Dr. Everett K. Gibson Jr. and other
government and university scientists said that they had identified
organic compounds and certain minerals that they concluded ``are
evidence for primitive life on early Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence consisted of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons,
which often have biological origins, and two minerals, magnetite
and iron sulfide, both of which are related to bacterial action on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The material was found in fragments of a meteorite picked up in
Antarctica in 1984. It is designated Allan Hills 84001, and
scientists are almost certain it fell to Earth from Mars about
13,000 years ago. The discovery gave new impetus to the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's revived program of Mars
exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Critics maintain that the supposed evidence of biological
processes could have nonbiological explanations. But McKay said
Thursday that his team had recently made some converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe our magnetite findings in the Allan Hills meteorite
are getting stronger and stronger,'' he said. ``We think these
particular elongated prisms are biogenic, and we're sticking to
that story. The only examples we find on Earth are all biogenic.''
</P>
<P>
   In their new research, the geochemists analyzed chips from an
orange-size meteorite that landed in Egypt in 1911 and was almost
immediately collected by scientists. The particular fragment of
this meteorite came from the British Museum in London and
presumably had been protected from most terrestrial contamination
by a glassy crust that formed during the meteorite's fiery plunge
through the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging some possible contamination, the research team
wrote: ``We suggest that this meteorite may contain two generations
of bacteria, an original Martian generation and a generation which
grew on Earth. The close proximity of the two generations might be
explained if the organic Martian remains served as favorable
attachment sites for the terrestrial bacteria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
