<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5758 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-DISABLED-MEDICAID-     03-18 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DISABLED-MEDICAID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF DISABLED SUE FOR MEDICAID SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They are the aging parents of mentally retarded
children who have cared for those children all their lives. And
they are increasingly worried about their children's futures once
they become too frail to assist them, or they've passed on.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, parents and other advocates of the developmentally
disabled will file a class-action lawsuit in US District Court in
Boston seeking to force the state to provide Medicaid services to
nearly 3,000 mentally retarded adults. The 3,000 have all been
deemed eligible for Medicaid services, usually for residential
programs. But they have been on a waiting list, some for as long as
two decades, for lack of state funding.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Tummino, assistant DMR commissioner for field
operations, says the state has been making considerable progress in
recent years tackling the waiting list, and has been ranked fourth
nationally in those efforts by the National Association of
Developmental Disability Directors.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Sarkissian, executive director of the Association of
Retarded Citizens of Massachusetts, charges that people on the
waiting list receive the services they need only when they fall
into dire circumstances -- when they are being abused, or their
caretakers die or become ill.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three-year-old Christina Anderson says she is no longer
willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   She has tended to all of her daughter Valerie's needs for her
entire life. Her 41-year-old daughter, who is mentally retarded,
deaf, mute and legally blind, is so dependent on her tht she
refuses to eat or sleep when she's not home.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson frets about what will happen if she falls seriously ill
or dies: Valerie, ``would just perish, literally. Because there is
no way to tell her I'm not here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wants to see daughter move into a residential program
soon, while she is still able to help others learn to communicate
with her daughter and to help her daughter adjust to a new way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   But her daughter already has languished for more than a decade
on the state Department of Mental Retardation waiting list for
services, without being given a hint of how much longer she must
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Neil McKittrick, an attorney at Hill &AMP; Barlow who is
representing the plaintiffs pro bono, said, ``The federal Medicaid
Act says that people are entitled to receive services with
`reasonable promptness.' And we say years is not reasonably
prompt.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents, McKittrick added, ``have done this for 45 years and
they've saved the Commonwealth millions of dollars. Now they need
some help.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some precedent for the lawsuit. Last year, a federal
judge ordered Florida to begin providing services to thousands of
developmentally disabled people within 30 days or risk having its
Medicaid funds frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Tummino said the waiting list in Massachusetts had been growing
at a rate of 13 percent a year since 1991, as more young people who
had been receiving special education entitlements turned 22 _ the
age when those entitlements end _ and signed up for Medicaid mental
retardation services instead.
</P>
<P>
   This year for the first time, Tummino noted, the state has
allocated funds to provide services to all those who age out of
special education, effectively stopping the waiting list from
growing further.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, under a three-year plan, the Cellucci
administration has earmarked a total of $15 million a year to pare
down the waiting list from a high of 3,400 in 1997 to a target of
2,700 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Tummino said, the administration is working on $50
million a year plan to eliminate the remainder of the wait list
over six years.
</P>
<P>
   But Sarkissian believes the state is moving too slowly given the
Florida ruling and the large budget surpluses available.
</P>
<P>
   Sarkissian estimates that to provide services to everyone the
wait list immediately, the state needs to allocate $118 million a
year, 40 percent of which would be covered by federal
reimbursements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
