<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-MARKETPLACE-70     03-18 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-MARKETPLACE-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: WHY DAIMLERCHRYSLER WALKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ DaimlerChrysler AG has been painting a grim picture of
Nissan Motor Co.'s balance sheet _ or rather, what is absent from
it.
</P>
<P>
   Since DaimlerChrysler stopped talking with Nissan last week
about purchasing a stake in the heavily indebted Japanese
automaker, Renault of France has stepped forward with an offer. But
investors seem more interested in why DaimlerChrysler walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, it has been saying that it decided against taking a
stake in Nissan in the interest of concentrating on the smooth
integration of Daimler-Benz and Chrysler Corp., which combined
their businesses only in November.
</P>
<P>
   In private, however, DaimlerChrysler has been telling fund
managers and analysts in Europe and the United States that even
though it had 30 people examining Nissan's financial statements and
operations for six months, it cannot say for certain that it firmly
grasped the full extent of the company's potential liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's disclosures have exposed Nissan to intense
scrutiny and left many wondering whether Renault kicked the tires
hard enough before making its offer on Tuesday. Renault's proposal
to acquire 35 percent of Nissan, which the Japanese automaker's
board is expected to accept on Friday, could provide as much as
$5.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   According to two fund managers and a fund-management analyst who
have been briefed by Daimler, the more its team looked at Nissan,
the more exposure there seemed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``In having to defend itself, the news that's coming out of
DaimlerChrysler about Nissan is not very positive,'' one of the
fund managers said.
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with DaimlerChrysler's research suggested that
Nissan's true liabilities _ not just debt but also such potential
obligations as pension contributions and hidden debts _ were twice
as great as the $21.2 billion that is publicly known.
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency in Renault's decision to bid and
DaimlerChrysler's decision to withdraw has left investors
skeptical, which is reflected in the depressed stock price of
Nissan and Renault. Credit-rating agencies have also expressed
reservations, and financial news coverage has been muted on what
would be a major foreign rescue of a leading Japanese corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is avid interest in matters like the steep
erosion in Nissan's sales in Japan, the effect of the stronger yen
on overseas sales, the higher-than-average interest rates Nissan is
paying and the shortage in its pension fund. Some Japanese have
long agonized over such things, but now these are gaining
international attention.
</P>
<P>
   There is little concern that Renault has the financial resources
to pay for a Nissan stake _ the French company is debt-free, has
ample lines of credit, and is 44 percent-owned by the French
government. Renault executives also insist they have an accurate
reading on Nissan's business, including its debts.
</P>
<P>
   According to a person close to the two companies' negotiations,
Nissan had at first been willing to supply only limited, and
opaque, information about its liabilities. But in recent weeks, it
gave Renault executives answers that Renault considered
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not offer a firm figure, this person conceded
that Nissan's real indebtedness was certainly greater than the 2.5
trillion yen _ now $21.2 billion _ disclosed in the company's last
annual report, reflecting the fiscal year that ended on March 31,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan had an additional 1.8 trillion yen in liabilities related
to its auto-leasing business for a total of 4.3 trillion yen in
debt, although many analysts and auto-company executives do not
regard leasing-related debt as a matter of concern.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the automaker's indebtedness outside what it is
required to disclose that has concerned others, including
DaimlerChrysler. Such so-called off-balance-sheet risks have long
been rumored at Nissan and at other large Japanese companies, and
Daimler is not the first potential buyer to have been scared away
by them.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is still smarting from the surprise it got when
it increased its stake in Mazda Motor Corp. to 33.4 percent in
1996, only to find out that Mazda's dealers had incurred enormous
debts for which Mazda was liable, Ford executives have said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, the Japanese Life Insurance Association
abandoned its efforts to sell Aoba Life Insurance Co. after a big
French concern, Pinault-Printemps-Redoute, cut its original bid in
half. Previously, the American International Group, the insurer and
financial-services company, was the leading suitor, but it walked
away.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is rampant that, among other things, Aoba was more
financially problematic than the suitors had been able to see from
public documents. ``No investment banker is being candid about what
happened there,'' said Craig Chudler, an equity strategist at Nikko
Salomon Smith Barney. ``But I think AIG and Pinault must have seen
something that shocked them.''
</P>
<P>
   Large Japanese companies such as Nissan are structured so that a
vast galaxy of satellite companies, typically suppliers of parts
and services, are locked into orbit around them by a combination of
investments, loans and business relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The potential liabilities associated with many of those
companies _ the losses they sustain, the debts they cannot repay,
the shortages in their pension funds _ often ultimately fall upon
the main company but are not fully reflected in its public
financial records, nor is such disclosure required.
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, the core company's investment in a satellite
is now worth half what it originally paid, the decline in value is
not necessarily reflected on the balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, for instance, has 201 affiliates whose overall
performance is reflected in its financial statements. Beyond that
cluster, Nissan is linked to 389 companies whose fortunes are not
reflected on its books but whose problems may become its own.
</P>
<P>
   Keiichi Tsuboi, a spokesman for Nissan, noted that its interests
in those 389 companies constitute less than 10 percent of its total
revenue on a consolidated basis, a limit imposed by Japanese
accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there are debts at the unconsolidated companies,
but we don't think the total debt is significant,'' Tsuboi said.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 1, many of the off-balance-sheet liabilities must
start to appear on financial statements under new accounting rules
that are expected to shake corporate Japan to its foundations _
though many obligations like loan guarantees may still remain
hidden.
</P>
<P>
   The new accounting rules will expose just the sort of
off-balance-sheet problems that Nissan disclosed last week. Its
plans to recapitalize the troubled sales unit of its troubled
truck-making affiliate, Nissan Diesel Motor Co., further raised
sensitivity to the issue of unseen liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan and Nissan Diesel said they would each invest 20 billion
yen ($170 million) in the unit, Nissan Diesel Sales Co., even
though Nissan's only exposure to it was through its 39.8 percent
stake in Nissan Diesel. ``A gap has emerged between the book value
of the investment made in domestic dealerships which are owned by
Nissan Diesel Motor Sales and the real value of those
dealerships,'' Nissan said in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
   The gap Nissan referred to was equivalent to roughly half the
book value of the investment in the sales unit, and its magnitude
surprised many analysts. Nissan Diesel sold only half as many
trucks last year as the year before, leaving its dealers with
bloated inventories and no way to repay their loans.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts had suspected as much, but because the sales unit
is not a public company and does not disclose financial
information, the analysts had no way of gauging the extent of
Nissan's exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm just stupid, but I had no idea the losses in that
business would run so high,'' said Peter Boardman of Warburg Dillon
Read here. ``Yes, it was good news in that they were able to
overcome a crisis, but it also allowed the market to see how big
the losses were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
