<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5767 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CRITICS-BOS &LR;      03-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CRITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMS NOT ENOUGH, INFLUENTIAL CRITICS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Oly-Dalessandro; s and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA AND MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reforms enacted by the International Olympic Committee this week
fail to ensure a new, more ethical era for the Games, according to
a US Senator poised to investigate the IOC and its chief corporate
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Senator John McCain (R-Ariz.) and David D'Alessandro,
president of the John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., said
Thursday that IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch must appoint
independent officials to two committees established by the IOC in
Lausanne, Switzerland Thursday to oversee the ethics of members and
to consider restructuring the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcement that Mr. Samaranch intends to oversee the
newly created IOC ethics commission causes great concern,'' said
McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, which will
conduct a hearing on the IOC next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It displays a failure to grasp even the most basic concepts of
ethics and reform,'' McCain said. ``This is clearly a conflict of
interest...I'm afraid the IOC leadership is less concerned about
reform than preserving the power of an elite few.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, speaking to reporters in Lausanne, said the Olympic
charter requires that he both appoint and chair any IOC-sanctioned
commission. Asked why he is presiding, Samaranch said: ``Because I
am the president. That is why I will preside.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro, meanwhile, said: ``I think Samaranch is having
some trouble `getting it,' at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinarily important to see who is on those
committees,'' D'Alessandro said. ``If they are all the old Olympic
group, people who have been involved off and on for years, than
it's not going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted separately, officials of six of the other 10 Worldwide
Sponsors of the IOC _ representing almost $1 billion in Olympic
financing _ said with near unanimity Thursday that while the
reforms are important, they represent only early steps in a long
process toward restoring the image of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive step that they came out and said they would
take certain actions, and they followed through,'' said Karl
Langsenkamp, director of public relations for Xerox. ``I don't
think it's the end, certainly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xerox, like the other companies involved _ and, I'm sure, the
American people _ are going to be gauging the strength of the
follow up by the IOC, and watching the other investigations that
are ongoing, to see what occurs,'' Langsenkamp said.
</P>
<P>
   In Lausanne Thursday, the IOC, as expected, took several steps
toward reform in the wake of the $1.2 million bribery scandal
involving the selection of Salt Lake City as the site of the Winter
Games in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The committee:
</P>
<P>
   --Adopted a new system to select the site for the 2006 games
that forbids IOC members to visit the various bid cities. A
15-member committee, including IOC members, outside advisers and
athletes will narrow the current field of six cities to two
finalists. The full assembly of the IOC will then choose the
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   --Established an ethics committee to oversee members, with a
majority of members from outside the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   --Created ``IOC 2000,'' which will study the structure of the
group and consider issues like how members are elected, the length
of their terms and the distribution of power.
</P>
<P>
   --Issued an audit by Pricewaterhouse Coopers, that pegged the
net worth of the IOC at $136 million at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As always with the IOC, long considered the most closed and
conservative of international sports bodies, observers wondered who
will appoint and control the new committees. For McCain and
D'Alessandro, the answer was clear: Juan Antonio Samaranch, the
78-year-old patriarch of the Olympic movement, who is often
criticized for running an autocracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to agree to have oversight and an ethics commission,
and to study term limits is real progress,'' D'Alessandro said.
``It would would have been unthinkable just some months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, it's not reform yet.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro, who for months has said publicly what some other
international sponsors of the game have said only privately, added
that what had been called for in Lausanne was much stronger, more
independent leadership.
</P>
<P>
   What Samaranch should have said, according to D'Alessandro, is
that the ethics commission should be entirely independent, IOC
members will be chosen by the individual countries represented by
the committee, with everyone's term limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got as much done as they could with Samaranch in
place,'' he said. ``But I think he's been energized by some
anti-American sentiment that's saying, `We can't listen to the
Americans.' Well, we contribute 70 percent of their budget. As long
as they take our money, they can take out complaints. Or, just
write us a check for our money, and we'll go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 worldwide sponsors of the IOC pay an average of $40
million for four-year contracts to use the Olympic symbol and
emblems, mascots and other game icons as part of their advertising
and promotional activities. Six of those sponsors said Thursday
that while the steps toward reform taken by the IOC were the best
news in months, it must be equally effective in following through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC made progress in addressing the improprieties of the
past and more importantly focused on the future by establishing
specific measures for 2006 host-city selection and organizational
reform,'' said Ben Deutsch, a spokesman for Coca-Cola, Inc.
``Ultimately the success of what was outlined this week is going to
be judged by the IOC's ability to define, embrace and enforce the
new reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
