<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SCOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTER D. SCOTT, EX-CHIEF WHO LED NBC INTO COLOR PROGRAMMING, DIES
AT 84  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Mo, Texas, Va.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Decker Scott, who stepped down as chairman of NBC in 1974
after a 36-year career that spanned the heyday of network radio and
TV's golden age, died on March 12 at Carmel Valley Manor, a
retirement home in Carmel, Calif. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from pneumonia, NBC said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who joined the National Broadcasting Company as a
salesman in 1937, led the network in the mid-1960s, when it
committed itself to color programming. NBC occasionally had shown
color programming since the 1950s, but some executives were wary of
making a costly commitment to the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Scott based his decision in part on data showing that families
with color sets watched television more than did families that
owned only black-and-white sets. He was credited with persuading
the network hierarchy, as well as those in charge at the corporate
parent, the Radio Corporation of America, and the film studios to
risk the significant increases in production costs.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal led to the adoption of a color schedule at NBC in
1965. A slogan advertising the new standard, ``The Full Color
Network,'' lives on in NBC's peacock logo.
</P>
<P>
   He was named chairman and chief executive in 1966. He was also
elected a director of RCA, which was bought by General Electric in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was born in Kansas City, Mo. He studied at Washington
University and graduated from the University of Missouri School of
Journalism in 1936. He arrived at NBC television with the advent of
the intercontinental coaxial cable in the early 1950s and became
vice president for TV network sales in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   He was president of the network in the early 1960s, when network
television grew significantly. In 1965, he succeeded Robert E.
Kintner as president and chief executive of NBC. Scott became
chairman the next year.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring to Carmel in 1974, he joined the board of Quail
Meadows, a real estate and hotel business.
</P>
<P>
   Scott is survived by his wife of 58 years, Arline Stenz Scott;
two daughters, Shelley S. Heeder of Alexandria, Va., and Valerie S.
Miro-Quesada of Houston; five grandchildren, and two
great-grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5769 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     03-18 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ETHICS OF WORM HUNTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH   
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A fascinating sidelight to Worm Watch '99 is how
the media _ mainstream, tabloid and otherwise _ has been
disseminating information about Dennis Rodman's disappearance from
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be a matter of how much we need to know versus how
much we want to know, with the fact most of us are bored by his
boorish behavior somewhat factored in.
</P>
<P>
   From the Lakers' end, team spokesmen continue to say Rodman is
away on ``personal non-basketball business.'' That's the polite way
of saying: ``That's all we need to tell you.'' The Lakers, by the
way, also reported that Magic Johnson missed a game with the flu
the day before he came out in 1991 and announced he contracted HIV.
</P>
<P>
   This Lakers stance leaves the door open to widespread
speculation. Drugs? Alcohol? Gambling? Some kind of freak accident
(no pun intended)? Is he on another suicide watch? Or, as the
Dallas Morning News' Frank Luksa suggests, this could simply mean
Rodman went shopping for a dress.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's telecast from Minnesota, Chick Hearn _ who
about 10 years ago less-than-tactfully handled James Worthy's
disappearance from the team on a road trip in Houston _ read a memo
that ``Rodman's people'' sent to the team thanking the fans, his
teammates and management for understanding his need for the time
off. Hearn could have left it at that, but he added a line of
information about a Rodman sighting over the weekend in Las Vegas.
Hearn said it was because Rodman has business to tend to in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, on KLAC's ``Laker Line'' radio post-game talk show,
callers kept throwing Rodman rumors out to host Larry Burnett. He
would not even get close to legitimizing them other than to say
he's heard them but would leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. That's probably the way it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Except this is Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly invites people into his bizarre life by writing
two tell-all books, ``Bad As I Want To Be'' followed by ``A Walk On
The Wild Side.'' He's likely saving material from this episode for
a third book, ``I Did It My Way.'' Also, as Phil Mushnick points
out in the latest TV Guide, ESPN's ``Up Close'' has had Rodman on
as a guest eight times in the last five years _ far more than
anyone else. And that's not counting his appearances with Jay Leno
on ``The Tonight Show.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Rodman acts as if he doesn't want to draw attention,
he lives off it.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Rodman showed up at the end of practice and told
coach Kurt Rambis he wasn't making the plane trip to Sacramento and
several newspaper reporters documented the bizarre event. The next
day, speculation about Rodman's ``personal crisis'' started.
</P>
<P>
   Any quotes directly from Rodman? Only a cryptic one to TNT's
Craig Sager. Other than that, news on Rodman has come from those
infamous nameless, faceless sources _ which, we hate to admit, are
sometimes nothing more than the reporter himself hearing enough
rumors to believe he has cause to write something.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to competitive celebrity journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and sports-talk radio dove in immediately with the
usual widespread spectrum of conclusions. Then Monday, the National
Enquirer contributed with a wild account of Rodman and wife Carmen
Electra's dual infidelity that has brought Pamela Anderson's
ex-husband Tommy Lee into the picture.
</P>
<P>
   So does this mean it's all on the record for the ``mainstream''
media to pick up and report? We're treading on Lewinsky-Clinton
ground now. Let's back up a minute.
</P>
<P>
   The original question _ why is Rodman missing? _ has been
answered, however lamely, to the team's satisfaction but maybe not
to the public's infatuation.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe the public just doesn't care anymore and the media
should start being more in tune with that.
</P>
<P>
   If this is fodder for a third book, eventually Rodman will
benefit financially from releasing the information and that could
be the only reason he's upset anything is coming out right now.
</P>
<P>
   This really !ital!is!off Rodman's business. The media should
leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   But why does the media care so much about Dennis Rodman? Why
does the public care?
</P>
<P>
   Because it's as if we're watching Rodman in a low-speed police
chase down the freeway, knowing what could happen next. Rodman is
that guy on the freeway overpass with his truck on fire leaning
into the back to grab a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to act responsibly and just turn the camera
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Challenge'' bonus round: Did you know Joe DiMaggio made
16 appearances on the old ``Sports Challenge'' TV show? Series
producer Dan Marrin called to add that fact the other day from his
home in Santa Monica after reading about the ESPN Classic tribute
to DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee Clipper was also paid the same as Jackie Robinson and
Ted Williams and all the rest who came on _ $317.63, which was the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists (AFTRA) scale
wage.
</P>
<P>
   Marrin, who sold the rights to the shows to former Classic
Sports Channel co-founder Steve Greenberg _ whose father, Hall of
Famer Hank Greenberg, was once a mystery guest _ said the most
successful three-man team ever on the show was the Lakers with
Jerry West, Gail Goodrich and Happy Hairston.
</P>
<P>
   ``West knew everything about every sport,'' said Marrin. ``He,
Tommy Henrich and Red Auerbach were the three most knowledgeable
sports guests.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN Classic, by the way, has back-to-back ``Sports Challenge''
shows twice a day Monday through Friday from 4 p.m. to 5 p.m. and 8
p.m. to 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be surprised if a new ``Sports Challenge''
materialized someday on ESPN. Marrin says he's been in discussions
about trying to get it up and running again.
</P>
<P>
   He said paying the participants would be a challenge, but the
rights fees to use old film and video clips these days make a show
like this more prohibitive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
_Kevin Kennedy, runner-up for the Dodgers managerial job last
winter, has found another way to draw checks from Rupert Murdoch:
He's been hired as a Fox Sports News baseball studio analyst. The
Tarzana resident and Valley native _ who also runs a baseball
academy in Arleta primarily for Japanese players _ loves the fact
he can stay home most days rather than the nearly daily travel he
was doing the past few years as a game analyst for ESPN. Kennedy,
who will also get to do game analysis work on the Fox Sports Net
Thursday night game of the week, doesn't anticipate that viewers
will read into his analysis any personal agenda when he critiques
managers or players _ especially the Dodgers personnel. ``I'll be
objective no matter who I'm talking about,'' he said. ``I'm a
baseball guy. That (agenda) won't be an issue. I enjoy explaining
how and why things happen in the game. I'm in a really nice
situation that I'd like to stay in for a long time.'' &QL; 
_The Walt Hazzard ``cover story'' piece that aired on Wednesday's
ESPN ``SportsCenter.'' The pictures of Hazzard's recovery process
from a stroke suffered three years ago were compelling enough, but
the interviews reporter Shelly Smith did with Hazzard's family were
equally upbeat and heartwarming. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
