<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-EAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMS COACH MUST MAKE GOLIATH-BUSTERS OF HIS DAVIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Duke sophomore forward Elton Brand was
walking from the interview area to the locker room Thursday
afternoon when he passed members of the Southwest Missouri State
team, who were standing in the hallway. It was quite a spectacle:
Brand, trailed by a throng of reporters, looked forward and smiled
as he entertained questions.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State players, who meet the top-ranked,
top-seeded Blue Devils (34-1) in Friday's NCAA Tournament East
Regional semifinal (7:38), ceased their conversations and stared at
the procession until Brand all but disappeared from view.
</P>
<P>
   SMS coach Steve Alford said the matchup has a
``David-vs.-Goliath-type of atmosphere.'' Anyone unfamiliar with
college basketball needed only to be in the hallway to know which
team represented David and which was the big guy.
</P>
<P>
   Alford has his work cut out for him. Sometime between Thursday
afternoon and Friday night, he must find a way to wipe the looks of
awe from his players' faces. If Brand can strike wonder in SMS by
merely walking through a corridor, imagine the impression he'll
leave after tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-seeded Bears (22-10) are 28-point underdogs entering
Friday night's game, and many figure the outcome will be decided
long before the final buzzer. In the other East Regional semifinal,
sixth-seeded Temple (23-10) meets 10th-seeded Purdue (21-12) at
9:55 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   You figure any team that believes it doesn't have a shot at
victory shouldn't bother showing up. Alford dismissed the notion
that the team would register a moral victory by being competitive.
`I am sure there aren't many people in this (interview) room that
picked us over Wisconsin and Tennessee (SMS's first- and second-
round opponents) and we were able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet believing you can beat Duke because you beat Wisconsin and
Tennessee is like believing a Hyundai can outperform a Bentley
because it excelled over a couple of Buicks. Here are a few reasons
SMS players had every right to be in awe of the Blue Devils:
</P>
<P>
   --Duke is in its 16th regional semifinal and is playing its 15th
game in the Meadowlands, where it has advanced to the Final Four
four times and has a 13-1 record. The two-time national champions
(1991-92) are the winningest team in tournament history with a
62-20 mark and a .756 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   --The Blue Devils own college basketball's longest winning
streak (29), and it their last 10 games, no team has come within 15
points of beating them. They lead the nation in scoring (93.6
points per game), scoring margin (26.3), and are second in field
goal percentage (51.7).
</P>
<P>
   --Duke's projected starting lineup (guards Trajan Langdon and
William Avery, forwards Chris Carrawell and Shane Battier and
center Brand) is 20-0 this season.
</P>
<P>
   --Brand is a first-team All-American, a Sporting News national
player of the year and joins Langdon as a Wooden and Naismith award
finalist. The Blue Devils' roster includes nine former high school
All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are dominant,'' said Alford. ``We come into this
tournament with a 20.5 (point) win margin. After five days of
watching tape, I'm trying to figure out how to get out of East
Rutherford with a win margin. We know we are going to have to play
very, very well, but that's what the game is played for.''
</P>
<P>
   SMS would also benefit from Duke overconfidence, but Brand said
that won't be likely. ``Coach (Mike) Krzyzewski has prepared many
great teams and many great ballplayers before us,'' said Brand. He
really lets us know what's going to happen before it even
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Many figure the Temple-Purdue game to be more compelling. The
contests matches two scrappy, physical teams that play tough
defense. Both reached the regional semifinal with second-round
upsets, Temple over third-seeded Cincinnati, Purdue over
second-seeded Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whoever gets the lead first will have some control,''
said Purdue coach Gene Keady. ``We really don't care about the
pace. I think the main thing is the control of Temple's offense
with our defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
