<HEADLINE>
BOSTON BANK OF COMMERCE SEEKS MERGER WITH CARVER BANCORP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Having recovered from years of nearly fatal loan
losses and a bitter internal power struggle, Boston Bank of
Commerce said Thursday it is attempting to merge with another
black-owned bank, the troubled Carver Bancorp. of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Bank of Commerce officials said they hope it is the first
step in assembling a franchise of minority-owned banks across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to grow by leaps and bounds is to acquire,'' said
Robert Patrick Cooper, Boston Bank of Commerce's senior counsel.
``We intend to do that nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Flush with capital and growing 33 percent a year on loans since
1996, Cooper said Boston Bank of Commerce, the city's only
black-owned bank, acquired 7 percent of Carver Bancorp.'s shares
over past months. Thursday it filed documents with the Securities
and Exchange Commission formally ``stating its interest in a
merger.''
</P>
<P>
   One catch in the deal, however, is that Carver Bancorp. doesn't
want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is that Carver's board does not believe a
combination is in the best interest of their shareholders at this
time,'' Boston Bank of Commerce said in a statement. Carver
Bancorp. officials couldn't be reached Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cooper said Carver Bancorp.'s shareholders could be
receptive to the deal and force the board to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accumulated a significant position in the company, and
we think our voice can be heard,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   While terms of a deal have yet to be hammered out, Cooper said
under Boston Bank of Commerce's proposal, the $400 million Carver
Bancorp. would buy the much smaller $108 million Boston Bank of
Commerce. But the new company would be controlled and managed by
Boston Bank of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Carver Bancorp., whose shares are traded on the American Stock
Exchange, has run up huge losses in recent years at its Carver
Federal Savings Bank in Harlem. Mounting financial problems in its
loan portfolio earlier this year forced the bank to disclose it
would likely report a loss of at least $5 million in the fourth
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they get out of this deal is a seasoned management team
that knows the African American market and knows how to turn around
a troubled institution,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Bank of Commerce, founded in 1966 as Unity Bank, was one
of the first local banks to make home loans minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The bank got hurt in the real estate crash of the early 1990s,
losing $3.5 million in three years. Regulators threatened to close
it down in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It was rescued by a Boston couple, Kevin Cohee and Teri
Williams, who invested $1 million and saved the bank.
</P>
<P>
   A bitter struggle for power ensued, resulting in the ouster of
chairman and chief executive Ronald Homer, who then sued the bank
for wrongful termination. The suit was settled for an undisclosed
sum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
