<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDIS RELEASE SEIZED IRAQI PLANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Saudi Arabia on Thursday released an Iraqi
plane it seized on Wednesday after the U.N. sanctions committee
failed to agree on whether such flights of religious pilgrims
violate U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock in the sanctions committee, which is composed of
the same nations as the 15-member Security Council, reflects the
continuing disagreement in the council over policy toward Iraq. A
similar debate last year also ended in disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said the plane that the Saudi authorities
detained at Jidda airport was carrying 111 Iraqis traveling to
Mecca for the haj, the pilgrimage to Mohammed's birthplace required
once in a lifetime of all pious Muslims who can afford it. Another
flight of 110 Iraqi pilgrims landed the previous day, but was
permitted to return to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Abdulrahman al-Ahmed, the Saudi charge d'affaires at the United
Nations, appealed on Wednesday in a letter to the sanctions
committee for guidance as to whether the Saudis should continue
holding the plane. The letter said that if the United Nations did
not provide advice on the issue by 11 a.m. Thursday, the Saudis
would ``allow the plane and crew to return to Iraq,'' which they
did.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said the sanctions committee held an emergency meeting
Thursday morning to examine the issue of whether U.N. resolutions,
in effect, provide for an air embargo against Iraq. The U.N. legal
adviser argued, as he did last year, that the resolutions required
Iraq to seek the committee's permission for all flights, even those
of a religious or relief nature, and that Iraq had failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats who attended the meeting said this view, which was
strongly endorsed by the American and British delegates, had been
vigorously challenged by Russia, France and China, among others,
which maintained that flights of no commercial or military benefit
to Iraq were exempt from the resolution's reporting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no consensus in the end,'' said Peter Van Walsum,
the Dutch representative on the Security Council who heads the
sanctions committee. ``So I concluded the only thing I could do was
thank the Saudi government for having brought the matter to our
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. resolutions provide for the seizure of assets in connection
with flights that take place without the committee's approval. But
Baghdad appeared to draw the obvious political lesson from the
sanctions committee's paralysis Thursday and flew a third plane of
pilgrims to Saudi Arabia, again without requesting the committee's
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has repeatedly used the haj to test the limits of the
sanctions regime, which faces increasing opposition in the world
body. In a related issue, the council has remained unable to devise
a financial system to defray the cost of the pilgrimage for Iraqi
Muslims. Last year, the council agreed that some of the oil money
that Iraq is allowed to spend on imports like food could also be
used to subsidize haj pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the committee created a voucher system under which
Iraqi pilgrims received a certificate in Baghdad that they could
exchange for cash in Saudi banks. But many pilgrims complained that
the system was inconvenient and humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   This year the committee agreed that pilgrims could collect their
money in cash before leaving Baghdad, but the deal collapsed when
Iraq and the sanctions committee disagreed over how the money would
be distributed. Iraq wanted the money paid to its central bank,
which would then distribute it to travelers. But the council said
such payments would breach economic sanctions and set a dangerous
precedent. Instead, it proposed that the Red Cross or another
independent agency distribute the funds. Iraq rejected this
proposal too, resulting in a deadlock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
