<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-JOURNALISTS-NYT     03-18 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-JOURNALISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR INTELLECTUAL MAGAZINE   IS SHUT IN CRACKDOWN BY BEIJING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The authorities have shut down a popular intellectual
magazine here for ``reorganization,'' the latest move in an uneven
tightening of controls over liberal publications.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly magazine, called Way, has a circulation of 20,000
and is widely read in academic circles. In recent years, under the
banner of interdisciplinary inquiry, it had branched out from its
original mandate to focus on the natural sciences, carrying essays
on the nature of freedom, the rule of law and the dangers of
totalitarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the authorities warned the editors to stick to more
scientific topics and the subsequent two issues were, in fact, far
less venturesome. But last week the Administration of Press and
Publications, which regulates books, magazines and newspapers on
behalf of the Communist Party, said Way must stop publishing while
it undergoes reorganization and changes its content.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's editorial director, Feng Xiaozhe, said in an
interview that the editors were trying to cooperate with the
authorities and hoped they could resume publishing within a few
months. He said it was too soon to know whether any editors would
be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a total liquidation of the magazine but a
temporary matter that we hope to resolve as soon as possible,''
Feng said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months, the authorities have closed or put
pressure on several liberal newspapers, magazines and book
publishers across the country, apparently reflecting official
nervousness in a year when social stability has been named the
paramount goal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fearing economic unrest, the leaders may fear
dissent related to the 10th anniversary of the suppression of the
student democracy movement in Tiananmen Square in Beijing in June,
and the 50th anniversary of the founding of the Communist state on
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by historical standards here, the intellectual crackdown
is relatively mild and inconsistent. Even as the authorities
intimidate or close some publications, many other magazines,
journals and books continue to appear that criticize directions of
society or delve into sensitive aspects of Communist Party history.
</P>
<P>
   This month in a rare direct attack on a major government policy,
an intellectual journal, called Strategy and Management, contained
a scathing critique of the social effects of the Three Gorges Dam
project on the Yangtze River. So far that journal, which has also
carried provocative articles on political subjects, has not been
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest repressive acts was the indefinite
suspension, on Dec. 29, of the Chinese-language book operations of
China Today Press. The press had published an influential, frank
series of books on topics like corruption and ideological disputes,
and a path-breaking collection of essays on political reform.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the press is now undergoing ``rectification,''
forced to study ideology and engage in written and verbal
self-criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
