<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW METEORITE EVIDENCE BOLSTERS LIFE-ON-MARS THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ New evidence presented here Thursday greatly
strengthens the case for the existence of traces of bacterial life
inside meteorites from Mars, and for the first time adds strong
indications that such bacteria may still be alive today beneath the
Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   The new signs of relic Martian life, unlike those first
presented in August 1996, look exactly like known fossils of Earth
life forms in their size, shape, and arrangement. And for the first
time, such apparent fossil formations have been found inside three
different meteorites, which formed on Mars during different eras.
</P>
<P>
   The new discoveries raise the strong prospect of a final
resolution to the fierce arguments among scientists over whether
these shapes found in rocks from Mars really are signs of life on
the red planet. After two-and-a-half years of controversy, the case
could be closed, one way or the other, within the next year, some
of the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the scientists who have been most skeptical of the
original claims of possible fossils in a Mars rock have begun to
temper their criticism. For example, some of those who claimed that
the rock formed at too high a temperature for life to have existed
inside it have now retracted such claims, in light of new evidence
that shows the rock could have formed at much lower temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   The new possible fossil shapes were found inside a meteorite
called Nakhla, which fell in the Sahara desert in 1911 and was
collected within a day of its impact. This greatly lessens the
possibility that anything found inside it could be the result of
terrestrial contamination, as some scientists have argued may be
the case with the suspected fossils reported in 1996 inside a
meteorite called ALH 84001. That meteorite lay on the ice in
Antarctica for 13,000 years before being found,
</P>
<P>
   In addition, while ALH 84001 is a rock that formed on Mars 4.3
billion years ago, Nakhla formed 1.3 billion years ago. Similar
possible fossils were also reported here Thursday inside yet
another meteorite from Mars, called Shergotty, which formed just
165 million years ago. If scientists can confirm that these really
are fossils of bacterial life on Mars, the long time span covered
by the three samples would make it very likely that such life would
still exist there now. Such life would have to be under the
planet's surface, which, because of ultra-violet radiation, is
inhospitable to life as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this proves out, we will have shown that life spans the
entire history of Mars, and is probably there today,'' said David
McKay, a scientist at NASA's Johnson Space Center who was the
leader of the team that reported the original signs of life in a
Mars meteorite and also led the team reporting these new findings.
</P>
<P>
   But McKay stressed that there are still some crucial tests that
must be carried out to prove, first of all, that the suggestive
shapes found inside the rocks truly are fossils of living
organisms, and second, that these organisms are Martian, not Earth
bacteria that somehow contaminated the rocks after they fell.
</P>
<P>
   Study of the chemical composition of these shapes, which is just
beginning, could provide clear evidence of their biological nature,
McKay said. And study of the different forms, or isotopes, of
certain atoms inside these formations could also prove decisively _
or disprove _ their Martian origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not claiming I have found new evidence for life on
Mars,'' McKay said. ``I have found features that have a startling
resemblance to known fossil life. I have not proven they are
bacteria. I have not proven they are from Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the answers should be known within about a year.
``My guess is that that material is all Martian,'' he said,
pointing out that many of the apparent bacterial forms seem to be
embedded in the rock itself.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the preliminary indications are far more positive than
they were for the original shapes found inside ALH 84001, McKay and
other scientists said during the annual Lunar and Planetary Science
Conference held here at the space center, where the new evidence
was presented.
</P>
<P>
   The original ``fossils'' were much smaller than any form of life
known to exist on Earth, and there were no clear signs of processes
such as cell division that would help to confirm their biological
nature. By contrast, the newly discovered shapes inside the Nakhla
meteorite are a perfect match for known terrestrial bacteria, and
include a chain of three apparent cells that match the way some
known bacteria divide and reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't tell people where the sample was from,'' said
McKay, ``a paleontologist would probably say `those are bacteria.'
''
</P>
<P>
   If McKay's discoveries are confirmed by further analysis, it
could have a profound impact on all planning for future Mars
missions, especially possible human missions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an active biosphere on Mars, how should astronauts
deal with that? Is it dangerous or not? We need to evaluate that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
