<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-AD-COL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS PAY $1   MILLION FOR 30-SECONDS DURING THE OSCARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind Shakespeare. It's Madison Avenue that's in love _
with Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation of the 71st annual Academy Awards, to be
broadcast on Sunday by ABC, will be ``brought to you by'' about 15
blue-chip advertisers paying an average of $1 million for each
30-second spot. That price, up 9.3 percent from an average $915,000
last year, is a historic high for the Oscars, reflecting the appeal
of the awards show as well as the current robust market for
commercial time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You swallow deep'' before spending such sums, said one
advertiser, Robert Fisher, president at Gap Inc. in San Francisco.
``But the entertainment value makes it the right thing for us to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers besides Gap will include AT&AMP;T, American Express,
Eastman Kodak, First Union, General Motors, McDonald's, Merrill
Lynch, Pepsi-Cola, the Pepsi-Lipton Tea Partnership, Charles Schwab
and Sears, Roebuck.
</P>
<P>
   If that seems like a Super Bowl sponsor lineup, it's no
coincidence: the parallels this year between the two are
significant enough to consider designating the program Oscar Bowl
LXXI.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the commercial rates are the second highest for
the year after the Super Bowl, an acknowledgment that the Oscar
broadcast annually is usually the second-most-watched program after
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   For another, for the first time, there will be Hollywood
equivalents of the Super Bowl pre-game and post-game shows: a
30-minute ``Oscar Preview'' program covering the celebrities'
arrival at the ceremony and an hourlong ``Politically Incorrect
Afterparty'' following the announcement of the choice for Best
Picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars are being held on a Sunday night, just like the Super
Bowl. That shift from Monday to Sunday _ the night with more
households watching television than any other _ should compensate
for any decline in ratings from last year's show, the most watched
in 15 years because of interest in the hugely popular nominee
``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for a good number'' in the Nielsen ratings, said
Marv Goldsmith, president for sales and marketing at the ABC
Television Network unit of ABC in New York, a division of Walt
Disney Co. that recently signed an agreement to broadcast the
Oscars through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ratings have fluctuated over the years because the broad
appeal of the movies is something you can't control,'' he added.
``But it is an event, an event that advertisers want to be part
of.''
</P>
<P>
   His remark points up that like the Super Bowl, the advertiser
ardor for the Academy Awards program is indicative of a growing
appetite for TV's so-called big events, the handful of shows that
still can draw huge audiences and ratings _ and presumably,
eyeballs to watch commercials _ as viewership for the broadcast
networks continues to erode.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend a higher percentage of time watching the Academy
Awards than any other awards show,'' said Jon Mandel, co-managing
director at Mediacom in New York, the media services unit of Grey
Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a total convergence of fashion and entertainment, the
Oscars has taken on a life of its own,'' he added. ``And any time
you can get half or more of a demographic group watching a program,
it's a winner for advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to the fact that 61 percent of an important
audience for marketers, women ages 18 to 34, watched the Oscars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell a lot of products to married women with children,
young adults and teen-agers, and this show delivers that kind of
audience,'' said Carl E. Gustin, senior vice president and chief
marketing officer at Kodak in Rochester. ``It's a wonderful
marketing tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodak, an Oscar advertiser since 1966, has bought two minutes of
commercial time to run three new spots from Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Worldwide in New York, a unit of WPP Group PLC. In one spot, for
professional portrait photography, a mother watches her two
children grow before her eyes. The others promote Kodak films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought more spots this year than we normally do,'' Gustin
said, ``because we have more to say this year, spending more time
defining our brand as more than just the `yellow boxes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Two financial advertisers will also be running new brand work.
One is Schwab, introducing the first campaign from its new agency,
the BBDO New York unit of BBDO Worldwide, part of Omnicom Group.
The campaign will carry the theme ``Ready to move up?''
</P>
<P>
   The other is Merrill Lynch, bringing out more new spots from the
first campaign from its new agency, J. Walter Thompson New York,
owned by WPP. Two minutes of commercial time will be devoted to
that campaign, carrying the theme ``Human achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the largest event-type programs,'' said Paul W.
Critchlow, senior vice president for marketing and communications
at Merrill Lynch in New York, ``a great vehicle to reach a highly
affluent audience, but one that's broad-based.''
</P>
<P>
   Other marketers introducing commercials during the show are
seeking a showcase for products.
</P>
<P>
   Gap will present the sequel to last year's popular musical
pitches for khaki pants that included the energetic ``Khakis
swing.'' There will be three spots, created in-house, with country,
go-go and soul soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the Oscars as the ultimate night for entertainment,''
Fisher at Gap said. ``And these spots work so well with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gap and Sears jumped in as Oscar advertisers when the previous
retail apparel sponsor, J.C. Penney Co., ended its participation.
Similarly, Pepsi-Cola, a unit of Pepsico Inc., and the Pepsi-Lipton
partnership, a joint venture of Pepsico and Unilever, climbed
aboard when the Coca-Cola Co. exited the beverage category.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Academy Awards works for us on many different levels,''
said Dawn Hudson, senior vice president for strategy and marketing
at the Pepsi-Cola North America unit of Pepsi-Cola in Purchase,
N.Y. Four spots for Pepsi-Cola, by BBDO New York, will introduce
``The joy of cola'' as the brand's theme, replacing ``Generation
next.''
</P>
<P>
   The show ``helps us kick off the summer selling season,'' Ms.
Hudson said, because it is closer to that important period than the
Super Bowl, where the flagship Pepsi-Cola product traditionally had
been advertised. The Oscars also precedes a big promotion tied to
the next ``Star Wars'' film, she added.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a new spot by Thompson New York from the tea
partners, for Lipton Brisk iced tea, part of the continuing
campaign for that product carrying the theme ``That's Brisk,
baby.'' The spot features animated figurines of Sherman Hemsley and
Isabel Sanford (``The Jeffersons'') in a bizarre battle with a
figurine of the actor Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   In likening the Oscars to the Super Bowl, Ms. Hudson came up
with one more comparison: ``It's amazing how many people think I
have endless tickets to the Academy Awards show. They are very hot
properties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
