<HEADER>
A5789 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-SPI     03-18 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENLIBRA' AN EMERGING PHILOSOPHY IN LAND MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Oregon Gov. John Kitzhaber recently took a top Clinton
administration official to see watershed restoration projects along
the Tualatin River.
</P>
<P>
   The projects included a restored wetland, a stream once enclosed
inside a pipe that is allowed to return to its natural course, tree
trunks placed in the river and seedlings planted on its banks _ all
done with state money by a coalition of local groups. The aim: to
restore the area drained by the river.
</P>
<P>
   Kitzhaber, in his trademark cowboy boots and leather jacket,
touted the citizen-based progress as a Western model of
``Jeffersonian democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not ready to go that far, George Frampton, director of
the White House's Council on Environmental Quality, concedes he was
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people got together and did it themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The watershed work is Kitzhaber's favorite example of
``Enlibra,'' a new philosophy that replaces federal orders and
enforcement with voluntary local collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Kitzhaber has promoted the philosophy as a uniquely
Western approach to resolving environmental issues. The name
Enlibra was coined by Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt, drawn from the
Latin words meaning ``in balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea won bipartisan support, and Washington Gov. Gary Locke
has used elements of it.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury is still out on whether it will sweep the West.
Does devolution of power to the local level herald a bright, new
era of cooperative problem solving _ or does it camouflage a
cowardly retreat from enforcement of federal law?
</P>
<P>
   This week, the debate over how to best manage natural resources
was elevated across the Northwest by the listing of several more
salmon in Oregon and Washington for protection under the Endangered
Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The debate comes as Washington, like Oregon, searches for the
right balance between broad, top-down mandates and local, voluntary
action.
</P>
<P>
   Todd True, a Seattle-based attorney for the Earthjustice Legal
Defense Fund, said, ``the opportunities are ahead of us to make a
success, or duck and look for an easy exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bakke, director of Oregon's Native Fish Society, said
Kitzhaber is ducking a showdown with powerful economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coho plan does more to protect the timber industry than it
does to protect the coho,'' Bakke said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Western Governors Association has hailed it as a
promising new approach in a region where people are groping for new
government structures to solve long-standing problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the Puget Sound, Wash., region, the Tri-County Process, an
alliance among Pierce, Snohomish and King counties, is wrestling
with chinook salmon protection that overlaps their boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the Columbia Basin, the Northwest Power Planning Council's
failures have driven people to experiment with the Columbia Forum
process, a collaboration of states, federal agencies and Indian
tribes.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Enlibra philosophy emerged to fill a vacuum.
Small-government Republicans rule Congress. President Clinton has
declared that the time of big government is over. So who will carry
out the complex reforms needed to preserve fish that permeate most
of the region?
</P>
<P>
   Will Stelle, regional director for the National Marine Fisheries
Service, conceded that his agency lacks local expertise and
personnel to direct salmon habitat improvement on that scale, and
is unlikely to get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too systematic a situation for the federal government
to regulate,'' agreed Frampton. ``The feds really can't tell people
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But the main tools for protecting salmon habitat _ zoning,
building codes, diking, drainage and water systems, logging rules
and the like _ are wielded by states and local governments. Federal
officials say these work better than anything they have to conserve
habitat on private land.
</P>
<P>
   Even if federal shock troops were available and eager for such
jobs, Kitzhaber warns that they would run up against resistance and
thorny property rights claims. Besides, the Oregon governor
believes that a key to salmon recovery is habitat restoration,
which government cannot make people do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relying solely on the (Endangered Species Act) to recover
salmon in Oregon would not only have triggered another divisive
battle, but would ultimately fail to recover salmon,'' Kitzhaber
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, relying instead on voluntary action made a virtue of
necessity. Oregon's GOP-dominated Legislature was in no mood to
slap major new rules on loggers and ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   So in developing his Oregon Plan for salmon restoration,
Kitzhaber took pains to use the carrot of cooperation and avoid the
state and federal stick. He left the bulk of decisions to local
watershed councils that are selected by county governments. They
typically include landowners, industries, environmentalists,
farmers, and tribal, state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Only by involving and energizing these local people, Kitzhaber
said, can the Northwest get action it needs to restore salmon and
streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that a new, more collaborative and less
confrontational approach is needed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon doles out $10 million annually to watershed groups to
conduct restoration projects and recommend changes in land-use
practices and even regulation. They have proved wonderful forums to
educate people and mobilize local action.
</P>
<P>
   What remains unclear is how, and when, state or federal
enforcement kicks in if voluntary efforts fail. Kitzhaber has
balked at backing cooperative plans with threats of a state
crackdown. He leaves the bad cop role to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, in contrast, pledges Washington state will step in with
tougher action after three years _ in part to avoid more onerous
restrictions from federal agencies or courts _ if voluntary efforts
and local government reforms fall short.
</P>
<P>
   Locke has accepted the Enlibra principle of involving local
citizens and interest groups, but does not hesitate to ask counties
and regional government groups to develop recovery plans and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also is pumping money into local watershed councils.
But in a departure from local control, Locke has backed a pact
between county, state and federal agencies, some Indian tribes and
the commercial timber industry to impose new, statewide logging
rules _ before input from citizens or local groups.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for watershed councils are mixed. Veteran observers
say the groups lack expertise, a consistent vision of what they
should achieve, and authority to carry it out. They favor
restoration projects, which are politically easier than imposing
regulations, which impose costs on certain people. And without
regulations to prevent further harm, even good restoration work can
be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, for instance, some watershed councils have dutifully
placed logs in streams to improve salmon habitat even while
timberland owners just upstream have logged almost to the stream
banks, eliminating the source of future stream logs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the value of restoration projects is uncertain. Scientists
have suggested that some may do as much harm as good. They say
prevention of habitat loss is more dependable and less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Kitzhaber also has pledged to write broader water quality plans
and launched collaborative efforts to develop new stream protection
requirements for farmers and timberland owners.
</P>
<P>
   These have yet to bear fruit. Though the timber industry has
pledged $130 million to fix roads that are bleeding sediment into
streams in the Coast Range, it has angrily rejected a costly
federal proposal for new logging restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Where salmon are threatened or endangered, promises won't be
enough to avoid potentially onerous federal restrictions. Last
summer, a federal court made clear that such voluntary efforts and
promises were ``necessarily speculative,'' and not enough to ensure
protection of the coastal coho salmon as the Endangered Species Act
requires. U.S. Magistrate Janice Stewart ordered the coho
protected, and rules to ensure that protection are expected to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Kitzhaber and the federal government initially responded with
outrage, and the governor worried aloud that support for salmon
recovery would evaporate. It didn't, and Kitzhaber and the feds
dropped their appeals and accepted the listing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
