r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      03-18 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, March 19 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOURNALISTS (Seattle) _ As their homeland prepares for
war, two visiting Yugoslavian journalists warned Thursday that
Kosovo's Albanians will suffer the consequences of any NATO
military strike against Serbian targets. ``I think NATO should
seriously consider the consequences of its actions,'' said Dorijan
Nuaj, editor-in-chief of an independent radio station in the Kosovo
capital of Pristina. ``I'd like to ask those NATO generals just
what they think the consequences will be for the Albanians because
they are the ones who are going to suffer the most.''
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Redmond. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-PROTECTION (Seattle) _ Oregon Gov. John Kitzhaber
recently took a top Clinton administration official to see
watershed restoration projects along the Tualatin River. The
projects included a restored wetland, a stream once enclosed inside
a pipe that is allowed to return to its natural course, tree trunks
placed in the river and seedlings planted on its banks _ all done
with state money by a coalition of local groups. The watershed work
is Kitzhaber's favorite example of ``Enlibra,'' a new philosophy
that replaces federal orders and enforcement with voluntary local
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-SPILL (Cordova, Alaska) _ This fishing village was full of
life and promise 10 years ago, just before the oil tanker Exxon
Valdez went aground on Bligh Reef and dumped 11 million gallons of
crude oil into the pristine waters of Prince William Sound. A
decade after the March 24, 1989, oil spill, the largest in U.S.
history, Prince William Sound appears serene and undisturbed, a
sublime sanctuary. But Cordova, the human epicenter of the spill,
still wears the scars of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   With three sidebars: EXXON-COPPER-RIVER, EXXON-TOURISM,
EXXON-NATIVES.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-COPPER-RIVER (Cordova, Alaska) _ Vivid in color and rich
in flavor, sockeye and king salmon from Alaska's Copper River are
to many connoisseurs the finest fish to hit the market in Seattle
each year. The spring delicacy, harvested from shallow, storm-swept
waters at the mouth of Alaska's fifth-largest river system, has
become the sustenance of this isolated fishing town.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-TOURISM (Cordova, Alaska) _ Kevin Quinn, president of
Points North Heli-Adventures, has taken over an abandoned cannery
bunkhouse and is opening remote reaches of the Chugach Mountains to
what he calls some of the world's best spring skiing. He is making
quite a few friends these days because he is investing in this
fishing town that has been hit by economic calamity since the 1989
Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-NATIVES (Cordova, Alaska) _ Her eyes downcast, Eyak native
Pam Smith lamented the sale of tribal land to the Exxon Valdez Oil
Spill Trustee Council. In Smith's view, the need to create a quick
profit has cost natives their birthright and land needed to
maintain their subsistence lifestyle and spiritual traditions.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS (Undated) _ For the past few weeks, the armada of
critics, pundits, Wall Street analysts and Vegas odds-makers who
handicap the Academy Awards have been almost unanimously saying
Sunday night's Oscar Fest is the most wide open of the '90s. That
consensus is beginning to look like an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-TIPS (Undated) _ After years of viewing the Oscars,
whether privately or at a raucous bash, each of us knows pretty
much what to expect. But for anyone seeking a more fulfilling
viewing experience, we offer these guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FARSCAPE (Undated) _ If anyone can't wait till ``Star Wars''
mania officially kicks into warp drive in May, there's always
``Farscape'' on the Sci-Fi Channel.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-EARTHLY (Undated) _ Just to get noticed, familiar stories
need special treatment. In ``Earthly Possessions,'' a pleasant HBO
film based on the Anne Tyler novel, it starts with the casting of
Susan Sarandon in a rare television role. Not a bad beginning.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SWEENEY (Undated) _ Talking head, one-person shows are,
more often than not, tricky balancing acts that turn into
laborious, unsatisfying moviegoing experiences. Fortunately, Julia
Sweeney recounts her very personal experiences in a funny, intimate
film based on her stage show.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-VOYAGE (Undated) _ ``Voyage to the Beginning of the World''
is a meditative, reflective journey through the past. This
prophetically sad film by 91-year-old director Manoel De Oliveira
was Marcello Mastroianni's 171st _ and final _ movie.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RAVENOUS (Undated) _ This darkly funny, subversively arch
horror film is smarter than most. At least for the first hour. But
``Ravenous'' stumbles. It doesn't know what to do with itself or
how to end its story.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HARMONISTS (Undated) _ If you were fortunate enough to
catch the harrowing 1994 German World War II drama, ``Stalingrad,''
you know that its director, Joseph Vilsmaier, has as strong a feel
for genre and character, and as clear an eye for the epic, as any
European filmmaker of this decade. In ``The Harmonists,'' he turns
that eye toward a totally different but no less structured movie
genre: the musical biography.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TRUE-CRIME (Undated) _ Like his last few films,
producer-director-star Clint Eastwood's latest offering, ``True
Crime,'' seems a return to the kind of flimsy storytelling and
sloppy filmmaking that characterized his career in the '80s. More
and more, his 1992 ``Unforgiven'' triumph seems a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column on the NBA season. It's been
wacky _ and ugly _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ Column on the Gonzaga-Florida NCAA
regional basketball semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Peoria, Ariz.) _ Struggling pitcher Ken Cloude
tries to secure the spot tentatively saved for him in the Mariners
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
