<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO TALKS BREAK DOWN, BUT DIPLOMACY GETS ANOTHER WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Kosovo talks at a dead end, and the
Yugoslav leader more recalcitrant than ever, the Clinton
administration was publicly pushing the threat of airstrikes on
Thursday, but officials said they were counting on avoiding
military action with another week of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's policy of using the threat of NATO
airstrikes to force President Sloboban Milosevic to sign a peace
agreement, has failed so far.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of responding to the threats, Milosevic has moved in the
opposite direction, building up his troops in Kosovo to such an
extent that there are now deep concerns about whether the 1,400
international monitors in Kosovo can leave safely before his troops
trap them by sealing their exit route.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as the administration tries to build up pressure among
its NATO allies for bombing, the U.S. military is warning that
airstrikes will not be so easy. Pentagon officials testified on
Thursday that Yugoslav air defenses are quite sophisticated, that
the terrain in Serbia and over Kosovo is difficult and the weather
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the administration's problems is the visit to
Washington starting next Tuesday of the Russian prime minister,
Yevgeny Primakov, one of the few allies that Milosevic has left and
a staunch opponent of NATO airstrikes against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   If any bombing started before Primakov's visit, which is
intended to help repair the frayed Washington-Moscow relationship,
he would certainly cancel. And senior U.S. officials said that it
would be almost impossible to order bombing while Primakov was
still in the United States. He is not due to leave until next
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On the immediate horizon for the administration is the
well-being of the monitors who work under the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, created by the administration's
special envoy, Richard Holbrooke, as part of a cease-fire agreement
with Milosevic last October.
</P>
<P>
   The administration would like the monitors, who include 170
Americans, evacuated over the weekend, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a dramatic move would send a signal to Milosevic that the
West was getting serious about NATO airstrikes, the administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the OSCE, where the United States is one of 54
members but not a decisive voice, control the evacuation decision.
Further, some European diplomats expressed concern that the
evacuation of the monitors could send the wrong signal to
Milosevic. The Yugoslav leader could well take advantage of the
vacuum by taking stronger military action in Kosovo against the
guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, European diplomats said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, which in the event of a peaceful settlement has
offered 4,000 U.S. troops to the envisioned deployment of 28,000
NATO peacekeepers, expressed its concerns on Thursday about an air
campaign. If airstrikes went ahead, it is envisioned that United
States fighter planes would be among the first to attack, NATO
officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force chief of staff, Gen. Michael Ryan, said that
Yugoslav air defenses are well dug in and that there was the
distinct possibility of losing aircraft. The Marine Corps
Commandant, Gen. Charles Krulak, said that ``it is going to be
tremendously dangerous.'' Krulak told the Senate Armed Services
Committee that there were still ``some bottom-line questions'' that
needed to be answered about air strikes. He listed them as: ``What
is the endgame? How long will the strikes go on? Will our allies
stay with us?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pentagon planners have said that the air defenses of the
Yugoslav military are far superior to those of the Bosnian Serbs,
who were hit four years ago during a NATO air campaign, and indeed
far superior to those of Saddam Hussein in Iraq. On the diplomatic
front, administration officials said they were not necessarily
optimistic about the results of more visits by Western officials to
Milosevic in the coming week but that diplomacy had to be
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not feasible to shut down the peace talks in Paris and
then bomb,'' said one administration official.
</P>
<P>
   There is no consensus among the top administration policy makers
on Kosovo about who should attempt to negotiate with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has no appetite to go,
because there is little guarantee of a positive outcome, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The energy secretary, Bill Richardson, has been mentioned within
administration circles, apparently because the Belgrade regime has
said it would welcome him.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who still faces hearings on his nomination as chief
delegate to the United Nations, had to get special dispensation
from Sen. Jesse Helms to go to Belgrade last week, and the
administration is reluctant to ask for the favor again, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   And as the administration discusses who to send as its envoy,
the Europeans are contemplating sending the co-hosts of the failed
peace talks, the French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine, and the
British foreign minister, Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a successful outcome of talks with Milosevic
looked slim. When the German foreign minister, Joschka Fischer,
offered Milosevic a menu of economic concessions, including the
lifting of trade sanctions, the Yugoslav leader shunted him aside
and went ahead with his troop build-up. Similarly, the Russian
foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, went to Belgrade last weekend and
came away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov went out of his way on Thursday to urge Milosevic to sign
the political document that was signed by the ethnic Albanians
Thursday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The administration ran into trouble on Capitol Hill Thursday
when Albright and Secretary of Defense William Cohen gave
closed-door briefings to both members of the House and Senate on
their Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who is a supporter of
airstrikes, said that he believed the administration was on the
right course but that President Clinton needed to personally better
explain the policy.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, there was so much dissatisfaction with the
briefings, that a bill offered by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, giving qualified support to the administration's plan of
deployment of NATO troops will be replaced by another much tougher
measure.
</P>
<P>
   A bill sponsored by Sen. Robert Smith, R-N.H., calling for the
withholding of congressional funds for U.S. troops in Kosovo until
Congress approves the deployment, will replace Ms. Hutchison's
proposal, Senate Republicans said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
