<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-LOANS-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN SAYS LOANS TO RUSSIA MAY HAVE BEEN USED `IMPROPERLY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told a
congressional panel Thursday that he suspected that much of the
$4.8 billion in loans sent to Russia last summer by the
International Monetary Fund ``may have been siphoned off
improperly.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Clinton administration's first public statement
supporting accusations that bailout money simply helped wealthy
Russian oligarchs move billions of dollars to Switzerland and other
safe havens.
</P>
<P>
   Financial regulators note that a huge flow of dollars left
Russia immediately after the monetary fund's cash was delivered to
the Russian central bank, suggesting investors were getting out
before the ruble was permitted to collapse on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Rubin's comments was particularly significant
because Russia's prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, arrives here in
five days on a mission to obtain the next installment of $22
billion in loans. It is unclear whether he will succeed, though
there is growing pressure on the IMF to lend Russia just enough
money to allow it to pay back several billion dollars that it owes
to the fund in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has been publicly pushing the move, which amounts to
accounting sleight-of-hand, for two months now, chiefly because it
would keep Russia from formal default.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin suggested Thursday that, despite endemic corruption and
Primakov's seeming inability to put together an economic plan, the
United States still had an interest in financially aiding the
country. The United States has the largest block of votes within
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Russia destabilizes, the costs to the United States are
going to be vastly greater than anything we can think of,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   After his testimony before a House appropriations subcommittee,
Rubin once again deflected reports that he might be planning to
resign. Such reports have sprung up repeatedly in recent years and
resurfaced after the conclusion of President Clinton's impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The relative calm in the world economy has contributed to the
revival of the rumors. And this week, the Treasury Department
announced that Rubin would not be attending an annual meeting of
Asian finance ministers in May, and would send his deputy, Lawrence
Summers, instead. The department said the meeting conflicted with
Rubin's commitments to make several commencement addresses.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation Thursday after his appearance before the House
panel, Rubin qualified his testimony by saying that ``it may have
been careless to use the word `improper''' because ``there is
nothing improper about moving money out of Russia or any other
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the capital flight may have helped buy
time for a group of Russia's wealthiest and most powerful business
executives _ who suspected the government would soon devalue the
ruble, and wanted to get their rubles converted into dollars
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The money from the fund, along with some funds from the World
Bank, went to the Russian central bank. And the bank spent it to
intervene in the markets and buy rubles for several weeks. Some
money may also have been provided to banks, giving their clients
access to dollars in return for ruble deposits. The result was that
the $4.8 billion was quickly drained away, and a similar amount
appeared in overseas bank accounts. This could have been avoided
only with capital controls, rules that prevent taking money out of
the country, which the United States has rarely supported in recent
years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Money is fungible,'' said Rubin, ``so it is hard to say
exactly what happened to it. I can't tell you exactly what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter experience of last July, though, has left the IMF
wary about making a second installment of the loan to Primakov's
government. Some fear that giving Russia more money than it
currently owes would invite a repetition of the capital flight.
Moreover, Russia has made scant progress on economic reforms that
the fund could seize upon as a reason for new loans.
</P>
<P>
   The budget Russia adopted recently is considered largely
unrealistic by both American officials and the fund itself. There
has been little progress on tax collection in Russia, the IMF says,
and just the other day the Russian Parliament cut a value-added
tax, angering fund officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are also angry. They argue that the fund's
conditions are far too stringent and will contribute to the
country's recession. The fund's managing director, Michel
Camdessus, engaged in an unusual public exchange with Primakov's
aides several weeks ago, and another top IMF official told the
Trilateral Commission here this weekend that Russia's government is
so weak that its economic commitments cannot be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, while more elliptical, made a similar point Thursday in
his testimony. ``If Russia is going to have a successful economy,
there are going to have to be a whole host of reforms that provide
the framework for a market economy,'' Rubin told the House
subcommittee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
