<HEADLINE>
TOURISM MAKING MODEST INROADS IN CORDOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Photos available through the Wieck Database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORDOVA, Alaska _ With his headband, long, curly hair and
cocksure manner, Kevin Quinn looks like someone more comfortable on
the ski slopes at Whistler in British Columbia or Big Sky in
Montana than in a Prince William Sound salmon cannery.
</P>
<P>
   But Quinn, president of Points North Heli-Adventures, has taken
over an abandoned cannery bunkhouse and is opening remote reaches
of the Chugach Mountains to what he calls some of the world's best
spring skiing.
</P>
<P>
   He is making quite a few friends these days because he is
investing in this fishing town that has been hit by economic
calamity since the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are bringing a new venue to Cordova,'' said Quinn, pointing
to the vast wild reaches of the Scott and Sheridan glaciers behind
Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the town's most ardent environmentalists are
blessing the venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's non-extractive; they've done their best to fit into this
community,'' said Kelly Weaverling, a bookstore owner who made
history here by being the first mayor in the United States elected
on the Green Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Other Southeast Alaska coastal communities have been transformed
into tourist havens. Juneau, the capital, plays host to more than
500,000 cruise-ship passengers each spring and summer. With its
colorful, bawdy history of the Klondike gold rush, Skagway draws
7,000 summer visitors a day, mostly off cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova remains a fishing village to the core. Nonetheless, it
draws about 10,000 visitors a year but is wary of being overrun by
more.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,500 tourists stopped in Cordova on cruise ships last
summer. They arrived twice a week on a schedule that locals could
tolerate. The visitors spent about $400,000, touring the Childs
Glacier and taking in the region's natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, some tour operators keep guests almost hermetically
sealed off in company-owned ships, hotels, railroad cars and even
buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industrial tourism doesn't leave money,'' said David Grimes,
who runs a rafting-outdoor adventure company.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness and nature-based tourism seems more welcome in
Cordova than a daily dose of cruise-ship passengers. A shorebird
festival each May has begun to draw ornithologists to see one of
the world's great concentrations of migratory birds. The Chugach
National Forest has fly-in cabins for rent.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, however, the picturesque, hard-working fishing
community has not marketed itself as a tourism destination.
</P>
<P>
   Points North Heli-Adventures Inc. could change that. Quinn is
touting ``adventures beyond dreams'' for skiers and promises a
summer operation that will airlift hikers to glaciers and
mountaintops.
</P>
<P>
   Will it work? Quinn needs Cordova, as much as or more than
Cordova needs him.
</P>
<P>
   Huge glaciers are fed by huge storms. On days when flying is
impossible, the helicopter adventure company will need to take its
guests sea kayaking, fishing or to the Mount Eyak ski area above
town.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there have been grumbles about showoff, hot-dog skiing
by Points North guides at Mount Eyak, which is equipped with a
rebuilt, 1930s-vintage chair lift that once carried Clark Gable up
the slopes of Sun Valley, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Until fishing recovers, if it recovers, tourism is about the
only way Cordova can grow. The locals vow to keep it under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cordova will always be a fishing town,'' said Dune Lankard, an
Eyak native and fisherman turned conservationist. ``Why make it a
metropolis? If you like Skagway or Juneau, move there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
