<HEADLINE>
COPPER RIVER AN ECONOMIC LIFELINE FOR CORDOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Photos available through the Wieck Database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 30 miles east of Cordova, the Copper River is a notorious
funnel of high winds from the state's interior matched only by the
ferocity of incoming storms off the Gulf of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys go home; the men stay around,'' said Robby Maxwell,
who makes fishing nets in the winter and navigates the Copper
River's shallows each spring.
</P>
<P>
   The mouth of the Copper River is the centerpiece to a
700,000-acre wetland that is the largest on the continent. ``The
Copper River Delta is the crown jewel of North America's
wetlands,'' marine biologist and gillnetter Dr. Riki Ott wrote in
her recent book ``Alaska's Copper River Delta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in Grays Harbor (Wash.), you see about 1 million
migrating shorebirds each year. We get 12 million of the same
species. It is the key spring staging area along the Pacific coast
of North and South America,'' said Pete Mikkelson, a retired
University of Alaska waterfowl biologist who runs an educational
retreat called Alaska Wild Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting the Copper River from industrial development has
become almost an obsession with fishermen and other residents of
Cordova. The Copper also has been championed by national
conservation groups, which are campaigning for a public purchase of
mineral and logging rights on native-owned land east of the river.
</P>
<P>
   From 1911 to 1938, the Copper River was the scene of major
development. The Copper River and Northwestern Railway was built to
carry copper ore from the upstream Kennecott mines to Cordova on
the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Copper River Delta today is protected as part of the
Chugach National Forest or as state critical wildlife habitat. But
since the copper mine closed 60 years ago, development proposals
have never died. They include:
</P>
<P>
   __The road: In the early 1990s, using ``highway maintenance''
money, Republican Gov. Wally Hickel started to bulldoze a road down
the old railroad bed. It would have linked Cordova to the
Anchorage-Valdez highway and the rest of the state. Opponents
feared the road would bring hundreds of sport fishermen to compete
for salmon with the town's commercial fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   But Cordova is not equipped to handle any influx of sightseers
and day-trippers. ``We have only one public bathroom,'' said Dune
Lankard, an Eyak native and outspoken conservationist.
</P>
<P>
   The road project was halted in court by the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers, which found more than 100 violations of federal
environmental and wetlands laws. But boosters still want it built.
</P>
<P>
   __The trail: Current Alaska Gov. Tony Knowles, a Democrat, wants
to create a recreation trail from tiny Chitina through the Copper
River wilderness and on to Cordova. Flanked by the Chugach Mountain
Range, running close to the snouts of great glaciers, the project
is being touted as North America's equivalent of the legendary
Milford Trek in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a destination point in and of itself for people who
want to see some of the world's most spectacular scenery,'' Knowles
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The project has its critics. ``There already is a world-class
trail: It is the Copper River,'' said David Grimes, who runs a
rafting company called Br'er Rabbit World Wide Escapades, Larks and
Adventures.
</P>
<P>
   __The logging project: The Chugach Alaska Corp., a native-owned
corporation set up under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act,
has proposed a 60-mile logging road from the river's delta to reach
mineral rights and 8,000 acres of old-growth forest it owns east of
the Copper River. The road would cross at least 100 salmon-spawning
streams.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, tried but failed last year to get
congressional approval to fund the road traversing national forest
lands.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are pressing Chugach Alaska to agree on a
conservation easement, which would let the native corporation keep
title to the land but sell all development rights, possibly to the
federal government, effectively precluding logging.
</P>
<P>
   The National Wildlife Federation argues that money from Exxon's
$900 million oil spill settlement should be used to buy up the
development rights. The proposed road and logging are about 70
miles east of Prince William Sound. A state-federal trustee council
has used settlement money to preserve about 650,000 acres of
sensitive habitat in the area of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the bird and mammal populations we are trying to
nurse back to health in Prince William Sound also rely on the
Copper River Delta,'' said Tony Turrini, Alaska director of the
National Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   A major conference on the future of the Copper River Delta,
sponsored by the U.S. Forest Service, will be held in Cordova early
in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
