<HEADLINE>
DOW CROSSES 10,000 AGAIN, THEN SLIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They huffed and they puffed, but U.S. stock traders
still couldn't push the Dow Jones industrial average to close above
10,000 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of a flurry of late buying, which propelled the average
to 10,001.50 just minutes before trading ended, the Dow finished at
9,997.62, an increase of 118.21 points. The rally, which took the
average to a new closing high, added 1.2 percent to its value.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also closed at a new high
Thursday, rising 18.73 points to 1,316.55, an increase of 1.44
percent. The Nasdaq composite index also had a good session, rising
33.99 points, or 1.4 percent, to 2,462.96, though it remains short
of the high of 2,510.09 it set on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of good news Thursday to make traders
ebullient. The Consumer Price Index stayed dormant in February,
rising one-tenth of 1 percent on falling prices for apparel and
fuel oil. And the report that third-quarter earnings by FDX Corp.,
the parent of Federal Express, more than quadrupled those of the
same period a year earlier, heartened investors worried that stock
valuations are outpacing earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the recent spike in oil prices and rising bond yields
concern some investors. ``Maybe the reason we're having such a hard
time breaking through this magic number is we're having real
powerful conflicting forces,'' said Douglas Cliggott, U.S. equity
strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities. ``On the plus side, the
earnings news is getting better. Over the long term that drives
stock prices. But the upward drift in bond yields is the bad
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the late move in stocks came from two unlikely quarters:
tobacco stocks and options traders.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 3 p.m., it was reported that a federal jury in Akron,
Ohio, had concluded that tobacco companies were not liable for $2
billion in damages sought by union health and benefit plans in that
state for the costs of treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Philip Morris Cos., the third-biggest mover in the
Dow, rose 3 3/4, to 42. Those of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., parent
of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, gained 1 11/16 to close at 30 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Another push for stocks came from traders who had bet against
the S&AMP;P's rising and then had to buy back the S&AMP;P options they had
previously sold.
</P>
<P>
   This buying was particularly strong at the end of the session
because March-dated options expired Thursday. If the traders had
not covered their positions, they would have been extremely
vulnerable to even higher stock prices Friday. But they waited
until the last possible moment to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that the buying couldn't prop the Dow average
beyond 10,000 again shows that there are many traders eager to sell
stock when the milestone is reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The psychological barrier is going to be real at 10,000
because every investor in a Dow portfolio has a profit,'' Alan
Kral, portfolio manager at Trevor, Stewart, Burton &AMP; Jacobsen in
New York, said. ``Until those people who are triggered to act by
the number 10,000 are done, there will be volatility here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
