</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE COMMITTEE PASSES GOP BUDGET; MEDICARE STILL A STICKING
POINT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Okla., S.D.)   (rk) 
 By   RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Budget Committee approved the Republican
tax and spending plan Thursday as the Clinton administration and
congressional Democrats stepped up their attacks on the measure and
labeled it irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   The committee sent the fiscal blueprint to the full Senate on a
11-to-9 vote along party lines after three days of debate. Both the
House and the Senate will vote on the plan next week, and unlike
last year, when the Republican Party was split over how hard to
push for tax cuts, Republicans appear united and all but certain to
adopt the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for setting aside $1.8 trillion of the projected
$2.6 trillion surplus over the next decade for Social Security and
using the rest for tax cuts. It would increase spending for the
military and for education, but would require cuts in a array of
other programs to remain within spending limits established in the
1997 bipartisan budget deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., who is chairman of the budget
committee, said the priorities set out in the bill were ``very,
very good'' and would allow Congress to do a better job of
addressing the nation's long-term problems than would the
Democratic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the Republican plan risked a return to deficits
by committing the country to sweeping tax cuts before the surpluses
actually materialized. They also denounced it for failing to set
aside any money explicitly for Medicare, the health insurance
system for the elderly, which faces insolvency in about a decade as
the population ages and medical costs increase.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore took the lead in attacking the plan
Thursday, saying it would work no better than Reagan administration
budgets in the early 1980s that promised tax cuts and increased
Pentagon spending but that led to huge deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried this kind of budget before and it nearly wrecked
the United States,'' Gore told a group of black newspaper
publishers at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pours hundreds of billions of dollars into open-ended,
extremely risky tax schemes, just sort of like a roulette table,''
Gore said. ``And that means the cupboard is bare when it comes to
saving Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans struck back by accusing Democrats of playing
politics with Medicare and blocking bipartisan efforts to put the
system on sounder financial footing. They said the key to
preserving Medicare in the long run was overhauling the system to
reduce costs. Also, Republicans said their budget would do more
than the president's to wall off Social Security's money and reduce
the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan calls for $350 billion to be set aside for
Medicare over the next decade, and $1.33 trillion to be set aside
for Social Security. The Republican plan, while setting aside $1.8
trillion for Social Security over the same period, does not earmark
any specific funds for Medicare other than $133 billion in the
Senate version that could be used for a variety of contingencies,
including Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find efforts by House Democrats to manipulate and frighten
older Americans by deliberately mischaracterizing our
accomplishments in the name of politics and demagoguery to be
deeply disappointing,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the
chairman of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats hammered away at their theme that the tax cuts
would come at the expense of Medicare and other domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide ever-growing tax breaks at the expense of
Medicare, our domestic priorities and debt reduction,'' said Sen.
Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader in the Senate.
``Or we can invest today to guarantee our health and retirement
security, pay down the debt, educate the next generation and make
our future more secure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
