<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILWATCH-COX     03-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILWATCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RailWatch comes under fire
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the nonprofit group RailWatch was launched this
winter, it claimed support from ``more than 300 public officials''
concerned about rail safety problems.
</P>
<P>
   At a Washington news conference in February, the group issued a
report titled ``Why is there a train accident every 90 minutes?''
It demanded action by Congress, which holds hearings on rail issues
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the public officials, including at least two in
Georgia, say they had no idea they were joining RailWatch when they
left their names at a convention booth in Kansas City, Mo., last
year.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the group has a quiet corporate backer: United
Parcel Service, the Atlanta-based shipping giant, which is both a
rail customer and competitor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, RailWatch has drawn as much attention to its own
tactics and motives _ and to the way special interest lobbying
sometimes works _ as to legitimate concerns about rail safety.
</P>
<P>
   UPS, working with a California public relations firm, helped
start RailWatch and provides financial support, spokesman Norman
Black confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither RailWatch nor UPS would reveal the extent of the
company's backing. But Ken Churchill, UPS vice president for public
affairs, is the only corporate representative on the group's board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
   UPS didn't participate in RailWatch's kickoff and isn't
mentioned in an ``About RailWatch'' section on its Internet site.
After media inquiries about the group's origins, however, the
section was reworded to add unnamed ``shippers from around the
country'' as backers.
</P>
<P>
   Black said UPS hasn't tried to hide its support but isn't
involved in how RailWatch is presented, despite having a seat on
its board and helping fund its activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not defensive in any way about our support of
RailWatch,'' Black said. On the other hand, he said, ``It's not an
organization we run.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would UPS help launch an attack on rail safety?
</P>
<P>
   Black said UPS has a general interest in transportation safety
and a financial interest in reliable rail service. It spends more
than $500 million a year having trailers moved by rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we've got 50 trailers on a train that goes down or is
delayed for some safety-related reason, we have a huge liability,''
Black said. ``And it doesn't even have to be that train, because a
safety problem on one slows down many others.''
</P>
<P>
   Service snarls that followed last year's merger of two big
systems, Burlington Northern and Sante Fe, heightened UPS'
discontent.
</P>
<P>
   The company's differences with railroads don't stop there. UPS,
which has a large long-haul truck fleet, wants limits on
triple-trailer trucks relaxed. The public relations firm that set
up RailWatch also runs another UPS-supported group advocating
relaxed limits, according to the industry journal Traffic World.
</P>
<P>
   The rail industry opposes bigger trucks because it would lose
business to them. It has supported lobbying groups such as
Coalition Against Bigger Trucks and Citizens for Reliable and Safe
Highways, or CRASH.
</P>
<P>
   Black, however, said UPS didn't help start RailWatch to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joined because our network depends on the railroads,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   UPS's role in RailWatch came to light after questions about the
authenticity of the list of local officials the group claimed as
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the list was compiled at a National League of Cities
convention in Kansas City in December. Officials who stopped by a
RailWatch booth could leave their names to get more materials.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Fox, executive director of Houston-based RailWatch, said
the booth was clearly marked as soliciting supporters. She said
visitors who left their names got follow-up materials stating they
would be listed.
</P>
<P>
   But after RailWatch's kickoff, some local officials told the
Houston Chronicle they had no idea they were on any list. Numerous
others told Traffic World and The Washington Post the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Toccoa Mayor James Neal, one of 16 Georgians named, said he,
too, was mystified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I wasn't appointed, and I don't remember being asked
to join,'' he said when contacted by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The same went for Calhoun city Councilman John Shelton, who
added: ``My family is basic railroad people. I'm not interested in
(the group's activities). I won't be party to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal said he went to the convention and may have left a business
card, though he doesn't remember doing so. ``I stop at booths all
the time and leave cards,'' he said. ``If leaving a card there was
tantamount to joining, I guess I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toccoa mayor said he didn't know about UPS' backing until
told by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hendrie of the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington
said launching a special interest group and then enlisting broad
public support is known as Astroturf lobbying _ meaning artificial
grass roots are used to add credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not new, but it is certainly a growing
phenomenon,'' Hendrie said. ``The intent is to create a bandwagon
effect by presenting a long list of supporters with no financial
stake. It also tends to get more favorable news coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said there was no attempt to create false support. She said
the group, which also includes rail accident victims and other
concerned citizens, is a product of sincere concerns that happen to
coincide with those of UPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a coalition of real people who have real concerns about
rail safety,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she regrets any confusion caused by the group's method
of enlisting supporters. She said a few officials have asked to be
removed from the supporters list, adding the entire list is being
re-compiled.
</P>
<P>
   Fox suggested railroad interests are behind attacks on RailWatch
``to divert attention to their safety record, which is not entirely
unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said UPS has ``made it clear to RailWatch that we were
very disappointed'' with the way the list of public officials was
handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the railroads to know UPS is part of this group and
they better understand why,'' he said. ``It's because they have a
lousy safety record in certain corridors of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom White, spokesman for the Association of American Railroads,
said RailWatch's initial report was ``pretty shoddy work and makes
an awful lot of unwarranted statements. It totally ignores the fact
the rail industry is the safest it's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on RailWatch's origin or methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we know is what we read about them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
