<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5809 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-PESTILLO-     03-18 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-PESTILLO-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE LABOR PEACE AT FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)  
 (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ When General Motors Corp. was paralyzed by a
54-day strike last summer, several Wall Street analysts offered the
same solution: GM's leaders should go to the home of Peter J.
Pestillo, the longtime labor czar of Ford Motor Co., and offer him
any sum of money, no matter how large, to fix their problems.
</P>
<P>
   GM never took this unsolicited advice, and the strike cost it $2
billion in after-tax profits. But Wall Street's perspective
highlighted the reputation of Pestillo, one of the most influential
yet little known executives in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, he has set labor policy for Ford and
indirectly for the entire auto industry, and, by extension,
influenced wages and costs across a wide range of industries. By
encouraging factory managers to work closely with workers and union
leaders, he has helped bring Ford's quality close to Japanese
levels.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Pestillo has quietly come to dominate auto
industry lobbying, playing a role in issues from air pollution to
fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Ford has not had a single strike in the
United States since 1986. By comparison, GM's strike-related losses
in the last three years approach the Microsoft Corp.'s entire sales
and profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his power, Pestillo, who will turn 61 on Monday, has
worked almost entirely behind the scenes. Like the invisible man of
Hollywood movies, whose presence can be inferred by his effect on
nearby objects, Pestillo has influenced Ford's recent success yet
has seldom appeared in public.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pestillo is being dragged reluctantly into the limelight. An
executive vice president for years, he became Ford's vice chairman
and chief of staff at the beginning of this year when a longtime
ally, William C. Ford Jr., became Ford's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Pestillo also became the chairman of the auto
industry's new lobbying arm, the Alliance of Automobile
Manufacturers, which has replaced the defunct American Automobile
Manufacturers Association. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pestillo may draw more attention in coming months. The United
Automobile Workers' three-year labor contracts with Ford, GM and
DaimlerChrysler AG will expire in September. The UAW's triennial
convention to draw up bargaining positions will open next Sunday,
the start of the negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare interview, Pestillo said that he believed his relative
anonymity had helped him, particularly in his many talks with the
UAW. ``To the extent you're less public, you can be more effective
in private,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most auto company labor negotiators are former factory managers
with MBAs, but Pestillo has a different background. The son of a
union machinist, he grew up in Plainville, Conn., and worked his
first summer after high school at a ball bearing company, where he
was a dues-paying member of the UAW.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Fairfield University, he worked his way
through Georgetown University's law school in Washington by holding
a series of government jobs, including one as a Capitol policeman.
</P>
<P>
   The many hours of guarding Congress coincided with his course in
labor law and contributed to a lifelong fascination with politics,
both at the national level and within unions.
</P>
<P>
   After stints at General Electric and B.F. Goodrich, Pestillo
came to Ford in 1980, and has been running its labor policy ever
since. He has worked to transform the way Ford factories are run,
transferring responsibility to assembly line workers.
</P>
<P>
   He has also forced out factory managers who could not get along
with workers or the union. ``In the old days, they were happy to
have loads of union grievances and disciplinary actions to prove
how tough they were,'' Pestillo said. ``Now we measure how
effective they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Harbour and Associates, a manufacturing consulting
firm, reported that Ford ran 4 of the nation's 10 most productive
car factories and 7 of the 10 most productive light truck
factories. (Japanese automakers operated most of the rest.)
</P>
<P>
   The UAW traditionally negotiates a three-year agreement with one
automaker and then demands that the others accept the same deal.
For most of the last 20 years, the union has gone to Ford first
because of its cooperative relationship, and Pestillo has used this
opportunity to negotiate deals that have cut Ford's costs but done
little to help its rival, GM.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers can now pay much lower wages, for instance, to
workers in their first three years of employment. Ford has been
hiring thousands to build its popular sport utility vehicles, but
GM has been thinning through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto industry leaders dispute how much credit Pestillo
deserves for keeping Ford free of strikes. Richard G. Wagoner Jr.,
the president of GM, said Pestillo had an easy task because Ford
closed unneeded factories in the early 1980s and has been expanding
since. ``I'm not aware of any special magic he has,'' Wagoner said.
</P>
<P>
   But that view remains a minority opinion. Indeed, John F. Smith
Jr., GM's chairman and chief executive, said in a separate
interview that Ford seemed to have benefited from Pestillo's close
relationship with the UAW and its current president, Stephen P.
Yokich.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich said that while his union maintained a businesslike
relationship with Ford, he considered Pestillo a friend, someone
with whom he enjoyed having a beer, playing golf or simply talking.
``That's the best reason we get along,'' he said. ``We both can
laugh at each other and enjoy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
