<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SPITZER'S INQUIRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 19:
</P>
<P>
   The police shooting last month of the West African immigrant
Amadou Diallo is provoking ever-larger protests. Well-televised
arrests at One Police Plaza trumpet the message that many New
Yorkers believe the steep drop in crime has been accompanied by an
increase in police harassment of minorities. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
says the demonstrations are being conducted ``for a highly partisan
political purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that nonviolent sit-ins have become an
established form of dissent when communities confront polarizing
issues, and orderly protests can challenge elected officials to
respond to civic concerns they might otherwise ignore. The fact
that the American Jewish Committee has joined with black officials
in questioning police conduct shows that worries about New York's
policing practices cross racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   In this context of community concern, the response of New York
state's attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, was appropriate. Spitzer
announced a civil rights investigation into allegations that the
police frisk many blacks and other minorities without
justification. Giuliani, while angry at the demonstrators,
correctly recognized Spitzer's right to conduct an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said that during his campaign for the
office last year he began hearing that New York City police were
targeting nonwhites for improper searches. The complaints became
more vocal and public after Feb. 4, when Diallo was killed in a
fusillade of gunfire from four white police officers. A grand jury
in the Bronx and federal prosecutors are investigating the
shooting. The U.S. Civil Rights Commission has announced plans to
hold hearings. What could distinguish the Spitzer investigation,
however, is that it is focused narrowly enough to analyze police
data quickly and make useful recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The Street Crimes Unit, whose officers were involved in the
shooting, has been credited with lowering the murder rate by taking
large numbers of illegal handguns off the street. Street Crimes
police also stop many more people than they arrest, frisking 27,000
last year and arresting 4,600. The attorney general will need to
determine whether this unit has followed police guidelines, which
allow frisking only if the officer ``reasonably suspects'' that a
person could endanger police or others.
</P>
<P>
   For Spitzer, who was elected last year by a slim margin, using
the civil rights powers of his office to look at this crucial issue
is a bold move. It would be easy for his political enemies to label
this investigation as anti-police. But as Spitzer has said
correctly, this inquiry, if done well, is ``good for cops'' because
it can help rebuild the city's faith in the methods of its Police
Department. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
