<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-ADVANCE19-CO     03-18 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-ADVANCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get the point, people?
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Late last summer, Duke's Will Avery
pulled an article off the Internet that included a list of college
basketball's best point guards. His name was nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It named everybody _ Mateen Cleaves (of Michigan State),
Arthur Lee (of Stanford) _ all those guys,'' Avery said. ``I
thought I could play with any of them and, if I worked hard, I
could play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery attached the article to the mirror on his dresser so that
he would see it every day. Why? ``I like a challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Every preseason story about Duke contained the following
sentence, in one form or another: ``Duke will go to the Final Four
and play for the national championship if William Avery can handle
the point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I read every one,'' Avery said. ``It was definitely a
motivating factor for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a junior at Augusta's Westside High, Avery was a superstar on
the court but didn't have the grades to go to Duke, his first
choice. Coach Mike Krzyzewski told him flat out: Shape up
academically or look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge. Avery went to Virginia's Oak Hill Academy,
got his act together and was accepted to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I would never make it into Duke, but I
proved them wrong,'' he said. ``I shocked a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenges are obviously the fuel that keeps the sophomore's
motor running, and, since ascending to the starting job at Duke, he
has played as well as any point guard in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Doubt it? Duke (34-1), which plays Southwest Missouri State in
tonight's East Regional semifinals, has two national player of the
year candidates in Elton Brand and Trajan Langdon. On Thursday,
when asked to pick Duke's MVP for this season, each picked Avery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything starts with Will,'' said Langdon, the only senior
among the starting five. ``He's the guy who breaks down the
defenses and puts pressure on the other team. If things aren't
going well offensively, he can create something without running a
play. He brings an unpredictability to what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the guys who have had special years for us, Will's has
been the most special,'' Krzyzewski said. ``He gives us some things
we haven't had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery's numbers are impressive. He is the team's third-leading
scorer (15.1), its assists leader (5.3) and has averaged more
minutes per game (30.7) than any other Duke player.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers do not begin to tell how Avery's play has
transformed Duke from what was a talented, but methodical, team a
year ago to one that now can physically dominate opponents on both
ends of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays from last week's second-round game with Tulsa
illustrate it best.
</P>
<P>
   On one possession, Tulsa was playing its very best defense,
making sure the powerful Brand did not get the ball inside. As the
shot clock ticked down, Avery simply stopped running the offense
and launched a 3-pointer from well beyond the NBA arc. The ball
went through as the shot clock expired. Later, Avery recovered a
loose ball 70 feet from the basket. Tulsa had three defenders back
but Avery blew past all three for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't be that good!'' CBS analyst Al McGuire screamed after
the play.
</P>
<P>
   But Avery is that good, and he's doing it at a place where point
guards are basketball royalty. The list of great ones includes
Tommy Amaker, Quin Snyder and Bobby Hurley. None of them could make
plays like Avery.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got him, we knew he was good, but we never dreamed he
would be this good, this fast,'' Krzyzewski said. ``And he's only
going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery has gotten so good, so fast, that Duke fans now wonder if
he will jump to the NBA if the Blue Devils win the national
championship. Avery insists he'll be back at Duke next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked too hard to get here,'' he said. ``Besides, I'm
having too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
