<SLUG> BC-COANGLERS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hooked on chance to fish with best
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Bud Goeke, retired at the age of 40, already
is the envy of most middle-agers. So what would spur the
Pinckneyville, Ill., family man to drive nearly nine hours on the
chance of fulfilling a dream?
</P>
<P>
   His proud young son.
</P>
<P>
   Goeke, one of the 165 anglers competing in the co-angler _ or
amateur _ division of this week's Wal-Mart FLW Tour bass tournament
at Lake Lanier, had pretty much decided he wasn't going to come
South with no assurance that he'd be able to fish in the richest
tournament in Georgia history. That was until 10-year-old Brandon,
who knows who most of the sport's top stars are, got involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told all of his friends we were coming to this
tournament,'' said Goeke, who was able to retire two years ago from
Caterpillar because of investments he made in a pizza restaurant
and rental property. ``He really wanted to come. I couldn't let him
down.''
</P>
<P>
   So Goeke packed up the car Tuesday morning and, with Brandon,
his wife Susan and 7-year-old daughter Katlyn, headed for Atlanta
from the southern Illinois town to make it to the pretournament
meeting later in the day. At best, he was told he'd be second or
third on the waiting list and would need that many no-shows to be
able to fish alongside the anglers he watches every week on those
TV fishing shows.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
