<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOREAN PRESIDENT LIFTS STATE OF EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Eager to avoid prolonging the strikes and
economic turmoil that have paralyzed this country since the
beginning of the month, President Jamil Mahuad Thursday lifted the
state of emergency he imposed last week and rolled back drastic
increases in gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   In return, opposition parties agreed to approve an austerity
package that Mahuad estimated will increase revenues by $520
million. The legislators also consented to an unpopular
presidential decree that freezes half of most bank accounts for as
long as a year.
</P>
<P>
   News of the accord was followed here by a marked relaxation of
the tensions in this Andean nation of 12 million that had
threatened to topple Mahuad's young government. Taxi drivers
removed barriers that had blocked many streets since Monday, and
some shops opened for the first time this week.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, lines formed for fuel at the new price of
about $1.20 a gallon, a huge drop from last week's $2.33 a gallon
(calculated at Thursday's exchange rate), but still above its
original 89 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   At a pre-dawn news conference at the presidential palace here,
Mahuad said that legislators would probably vote on the austerity
package soon and called on Ecuadoreans to ``return to peace and to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   With nearly $3 billion in damages caused by El Nino, along with
low oil prices and the highest inflation rate in Latin America,
Ecuador had been struggling with an economic crisis even before
Mahuad, a 49-year-old Harvard-educated lawyer, took office in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Several bank failures led him to declare a weeklong bank holiday
on March 8 and a 60-day emergency the next day. The Ecuadorean
currency, the sucre, nearly disintegrated as savers rushed to buy
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was announced hours after the powerful Ecuadorean
military made its first statement on the issue, which pointedly
reminded quarreling civilian elites of ``the very serious
responsibility weighing upon them'' and urged lawmakers to ``reach
the solutions which the Ecuadorean people urgently demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad was able to obtain the agreement by stitching together a
tenuous coalition in the Ecuadorean Congress. His Popular
Democratic Party had been in an alliance with the conservative
Social Christian Party, but that group abandoned him this week
after condemning the austerity measures as ``inhuman.''
</P>
<P>
   The new coalition brings together nine parties from the
center-right to the far left. They account for total of 70 of the
121 seats in Congress, but the alliance appears to veteran
political analysts to be unwieldy, unworkable and unlikely to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very complicated cocktail, one that I cannot see
functioning in the long term,'' Rodrigo Paz, a former finance
minister and mayor of Quito, said. ``All the classic problems of
Ecuadorean politics could emerge again, because it is much easier
to form an association with one party than with five or six that
have diverse ideologies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
