<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5818 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSILE-HOUSE-HNS &LR;      03-18 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-HOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE JOINS SENATE IN APPROVING MISSILE-DEFENSE SYSTEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House joined the Senate on Thursday in voting
to develop and deploy a nationwide missile-defense system capable
of intercepting long-range nuclear warheads fired on the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But while the House vote of 317-105, and the Senate vote
Wednesday of 97-3, embraced the idea of anti-missile defense as
policy, the approval did not authorize any funding for construction
of such a system or set a deadline for its deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bipartisan vote in both chambers does place
considerable pressure on President Clinton, who is scheduled to
decide in June of next year on whether to build a network of radar
and missile interceptors designed to knock down any nuclear
warheads intentionally fired by rogue nations or accidentally
launched from China or Russia.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton gives the project a green light, it would still be
2005 at the earliest before it would be ready, according to
Pentagon officials, who have warned lawmakers that any system built
would not be the kind of ``umbrellalike'' space- and land-based
network originally envisioned in President's Reagan's Strategic
Defense Initiative of 1983 known as ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can build a system that knocks some incoming (missiles)
down. But we can't build one that can get all of them if there's a
full-scale attack,'' said one Defense Department official.
</P>
<P>
   The debate in the House and Senate, however, centered on the
possibility of a single or limited missile attack by a nation such
as North Korea or Iran. That concern was heightened in a classified
briefing that lawmakers were given Thursday on the House floor by a
special panel headed by former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The panel was authorized by Congress to study the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers told reporters later that Rumsfeld said at least 25
nations now have or will soon have a ballistic weapons capability
that enables them to launch nuclear missiles at the United States.
Rumsfeld also stressed in the briefing that North Korea and others
are dedicating huge spending efforts to developing long-range
missile programs.
</P>
<P>
   House Intelligence Committee Chairman Porter Goss, R-Fla., said
the Rumsfeld panel's report makes clear that ``the threat is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is growing and more immediate than many have thought,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said the sense of urgency over whether to pursue
``Star Wars II,'' as one member called it, was heightened by North
Korea's test last August of a three-stage missile. That test, which
followed a trajectory over Japan, caused some Democrats who had
long been opposed to spending the billions it will require to build
an anti-missile defense system to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James A. Traficant, D-Ohio, was one of them. ``Who are we
kidding. We've got to do something,'' he said, citing the Korean
test. ``You cannot protect America with a neighborhood crime
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Reps. Jim Turner of Crockett and Sylvestre
Reyes of El Paso, also cited the successful North Korean test and
reports of Chinese espionage at the Los Alamos nuclear facility in
New Mexico as one reason they favor making it the policy of the
United States to deploy a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Although it drew strong bipartisan support, nearly half of the
House Democrats and a handful of Republicans voted against it,
insisting that it would only create another nuclear arms race and
end up draining precious resources from other deserving government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cold War is over, but they still want Star Wars,''said
Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass, who accused the lead Republican
sponsors of the legislation of playing politics with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real danger is that it could touch off a new arms race
between us, the Russians, the Koreans and the Chinese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Markey reminded his colleagues that ``the deterrent of an
overwhelming massive retaliatory response'' from the United States
would keep even rogue states from firing missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what kept the Soviets from firing at us, and that's the
threat that will keep other countries from firing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote in the House followed an unsuccessful attempt by
Democratic opponents to amend the legislation to make it look more
like the bill passed by the Senate. That measure contained two
compromise provisions that caused Clinton to withdraw a threatened
veto.
</P>
<P>
   One provision would force funding decisions for any missile
defense project to be made through regular congressional
appropriations channels each year. Another ties the development and
deployment to continued arms reductions efforts with the Soviet
Union. Language in the bill would leave final deployment decisions
to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Before the changes were made in the Senate bill, some Democrats
had voiced strong objections to the measure, saying that deploying
a missile defense system might violate the Anti-ballistic Missile
Treaty with Moscow. They also expressed concern that the votes in
Congress could set back steps taken by the Russian Parliament
earlier this week toward approving the second strategic arms
reduction treaty known as START 2.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill allows for no ``wiggle room,'' said Rep. Curt
Weldon, R-Pa., the chief sponsor of the measure. Weldon's bill
mandates that the president must build and deploy a missile defense
system, although it does not say when or what kind.
</P>
<P>
   But few House members expect Weldon's bill to be the one that
reaches Clinton's desk. Both the House and Senate versions will be
merged into a compromise measure in conference between the two
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   A missile defense system has long been a priority among
Republicans since Reagan unveiled his strategic defense initiative.
The Pentagon spent more than $50 billion on SDI, but never
developed a single system capable of doing all that Reagan had
promised. But some of that research was successful and has been
applied to other defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has had no official policy on missile
defense, Presidents Bush and Clinton have included funding in the
defense budget proposals to keep the research going. Clinton, for
example, included $10.5 billion spread over five years in his 2000
budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
