<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS DOES LITTLE THINGS TO HAVE A BIG DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Never mind that Troy Glaus hit two home runs,
added an RBI single and drove in six runs Thursday in the Angels'
13-7 victory over the Colorado Rockies at Tempe Diablo Stadium,
manager Terry Collins says.
</P>
<P>
   That was nice, but Collins is taking note of the little things
Glaus is doing at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day he drove the ball to right field with two
strikes,'' Collins said. ``That's what I want to see. When he's
behind in the count, he'll go the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus has been working with hitting coach Rod Carew to improve
his stroke, which is what he needs to do to beat out Dave Hollins
for the starting spot at third base. Collins says neither player
has an edge at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins has been bothered off and on by a sore left hamstring
all spring, and he's coming off an injury-plagued 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to factor that in,'' Collins admitted, ``but we've
also got to factor in _ is Troy Glaus ready? He tore it up last
spring, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus knows if he doesn't win the starting spot, he goes back to
Triple-A. So it's all or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give them a reason to keep me,'' he said. ``Because
they have the option to send me out. I have to eliminate all
possibilities of that.''
</P>
<P>
   With his big day Thursday, Glaus is hitting .429 (12 for 28)
with two homers and a team-leading 14 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Mo better: Wednesday afternoon, Mo Vaughn told reporters he
wasn't worried about his offense after a slow spring start. But he
went to his room Wednesday night and did something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at some tapes from last year,'' he said. ``I've got a
good set-up now. It's about time. Regardless of the workouts you do
and the hitting in the offseason, it's a couple of weeks before you
trust yourself at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Vaughn drove in two runs with a double in the first
inning and also had a single in the Angels' 21-hit attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took batting practice with a purpose today, and he went
into the game today with a purpose,'' Collins said. ``He hit four
balls on the button.''
</P>
<P>
   The edge: Starting pitcher Ken Hill gave up one run and four
hits in four innings Thursday while making 74 pitches. His
surgically repaired right elbow is obviously fine, so now it's
about getting back ``the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing for me is mentally getting the edge back, the
killer instinct,'' Hill said. ``That's what I'm mainly trying to
work on, getting a feel for everything and being aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   That's more like it: Garret Anderson played all nine innings in
right field Thursday, had three hits and showed the kind of hustle
that's expected from him.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of trade rumors all winter and during spring
training, Anderson was yanked from a game last season when he
failed to run hard on an infield grounder in Baltimore. But even in
a blowout spring game like Thursday's, Anderson worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed with the way he's running the ball out,
he's running hard,'' Collins said, adding that even getting thrown
out trying for an extra base _ as Anderson did Thursday _ is a good
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to continue to try it,'' Collins said. ``We want to be
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Pitcher Jack McDowell is planning to throw this weekend
for the first time since having shoulder surgery Feb. 3. Early
estimates pointed to a possible return by August, but McDowell is
shooting for the All-Star break. . . . The Angels travel to HoHoKam
Park in Mesa today to play the Cubs beginning at 12:05 p.m. Steve
Sparks will start for Anaheim against Chicago's Terry Mulholland.
</P>
</TEXT>
