</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BROWSER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S SLIMMED-DOWN WEB BROWSER AIMS TO BROADEN DISTRIBUTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The pitch was given on a stage designed to resemble a
homey living room, but when Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates,
introduced a new version of his company's Web browser Friday, the
most surprising new feature was all business.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the redesign was about trimming fat to produce a
leaner program, the new browser, Internet Explorer 5.0, includes a
feature that enables Internet sites to distribute their own
versions of the program, customized with, for example, basic search
or multimedia features or their own logos.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it will appear to Web surfers that the browser
comes from companies like Alta Vista, Yahoo or Lycos _ all of which
already have signed on _ not from Microsoft Corp., which until now
has jealously guarded its branding.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp., Microsoft's chief rival in the
browser market, has allowed this kind of customization of its
Navigator browser for some customers, like the At Home cable modem
service. In addition, it publishes its source code, so that any
programmer can customize any feature.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials said that while they would lose some prime
real estate for displaying their own brand, the customization
feature would persuade online businesses to standardize on Internet
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Explorer 5.0 also includes features designed to make
surfing the Web faster and simpler. But thousands of customers
discovered there was nothing fast or simple about downloading the
new browser.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 can be set to log on to the Internet whenever the
computer is turned on, to check for updates or repairs to the
operating system. People who had employed this feature turned on
their computers Thursday to see a ``Critical Update'' notice,
informing them that the new browser was available. But traffic at
the download site was so heavy that many were unable to log on.
</P>
<P>
   Yusuf Mehdi, director of Windows marketing, said the company had
prepared for heavy traffic but that he did not know how many people
had tried, successfully or not, to download the new browser.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Netscape and Microsoft have sought to attract
customers with new features. But Microsoft seems to be retreating
from that strategy. It reduced the number of menu buttons on the
browser's top line to 11 from 13 and cut the size of the most basic
browser functions by about half compared with version 4.0 _ to 6.5
megabytes versus 14 megabytes. But consumers who choose this
skeletal version will have to download additional features as
needed while surfing the Web. The fully loaded browser, including
programs necessary to view multimedia and other nontext information
on the Internet, still will be 29 megabytes, verses 40 for version
4.0.
</P>
<P>
   Mehdi said the changes were driven by consumer research
indicating that customers wanted a simpler browser.
</P>
<P>
   But David Kerley, an analyst for Jupiter Communications, a
market research firm in New York, said he saw a larger trend. The
battle for browser market share, he said, would no longer be won by
impressing consumers with features but by cutting better strategic
deals for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Gates ended the program by introducing a so-called radio toolbar
that allows users listen to one of 350 radio stations while they
surf other sites.
</P>
<P>
   But to use this feature, ``you're going to want a fast
connection,'' Mehdi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
