<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-800&AMP;ADD-     03-18 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS ON KOSOVO WIND UP AS ONLY THE ALBANIANS SIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Peace talks on Kosovo concluded Thursday night with
representatives of the ethnic Albanian majority in the province
signing an agreement on autonomy that was worked out by
international mediators, while the Serbian authorities still
refused to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   That left France and Britain, co-chairmen of the talks, with
little choice but to declare the negotiations over, since most of
the ethnic Albanians plan to leave on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said on Thursday night that Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine of France and Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of
Britain, who were in Bonn on Thursday, would end or suspend the
talks on Friday, possibly giving the Serbs until Wednesday to
change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   That would give Serbian delegates one last chance to go to
Belgrade and would give President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
a last chance to accept agreement before NATO would be forced to
decide whether to make good on its longstanding threat to bomb
Serbian military targets if Milosevic stands in the way of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's stubborn refusal to compromise appeared to be making
the allies more determined than ever to show that this time they
mean business. President Jacques Chirac of France conferred with
military and security advisers on the issue Thursday, and the mood
in Paris was one of grim resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30,000 to 40,000 Serbian troops and special police forces
continued deploying in and around Kosovo on Thursday into positions
that could allow them to start a large-scale offensive against
ethnic Albanian positions or retaliate against them in the event of
NATO air strikes. Those deployments are in violation of pledges
Milosevic made last fall to withdraw most of those forces and stop
attacks that have driven more than 200,000 civilians from their
homes in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on Serbian troop positions, its sophisticated air
defense system and other military targets could begin as early as
next week, the allies say, unless Milosevic decides to accept the
peace plan and 28,000 allied-led peacekeepers to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley K. Clark, NATO's top military commander, said on
Thursday after visiting NATO troops already gathering in Macedonia,
``There should be no doubt in the minds of the Serb military and
police leaders that should NATO act, their military and police
forces would be devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the decision is made, NATO military forces are prepared to
act,'' Clark said. NATO is prepared to devote 400 American and
European planes, including B-52 bombers with cruise missiles, to
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which is a co-sponsor of the talks here along with the
United States, France, Britain, Germany and Italy, opposes the use
of military force against the Serbs but appealed to them on
Thursday to settle peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor S. Ivanov, conferred by
telephone from Moscow with Cook and Vedrine, who returned to Paris
on Thursday night, and with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov appealed to the Serbian leadership to let delegates here
sign what he called ``the political document put forward by the
working group.'' European, American and Russian mediators at the
talks worked out the 81-page agreement that the Albanians signed on
Thursday night, but the Russian mediator, Boris Mayorsky, was the
only mediator who did not also sign as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Thursday, the mediators met with the Serbian
delegation again, but Philip T. Reeker, the chief spokesman for the
talks, said there had been no change in the Serbian position. The
Serbs left the talks before the Albanian signing ceremony on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hill, the American negotiator for the six sponsoring
``contact group'' countries said the Serbs had demanded
unacceptable changes to the autonomy agreement and were refusing
even to discuss military and police measures to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Serbia would remain sovereign over Kosovo
for the next three years, though the Albanians would have home
rule, their own legal, educational and administrative systems, and
an Albanian police force.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NATO peacekeeping force, including 4,000 Americans,
the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army would disband and the Serbs would
withdraw all but 1,500 security forces from the province within a
year. The remaining Serbian soldiers would guard the frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 of the peacekeepers would remain in Macedonia, where
the alliance now has 10,000 soldiers ready to move into Kosovo
under the command of a British general, Sir Michael Walker, but
only if there is finally a peace agreement. After three years, an
international conference would be called to discuss the future of
the province.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright, who secured the Albanians' agreement in principle to
the accord at the first phase of negotiations in Rambouillet
outside Paris last month, told four of their leaders here in a
20-minute telephone call on Thursday afternoon that their decision
to sign was ``a very important step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, said she had also called on
the ethnic Albanians to maintain unity and calm in what could be
difficult days ahead, including the possibility that Serbian forces
might be preparing for a large-scale assault in Kosovo against
Albanian positions near Drenica.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something like that happens, next Wednesday is the
earliest day NATO is likely to make a decision on whether to go
ahead with air strikes, according to alliance officials in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   They said it would take 48 hours from the time the NATO
secretary general, Javier Solana, gave the go-ahead for bombs to
start falling.
</P>
<P>
   French officials said a French-led NATO extraction force that is
based in Macedonia was prepared to go into Kosovo if necessary to
evacuate the 2,000 civilian observers. Milosevic agreed to the
observers in October to oversee a cease-fire that both Serbian and
Albanian forces have often violated since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
