<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-ESPIONAGE-BOS &LR;      03-18 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ESPIONAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS RUDMAN TO PROBE CHINA NUCLEAR SECRETS LEAK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Thursday ordered former Senator
Warren Rudman, a New Hampshire Republican, to lead a review of the
security threat to US nuclear research labs in the wake of
suspicions that China stole nuclear weapons technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am determined to do all that is necessary to protect our
sensitive national security information and to prevent its
diversion to foreign countries,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered his Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board, chaired by
Rudman, to conduct an analysis of the security threat at the
Department of Energy's weapons labs and analyze the adequacy of the
measures that have been taken. Clinton asked Rudman to share his
findings with Congress and the public within 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said
Clinton acted on the recommendation of his National Security
Adviser, Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger. Some Republicans have demanded
Berger's resignation, saying the administration has mishandled the
alleged espionage case.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have accused the White House of dragging its feet in
investigating China's alleged use in the mid-1980s of secrets from
the Los Alamos, N.M., nuclear research lab on making miniaturized
nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy denied the Clinton administration was caving in to
political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy felt it was prudent and appropriate that we take this
step,'' he said. Leavy said Berger consulted with Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson and they agreed to make the recommendation to
Clinton, who called Rudman Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The review is expected to addresss the present
counterintelligence security threat, how it evolved over the last
two decades and steps the administration has taken to counter it,
as well as recommending additional safeguards that may be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The review will be conducted by Rudman and four others on the
independent, bipartisan, 12-member advisory panel that advises the
president on national security matters. Among those chosen Thursday
were vice chairman Anthony S. Harrington, a Washington lawyer, and
Dr. Sidney D. Drell, a professor and deputy director of the
Stanford University Linear Accelerator Center. The remaining two
members have yet to be named.
</P>
<P>
   The review is the second one ordered this week. On Monday, CIA
head George Tenet asked for a damage assessment of how much nuclear
weapons techonology, if any, was lost to China through a suspected
spy working at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is holding hearings on the espionage case, and some
House members are demanding that a 700-page classified report on
technology transfers to China be made public.
</P>
<P>
   A Taiwanese-born computer scientist, Wen Ho Lee, was fired from
Los Alamos last week for violating security regulations amid
suspicions that he leaked secrets to the Chinese in the 1980s. The
FBI has been investigating the case since 1996, but Lee has not
been charged with any crime. Richardson, the energy secretary, said
he did not know if Lee would be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Richardson told Congress he planned to tighten
security at the nation's nuclear weapons laboratories. Former CIA
Director John Deutch is to help decide whether too many foreign
visitors are admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Chinese diplomat Thursday denied allegations that
his country stole nuclear weapons designs. The official blamed a
Cold War mentality and ``political atmospherics'' for the furor
that has prompted FBI and Energy Department investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department, responding quickly, said the United
States remains ``deeply concerned about reports of China's attempts
to illegally acquire sensitive US technology.''
</P>
<P>
   That concern is ``shared widely by both branches, the executive
and legislative branches of government, by both political
parties,'' said James P. Foley, the deputy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no division there. The Chinese should not read our
concern over espionage as a partisan matter or a matter that's
manufactured by opponents of US-China relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese diplomat, He Yafei, a minister-counsel at the
Chinese Embassy, insisted ``the Sino-US relationship has become the
victim of party politics in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Monica Lewinsky scandal, he said: ``You all know how
party politics play, especially when you're nearing a major
election. You have seen the outcry or the big media coverage on the
Lewinsky issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat accused critics of harboring Cold War instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are sorry there is no more Soviet Union and they don't
know how to act,'' said He, referring to those accusing China of
espionage at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   But, asserting the two nations and the world benefit from
scientific exchanges, the Chinese diplomat cautioned: ``Don't go
too far so that normal scientific exchanges are affected. It will
not only hurt other countries, but it will hurt US interests, too,
because in the long run any advance in science and technology is
not dependent on scientists of one country alone.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the dispute could harm improving relations between
Washington and Beijing, and that some Chinese scientists were
questioning whether to continue scientific exchanges ``to advance
our knowledge of nuclear science.''
</P>
<P>
   With Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongii due here next month, He
said ``there are some people in the United States who do not want
to see progress in the Sino-US relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not identify anyone, and specifically excluded Berger,
who supports closer ties with China. On Sunday, Berger said
``there's no question'' China benefited from important information
leaked from the Los Alamos laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the allegations of espionage and theft, He replied
that ``nothing of this sort has ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China never benefited from anything that is illegal,'' the
diplomat said. ``We have normal exchange programs. Of course each
side will benefit from these exchange programs, otherwise it will
be meaningless. But it has nothing to do with nuclear military
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, He returned to his central theme, that US-Chinese
relations generally and scientific cooperation specifically were in
jeopardy from people opposed to progress between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let Chinese-US relations become hostage to that,'' He
implored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
