</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-CRISIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOREAN LEADER RESCINDS STATE OF EMERGENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ As street barricades came down and striking
transportation workers went back to their jobs, Ecuador regained a
semblance of normalcy Thursday following two weeks of turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadoreans breathed a collective sigh of relief when President
Jamil Mahuad announced early in the day that he had lowered
gasoline prices and lifted a week-old state of emergency, which, he
said, ``is no longer justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad rescinded the emergency decrees after opposition deputies
in Congress pledged to support a package of tax increases designed
to address the South American nation's worst economic meltdown in
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecuador was on the brink,'' one senior Western diplomat said.
``But it looked over and decided not to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is giving off signals that it wants to turn the
crisis into an opportunity,'' said an editorial in the Quito daily
El Comercio.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad reportedly was also considering a gradual freeing up of
bank accounts that had been partially frozen last week to halt
capital flight.
</P>
<P>
   If the accord between the president and opposition deputies
holds, it would break months of gridlock. There were signs late
Thursday, however, that the fragile alliance could fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   A bloc of deputies from the Democratic Left Party threatened to
withdraw their support for the president's economic measures unless
Mahuad, who raised gasoline prices by more than 100 percent last
week, cuts fuel costs further.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders said the government had promised to restore
gasoline prices to the levels they were at before the state of
emergency was imposed. Even with Thursday's price cuts, gasoline
cost about 35 percent more than it did before the emergency decree.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition groups that had led massive demonstrations against
the government's economic policies and had called for Mahuad to
step down said they would decide Saturday whether to continue their
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador's troubles were brought on by government overspending,
falling oil prices and $2.6 billion in flood damage caused by the
El Nio weather pattern last year. A government bailout of several
failing banks, coupled with the financial crisis in Brazil,
provoked capital flight, inflation and major devaluations of the
sucre _ the Ecuadorean currency.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a $1.6 billion budget deficit, equal to 7 percent
of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Banks were ordered shut last week. When they reopened Monday,
savings and checking accounts were partially frozen to prevent a
run on deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for revenue, Mahuad raised gasoline prices and
declared a state of emergency. The decrees provoked a nationwide
transportation strike, with Indian groups blocking sections of the
Pan-American Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters clashed with riot police and called for Mahuad to
resign. At one point, Mahuad and his aides considered closing the
Congress and ruling by decree, according to U.S. Ambassador Leslie
M. Alexander. Analysts said the disturbances cost the nation $22
million a day.
</P>
<P>
   The lifting of the state of emergency Thursday, however, calmed
tensions nationwide. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Restaurants and supermarkets were back in business, and private
schools were scheduled to reopen Friday. Public schools remained
shut because of delays in the payment of teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   In Quito, some people said they would accept the new gasoline
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the obligation to support the state with our gas
taxes,'' one motorist said.
</P>
<P>
   The accord hammered out Thursday called for reinstatement of the
income tax, which had been abolished last year; the elimination of
a host of tax shields; and new taxes on banking transactions,
luxury cars and corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting revenue, plus rebounding oil prices, were expected
to bring in $520 million and close the budget deficit to about 3.5
percent of GDP, lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the economic measures are enacted, analysts warned
that they are more of a Band-Aid than a long-term solution. Still
lacking, they said, are plans to cut government spending and
privatize inefficient state industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like emergency medicine,'' said political scientist
Fernando Bustamante. ``You do it to sustain and stabilize the
situation so that later, you can do what you need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Western diplomat predicted that Ecuador will remain
in dire economic straits for months to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to see an Ecuador in good shape or in good
health. You will see an Ecuador that still has to deal with
fundamental problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
