<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Dogs use depth, take lead
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ SMU senior All-American Martina Moravcova put on a
spectacular show Thursday, but her efforts were not enough to put
the Lady Mustangs in first place.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, host and pre-meet favorite Georgia took the lead after
the first day, and the Lady Bulldogs hope to add to it tonight
contending in three relay events and having Kristy Kowal favored in
the 100-yard breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's finals begin at 7 p.m. in the Gabrielsen Natatorium at
the Ramsey Center on the University of Georgia campus. The
championships conclude with finals beginning at 7 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After the first day, Georgia leads with 143.5. Following are:
SMU 137.5, Stanford 129, Southern Cal 93 and Arizona 90. Most
expect the three-day race for the team championship to be among
those teams.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Wimer, a member of SMU's winning 200-yard freestyle
relay team said the Lady Mustangs ``are off to a good start. We
have some good sprinters.''
</P>
<P>
   With Moravcova earning the right to stand at the top of the
podium twice, Georgia built its lead by earning a fourth-place
finish in the 200-yard freestyle relay, a fourth and sixth in the
200-yard individual medley, a fourth in the 500-yard freestyle and
a fourth in the 50-yard freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bulldogs have depth on their side with 17 swimmers
competing in the championships. SMU has 11 and defending champion
Stanford 13.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches of the top five ranked schools expected this meet to
be fast and fourth-ranked SMU showed why very early.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Mustangs set a pool record in the first event in the
time trials in the 200-yard freestyle relay. That mark, 1:29.32,
lasted a handful of hours. SMU came back to make the mark faster
with a 1:28:94 to win the NCAA title in that event.
</P>
<P>
   That SMU win meant Moravcova, who swam the opening leg in 22:22,
was for a few minutes an 11-time NCAA champion. In less than a half
hour, she was back in the pool winning easily in the 200-yard
individual medley for her 12th title.
</P>
<P>
   Moravcova's 1:55.64 was the second-fastest 200-yard individual
medley in history, behind the time of 1:55.54 set by former
Stanford and U.S. Olympic swimmer Summer Sanders in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
