<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5844 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS-AR     03-18 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS-ART-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST IN NEW YORK PROTESTS: MAKING A DATE TO BE ARRESTED
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It went according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, the president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, arrived at Pennsylvania Station from
Washington shortly after 11 Thursday morning, looking like a
businessman eager to keep an appointment. There to greet him was
his host, the Rev. Al Sharpton, who had arranged for him to be
arrested in about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   As Sharpton's driver maneuvered the purple van downtown, the two
men talked about the matter at hand: the daily acts of civil
disobedience to protest last month's shooting death of an unarmed
African immigrant by four white police officers. Then the car phone
rang; it was an aide delivering a report from outside police
headquarters, the now-familiar scene of the protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk right up and start the pickets,'' Sharpton instructed.
``We're about five minutes away.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour and a thousand chants for justice later, 59 people were
arrested outside 1 Police Plaza on charges of disorderly conduct.
Among those led away in plastic handcuffs were Mfume and three
members of Harlem's black elite: state Sen. David Paterson; his
father, Basil Paterson, a former deputy mayor and New York
secretary of state, and former Manhattan Borough President Percy
Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Standing shoulder-to-shoulder in crisp suits, just a few feet
from a revolving door to the glass and brick headquarters, the four
men made a striking image for the scrum of news photographers. Not
only did it bring to mind past acts of civil disobedience, from the
civil rights movement to protests against apartheid, but it also
underscored the arrests earlier this week, in the same spot, of
former Mayor David Dinkins and Rep. Charles Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth day of daily acts of civil disobedience in
front of police headquarters, acts that have ended with people
detained for about an hour and then released.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters' demands are simply stated, if not simply
achieved, ranging from a residency requirement for all police
officers to the arrests of the four officers involved in the
shooting death of the immigrant from Guinea, Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the carefully scripted parade of celebrities in
handcuffs has drawn unflagging news coverage to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   And with each passing day, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani seems less
patient with the tradition of nonviolent protest, no matter how
civil. At a news conference held two hours before Thursday's
arrests, Giuliani mocked former Mayor Ed Koch for saying that he
might volunteer to be arrested, and suggested that the daily
protests were highly political and ``getting silly, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is getting to be a really abusive situation in
the sense of trying to use the police in ways that are highly
inappropriate,'' he said. ``I think they are over the top now. This
is the piling-on time where everybody is hoping, `Let me see if I
can get on camera.' And, unfortunately, you keep obliging them.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, organizers say, the mayor was also keeping to the
plan. By ridiculing civil disobedience, they say, he only
reinforces prevailing perceptions that he has no ties to or
understanding of the city's black residents, and that he is
predisposed to defend the police department no matter how egregious
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I follow the Muhammad Ali technique of rope-a-dope,'' Sharpton
said. ``I lay back and let the guy beat himself up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo case has created another tug-of-war between two men
whose history is so antagonistic that Giuliani often refuses to
utter Sharpton's name. The mayor has contended that the minister is
little more than a loud-mouthed media creation who lives to incite
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton countered that he has a significant following among
black New Yorkers, as the voting in his past political campaigns
has shown, even though they were unsuccessful. Sitting in the
Harlem office of his organization, the National Action Network, he
said that everyone from Cardinal John O'Connor to President Clinton
has met with him because everyone but the mayor recognizes him as a
leader. And, the minister added, Giuliani has underestimated him _
and all the other black leaders in the city that the mayor has
refused to meet _ at his own risk.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sharpton and others say, black and Hispanic residents have
been galvanized by two recent developments: the firing of 41
bullets at Diallo in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building
on Feb. 4, and the perception that Giuliani was too quick to defend
the police and too slow to mourn the young man's death. And they
say that the mayor's use of statistics _ including those that
suggest a growing restraint among the city's officers _ to
distinguish reality from misperception, shows that he is out of
touch with the experiences of young black men living in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After a few demonstrations, including one in the city's
financial district that led to Sharpton's arrest, coalitions began
to form among black leaders who do not always shared the same world
view. Then, late last month, the board of the National Action
Network gave Sharpton the go-ahead to organize sustained nonviolent
protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to find a tactic that all people can participate in
if they choose to,'' explained the Rev. Herbert Daughtry, one of
the organizers and the pastor of the House of the Lord Pentecostal
Church in Brooklyn. With civil disobedience, he added, ``Nobody is
hurt, and yet it makes the point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
