<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS-AR     03-18 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the point.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sharpton, his legal adviser, Michael Hardy, and others said that
a lot of planning went into the mechanics of the daily protests.
They considered several sites, including City Hall, before choosing
police headquarters. They wanted to avoid having the same people
arrested day after day, to demonstrate the widespread outrage over
the case. To expedite processing after arrests, they advise
participants to have photo identification and no outstanding
warrants, and they recently began providing the police with the
names of those about to be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, city officials say that Police Commissioner
Howard Safir _ and not Giuliani _ has handled the response to the
protests, although the mayor receives periodic updates. One Police
Plaza now sports rows of blue sawhorses that are used to corral the
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Before the events of Thursday, the protests had received the
most media attention on Monday, when Dinkins, Rangel and Sharpton
were arrested. The image of a former mayor and the dean of the
city's congressional delegation being led off in handcuffs angered
Koch, who said that such a decision had to have been made by the
mayor himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think an ordinary cop or even the police commissioner
would handcuff the highest black elected official for the state of
New York in Congress and a former mayor without checking with the
mayor?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But Police Inspector Michael Collins said that the arresting
officers were simply following the policy laid out in the
department's patrol guide.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Roche, the mayor's press secretary, said that the mayor
played no role in that decision. In addition, Sharpton pointed out:
``It makes a dramatic picture. You don't hear me complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicity is part of the reason why prominent people in the city
have volunteered or been enlisted to be arrested. The other reason
is that they believe in the cause _ and, despite any past
differences _ in Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have chosen different paths'' on issues over the years,
Paterson, the state senator, said. ``But on this one, I think this
has been one of his absolutely best efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Bill Perkins, who was arrested earlier this
week, agreed: ``I think this thing could have been managed quite
differently. It could have been more inflammatory, much more
divisive. It could have been petty, and I don't think we see a
petty movement. We see a high-quality movement.''
</P>
<P>
   That movement, for now, is being run out of Sharpton's office,
where plaques on the wall are meant to prove his standing in the
community, and where a black-and-white portrait of Martin Luther
King Jr. gazes down at him. With a few minutes to spare before
leaving to meet Mfume at Penn Station, he answered the phone and
worked out details for protests to come.
</P>
<P>
   Friday has been named State Legislators Day at the protest,
Sharpton explained, with Assemblyman Keith Wright of Harlem and
others planning to be arrested. Monday is to be Lawyers Day,
although Dick Gregory is also planning to be arrested that day.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rang. It was Dennis Rivera, the president of local
1199, the mammoth National Health and Human Services Employees
Union, calling to volunteer his services.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be wonderful,'' Sharpton answered, taking notes.
``Can you do that Wednesday. We can make that Labor Leaders Day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
