<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5849 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-ART-NY     03-18 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP BILL ON PATIENTS' RIGHTS CLEARS SENATE PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Mass., Conn., Okla.)  (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of The New York Times.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate committee approved legislation Thursday
night to create a wide range of new rights for patients, but
Democrats said the protections fell far short of what was needed to
help people deal with insurance companies and health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The question of patients' rights stirs more public interest than
many issues before Congress, and Thursday's battle was only the
first stage of a conflict likely to continue into next year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   By a party-line vote of 10-8, the panel, the Committee on
Health, Education, Labor and Pensions, approved the bill and sent
it to the Senate floor. On the floor, Democrats will try to force
an open-ended debate on patients' rights and the techniques used by
HMOs to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was written mainly by the committee chairman, Sen.
James Jeffords, R-Vt., and reflects the approach favored by most
Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time,'' Jeffords said, ``millions and millions
of people will have protections they did not have before.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant provision of the bill would allow people in
employer-sponsored health plans to appeal decisions denying them
coverage for specific services. Patients could appeal to an
independent medical reviewer if a health plan refused to pay for
care on the ground that it was medically unnecessary or
experimental.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee rejected a Democratic amendment that would
have made it easier for many patients to sue HMOs and other health
plans under state law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the senior Democrat on the
committee, repeatedly denounced the Republican bill as a sham,
saying it was full of loopholes and empty promises. ``If you have a
right without a remedy, you don't have a right,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill defines different rights for different
groups of people, depending on the nature and source of their
insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said, for example, that the grievance and appeal
procedures required by their bill would be available to more than
120 million people with health benefits provided by employers. But
many of the other consumer protection standards would apply only to
a subset of this group _ 48 million people in health plans
regulated exclusively by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   These standards would require health plans to pay for emergency
care in any situation that a ``prudent lay person'' would regard as
an emergency. They would also prohibit health plans from
restricting what doctors tell patients about treatment options.
Doctors say some HMOs have enforced ``gag rules,'' forbidding
doctors to tell patients about expensive treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican bill, health plans would have to allow
patients to go directly to obstetricians, gynecologists and
pediatricians for routine care, without getting a referral or prior
approval from a family doctor or internist. For an extra charge,
consumers could buy coverage allowing them to use doctors outside
the network of physicians selected by their health plan.
</P>
<P>
   The House, which passed a patients' bill of rights last year by
a vote of 216-210, is working on similar legislation again this
year.
</P>
<P>
   After the impeachment of President Clinton, some politicians
predicted that Republicans and Democrats would cooperate to produce
tangible results on issues of concern to voters. But the guerrilla
warfare in the Senate committee over the last two days tends to
disprove that prediction. The disagreements involved not only big
questions, like the right to sue, but countless little details as
well.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Thursday, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said:
``This is pretty depressing. It's greed prevailing over need.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats suggested that Republicans were trying to protect the
interests of the insurance industry and employers. But an aide to
Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the assistant Republican leader, said:
``Insurers hate our bill, and we don't care. This wasn't written to
satisfy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers objected to some of the proposed new appeal rights for
patients. Paul Dennett, vice president of the Association of
Private Pension and Welfare Plans, which represents large
companies, said, ``Many good employers and insurance companies
allow external review, but it is by no means common practice yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans said they had limited the scope of many
provisions of their bill because they did not want to usurp the
states' authority to regulate insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy said the federal government needed to set minimum
nationwide standards because there were many gaps and
inconsistencies in state laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican bill leaves two-thirds of Americans out,''
Kennedy said. ``It leaves behind our nation's most vulnerable
health care consumers and patients _ the people who purchase
insurance by themselves without assistance from their employer, and
many of the people who work for small businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
