<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      03-18 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS NEAR DEAL THAT WOULD SEND FOLEY TO THE SEAHAWKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Minn., Ill.)   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glenn Foley's career as a New York Jets quarterback is days, if
not hours, from ending, but Foley may get in a trade what he could
no longer get with the Jets _ the chance to compete for a starting
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and the Seattle Seahawks are close to a deal that would
have Foley in the Seahawks' off-season passing camp next week
competing with the current starter, Jon Kitna, whose hold on the
job is tenuous under Mike Holmgren, Seattle's new coach.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Jets would receive a middle-round draft choice
from Seattle, with the slim possibility that the draft pick becomes
a higher one if Foley, 28, starts a majority of the Seahawks' games
next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets would also be free of Foley's $2.05 million annual
salary, giving the team valuable room under the salary cap as it
tries to fill other needs through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the teams were discussing specific trade terms. The
Jets' bargaining position is limited, however, because it is
believed they will release Foley soon because a workout bonus
payment schedule begins on Monday. Foley is set to earn $10,000 for
each of the 40 off-season conditioning workouts the Jets will begin
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who was exposed but unclaimed during last month's
expansion draft for the Cleveland Browns, no longer fits into the
Jets' plans. Vinny Testaverde is the starter, and the Jets recently
signed Tom Tupa, a punter and quarterback. The Jets also have
quarterback Ray Lucas. If the Jets have any doubts that Lucas and
Tupa can handle the backup responsibilities, they can always sign a
veteran free agent later _ at considerably less than the $2 million
Foley would earn.
</P>
<P>
   Foley has indicated his first choice is Seattle, which has
unsuccessfully pursued several second-level quarterbacks this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Few teams have expressed interest in Foley, though Minnesota and
Chicago have made inquiries. Each of these teams, including
Seattle, could wait for the Jets to cut Foley next week and sign
him without having to compensate the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, the Jets' seventh-round choice in 1994, opened last
season as the starting quarterback following several injury-filled
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When Foley hid a rib injury from Coach Bill Parcells during a
losing effort in the Jets' second game, Parcells began to sour on
Foley. By the sixth game, Parcells had switched to Testaverde. As
Testaverde led the Jets into the playoffs, Parcells also was irked
when Foley commented that hidden forces had led to his benching.
</P>
<P>
   Foley completed 58 of 108 passes for 749 yards with 4 touchdowns
and 6 interceptions before being replaced last season. He has never
thrown more than 110 passes in a season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
