<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA CAN'T WIN IN COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's representing the NCAA in court these days, the Los Angeles
District Attorney?
</P>
<P>
   First, it lost $54 million in the restricted-earnings lawsuit
filed by assistant coaches. Last week, a federal judge struck down
the use of minimum standardized test scores to determine freshman
eligibility. Now, the Black Coaches Association has challenged the
NCAA to improve its minority hiring or _ what else? _ face legal
action.
</P>
<P>
   No issue packs the power of U.S. District Court Judge Ronald
Buckwalter's ruling that Proposition 16, which uses SAT and ACT
scores to determine eligibility, was unfair to African-Americans.
Studies show African-Americans consistently score lower on
standardized tests than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Before Buckwalter's ruling, incoming freshmen needed to score at
least 820 on the SAT (out of 1600) for initial eligibility. Now,
athletes will be eligible as freshmen with a 500 SAT, for instance,
as long as they have the necessary grade-point average in core
courses.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA can't win. It created the eligibility standards in 1986
in response to complaints it was exploiting athletes who couldn't
handle legitimate college work. Now, those standards are
discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pac-10 and across the nation, Buckwalter's ruling favors
schools that lack a strong commitment to admissions standards, like
Washington State, Arizona and Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   On the local front, both UCLA and USC say they'll maintain
current standards. If true, they'll face a competitive
disadvantage, unable to admit players who are accepted elsewhere.
(Of course, the massive talent base in Southern California offsets
any discrepancies in admissions.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge's ruling opens the oor for schools with lower
admissions standards while other schools maintain higher
standards,'' said USC's Fred Stroock, special assistant to the
athletic director. ``The level playing field the NCAA seeks is
disappearing pretty rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter denied the NCAA's request for a stay, leaving the
member schools with no guidelines until the association develops
new eligibility standards. That could take months.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are sitting tight and waiting for the NCAA to say what
direction to take,'' said Mike Matthews, the Pac-10's assistant
director for compliance and enforcement. ``The NCAA isn't advising
schools to do one thing or another. There simply is no
initial-eligibility rule right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It may take six weeks or six months, but eventually the NCAA
will institute new guidelines. Most likely, they'll follow the
former standards as closely as possible within Buckwalter's
parameters. He did not outlaw the use of standardized tests in
general; he outlawed the use of standardized tests as a limiting
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Stroock thinks the new model may expand the sliding-scale format
that was adopted several years ago, in which low SAT scores require
a high GPA, and vice versa. In the new model, a 400 SAT would
require a 3.0 GPA, and a 500 SAT would require a 2.9 GPA, and so
on. That would fit Buckwalter's demands, since incorporating the
lowest score possible (400) eliminates the minimizing aspect of the
SAT.
</P>
<P>
   This much is sure: The new system cannot rely solely on GPA;
high schools have different grading scales and systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex issue, and there's no simple solution,''
said Stroock, who spent eight years at UCLA before moving downtown.
``When eligibility issues have come up in the past, there's been no
consensus agreement, just majority agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's majority confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rise of the lower seeds: Five teams in the Sweet 16 are seeded
ninth or lower _ making this the most upset-filled tournament since
the field expanded to 64 teams in 1985. Never before had four low
seeds advanced to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors help account for the upsets _ the scholarship
reductions (from 15 to 13), which disperse talent, and the flight
of top players to the NBA, which has weakened the heavyweights not
named Duke.
</P>
<P>
   If North Carolina had Vince Carter and Antawn Jamison, if
Arizona had Mike Bibby, if Kansas had Paul Pierce, perhaps someone
would be worthy of the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the week: Ohio State forward George Reese on his first
encounter with husky-voiced coach Jim O'Brien: ``I thought he was a
gangster. I thought, `You must be related to the Gambinos.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Friday fodder: If Nevada-Las Vegas is found guilty of NCAA
violations _ the latest allegations involve an assistant coach
using a student manager to make car payments for ex-Rebel Tyrone
Nesby _ and if coach Billy Bayno loses his job, here's a name to
consider: John Thompson. The former Georgetown coach loves Las
Vegas and is often spotted at casinos playing the slots.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to be Tark: Fresno State coach Jerry Tarkanian, who
also experienced bouts with NCAA violations while coaching at UNLV,
has signed a one-year contract extension despite failing to make
the NCAA Tournament in any of his four seasons. His players have
had a slew of legal problems, including that small matter f point
shaving.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming Cardinal: Stanford has strengthened a brilliant
recruiting class with the additions of Alameda St. Joseph's-Notre
Dame power forward Justin Davis, who UCLA wanted desperately, and
Tyler Besecker, a gifted 6-6 walk-on from Mercer Island (Wash.). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
