<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5864 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BUYER-PROGRAMS-AR     03-18 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BUYER-PROGRAMS-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU SPEND A MILLION, THEY'LL THROW IN A JAGUAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, La., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
(af) 
 By JANE WOLFE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When Sara M. Dunham regularly drives the seven hours
from her home in Baton Rouge, La., to spend about $200,000 a year
at the flagship Neiman Marcus store here, her rewards go beyond the
clothing, jewelry and furs she buys.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of In Circle, the Neiman Marcus frequent-shopper
club, she and her husband will be treated this year to a free week
in Milan, with first-class flights and hotels. Last year, it was
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But now Mrs. Dunham's loyalty may be tested. Other high-end
retailers, especially Saks Fifth Avenue and Bergdorf Goodman, which
like Neiman Marcus is a unit of Harcourt General, are also trying
to lure shoppers like her. The new competition has meant enhanced
loyalty programs with more perks like special discounts, trips
abroad and exclusive social events inside and outside the stores.
</P>
<P>
   The retailers say the programs show how important those shoppers
are to them. ``Neiman's, Saks, and Bergdorf's all go after the
richest 2 percent of the nation's people,'' says Howard L.
Davidowitz, a New York retail consultant. ``You're shooting for a
class of people who spend $6,000 for a dress. You have to coddle
these people constantly because you cannot afford to lose even a
few of them as customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Which program is best? It depends on whether a shopper wants
merchandise discounts or other goodies. The value of the bonuses
usually ranges from 1 percent to, at higher levels, 6 percent of
the amount spent. Because most programs require use of the
retailers' own charge cards _ or special, affiliated cards _
shoppers should also compare their terms, interest rates and
rewards with those of other credit cards, some of which offer
frequent-flier miles or other rewards of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The latest retailer to join the fight is Bergdorf Goodman.
Hoping for quick gains, Bergdorf's, unlike Neiman's and Saks, will
allow customers to earn award points on any credit card, although
its own card will earn twice the points.
</P>
<P>
   Saks, meanwhile, is making its biggest splash among the
designer-label set with its four-year-old Platinum Events, each
more lavish than the last. Last month, 40 Platinum members, who
spend at least $10,000 a year, and their spouses or friends, dined
on leeks with caviar, lobster-filled zucchini blossoms and rack of
lamb with gingered eggplant at Chanterelle.
</P>
<P>
   In attendance were Philip B. Miller, the Saks chief executive,
and Donna Karan, who told the guests that she would be in the
flagship store the next day to help them design their wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bergdorf Goodman and Neiman's offer their members shopping
nights when the stores are closed to everyone but them. They are
feted with cocktails and food and have a chance to chat with
designers and executives. At Neiman's events, there is another
bonus: double In Circle points.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty programs are also offered by chains like Bloomingdale's,
a unit of Federated Department Stores; Marshall Field's, a unit of
Dayton Hudson, and Nordstrom. The plans can provide discounts or
gift certificates for users of the stores' charge cards or
affiliated Visa cards.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard G. Barlow, publisher of the Colloquy newsletter,
which tracks frequent-buyer and traveler programs, says these other
plans, which require just $500 or $1,000 of purchases, are not
snobbish enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make the customer feel important, you've got to be
exclusive,'' Barlow said. ``Neiman's realized before anyone else
that since so many stores have the same merchandise, it's no longer
sufficient to focus on what you sell but rather on who is buying
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The retailers disagree over how shoppers want to be rewarded.
Members of the Saks First program, who must spend a minimum of
$2,000, get points redeemable only at Saks. ``We did extensive
research that showed our customers really did not want trips,''
said Sheri Wilson-Gray, marketing vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, serious shoppers appreciate some things that they can't
secure themselves. ``Even if you have great wealth,'' Ms.
Wilson-Gray said, ``it's not necessarily within your power to call
up Donna Karan and say, `Will you personally help me create my
spring wardrobe?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman's In Circle was inspired by AAdvantage, the American
Airlines frequent-flier program; American started it in 1981,
shortly after moving to Dallas. ``Since they were in our own
backyard, we were watching them very closely,'' said Billy J.
Payton, Neiman's marketing vice president. ``We knew that
recognizing and rewarding customers based on spending was driving
market share in the airline industry and we were trying to develop
the same kind of program.''
</P>
<P>
   In Circle, founded in 1984, gives one award point for each
dollar spent. It has grown to 150,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Like the airlines' frequent-flier programs, the stores' plans
encourage the notion that spending in the pursuit of ostensibly
free awards is downright thrifty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My secretary was reading my Neiman's statement and said to me,
`You're just $200 short of getting the award for 3,000 American
Airlines points,' '' said Nancy O. Lemmon, a civic and social
leader here. ``So I raced down to Neiman's and spent more than $200
for a sweater and got the points.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who spend $100,000 can choose tickets to the Super Bowl or
the Kentucky Derby, including first-class airline tickets and hotel
rooms. Spend a million and get a Jaguar S-Type, or a one-week
annual stay for life (and for the life of your children) at the
Four Seasons Punta Mita resort near Puerto Vallarta on Mexico's
west coast, or one million frequent flier points.
</P>
<P>
   At her award level, Mrs. Dunham has missed a trip only one year
in the history of In Circle, when she was in a hospital. Neiman's
sent over a food spread that included its chicken soup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
