A5867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAIN-WRECK-650&AMP;ADD-N     03-18 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-WRECK-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ASSERTS TRUCKER TRIED TO PASS GATES BEFORE CRASH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A possible witness has come forward in the deadly
crash of an Amtrak train and a truck on Monday night in
Bourbonnais, Ill., and a federal official said Thursday night that
the man told investigators he saw the truck driver try to snake
through the lowered crossing gates.
</P>
<P>
   The man called Amtrak on Wednesday, saying he was driving a car
behind the truck. Federal investigators did not say why he did not
come forward earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A federal safety official in Washington familiar with the
investigation, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that the
motorist had told investigators that he saw the truck go around the
gates.
</P>
<P>
   At the crash site, John Goglia, a member of the National
Transportation Safety Board, said, ``We need to analyze what this
person saw and see how it fits with the other facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The work of identifying the dead passengers on the train, the
City of New Orleans, moved forward. The coroner of Kankakee County,
James Orrison, said he had 11 bodies, and that most had been
identified from medical records. Orrison said he believed the 11
matched Amtrak's list of passengers unaccounted for. He said he
would release the names on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, investigators, after re-enacting the conditions
at the time of the crash, said the truck driver might have snaked
his load of steel around crossing gates after waiting as long as 21
seconds when lights began to flash and he saw no train.
</P>
<P>
   Safety board officials said preliminary tests showed that the
truck and train were not perpendicular when the crash occurred,
suggesting the truck was moving around the gates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, John R. Stokes, 58, from nearby Manteno, Ill.,
has repeatedly told investigators that he did not drive around the
gates, but was in the crossing when he saw the signal lights and
the oncoming train. Officials are testing his account by studying
tire tracks at the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The re-enactment on Wednesday night offered several important
pieces of evidence, investigators said. At the same hour as the
crash, approximately 9:50 p.m., they placed a similar locomotive on
the rails approaching Bourbonnais. On McKnight Road, where it
crosses the tracks next to a steel mill, they drove a tractor
pulling a flatbed truck loaded with steel.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found that the crossing gates were working
properly. Warning lights are intended to flash, and bells ring,
when a train is about 27 seconds from the crossing. Gates are then
lowered.
</P>
<P>
   The tests showed that the driver could not have seen the train's
headlight until it was 644 feet from the crossing, the
investigators said. With the train traveling the maximum 79 miles
per hour, the driver would have seen the train for at most 5.6
seconds before it reached the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   That calculation means the driver could have been waiting for as
long as 21 seconds after the lights flashed, before he could see a
train, said Robert Lauby, director of railroad safety for the
safety board. Too many drivers, officials said, will interpret that
interval as a sign that no train is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``What difference does it make when he can see the train?''
asked Jack Burke, a spokesman for the Illinois Central Railroad,
which maintains the crossing and owns the tracks over which Amtrak
operates the City of New Orleans. ``The gates are down. The lights
are flashing. The 26 seconds is there for traffic on the tracks to
clear, not for you to try to beat the train.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they also found that the truck could have
zigzagged its way around the crossing gates without hitting the
gates.
</P>
<P>
   Also, investigators learned that it is common for the gates at
that crossing to be triggered by freight cars on side rails, a
railroad official said. Drivers at the steel mill, Burke said, may
have become accustomed to false alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said it could take nine to 12 months to determine
a cause.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The only witnesses known before Thursday were the truck driver
and the Amtrak engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer, whose name has not been made public, did not
suffer serious injuries but remains sedated in a hospital in
Kankakee. An Amtrak board member has said that the engineer said he
saw the truck drive around the gates, but the federal investigators
have been unable to interview the engineer.
</P>
<P>
   While the investigators prepare to go home, 22 of the 116 people
injured remain in hospitals. A total of 216 passengers and crew
members were on the train, Amtrak said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
