 Column: Keep Mum About Evil Former Boss
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I recently resigned from my job in the accounting field.
I was working for a very difficult boss. After years of trying to
get along with her, I decided it would be in my best interest to
leave the company. Now that I'm job hunting, how honest should I be
about the reason I quit? What should I say when prospective
employers ask me why I left my old job?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Here's how much bad stuff you should say about a
former boss when you're job hunting: Zero. Zip. Nada.
</P>
<P>
   You never know. Maybe the person interviewing you is the
next-door neighbor of your old boss whom you've just described as
an inept boob. Maybe they're best friends from college.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the interviewer is just thinking, ``Hmm, if this person
is saying all these negative things about their last boss, what
will they say someday about ME?''
</P>
<P>
   A bad boss may have been the main reason you left your job, but
it probably wasn't the only reason. When asked why you left, focus
on the other reasons _ and emphasize the positive ones. Maybe you
wanted some new challenges. Maybe you wanted to gain new skills.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Mandel, counseling director at Alumnae Resources in San
Francisco, suggests shifting the focus to why you want to work at
the firm you're visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where doing research on companies is important,''
Mandel said. ``You can say, `I'm applying because I really consider
you a leader in the community banking field.'''
</P>
<P>
   If discussing your old job is stressful, consider practicing
your response. Mandel has had clients who couldn't answer questions
about their old job without breaking into tears. That doesn't sound
like your situation; but it still couldn't hurt to rehearse with a
friend, or in front of a mirror, or even with a video camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to know if your body language is betraying any
negativity,'' Mandel said. ``A job interview is not the place to
unload about how badly you were treated. You can do that with your
friends and relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer Job
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like my 13-year-old son to get a job this summer. Does he
need a work permit? What are the laws that govern teenage
employment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal law says that most kids can't be officially employed
until they're 14 years old. So your son is still limited to
informal work like lawn mowing or _ in this high-tech era _
designing Web pages for friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only things I know of for 13-year-olds are jobs helping
their neighbors, like baby-sitting or weeding gardens,'' said Susan
Hoganson, executive director of Enterprise for High School
Students, a San Francisco nonprofit that helps teens get jobs.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably not the only parent thinking about summer jobs
for their kids at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   So here's what federal law says about summer work for teens,
according to Hoganson:
</P>
<P>
   _Kids younger than 18 need a work permit to hold a job. These
can usually be obtained from your local school district.
</P>
<P>
   _Kids ages 14 through 17 can work up to eight hours a day or 40
hours a week during the summer. Their shifts must fall between 7
a.m. and 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _Kids ages 14 and 15 are prohibited from working in some
hazardous fields like manufacturing and construction. Kids ages 16
and 17 have more leeway but still aren't allowed to drive motor
vehicles on the job or use certain tools such as power saws and
meat slicers.
</P>
<P>
   More questions about summer jobs for teens? Talk to the
vocational counselor at your child's school. Or in San Francisco,
contact Jobs for Youth at (415) 861-5627 or Enterprise for High
School Students at (415) 896-0909.
</P>
<P>
   `Weird' Rules
</P>
<P>
   Q: My company recently designated all its employees as nonexempt
and adopted a policy that discourages overtime or comp time. Here's
the problem: We don't have time cards, and there seems to be a
double standard. Some employees are given comp time
surreptitiously, while the rest of us are told it's not available.
This all seems weird and illegal to me. What can we do about it?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: ``Weird'' is right: It's highly unusual for a firm to
suddenly reclassify all its employees as nonexempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cases we hear about usually go the other way _ where a
company tries to classify everyone as exempt, to avoid paying
overtime,'' said Conley Baker, a human resources consultant with
the Employers Group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Your situation sounds potentially illegal, too, for a couple of
reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _Employers are required to keep daily time records for their
nonexempt employees. Without time cards or a time clock, it's hard
to see how your firm would be in compliance with the law.
</P>
<P>
   _California and federal laws severely limit the use of comp time
for nonexempt employees, except in workplaces governed by union
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can provide time off within a 40-hour week _ giving
someone two hours off on Tuesday, for instance, to make up for a
10-hour day on Monday. But companies generally can't use comp time
as a substitute for overtime pay when nonexempt workers put in more
than 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
   I'd suggest pointing out these potential legal land mines to
your firm's personnel manager. The company should hire an
employment lawyer to draft better policies _ or at least seek
advice from an association like the Employers Group at (415)
495-2527 or the California Chamber of Commerce at (916) 444-6670.
</P>
<P>
   What if the company refuses to shape up? You can file a
complaint with the California Labor Commissioner at (415) 557-7878.
Or contact the Employment Law Center in San Francisco, which offers
free legal advice to low-income workers at (415) 864-8208.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
