<SLUG> BC-FENGSHUI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Business the Feng Shui Way
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Several hundred fashion designers, accountants and seamstresses
gathered in the entryway of Esprit de Corp.'s headquarters as a
black-clad Tibetan Buddhist teacher reached up his hands and
scattered bright red-dyed rice into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray that Esprit Corp.'s business will be more and more
prosperous and more and more successful,'' said Grand Master Thomas
Lin Yun.
</P>
<P>
   Lin Yun was visiting the San Francisco clothing company this
week to bless and celebrate its use of feng shui, the ancient
Chinese art that claims to foster well-being and prosperity through
the systematic arrangement of furniture and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Developed 3,000 years ago in rural China, feng shui (pronounced
``fung shway'') is said to promote well-being by fostering a good
flow of ch'i or life-energy through buildings.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of American businesses today are openly
bringing feng shui into their workplaces to boost their bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   Some are doing it to attract Asian customers _ many of whom
wouldn't dream of staying in a hotel or leasing an office without
the seal of approval of a feng shui master.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a place where the East meets the West,'' said
Frank Williams, architect of a new luxury apartment building on
Second Street that is being constructed with advice from feng shui
experts. ``This was to make sure that someone with a strong belief
in feng shui would be able to choose to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   But other U.S. firms, including Esprit, are incorporating feng
shui for internal reasons that have nothing to do with &LR;   &LR; marketing
to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   They are hoping that feng shui will foster a more harmonious
working environment, which in turn will boost productivity and
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying that we love our building, we love the people in
our building, and we want to create an environment that everyone
feels comfortable in,'' said Esprit CEO Jay Margolis.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say companies are throwing their money away when they
fork over fees of up to $300 an hour to feng shui consultants.
</P>
<P>
   There's no organization that licenses or issues credentials to
feng shui practitioners, who range from scholars who have spent
years studying Eastern philosophy to dabblers who skim a book or
two and then dub themselves feng shui ``experts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a party game, it's not bad. But I don't think it has any
place in modern business,'' said Barry Beyerstein, a biopsychology
professor at Simon Fraser University in Vancouver who is on the
executive council of the Committee for Scientific Investigation of
Claims of the Paranormal. ``If I worked at a place that was doing
this, I'd start looking for a new job. I'd be wondering, `If
management is this desperate, what else is going wrong?'''
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui had its roots in the rigors of ancient agricultural
life in China. For instance, early feng shui teachers told people
to build their homes facing south, which would have helped farmers
create a sunny and warm living space.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all feng shui adherents today share certain basic
practices. They all, for example, use an octagonal chart called a
ba-gua at a site to see which portions of a building match up best
with such desirable qualities as wealth, fame and flourishing
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also very different schools of thought within feng
shui about how to use the ba-gua _ so that two different
practitioners might easily give conflicting advice about where to
place pieces of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   And none of the different feng shui approaches has ever been
scientifically tested or proven.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you measure something that claims to promote good
luck?'' scoffed Dr. Wallace Sampson, a Los Altos oncologist who is
editor of the Scientific Review of Alternative Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feng shui is potentially testable, but the claims are so vague
it would be like nailing a custard pie to the wall,'' Beyerstein
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners who have used feng shui say they don't need a
scientific study: Their own subjective experience has convinced
them it works.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Takayama, president of the small Fremont biotech firm Lab
Vision Corp., hired San Francisco feng shui consultant Deborah Gee
to analyze his office last year. Gee suggested changes such as
moving the reception desk, moving some plants, painting a few walls
red, and hanging wooden flutes in Takayama's private office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm more productive now,'' Takayama said. ``And
everyone comments on the changes to our lobby. They say it's a good
feeling to be there and walk through there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Berkeley restaurant owner Christophe Kubiak credits
feng shui with boosting business at his new eatery, Voulez-Vous on
College Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too much into energy and all that, and I don't want to
have a Buddha sitting by every door, but after feng shui, we saw an
80 percent increase in our business,'' Kubiak said.
</P>
<P>
   At Esprit, the person who introduced the idea of feng shui is
none other than Alison May, the chief financial officer. On her
bookshelf, a copy of ``The I Ching Workbook'' is sandwiched between
binders labeled ``Financial Review Package 1998'' and minutes from
corporate board meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Esprit embarked on its feng shui makeover in late 1998. Among
the changes it made: painting many of the doors bright colors based
on the ba-gua, adding a small bamboo fountain to the front
reception desk, relocating or partitioning some offices, hanging
bright-colored banners over certain areas, adding mirrors and
Esprit promotional artwork throughout the building and hanging
wooden flutes in the bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked really hard last year, but we've had much better
results in 1999 (after doing feng shui) than we did in 1998,'' said
May. ``Is feng shui the determining cause? I don't know. But I do
know our financial performance so far is twice as good as last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  There are no hard data on how many American businesses are
turning to feng shui or on the amount of corporate money going to
feng shui consultants.
</P>
<P>
   But interest is clearly growing. Villard Press, a division of
Random House, published a book last year called ``Feng Shui at
Work.'' Its author, Kirsten Lagatree, was just hired to write a
bimonthly feng shui column in the real estate section of the Los
Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of feng shui practitioners and thousands of
American businesses that have received feng shui advice at all
levels of expertise,'' estimated Steven Post, a San Francisco feng
shui practitioner who studied under Lin Yun, who is based at a
Berkeley temple.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the spread of feng shui in the workplace is due
in part to American businesspeople's increased contact with Asian
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first exposure was when I helped set up a manufacturing
plant in Singapore several years ago, and they hired a feng shui
expert,'' said Takayama, the biotech executive. ``Everything felt
right. It seemed magical.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say it just shows how unnerved people are by today's
fast-changing, competitive economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstitions show up where there isn't any tried-and-true way
of succeeding,'' said Beyerstein. ``People are looking for a hedge,
a way to get a leg up in this dog-eat-dog world. It doesn't matter
how outrageous it is: If you tell them something will improve their
bottom line, they have an odd ability to believe it without
checking it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
