<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FCC Opens Up Telephone Services
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
California consumers may soon have more choice for local phone
service and high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators ruled yesterday that regional Bell companies,
such as Pacific Bell, must make it easier for competing local phone
companies to set up their own equipment within the Bells' central
switching offices.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling eases restrictions on where competitors can place
their gear and prevents Baby Bells from limiting the type of
equipment that's allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC order is a win for companies such as Santa Clara's Covad
Communications and San Francisco's Northpoint Communications, which
are trying to construct nationwide local phone networks to offer
high-speed Internet access. Both companies say their plans have
been delayed by the Baby Bell phone companies, which have made it
difficult for them to locate equipment _ such as routers and
switches _ which are necessary for providing high-speed Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's order will make it cheaper and easier for companies to
roll out services such as digital subscriber lines, which access
the Internet up to 50 times faster than traditional modems. The
ruling should help consumers by giving them more choices for
Internet service in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings competition a whole lot faster,'' said Dhruv
Khanna, executive vice president of Covad. ``If I can get into a
central office in one month rather than six months, it helps the
consumer. And if my costs are considerably reduced, I can go into
central offices that I wouldn't necessarily go into and offer
service in more places.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came after Covad and others complained about being
denied access to competitors central offices. The 1996
Telecommunications Act, which lifted regulations on the phone
industry, mandates that competitors be allowed access to the
regional Bell companies' offices.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't been happening, Khanna said. He said Covad has
often waited six months before gaining access to a site and has
been charged up to $400,000 for locating its equipment in 10-foot
by 10-foot cages.
</P>
<P>
   Once allowed into the office, Khanna said, the companies were
not given access to the entire central office and were told where
they could place their equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the incumbents have insisted on a separate entrance
for us, a separate walled-off area and separate cage for our
equipment,'' Khanna said.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC said yesterday that the incumbents cannot discriminate
against competitors and must give them equal access. The ruling
allows competing companies to inspect a central office to verify
space constraints, install a wider range of equipment and rent a
small area, rather than a huge, expensive cage.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials said they need more time to review the
decision, but said they believe the company is already doing much
of what the FCC requires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-two competitors operate from our offices, they have
installed 1,264 cages and they are locating in 102 of our central
offices,'' said Bill Mashek, a spokesman for Pac Bell. ``We have
more co-location space and cages than any other company in any
other state.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashek said the company might challenge portions of the FCC's
decision if it gives competitors unfettered access to the entire
central office, rather than a specific, walled-off area.
</P>
<P>
   Mashek said that could pose security risks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
