<SLUG> BC-THEFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Big Money For Thieves In Hardware
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jamie Beckett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
High-technology companies are losing about $250 million a year to
hardware thieves, who can make more money stealing a suitcase of
microprocessors than a suitcase of cocaine, according to a study
released yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Those thefts represent about 0.1 percent of industry revenues,
according to the report prepared by Rand, a Santa Monica nonprofit
organization, for the American Electronics Association and the
International Electronics Security Group.
</P>
<P>
   Indirect costs _ such as lost business and added security and
insurance needs _ raised the total cost to more than $1 billion
annually, the study said. It estimated that thieves steal another
$4 billion in equipment from business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, especially laptops, are the most popular item among
thieves, accounting for 44 percent of stolen goods, the study said.
Other popular items: disk drives (33 percent), semiconductors (11
percent) and cellular phones and pagers (4 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The study did not include theft of software, or theft from
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, most of the thefts weren't large heists _ only 3
percent resulted in losses of $100,000 or more, while 80 percent
were for items worth less than $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers surveyed 95 high-technology manufacturers that
collectively account for 40 percent of the sales volume in the
computer, semiconductor, hard-disk drive and cellular phone
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the study was released, the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, U.S. Customs Service and the San Jose Police
arrested eight people in San Jose who they said were involved in a
series of chip thefts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
