<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-PARADISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS STAGE-DIVING CASE SETTLEMENT NEAR, CLUB OWNER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER AND STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a move which could bring an end to an embarrassing
chapter in Boston sports history, a woman who was injured when two
New England Patriots players dived off the stage of the Paradise
nightclub in Boston has been offered a a $1.2 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed settlement has not yet been formally signed, but
all the parties involved in the incident have agreed to its terms
in principle according Paradise owner Seth Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on the table now, and it's just a matter of dotting the
Is and crossing the Ts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If signed, the settlement would end the lawsuit and resulting
negative publicity for the football team and the nightclub, whose
liquor license was suspended for five days because of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing has been a nightmare for everybody,'' said
Greenberg, who confirmed that a settlement has been negotiated.
``It was bad for the players, bad for the girl, and terrible for
the club. But hey, it happened, we settled, and people move on.''
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, insurance companies for the Paradise and
Everclear, the band playing at the club the night of the incident,
will each contribute $100,000 to the settlement. The remaining $1
million will be paid by the two Patriots players, quarterback Drew
Bledsoe and lineman Max Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who reportedly does not have liability insurance, will
personally pay $600,000, sources said. Bledsoe will reportedly pay
$400,000, half from an insurance policy and half from personal
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe earns $42 million over seven years and Lane $11 million
over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Tameekea Messier, the woman injured in the
stage-diving incident, had been seeking $3 million, sources said.
Messier reportedly incurred medical bills of roughly $35,000 as a
result of her injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most lawyers said this case would settle for $200,000,'' said
Greenberg, ``but because of the publicity surrounding it and the
players involved, the case was able to get much more.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred Nov. 11, 1997, when the 305-pound Lane and
235-pound Bledsoe leaped off the stage into a ``mosh pit'' of fans.
Lane allegedly landed on Messier's forehead, while Bledsoe
allegedly struck her head and neck.
</P>
<P>
   After the stage-diving accident, Messier underwent neck surgery
at St. Elizabeth's Medical Center to have two spinal discs removed
and three vertebrae fused. According to her lawyer, she is able to
work and is doing well, but still has pain in her upper back and
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Messier later sued the two players, alleging that they were
negligent or reckless, as well as the band and the club, claiming
that they also were negligent.
</P>
<P>
   The players have admitted to diving off the stage, but deny that
they caused Messier's injuries. A lawyer for the nightclub
contended that Messier may have had a medical condition that
contributed to her injuries.
</P>
<P>
   With the Paradise facing mounting legal bills, the club agreed
to settle, Greenberg said. He said the nightclub's legal fees have
already reached $200,000 as a result of the case. The cost of
insuring the club will more than double as a result of the
settlement, from $75,000 a year to $160,000 a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Messier, Bledsoe or their lawyers were
unsuccessful Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at their homes, Messier's mother and brother said they
were unaware of any settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
