<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5882 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-1ST     03-18 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PONDERING A SENATE RACE, MRS. CLINTON STUDIES NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS.: Subs to correct figure in lede, and adds phrase for
clarity) 
(wg) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the month since announcing her interest in a U.S.
Senate seat from New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton has discussed her
potential candidacy with more than 50 influential Democrats in the
state, including the major party chairmen from the suburban and
upstate counties crucial to winning a race.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials say Mrs. Clinton did not hint at her ultimate
decision, but she is systematically studying the politics and
issues of a state where she has never even lived. And a number of
Democrats said Mrs. Clinton has told them she plans to do polling
and that she is looking for ways to raise money even before she
makes a decision on the race. Many officials describe their
conversations with the first lady as lengthy and very detailed
about local issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's obviously been doing her homework,'' said Steve Pigeon,
the Democratic chairman of Erie County, the state's largest
Democratic stronghold outside of New York City. Pigeon said he
spoke by phone to Mrs. Clinton for an hour on Monday night. ``I
have to explain to a lot of candidates who come to me that you
can't view upstate monolithically,'' he said. ``She already knew
the vast differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigeon said that Mrs. Clinton told him that she does not want
her delay in making a decision to undercut the ability of other
potential Democratic candidates _ like Rep. Nita Lowey of
Westchester County _ to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the possible impact on other likely
candidates and their ability to raise money if Mrs. Clinton does
not run, many Democrats have been irked by her announcement that
she will not make a decision until ``later this year,'' perhaps as
late as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In apparent response to that concern, the first lady and her
advisers are exploring fund-raising options: ``She said they're
looking for vehicles to raise money to be used for whoever the
candidate is,'' Pigeon said. ``I think as long as she's raising
money that can be used no matter who runs, whether it's her or
Nita, that can buy some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Election law lawyers said Thursday that such a vehicle might
involve a committee, allowed under federal election law, that would
raise money for an unspecified Senate candidate in donations of up
to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In making her calls, Mrs. Clinton works from a list of 200 names
provided by Harold Ickes, a former White House official and a
veteran of New York politics. Mrs. Clinton's advisers say she has
methodically made her way through the Democratic power structure in
New York state: labor leaders, major county leaders and county
executives, fund-raisers, members of the New York congressional
delegation and leaders of black, Jewish, Hispanic and women's
groups.
</P>
<P>
   She has also had meetings at the White House with a number of
New York officials _ on Thursday with New York City Comptroller
Alan Hevesi and last Friday with Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said that he and the first lady spoke for more than an
hour, half of which he said was spent on Amadou Diallo, the unarmed
African immigrant whose shooting death by the New York City police
has led to protests against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a potential
opponent of Mrs. Clinton. Hevesi said Mrs. Clinton brought up the
case herself but made no comment on Giuliani's handling of it.
</P>
<P>
   Silver met for an hour and 45 minutes with the first lady. In
another indication that Mrs. Clinton may be positioning herself as
a candidate, Silver said that she elaborated on her remarks last
year that a Palestinian state was ``very important'' to Middle East
peace. Giuliani has said her comments were ``a very big mistake,''
while political analysts have said her remarks could give the mayor
a chance to cut into any support she has among Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Mrs. Clinton told him that her remarks were a
``reflection of her discussions'' with Yitzhak Rabin, the late
Israeli prime minister, ``and that Rabin had told her that ``it was
very difficult to negotiate with a nonentity.'' Silver added that
Mrs. Clinton said her remarks ``are not inconsistent with American
policy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Upstate and suburban Democratic party officials, who seem
stunned by the first lady's attention, say Mrs. Clinton hasn't told
them whether she plans to run. But most have come away from
conversations with Mrs. Clinton believing that she will be a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was talking to a political pro,'' said Steve
Paquette, the Onondaga County Democratic chairman, who spoke to
Mrs. Clinton for a half-hour last Thursday. ``I honestly think for
her to be taking the next broad step of calling folks like me,
that's more than sticking your toe in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton makes her calls from the family quarters of the
White House, often at the end of the working day, and sometimes
after a call first from Ickes _ who now has his own Washington
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockland County Democratic chairman, Paul Adler, said last
week that Ickes called and asked him about local issues, and that
Mrs. Clinton then called to talk about property taxes, suburban
development, the regional economy and transportation into New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key here is that they're listening,'' Adler said.
``They're not coming in here and saying, `We ran two races
exceedingly well, shut up, sit back and enjoy the ride.' They're
saying, `How do you think we should do it, what makes your county
tick?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ickes said that Mrs. Clinton is educating herself about New York
through her phone calls, which she makes alone. ``She's finding out
the lay of the political landscape, the lay of the issue
landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most Democratic Party activists are clamoring for Mrs.
Clinton to run, many have also told her the race will be very close
and that she should expect personal attacks for her role in the
Whitewater scandal and her spectacularly profitable trades in the
commodities markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly indicated that it would be a tough race,'' said
Dominic Baranello, the Democratic chairman of the heavily
Republican Suffolk County. Baranello said he told Mrs. Clinton last
week that the Republicans ``would revive many of the issues we've
been hearing about ad nauseum'' and that ``she has to be prepared
to handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local Democratic leaders say they have been taken aback by
the intricacy of Mrs. Clinton's questions. ``She was curious about
why there was a large Jordanian population in Yonkers,'' said
Alpert, the Westchester Democrat, who spoke to Mrs. Clinton for
nearly an hour. ``I did not know the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Alpert also said that he and Mrs. Clinton talked about friends
and colleagues they had in common in Westchester _ Ron Brown, the
late secretary of commerce who was a Democratic district leader in
Mount Vernon in the 1970s; and Toby Nussbaum, a former county
Democratic finance chairman who is married to Bernard Nussbaum, a
friend of Mrs. Clinton's and a former White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert said Mrs. Clinton told him that they are ``relatives''
because of their mutual friends.
</P>
<P>
   On March 5, the president and Mrs. Clinton had a small dinner in
the family quarters of the White House for important New Yorkers.
The guests included Carl McCall, the state comptroller; Randi
Weingarten, the president of the United Federation of Teachers;
Dennis Rivera, the president of Local 1199, of the National Health
and Human Service Employees Union; Bill Lynch, longtime adviser to
former Mayor David Dinkins; Victor Kovner, a First Amendment lawyer
and a corporation counsel in the Dinkins administration; and Sarah
Kovner, who is a special assistant to the secretary of health and
human services and Kovner's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The guests were up until 1:30 a.m. having dinner and watching a
movie. Afterward, the New Yorkers slept over at the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
