</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred Nov. 11, 1997, when the 305-pound Lane and
235-pound Bledsoe leaped off the stage into a ``mosh pit'' of fans.
Lane allegedly landed on Messier's forehead, while Bledsoe
allegedly struck her head and neck.
</P>
<P>
   After the stage-diving accident, Messier underwent neck surgery
at St. Elizabeth's Medical Center to have two spinal discs removed
and three vertebrae fused. According to her lawyer, she is able to
work and is doing well, but still has pain in her upper back and
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Messier later sued the two players, alleging that they were
negligent or reckless, as well as the band and the club, claiming
that they also were negligent.
</P>
<P>
   The players have admitted to diving off the stage, but deny that
they caused Messier's injuries. A lawyer for the nightclub
contended that Messier may have had a medical condition that
contributed to her injuries.
</P>
<P>
   With the Paradise facing mounting legal bills, the club agreed
to settle, Greenberg said. He said the nightclub's legal fees have
already reached $200,000 as a result of the case. The cost of
insuring the club will more than double as a result of the
settlement, from $75,000 a year to $160,000 a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Messier, Bledsoe or their lawyers were
unsuccessful Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at their homes, Messier's mother and brother said they
were unaware of any settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
