<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV JOURNALISTS WARN OF NATO STRIKE CONSEQUENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As their homeland edges toward all-out war, two visiting
Yugoslav journalists warned Thursday that Kosovo's Albanians will
suffer the consequences of any NATO military strike against Serbian
targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think NATO should seriously consider the results of its
actions,'' said Dorijan Nuaj, editor in chief of Radio Contact, an
independent radio station in the Kosovo capital of Pristina. ``I'd
like to ask those NATO generals just what they think the
consequences will be for the Albanians, because they are the ones
who are going to suffer the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 16,000 and 21,000 well-equipped Yugoslav army troops are
now on the perimeter of Kosovo, and another 14,000 to 18,000 are
deployed in the province. Military analysts say the Serbs are
capable of inflicting heavy casualties throughout Kosovo in
retaliation for any NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his blunt warning, Nuaj is no Serb nationalist, nor is
he a supporter of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old editor is half Albanian and half Montenegrin,
placing him in a very precarious position in today's strife-torn
Balkans, where one's name and ethnicity can mean life or death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks about leaving, but there is really no place
for me to go,'' said Nuaj, who fears hostilities will ``probably''
erupt by the time he returns home on March 27. ``So I have a very
personal interest in seeing some kind of peace in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuaj is also caught in the middle of a difficult and sometimes
dangerous battle to liberalize the media in Yugoslavia. Milosevic's
Ministry of Telecommunications banned Radio Contact last year after
the station had been on the air for only 10 days. The government
didn't like the station's independent programming, which included
both Serbians and Albanians _ some of whom were openly critical of
Milosevic's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shut us down because we broadcast in the Serb language
and they won't tolerate an independent Serb-language radio station
in Kosovo,'' said Nuaj, who was in Seattle, Wash., as part of a
six-member group of young journalists from Serbia and Montenegro on
a weeklong U.S. tour sponsored by the U.S. Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government wants to control what the Serb people hear.
They don't care that much about Albanians because they can't
control them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   After it was banned by the government, Radio Contact was given a
satellite frequency by the British Broadcasting Corp. and now beams
a daily 15-minute Serb-language report that can be heard all over
Europe _ including in Kosovo. The station has also received
assistance from the U.S. Agency for International Development and
the Open Society Institute of financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people have been killed in a year of fighting in
Kosovo, a province of Serbia, the dominant of two remaining
republics comprising Yugoslavia. Montenegro is the other.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Kosovo's 2.2 million people are ethnic
Albanians, and most favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Nuaj and a colleague, Bojan Cvetkovic, say Milosevic and
most Serbs will never allow that. Nor will they agree to a NATO
military presence in Kosovo, as called for in the peace agreement
signed in Paris Thursday by the Albanian side.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic allows NATO into Kosovo, he will be dead
politically,'' said Cvetkovic, a 28-year-old Serb radio and
newspaper reporter in the town of Smederevska Palanka, 40 miles
south of Belgrade. ``There will be riots in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Cvetkovic said ``all sides are bluffing'' as the situation in
Kosovo grows increasingly serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he has faced economic troubles like he does right
now, Milosevic made some kind of conflict so people would rally
around and forget their problems,'' Cvetkovic said. ``And I think
NATO is really afraid to send troops in on the ground. The
Americans are trying to push the Europeans into doing it. There are
so many competing interests just among the Western countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic puts on such a good poker party.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuaj said this potentially deadly game of bluff has now become
so serious that Milosevic himself ``probably doesn't know what he
is going to do in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a question of airplanes and air strikes,'' he
said. ``We are looking at a humanitarian disaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
