A5889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-630&AMP;AD     03-18 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TOLD OF DRAFT INDICTMENT THAT INCLUDED HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton was named in an
indictment drafted by a top aide to Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, but the document was never presented to a grand jury, and
no charges were brought against the first lady, the aide testified
in U.S. District Court here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure came from the deputy independent counsel, W.
Hickman Ewing, who was subpoenaed as the first witness for the
defense in the contempt-of-court trial of Susan McDougal, a former
business partner of the Clintons'.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was not asked what charges he had specified in the draft
indictment he drew up against Mrs. Clinton, but he suggested that
he considered her responses to questions put to her under oath as
less than forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who is in charge of the Arkansas phase of the Whitewater
inquiry headed by Starr, testified that he wrote the indictment in
late 1996 after becoming convinced that Mrs. Clinton had not been
truthful in discussions with Starr's staff. The independent counsel
has been investigating the Clintons' involvement in a complex
series of loans and land deals that collectively have come to be
known as Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal and her late former husband, James McDougal, were
partners of the Clintons in the Whitewater venture. McDougal died
last year in a federal prison, and Ms. McDougal has twice refused
to answer questions from a grand jury about their financial
dealings. By calling a Starr prosecutor, she was attempting to show
that she was pressured to falsely implicate the Clintons, an
assertion the prosecutors have insisted is bogus.
</P>
<P>
   That Starr's office had drafted the indictment against Mrs.
Clinton has been known for months, but details were never
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The OIC illegally leaked this information a long time ago,''
David Kendall, the Clintons' lawyer, said in a statement Thursday
after Ewing's testimony. ``The mere fact that this prosecutor's
office drafted a frivolous indictment three years ago has no
significance whatsoever, except as a possible violation of the
Paperwork Reduction Act of 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in conflict with other interviews that we had already
done,'' Ewing said of Mrs. Clinton's answers to questions from
prosecutors in two meetings, including an April 1995 session at the
White House. Ewing said the conflicting information came from
interviews with some of Mrs. Clinton's former partners at the Rose
Law Firm in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing testified that based on what he knew at that point he had
questions about what Mrs. Clinton was saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had doubts?'' asked Mark Geragos, Ms. McDougal's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is correct,'' Ewing responded. ``The same was true of the
president,'' he continued, referring to an interview with the
president conducted by prosecutors the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you tell people you thought she was lying?'' Geragos
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I used the `L' word, but I certainly expressed
internally that I had some problems with some of the answers of the
president and the first lady,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you have a draft indictment?'' Geragos asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say positively,'' Ewing said, but Geragos persisted
until Ewing added: ``I would say yes, but qualify that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said it was not unusual for prosecutors to circulate
proposed indictments, whether or not a charge was ever brought.
``You're always thinking about what possible crime could it be,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever graded Mrs. Clinton's testimony, Ewing
recalled that he had, in a reference to one of Mrs. Clinton's
interviews with the independent counsel's staff. He said he had
given her an ``F'' because ``she had used the words `I don't
recall' about 50 times.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No charges have been brought against the Clintons in the
Whitewater investigation. Ms. McDougal is charged with blocking the
inquiry by refusing to testify to a grand jury about
Whitewater-related matters despite a judge's order to do so and a
grant of limited immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing insisted Thursday that Starr's team was interested only in
obtaining the truth, even as he acknowledged that the Clintons were
potential targets of their inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted any information (Ms. McDougal) had, including the
Clintons,'' Ewing affirmed. ``It was our duty to investigate
whether the Clintons did anything illegal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
