<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE WOULD BE FIRST EVER AT AMERICA WEST
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER CORBETT and MAX JARMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of bad blood and months of back-and-forth threats,
it has come down to the last minute for America West Airlines and
its 2,400 flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   By 10:01 tonight, the Tempe airline could suffer its first
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible scenarios are:
</P>
<P>
   _ A deal between the airline and the Association of Flight
Attendants.
</P>
<P>
   _ A shutdown of all operations if flight attendants strike
selected flights.
</P>
<P>
   _ An extension of talks if progress is being made.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side was hazarding a guess on what would transpire
tonight, leaving thousands of passengers up in the air about their
scheduled trips on America West during one of the busiest weekends
in the Valley's tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   As contract talks continued toward the deadline, pilots for the
Tempe carrier were being asked to support the flight attendants by
following flight operations to the letter, which could result in
flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Even as negotiations continued, the company was taking a
get-tough stand, with Stephen Johnson, America West senior vice
president for corporate affairs, saying the carrier will fire
striking workers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zack, AFA communications director, dismissed the company
stand as a bully tactic. Firing strikers is illegal and the union
would go to court to win jobs back for the flight attendants, just
as it did in a 1993 Alaska Airlines strike, he said.
</P>
<P>
   America West lead negotiator Greg Garger said last month that
the union's CHAOS tactic _ striking selected flights _ amounts to
an illegal, intermittent strike and the company will consider
testing it in court.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA had a dry run Thursday at Sky Harbor International
Airport for CHAOS, which stands for Create Havoc Around Our System.
Flight attendants learned about the timing and where they should go
if the union decides to strike a flight they're working, Zack said.
</P>
<P>
   AFA has strike-related events planned today in Washington, D.C.;
Las Vegas; and Tempe. Flight attendants and other labor union
members are expected to gather in Washington's Franklin Park,
across from the National Mediation Board offices where the two
sides are negotiating with the help of a federal mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Another rally will be staged at Fashion Show Mall in Las Vegas,
and there will be a candlelight vigil in downtown Tempe at America
West's Tempe headquarters in the hour leading up to the strike
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots became involved after an anonymous letter from a
``Concerned Captain'' was distributed to other America West pilots,
which urged them to ``do everything in our power to slow this
operation down and put pressure on this management.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter suggested a number of ``legal'' actions such as:
</P>
<P>
   Following to the letter all federal aviation regulations, flight
operations manual, aircraft manuals and flight training manual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not push back from the gate with anything but a legal
aircraft,'' the letter asserts. ``Write up every discrepancy no
matter how minor, especially at field stations.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter also suggested that if a flight is targeted for CHAOS
action, the captain should take responsibility for ensuring that
any replacement flight attendants are knowledgeable in all areas of
flight safety.
</P>
<P>
   According to their union contract, the pilots can show support
for the flight attendants by walking in picket lines or attending
rallies as long as they are out of uniform. They also can support
the flight attendants through public statements.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot, however, take sympathy action that would affect the
airline's operation, according to Donald Steinman, chairman of the
Airline Pilots Association local union that represents America West
pilots. That includes any work stoppages or organization action in
support of the flight attendants' picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   The union doesn't officially sup port the letter, and Steinman
said it won't ask the pilots to do anything that would put their
jobs in jeopardy or violate their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all procedures they should be following anyway,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, representatives of the two sides resumed their
discussion, with the help of a mediator, about 9 a.m (Arizona time)
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed as a result of (Wednesday's) meeting,''
union President Bill McGlashen said be fore the second round of
talks. ``No proposals were exchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   America West's Johnson would not comment Thursday on negotia
tions and said it was inappropriate for him to speculate on whether
the two sides will work out differences before the deadline. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Max Jarman can be reached at 444-7351 or at max.jarman &LR; pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
