<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS PANEL TO ANALYZE SECURITY THREATS AT NUCLEAR LABS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Ala., Neb., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton asked an advisory panel Thursday
to analyze security threats at the Energy Department's nuclear
laboratories, after suspicions surfaced that China stole
nuclear-weapons designs from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am determined to do all that is necessary to protect our
sensitive national security information and to prevent its
diversion to foreign countries,'' Clinton said in announcing the
review by the president's Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board.
</P>
<P>
   The president's announcement was one of a series of steps the
administration has taken in recent days to try to reassure an angry
Congress and the public that it has tightened security to prevent
the transfer of sensitive technology information to China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the board would analyze how security threats had
evolved over two decades and what steps could be taken to counter
them.
</P>
<P>
   The president asked the board's chairman, Warren Rudman, a
former Republican senator from New Hampshire, to report back within
60 days. Clinton asked the board to deliver its report to Congress
and to release an unclassified version to the public ``to the
fullest extent possible consistent with our national security.''
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said
Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser, had
recommended the review. Nuclear security has become a sensitive
issue in recent weeks after assertions have grown that China has
obtained American atomic data to help update its own warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The latest suspicions have focused on Wen Ho Lee, an American
engineer born in Taiwan, who was dismissed last week from his job
at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico for violating
security rules. He has not been charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   There were clear signals Thursday that the nuclear security
issue will not abate soon.
</P>
<P>
   Berger was criticized by Sens. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., and Bob
Kerrey, D-Neb., the chairman and ranking Democrat, respectively, of
the Senate Intelligence Committee. The senators said Berger's
recent comments that the administration had briefed Congress
repeatedly since 1996 about possible thefts of nuclear secrets by
China were ``misleading and inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelby and Kerrey said Berger left the impression that Congress
was lax about security at the labs when, in fact, lawmakers
familiar with intelligence issues had pushed the Energy Department
to strengthen security.
</P>
<P>
   The president's Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board was created
by President Eisenhower in 1956, abolished by President Carter in
1977 and reinstated by President Reagan in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Its members serve without compensation and review the
performance of all agencies engaged in gathering and evaluating
intelligence. Members have included distinguished scientists, while
its chairmen have typically been retired military officers or
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said four of the panel's 12 members would work with Rudman
on the inquiry. He said he did not know the identities of all four,
but that one was Sidney Drell, a Stanford University physicist who
heads the University of California president's council on the
laboratories. A number of the Energy Department labs are operated
by the University of California under contract to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji scheduled to visit
Washington next month, a Chinese diplomat in Washington played down
tension between the United States and China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990318.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-ADVANCE1     03-18 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-ADVANCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hungry RedHawks expecting a win
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ On a basketball mystique scale of 1 to 10, the
University of Kentucky will take an advantage of about 10-2 into
today's Midwest Regional semifinal against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats have an 85-35 record in 41 NCAA appearances and
have won seven national championships, including two in the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks have made 16 trips and have a 6-15 record. Until
last weekend, they had never won twice in the same tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But when Miami coach Charlie Coles was asked if he has any
concern about how his players would react to the UK aura, he shook
his head vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about that, I really don't,'' Coles said. ``I
worry about us. I'm constantly asking my players, `Are you full? Do
you have the same desire? Can we play in St. Louis the way we
played in New Orleans (where the 10th-seeded RedHawks upset No. 7
Washington and No. 2 Utah)?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to New Orleans as a very hungry team that wanted to
prove we were better than we played against Kent State (a loss in
the finals of the Mid-American Conference tournament).''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, Coles' players said they aren't full, that their
appetites have been only whetted, not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hungry,'' point guard Rob Mestas said. ``Everybody
in the country knows about Kentucky and their tradition. We see
this as a chance to put Miami on the map, to show people we can
play with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Wally Szczerbiak, who is averaging 33.5 points a game in the
tournament, said, ``We really don't care what anyone thinks. No one
believed we could win two games in New Orleans except us and no one
believes we can go any further except us. And that's fine, that's
the way we like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burly forward John Estick put it even more succinctly. ``Of
course we're still hungry. If anyone's not still hungry, they're
pretty stupid. There's a lot more stuff to be won. Just because
we're in the Sweet 16, that's nothing. We want to get to the Final
Four, to show everyone we're a force to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky utilizes a two-platoon system and no starter has
averaged 30 minutes. Four Miami starters _ Szczerbiak, Damon
Frierson, Mestas and Estick _ are averaging 34-plus minutes.
</P>
<P>
   UK opens with Wayne Turner (6-4), Desmond Allison (6-5), Heshimu
Evans (6-6), Scott Padgett (6-9) and Michael Bradley (6-10), then
brings in Saul Smith (6-2), Ryan Hogan (6-3), Taysham Prince (6-8),
Jamal Magloire (6-10) and Jules Camara (6-10).
</P>
<P>
   ``It came about because the guys in the second group have proved
they deserve playing time,'' said UK coach Tubby Smith. ``I don't
see them (the second group) as second-stringers. I see them as a
weapon for helping us wear down our opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak promised that the RedHawks will be ready, and aware
of how many players UK rotates in and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like this is going to be our first 40-minute game of
the year,'' Szczerbiak said. ``We've played 31 games and we didn't
come out (of the lineup) very often. You build up a threshold, a
tolerance. We're used to playing 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak said the RedHawks may even be able to use Kentucky's
tactics to their advantage. ``With a platoon system,'' he
explained, ``sometimes you get out of the flow of the game. If we
get off to a hot start, we'll be warmed up and ready to go and
they'll be cold because of the way they go in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
