<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIAMI-MURNEN19-CO     03-18 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-MURNEN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murnens give Miami `a little something extra'
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The last basketball game Kurt Murnen saw was the
Miami RedHawks stumbling performance against Kent in the
Mid-American Conference tournament championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to poor defense and even worse shooting and ball
handling, Miami lost not only the game, 49-43, but apparently any
momentum heading into the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later _ on the evening of March 4 _ Kurt
Murnen, 19 years old, died from complications of his 2-year battle
with bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the RedHawks had competed against Kurt, who had been an
Alter High basketball star, and the rest of the players knew him
from his visits to Oxford. Told in November that nothing more could
be done to stop the spread of his cancer, Kurt had refused to
concede and made several trips to Millett Hall to see Miami play.
</P>
<P>
   He had a special affection for this team and especially for his
older brother, Jay, who is the head student manager of the RedHawks
and has a life-and-death story of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Had his health somehow taken a turn for the better, Kurt had
planned to enroll in classes at Miami to be closer to Jay.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone noticed that the last time or two Kurt showed up at
Millett, he was so short of breath, he could not make it up the
gymnasium steps without resting every few feet. And when the news
of Kurt's death hit the team, it shook enough people that coach
Charlie Coles was glad Jay took a few minutes to address the
RedHawks players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys Kurt's last game was that one against Kent and
I guess he decided we needed some real help,'' Jay said. ``I told
them he finally decided to give up his fight, so he could give us a
little divine inspiration come tournament time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think he has. I think he helped us in that Washington
game and especially against Utah. Now, I just hope he shows up
against Kentucky. I really think he gives this team a little
something extra.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source, something has transformed a Miami team that
lost three of its last six MAC games. Now the RedHawks _ from
cover-boy hero Wally Szczerbiak and humanist coach Charlie Coles to
the unheralded support players who have turned giant killers in the
dispatches of seventh-seeded Washington and No. 2 seed Utah _ are
the most embraceable Cinderellas left in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into tonight's Sweet 16 matchup with Kentucky at the
Trans World Dome, Miami has made its storied tournament run fueled
_ in part _ on Kurt Murnen's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Before last Sunday's game against Utah, Szczerbiak _ the hottest
player in the tournament, averaging 33.5 points and 9.5 rebounds a
game _ looked into the CBS cameras at courtside and said the rest
of the postseason was dedicated to Kurt.
</P>
<P>
   And as the team headed to the dressing room for final
instructions, Szczerbiak caught up to Jay, grabbed him by the
shoulder and said, ``This one's for you.'' Later, that promise was
mentioned during the CBS broadcast, as cameras focused on Jay, who
keeps a program from his brother's funeral service in the breast
pocket of his jacket _ ``so it's right over my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Murnen stirs support and devotion from RedHawks players and
coaches because he's more than just a four-year manager and someone
who once tried out for the team. He's also The Comeback Kid _ a guy
whose dramatic story Coles has used to inspire his team during this
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Murnen brothers had both followed in the basketball
footsteps of their dad, Pat Murnen, the captain and a top
scholar-athlete of the University of Dayton basketball teams of the
late '60s and early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   After lettering in three sports at Alter, Jay went to Miami and
took on managing duties, as he contemplated a walk-on bid that
following season. But then one April night in 1996, while horsing
around with some buddies in his Emerson Hall dormitory, Jay tried
sliding down a banister and lost his balance.
</P>
<P>
   He plummeted nearly three floors, landing head-first on a
concrete floor. His skull was fractured, his collarbone broken and
he nearly died right there. A rescue team finally arrived and soon
he was taken by CareFlight to Miami Valley Hospital, where he
drifted between comatose and semi-comatose for three months.
</P>
<P>
   If he did live, doctors wondered if he would wake up. And then,
would he even be able to think, much less talk or walk?
</P>
<P>
   Progress was slow, but Jay had a guardian angel in Kurt, who was
at his bedside everyday, holding his hand, mopping his brow,
coaxing him to awaken. Finally, Kurt got his brother to wink and
then to write a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother pulled me back to life,'' Jay said.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Jay's status improved, Kurt was diagnosed with
bone cancer. Yet, even with his surgeries and chemotherapy, he
refused to shelve his basketball and before the season ended he was
playing with a shunt in his chest and a padded chest protector
beneath his Alter jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything that went on with me and then coping with my
brother, it wasn't always easy. I had some real down times,'' Jay
said. ``But one guy was always there for me. Charlie Coles really
took an interest. He'd bring me into his office, shut the door and
just talk. He wanted to know how I was doing, how Kurt was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ` `Jay Murnen is one of my good friends,'' Coles said. ``The kid
is tough for all he went through. And he's conscientious. You can
count on him for anything. He handled himself pretty well this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay said it wasn't easy: ``Every time we went on the road, I had
to call home and give Dad the number so they could reach me quick
if something happened. I knew right before the MAC tournament
things were bad. Before I left home I told Kurt I loved him and he
told me that he loved me, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time we were in Toledo, I dreaded going back to my
hotel room. I didn't want the message light on my phone to be
blinking. Then, when we finally got back to Oxford, I called my
parents and asked them what was happening. They said, `We're here
with your brother...and he's dying.'''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jay got to Dayton, Kurt had died. Though devastated,
he was buoyed by the Miami team. Coles called and then three
coaches attended Kurt's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Kurt was buried, I went back to Miami that day,'' Jay
said. ``As soon as he saw me, Charlie hugged me. He told me,
`You've got support here. You're with people who love you.' And
I'll tell you, Miami basketball has been good for all of us now.
It's been a place I could put my mind into the last few weeks and
now my parents feel some of that, too. They're coming out here for
the Kentucky game.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Jay smiled: ``The way I see it _ Dad, Mom, me and
Kurt _ we'll all be here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
