<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES BILL TO CREATE MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following the Senate's lead, the House decisively
approved a bill on Thursday to field a system to defend the country
against a limited long-range missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a similar bill approved by the Senate on Wednesday, the
measure adopted by the House, 371-105, simply embraced the
principle of a national missile defense system. The Senate version
declares that the country install such a system ``as soon as
technologically possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House supports the Senate version, but not the House
bill, because the Senate measure explicitly backs continued
negotiations with Russia to reduce its still formidable nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., told reporters that the House
would probably accept the Senate's language when House and Senate
negotiators meet to reconcile differences between the two versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's action is a victory for the American people and their
personal security,'' Hastert said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The two bills have the strongest bipartisan support yet for a
system to defend against attacks from rogue nations like Iran and
North Korea, or missiles launched accidentally. China as well as
Russia has missiles capable of striking the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the mounting congressional pressure, and the more
menacing threats from North Korea and Iran, the White House
withdrew a veto threat of the Senate bill on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the 15-word House bill came after a rare 90-minute
closed briefing on the floor attended by about 250 lawmakers. The
legislators heard from former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld,
who headed a bipartisan commission that reported last year that
North Korea and Iran were much closer to developing a ballistic
missile threat than the Central Intelligence Agency had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate debated its version of the bill for three days,
adopting two amendments, the House Republican leadership barred all
amendments and wrapped up the House debate in one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Senate bill, the House one does not authorize a
specific antimissile design or appropriate money to pay for it.
Indeed, the bill is so vague that its chief Democratic sponsor,
Rep. John Spratt Jr. of South Carolina, said lawmakers could read
into the measure whatever conditions they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   All but two Republicans _ Constance Morella of Maryland and
Vernon Ehlers of Michigan _ supported the bill. But Democrats were
sharply divided, with 103 for the bill and 102 against it.
</P>
<P>
   The lone independent, Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, voted
against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The two top Democrats, Reps. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the
minority leader, and David Bonior of Michigan, the minority whip,
opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's critics said the measure would commit the country to
spend billions of dollars on a defense that terrorist states could
circumvent with cruise missiles or car bombs. Rep. Lynn Woolsey,
D-Calif., said: ``What are really investing in? I fear what we'll
be investing in is a false sense of security.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics said the measure relied on as yet unproved
technology and also risked alienating Russia, which has conditioned
further reductions in its nuclear arsenal on Washington's
compliance with the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty of 1972. Fielding
an anti-missile system would require changes in that treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not do anything to advance the technological capacity
to protect our nation,'' said Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Calif., ``and
could reverse efforts to reduce Russia's nuclear arsenal. This bill
is a blank check for defense contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters said the cost of a limited system _ now budgeted
at $10.5 billion _ would be well worth it. ``The cost of inaction
and the cost of vulnerability are much higher,'' said Rep. Jim
Turner, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., said: ``Today, we live in an age
of ballistic missiles. Our adversaries are making faster and faster
missiles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
