<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY DOESN'T CHANGE ANGELS' SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  TEMPE, Ariz. -- For those who hang out outside the ballpark
before games, waiting for your favorite ballplayers to arrive and
sign autographs, you are hereby notified that Angels pitcher Steve
Sparks might slip right past you.
</P>
<P>
   If you're watching for a Mercedes Benz with tinted windows to
pull into the parking lot, you might catch Mo Vaughn, but not
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks is more likely to pull up in a mini-van.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Sparks can't afford a Mercedes -- he signed a
one-year contract during the off-season for $1.35 million. It's
just that Sparks, his wife Michelle and their two children (Alexa
and Blake and another on the way) have learned to live a frugal
lifestyle -- out of necessity.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you spend nine years in the minor
leagues, in places like Helena, Montana and Beloit, Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks has spent the off-seasons working odd jobs, including one
as a substitute teacher near his home in Sugarland, Tex. As
recently as the fall and winter before the 1998 season, Sparks
would wait for that 5:30 a.m. phone call from the school district
office for the invitation to teach.
</P>
<P>
   This past off-season, Sparks was ``Mr. Mom, shuttling the kids
to and from school and taking care of household duties while
Michelle went to work. ``She takes care of everything during the
season, so it's my turn to help out, Sparks says.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the way Sparks and Michelle run their lives and
take care of the family. It has worked in the tough times, so
there's no reason to change, Sparks believes, now that he's making
good money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'll change anything,'' said Sparks, 33.
``We're pretty much grounded in what we want to do with our lives.
I'm never not going to work. ... Neither of us grew up with much.
So we appreciate and are thankful for the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might super-size at McDonald's, or buy two-ply toilet
paper, but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks earned this year's salary because of last year's
performance. After joining the club in June, Sparks went 9-4 with a
4.34 ERA in 22 games (20 starts). He had a six-game winning streak
from June 29-Sept. 2 and pitched into the seventh inning or later
14 times.
</P>
<P>
   He was about as reliable as a knuckeballer can be, even though
there was no reason to expect anything from him.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks had reconstructive surgery on his right (pitching) elbow
after injuring it in spring training of 1997 while playing for the
Milwaukee Brewers. He didn't pitch at all in 1997 then went job
hunting after the Brewers released him. He called general manager
after general manager but found no takers until getting Angels
general manager Bill Bavasi on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we had some pretty good hitting clubs, and I
noticed if knuckleballers are on, there was really no defense
against them,'' Bavasi explained. ``And the hitters would be a
little off in the next game too. They'll give you a lot of innings
and a completely different look.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi agreed to give Sparks a shot, but Sparks didn't exactly
set the world on fire. He was 0-4 at double-A Midland and 0-4 at
triple-A Vancouver. The win-loss record was deceiving, though. It
wasn't an indication of how he was throwing, and the Angels called
him up on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a weapon not a lot of people have,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``And when it's working, he wins games. Right
now the challenge is making sure we have a guy who can catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Molitor said it was the best knuckleball he ever faced.
Coming from Paul Molitor, that was good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks thought he had arrived in 1995, when he went 9-11 with a
4.63 ERA with the Brewers. That, after eight full seasons in the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subconsciously, after that year I felt I could pitch there for
a while,'' Sparks said. ``I didn't take it for granted, but
subconsciously I felt I belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sparks found himself back in the minors for much of
1996, then blew out his elbow in spring of 1997 when he tried to
halt his throw on a relay to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally got another opportunity to pitch in the big
leagues with the Angels last season, Sparks went to the mound with
a do-or-die attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally felt every start I was pitching for my job, he
said. ``I put a lot of pressure on myself. I'll do the same this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this year, who knows? Sparks is well-aware that
knuckleball pitchers have a history of pitching well into their
40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel if I can stay in shape I can stay for a while,'' he
said. ``Some of those guys (knuckleballers) leave because of a knee
or a hip, not their arm.''
</P>
<P>
   KNUCKLEBALL LONGEVITY
</P>
<P>
   Player, age of retirement, years in majors
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt Whilhelm, 49, 21 years
</P>
<P>
   Phil Niekro, 48, 24 years
</P>
<P>
   Joe Niekro 43, 22 years
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Hough, 41, 20 years
</P>
<P>
   Tom Candiotti, 41, 16th year (active)
</P>
<P>
   Wilber Wood, 36, 17 years
</P>
</TEXT>
