<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NUHN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good fortune, good decisions and hope bring O'Brien and his team
to Regional
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ He is 48 years old, Hollywood handsome with a
coif of white hair always combed perfectly. If you were casting a
college basketball coach, you would cast Jim O'Brien the moment he
walked into your office.
</P>
<P>
   That Ohio State did cast him two years ago after the Randy Ayers
Era became a never-ending parade of Buckeyes onto the police
blotter is almost as much a result of good fortune as it was a good
decision.
</P>
<P>
   First, two high-profile coaches, Rick Barnes and Tubby Smith,
had to turn down the Buckeyes, while another, Mike Montgomery, used
the leverage of the OSU opening to get himself a sweetheart deal at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   File that in the good fortune category.
</P>
<P>
   Next, O'Brien was unhappy at his then-job at Boston College
because the school's admission office had just rejected two of his
prized recruits despite the fact they met all NCAA standards.
</P>
<P>
   File that in the good fortune category.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, OSU athletic director Andy Geiger decided despite
O'Brien's career coaching record of 235-217 at St. Bonaventure and
BC, that there was more to the man than the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   File that in the good decision category.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien came to Columbus in 1998 with a totally Eastern
background _ born and raised in Brooklyn; college star at BC;
coached in the East for 20 years, 15 as a head man. Predictably,
there was culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``After spending my entire adult life in the Northeast, I had no
idea how the other half lived,'' he said. ``My eyes have been
opened. When I was first contacted by Ohio State, guys would call
me and say, `You're involved with Ohio State?' I was like, `What's
so great about Ohio State?' Then I got here and said, `Oh, my God.
This is a great opportunity.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far it has been opportunity grabbed. When O'Brien's second
OSU team lined up Thursday night for the NCAA South Regional
semifinal against Auburn, it was the school's first visit to a
Regional in seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in March, O'Brien remembers ``going out and recruiting
my brains out'' during the week, then sitting at his house,
watching the tournament on TV on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of all the coaches who go to the tournament year
after year,'' he said. ``I was wondering if they truly appreciate
it. And I was thinking they couldn't appreciate it unless they
experienced the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd just experienced the other side: an 8-22 record that
included 1-15 in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where you want to be in March,'' he said. ``And the
best part of all this is what the players are feeling now. I've
been telling them from the beginning _ unless you've been here, you
don't know what you're missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what they were missing, but they didn't. Now they know.
And next year, the kids will know they want to get back here. You
can't overestimate how important that is.''
</P>
<P>
   In three of his last four years at BC, he had gone to a Regional
final in 1994 and been eliminated in the second round in both 1996
and '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last March was horrid,'' O'Brien said. ``But the players
didn't know. You can talk to them all you want. Other than Scoonie
(Penn), no one on this team knew. You don't appreciate all this
unless you struggle to get it. But once you get here, you want to
be here every year.''
</P>
<P>
   This year then will carry over to next. Whatever happened
against Auburn, that's O'Brien's hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
