<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-UPDATE1_SFCHRO     03-18 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-UPDATE1_SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (adds credit line)   Column: Why This Columnist Finds Boring the Obsession With Dow 
 10,000 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Two-and-a-half lousy points.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but this obsession with the industrials
closing above 10K is about as exciting as watching grass grow. That
is to say, it's slightly more scintillating than watching the
Senate put the president on trial when everybody knew the upper
house would never toss the Defendant in Chief out on his keister.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Dow, however, at least there's a snowball's
chance in Hades that history will repeat itself. Just as it took
more than six years for the Dow to close above 1,000 after first
hitting the mark, it might take another six years before the
storied stock market index reaches the latest but arbitrary
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   There's a better chance that the industrials will close above
10,000 before the weekend starts. But don't expect me to be glued
to CNBC, I'll be outside cutting my lawn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KICKING IN:  &LR; San Francisco Soccer Development Corp., the
company that owns the San Francisco Bay Seals, has scored an
institutional shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Peacock Financial, a publicly held holding company that is
traded over the counter, has taken a 5 percent stake in the minor
league pro soccer team. What's more, Peacock has secured an option
to buy an additional 5 percent on top of that over the next six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Peacock Financial of San Jacinto (Riverside
County) to swap $100,000 worth of its shares for 200,000 shares of
Seals stock. Of course, a hundred-thousand bucks wouldn't even
cover the minimum annual salary of an NBA bench warmer, but it's a
start.
</P>
<P>
   Another disconcerting thing is that Peacock isn't exactly GE
Financial. Still, it is an institutional shareholder nonetheless,
and that should help raise the profile of minor league soccer team
within the financial community, says Yan Skwara, director of
corporate finance for the Seals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being that Peacock is publicly traded, it continues to expose
the offering to Wall Street,'' Skwara says.
</P>
<P>
   Peacock, whose stock is trading at 15 cents a share on the OTC
Bulletin Board, is trying to rebound from a rocky real estate
development past, Skwara says.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: Investing in minor league soccer is mostly about
helping the world's most popular sport maintain its footing on
American turf. If you want to quadruple your money, may I suggest
you invest in an Internet stock with fat annual loss projections.
</P>
<P>
   As regular readers of Street Smarts may recall, this column
reported that the Seals minor league soccer club hopes to raise $1
million through a private placement. So far, a handful of
individuals have invested in the Seals, but Peacock is the first
investor to buy a block, Skwara says.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note that Skwara is also the chief executive
of the San Diego Flash, which competes with the Seals in the same
league. Their teams are rivals in the top rung of the United Soccer
League, which is comparable to baseball's Triple A level. In a
spirit of cooperation that you aren't likely to find between, say,
the Raiders' Al Davis and the 49ers' Bill Walsh, Skwara has the
unusual role of also overseeing the Seals' corporate finance
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Why help a competitor raise money?
</P>
<P>
   Because professional soccer in the United States needs all the
financial help it can get, says Skwara, an investment banker and a
former stock broker.
</P>
<P>
   In short, raising the economic values of other teams should pump
up the price of his San Diego franchise, he says. He believes that
minor league soccer franchises could see their values increase
because the number of teams to be allowed in the United Soccer
League's top division is being capped at 32.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, thinking longer term, Skwara contends that San
Diego and the northern Bay Area deserve to have big-league soccer
and that both the Flash and Seals could possibly join Major League
Soccer some day. (The Bay Area's lone major league franchise is the
San Jose Clash.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our business plan for both the Flash and Seals to
become Major League Soccer franchises,'' Skwara muses.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Major League Soccer would have to drastically revamp
its policies and financial structure for its franchises to see
significant leaps in value. But Skwara is betting that the sport's
top professional league is moving in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Skwara plans to implement an alternative exit
strategy for investors. The Flash's CEO plans to take his soccer
franchise public in June.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego club is wrapping up a $1 million private placement
similar to the one now in progress for the Seals. Once that is
done, the Flash is expected to offer stock to the public for about
$5 a share in June.
</P>
<P>
   The offering is expected to be managed by Lloyd Wade Securities
of Dallas, which currently owns about 2,000 shares of the Flash,
and First Midwest Securities of Milwaukee, which was the lead
manager of a 1997 IPO for the Orlando Predators of the Arena
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that we can execute this offering effectively,''
Skwara predicts.
</P>
<P>
   He has reasons to be optimistic. The Flash expects to grow
merchandising revenues, is talking to San Diego officials about a
possible new stadium and has had a corporate sponsor for more than
a year. Delta Air Lines provides free airline tickets to the team
worth upwards of $50,000 in exchange for marketing rights. (A
similar deal between the Seals and Delta was just cut this week.)
</P>
<P>
   And if the Flash's IPO is successful, don't be surprised if
Skwara plans a similar offering for the Seals. That, of course,
assumes that the San Francisco team sells out its private placement
first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
