<SLUG> BC-CUBA-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$6 MILLION HELD FOR CUBA MUST GO TO U.S. FAMILIES, JUDGE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal judge ruled Thursday that more than $6.2
million owed to Cuba by telephone companies in the United States
must now be paid to the families of three Cuban-Americans who were
killed in 1996 when their planes were shot down over international
waters by Cuban fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge James King ordered that the money, part of
an estimated $19 million in payments to Cuba held in escrow because
of legal wrangling over the attack, be released to the fliers'
relatives, a move that seems to clear the way for garnishment of
other Cuban assets.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over this money, owed to Cuban communications
company Empresa de Telecomunicaciones de Cuba SA by AT&AMP;T and other
companies, is why Cuba suspended direct dial telephone service to
the United States on Feb. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this is a step in the direction of justice, but our
goal is to have the criminals behind bars,'' said Miriam De la
Pena, whose son, Mario De la Pena, was among four pilots killed on
Feb. 4, 1996, while searching for Cuban rafters in the Florida
Straits.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban MIGs shot down two small planes, killing De la Pena and
three other members of the Miami organization Brothers to the
Rescue, prompting the families of three of the fliers to sue the
Cuban Air Force and the Republic of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   They won a judgment of $187 million in 1997, but had no way to
collect the money _ officials in Havana ignored the judgment _
until they went to federal court in Miami to try to seize Cuban
assets in the United States. They sought the money owed to the
Cuban government by American companies that provided long-distance
telephone service to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Today, King ruled that the fliers' relatives were entitled to
$6.2 million _ part of about $19 million _ from AT&AMP;T, MCI
International Inc., and other American companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reviewing the court's opinion and considering our
options to appeal,'' said Dianne Bernez, a spokeswoman for AT&AMP;T,
which had the largest amount _ more than $4 million _ affected by
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bernez said that AT&AMP;T believed that Empresa de
Telecomunicaciones, a venture between the Cuban government and an
Italian communications corporation, ``is an independent legal
entity that is not liable for the deaths'' of the fliers.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the fliers' relatives argued that the Cuban
telephone company was largely owned and controlled by the Communist
government, and that the government was liable for the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also said that the ruling may clear the way for
other garnishments involving business between Cuba and U.S.
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling goes against the wishes of President Clinton and his
advisers, who had argued that the long-standing U.S. trade embargo
with Cuba prohibited any financial dealings with the Cuban
government, including garnishments, unless specifically permitted
by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Cuban government's decision to sever the telephone
links between the U.S. communications companies and Cuba,
long-distance telephone service was never really cut off to the
island, because calls were rerouted through other countries, like
Mexico, and placed by companies not named in the lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
