<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-AVERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S WILLIAM AVERY ERASES ALL DOUBTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In retrospect, it seems absurd. Duke, a
team that has won 34 of 35 games by an average margin of 26 points,
started the season with this unanswered question:
</P>
<P>
   Could sophomore William Avery replace point guard Steve
Wojciechowski?
</P>
<P>
   Wojciechowski was the emotional and spiritual leader of last
year's team that finished 32-4. He was a scrappy player who made
the most of limited ability. Avery was clearly a talented player,
but as a freshman he got few chances to show his ability to run a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year he was more of a hired gun,'' said sophomore center
Elton Brand. ``He got in the game and started jacking it up. He
didn't care, he kept shooting and shooting; he was more worried
about the points.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the points are still there (15.1 per game). But so
are the assists (5.2 per game). Avery, a 6-foot-2, 185-pounder, has
proven that he can run Duke's offense and spark its defense.
Whether it is half-court or full-court, Avery is in the driver's
seat of the Blue Devils' 93-points-a-game machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had probably the most important, terrific year of all of
our kids,'' Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said. ``We had the belief he
would be really good, but he's been better. He's a very hard worker
and wants to learn. He prepares well. He really likes to play and
I've tried to give him a lot of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   During the recruiting process, Krzyzewski questioned Avery's
grades, which were borderline for Duke. After the meeting, Avery
firmly told his mother: ``I'm going to Duke.'' He attended Oak Hill
Academy in Virginia, a prep school, to improve his grades and his
game.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Avery averaged 8.5 points and 2.5 assists per game.
His inconsistent freshman season planted the seeds of doubt coming
into this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what people were saying, and I took it as a
challenge,'' Avery said. ``I like challenges. I wanted to prove to
everyone that I could do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand, Avery's roommate, leads Duke in scoring and rebounding.
But the sophomore center says that Avery is the Blue Devils' most
valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   And Avery seems intent on proving his roomie's theory. When
senior Trajan Langdon was sidelined for three games with a broken
foot recently, Avery, the team's only other true guard, scored 55
points and made 9 of 20 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm aggressive and attacking, the team plays that way,''
said Avery, a native of Augusta, Ga. ``A point guard has to lead,
whether by example or by being vocal. I'm more of an example guy
and not that vocal. I'm more vocal now than I have ever been in my
basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a natural thing for me. It's something I've had to
work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery had a career-high 30 points against Cincinnati. That was
Duke's only loss, but Avery's feathery-soft runner from the
baseline tied the score at 75-all. He's shooting a remarkable 50
percent from the field, 41 percent on his 3-pointers and 81 percent
from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's showed everyone he can move this team to
victory,'' Brand said. ``He's playing a great floor game, he's
getting assists, scoring, playing great defense. That's all you can
ask in a point guard.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
