<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-NYT &LR;      03-18 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: LONG-SHOT HOUSE VOTE TO LIMIT STEEL IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With surprising force and fury, the House vote to limit steel
imports reflects a strong sense of frustration within the domestic
steel industry over low-price steel that landed on U.S. shores
during economic crises in Asia and Russia last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure, a violation of world trade rules and a
long-shot at best in the Senate, would do little to help the U.S.
steel industry in the long run, even if the measure _ or a form of
it _ were to be enacted. The industry is still losing about 10,000
jobs a year, is saddled with plants that are very expensive to run
and is constantly buffeted by economic forces beyond its control
from lands far away.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, this measure, decried as a protectionist gift to
gain union votes for the 2000 election by both parties, comes as
the U.S. steel industry begins to recover from the wave of imports
that drove down steel prices to 25-year lows last year. The
industry is about to benefit from a growing demand for steel
products from an economy that continues to remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   That is the good news for the short run. Within the next year,
analysts expect that there will be enough demand to keep U.S. steel
manufacturers running at full capacity. Just this month, steel
makers pushed through a price increase and have seen that imports,
which last year caused havoc in steel prices, are now beginning to
return to more normal levels _ in January 1999 steel imports came
to 2.7 million tons, compared with 2.5 million tons the previous
January.
</P>
<P>
   Still, U.S. steel makers fear that what happened to them in late
1998, when low-cost imports from Japan, Russia, Brazil and other
economically troubled countries soared to nearly 4 million tons a
month, or nearly 40 percent of the domestic market, will happen
again. They contend that the industry, which faces falling
employment and marginal profitability, cannot sustain a similar
blow.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, even though many in the steel industry readily
admit that the House's 289-141 vote for import limits was largely
symbolic, it represents a renewed belief in the need for
protectionist measures _ a view that free-trade advocates say is
dangerous and which runs afoul of the Clinton administration's
free-market views. A presidential veto remains possible. In fact,
the House-passed measure is the first in a package of about eight
trade bills that the steel industry and unions want to see
introduced in the 106th Congress. The measure would limit steel
imports to pre-1997 levels, in violation of World Trade
Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This measure is both symbolic and real,'' said Curtis ``Hank''
Barnette, the chief executive of Bethlehem Steel, who will speak on
behalf of the bill before the Senate Finance Committee next
Tuesday. ``We are actively working with other steel companies and
the unions to carry our message as forcefully as we can. We're
pleased that the House has recognized what we are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers of America,
also praised the measure. ``With 10,000 steelworkers already out of
work, three major steel producers in bankruptcy, another on the
brink, and virtually every steel producer experiencing huge losses,
action isn't an option; it's an absolute necessity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, say that the steel industry's concerns are
overstated and that their approach is dangerous _ a continuation on
a decades-old pattern of calling on Washington for help. ``This is
very blatant politicking on behalf of Congress to appeal to special
interests in the steel industry and unions,'' said Waldo Best, an
analyst with Morgan Stanley. ``It creates the image that something
is being done, but nothing is really being done. This is a very
political piece of legislation that won't do anything meaningful
for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Crandall, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research group, said the measure
``doesn't mean much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that the surge of imports had some effects
on steel makers, but this measure will have little impact on the
industry in the long run,'' he said. ``The real problem for
old-line big steel is that they are being eaten alive by the
mini-mills, which are making life miserable for these big guys. We
are talking about a long-drawn out end game for big steel.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last half-century, the American steel industry has
continued to shrink; today it has about 170,000 employees compared
with 500,000 in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the steel producers complain about low-cost imports,
users of steel benefit. General Motors Corp., for instance, opposes
the limits. ``We are in opposition to this resolution and think
it's a rush to judgment that will probably have serious economic
implications,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas steel producers often operate in the same way as big
steel makers here but, at times of economic turmoil in their home
countries, they have shipped steel products to the United States at
extremely low prices in an attempt to to stabilize their economies.
These overseas producers often have far lower labor costs than in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hoffman, a steel analyst with Prudential Securities, said
that by the time United States steel companies _ which have
successfully filed anti-dumping suits against Brazil and Japan _
got relief in the form of high tariff protections, the crisis would
have passed. Moreover, Hoffman said the House vote also reflected
anti-Clinton sentiment both in the House and in the industry over
the administration's slow response.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of free trade and some steel importers were adamant
in their opposition to import restrictions. ``This is one of the
worst pieces of legislation to come out of the House, and that's
saying a lot,'' said Dan Griswold, associate director for trade
policy studies at the Cato Institute. ``There is not a steel crisis
issue. Just look at the high level of steel shipments.''
</P>
<P>
   David Phelps, the executive director of the American Institute
for International Steel, a trade group, added: ``The steel industry
is historically addicted to trade protection and that addiction has
yet to be broken. We hope the Senate will give this ridiculous bill
the indecent burial it deserves.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
