u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHROP-EARNINGS-NYT     03-18 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHROP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHROP GRUMMAN TO RESTATE RESULTS FOR A WRITE-OFF LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Northrop Grumman Corp. said Thursday that it would
restate its results for the fourth quarter of 1998, taking a loss
because of a write-off associated with an investment in a start-up
rocket company.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop said it had written off $30 million it had provided to
Kistler Aerospace Corp. because of uncertainty over Kistler's
ability to raise the money needed to complete its K-1 re-usable
launcher vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Northrop will report a loss for the fourth quarter
of $3 million, or 4 cents a diluted share, rather than the net
profit of $17 million, or 24 cents a share, the company announced
in February. The adjustment is being made to fourth-quarter
earnings because the company has not yet filed its yearly financial
statements with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement is the latest in a series of jolts to
its earnings that the big military contractor experienced in the
last year, when the company was hurt by the collapse of its planned
acquisition by Lockheed Martin Corp., cutbacks in production by
Boeing Co., a major customer, and problems with some military
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also reflects the financial challenges facing
the small companies trying to develop re-usable launcher vehicles
that could hoist satellites into orbit far more cheaply than either
the space shuttle or the expendable rockets now used.
</P>
<P>
   Of these companies, Kistler, based in Kirkland, Wash., is
considered the front-runner and the best financed, having already
raised $450 million. Its chief executive, George Mueller, headed
the Apollo project and other manned space programs at NASA. And the
company has already signed up a customer, Space Systems/Loral,
which agreed to pay more than $100 million for 10 launchings.
</P>
<P>
   But Kistler, which needs to raise several hundred million
dollars more, canceled a $300 million junk-bond offering last year
after market conditions soured. When the rocket company ran short
of cash, Northrop, which has a $145 million contract to build
composite structures for the Kistler launcher, deferred payment on
$30 million worth of work.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the two companies agreed to convert that debt into
preferred stock in Kistler, but Northrop and its auditors
determined that the investment had to be written off.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Waugh, Northrop's chief financial officer, said in a
statement that his company still thinks Kistler's concept ``has
significant promise for future business.'' He said Northrop would
invest an additional $30 million before the first test flight if
the K-1 program remained viable. Northrop also has the option to
purchase up to $120 million more in stock, Kistler officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kistler's launcher will be based on engines developed by the
Soviet Union for its moon program but never used. The vehicle's two
stages will return to earth using parachutes and air bags. Kistler
hopes to conduct its first test flight early next year from the
Australian desert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
