<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-BKC-MARYLAND-STJO     03-18 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-BKC-MARYLAND-STJOHNS19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Red Storm blows away Terps
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Now Maryland knows how Indiana suffered. Five
days after handing the Hoosiers their worst NCAA Tournament defeat,
St. John's stormed to 19-point halftime lead, extended it to 26,
then withstood a frantic Maryland rally for a 76-62 win Thursday
night in the NCAA South Region semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley's 24 points put third-seeded St. John's (28-8)
into Saturday's final and leaves the Red Storm one win shy of its
first Final Four since 1985. No. 2 seed Maryland, meanwhile,
finishes 28-6 and, as ever, still looking for its first Final Four
appearance after a disastrous dry spell late in the first half that
allowed St. John's to close with a 19-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   For Maryland, Laron Profit knew, the time was now after a season
spent in Duke's shadow. ``Maryland has been on the cusp of
greatness and had their opportunities,'' he'd said, alluding to the
John Lucas-Len Elmore teams of the early '70s, the Len Bias teams
of the '80s, the Joe Smith teams of the '90s _ none of which had
ever reached the Final Four. ``We feel like this is our
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only for Maryland basketball, but we're being a little
selfish,'' said the senior swingman. ``This is our last time around
and we want to go out with a bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Profit and Co. were quickly living one last nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The night began promisingly enough. After St. John's took an
early 9-4 lead, the Terps quickly drew even on two free throws and
a 3-pointer by Terence Morris. Then Steve Francis scored on a drive
for his first basket. It was also his last in a disastrous first
half for Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   As it had in last Saturday's destruction of Indiana, St. John's
began in man-to-man defense, then switched to a 2-3 zone. The zone
undid Maryland, as it had Indiana. Profit hit a pull-up jumper over
the zone for a 19-18 Terps lead. Then St. John's rained on the
Terps.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland missed its last 10 shots of the half. The Terps also
committed eight of their 13 first-half turnovers once St. John's
went to a zone. And playing as tough and unselfishly as they did
against Indiana, the Johnnies blew it open with a 20-0 rush to
close the half.
</P>
<P>
   With Maryland center Lonnie Baxter sitting out the last 17
minutes of the first half after drawing two quick fouls, St. John's
dominated inside. The front line of Ron Artest, Lavor Postell and
Tyrone Grant combined for 15 points and 11 boards.
</P>
<P>
   But the backcourt ruled, too. Bootsy Thornton torched Maryland's
man-to-man for nine points (4-for-8 from the floor) and Barkley,
the point guard, had eight points and seven assists. In the second
half, St. John's opened up a 22-point bulge, 41-19, before Brian
Watkins finally tipped in yet another Maryland miss. It was the
Terps' first points in 10:27.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
