<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAARDP19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gonzaga grabs win against Florida
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cinderella is alive and well in the West Region of the
NCAA Tournament. In fact, she's only one win away from the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga continued its surprising tournament run Thursday by
defeating Florida 73-72 in the region semifinals in Phoenix.
Trailing by one in the final seconds, Gonzaga's Casey Calvary
tapped in a missed shot by Quentin Hall for a one-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Florida had a chance to win, but Eddie Shannon's 3-point attempt
bounced off the rim at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs (28-6), who had never won an NCAA Tournament game
before this year, Saturday will face the winner of the
Connecticut-Iowa semifinal for a berth to the Final Four. Gonzaga,
making only its second NCAA appearance in school history, opened a
10-point first-half lead and held off a late run by Florida (22-9),
which was making its first Sweet 16 appearance in five years.
</P>
<P>
   In the South Regional, St. John's (28-8) routed Maryland 76-62
to move within a game of its first Final Four appearance since
1985. St. John's closed the first half with a 20-0 run, opening a
38-19 halftime, and survived a 19-2 spurt by Maryland in the second
half to advance to its first regional final since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley scored 24 points to lead St. John's, which will
play the winner of the Auburn-Ohio State semifinal Saturday for a
trip to the Final Four. Maryland (28-6), which tied its lowest
scoring output of the season in the loss, was eliminated in the
region semifinals for the fourth time in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kentucky (27-8) will continue its quest for a second straight
title tonight when it faces surprising Miami of Ohio (24-7) in the
Midwest semifinals. Kentucky, which has won 19 of its last 20
tournament games over the last four years, will have to contend
with Miami senior Wally Szczerbiak, who has scored 67 points in two
tournament games. The other Midwest semifinal matches top seed
Michigan State (31-4), which has won 20 straight, against 13th seed
Oklahoma (22-10), the lowest seed remaining in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ Southwest Missouri State (22-10) will become the latest team
to attempt to halt Duke's run to the Final Four as the teams meet
in an East semifinal. Southwest Missouri State, the 12th seed,
upset Wisconsin and Tennessee in its first two games, but will face
a Duke (34-1) squad that has won 29 straight, including 41-point
victories in its two tournament games. Temple (23-10) meets Purdue
(21-12) in the other East semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
