<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-REPORT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House wanted Audie, and they got him
 &HT;    By staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Rep. Jerry Madden (R-Richardson) on Thursday
rallied the troops behind the most famous World War II soldier of
them all, Texan Audie Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Madden and the dozens of other House members who wore
``WE WANT AUDIE!'' pins during Thursday's session wanted a portrait
of Murphy, the most decorated soldier of World War II, re-hung in
the House chamber. Members returned this January to find that the
portrait had been replaced by one of Gen. Ernest Othmer Thompson,
commander of the Texas National Guard, member of the Railroad
Commission and onetime mayor of Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was ``the common Texan who rose to historic proportions,
just like at the Alamo, so we think his proper place is here,''
Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Crawford, executive director of the State Preservation
Board, said Murphy's portrait was removed about six months ago so
it could be part of an exhibit at the Capitol Visitors' Center
honoring Texas winners of the Medal of Honor. Most of the artifacts
displayed there were removed at the end of February, but as of
Thursday morning, Audie was still absent from the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said Madden called him Thursday morning to let him know
that he was launching his Audie campaign that day _ and by Thursday
afternoon, Audie was back. Crawford said the Preservation board
planned to return the Murphy portrait all along .
</P>
<P>
   `` It makes us look like we're pretty responsive, though,''
Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN RECORDS LAW REVISED
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a bill Thursday that would require the
attorney general to render opinions on open records law requests
within 45 days and cut down the length of an extension.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, by state Sen. John Carona (R-Dallas), also would
prohibit a state agency from asking the attorney general to
reconsider an open records opinion against it.
</P>
<P>
   Current law now allows the attorney general to issue an opinion
within 60 days and provides the possibility of 20 additional days,
if the attorney general notifies the agency and the person who
seeks the information.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGENCY SPENDING BILL SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   A $110 million emergency spending bill for items ranging from
boll weevil eradication to child protective services won Gov.
George W. Bush's approval on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With his signature, Bush turned into law a bill that would
include funding for teacher training for improved reading skills;
assistance to cotton farmers hard hit by drought; and funding for
disaster relief including flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Sen. Bill Ratliff (R-Mount Pleasant) has a price tag
that includes $103 million in state general revenue funding.
</P>
<P>
   It is effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER IMPROVEMENTS APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Senate unanimously adopted legislation on Thursday to
help improve border conditions.
</P>
<P>
   University research into environmental issues affecting the
Texas-Mexico border region would be encouraged through the
state-funded Advanced Research Program, under one bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The well-being of Texas communities on the Rio Grande is tied
to their sister cities in Mexico,'' said Sen. Carlos Truan
(D-Corpus Christi), bill author. ``Their problems become our
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
