<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-UNION-SUIT-NY     03-18 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-UNION-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDICT BACKS CIGARETTE MAKERS IN SUIT BY UNION HEALTH PLANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Minn., Miss., Ohio, Texas)  (rk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a major legal victory for tobacco companies, a federal jury
in Akron, Ohio, ruled Thursday that the companies did not have to
repay dozens of union health and benefit plans in that state the
costs of treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit by the union health plans, which was patterned after
recent tobacco cases brought by state attorneys general, was the
first of its kind to reach trial. As a result, it was viewed by
industry analysts as a watershed. A verdict in favor of the union
plans, which were seeking up to $2 billion in damages, could have
created financial turmoil for some cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   In the class-action lawsuit, more than 100 union health plans in
Ohio representing a variety of building trades said cigarette
makers had conspired to hide evidence of smoking dangers and, as a
result, should have to reimburse the plans for health care costs.
The jury deliberated over three days before returning a verdict in
favor of the companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with this jury's verdict,'' said a statement
released Thursday by the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., a
subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC. ``The trial demonstrated that
when the tobacco companies have an opportunity to present the facts
in response to speculative allegations about their conduct, the
allegations collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The other defendants in the case included Philip Morris Cos.,
the RJ Reynolds Tobacco Co., a subsidiary of the RJR Nabisco
Holdings Corp. and the Lorillard Tobacco Co., a subsidiary of the
Loews Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Coughlin, the union funds' chief lawyer, told The
Associated Press he was disappointed in the jury's assessment of
the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to understand how somebody could look at all that
activity and then say that's all right or that didn't impact
millions and millions of people,'' Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, tobacco company stocks rose, with a share of
Philip Morris stock gaining $3.75 to close at $42. A share of RJR
Nabisco gained $1.6875 to close at $30.3135.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict represented yet another tilt in the unsettled legal
seesaw affecting the tobacco industry. Last month, a state jury in
San Francisco granted the biggest tobacco award in history when it
ordered Philip Morris to pay $51.5 million to a woman who said her
inoperable lung cancer had been caused by more than 35 years of
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The recent $206 billion settlement between tobacco companies and
46 states did not cover ongoing or future lawsuits brought by
individual smokers or groups like the health insurance plans.
Before that accord, the industry had reached settlements worth some
$40 billion over 25 years with four other states, Florida,
Minnesota, Mississippi and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The state lawsuits were filed to seek reimbursement of Medicaid
money spent treating smoking-related illnesses. The union lawsuits,
which have been filed in several states, have tried to follow that
model by asserting that the producers are liable for reimbursing
similar health-fund costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
