<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. TRADE DEFICIT SOARS TO ALMOST $17 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit jumped to a new monthly record of nearly
$17 billion in January, fueled by a flood of imports from China
that could stir further protectionist sentiments in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Among the imports pouring into the nation was Chinese-made
steel, which increased 65 percent from December. The House passed a
bill Wednesday that would sharply limit steel imports, ignoring
opposition from the Republican leadership and a White House warning
that the measure would violate world trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The House's vote to limit steel imports reflects a sense of
frustration within the domestic steel industry over the low-priced
steel that landed on U.S. shores during the economic crises in Asia
and Russia last year.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO COMPANIES WIN OHIO SUIT
</P>
<P>
   In a significant legal victory for tobacco companies, a federal
jury in Akron, Ohio, ruled that they do not have to reimburse
dozens of union health and benefit plans in that state for the
costs of treating smoking-related illnesses. A verdict in favor of
the union plans, which were seeking up to $2 billion in damages,
could have created financial turmoil for some cigarette makers.
After the verdict, tobacco company stocks rose, with shares of
Philip Morris gaining $3.75, to $42.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA WEST TALKS CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   America West Airlines and its flight attendants met in
Washington for a second day of federally mediated talks in an
attempt to reach an agreement before a strike deadline at midnight
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co., according to aerospace industry analysts, is banking
its future on Alan Mulally, the newly appointed head of its
troubled commercial airplane division.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT UPDATES ITS BROWSER
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft chairman Bill Gates introduced a new version of his
company's Web browser that includes a feature that enables Internet
sites to distribute their own versions of the program. Netscape
Communications, Microsoft's chief rival in the browser market, has
allowed this kind of customization for some customers.
</P>
<P>
   HACKER SAID TO REACH PLEA BARGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mitnick, perhaps the nation's most notorious computer
hacker, has reached a plea bargain with federal prosecutors that
could pave the way for his release from prison, people familiar
with the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHROP GRUMMAN TO RESTATE RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman said that it would restate its results for the
fourth quarter of 1998, taking a loss because of a write-off
associated with an investment in a start-up rocket company.
</P>
<P>
   ADOBE POSTS STRONG PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   The computer graphics software maker Adobe Systems posted a
first-quarter profit that was stronger than expected and said it
would also beat second-quarter forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI POSTS 11% GAIN IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Gucci Group reported an 11 percent increase in fiscal 1999
earnings and said the strong results showed that the Italian
fashion house needed no help from LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton,
the French luxury goods maker that is trying to take it over. The
figures were hastily released on the day LVMH said its own earnings
in fiscal 1998 and the first half of fiscal 1999 slumped. LVMH
chairman Bernard Arnault attributed the bad results to losses at
the DFS Group, a duty-free operator acquired in 1997 that lost $37
million in 1998. Without those losses, he said, LVMH earnings would
have risen 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nike earnings rose 70 percent in the third quarter, partly
because of cost cutting.
</P>
<P>
   FDX, the parent company of Federal Express, posted profits that
were better than expected despite the drag of $90 million spent on
preparing for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   BMW said that its profit fell nearly 28 percent in 1998 as
losses at the British unit Rover dragged down corporate earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
