<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-LVMH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH EARNINGS UP, GUCCI SAYS IT DOESN'T NEED HELP FROM A SLUMPING
LVMH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Gucci Group NV reported an 11 percent increase in fiscal
1999 earnings Thursday and said the strong results showed that the
Italian fashion house needs no help from LVMH, the French luxury
goods maker that is trying to take it over.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were released hastily on the day LVMH said its own
earnings in fiscal year 1998 and the first half of fiscal year 1999
slumped, dragged down by the economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings results of both companies were disclosed on the eve
of meetings in the Netherlands, where Gucci is incorporated, with
executives of LVMH, to try to negotiate a compromise solution to
their wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH had been amassing Gucci shares and is now its biggest
stockholder, with a 34.4 percent stake. It had been pressing for
board representation in what Gucci had called part of a hostile
attempt to acquire the company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed Gucci's share price up as much as 9 percent
after it reported profits for the year ended Jan. 31 of $3.28 a
share, compared with $2.86 a share in fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, LVMH said that earnings in the last half of 1998
dropped 48 percent, as shrinking numbers of Japanese tourists cut
into sales. Roughly 70 percent of LVMH's revenues depend on Asian
sales or on Asian tourists who purchase LVMH products like Louis
Vuitton bags and Givenchy perfumes on European tours or at
airports. But LVMH said it expects profits to improve 15 percent
this year, as the Asian slump in demand for luxury products with
European names bottoms out. That news helped strengthen LVMH's
share price by as much as 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's brawl with LVMH intensified last month when the Italian
fashion house strengthened its resistance to an unwanted takeover
by issuing shares to an employee pension fund that diluted LVMH's
share to 25 percent. LVMH sued in an Amsterdam court to block
Gucci's plan, but the court suspended the voting rights of both
LVMH and the Gucci fund pending a ruling in April. In the meantime,
both companies are sending executives to the talks Friday to try to
reach an out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Domenico De Sole, Gucci's chief executive, fired a parting shot
before the talks, inviting investors and analysts to ``compare our
excellent results with the 1998 results that LVMH published
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's results, he said in a statement, ``underline our success
in managing the company in the difficult economic environment that
prevailed in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Gucci will provide details of full year results on Monday. But
an increase in revenue to $1.04 billion, from $975 million the year
before, appeared to demonstrate Gucci's success in shifting from a
reliance on Asian tourists to young European and American
consumers. De Sole predicted that sales and earnings would continue
to rise this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Arnault, LVMH's chairman, showed his feisty side, saying
there was ``no question of today launching a takeover bid'' for
Gucci, which he described as ``risky.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Paris, Arnault attributed LVMH's overall
bad results to losses at the DFS Group Ltd., a duty-free operator
acquired in 1997 that lost $37 million in 1998. Without those
losses, he said, LVMH earnings would have risen 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian crisis, he said was ``past the turning point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
