r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAKEOVER-SFCHRON &LR;      03-18 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEOVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Getting Ch'i to Flow Smoothly
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
(Editor's note: At the request of The Chronicle, Deborah Gee
offered to go through a feng shui consultation with a downtown San
Francisco travel agency. Her assignment: two merged companies, one
office, 26 travel agents who started working together for the first
time this week.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deborah Gee started her survey, which was offered free of charge,
of the S.R. Travel Agency in the same place she starts all her
corporate feng shui work _ at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you may not physically have clients walking
through the door because you do business electronically, the front
door is still symbolic,'' Gee explained to the agency's general
manager, Barbara Peterson. ``The reception area's color and design
determine how ch'i (energy) will flow through the rest of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui is the ancient Chinese art of placing buildings and
furniture in a way designed to ensure the smooth flow of ch'i, or
life energy.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called ``acupuncture for buildings,'' feng shui also
uses accessories like mirrors, plants and fountains to redirect the
flow of ch'i.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  It's becoming more common in American workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   And it would be hard to find a more typical workplace than S.R.
Travel's 10th-floor office: Lots of cubicles and computers. White
or gray walls with scattered travel posters. A fortresslike
reception desk near the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Gee zeroed in right away on a corner of the reception desk that
jutted toward the front door.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that, according to feng shui, sharp angles on
furniture or buildings can shoot sharp negative ch'i at the people
in their path.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an angle here; I can feel it because of my
training,'' Gee said. ``What I recommend is a plant here, something
that will hang and soften the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee then moved on into Peterson's pentagonal private office. Her
advice:
</P>
<P>
   _Move the desk away from its current spot directly in front of
the door. ``When you are in the direct path of the door, the ch'i
comes right at you and distracts you,'' Gee said.
</P>
<P>
   _But keep the desk facing generally toward the door. ``If your
back is to the ch'i as it comes in the door, you won't benefit from
it,'' she said. ``Having your back to the door also symbolizes
turning your back on opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   _Buy a potted plant for one corner with ``stagnant'' ch'i.
``Stagnant energy is going to slow down your thought processes,''
Gee said. ``I'd suggest a tall floor plant that will keep the
energy flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   _Hang award plaques on one particular wall _ the side of the
room that feng shui links to the achievement of fame or good
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   _Install a small decorative fountain in front of the fifth wall
of the office, which is slanted. ``Because you have a slanted wall
in the `career' area of the room, it will minimize the flow of ch'i
into your career,'' Gee warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't worry _ we're going to fix that!'' she added with a
laugh. ``Because the career area is also associated with the
element of water, you should add one of those wonderful-sounding
water fountains. It will complement and neutralize the slanting
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Gee moved on to other parts of the office _ such as a big
room filled with cubicles for a dozen travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news: Almost all the agents were positioned so that their
backs were facing the entries to their cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   Gee's solution? Install mirrors on the cubicle walls in front of
each agent. ``Whatever you are doing workwise, a mirror will double
it symbolically so you get twice as much business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And hang tubular metal wind chimes or multifaceted crystal
globes from the ceiling over each agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there's no wind in here, the symbolism is that the
chime redirects the flow of ch'i,'' Gee said.
</P>
<P>
   The travel agents _ absorbed in their computers and phone
conversations with clients _ barely looked up as Gee passed by.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson predicted her staff would respond positively to
most of Gee's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agents understand bad energy,'' she said. ``They come into
my office sometimes and say, `There's really bad energy out
there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson added that feng shui would be far more popular with
both employees and managers than another possible strategy for
solidifying the newly merged agency _ namely, taking everyone on a
ropes course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be less expensive to put up mirrors than to go to a
team-building retreat in Napa for two days, which is what we'd been
talking about,'' Peterson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
