<SLUG> BC-BKC-MD-STJOHNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S TURNS MARYLAND UPSIDE DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The bitter losses to Stanford and Duke and
Connecticut would prepare them, coach Mike Jarvis told his team in
offering solace only a few weeks agos. On Thursday night, those
defeats seemed like fond memories as St. John's delivered a
staggering 76-62 victory over second-seeded Maryland in the South
Regional semifinal of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The result embraced the sort of postseason success St. John's
could only have imagined just two weeks ago, when Connecticut
manhandled St. John's in the Big East Conference tournament final.
Now, St. John's, a team that was in nobody's preseason top 25, is
one victory _ against either Ohio State or Auburn _ from the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   For three-quarters of the game, St. John's did to Maryland what
no team _ not even top-ranked Duke _ had done this season: Take the
Terps out of the game and cause them to self-destruct. The first
half ended with a 20-point run by the Red Storm that was all you
needed to know about the game.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had used Maryland's favorite poison to kill it: The
Red Storm turned the high-octane running offense the Terrapins
favor to ignite an extraordinary run that had former St. John's
coach Lou Carnesecca accepting congratulations at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland was playing not only to get to the Final Four, but also
to exorcise nearly 25 years worth of demons. The Terrapins have
been to the Round of 16 four times in the last six years, but have
got no closer to the Final Four since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Gary Williams alone was 0-3 in regional semifinals since
taking over at Maryland in 1989, a failing the volatile coach is
reminded of approximately as often as he screams at his players.
Previous Maryland teams failed for a variety of reasons _ last
year, for instance, the Terps lost to the defending national
champion, Arizona, and in 1980, as a second-seeded team, they lost
to third-seeded Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   But this season's version set records for victories in the
regular season (25) and in Atlantic Coast Conference play (13) and
a loss here was bound to haunt Maryland more than any of the
others.
</P>
<P>
   The ghosts must have been weighing heavily on Williams'
shoulders in the first half. St. John's played an extraordinary
first half, using man, zone, press and trap defenses to hold
Maryland _ averaging 85 points a game _ to 19 points. The Terrapins
did not score for the last 8 minutes 25 seconds of the half.
</P>
<P>
   That freed St. John's, with the unflappable point guard Erick
Barkley handling the vaunted Maryland press, to explode on a 20-0
run before intermission. The Red Storm went into the locker room
up, 38-19.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland had 13 turnovers and only seven field goals in the
first half. St. John's, shooting just 42.4 percent from the field,
had 10 assists on 14 field goals, and just five turnovers against
the pressure defense. So stunning was St. John's dominance that
Williams, who sweats so much that opposing fans in the ACC call for
him to toss his jacket, was rendered speechless. There was no rant
that could stop this run.
</P>
<P>
   There was no hint of Maryland's drought in the early going. St.
John's was trailing by 19-18 with 8:25 left in the half. The Red
Storm was slow to set up its halfcourt offense and struggled with
its perimeter shooting (1 of 7 on 3-pointers to that point), unable
to work the ball inside. But after a television timeout, the Red
Storm was untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   The run began with a thread-the-needle pass in traffic from Ron
Artest to Bootsy Thornton for a layup. On the next trip down,
Artest got one of his three first-half blocks on the Terps'
spectacular guard Steve Francis, and that led to another easy
Thornton layup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
