<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-COLES-TEX </SLUG>
 
Miami of Ohio's Charlie Coles still has heart for coaching 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When Charlie Coles woke up, the doctors were there.
The prognosis was rather cheery, given that they had just saved his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there was no serious damage to the heart,'' he
recalls, ``and it looked like if we treated it with medication, it
would be OK and I could keep on coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, oh man, that's all I wanted to hear. I never, ever asked
anyone for another opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Feb. 28, 1998, and Coles _ basketball coach at Miami of
Ohio _ had just suffered a heart attack on the court during a MAC
tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   For awhile, it seemed as if Coles' life and coaching career _
two entities he admits have become fused over the past 34 years _
were over.
</P>
<P>
   It is a year later, and the RedHawks (24-7) are living the
largest moment in the school's basketball history. Tonight, they
will face Kentucky (27-8) in the Trans World Dome in the first
Sweet 16 game Miami has played.
</P>
<P>
   Coles, 57, is glad he didn't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give thanks every day, I honestly do,'' he says. ``I had
bypass surgery in '85, and that was scarier, because I actually
knew what was going on. This last deal was just kinda quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never asked anyone any more about it ... because if
they'd come to me and said, `Well, it's your choice _ you can go
back to coaching, but if you do ...'
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't know what I would have done. I love coaching,
but I love my family, too, and they love me. I just never wanted to
hear anyone put that choice on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, it has become quietly obvious that Coles is one
of the best coaches in America. The portfolio, of course, is a bit
thin by marquee standards.
</P>
<P>
   From 1986-91, he was the coach at Central Michigan, dispatching
Dan Majerle to the NBA, among other accomplishments. He has been
the coach at Miami for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The other years were spent as an assistant, or, more often, a
high school coach _ including three years at Toledo Central
Catholic High in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   He is full of praise for successful Division I-A coaches such as
Tubby Smith, Roy Williams, and Rick Majerus. But there is no envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just always wanted to be a coach,'' he says, ``and the level
I coached at never mattered much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't interviewed for that many jobs. If I can
coach, I can be happy, and I was just as happy at Toledo Central as
anywhere else. A coach is a coach is a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this is his third trip to the NCAA Tournament, he has
mostly built a collection of lifelong friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I ever saw him,'' says Michigan State coach Tom
Izzo, ``I was a senior in high school, and had gone down to the
state tournament. I watched him drag a player off the court because
he was upset at the way the kid was acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those who played for him have always loved and respected
him. Anything good that happens to Miami in this tournament, they
deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles says the good has already happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've coached 34 years and been married to a wonderful wife
\RDelores\S for 35, and I have two great kids,'' he says. ``I feel
that I have been fulfilled in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my goal to coach all of my life ... and I guess I've
just about done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I try to watch myself now. Whenever I get upset and start
yelling on the court, the kids just think, `Coach is hollering;
he's OK.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But later, I'll get down on my knees and say, `Lord, you know
I didn't really mean that, don't you?'''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
