<SLUG> BC-BKC-EASTCAPS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Regional scouting report
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   DUKE VS. SW MISSOURI STATE
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 7:38 p.m. today; Continental Airlines Arena, East
Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   TV; radio: CBS; WQXI (790 AM).
</P>
<P>
   Records: Duke 34-1; SW Missouri State 22-10.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Mike Krzyzewski is 539-213 overall, 466-154 in his 19th
season at Duke; Steve Alford, 154-76 overall, 76-47 in his fourth
season at SW Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Duke, the No. 1 seed, won its first two NCAA
Tournament games by 41 points each, beating Florida A&AMP;M 99-58 and
Tulsa 97-56; SW Missouri State, the No. 12 seed, defeated Wisconsin
43-32 and Tennessee 81-51.
</P>
<P>
   Starting lineups: Duke _ guards, William Avery (6-2, so., 15.1
ppg) and Trajan Langdon (6-3, sr., 17.0 ppg); center, Elton Brand
(6-8, so., 17.8 ppg); forwards, Shane Battier (6-8, so., 9.6 ppg)
and Chris Carrawell (6-6, jr., 9.8 ppg); SW Missouri State _
guards, Kevin Ault (6-3, jr., 11.9 ppg) and William Fontleroy (6-3,
jr., 10.9 ppg); center, Danny Moore (6-10, sr., 16.5 ppg);
forwards, Ron Burton (6-6, jr., 5.4 ppg) and Ken Stringer (6-5,
jr., 5.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Southwest Missouri is in its first Sweet 16 thanks to
defense. The Bears held their first two NCAA opponents to 30-of-108
shooting from the floor, 27.7 percent. They also have an underrated
post player in Danny Moore, who has 37 points and 20 rebounds in
two tournament games. But none of that matters against a Duke team
that has won its last 11 games by an average of 30.8 points. The
Blue Devils have too much athleticism, and Trajan Langdon is back
after sitting out three games with an injured foot.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Duke 85-50.
</P>
<P>
   PURDUE VS. TEMPLE
</P>
<P>
   When; where: Approximately 10:10 p.m. today; Continental
Airlines Arena, East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   TV; radio: None in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Temple 23-10; Purdue 21-12.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: John Chaney is 604-218 overall, 379-159 in 17 years at
Temple; Gene Keady is 453-199 overall, 415-180 in 18 seasons at
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Temple, the sixth seed, defeated Kent 64-51
in the first round and upset third-seeded Cincinnati 64-54 in the
second round; Purdue, the 10th seed, beat Texas 58-54 in overtime
in the first round and upset No. 2 seed Miami of Florida 73-63 in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Starting lineups: Temple _ guards, Pepe Sanchez (6-4, jr., 5.8
ppg) and Rasheed Brokenborough (6-4, sr., 11.7 ppg); center, Kevin
Lyde (6-9, fr., 7.4 ppg); forwards, Lamont Barnes (6-10, jr., 12.9
ppg) and Mark Karcher (6-5, so., 13.0 ppg); Purdue _ guards, Tony
Mayfield (6-1, sr., 2.6 ppg) and Alan Eldridge (6-1, sr., 6.8 ppg);
center, Greg McQuay (6-7, jr., 10.8 ppg); forwards, Brian Cardinal
(6-8, jr., 11.6 ppg) and Jaraan Cornell (6-3, jr., 15.2).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: A couple of giant killers play for a chance to meet
Duke. Purdue came into the tournament on a low note, having lost
five of its last six regular-season games. Keady finally has
settled on a starting lineup after using six different ones during
the season. It is Purdue's fourth trip to the Sweet 16 in the '90s,
but the Boilermakers have yet to reach the Final Four under Keady.
Temple drives teams crazy with a matchup zone defense that forces
teams to hit from the outside. In the tournament, that defense has
been especially effective, as Kent and Cincinnati hit only 14 of 45
3-pointers, 31.1 percent. If Purdue misses early and gets
impatient, the Boilermakers could be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Temple 57-47.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
