<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDGES-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WHO VOTED FOR HOLYFIELD TESTIFIE AT HEARING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The judge who scored Saturday night's heavyweight
unification bout in Evander Holyfield's favor sat in a witness
chair Thursday and watched a videotape of the fight's fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenia Williams scored the round for Holyfield despite Lennox
Lewis' decisive edge in punches landed. Of the other two judges,
one voted for Lewis and the other called it a draw, and the fight
resulted in a draw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the videotape of TVKO's pay-per-view telecast showed
Williams something different. ``From what I saw, I'd have to say
Lewis was the winner,'' she testified before a hearing of the New
York Senate Committee on Investigations, Taxation and Government
Operations. ``Based on the punches I saw connecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she defended her scoring of the round. ``What I saw is
not what the camera saw,'' Williams said, her lawyer beside her.
``They're at a different angle than I saw. I only scored the blows
I saw. I can only score what I could see.''
</P>
<P>
   With multiple angles and close-ups, television can present an
unobstructed view of the fight, while judges have a single view,
looking up from ringside.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw live is different from what I saw on TV,'' Williams
added.
</P>
<P>
   The committee convened the hearing as the outcry increased
following the draw in the fight at Madison Square Garden. The
Manhattan district attorney has launched a criminal inquiry, and
the state attorney general is conducting an investigation of the
sport. Sen. Roy M. Goodman, R-Manhattan., the committee chairman,
said there was a need to ``dissect the events of the
Holyfield-Lewis fight to determine if a malignancy existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite testimony that many of boxing's practices required
reform _ such as promoters paying fight judges, and sanctioning
bodies choosing the judges and rating fighters in ways that do not
adequately reward their records _ the hearing's main revelation was
that Williams had a lousy judging perch.
</P>
<P>
   On numerous occasions, she said, she pushed photographers out of
her way. She tried to get a better vantage point by sitting on a
table, but it was uncomfortable. During Round five, she said, her
view was blocked by Lewis' back, keeping her from tallying punches
apparently seen by the other judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did notice that she had the worst seat of the lot,'' said
Larry O'Connell, the judge who scored the fight a draw but was
quoted in a London newspaper as saying he had erred. ``She was
surrounded by photographers.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said his position and that of the third judge, Stanley
Christodoulou of South Africa, who scored the bout for Lewis, was
unimpeded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   How the judges were selected interested the committee because
the titles of the IBF, the WBC and the W BA were at stake. Each
organization chose a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Sulaiman, the WBC president, testified by phone that his
intention was that all three judges should be from neutral
countries and would not favor Holyfield, an American, or Lewis, an
Englishman. But after the IBF chose Williams, an American, Sulaiman
switched to O'Connell, an Englishman, from Daniel van de Wiele, a
Belgian.
</P>
<P>
   Williams ``was not a good choice,'' Sulaiman said. ``We needed
an experienced judge from a neutral country.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the other judges, Williams' $5,150 fee, travel and lodging,
at the Pennsylvania Hotel in Manhattan, were paid by Don King, the
promoter, through sanctioning fees paid to the State Athletic
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she was not offered special favors or money to
influence her scoring. ``It was strictly objective,'' she said. She
also said she had not been persuaded with financial help because of
her recent filing for personal bankruptcy. ``Absolutely not,'' said
Williams, who is an accountant for the municipal government of
Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman tried to find a personal link between Williams and
Robert W. Lee, the president of the IBF, that might have affected
her judging. (Holyfield holds the IBF and WBA heavyweight titles.)
But Williams said Lee was no more than a mentor who helped her
understand the fine points of judging.
</P>
<P>
   Lee canceled his testimony on the advice of his lawyer. The IBF
is the subject of a continuing federal investigation into
allegations that it sold rankings and arranged fights in return for
kickbacks, The Star-Ledger of Newark, N.J., reported this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
