<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midwest Regional scouting report
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN STATE VS. OKLAHOMA
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 7:55 p.m. today; Trans World Dome, St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Michigan State 31-4; Oklahoma 22-10.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Tom Izzo is 86-40 in four seasons at Michigan State;
Kelvin Sampson is 103-54 in five seasons at Oklahoma, 279-202
overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: No. 1 seed Michigan State won according to
form, defeating Mount St. Mary's 76-53 in the first round and
Mississippi 74-66 in the second. Surprising 13th-seeded Oklahoma
first knocked off Arizona 61-60 and then North Carolina-Charlotte
85-72.
</P>
<P>
   Probable lineups: Michigan State _ guards, Mateen Cleaves (6-2,
jr., 11.8 ppg) and Jason Klein (6-7, sr., 9.9 ppg); center, Antonio
Smith (6-8, jr., 6.8 ppg); forwards, A.J. Granger (6-9, jr., 6.3
ppg) and Andre Hutson (6-8, so., 8.5 ppg). Oklahoma _ guards,
Michael Johnson (6-0, sr., 11.6 ppg), Alex Spaulding (6-3, so., 3.9
ppg) and Eric Martin (6-5, sr., 12.4 ppg); forwards, Eduardo Najera
(6-8, jr., 15.7 ppg) and Ryan Humphrey (6-8, jr., 11.1 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: History looks unkindly upon the Sooners, only the third
No. 13 seed to make the Sweet 16; neither of the other two _
Valparaiso or Richmond _ advanced. They have a shooter's chance of
an upset, having connected on 23 3-pointers in their two tournament
victories. They took Arizona's Jason Terry out of the game in the
first round; he shot only 4-of-17. Now comes the challenge of
Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves. Cleaves, though, is unselfish
enough to create opportunities for others. While not flashy, the
Spartans work the boards hard, with an 8.6 rebounding margin this
season. Their depth is too much, with an all-Big 10 player, Morris
Peterson, coming off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Michigan State, 75-63.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY VS. MIAMI
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 10:15 p.m. today; Trans World Dome, St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   TV: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Kentucky 27-8, Miami of Ohio 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Tubby Smith is 62-12 in two seasons at Kentucky, 186-74
overall; Charlie Coles is 62-28 in three seasons at Miami, 154-113
overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Kentucky, the No. 3 seed, opened with an
82-60 win over New Mexico State, then outlasted Kansas in overtime
92-88. No. 10 seed Miami of Ohio upset No. 7 Washington 59-58 and
No. 2 Utah 66-58.
</P>
<P>
   Probable lineups: Kentucky _ guards, Wayne Turner (6-2, sr.,
10.7 ppg) and Desmond Allison (6-5, fr., 4.7 ppg); center, Michael
Bradley (6-10, so., 10.3 ppg); forwards, Heshimu Evans (6-6, sr.,
11.8 ppg) and Scott Padgett (6-9, sr., 12.5 ppg). Miami of Ohio _
guards, Rob Mestas (5-10, jr., 7.1 ppg), Damon Frierson (6-4, sr.,
13.1 ppg) and Anthony Taylor (6-1, jr., 3.8 ppg); forwards, Wally
Szczerbiak (6-8, sr., 24.3 ppg) and John Estick (6-6, sr., 8.5
ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Does Wally have an encore left in him? Szczerbiak
carried the RedHawks in the first round with a 43-point, 12-rebound
tour de force. Against Utah, he passed off and still got 24 points
and seven rebounds. Kentucky scrambles a defense capable of
shutting down one such pivotal player. While Miami makes its first
trip to the Sweet 16, the senior-driven Wildcats still don't know
what it feels like to lose in the postseason under Smith. It also
appears Kentucky has regained its shooting eye; after finishing
last in the SEC in 3-point shooting; the 'Cats have hit 19 of 38
3-point attempts in two NCAA Tournament games. Confidence and
experience are powerful allies.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Kentucky, 85-65.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
