<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-POWER-PACS:GIA     03-18 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-POWER-PACS:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS' NEW POWER TOOL: PACS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Although the elections of the year 2000 are still many months
away, if one tuned into the talking heads on Sunday morning or
picked up a local or national newspaper, it would seem they're just
around the corner.
 &HT;    Charmaine White Face, A Lakota woman living in Rapid City, S.D.,
served as the treasurer of the Oglala Sioux Tribe for a short time
several years ago. The tribal council ousted her because she was
investigating questionable expenditures of tribal money. She has
accused Sen. Tom Daschle (D-S.D.) of accepting a $10,000
contribution from the tribe. Sen. Daschle denies this.
 &HT;    Charmaine is concerned because she believes this alleged
contribution was illegal since the funds came from federal dollars.
Most expenditure from tribal funds come from their General Fund.
This fund is a mixture coming from many sources including
charitable donations and tax dollars collected by the tribe in a
tax sharing agreement with the state of South Dakota. It would be
nearly impossible to pin down exactly from which account a
political contribution originated. The tribe has denied making any
political contributions from any account holding federal dollars.
 &HT;    Tribal political action committees (PACs) are relatively new in
Indian country. In the past the Indian nations had little extra
money to contribute to non-Indian politicians. But as could be seen
last year when the tribes in Minnesota spent at least $186,000 on
political contributions, ``the times they are a-changing.'' The
extra, independent funds, generated by tribally owned and operated
casinos have made the difference. Tribes are more apt to contribute
to national and local political contenders today because they have
so much more to protect.
 &HT;    Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota made himself real popular with
the Indians of that state when he called tribal sovereignty an
``oxymoron.'' He said, ``Are you a part of the United States or are
you a sovereign nation? If you're your own sovereign nation, then
take care of yourselves.'' Whoa, Jesse! Tribes are recognized as
sovereign nations by the U.S. Constitution. Most of the federal
dollars they receive in aid from the federal government is provided
because of the treaty agreements they signed as sovereign nations.
 &HT;    I am told that the tribes did not contribute to Ventura's
campaign fund. They contributed instead to the campaign of his
opponent, Hubert Humphrey III. Sour grapes? Maybe.
 &HT;    Canterbury Park in Shakopee, Minn., will be pushing the
Legislature to allow them to put slot machines and blackjack tables
at their racetrack. This could put a severe crimp in the profits of
the Indian casinos located near Shakopee and Prairie Island. Tribal
leaders fear Ventura may be more apt to support this legislation
than his predecessor, Gov. Arne Carlson. His recent comments lend
credence to these fears. You can expect the tribes to put up many
PAC dollars for candidates supporting their opposition to the
Canterbury proposal.
 &HT;    According to a recent Associated Press story, Indian tribes are
among the largest contributors of Minnesota's 340 PACs. Because
many tribes now have independent dollars from their casinos and
bingo parlors, you can expect them to become much more active
politically. They realize that the local and national politicians
hold much of their future in their hands.
 &HT;    This becomes even more apparent when you realize the Oglala
Sioux Tribe of the Pine Ridge Reservation shifted its elections for
tribal officials to coincide with the national elections in
November. Several tribes are now doing this because historically,
Indian voters have turned out at a far higher rate for tribal
elections than for state or national elections.
 &HT;    For generations the tribes were whipsawed between the state and
national politicians. They lost millions of acres of land and
millions of dollars in minerals and natural resources at the hands
of politicians representing their constituents _ the white
ranchers, farmers, state governments, mining interests,
corporations and land speculators. At last tribes are able to hire
lawyers to represent their interests, and are able to contribute to
the campaigns of politicians who regard them as genuine
constituents. They are set to hang on to what little is left and,
if possible, expand upon it.
 &HT;    Perhaps Campaign 2000 is starting a little early, but you can
count on the Indian nations of America to be right in the middle of
it, PACs at the ready. I suspect that when Charmaine White Face
complained of a supposed $10,000 contribution to Daschle, she never
thought she'd see the day when this would be commonplace.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago (Nanwica Kciji) 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
