<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-ASSIMILATION     03-18 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-ASSIMILATION:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEINFELD, FRIENDS AND FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    British expatriots at New York's National Review and Forbes
magazines toss verbal bricks at non-English speaking immigrants and
falsely accuse them of not contributing to the economy, which they
do; of not learning English, which they do; and, of not
assimilating and becoming good Americans, which they do. Actually,
it's these British critics who don't assimilate, but that's a topic
for another column.
 &HT;    At hand is the question: do the majority of immigrants, most of
whom are Hispanic, assimilate into American culture? First,
language arts _ Do they learn English? Yes, the 1990 Census showed
flash cards to native-Spanish speakers that self-graded English
speaking ability. Some 90 percent of the interviewees said they
spoke English well. Of course, that's subjective, but isn't the
view that they don't, subjective also? So, whom do we believe, the
Madison Avenue British transplants, or the Census Bureau that
interviewed thousands of people?
 &HT;    As to contributions to the economy, while the British work for
salaries at magazines and journals, immigrants tend to form
businesses. Which class is more valuable, a handful of writers and
editors, or hundreds of thousands of business owners and employers?
The acknowledged tendency of immigrants to form businesses,
especially among the Mexican immigrants, is transforming an entire
community of 20 million into an entrepreneurial class. A Mexican
and Mexican American class that is less dependent on government
assistance than ever.
 &HT;    Studies show that these immigrants are particularly brand-name
conscious; and spend larger shares of their income on rent and food
than most people, thus injecting a constant cash flow into
neighborhoods long abandoned by previous European immigrants and in
the case of Los Angeles, neighborhoods abandoned by blacks.
 &HT;    Interestingly, they spend larger amounts per capita on movies,
video rentals and premium cable channels. In a previous life, I set
sales records for cable sales for a large company by selling HBO to
Spanish-speaking households who used repetitive movies to learn
English.
 &HT;    Using these facts as a base, what do Hispanics watch on
television and can we use their viewing habits as indicators of
assimilation, the remaining category of behavior that the British
emigres in New York point out as a deficiency of Hispanic
immigrants.
 &HT;    According to the Nielsen Hispanic Television Index, Hispanics
rated ``Seinfeld'' as No. 1; ``ER'' second and ``Monday Night
Football'' third. Football aside, the Hispanic funny bone continues
with ``Friends' tied with ``Veronica's Closet'' for fourth.
Seriousness infects the Hispanic households with the ``X-Files''
(No. 7), and ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' tied for 9th with ``Party of
Five.'' The viewing habits of blacks are totally different from
those of Hispanics and Anglos (non-Hispanic whites), except for
some football.
 &HT;    What's interesting here is that we already know from the 1990
Census that most Hispanics consider themselves to be English
speakers, good English-speakers. And we know from the Census Bureau
that children of Spanish-speaking immigrants tend to be bilingual
and that their children hardly speak Spanish at all. These facts
are generally ignored by the media and by the anti-immigrant
xenophobes among us. In fact, the widespread perception is the
opposite of the facts.
 &HT;    But, the truth and facts all come home with these Nielsen
television reports, don't they?
 &HT;    For example, among Hispanic viewers 12-17 years of age, 15 of
the top 20 shows they enjoy are also in the top 20 for ALL American
viewers in the same age group. Among Hispanic viewers 50 years of
age plus, 15 of their top viewed shows were the same as ALL
Americans of that age group.
 &HT;    Among the top 20 shows that Hispanics watch, only one, ``ER''
has any Hispanic principals, proving that shows that intentionally
place Hispanics in view don't necessarily draw Hispanic viewers. In
contrast, among the top shows viewed by blacks, most have black
characters. While there is a noticeable absence of Hispanics on
television, before or behind the cameras, featuring a Hispanic
actor doesn't guarantee success for any television show among
Hispanic viewers.
 &HT;    This survey was not conducted in homes where much of the TV
viewing is in Spanish because such places are only in demographic
pockets around the country and Spanish-language television isn't
available in all 50 states. Thus, the survey features
English-speaking and bi-lingual homes only. But doesn't that
include most of the 30,000,000 Hispanics. Again, over 90 percent of
Hispanics identified themselves as `good' to `excellent' English
speakers in the 1990 Census.
 &HT;    While most favorite Hispanic programming parallels that of the
rest of the country, some questions present themselves vis-a-vis
the Hispanic top 20. Why does the ``Wonderful World of Disney''
rank 15th with them, but only 44th with the rest of the country?
``Touched by an Angel'' is No. 6 among all Americans, but only 17th
with Hispanics. ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' is the 9th most watched
show by Hispanics, but only 46th among the rest of America.
Hispanics rank ``Sabrina, Teenage Witch'' 20th, while the rest of
America ranks it 61st. And, among Hispanics, ``The Simpsons'' ranks
13th, while the rest of America ranks ``The Simpsons'' 31st.
 &HT;    There are some differences between Hispanic viewers and the rest
of the country, but they tend to be minor. The most obvious
conclusion one can reach is that Hispanic households that speak
English and/or are bi-lingual are almost totally assimilated into
American culture.
 &HT;    At least they like Jerry Seinfeld, ``Friends'' and football. You
can't get more American than that, can you?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
