<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITERARY-AUTHENTICITY     03-18 1541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERARY-AUTHENTICITY-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `RIGHT' TO TELL
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By JENNIFER CHING 
 c. 1999 A. Magazine)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Times have certainly changed since the classical exoticism of
``Diary of a Geisha Girl,'' the 1959 first-person account (``as
told to'' author William Vaneer) of a Japanese geisha who comes to
America and pursues her life-calling as a prostitute.
 &HT;    The diversity of today's readers and critics has raised the
degree of scrutiny on white authors taking on such `ethnic'
projects. Then again, when Puccini's overwrought ``Madame
Butterfly'' is merely transformed into Broadway's gaudy ``Miss
Saigon,'' can we really say we've made progress?
 &HT;    Arthur Golden's ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' became a word-of-mouth
bestseller and critical hit last year, prompting Steven Spielberg
to direct an upcoming film version.
 &HT;    ``Rarely has a world so closed and foreign been evoked with such
natural assurance,'' raved John Burnham Schwartz in The New Yorker.
Journalist Pico Iyer proclaims in the publisher's notes, ``I still
can't quite believe that an American male can so seamlessly enter
the soul of a Japanese woman with such perfection.''
 &HT;    Lurking in the shadows of all the hype, however, is an
uncomfortable double standard in debate over authorship and
authenticity, one that arises when narration jumps the thin line
separating memoir from fiction. Reviews cite author Arthur Golden's
Ivy League background and exhaustive research with great
acclamation. Proclaiming that the story and characters transcend
`authenticity,' critics praised the historical accuracy and
surprising depth of Sayuri, the geisha who faces love and loss in
thick, Gothic romance style. Little skepticism has been voiced,
particularly because Golden's identity is situated so far away from
a 1930s geisha.
 &HT;    At issue is not the quality of the text or the credentials of
the author, but the absence of critical voices examining these
cultural projects and the ease with which the American public
embraces a white male's appropriation of a geisha's story.
Authenticity is a terribly messy issue for both the writer and the
critic _ if it is actually possible to divorce the two identities
from each other. The `truth' is a political and literary minefield
for biographers, who are subject to the incessant reality checks of
their readers. Authors of fiction, on the other hand, can hijack
history without criticism (the literary imagination, after all, is
an expansive, forgiving space).
 &HT;    Asian American literary critics have largely refrained from
voicing skepticism for ``Memoirs,'' ignoring the impact of such
books on Asian Americans. Other recent novels, such as David
Gutterson's ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' and Danielle Steel's
``Silent Honor,'' employ Asian American history as a backdrop to
fictional tales. But while such works have created a literary
frenzy around the `discovery' of events such as the internment of
Japanese Americans during World War II, they have done so through
an inherently limiting lens.
 &HT;    Both (albeit vastly different) novels frame the internment
experiences of Japanese American women by their affairs with white
men. Although point of view is, of course, the author's choice, the
mass marketing of these works has the effect of relegating the
historical and fictional writings of Japanese Americans such as
Hisaye Yamamoto to the margins.
 &HT;    And while the publishing industry acknowledges that Asian and
Asian American culture is hot, it is unwilling to embrace writers
that go beyond the accepted, comfortably `authentic' narratives
that ponder worn themes of the struggle between East and West or
between the `old country' and America.
 &HT;    The answer is not for the Asian American literary community to
gripe each time a white author rides to commercial success on the
back of Asian American history, but to push a dialogue on
authenticity _ regardless of ethnicity _ into the popular
conversation. White authors and publishers have become savvy in
recent years about justifying ethnic pursuits. But while Kimiko's
innocent sexual exploits in ``Diary of a Geisha Girl'' now seem
outlandishly dated, appropriation continues unfettered unless
critics speak out.
 &HT;    Knopf sent vintage kimonos to bookstores for ``Memoirs'''
publicity, for example, and actress Bernadette Dunne read the novel
for the audiocasette version with a lilting accent. And the
`accents' that riddle Richard Olen Butler's narrative voices in his
1993 Pulitzer Prize-winning collection of short stories, ``A Good
Scent from a Strange Mountain,'' are short-shrift imitations of
real Vietnamese American voices.
 &HT;    Asian American writers, meanwhile, face their own authenticity
dilemma, one that has long plagued writers of color. Perhaps all
writers are `cultural impersonators,' as literary critic Henry
Louis Gates, Jr. argues. The fondness of publishers for the sales
value of `authentic' tales (read: ones that emphasize the typified
struggle with ethnicity and outsider themes) means Asian American
writers are ultimately bound by the straitjacket of mainstream
perception.
 &HT;    When my mother and I watched ``The Joy Luck Club'' on video
recently, I was hoping to engage her in an intense, generation
gap-filling experience. Instead, she kept shaking her head at the
screen. ``It's so fake,'' complained my mother. ``All this
melodrama. Who walks around talking about swan feathers?''
 &HT;    I wonder if ``My Joy Luck Club: Memoirs of My Aunties' Horrors
in China'' would have been more authentic to my mother, or if there
is greater `truth' to a purportedly biographical narrative. When
Maxine Hong Kingston's ``Woman Warrior: Memoirs of Girlbood Among
Ghosts'' received a National Book Award in 1975, many Asian
American writers were incensed by the publisher's decision to
market the book as nonfiction (viewed as a strategic decision in
order to guarantee an award for Kingston, who was otherwise
predicted to lose in the fiction category to Toni Morrison). In the
years since, however, ``Woman Warrior'' has become part of the
ethnic canon of biographic literature and a requirement for many
history, literature and women's studies classes.
 &HT;    ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' seems to demand charitable readings, for
many find it difficult to criticize another person's experience, as
lived or as researched extensively.
 &HT;    The same goes for ``The Accidental Asian,'' a 1997 autobiography
by Harvard law student Eric Liu that skirts the line between
personal and social commentary. Several reviewers praised Liu's
honesty, while few examined his privileged perspective and
assimilationist arguments. The reaction to ``The Accidental Asian''
gets to the core of political and literary divisions in criticism;
writing quality and anecdotal interest are lost among concerns that
popular success anoints Liu as our `spokesperson.'
 &HT;    These issues recall debates that have long plagued minority
writers, from Zora Neale Hurston and Ralph Ellison to contemporary
Mexican American author Richard Rodriguez. The competition is
vicious for authors of color that yearn to speak out beyond the
comfortable niches of established themes. Liu lives (as most of us
do) on the intersections of ethnic identities that don't define
themselves clearly into convenient political categories. The
struggle to tell `real' stories of divergent minority experiences
is alive and well.
 &HT;    ``There's really no such thing as authenticity,'' a friend
emails to me as I write this commentary. ``There's only good
writing and boring writing.''
 &HT;    As a writer, I understand his claim and implicitly trust it. As
a critic, however, I also recognize that such a judgment is bound
by the realness of an author's voice and project to me, a visceral
impression that cannot be separated from my own storytelling and
the world that I see: the world where the responsibility of
exposure is often ignored or passed onto an imagined community of
responsible, enlightened readers.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 A. Magazine)
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
