</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448; fax: 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR ONCE, PUT THE TEACHERS FIRST. Politicians refuse to face the
hard truth about what needs to be done to improve public education:
Put teachers first, insists columnist Bill Maxwell. Lawmakers
should stop the sleight-of-hand approach to education immediately,
he says, and pass legislation that sets teacher salaries high
enough to attract the best and the brightest and to keep competent
teachers in the classroom, high enough to endow the profession with
the dignity _ and respect _ that it deserves. ``Without good
teaching, effective learning is virtually impossible for most
students,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-RESPECT-TEACHERS:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS' NEW POWER TOOL: PACS. Tribal political action
committees (PACs) are relatively new in Indian country, notes
columnist Tim Giago. In the past the Indian nations had little
extra money to contribute to non-Indian politicians. ``But the
times they are a-changing,'' he says, as could be seen last year
when the tribes in Minnesota spent at least $186,000 on political
contributions. The extra, independent funds, generated by tribally
owned and operated casinos have made the difference. ``Tribes are
more apt to contribute to national and local political contenders
today because they have so much more to protect,'' he points out.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-INDIAN-POWER-PACS:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   RACE AND GENDER DO MATTER IN HEALTH CARE. A recent study
published in the New England Journal of Medicine, confirms what
many women and African Americans already suspected: There is bias
in the way they are treated in the health-care industry, notes
columnist Akilah Monifa. ``The race and sex of a patient
independently influence how physicians manage chest pain,'' the
study showed. U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher, commenting on the
study, notes the severe consequences this bias could have: ``It's a
matter of life and death whether a patient gets ... therapy. Blacks
are 40 percent more likely (than whites) to die of heart disease,
and this could be one factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-HEALTH:RACE-GENDER-BIAS:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   SEINFELD, FRIENDS AND FOOTBALL. How assimilated are Hispanics?
Television viewers and their preferences, reported in a Nielsen
Hispanic Television survey, is a good index, observes columnist
Raoul Lowery Contreras. There are some differences between Hispanic
viewers and the rest of the country, but they tend to be minor, he
says. The most obvious conclusion one can reach is that Hispanic
households that speak English and/or are bi-lingual are almost
totally assimilated into American culture. ``At least they like
Jerry Seinfeld, ``Friends'' and football,'' he writes. ``You can't
get more American than that, can you?''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-HISPANIC-ASSIMILATION:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
   THE `RIGHT' TO TELL. Authorship may be sacred, but critics must
push for a popular dialogue on authenticity, suggests Jennifer
Ching in A. Magazine. A good example is Arthur Golden's ``Memoirs
of a Geisha'' which became a word-of-mouth bestseller and critical
hit last year, prompting Steven Spielberg to direct an upcoming
film version. ``At issue is not the quality of the text or the
credentials of the author, but the absence of critical voices
examining these cultural projects and the ease with which the
American public embraces a white male's appropriation of a geisha's
story,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-LITERARY-AUTHENTICITY-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
