<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-SIDE-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS PUT DUCHESNE ON WAIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Steve Duchesne's career as a King may end as soon as
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   And if it isn't over that quickly, the likelihood is it will be
within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings placed the disappointing Duchesne on waivers Wednesday
morning, triggering a 48-hour period during which any NHL team can
claim him. If the 33-year-old rushing defenseman is not claimed by
this morning - which is likely, because his contract calls for him
to receive $7.5 million the next two years - there's a strong
possibility the Kings will deal him by Tuesday's NHL trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Other options would be to buy out Duchesne's contract (for
two-thirds of the remainder, or $5 million), demote him to a
minor-league team, or keep him on their roster. Kings general
manager Dave Taylor, saying the decision to waive Duchesne was his
alone, sounded Thursday very much like a man anxious to cut his
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt at this time, this was our best option,'' Taylor said.
``I don't think Steve has performed as well as he's capable of
performing. Maybe a change of scenery would be best for Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne was the Kings' key acquisition last summer, signed to a
three-year, $11.75-million contract as a free agent after a
56-point season with the St. Louis Blues. Duchesne, who began his
career with the Kings in 1986, has 23 points this season and a
minus-6 defensive rating. He has shown no sign of turning his game
around, has been a defensive liability, and has been scratched from
the Kings' last four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm disappointed that the team's giving up on me
like this after seven months,'' said Duchesne, clearly distraught.
But I'm staying positive and I'm going to be ready for whatever
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne's contract contains a no-trade clause, meaning any deal
the Kings make would be subject to his approval. It is believed
that Philadelphia and Ottawa - teams Duchesne previously has played
for - are teams that might be interested in acquiring his services.
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne is believed to be amenable to a trade, realizing his
situation with the Kings has deteriorated. But any team that would
trade for Duchesne almost certainly would demand that the Kings pay
a sizable portion of his salary, which Taylor acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we signed Steve, we felt we were getting a veteran player
who would play well for us and provide some offense from the blue
line,'' Taylor said. ``And I think Steve would admit he hasn't
played as well as he's capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt bitter that the Kings have lost faith in him in
a relatively short amount of time, Duchesne said, ``Why would I
badmouth somebody? I've got a lot of respect for Dave, and I've got
a lot of respect for (Coach Larry Robinson). I'm trying to have a
little class. The game has been good to me. Why should I start
blasting the organization, my coach or GM?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
