r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-MODANO-STARS-TEX     03-18 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MODANO-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO'S ALL-AROUND PLAY MERITS MVP REGARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In Pittsburgh, fans are convinced Jaromir Jagr is the
NHL's most valuable player. In Philadelphia, the push is for Eric
Lindros. In Ottawa, they're pumping Alexei Yashin as a possible
candidate for MVP.
</P>
<P>
   And in North Texas...
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more of a team concept,'' Stars center Mike Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but whatever happened to the
best-player-on-the-best-team concept of MVP? What about Mike
Modano?
</P>
<P>
   With Yashin leading the NHL in goals with 39 and bringing his
Eastern Conference-leading Senators into Reunion Arena tonight for
a 7:30 showdown with the NHL-leading Stars, talk of the Hart Trophy
can move to center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr seems to have one hand on the Hart Trophy, and with a
league-leading 103 points, the trophy is Jagr's to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Modano is not among the top five scorers in the league, but his
value might not be best measured in scoring. The NHL is a game that
puts a premium on multi-dimensional two-way players _ those who can
carry the puck into the offensive end and keep an opponent from
doing so at the other end _ and that's a dimension Modano gives the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say he's one of the top three or four players in the
league right now,'' said Stars winger Brett Hull, who is expected
to return to the lineup tonight after missing 11 games with a
hamstring pull. ``He just does so many things so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano ranks eighth in the NHL in scoring with 73 points (30
goals, 43 assists). What's more, he has 26 points more than Hull,
the next-best Star. Modano hasn't missed a game this season, is a
plus 27, has scored only six of his 30 goals on the power play and
has contributed three short-handed goals and six game-winners.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he is consistent in all areas instead of
dominant in one or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has really become a complete player, that's the greatest
thing you can say about him right now,'' said Stars defenseman
Craig Ludwig, who has been Modano's teammate for the past eight
seasons. ``The criticism people used to have about Mo is he would
take games off. They don't say that about him anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the Stars' most reliable scorer, Modano has
turned into their top checking center. Under coach Ken Hitchcock's
system, Modano typically is paired against an opponent's best
players. He often is on the ice against Peter Forsberg and Joe
Sakic of the Colorado Avalanche or Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya of
the Mighty Ducks. He sees his share of Jagr and the Red Wings'
Steve Yzerman and he'll likely go head-to-head with Yashin tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It's a part of the job he has come to love.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came up, it was all about scoring, who could
score the most, who could have 50 goals, who could have 100
points,'' Modano said. ``If you didn't score at least one goal, you
had a bad game back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the league has changed and my role has changed. Now, I can
do other things, maybe not score, and still have a good game.
That's a good feeling when you can go into a game and know there
are a lot of other things besides scoring that you can do to help
your team win.''
</P>
<P>
   And Modano has helped his team to a league-best 42-13-12 record.
Granted, he has a great supporting cast. As part of the plan to
check the other team's best players, Modano is accompanied by
winger Jere Lehtinen and defenseman Derian Hatcher on most shifts.
Lehtinen is last year's winner of the Selke Trophy for best
defensive forward and will again be in the running for the award
this season. Hatcher might well be the best defensive defenseman in
the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   And Modano is proving this season that he can also function
without some of his top teammates. In games without Hull, Modano
has 10 goals and 12 assists for 22 points in 21 games and the Stars
are 11-3-7 in that span. The Stars as a team have struggled at
5-5-2 with second-line center Joe Nieuwendyk out of the lineup, but
Modano has responded with five goals and nine assists (14 points)
in those 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at how to stop that team, the first thing you
look at is how do you stop Modano,'' said Penguins winger Rob
Brown, a former Modano linemate with the 1993-94 Stars. ``He's done
such a great job of learning the checking game that he creates
turnovers with his defense and can convert with his offense. It's a
different game in the NHL now, you have to be a two-way player, and
he's done a great job of adapting.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano still would need a hard push in the final 15 games to
reach 100 points _ a plateau he has coveted since he started his
career. However, he's not that far away from tying his
single-season career high of 93 points.
</P>
<P>
   And even if he didn't hit a scoring high, the season's success
meter awaits Modano and his teammates in the playoffs. And then
Modano might be able to truly measure how valuable he is to his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to work a long time just to get to this point, so I'm
not going to do anything to change that plan,'' said Modano, who
was seventh in MVP voting two seasons ago. ``There's always going
to be an emphasis on numbers. But so far, \Rbeing a two-way
player\S has worked for me, so I'm just going to keep working hard
at that and not worry about the individual stuff.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
