<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' PLANS GO ASTRAY, AND THAT'S JUST THE HALF OF IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Don Nelson's original plan was to get the
Mavericks pointed in the right direction with a few wins, then turn
the franchise's coaching reins over to his son, Donnie, in time for
the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   However, at the rate the Mavericks have won games since the
elder Nelson took over as coach, his son may have to wait a little
longer before becoming the team's coach.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reasons, the Mavericks have not produced their fair
share of victories under Nelson. They enter the midpoint of this
shortened, 50-game season with tonight's road game at 7 against the
Detroit Pistons as owners of a disappointing 8-16 record.
</P>
<P>
   This season's Mavericks' team has blown too many leads and
doesn't seem to have the killer instinct to put teams away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all right,'' guard Michael Finley said in summing up the
first half of the season. ``It's nothing to write home about and
nothing to brag about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a long ways to go to get to the point where we
want to be and where we need to be in order to get some respect
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks reach the midway point coming off perhaps the most
embarrassing loss of the season _ an 88-87 defeat to a New Jersey
Nets team that was 3-17 before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Short lineups. Tall lineups. A lineup of former Phoenix Suns
players. Rookie Dirk Nowitzki, a 7-footer, guarding 5-3 Muggsy
Bogues. Nine different starting lineups.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has tried it all, and the shuffling has only netted the
Mavericks a .333 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said injuries to starting small forward Cedric Ceballos
and backup point guard Robert Pack hindered his team's growth
process. Ceballos fractured both wrists 13 games into this season
and is probably out for the season. Ceballos was averaging 12.5
points a game, and was a viable offensive weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Pack suffered a slightly torn right hamstring Saturday and is
sidelined for two to four weeks. He was a spark plug when spelling
Steve Nash. Pack had averaged 9.4 points and 3.3 assists in only
19.6 minutes of playing time, and did not publicly complain when
Nelson gave the starting point guard position to Nash in training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Nash signed a six-year, $33 million contract extension before
the season, then suffered through his worst NBA shooting slump. He
also was hampered by a fractured nose and a viral infection, but
has tried to keep his spirits high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled, but we've shown some life here, and we've
shown some potential and some ability,'' Nash said. ``It's been
obviously an unfortunate record.'' Import misfires Nowitzki's
struggles are what surprised Nelson the most. Nelson went so far as
to convince Mavericks owner Ross Perot Jr. to fly to Germany last
summer to meet Nowitzki's parents and convince him to come to the
NBA immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki, who is accustomed to playing only two games in a week
instead of the plethora of back-to-back games the NBA has on its
docket, tried to tell Nelson he wasn't ready for the NBA. After
Nowitzki made nine starts, he said Nelson asked him if it was OK to
remove him from the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he wouldn't struggle at all, but I do understand
it,'' Nelson said. ``I knew it was a possibility, but he's playing
pretty well right now.'' The few, the proud Gary Trent, Shawn
Bradley, A.C. Green and Pack were the most impressive Mavericks
players during the first half of the season. Trent, who becomes a
free agent after this season, is a monster on the low box and has a
soft shooting touch.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had his offensive game de-emphasized by Nelson, and he
responded with some of the best basketball of his six-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think if we would have stayed healthy we would have
been right where we wanted to be,'' Nelson said. ``But we lost two
major players, and that makes it pretty tough for us right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled in scoring, and that's where the loss of
Cedric doubly hurts us. And we had gotten used to Pack giving us
that spark off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Mavericks are still misguidedly talking about making
a run for the playoffs this season. But first-half losses to teams
like Vancouver, Golden State and New Jersey took care of that.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Trent, Green and Samaki Walker become free
agents on July 1. The Mavericks are also already over the salary
cap, and they dealt their 1999 first-round pick _ it will be a
lottery pick that Nelson reluctantly didn't protect for at least
one year _ to Phoenix in the Nash trade.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, unless Nelson tweaks the roster with some
low-rent players, Mavericks fans can expect what they see this
season next season.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 16-50 last season after he fired Jim Cleamons and took
over the coaching chores on Dec. 4, 1998, knows he needs a lot of
players to step up if the Mavericks hope to improve their record
from the first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for better play and a real improvement in Nash and
just everybody,'' he said. ``We really need everybody to improve _
Nowitzki _ everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If the improvement doesn't come, Nelson may be coaching well
into the millennium, and his son's coaching career will be placed
on hold.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
