<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-BRED SIBLINGS ON SERIOUS RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big brother is muscular, dark and handsome. But with those
killer looks comes a bad-boy attitude. He can be stubborn and
impatient, and has trouble with authority figures.
</P>
<P>
   The well-behaved little brother is lanky instead of buff, with a
lighter complexion and an easygoing personality.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know they were related, you might never suspect.
But they share an important trait: 4-year-old racehorse Desert Air
and his 3-year-old brother Desert Demon run fast and bring home
money. Houston-based Mt. Brilliant Stable can be thankful for that.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Desert Air traveled from New Orleans to Hot
Springs, Ark., to capture the $125,000 Razorback Handicap at
Oaklawn Park. Now Desert Demon makes the same trip for tomorrow's
$125,000 Rebel Stakes, and he should be one of the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he runs like his brother did,'' trainer Mike Stidham said,
``we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Stidham's best efforts, Desert Air is a front-runner
loathe to let another horse take the lead. Desert Demon doesn't
mind hanging with bottom-dwellers at the back of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   In the Risen Star Stakes at Fair Grounds on Feb. 21, Desert
Demon looked like a winner in midstretch when he charged from 10th
place into second. He couldn't keep up with Ecton Park, Answer
Lively and Kimberlite Pipe in the last furlong, but finished a
solid fourth. That performance looks even better in hindsight,
since those three colts dominated Sunday in the Louisiana Derby.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Manzotti, Desert Demon has two victories from 11
starts, and he took the $150,000 Gallery Furniture Juvenile on
Texas Champions Day in December at Sam Houston. Should he win
tomorrow, he likely will return for the Arkansas Derby on April 3.
Otherwise, he is a possibility for the Lone Star Derby at Grand
Prairie on April 18, since Stidham will be stabled there.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone, having a sensational meet at Fair Grounds, will
ride Desert Demon in the 1 1-16 mile Rebel, which has drawn an
11-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to now, he's shown us that he's probably a cut below the
best 3-year-olds,'' said Stidham, known for objectivity in
evaluating his horses. ``I'm hoping that as he matures a little
bit, maybe he can catch up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching up is something Desert Demon loves to do. Desert Air,
on the other hand, would rather blaze the trail.
</P>
<P>
   For all their differences, the Texas-bred siblings make a nice
one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   EXPLOIT'S EARLY RETIREMENT
</P>
<P>
   Three-time stakes winner Exploit lost for the first time
Saturday, and then the news got worse. He chipped his left knee in
the race and has been retired.
</P>
<P>
   The near-black 3-year-old colt, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis,
had been among the leading Kentucky Derby contenders and was
undefeated in five races until stablemate Prime Timber passed him
in the stretch of the San Felipe Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Exploit would have needed knee surgery to run again, trainer Bob
Baffert said, but now he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so sought after as a sire, we decided to retire him,''
Baffert explained. ``It's a big blow to the barn. He's been a great
little racehorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Fret not for Baffert. As he tries to make it three in a row in
the Derby, his list of 3-year-olds still includes Prime Timber,
Straight Man and General Challenge, plus his filly tandem of
Excellent Meeting and Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is proper to sympathize with those who backed
Exploit in the first two pools of the Kentucky Derby Future Wager.
He closed at 8-1 in the first pool, 14-1 in the second, and took
$37,780 in nationwide wagers that now are worthless.
QUICK HITS
GOING ONCE, GOING TWICE
</P>
<P>
   Fasig Tipton's 2-year-olds in training sale will be held at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie at 10 a.m. Tuesday. Buyers have an
opportunity for a sneak preview when the horses work out over the
surface at 10 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, sponsored by the Texas Thoroughbred Association,
features 267 juveniles. The overall numbers are lower than last
year, but sales officials said the quality of the horses is up.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL BARNS
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero, another key Triple Crown prospect preparing for the
April 10 Santa Anita Derby, has a new trainer. Richard Mandella
replaces Wally Dollase, fired this week as private trainer of the
California division of Saudi Arabian Prince Ahmed Salman's
Thoroughbred Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Dollase had done well in his brief stint with Salman, so the
firing came as a surprise. The horses will be distributed among
several other trainers. Baffert was asked to take a few, but
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel right about what they did,'' Baffert told ``Daily
Racing Form''.
</P>
<P>
   HERE AND THERE
</P>
<P>
   Oaklawn Park leading jockey Tim Doocy, who tied for second in
last summer's Lone Star Park standings, will instead ride this
summer at Prairie Meadows in Iowa, said his agent, Jack Moody.
Returning to Lone Star after a year's absence will be Donnie Meche,
fifth in the races-won standings at Fair Grounds, ahead of Marlon
St. Julien.
</P>
<P>
   Brocco, an 8-year-old Kentucky sire, has been sold to an
Australian farm due to libido problems. But any effort to get him
interested in his job is time well spent. Two record-breaking
2-year-old colts sold this week at a California in-training auction
_ one for $2 million, the other for $1.1 million _ and both were
sons of Brocco.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Derby winner Kimberlite Pipe has been nominated to the
Triple Crown for the $6,000 late fee. He probably will run next in
the April 10 Blue Grass Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet is due to compete in the April 3 Oaklawn Handicap
against Behrens and Precocity. Banshee Breeze and Manistique are
being pointed for Oaklawn's Apple Blossom Handicap on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop arrived in Dubai on Monday for the March 28 Dubai
World Cup, a $5 million race. Silver Charm and Malek are to show up
today.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
