<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S UPSETS SECOND-SEEDED MARYLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The evening was not a total loss for
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Terrapins' band got a huge reaction from the Thompson-Boling
Arena crowd before the game when it broke into the Tennessee fight
song, ``Rocky Top.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, however, the Maryland basketball team hit rocky
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's pitched the Terps into an abyss with a 20-0
first-half run Thursday night that spanned more than eight minutes
and the South Region's No. 2 seed could never climb out.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm (28-8) kept rising with a 76-62 victory that
thrust them into the Elite Eight for the first time since 1991, one
step away from the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God we got off to a great start against a great team and
our kids played great defense,'' St. John's coach Mike Jarvis said.
``The first half was incredible. Until I was told we had a 20-0 run
I didn't know how good it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it worked out we needed the 20 points. So the journey
continues. We're going to try enjoy the moment because they don't
come very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley led the Red Storm with 24 points and nine assists,
seven in the first half when St. John's built a 38-19 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with a lot of heart and really played together
tonight,'' Barkley said. ``We executed on offense and broke their
pressure in the first half, which got us off to a great start.''
</P>
<P>
   Down by one almost 12 minutes into the game, St. John's turned
things around.
</P>
<P>
   It began innocently enough when guard Bootsy Thornton flashed
loose underneath for two layups on feeds from Ron Artest and
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   The blitz gained momentum when Barkley made a 3-pointer from the
top of the key and Artest scored on a breakaway jam in transition.
The Red Storm got two free throws each from Collin Charles and
Barkley and Tyrone Grant closed the half with a layup.
</P>
<P>
   Stunningly, St. John's went in at the half with a 19-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we could have done that was together,'' Thornton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland went the last 8:26 of the half without scoring. For the
first 20 minutes, the Terrapins made 7-of-23 shots and had 13
turnovers. Second team All American Steve Francis scored two of his
13 points in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's drought continued for two minutes of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Terps did make the game mildly interesting with a 21-4
sprint of its own to close to 60-51 with 5:19 to play. But St.
John's kicked the Terps back down when Barkley hit a 3-pointer and
Reggie Jessie made two free throws in succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little lapse in the second half, but we stayed
together and that's how you win,'' Artest said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2331EST &QL; 
