r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GWYNN-COMMENTARY-     03-18 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGING GWYNN HASN'T LOST ARTFUL TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Tony Gwynn figures he has something to prove
this year. He ``slumped'' to a .321 average in 1998, so he figures
he has to show he still can hit, that he's not slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been that way my whole career,'' he said. ``My career
really is based on proving people wrong. `He doesn't hit with any
power, he doesn't drive in any runs, he doesn't do this, he doesn't
do that. He doesn't run well, he doesn't look like an athlete.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn is right. And he's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't hit with any power. In the Year of the Homer, he hit
16. It was one short of his career high.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't drive in runs. He's topped 100 once in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   He's no longer a gazelle, either, in speed or build. He looks
more like a beachball than an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn, San Diego Padres outfielder and one of the nicest
guys in the history of professional sports, is quite simply one of
the greatest hitters ever.
</P>
<P>
   His career batting average is .339. Only 15 players in the
history of the game can beat that. It's the best in the game since
Ted Williams retired with a .344 average in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   He is 72 hits shy of 3,000, the magical number that will punch
his ticket to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Sure he has his critics, but then there are people who didn't
think Frank Sinatra could sing or that ``Casablanca'' was a great
movie.
</P>
<P>
   No, Gwynn has nothing to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting a baseball is an art, and Gwynn is the game's
Michelangelo. His paintbrush is the small, skinny bat he uses to
unerringly make contact with balls coming in at all speeds and
angles.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting a baseball might be the most difficult thing to do in
sports, but Gwynn makes it look ridiculously easy. He failed to
make contact with less than 6 percent of his swings last year. He
struck out only 18 times.
</P>
<P>
   So what if right field typically is manned by sluggers such as
Sammy Sosa, Juan Gonzalez, Manny Ramirez and Vladimir Guerrero? So
what if he doesn't crush 450-foot home runs? Gwynn is still worth
the price of admission, even in an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Giants the other day he took a couple of strikes,
then flicked out his bat and slapped a clean single the opposite
way. Artistry in action.
</P>
<P>
   Hit No. 3,000 might be an opposite-field poke. It might be a
line drive up the middle. It might be a ground ball between first
and second. Chances are it will be a single, although Gwynn is on
the verge of passing Babe Ruth in the all-time doubles category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want it to be clean,'' he said. ``I'll take an infield
chopper as long as it clean. The bottom line is, a hit's a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   A hit is a hit, and Gwynn's been cranking them out with
regularity since he made it to the majors to stay in 1983. He hit
.309 in 86 games that year. The following season he batted .351 and
won the first of his eight batting titles.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Boggs was the standard good hitters were measured by when
Gwynn came up. Boggs hit .349 as a rookie in 1982, and set an
American League record with 200 hits in the next seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boggs was the guy to try to emulate and try to keep pace
with,'' Gwynn said. ``For a long time there he was leading the
pace. Nobody was even close.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boggs began to slow down in 1992, when he hit .259. Gwynn,
who never has hit less than .300 in a full season at any level,
surged at about the same time. He ``only'' hit .317 that season,
but followed that with averages of .358, .394, .368, .353 and .372.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs is also closing in on the magical 3,000 and the sure
ticket to the Hall of Fame; he needs 78 hits. But Gwynn will get
there first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five or six years, it's kind of flipped over,''
Gwynn said. ``I'm proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn openly talks about 3,000 hits and what it means. He knows
it's a number that no critic can argue with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that everybody who's got 3,000 hits is in the Hall of
Fame, except for Pete Rose and the guys who haven't been out of the
game five years,'' he said. ``Yeah, my resume looks pretty good.
There are some things I've done that haven't often been done. But
that's the one thing I feel like I have to do to validate what all
I've done. It's out there. You just kind of methodically plod your
way to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, just like Michelangelo methodically painted that ceiling.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
