A6132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOLEY-NOSENATE19-COX     03-18 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLEY-NOSENATE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's Foley says he won't be Senate candidate
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One of the first to get in and now one
of the first to get out, U.S. Rep. Mark Foley announced Thursday
that he's not going to run for the U.S. Senate after all.
</P>
<P>
   Groans of political despair could be heard throughout Palm Beach
County and the Treasure Coast as those who hoped to replace Foley
and those who hoped to replace them suddenly became without hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really? You're kidding,'' said a stunned Palm Beach County
Commissioner Mary McCarty, who has been busy building a
congressional campaign. ``He's not running? Really? You're kidding.
You're kidding. Really? Can I call you back?''
</P>
<P>
   Foley, a West Palm Beach Republican in his third term, appeared
to be a certain candidate in the race to replace Connie Mack, who
announced last week that he will not run for re-election next year.
Rumors about Mack's departure had spread for weeks and Foley was
among a handful of Florida congressmen and other elected officials
who said they would run for Mack's Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more ambitious members of Congress, Foley has long
dreamed of running for statewide office. As he began sending
signals that he would soon announce the formation of his campaign,
McCarty, a Republican, and Democratic Palm Beach County
Commissioner Carol Roberts both talked about running for his seat.
That spawned talk among others about running for their jobs. And on
and on it went.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and McCarty both talked to Washington political
consultants. McCarty even announced the formation of a 10-member
exploratory committee and began polling the district about how
voters feel about a female candidate. Roberts took a more pragmatic
approach, saying she wasn't going to move too fast until Foley made
a formal announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark started talking in the last week with some of his most
trusted supporters and they told him it was not in his best
interest to run for the Senate,'' said a source close to Foley.
``They very candidly said that Mark was not likely to win. I think
it took some time for him to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently appointed to the Ways and Means Committee, Foley, who
is a deputy whip, also was persuaded that he should be content with
building on his increasingly influential role in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked at the race and I think I have a pretty good gut
instinct for what can be done realistically and what can't,'' Foley
said. ``I feel really comfortable with this decision and I wanted
to make it quickly enough so that other people looking at my seat
and other races could make their own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those caught in the backwash are West Palm Beach City
Commissioner Al Zucaro, who was thinking about running for Roberts'
seat, and Boca Raton City Councilwoman Wanda Thayer, who was
looking at McCarty's seat. Zucaro said he wasn't too disappointed
because, ``I think there's enough to do in the city of West Palm
Beach that it wasn't a foregone conclusion that I would run.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state Democratic Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson
said Thursday he will run for Mack's seat. Other potential
Democratic candidates include U.S. Rep. Peter Deutsch of Fort
Lauderdale and former state Sen. Rick Dantzler of Winter Haven.
Deutsch, who like Foley has all but formally announced, is now
hinting that because of family considerations he may change his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bill McCollum (R-Altamonte Springs) is a probable
candidate for Mack's Senate seat. Potential Republican candidates
include state Senate President Toni Jennings of Orlando and U.S.
Reps. Charles Canady of Lakeland and Joe Scarborough of Pensacola.
Former state Sen. Charlie Crist of St. Petersburg, who ran against
U.S. Sen. Bob Graham last year, says he will run.
</P>
<P>
   For those who dreamed of Foley's seat, they can now turn their
eyes toward U.S. Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Boca Raton. Wexler said he
will make a decision about running for the Senate during the
summer. Wexler seems less inclined to run than Foley was, but if he
does, another Palm Beach County commissioner, Democrat Burt
Aaronson, says he may run for that seat. If Wexler leaves, the
political dominoes will begin falling all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer George Bennett contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
