<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TORRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE WILL MISS 6-12 WEEKS FOLLOWING SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The doctor who performed prostate cancer surgery
Thursday on Joe Torre deemed the two-and-a-half-hour procedure
successful, said that he does not believe the cancer has spread and
speculated that Torre would not be able to return and manage the
Yankees for at least another six to 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Catalona, a Washington University urologic surgeon
and prostate cancer researcher, spoke optimistically about Torre
making a full recovery and spoke repeatedly about when the
58-year-old manager should try to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very routine,'' Catalona said at a news conference at
Barnes-Jewish Hospital after he had removed Torre's prostate gland
and surrounding lymph nodes. ``I think he had a very early prostate
cancer and the operation went very smoothly. Everything looked
fine. The lymph nodes looked clean. The prostate looked clean. It
was a routine, textbook operation. It went very well.''
</P>
<P>
   While Catalona said he would not know if Torre's cancer had
spread until the pathology specimen is returned in a few days, he
indicated that Torre's tumor was so negligible that it was only
detectable because his annual prostate specific antigen test was
elevated. Catalona said that when he held Torre's prostate after
removing the walnut-sized gland at the base of the bladder, it did
not seem abnormal and added that the lymph nodes looked
``absolutely normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Catalona, who described Torre as being ``very amusing'' and
telling jokes until the moment he received anesthesia, emphasized
again and again the importance of Torre not trying to return to his
manager's job prematurely. During the 20-minute news conference,
Catalona made five references to the significance of Torre letting
himself recover properly and seemed to be intimating that his
absence from wearing a Yankee uniform will probably stretch to the
three-month mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The usual patient is in the hospital for three to four days
and then we don't like them to return to full activity until at
least six weeks,'' Catalona said. ``I'm going to encourage him not
to go back too soon. He's got a very stressful job. I hope he'll
give himself time to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, who received a call from Ali Torre, Joe's
wife, shortly after the surgery ended, said he planned to echo
Catalano's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe knows that I want him to take his time coming back,''
Steinbrenner said in a phone interview from Tampa, Fla. ``That's
his life. This brings everything into perspective for people when
you have cancer and life-threatening situations. Everything else
doesn't matter, especially the score of a baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre's cancer was diagnosed during a PSA test, the early
detection test for prostate cancer that was developed by Catalona
in 1989. Catalona is also responsible for the safer version of the
radical prostatectomy that he performed on Torre. This reduces the
risk of damaging the nerves on the back side of the prostate, which
are responsible for potency, and the sphincter muscle, which is at
the tip of the prostate and is responsible for urinary control.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old doctor, who has performed more than 2,200
operations using this nerve-sparing technique, likened the nerves
that are located along the wall of the rectum to railroad tracks
and said the prostate sits above them like a box car.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is just very gently lift the prostate and
separate it from these nerves and remove it without damaging the
surrounding nerves,'' said Catalano, who was recommended to Torre
by Bob Watson, the former general manager of the Yankees who also
had prostate cancer surgery done by Catalano.
</P>
<P>
   The most common side effects of this surgery are incontinence or
impotence, and although Catalano said that impotence is always a
possibility, he said Torre's surgery went so well that he should
regain normal function. Torre is one of an estimated 179,000 men
who will contract prostate cancer in the United States this year,
according to Barnes-Jewish Hospital. It is also estimated that
37,000 will die from the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Catalona said Torre will be walking more and eating
within a few days, he reiterated that the manager should not return
to work ``before six to 12 weeks.'' He said that stress is a major
factor in the rate of recovery and that some of his patients who
have returned to work too soon have not felt normal for months
after the surgery. Catalona usually recommends that patients return
to work on a part-time basis, leaving after half a day to go home
and take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with the kind of job that Joe Torre has, he can't take a
nap at noon,'' Catalona said. ``It's going to be important for him
to allow himself time to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who is content with Don Zimmer as the interim
Yankee manager, was also adamant about preventing Torre from doing
too much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wehling, a former public relations director with the St.
Louis Cardinals who acted as Torre's spokesman Thursday, said the
manager was thankful for the hundreds of cards, calls and flowers
he had received. Wehling suggested that Torre is quite aware of the
importance of healing. ``Certainly, his priority is this situation
and his family and he wants to take care of that and make sure that
when he returns to the Yankees that he's either at 100 percent or
close to it,'' Wehling said.
</P>
<P>
   While Catalona said there is always a chance that cancer can
recur, he spoke positively about Torre's future. If the cancer is
totally contained in the prostate and does not spread and the
prostate is removed, then the cancer should be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the survival statistics on men who have
organ-confined prostate cancer,'' Catalona said, ``their survival
is almost the same as the general population who never had prostate
cancer to begin with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
