<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT COURSE WHERE HOUSE WAS DESTROYED, LOWERY SHOOTS A 67 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ As Steve Lowery walked down the fourth fairway
Thursday, he passed by the charred remains of his home.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, Lowery's house was destroyed by a fire fueled by
30-mile per hour winds. Lowery's wife, their three children and the
family dog escaped unharmed. But the pain, the memories and the
helpless feelings that accompany such a catastrophe remain fresh in
Lowery's mind.
</P>
<P>
   All of that made Lowery's performance Thursday even more
improbable and impressive. Shooting a five-under-par 67 at Bay Hill
Club and Lodge on the golf course adjacent to where his home used
to stand, Lowery was just one stroke behind the leader, Tim Herron,
after the opening round of the Bay Hill Invitational. In third
place was Dicky Pride (68), another Bay Hill resident and a close
friend of Lowery's, who has helped him cope with the fire.
</P>
<P>
   It was another eventful day for Lowery in what has been an
emotional period. Anyone who walks down the fourth fairway at Bay
Hill can see the remnants of Lowery's house. Even a faint smell of
smoke is still in the air. Yet, when Lowery passed by Thursday, he
refused to look. Lowery knows he is fortunate, and he is determined
to get on with his life.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, he made a par at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that it helps put the fire behind me,'' Lowery said of
Thursday's round, which included six birdies and just one bogey.
``Hopefully, I can get back to playing golf. We are really doing
good. My family is good. We are going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The community has helped by opening its arms. Arnold Palmer and
his wife, Winnie, let the Lowerys use a guest house at Bay Hill,
where they stayed immediately after the fire. Since then, the
Lowerys have moved into a condominium in nearby Isleworth, where
Tiger Woods and Mark O'Meara live. Lowery can even laugh about the
ordeal now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to get past it where it's a little more
lighthearted,'' Lowery said, smiling. ``I'm OK with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery and his wife have not decided if they will build a house
at the same location or settle elsewhere. But, with his family back
to a somewhat normal routine, Lowery has returned to golf, although
not a day goes by when he does not think of the fire or how it
could have been far more tragic.
</P>
<P>
   The cause is still unknown, although an electrical problem in
the attic wiring is suspected. Lowery's wife, Kathryn, and
children, Kristen, 7; Lauren, 3), and Stephen Brent, 1, all left
the house quickly after the blaze started around 2 p.m. Bogey,
their English springer spaniel, ran into the house during the blaze
and was hiding under a coffee table, but he was rescued by
firefighters. Fire trucks responded within four minutes, but by the
time they arrived, the fire was out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had happened at night ... ,'' said Pride, his voice
trailing off. ``We're all very thankful.''
</P>
<P>
   While the fire was taking place, Lowery was competing in the
final round of the Tucson Open. His wife called PGA Tour officials,
but left instructions that her husband should not be told the news
until his round ended. Lowery, who has not won on the tour since
the 1994 Sprint International, closed to within one stroke before
tying for 20th place.
</P>
<P>
   It would make a great story if Lowery won this weekend. But he
has already gained the admiration of many. ``I tell you what, he
made a good par on four,'' Pride said. ``Steve's a very mentally
tough person. He's been through a lot. I'm sure they'll get through
it. But I wouldn't wish this on anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
