<SLUG> BC-HACKER-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRISONED COMPUTER HACKER REACHES PLEA AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Mitnick, perhaps the nation's most notorious
computer hacker, has reached a plea agreement with federal
prosecutors that could pave the way for his release from prison,
people involved in the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   David Schindler, an assistant U.S. attorney in Los Angeles,
confirmed that a filing had been made under seal in U.S. District
Court here regarding Mitnick, but he would not discuss its contents
or even confirm that it was a plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Randolph, Mitnick's attorney, also declined to comment.
``I don't want to impact the case involving my client,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times reported Thursday that under the
agreement, Mitnick would plead guilty and be given a sentence of
about five years. But he could be out of prison in about a year,
given the time he has already served and time off for good
behavior. A person involved in the matter said the article was
essentially accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement, which still requires the approval of U.S.
District Judge Mariana Pfaelzer, who is presiding over the case,
would avoid a trial that was scheduled to begin in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick, 35, who has been breaking into computers since he was a
teen-ager, is charged with stealing millions of dollars' worth of
software from several manufacturers during a two-and-a-half-year
spree. He is also charged with stealing files containing passwords
and fraudulently using cellular phones in order to make calls and
computer connections untraceable.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick has been in prison since February 1995, when he was
arrested in North Carolina after being a fugitive for more than two
years. His downfall came, officials said, after he broke into the
home computer of Tsutomu Shimomura, a researcher at the San Diego
Supercomputer Center, who then began a sophisticated electronic
hunt for the intruder.
</P>
<P>
   Even after he leaves prison, Mitnick will not be able to use a
computer or a cellular phone for three years without approval from
his probation officer, according to a ruling in a previous
conviction by Pfaelzer. It is possible new conditions will be added
to his probation by the latest settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick first came to national attention as a lonely, overweight
teen-ager who broke into a North American Air Defense Command
computer. He became the embodiment of the hacker _ a young person
subsisting on munchies and working through the night tirelessly
trying to penetrate corporate and government computers using a
personal computer and modem. Some experts said such activities
posed a grave threat to electronic commerce and privacy. Others saw
them as little more than juvenile pranks.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's supporters say the extent of his crimes has been
exaggerated by the government and the press. A World Wide Web site
set up by such supporters maintains that Mitnick never profited
from his actions and instead did what he did as a means of
``satisfying his intellectual curiosity and applying Yankee
ingenuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackers broke into the The New York Times site on the World Wide
Web last September, protesting articles by John Markoff, a Times
reporter who covered Mitnick's arrest and then wrote a book about
the case with Shimomura.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rasch, former head of the Department of Justice's computer
crime unit, said Mitnick had symbolic importance but that ``he's
not that important'' in terms of damage done. ``The techniques that
he had and the skills that he had were about average,'' said Rasch,
who is now a lawyer working on Internet issues. ``He was just more
aggressive at doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Kevin are not the real threat to electronic
commerce,'' he continued, adding that bigger threats come from
foreign governments and a company's competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if found guilty on all counts and given a stiff sentence,
Mitnick could have been in jail for years to come. ``Both Mitnick
and DePayne face life sentences, not realistically but
potentially,'' said Richard Sherman, an attorney for Lewis DePayne,
a friend of Mitnick's who is a co-defendant in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four years Mitnick has been in prison this time, 22
months were for violating an earlier parole and for cellular phone
fraud. The rest of the time he has been awaiting trial on the
current charges. The judge denied him bail because he had fled in
1992 when he was being sought by law enforcement officials for
violating the terms of the earlier parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
