A6138 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     03-18 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN MAY RETURN BEFORE END OF TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Dennis Rodman, apparently nearing the end of his
combination therapy session/vacation, has informed the team he will
return soon, perhaps by the end of this road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, speaking by telephone from an undisclosed location,
spoke with Lakers executive vice president Jerry West and general
manager Mitch Kupchak on Thursday, according to team spokesman John
Black.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's making some progress taking care of the personal
business he had to take care of, and he expects to join the team
within the next several days,'' Black said. ``Hopefully, on this
road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   That should be welcome news to a team that's struggling
defensively and in danger of posting a losing record on this
six-game trip. Rodman skipped practice in Los Angeles last
Saturday, then told the team he would not be traveling with it.
Since then, the Lakers have gone from 9-0 with Rodman to 1-2
without him.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is being paid his $12,195 per game, but he's also being
fined by the team for the extended absence, during which he's
reportedly spent time in at least a couple of vacation spots.
</P>
<P>
   He's averaging 10.3 rebounds and 24.8 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   Wohl's return: Dave Wohl, who joined the team Thursday for his
second stint as an assistant coach, said he's happy to be back,
even if it's just for the last 26 games of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever been with this team before, it's an experience
you don't forget,'' said Wohl, an assistant from 1982-85. ``The
three years I was here we got to the Finals, we won the
championship. I think any player or coach would look upon that as a
tremendous achievement. . . . It's kind of like coming home in a
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Kurt Rambis' coach, Wohl now works for him. And he's not at
all surprised at Rambis' success as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see he had a mind even at the end of his playing
career, where he was like another coach on the floor. It's kind of
nice to see him grow into that role,'' Wohl said. ``He's very
organized, very focused, same personality. Unfortunately, some
people become a head coach and their whole personality changes.
That's gonna be one great advantage for him _ he is who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Always Blount: Corie Blount, waived by the Lakers last week,
played 12 minutes against his old mates as a Cleveland Cavalier on
Thursday. Blount, a Monrovia High graduate, said the parting was
amicable and that he asked to be let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my agent to see what he could do. I didn't want to sit
on the bench all year,'' said Blount, who was stuck on the bench
once Rodman arrived. ``I know it's a business. They've gotta do
what they've gotta do. . . . I wasn't heartbroken.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount said he also had offers from Vancouver, Seattle and
Denver _ where he would have been reunited with buddy Nick Van
Exel. Cleveland, he figured, offered the best opportunity for
significant playing time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
