</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC ANNOUNCES SOME CHANGES, BUT STILL FACES CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Even as it offered a framework for
reform Thursday, the International Olympic Committee continued to
raise questions about just how vigorously it is determined to root
out corruption that has gravely damaged the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee made an experimental change Thursday,
forbidding members to visit the six cities bidding to become host
to the 2006 Winter Games, it also formed an ethics commission that
will be only partly independent.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics commission will consist of seven or eight persons, a
majority from outside the IOC. The commission members, however,
will be appointed by Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC president, and
will include as many as three IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether such a commission could be truly independent and
trustable, given the IOC's punctured credibility in the area of
ethics, Richard W. Pound, an executive board member from Montreal,
said: ``Wait and see who the outside people are. If they are my
sister, my brother and my cat, you can question it. We are trying
hard to make this work. We are not going to gloss it over.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch also named himself chairman of a reform commission
called IOC 2000, which was announced Thursday and will examine such
proposals as term limits, democratic elections, open meetings and
open financial records. Last month, Samaranch was sternly rebuffed
by American and European officials in his attempt to head an agency
to oversee a worldwide effort to control doping. Both the Americans
and Europeans felt he lacked credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch took no action when Pound told him of a million-dollar
bribe offer in the 1980s or when Toronto sent a lengthy warning in
1991 about abuses in the bidding process. Asked why he should head
the reform commission, the 78-year-old Samaranch said defiantly
Thursday: ``I am president of the IOC. This commission must be
presided over by the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the reform commission came a day after the
expulsion of six IOC members linked to the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We promised to clean house; we did it,'' said Samaranch, who
vowed to complete his term, which ends in 2001. ``We promised to
study a new structure of the IOC; we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one worldwide corporate sponsor of the Games, however,
was not encouraged by the two-day meeting, during which the IOC had
promised to show that it was serious about widespread reform.
</P>
<P>
   David D'Alessandro, president of the John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co., said that the IOC seemed to set a double standard on
Wednesday, expelling members who asked for illicit gifts and favors
but not those who received improper benefits without asking.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that the IOC ``continued its incestuous nature'' by
not appointing a completely independent ethics commission and by
having Samaranch run its reform commission.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro also said that Samaranch showed a ``very weak
leadership position'' by saying he would study reform, rather than
demanding that certain changes be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Samaranch should have been much stronger,''
D'Alessandro said from Boston. ``He put the sponsors in a
wait-and-see attitude again. Absolutely nothing breathtakingly
performance-oriented happened. He didn't say: `We must have term
limits. Some of you will have to vote yourselves out of a job.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a potentially enterprise-killing scandal on his
hand,'' D'Alessandro continued. ``I see this as a continuation of
the nobility attitude: `Please media, please sponsors, leave us
alone and we will go off and study so we can come back with the
least that we can get away with.' It is a very weak leadership
position to appoint a study group when everybody knows what you
have to do. The sponsors shouldn't be saying all is well. We have
no idea whether there is going to be true reform.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Next, the IOC faces a hearing before the U.S. Senate Commerce
Committee on April 14. The committee chairman, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., is threatening to revoke the IOC's tax-exempt status in
the United States and to limit its access to television rights fees
paid by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to study the problem has passed,'' McCain said. ``The
abuses are well-documented. It is time for the IOC to take action.
Until reforms are implemented, the IOC will be unable to restore
its reputation. All IOC members should act with speed to expedite
reforms that are badly needed.''
</P>
<P>
   If John Hancock lost the ability to deduct its sponsorship and
advertising fees, its costs would increase by 40 percent,
D'Alessandro said. Worldwide sponsorships cost $40 million and
more. Hancock, upset by the IOC's slow pace at reforming itself,
has already canceled negotiations with NBC for $20 million in
Olympic-related advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm afraid of is that this slow, torturous, weak
leadership is going to cause the Olympics to be devalued even more
than they already have been,'' D'Alessandro said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, often criticized for its insular behavior, released
financial records Thursday that showed that it had a $207 million
bank balance at the end of 1998. The records also said that the IOC
paid $204,000 last year to cover the living expenses of Samaranch,
who is unpaid. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
