<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ADULTERER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ADULTEROUS GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 19:
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, Maj. Gen. David Hale's adulterous conduct with
the wives of four subordinates was a disgrace. Under military law,
it was also a crime. On the eve of his court-martial, the retired
general, after adamantly insisting on his innocence for months,
agreed to plead guilty to eight counts of misconduct for committing
adultery and lying to the Pentagon's deputy inspector general about
it. He could have been punished with up to 11 years in prison. The
sentence imposed by the judge at the court-martial _ a reprimand
and an order to pay $22,000 in penalties _ is surprisingly light
given the devastating effect his betrayals had on officers directly
under his command.
</P>
<P>
   Hale now bears the shame of being the highest-ranking officer to
be court-martialed since 1952. The conviction sends an important
message that the Army is getting serious about eradicating the
perception that senior officers are allowed to get away with sexual
transgressions that would result in charges against junior officers
and enlisted personnel.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself is progress. Last year Hale was allowed to retire
honorably and quietly after complaints were filed against him by
one of the wives. But public outrage at the case prompted Defense
Secretary William Cohen to bar officers accused of misconduct from
retiring until the charges against them are resolved. Given the
vigorous prosecution in 1997 of Sgt. Maj. Gene McKinney on sexual
misconduct charges, the Army cannot be seen as tolerating similar
behavior in its commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Hale maintains that his adulterous relationships, though
violations of the Code of Military Justice, were consensual. But
the affairs destroyed morale and trust among those under his
command. It is that consequence that makes his conduct worthy of
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   That is not necessarily true in all cases involving adultery
charges. The military should not be in the business of policing
private, consensual relationships that do not affect military
discipline. In fact, a Pentagon committee appointed by Cohen last
year recommended that adultery remain a crime under military law,
but be pursued only when the adultery disrupts order and the
functioning of the military unit. Those proposed guidelines are
still being reviewed. Even if they were in place, Hale's conduct
would remain culpable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-99 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
