<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: POSTELL IS ST. JOHN'S SILENT SPIKE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ On a modest farm in Guyton, Ga., a
grandfather introduces his grandson to the virtues of patience and
delayed gratification. They greet the dawn and begin a routine that
has no tolerance for shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Saturday ritual: wake up, eat, do chores. At the end
of the day, if tasks are completed to the grandfather's
satisfaction, the grandson can drive the tractor. This is how Lavor
Postell, the St. John's junior forward, learned the first crucial
basketball fundamental: moving without the ball.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Postell is St. John's silent spike, the subtle
reason St. John's basketball has re-emerged as a national power. A
dynamic new coach in Mike Jarvis, a star player in Ron Artest, a
phenomenal freshman guard in Erick Barkley. Then there's Postell, a
presence, much like faith, that is felt long before it's seen.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 games this season, Postell has come in and out of the
lineup. He is absorbed by the flow of a game, and then, like a
chameleon, takes whatever shape is needed to help propel the team
to victory. Sometimes he does so with his outside shot, sometimes
with passing or rebounding; consistently with defense. But he
almost always goes unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Indiana, Postell recognized the need to
attack. After two long jump shots he sliced through the Hoosiers'
defense for a pair of baskets, then scored on a resounding dunk
that permanently altered the game's flow.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Indiana players knew something had happened, but
they couldn't put a collective finger on it. There had been Artest
and Barkley, for sure. But there had been something else. Postell,
the Silent Spike, had spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Postell's mother and stepfather, Sarah and Fred Peterson,
notice; his high school coach, Willie Boston, notices. In fact, all
of Albany, Ga., notices.
</P>
<P>
   But for much of the nation, St. John's is the Ron Artest show.
``He's really not into all of that stuff,'' Sarah Peterson said.
``He's never been like that, always quiet, keeps to himself. If
people notice, they notice. His actions speak louder than words.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, as Jarvis began his first season as St. John's
coach, he felt the team would be better served if Postell, a
starter as a freshman and sophomore, came off the bench. Postell's
reaction to that change has as much to do with St. John's success
this season as his play does.
</P>
<P>
   He called his high school coach, called his mother, just so
Albany, Ga., would not be surprised. His reaction was like that of
the seasoned farmer who gets a dry spell when he expects rain. ``I
guess it's just something I'll have to adjust to,'' he said. He
almost immediately became a spark off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Through the benchings and unbenchings, Postell never considered
leaving the university. In an era when talented players' use of a
school is often mercenary, Postell never lost sight of the fact
that he had signed with the institution, not the coach. Brian
Mahoney had recruited him and left before Postell ever saw the
campus; Fran Fraschilla was dismissed after two seasons. Then came
a new regime and the loss of his starting role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, `Did you sign with the coach or the school?'''
said Boston, Postell's coach at Westover High in Albany. ``Without
even hesitating, he said, `The school.'''
</P>
<P>
   Postell was born in Albany, his mother's only child. Her parents
played a major role in Lavor's upbringing and education, especially
her father, a minister who instilled hard work and the no-shortcut
approach to life in his grandson just as he had with nine children.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his peers moved on a fast track; Postell took the long
way. In 10th grade he took a job in a grocery store bagging
groceries, then he took a job at Dairy Queen. Every day, Postell's
mother sees the consequences of taking shortcuts. Sarah Peterson is
a corrections officer at Autry State Prison, where some of Lavor's
high school classmates are incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't his mother's job that made Postell see the right
path. ``I've worked here for five and a half years,'' his mother
said. ``He's been doing pretty good for a long time. He's quiet;
never says anything bad about anybody and he works hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Postell's grandfather died in 1994, on the eve of a state
championship game. The death had a disastrous effect on Postell's
performance but, almost overnight, helped put his goals in focus:
commitment to college education, basketball as a means of achieving
it. St. John's was the institution from which to receive it; New
York was the city in which to enjoy it. With goals so sharply
defined, it doesn't matter whether Postell is on the bench or off
it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
