<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-NH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI TESTS WIDER APPEAL WITH NEW HAMPSHIRE VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Looking more than ever like a candidate for
the Republican national ticket next year, New York Gov. George
Pataki made his first political trip to New Hampshire Thursday,
even as he acknowledged that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas should be
seen as the front-runner for the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki joined a long list of politicians who, like models on a
runway, are taking their turns before the critical eyes of
Republican activists in this state. He held a private lunch meeting
with the party's state committee and was planning to address the
annual Lincoln Day dinner of the Manchester Republican Party
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Pataki, his host, Stephen Duprey, the
state party chairman, backed away from his comment on Wednesday
that the governor was getting too late a start to compete with
presidential hopefuls like Bush, Lamar Alexander and Steve Forbes,
who still have organizations left over from their 1996 campaigns.
New Hampshire's primary, the first in the nation, is 11 months
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me take part of my foot out of my mouth,'' Duprey began,
before insisting that Pataki could not be counted out. Yet moments
later, he said: ``Is it late to get into a race? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Pataki has coyly played the part of the not-quite
candidate, conceding that he is thinking of running for president
but declining to say when he will decide whether to formally enter
the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's trip, his first visit to New Hampshire in several
years, was packed with the trappings of an early campaign swing. A
jet chartered by his political action committee ferried him, his
aides and a contingent of reporters here from New York; he held two
fund-raisers before his dinner speech, both closed to the press; he
gave two television interviews, and at each stop his aides stood
ready with glossy folders filled with flattering newspaper
clippings about Pataki to hand to local reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The governor insisted that his purpose was simply to spread the
gospel of competency according to Republican governors. But as a
member of New Hampshire's Republican state committee said Thursday,
``He wouldn't be here if he weren't running.''
</P>
<P>
   Since winning re-election in November, Pataki has made a series
of trips around the country to raise his profile and test support
among party leaders. But he remains no more than an afterthought
when Republicans _ even those in New York _ are polled about their
choice of a presidential nominee in 2000, raising speculation that
he is really seeking the vice presidential slot. And as Duprey
noted, Pataki lags several other candidates in fund raising and
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, conceding the front-runner status of Bush, said:
``I think there's a great deal of reason to respect the candidacy
of Bush. He's been an outstanding governor, he has a national
network, and he's a terrific guy with a very broad vision and a
very successful background.'' But, he added, ``I think there are a
number of others out there who are very credible and strong
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's message here is the same one he took recently to
Missouri and Illinois: that the national image of the party should
be shaped more by governors like him who have executive experience
in solving problems and setting fiscal policy, and less by
congressional leaders and others who have focused on the
impeachment of President Clinton and on divisive social issues. Not
coincidentally, those issues put him at odds with the mass of
Republican primary voters around the country, since the governor
favors abortion rights and gay rights, raising serious questions
about his ability to compete in those primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we seemed like an angry party and a negative
party that was opposed to things, as opposed to being positive and
talking about the issues we've been able to deal with and handle
successfully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That message might be more palatable to Republicans in this
crucial state than in Missouri, where Pataki's speech a few weeks
ago was boycotted by the party's social conservatives. Several
members of the state party committee here said that New Hampshire's
brand of conservatism, like Pataki's, did not focus on people's
private conduct. Duprey, the state party chairman for six of the
last seven years, favors abortion rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
