<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORTILLA-INVASION-LAT     03-18 2102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORTILLA-INVASION-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRAPIDO, WRAPIDO
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HOUSTON _ When Alfredo Lira started his tortilla business in
Houston in 1977, he didnt have a dime. All he had was a former
chicken-processing factory with a leaky roof and some used
tortilla-making equipment from his brother-in-law. But with help
from friends and hard work, he built La Espiga de Oro into one of
the biggest tortilla-making operations in the region, supplying
supermarkets, restaurants and food distributors across the country.
His tortillas have even accompanied NASA astronauts into space.
 &HT;    But when Mexican food companies like Gruma and Grupo Industrial
Bimbo came inquiring about buying his business, the dapper
54-year-old politely showed them the door. ``Im not ready to
retire,'' he says.
 &HT;    Unlike Lira, though, most mom and pop tortilla shops across the
United States are taking the check. The corner tortillerias, as
they are known, are now being flattened by Mexicos food giants.
 &HT;    Bigger than bagels. Over the past 10 years, Gruma, through its
U.S. subsidiary, Las Colinas, Texas-based Mission Foods, has been
buying up tortilla factories across the country, from as far south
as El Paso, Texas, to as far north as Zillah, Washington. Bimbo
entered the fray five years ago, first buying up tortilla plants in
Oklahoma City and Toledo, Ohio, and later acquiring Fort
Worth-based Mrs Bairds Bakeries in March 1998 for an undisclosed
price. And in June 1998, Agrobios, a unit of Mexican conglomerate
Desc, shelled out US$142 million for Authentic Specialty Foods
Inc., a publicly traded company in Grand Prairie, Texas that owned
the Victoria line of salsas, chiles and other Mexican products as
well as three tortilla makers in Texas.
 &HT;    Whats so tasty about the U.S. tortilla market? Its hot growth
rate. According to the Dallas-based Tortilla Industry Association
(TIA), U.S. sales of tortillas have mushroomed from $300 million in
1980 to well over $3 billion last year, exceeding sales of all
other ethnic breads combined, including bagels, croissants and pita
bread. Over the past 15 years, tortilla sales been growing around
10 percent per year and are now accelerating toward $4 billion by
2000.
 &HT;    Why such growth? The increasing population of Mexicans in the
U.S. _ up about 40 percent to almost 19 million since 1990 _ is the
most obvious reason. But the biggest demand is coming from
non-Latinos, who are gobbling up almost 60 percent of all tortillas
sold in the U.S. Traditional soft tacos, crispy taco shells and the
more recent phenomenon, wraps, are being filled with everything
from meat to vegetables to pate. While the little Chihuahua may
say, ``Yo quiero Taco Bell,'' white-bread, national fast-food
chains, such as Long John Silvers and Subway, are serving tortillas
to the mainstream, too. ``The non-Hispanic culture has found that
the tortilla is a good piece of bread,'' says Irwin Steinberg,
president of the TIA, which has about 150 members. ``Its relatively
inexpensive and extremely healthy in terms of other breads you can
buy.''
 &HT;    Since thousands of years before Christ, people have been eating
tortillas in Mexico, but the flat, pancake-like food has never been
a particularly big growth business there. For years, the government
has kept a tight lid on tortilla prices. So Mexican companies
naturally followed migrants northward to take advantage of the
growing appetite for Mexican food and the ability to charge more
for a bag of tortillas _ about 55 to 60 cents per pound, versus 15
cents in Mexico.
 &HT;    While the government recently lifted price controls on
tortillas, its still not a booming business. When Mexicos
economically strapped consumers balked at paying more for their
precious staple, Mexican tortilla makers agreed to cap prices at
around 20 cents per pound, keeping a squeeze on margins. And
despite the convenience of buying packaged tortillas at a
supermarket, Mexicans still prefer buying freshly made product at
their corner tortilleria.
 &HT;    So for Mexicos major food companies, the big market for packaged
tortillas is the United States. ``Any company in Mexico is looking
for U.S. dollar revenues right now,'' says William Landers, who
follows Latin American food and beverage companies for Lehman
Brothers in New York. ``And Mexican food is still the most popular
food going.''
 &HT;    Through Mission Foods, Gruma has probably gone after the U.S.
tortilla market the longest _ and with the most gusto. Since
entering the U.S. in the late 1970s, it has built or acquired 13
tortilla factories in eight states. Gruma, whose U.S. sales
represent roughly half its US$ 1.3 billion total annual sales, now
controls the largest chunk of the U.S. tortilla market with about
24 percent, followed by Springdale, Arkansas-based Tyson Foods (5
percent), and Omaha-based ConAgra and Bimbo (3 percent each).
 &HT;    There are still pockets of the country that Mission doesnt
reach, such as the Midwest and parts of the Eastern seaboard. So
Martin Ricoy, who was head of Kaiser-Roth _ the U.S. unit of
Mexican hosiery giant Synkro _ before becoming chief executive of
Mission two years ago, is on the prowl for new targets. ``Our
strategy is to grow internally but also through acquisitions,'' the
50-year-old Mexico City native says. ``We dont know that we ought
to be the dominant player. But we want to be the biggest player.''
 &HT;    Right now, 80 percent of Mission Foods $600 million in sales
comes from supermarket chains like Albertsons, Kroger and Vons; the
rest comes from the food service business, including national
fast-food chain Taco Bell and salty snacks company Frito-Lay. Thats
a more lucrative area currently dominated by Tyson that Ricoy would
like to develop further. ``Food service is an area where we believe
we still dont have our fair share, so were going after more share
dramatically,'' he says.
 &HT;    Takeovers a la mexicana. Last year, Mission had a big enough
presence that it began advertising on network TV in certain
markets. Its latest commercial, which recently played in pricey
prime-time on the CBS affiliate in Houston, shows a busy American
family rushing in and out of their kitchen, catching meals on the
fly. ``Wrap it. Roll it. Make it with Mission Tortillas,'' the
cheerful voice-over says. New TV commercials are in the works that
will debut this spring.
 &HT;    The acquisition trail hasnt always been pretty. A year and a
half ago, when Mission bought El Ranchito, a 50-year-old tortilla
factory in Zillah, Washington, the new Mexican owners closed the
plant two weeks before Christmas and let go all 80 employees, some
whose parents and grandparents had worked for the company. Gruma
then shifted production of the Ranchito brand to its facility in
nearby McMinnville, Oregon. It did the same thing last year in
Houston with its acquisition of La Predilecta. In both cases, the
owners were forced to sign multi-year non-compete agreements. Ricoy
defends the companys actions, saying the plants were old, with
outdated equipment.
 &HT;    With Grumas strong lead, Bimbo is fast trying to play catch up.
The $2.3 billion company has been exporting Mexico-made Tia Rosa
brand tortillas into Texas for years. But with its acquisition of
$300 million (1997 sales) Mrs Bairds, it is now the number-two
player in the Texas tortilla market with an 18 percent share
(versus 31 percent for Mission and 14 percent for Authentic
Speciality Foods). Along with the Bimbo and Tia Rosa brands of
tortillas, the firm now has Mrs Bairds and the C&AMP;C and San Marcos
labels in South Texas. It also has tortilla factories in California
and plans to move farther into the southern and southwestern United
States.
 &HT;    ``The United States represents a large potential market where
our company has been successful for the past 25 years,'' Juan
Muldoon, president of Bimbo Bakeries USA, the U.S. subsidiary for
Grupo Industrial Bimbo, said in a faxed response to questions from
Latin Trade. ``We definitely want to be a player in the industry.''
 &HT;    Bimbos expansion may be limited by its access to capital. In
June 1998, Bimbo had trouble lining up a syndicated bank loan to
buy Mrs Bairds because of the crumbling of emerging markets around
the world. It was forced to sweeten its terms, doubling its banking
fees and spread and shortening the grace period on repayment.
Muldoon says financing is up to its parent company. (Bimbo CEO
Daniel Servitje in Mexico City has said publicly that the company
would probably have to use borrowed funds for its expansion in the
United States.)
 &HT;    Money will be key, because Bimbo and Gruma face a tough
competitor in $6.3 billion Tyson Foods, the largest U.S. chicken
processor that has also become second-largest U.S. tortilla
producer. Tyson got into the business in 1983 by acquiring Mexican
Original, a popular Mexican restaurant in Fayetteville, Arkansas,
that had become a major supplier of tortillas to restaurants,
retailers and food distributors with sales of around $13 million.
Tyson expanded the company aggressively, opening up additional
plants in Fayetteville, Sanford, North Carolina, and Portland,
Indiana. The division now distributes tortillas to as far away as
New York City and has about $150 million in sales.
 &HT;    How does Tyson feel about Mexican titans like Gruma and Bimbo
moving in on its turf? ``Competition is competition,'' says Wayne
Beach, director of sales and marketing at Mexican Original. ``It
doesnt matter where it comes from.''
 &HT;    Another 800-pound gorilla that is moving in on the business is
$23 billion Con-Agra. The agricultural giant entered the business
six years ago when one of its major customers, Taco Bell, requested
it. It started with a plant in 1992 in Omaha, then acquired in May
1998 another tortilla maker, Louisville, Kentucky-based Mesa Foods.
With sales upwards of $50 million, Mesa Foods tortilla division,
Casa de Oro, is now scouting for more. ``Ten percent is pretty
heady growth for any food category,'' says Ted Longacre, Casa de
Oros president. ``So wed like to have a few more facilities.''
 &HT;    Longacre says Casa de Oro is trying to compete with the Mexican
giants on technology, trying to develop the best way to spit out
the best-tasting tortillas at the lowest cost. ``We have to figure
out how to win, both on the technology side and service to the
customer,'' he says.
 &HT;    With the competition getting stiff, Mexicos Desc is already
thinking about getting out of the U.S. tortilla business. At press
time, Authentic Specialty Foods was looking for a buyer for its $26
million (sales) tortilla division, which includes Calidad in
Dallas, La Monita in Houston and Tortilla King in San Antonio.
Mission Foods is the most likely suitor. ``The market is huge, and
so is its potential,'' says Francisco Hernandez, president of the
Texas direct sales division of Authentic Speciality Foods. ``But
its not our core business.''
 &HT;    The Tortilla Industry Associations Steinberg thinks
consolidation will continue, with smaller tortilla companies
getting swallowed up by bigger Mexican outfits like Bimbo and
Gruma. ``A lot of companies are opting to take the money and leave
and not try to compete,'' he says. ``Well eventually see 20 percent
of the players control 80 percent of the market.''
 &HT;    That doesnt frighten La Espiga de Oros Lira, who thinks he can
make a better product and provide better service than the tortilla
giants. ``Somebody (another tortilla company owner) told me, Bimbo
and Mission are like elephants, and we are like ants,'' Lira says.
``But I can bet money that more ants eat elephants than elephants
eat ants.'' Yes, unless the elephants stomp on the ants first.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
