<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6162 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     03-18 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY WOOD SHOULD RETURN; WILL WE RECOGNIZE HIM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The most depressing local sports story of
the past 12 months wasn't, as it turns out, the Mavericks'
wanderings, or the Cowboys in the playoffs, or even the fact that
both Randy Johnson and Roger Clemens wouldn't mess with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It came Tuesday, when the news came that pitcher Kerry Wood
would have to undergo major reconstructive elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   They call it ``Tommy John surgery,'' after the Dodger whose
reconstructed pitching wing revolutionized modern sports medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry Wood has about as much in common with Tommy John as a
bullwhip does to a butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   The news is awful. The outlook is historically bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, the Grand Prairie High graduate and National League rookie
of the year, won't be back until the 2000 season at the earliest.
And even then, the question remains, will we recognize him?
</P>
<P>
   When Wood says, as he did at a news conference, ``It all depends
on the individual and on his work ethic,'' he suggests that he
plans an aggressive rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There've been cases where a guy has come back stronger, and
there've been cases when a guy hasn't come back as strong,'' Wood
said. ``The doctors do the surgery, and then it all depends on the
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Another pitcher, Jose Rijo, thought he could come back from
``Tommy John surgery'' in the spring following his 1995 operation.
His elbow balked again, and the Cincinnati Reds' four-year,
$22-million investment proved a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Success after ``Tommy John surgery,'' the medical journals tell
us, is relative. Power pitchers, like Wood, often have to learn to
become finesse pitchers, like John.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood, a finesse pitcher? Sigh. What awful news.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it depends.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Tom Candiotti had the surgery, and he has flutter-balled
his way to 147 wins in his big-league career. The White Sox' Scott
Eyre, on the other hand, had his elbow reconstructed in 1994 and
has won but seven.
</P>
<P>
   There are ominous question marks lingering over the
once-so-bright careers of, among others, Cal Eldred, Butch Henry,
Steve Karsay and Jeremi Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is only 21 years old. Even with a lengthy and complicated
rehab, he could be only 24 when he returns. That's not too old to
learn how to pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   But will we recognize him?
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' Darren Dreifort took the advice of noted surgeon
Dr. Frank Jobe, the man who invented the procedure, and had his
elbow redone in March, 1995. Dreifort was 22. The surgery cost him
most of two seasons, but he is back throwing in the mid-90 mph
range and has become a valued Dodger starter.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said, ``If it was going to happen, it was going to happen.
It was inevitable, I guess. I felt that way from the time my
velocity picked up _ I felt it could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood, the doctors will tell you, is a victim of the
system. High school teen-agers don't get drafted by relying on the
proverbial crafty assortment of change-ups and curveballs. If you
can't make a radar gun hum, you won't be drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Wood becomes the new poster child for Overthrowers Anonymous. It
was ``inevitable''?
</P>
<P>
   That's not pitching. That's self-abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Much will be made of Wood's pitching delivery and its alleged
flaws and the fact that Kerry had a tendency to throw across his
body. Let me suggest, however, that there are healthy pitchers in
every spring camp who throw across their bodies. Oakland's Kenny
Rogers, to name one.
</P>
<P>
   Wood overthrew because that's the only way he knows how to
pitch. His rehab, therefore, could end up being not only to his
elbow but between his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Koch, on the other hand, refused to change. The No. 4
overall pick in the 1996 draft, Koch was a 100-mph fireballer in
the Toronto chain when his elbow blew out in 1997. Anybody who has
ever seen Koch pitch _ either at Clemson or on the U.S. Olympic
team _ remembers him.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors told Koch that he would be out for 18 months; he
returned in nine. He immediately began throwing 95 mph in spring
training and ended up starting 27 games in the minors last season.
Koch is a hot prospect again.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe was 48 years old and had a pioneer's vision, when he took a
tendon out of John's right arm and implanted it in the left in
1974. John returned to the mound two years later, pitched 14 more
big-league seasons and can still throw batting practice, he says,
for his son's school team.
</P>
<P>
   But Wood was special. In baseball's greatest summer, he struck
out 20 Houston Astros in one game and vaulted onto the marquee as a
featured player.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to envision Kerry Wood as anything other than a
hard-throwing 20-year-old, helping to pitch the Cubs into the NL
playoffs. It's hard to imagine Wood as anything but the way he was
in the summer of '98.
</P>
<P>
   Cherish that memory. Sadly, history suggests it may be all we
have.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
