<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INQUIRY OF NYC POLICE EXPANDS TO INCLUDE ELITE STREET CRIMES
UNIT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A continuing investigation by federal prosecutors
into the tactics of the New York City Police Department will be
expanded to give increased scrutiny to the Street Crimes Unit, the
elite squad that includes four officers who fatally shot Amadou
Diallo, the Justice Department announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry, to be conducted by Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney
in Manhattan, will focus on whether members of the Street Crimes
Unit have systematically deprived people of their constitutional
rights through ``stop and frisk'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White's inquiry will broaden an investigation by the U.S.
attorney's office in Brooklyn, which began 18 months ago after the
alleged police torture of a Haitian immigrant, Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   City officials were formally notified of the expanded
investigation earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, state Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer said he
would review assertions that officers routinely stop people on the
streets and frisk them without justification. Earlier this month
the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights said it would hold hearings on
the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Street Crimes Unit sends teams of officers into
neighborhoods to hunt down suspects and seize illegal guns. It has
been criticized by civil rights groups who contend that its members
have stopped and searched tens of thousands of people, based on
their race, without arresting the vast majority of them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White's investigation is likely to focus on the unit's
stop-and-frisk policies, as well as on the screening and training
of officers.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman for Police Commissioner Howard
Safir, said on Thursday night: ``We will fully cooperate with this
investigation, just as we have with all of the other
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department portrayed Ms. White's focus on the Street
Crimes Unit Thursday night as an expansion of the original
investigation authorized by the agency under a 1994 law that allows
federal officials to investigate whether ``patterns or practices''
in police departments deprive people of civil rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
