r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FLORIDA-T     03-18 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FLORIDA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA TAKES BITE OUT OF FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Gonzaga Bulldogs continued their improbable,
history-making run in the NCAA Tournament. They got a game-high
five 3-pointers from Richie Frahm and a Casey Calvary tip-in with
4.4 seconds remaining to defeat Florida, 73-72, in a West Regional
semifinal game last night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, a small school in Spokane, Wash., became the first No.
10 seed to advance to a regional final since Temple in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest moment in our basketball lives,'' Gonzaga
coach Dan Monson said. ``The only thing that could be sweeter is if
we make it to the Final Four. We've still got to come back and play
Saturday. But we're 40 minutes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga hit nearly as many 3-pointers (12) as 2-pointers (13).
They had leads of seven and 13. But with 45.7 seconds to go, they
were down, 72-69, after Florida center Greg Stolt hit his fourth
3-pointer of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida swarmed Frahm, who passed out of a double team to hit
Jeremy Eaton for a layup with 19.7 seconds left. On the inbounds
pass, Gonzaga guard Quentin Hall pressured Brent Wright into a
traveling call. That set up the winning basket. Hall's runner in
the lane was put back by Calvary, who outdueled Wright to give
Gonzaga the victory in a game that had eight lead changes and six
ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had both hands on the ball, and the ball bounced around and
went in,'' Calvary said. ``I was nervous to get the shot off. The
last time I made a game-winning shot must have come when I was the
third or fourth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida had one good chance at victory following Calvary's shot.
Guard Eddie Shannon ran the length of the court, but his
desperation, off-balance three-pointer rimmed out at the buzzer,
sending the sixth-seeded Gators home.
</P>
<P>
   A despondent Shannon lay on the court for several moments. Just
a few feet away, jubilant Gonzaga players celebrated in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were unlucky; they were lucky,'' said Florida guard Teddy
Dupay. ``We should have gone further. We had the game won. This is
the worst I've felt in basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Frahm led all scorers with 17 points. He was 5 of 8 from the
3-point line, and hit three consecutive three-pointers in a 2:15
span late in the second half. Calvary had 12 points, and Matt
Santangelo added 11 points and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   Stolt led the Gators with 16, and Wright had 15. But they were
poor shooters from the 3-point line (6 of 24), beginning the game
making one of their first 13 3-pointers.
</P>
</TEXT>
